<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIS is not the way it's supposed to end.
</P>
<P>
   Not when an individual has been such an integral part of three
championship teams. Not when he has the numbers and professional
portfolio worthy of the Hall of Fame, not to mention the Dallas
Cowboys' Ring of Honor at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But it's happening to Michael Irvin, and it's an awkward,
uncomfortable and quite humiliating thing to see.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of reason to say Irvin deserves any indignity
heaped upon him, though it would be difficult to imagine an
embarrassment or slur worse than he has attached to his own name.
He has shamed himself, his family and the Dallas franchise that
rewarded him so handsomely with both money and the fame that
eventually brought him down.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there remains a reason to feel queasy at seeing the final
act unfold, if for no other reason than as a cold, stark reminder
of all that Irvin has thrown away, which also includes his NFL
legacy. And that is a shame.
</P>
<P>
   For while Irvin's actions away from the football field are
indefensible, so has he been for the past 11 seasons, including 10
on the receiving end of all those passes from quarterback Troy
Aikman. What's more, while Irvin has been anything but a role model
in his personal life, the truth is that when it comes to this game
at which he excels, he has always been the consummate pro. He
practices hard, plays hard, bleeds Cowboys blue and cares about
winning as much as any player who ever wore the famous helmet with
the star on the side, even though he often crosses the line with
his strutting peacock routines.
</P>
<P>
   What is just the slightest bit regrettable isn't seeing Irvin,
the repeatedly unrepentant bad boy, getting his comeuppance in the
form of club owner Jerry Jones dangling his name in trade talks. It
is seeing a sports hero, who could have and would have had it all
in Dallas because of his immense talent, twist in the wind at the
end of his career as a result of his own personality flaws.
</P>
<P>
   They have always been and always will be interchangeable pieces
in the business machine of pro football. There is nothing new in
that. And the fact Jones is making himself unavailable to the media
to discuss the situation with Irvin for the upcoming season speaks
loudly that the Cowboys would actually prefer that one of their
all-time greatest wide receivers not be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys prepare for the start of training camp, just more
than a month away, and look ahead to their prospects for the 1999
season, the outlook for success is bleak even with Irvin in the
lineup. So the owner who has been hogtied by the very same salary
cap he helped invent and exploit is looking for ways to alleviate
his financial burden, and if he also happens to lose one of his two
biggest public-relations nightmares _ don't forget Leon Lett, who
has just been suspended a third time for violating the NFL
substance-abuse policy _ then all the better.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Irvin was a simultaneous symbol of how
good the Cowboys could be as football players and how bad they
could be as people. In the eyes of so many Dallas-haters around the
nation, he was the Cowboys, all wearing one set of shoulder pads
and a single jersey, No. 88.
</P>
<P>
   For so many of those years as Irvin was hauling in 740 passes
for 11,737 yards and 62 touchdowns, his sheer talent and desire to
compete and win were enough to make him indispensable to the
Cowboys, even after his sordid cocaine-and-hookers bust in 1996
that resulted in a five-game suspension by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, after a year when his production fell off to just
one touchdown catch all season and he was virtually abandoned by
first-year head coach Chan Gailey's offense after Thanksgiving,
Irvin, who carries a base salary of just under $3 million against
the cap, finds himself to be quite disposable. Except that his rap
sheet, including probation terms that could send him to jail for
even a minor slip-up, makes him unwanted by other teams.
</P>
<P>
   And the handwriting is on the wall in Dallas, where Irvin, 33,
is being permitted to enter the final year of his contract without
an offer of the kind of extensions given to Aikman and running back
Emmitt Smith. Their skills, too, are eroding, but they have earned
the right to be part of the organization and of Cowboys lore to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Michael Irvin, who has finally been run down by his
past.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the way it's supposed to end. Not sad, just pathetic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
