<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TOGETHERNESS CAN'T OFFSET CAMBY'S FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They have climbed this mountain four times in
eight years now, and never made it over the peak, to the other
side, where the championship series awaits. The Indiana Pacers have
kept coming back, though, with an earnest spirit and a united core.
Along the way, these anti-Knicks made one celebrated coaching
change, tinkered a bit, but the principal players remained the
same.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers of Dan Quayle's home state have been the Eastern
Conference franchise of family values, their foundation built with
teamwork and trust, with the conviction that persistence and
patience would be rewarded in the end. As the showdown with the New
York Knicks became inevitable, the Pacers clung to the belief that
the team which refused to let a work stoppage stop it, which
practiced conventional basketball logic, would ultimately outlast
an opponent which all season long has defied it.
</P>
<P>
   And continued to defy it on Wednesday night, precisely in the
manner that Marcus Camby refused to be stereotyped, even dismissed,
as too weak and too soft.
</P>
<P>
   It was raw and utter defiance, the way Camby picked the Knicks
off the floor in the second quarter of the pivotal fifth game at
Market Square Arena and took them for a rousing ride on his
magnificent wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   This brutal reality now faces the once-favored Pacers after
losing, 101-94, in Game 5: elimination Friday night, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The edge they believed that would carry them home was altered
and downright rejected, the way Camby treated so many of their
shots at the rim. Months ago, the Pacers practiced when the league
was padlocked three months by a lockout. They went through the
short season thinking a dividend on that investment was coming.
``Yeah, at the end, you'd think so,'' Larry Bird said. ``But you've
got to understand that 5 of our top 9 players weren't even there.''
</P>
<P>
   And not enough of them were there on Wednesday night. Instead,
it was Camby dominating inside, and Latrell Sprewell and Allan
Houston winning the perimeter war with Reggie Miller, and Larry
Johnson showing up late with two huge threes. The Pacers once again
failed again to demonstrate that brotherhood determines who plays
on and who goes home.
</P>
<P>
   All the standby team-sport cliches are on the line in this
series, all the accredited visions of how to grow a champ. Three
times in seven years the Pacers reached Game 7 of the conference
finals, a step away, and were beaten, on the road, by Patrick
Ewing, Shaquille O'Neal and Michael Jordan. When the three
all-league teams were announced Tuesday by the National Basketball
Association, there wasn't a Knick _ or Pacer, for that matter _ to
be found. Shouldn't one then assume that intangible factors such as
familiarity and continuity and stability would be more significant
than ever and inevitably play out Indiana's way?
</P>
<P>
   While the Pacers were bonding until David Stern opened his
doors, Patrick Ewing was flabbing out in the negotiating room,
setting in motion the chain of events that turned the Knicks'
season into a Jerry Springer script. When the lockout ended, the
Knicks were re-made in the manner of a Latrell Sprewell dash down
court, Sprewell and Kurt Thomas added on the eve of the season,
while the unproved Marcus Camby was forced on an insecure coach who
only wanted players he could trust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after all the fussing and feuding and firing, these Knicks
were thrown into the playoff microwave and came out smoking, all
the way to within one game now of the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   After Game 2, the Knicks had plunged back into emotional turmoil
for pushing the injured Ewing too hard and lost him for good.
Naturally, after they won Game 3 by the grace of Jess Kersey's
whistle, Jeff Van Gundy decided it was high time for a major lineup
change. Suddenly faced with the electric Sprewell going up against
the defensively challenged Chris Mullin, Bird yawned. Told the
Knicks ``to just go out and play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to tinker when the coach believes in you, and
when you believe you have the best team,'' said Mark Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   This all sounded good and wholesome, the Indiana Pacer way. But
then, Utah's practitioners of clearheaded practice had already been
bounced from these playoffs by the highly combustible Blazers,
before a match was taken to their title series dreams by the San
Antonio Spurs. Now, suddenly, the Knicks have the well-practiced
Pacers on the Garden mat.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long climb up the championship mountain. Sometimes, at
higher elevations, the audacious and illogical have the better
chance to survive because, the Knicks proved on Wednesday night,
you can't practice pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
