<HEADER>
A9794 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-SPRINT-KAN &LR;      06-10 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON BRINGS HIS PUSH FOR BUSINESS DIVERSITY AWARENESS TO KANSAS
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ and ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jesse Jackson came to Kansas City on
Wednesday to publicly praise several local companies for their
diversity efforts. Behind the scenes, he urged the city's largest
private employer to do more.
</P>
<P>
   The public visit included breakfast with a black ministers'
group and a tour of the Negro Leagues Baseball Museum with baseball
legend Buck O'Neil. Jackson joined former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver and
other local black leaders to expand a minority-investment program.
Jackson was the featured speaker at a luncheon that raised money
for his Rainbow//PUSH Coalition while honoring the diversity
efforts of two local businesses and the city of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But in between the speeches and handshakes, Jackson used
virtually every minute available to talk with officials of Sprint
Corp. He said he was asking the company to add more minorities and
women to its boardroom, executive-level jobs, construction projects
and vendor lists.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and others who participated described the talks as
cordial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have agreed to work out a relationship that is mutually
beneficial,'' Jackson said before leaving for an appearance in
Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is super-competitive,'' said Ben Watson, senior
vice president of human resources for Sprint. ``We are believers
that diversity makes us stronger and they are bringing us ideas on
how we can be stronger as a more diverse company.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Sprint is expected to name an African-American to its
board of directors for the first time, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sprint hired nearly 12,000 new employees, Watson
said. Of that number, 34 percent were minorities, 20 percent
African-Americans. The company also established a call center in
the 18th and Vine Historic District.
</P>
<P>
   Watson was one of about four Sprint executives who met with
Jackson as he walked from one appointment to the next, in a hurried
boardroom meeting after the luncheon, and during Jackson's car ride
to Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   William T. Esrey, Sprint's chairman and CEO, called Jackson from
Paris as Jackson took his morning tour of the Negro Leagues Museum.
Sprint's board of directors is in Paris for meetings this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications giant is the metropolitan area's biggest
private employer and a $17 billion company. But while Sprint was a
major funder of the luncheon, the $25,000 that it donated to the
effort has been placed in an escrow account until negotiations with
the corporation progress further, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can choose to be a contributor, but until we resolve
these matters, we are holding the money,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson and others involved in the negotiations with
Sprint stressed that it is just one of many companies at which PUSH
is seeking change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not just Sprint,'' Jackson said. ``Let's take a look at
all of corporate Kansas City. Let's challenge them.''
</P>
<P>
   The company became a focus of minority groups' attention in
February. The Rev. Wallace Hartsfield was asked by a group of local
minority contractors to question Sprint about what they considered
a lack of women and minorities' being used to construct its new
world headquarters in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint spokeswoman Laura Meyer said that from the beginning,
Sprint has committed to spending at least $40 million with
businesses owned by minorities and women, out of the estimated $750
million it will cost to build the Sprint campus.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said more opportunities would be available to those
businesses after building construction proceeds to interior work,
where smaller firms have more opportunities to bid.
</P>
<P>
   Some minority business owners said Sprint has been making
strides, but shouldn't need prodding to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus is the largest private project in the world. Sprint
had a grand opportunity to set an example, with levels of minority
participation never before achieved. They missed that and they are
now playing catch-up,'' said Donald Gardner, owner of Group One
Architects, a minority firm.
</P>
<P>
   In his luncheon speech, Jackson used a baseball analogy to make
the point for inclusion. He wore a replica jersey of the Negro
Leagues' Kansas City Monarchs throughout much of the day, including
during the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   American companies right now are operating without the talents
of women and minorities, he said. Before the black baseball leagues
were allowed to join the white leagues, neither collection of
talent was at its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how good American business can be until all of
the players are at the table,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City-based law firm of Shook, Hardy &AMP; Bacon also
sponsored the luncheon. The firm represents Rainbow//PUSH on
telecommunications issues.
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon, St. Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System,
Kansas City Power &AMP; Light and the city of Kansas City were honored
for their diversity efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Rainbow//PUSH organization bought $2,000
worth of stock in Sprint to make it a part of Jackson's Wall Street
Project, an effort to buy stock in major corporations as a means of
gaining access to those companies. Jackson started the project
about a year ago at the national level, and is now encouraging
similar efforts in local communities.
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City chapter of the Wall Street Project was organized
Wednesday in a breakfast meeting attended by nearly 100 of the
area's most prominent black ministers and other activists.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Cleaver and the Rev. Sam Mann were chosen as
co-chairmen of the Kansas City Wall Street Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``By being stockholders, you wind up being able to talk to
someone on the inside, not just on the outside,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he hoped the local chapter would eventually buy
$2,000 to $5,000 worth of stock in Kansas City's top public
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield said the discussions with Sprint had gone well. But
he said Sprint, like all major employers, has unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hoping and praying that our relationship with (Sprint)
will lead to more,'' Hartsfield said. ``I want to be able to brag
about a company that was bodacious enough and creative enough to do
what's right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
