<HEADLINE>
HUMANA CONSIDERS SELLING OR TRANSFERRING OPERATIONS OF CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Humana Inc. is evaluating whether to sell or
transfer the operations of about 50 clinics around the country,
including seven in the Kansas City area, a Humana spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Humana assumed control of the clinics June 1 from FPA Medical
Management Inc. as part of the bankruptcy reorganization of
Miami-based FPA. Twenty-one of the clinics, including the ones in
the Kansas City area, had been operated by Humana earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area clinics are known as the Prime Health
Medical Group. They serve 60,000 to 70,000 patients, comprising
Humana members and others. The clinics employ about 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   Humana spokesman Jose Marques said the company wanted to
concentrate on providing health insurance rather than operating
clinics. However, he said there was no timetable for changing the
status of the clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 priority when we agreed to assume operational
responsibility for these medical centers was to maintain continuity
of care for our members,'' Marques said. ``Any future decisions we
make concerning the clinics will be made on the same premise.''
</P>
<P>
   FPA, formerly based in San Diego, took over management of eight
area Humana clinics in June 1998, one month before it filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy. The company subsequently closed a clinic in
Kansas City and merged it into another.
</P>
<P>
   Humana, based in Louisville, Ky., is one of the largest publicly
traded managed health-care companies, with about 6.1 million
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
