<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART     06-10 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS RIDE SPREWELL AND CAMBY TO TAKE 3-2 SERIES LEAD OVER
PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ After being eliminated by the Indiana Pacers in
last year's playoffs, the New York Knicks decided to make the
emotional decision to trade Charles Oakley for Marcus Camby last
summer for critical occasions just like this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held on to the athletic Camby's buoyant presence and
stayed close enough to the Indiana Pacers in Game 5 of the Eastern
Conference finals to grab an improbable, 101-94, victory Wednesday
night in front of a stunned crowd at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 6 of this best-of-7-game series at Madison Square
Garden on Friday night, the Knicks, who lead, 3-2 , need just one
more victory to advance to the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   To put them in such an amazing position, Camby was everywhere _
blocking shots, making free throws, flying in for put-back dunks _
in the fourth quarter as the Knicks made up a six-point deficit to
take the lead with 6 minutes 35 seconds left. There were a series
of lead changes, but that ended when Larry Johnson hit consecutive
3-pointers to give the Knicks an 89-84 lead with three minutes
left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camby ended the game with 21 points and 13 rebounds, while
Latrell Sprewell did not pass up a single shot opportunity on his
way to 29 points. The Pacers were led by Reggie Miller, who had 30
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks absorbed the Pacers' intense initial blast and made
up a 14-point deficit at the end of the first quarter to exit the
half with the score tied, 42-42, thanks in large part to the
omnipresent Camby.
</P>
<P>
   When things looked bleak, Camby came up with points and blocks
to give the Knicks some semblance of offense and defense, pulling
the Knicks back into the game after their out-of-control start.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' Allan Houston, a little more focused, a little more
aggressive than he was earlier in the series, shrugged off his
2-for-7 start and delivered six consecutive points off jumpers and
runners, giving the Knicks a 50-46 lead three minutes into the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers turned to Chris Mullin, who came up with a couple
of nifty pump fakes on Sprewell to give the Pacers back the lead,
52-50, with 7:29 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was hot, but he was also in foul trouble. That left
Charlie Ward to guard Miller, who went right at the shorter player.
Miller scored eight straight points on Ward and gave the Pacers a
67-61 lead on a fall-away jumper with two minutes left in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed Camby, but with three fouls in the first half,
he was being saved for the end of the third. When he came back in,
the Knicks went right to him. In his brief time on the floor, he
delivered three free throws, two rebounds and altered a shot by
Jalen Rose to help keep the Knicks close. They were down by 69-65
at the end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was not on the floor for the Knicks' final two minutes
of the third after he had been beaten by Mullin. For two days,
Sprewell had to hear how old-man Mullin had dominated him in Game
4. He came out with the intent of putting a few gray hairs into
Mullin's crewcut as he went on a shooting binge in the frantic
first quarter. That was not necessarily a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was off, and the Pacers went on a 9-0 run to start the
game. But Sprewell made a few circus shots and topped that spurt
with a 10-0 run. Problem was, the Knicks defense broke down and
allowed an 11-2 run by the Pacers that culminated with a 3-pointer
from 28 feet by Mark Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   That shot gave his team a 22-12 lead with 2:15 left in the first
quarter. After the Knicks missed their final 11 field goals of the
first quarter, the Pacers had a 28-14 lead after an emotional,
up-and-down opening to the game.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Knicks' two key starters, Houston and
Sprewell, were a combined 4 for 12, which was not the initial punch
coach Jeff Van Gundy had been counting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on them,'' Van Gundy said before the game. ``It's no
secret they have to produce for us to win. That's one of the main
reasons I put Latrell in to start. I thought it would help him be
more efficient. I didn't think he had played well the last Atlanta
game or the first four Indiana games as far as shooting percent.
You'll always be second-guessed, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-guessing ended when the Knicks got their act
together. Once Camby got revved up, so did the rest of the team.
Camby scored eight points, came up with two two blocked shots and
created havoc for the Pacers as the Knicks made up their
first-quarter deficit and tied the score at halftime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camby was displaying the same zeal he has the entire series,
living up to the remarks of coach Larry Bird, who called him the
best player on the floor after Game 3. Although Dale Davis and
Antonio Davis combine to make a fearsome duo _ and combined for 16
first-half rebounds Wednesday night _ Camby did not flinch as he
took a dish from Chris Childs and exploded for a dunk over both
with 1:10 left in the half, tying the score. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about Marcus?'' Larry Johnson said. ``He's
been everywhere. He's not intimidated by anyone.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
