</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAUTAUQUA-REVIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY TURNS BACK CLOCK FOR EDUCATIONAL `REVIVAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mo. _ Lexington folklore says that only four
townspeople voted for Abraham Lincoln for president, and two of
those four were run out of town. So Elizabeth Van Lew, a Southern
belle turned Union spy during the Civil War, would have had few
friends in a Lexington crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But this is 1999, and Lexington has welcomed Van Lew, Gen.
William Tecumseh Sherman, Sojourner Truth and other Union
sympathizers to town for a weeklong chautauqua with a Civil War
theme. The event runs through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Heartland Chautauqua, produced by the humanities councils of
Missouri and Illinois, revives a tradition of traveling tent shows
that provided education and entertainment in small towns across
America around the turn of the century. At least four chautauquas
were held in the early 1900s in Lexington, before radio, television
and cinema made the shows obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chautauqua was a big social event, with everybody getting
together to eat picnic lunches and see the famous orators and
musicians,'' said Marilou Edwards, executive director of the
Lexington Tourism Bureau. ``I think people are getting that same
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   The program has been six months in the making for Lexington, a
Lafayette County city about an hour's drive east of Kansas City.
The humanities councils provide the tent, the equipment and the
scholar-actors. Each of six host communities in Missouri and
Illinois does the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington Tourism Bureau spearheaded its community's
chautauqua, collecting cash and in-kind donations from
organizations and businesses in nearby Lexington, Richmond,
Higginsville, Grain Valley and Odessa. The tourism bureau booked
musical entertainment each evening and arranged for the performers
to put on daytime programs at schools, senior centers and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so easy to perform,'' said Alice McGill, a professional
storyteller who portrays freed slave Sojourner Truth. ``Once you
enter a community, because of all the work they have done, it feels
like there is already a bond, that they are eager to support you.''
</P>
<P>
   The town, whose battle site is part of Civil War history, has
taken on its part with vigor.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, almost 250 people helped raise a yellow and white
striped tent at the Battle of Lexington State Historic Site. The
Friends of the Anderson House, volunteers who perform
living-history demonstrations at the site, are appearing in period
dress each evening to hand out paper fans and sell programs. A
local resident donated the use of a chautauqua organ, made in 1887,
that she found in her attic.
</P>
<P>
   Only that kind of enthusiasm makes a chautauqua work, said
Barbara Gill, deputy director of the Missouri Humanities Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it not a project that we are putting on but a
community project,'' Gill said. ``We are the facilitators, but they
are the folks who really are doing it. It's their chautauqua.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
