</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOW OR NEVER FOR WNBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twenty three years after the American Basketball
Association died, we're witnessing the resurrection of its spirit.
</P>
<P>
   It's a red, white and blue sun rising majestically in the June
sky.
</P>
<P>
   It's one former ABA team, the San Antonio Spurs, advancing to
the NBA Finals and another, the Indiana Pacers, two victories away
from turning the NBA's swank soiree into a rollicking ABA reunion.
</P>
<P>
   It's one former renegade league, the ABL, feeding the WNBA
enough extraordinary players to transform women's professional
basketball as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   It's awesome and a little eerie, the confluence of events that
basketball acolytes can see so clearly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 ABA founder Dennis Murphy's creation died in a hotel
conference room in Cape Cod, Mass. Four of the league's teams _ the
Spurs, Pacers, Denver Nuggets and New York Nets _ were absorbed
into the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ABL some 20 years later, the ABA had terrific talent
but not nearly enough television exposure. Its teams were fashioned
to push the ball up the court, but the league, as constructed,
couldn't stand on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The ABA created a more exciting brand of basketball, then turned
the blueprint over to the NBA, which ran with it. Attendance during
the first season after the ABA-NBA merger reached an all-time high
and television ratings increased 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the influx of talent from the defunct ABL, the WNBA,
which begins its third season tonight, will be more fun to watch.
But how many more people will notice?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question rolling around in the stomachs of the NBA
suits backing the sister season. No less than the future of women's
professional basketball is riding on the league's balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every year is a crucial year for the WNBA,'' said
Cleveland Rockers coach Linda Hill-MacDonald. ``We certainly have
not gotten to the level that we want in terms of exposure and. . .
. I don't think the game is accepted at the level that's as far as
it can go.''
</P>
<P>
   No question the NBA has the machinery to exploit the women's
game. But does it have the patience and vision to develop it?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA didn't just fall into this monopoly. It stealthily
killed the ABL with the ol' back-door play, consistently beating
its overmatched rival to TV and product endorsements. It served its
own interests. Now we'll find out how serious it is about doing
what's best for the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of businesses fold after Year Two. So we're
ahead of the curve,'' said Detroit Shock coach Nancy
Lieberman-Cline. ``We have to maintain our focus and put the league
first and not us individually.''
</P>
<P>
   The league is lucky that way. It is loaded with players who have
more game than ego. If anything, the players might be too
unpretentious for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Kara Wolters, one of the newest members of the two-time
defending champion Houston Comets. She broke her toe trying to load
her luggage for the trip to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't she know she's supposed to pay people to deal with her
baggage, be it Samsonite or psychological?
</P>
<P>
   Wolters is an ABL refugee playing on a team outside her native
Connecticut for the first time in her life. Nevertheless, she
should feel right at home. In the May draft, 20 of the first 25
picks were players from the little league that couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-ABLers Dawn Staley, Yolanda Griffith, DeLisha Milton and
Natalie Williams are the real deal. They'll make you remember their
names, same as Julius Erving, Moses Malone, Artis Gilmore and
Maurice Lucas did an entire generation of NBA fans.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The NBA wasn't one starless night after another
before Magic and Larry and Michael leaped up into the sky. People's
perspective tends to get lost in the black hole of hype.
</P>
<P>
   So it is on the women's side. Some awfully good players preceded
Lisa Leslie, Rebecca Lobo and Chamique Holdsclaw. UCLA's Ann
Meyers, for one. USC's Cheryl Miller, for another.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, who led Tennessee to three NCAA titles in four years,
was the No. 1 overall draft pick of the Washington Mystics last
month. Coach Nancy Darsch hears people talk as though she's the
guardian of the game's greatest jewel, its Hope Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know what to say, except that most peoples' memories
must be shorter than Utah Starzz point guard Debbie Black.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw could one day develop into the player against whom all
others are judged. But right now, Mystics teammate Nikki McCray has
a prettier pull-up jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been around women's basketball for 20 years, she has
some pretty stiff competition,'' Darsch said of Holdsclaw. ``But if
you've been watching women's basketball for five or six years, then
I think you're very, very impressed with Chamique and you see her
as the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Holdsclaw has something Michael Jordan does not: a
college diploma. She graduated last month with a degree in
political science. In the world of women's basketball, that doesn't
make her noble, just normal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977 Holdsclaw was born and the NBA arrived. Its finest
season was capped by a final featuring two teams, Portland and
Philadelphia, laden with former ABA players. Two years later, Magic
Johnson and Larry Bird and cable television would carry the NBA
into another stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe the melding of the ABL and WNBA will rocket the
women's game into orbit. All we can say is they better strap
themselves in tight because it's going to be a bumpy ride. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
