<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DRUGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS WORKS TO HALT ILLEGAL SALES OF PRESCRIPTION DRUGS OVER
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Warning of potentially dangerous and frightening
consequences, Kansas Attorney General Carla Stovall on Wednesday
said she had filed lawsuits to stop illegal Internet sales of
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only a matter of time before somebody dies as a
result of taking medications that are prescriptions and//or
controlled substances obtained over the Internet,'' Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the attorney general and the Kansas Board of
Healing Arts used the Internet to buy such medications as Viagra,
used to counter impotency, and diet drugs Meridia and Phentermine.
</P>
<P>
   Those purchases, including several made by a minor under the
supervision of the attorney general's office, formed the basis for
the legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   Stovall, in conjunction with the Board of Healing Arts and the
Kansas State Board of Pharmacy, filed six lawsuits in Shawnee
County District Court to halt the Internet prescription sales.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said she thought Kansas was the first state
to crack down on the Internet prescription business.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Association of Attorneys General in Washington,
spokesman Chris Privitt said he was aware of no other states that
were active in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a new concept to pursue this, and certainly Kansas
has been in a leadership role,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, Attorney General Jay Nixon's office has filed no
similar cases, but spokesman Scott Holste said, ``We're certainly
very interested in looking at these businesses that sell these
drugs through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Stovall said there were at least ``a couple of hundred'' Web
sites where prescription drugs can be purchased without the buyer
being examined by a doctor licensed to practice in Kansas and
without obtaining a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many of these companies that we don't have the
resources to go after all of them now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stovall said temporary restraining orders that direct a halt to
the practice had been signed by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Named as defendants in the actions were seven companies selling
prescription-only medications, six doctors not licensed to practice
medicine in Kansas but who are prescribing the medications, four
individuals doing business under fictitious names and three
non-Kansas pharmacies that are dispensing the medications without
being registered in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   All of those named in the lawsuits were from out-of-state
locations such as Virginia, Florida, Washington, Hawaii, Nevada,
California and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Convictions under the state's consumer protection and pharmacy
laws carry penalties of $5,000 for each violation.
</P>
<P>
   One case was filed in February by the Board of Healing Arts, and
the rest were filed Monday and Wednesday by the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the companies sold prescription drugs to a minor, who
was acting under the direction of one of the attorney general's
agents.
</P>
<P>
   From one of them, the minor was able to buy the diet drug
Meridia, a controlled substance. Controlled substances are
addictive or have a high potential for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Using his correct age and paying with his mother's credit card,
the minor also was able to purchase Viagra from two other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should greatly alarm and be yet another enormous red flag
to parents regarding the importance of always monitoring their
children's Internet activity,'' Stovall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
