</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS-DUVAL AN EXPENSIVE OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you plan to traipse after those
ready-for-prime-time players Tiger Woods and David Duval as they
spend a pleasant summer evening going club head-to-club head to
determine the best darned golfer in the universe, be prepared for
some sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval, both wealthy young men, can afford tickets to
the $1.5 million ``Showdown at Sherwood,'' the made-for-TV event
being promoted by IMG, the athlete management company, with the
blessing of the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   So can Hollywood types, tycoons and the winner or winners of
Wednesday night's lotto jackpot, whether there was one or a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us might have to draw down the savings account or
take out an equity line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the Aug. 2 event, which will be shown live on ABC
beginning at 5 p.m., are expensive on the low end and out of sight
on the high side.
</P>
<P>
   For $225, you can buy a ticket and wander about one of the most
over-the-top golf courses in America, watch a little golf and dream
about what it's like to be really rich. Act fast, though, because
only 1,500 of these tickets are available.
</P>
<P>
   Got a little extra cash and an itch to hobnob with the rich and
maybe famous? Then spend $550 for one of the 200 regular clubhouse
passes being offered. This gets you into the event, the expansive
and stunning clubhouse, pre- and post- match parties and VIP
parking. Food is included in the price, but the booze isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared to open that checkbook a little wider?
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood Country Club, in conjunction with Tickets.com, is
offering 50 special auction packages to the event. On four of them,
the bidding will start at $2,000. No telling how high it will go.
</P>
<P>
   And this could be a deal. Each package includes golf for two at
the course designed by Jack Nicklaus and home to Greg Norman's
annual Shark Shootout. Also included are two clubhouse tickets to
the match, VIP parking and a poster autographed by Duval and Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are 46 packages with a minimum bid of $1,400. This
includes two clubhouse tickets, parking and the poster.
</P>
<P>
   You can aim your Web browser at www.tickets.com or call
1-800-TICKETS.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can sit back in the comfort of your own home and point
your clicker to ABC. You'll get a better view of the action, won't
wear yourself out walking the course and your beverage of choice
will be just a few steps away.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at IMG could not be reached Wednesday to comment on
the ticket pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Woods, ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in the world
respectively, will compete in the match-play event for $1.5
million. The winner pockets $1.1 million while the loser gets
$400,000, which makes losing seem to be not too terrible a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval are donating $200,000 to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Duval replaced Woods as the world's top-ranked golfer earlier
this season after winning 11 times since the autumn of 1997,
including four victories this year. Woods has won three times,
including last week's Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first live network telecast of a golf event in
prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet home: El Caballero Country Club member Ron Cherney
got a different view of his home course this week. He caddied for
Las Vegas resident Brady Exber in Monday's 36-hole U.S. Open
qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is El Cab a tough course to play, it gives walkers a
good workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a train ran me over. The pace of play was
relatively slow, but it was a ton of fun. I really enjoyed it,''
Cherney said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time he has toted a bag in an Open qualifier
at El Cab. And he was impressed with Exber, although he failed to
qualify for the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real good player, but he didn't have a great day. He
was a lot of fun to follow and he had a great attitude,'' Cherney
said of Exber.
</P>
<P>
   Players of that caliber also manage to put themselves into a
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit the ball a lot farther than the average club player,
that's for sure. And they are much more exacting and focus a little
bit better.And they try harder on each shot than the average club
player,'' Cherney said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherney has his own qualifier coming up. He's going to try to
for a spot in the U.S. Senior Open in a few weeks during a
tournament at Mountain Gate Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Murray date set: The Jim Murray Memorial Foundation will host
its first fund-raiser, the Jim Murray Inaugural Golf Classic, on
Aug. 16 at Riviera Country Club in Pacific Palisades. Arnold Palmer
is the honorary chairman. The foundation will award scholarships to
first-year college students studying journalism. Murray is a former
Los Angeles Times sports columnist. For information, call (310)
476-8948. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
