<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER BREAKS FREE, BUT KNICKS HOLD FAST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Before the between-game adjustments were made _
before Jeff Van Gundy went back to his film room and chalkboard for
Game 5 _ Reggie Miller made an analogy as to how difficult it is to
match up with his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys it's like an overflowing dam,'' Miller said
after his offensive ineptitude in Game 4. ``The water is getting to
the top, the dam is gonna burst. And when it does, there'll be a
flood.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller had just emerged from another lackluster individual
performance, the kind of 3-for-10 game that makes people inquire,
``What's wrong with Reggie?'' But the Pacers, this multipronged
offensive gadget that the Knicks are starting to figure out the
directions to, had forged out a victory on the strength of their
fourth through eighth offensive options.
</P>
<P>
   He needed to take over a game.
</P>
<P>
   Miller finally broke through Wednesday night, finding his range,
his points and his complete game. He went back to being the Reggie
New York Knows and Hates, the villainous character who complains
after each shot that he was not only fouled but also had all his
valuables stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Obnoxious. Insufferable. But so good. Yet he had so little help
in a game the Pacers had to have Wednesday night, a game that the
Knicks worked so hard to get back into and won, 101-94.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4, Chris Mullin, Jalen Rose, Antonio Davis and Dale
Davis scored 63 of Indiana's 90 points. Van Gundy had to do
something, had to rely on some sort of energy mass to combat all
those Indiana weapons.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday night Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby became
those players. Driving, dunking, doing all the intangibles to keep
the Knicks in this series, the two most-maligned players this
season responded to playoff pressure as if they were the hardened
playoff veterans.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller kept stepping up, the old man holding off the
youngsters with head fakes and runners and every imaginable flop
known to the game.
</P>
<P>
   He drew a foul and hit a double-clutch runner in the lane with 6
minutes 7 seconds left, converting a 3-point play to put Indiana on
top, 80-79 _ their last lead. He pulled them to within four on a
3-pointer with 2 minutes left, but again, he never received help.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Van Gundy was beginning to resemble a worried
engineer _ plugging one hole in a dike just as another starts to
leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a unique team,'' the Knicks coach said prior to Game
5. ``We were talking about it the other day. Not many NBA teams
have a very, very explosive offensive team where you have to guard
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, you can't just say, `Miller, Smits or Miller, Smits,
Jackson or tonight we're going to concentrate on the perimeter,
because their post-up game will hurt you.' In the post. Behind the
3-point line. Keep them off the free-throw line.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy went on to say he wanted the Knicks to do a better job
of keeping the Pacers out of the middle, to cut off penetration
before it gets too deep.
</P>
<P>
   Smits began to establish himself without Patrick Ewing in the
lineup in Game 3, scoring 25 points, 15 straight during a binge in
the second quarter. But he wilted in the game's final minutes along
with Miller, and the Knicks went on to win on an improbable 4-point
play by Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Smits' nor Miller's talents surfaced in Game 4, and yet
Rose had one of the most clutch games of his career. The Pacers'
sixth man made every important shot as the Knicks tried to crawl
out from a first-half hole they had dug themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Allan Houston, who guarded Rose for most of the
game, and Latrell Sprewell, assigned to check Mullin, had forgot
that the two Pacer swingmen were deadly left-handed shooters.
</P>
<P>
   There is a thought circulating around the league that San
Antonio's frontline and overall depth will be too strong for anyone
coming out of the Eastern Conference. Well-rested and clicking as
well as they have all season, the Spurs seem to have every
imaginable advantage headed into the league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they don't have the Pacers' multitude of offensive options,
diverse players with so many different skills. And it remains to be
seen if they have the heart of the Knicks, a group of players that
won't die.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about their five-game war with Miami. If the Knicks can
win on Friday or Sunday and get out of this round, they will have
dodged the most lethal bullet in pro basketball's post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan and David Robinson are awesome in their own right,
but the Spurs don't have the backcourt to match up with Sprewell
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After weathering a gauntlet in Indiana, San Antonio would be a
piece of cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
