<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARENA-MANAGEMENT-KAN &LR;      06-10 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARENA-MANAGEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY WANTS TO MANAGE KEMPER ARENA, BARTLE HALL IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GROMER JEFFERS JR.  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Philadelphia company with ties to Mayor Kay
Barnes' chief campaign consultant is interested in managing the
city's convention and sports facilities, including Bartle Hall and
Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ SMG _ manages about 40 facilities in the United
States and Europe, including the Louisiana Superdome, Soldier Field
in Chicago, the Spectrum in Philadelphia, Mile High Stadium in
Denver, and the Moscone Center in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Briglia, a vice president for SMG, said he had met with
several Kansas City Council members in recent months. Briglia said
he also plans to meet in coming weeks with Barnes, who has said she
favors studying the privatizing of facilities such as Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very interested in coming to Kansas City and managing
Kemper Arena and Bartle Hall,'' Briglia said. ``We have met with
some of the elected officials and we hope to meet with the mayor
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Briglia said his company's efforts to manage Kansas City's
convention facilities were boosted by a poll prepared by Pat Gray,
the top political consultant for Barnes during her mayoral
campaign. The poll, done in 1997, gauged Kansas City residents'
feelings about privatizing convention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us a comfort level in which to meet with elected
officials,'' Briglia said. ``Unfortunately, the former
administration didn't embrace taking a look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   SMG is not the first company linked to Gray that has an interest
in managing a Kansas City department.
</P>
<P>
   On May 28, The Kansas City Star reported that Gray was working
for Environmental Management Corp., part of a consortium called
EA2//Systems, at the same time he was running Barnes' campaign.
EA2//Systems is interested in managing the Water Services
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, whose involvement with Barnes' campaign and EA2//Systems
did not violate any laws, did not return telephone calls made to
his office Wednesday for comment about his work for SMG.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was not available for comment Wednesday, said Joe
Serviss, her chief of staff. But Serviss said he did not think that
Barnes had met with SMG officials or that she had any plans to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Serviss said Barnes also did not know about any relationship
that SMG had with Gray. ``We don't know about any contracts with
anybody locally,'' Serviss said.
</P>
<P>
   But Serviss noted that SMG, once known as Spectacor, has been
trying to manage Kansas City's convention center for years.
``Twenty-five years ago, I had Spectacor come to the city when I
was a councilman,'' Serviss said. ``It's like deja vu.''
</P>
<P>
   Briglia would not provide The Star with the poll data Gray had
generated, but he said most of those surveyed favored privatization
of the city's convention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly feel that taxpayers should not heavily subsidize
these venues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Briglia said he had hired Gray _ who has built a reputation as
one of Kansas City's savviest and busiest political consultants _
only to do the poll _ not to put him in touch with elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet independently with city officials and elected
officials,'' Briglia said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Evert Asjes, who said he had had conversations with
SMG regarding management of Kemper, said Wednesday he was not aware
that the company had at one time hired Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them (SMG), when we're ready to go that way, we will
let them know,'' Asjes said. ``But there are four major management
companies interested. And they all go around looking for
business.'' Asjes said he could not recall specific names of the
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Reports about Gray's ties to a St. Louis company that wants to
manage the Water Services Department raised a furor last week.
Angry city workers and some area ministers confronted Barnes and
demanded that she explain her relationship with Gray and
EA2//Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling their ire was a document outlining a plan for taking
over the operations of Water Services, obtained anonymously through
the mail by The Star. It included a strategy to elect a mayor and
council that favored privatization and a plan to discredit the
department so the public would support a private takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has declined to comment on the document, saying it could
have been stolen or altered.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who also has declined to comment on the document's
contents, said she had met twice with officials from EA2//Systems,
and one 45-minute meeting included Gray. But she said she had not
been influenced by Gray and had been an advocate of exploring
privatization for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Jim Rowland, however, said Wednesday that he hoped
future discussions about privatization could avoid politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Gray is just an unfortunate sidebar to this whole thing,''
Rowland said. ``We need to seriously evaluate the delivery of
services. We can't afford to be distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in some cities that have contracted with SMG have seen
improvements in the management of convention facilities. For
example, SMG took over management of the 1.2 million-square-foot
Greater Columbus Convention Center in Columbus, Ohio, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Lalonde, a spokesman for the Greater Columbus Convention
and Visitors Bureau, said SMG had worked with his group to attract
more trade associations and conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jennison, executive director of the public authority that
owns that convention center, said Wednesday that he had just signed
off on a two-year extension of SMG's original three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done an excellent job in managing our facilities,''
Jennison said. ``Their national presence in the marketplace gives
us some clout we didn't have as a stand-alone facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's convention facilities and arenas have weathered
some highly publicized complaints in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   After Wal-Mart Stores Inc. held its 1997 manager's meetings at
Bartle, more than 10,000 delegates left town disappointed and
disgusted over dirty restrooms, poor lighting in meeting rooms and
other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart complaints also were the last straw for the
then-director of city convention facilities, who was forced to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the city has spent hundreds of thousands of dollars
on facelift work and infrastructure improvements at Bartle. Nearly
two dozen vacant maintenance jobs also were filled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wal-Mart's annual sessions for managers from its 2,300
stores worldwide are booked at Bartle through 2002, and the company
has options through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In February, The Star reported that a key tenant _ the Kansas
City Blades hockey team _ and several patrons had complained that
the upkeep of Kemper Arena was unsatisfactory. Other problems,
brought to light during the Big 12 Conference men's basketball
tournament last season, involved a leaky roof.
</P>
<P>
   The city's director of convention and entertainment centers
promised corrective measures to clean up trash, fix deteriorating
stairs and remedy storage problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
