<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON PATIENT WITH HUNDLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Texas Rangers stole six bases Tuesday night
against the Dodgers and catcher Todd Hundley felt the brunt of it.
He heard the boos, and in comparison to New York . . . they're
still pretty darn loud.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers manager Davey Johnson says he's content to wait for
Hundley to get better, targeting the other side of the All-Star
break as when his catcher will begin to play as management
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play behind the plate will get better,'' said Hundley, who
didn't start Wednesday against the Texas Rangers. ``I'll be the
first one to say it's been tough. I haven't produced like I should,
like I need to. I'll also be the first to tell you no one is more
frustrated and trying harder than I am. I have to be patient and
that's not one of my better traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick to the game is how you deal with failure. It's a
failure game.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Hundley is dealing with it the way you'd
hope _ by working hard.
</P>
<P>
   However, as big a crutch as his .224 average is, the bigger
problem appears to be how much teams are running on him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says that's unfair, and the blame should fall more on
the pitchers for not holding runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Rangers) had walking leads,'' Johnson said. ``By and
large, you steal off the pitcher. The only guy I know that might
have got three of the six is on the other team (Ivan Rodriguez),
but he's so good. He's the best I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking more to the second half of the season with
(Hundley) in all areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a statistically oriented man, need look no further than
the stat sheet to make his case for catchers. By all accounts,
Dodgers rookie catcher Angel Pena is one of the best young
defensive catchers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Pena entered the series finale against Texas throwing out 2 of
15 (13 percent) would-be base stealers. But before being sent to
Triple-A Albuquerque, Paul LoDuca threw out three of seven.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the first things recently appointed pitching coach
Claude Osteen was asked to do was work on the pitchers in
quickening their deliveries home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bazooka back there couldn't throw some of those guys out,''
Hundley said in regard to the Rangers' six stolen bases. ``It's a
matter of timing and everything coming together; pitchers holding
runners on, changing their times to home and making the throws to
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth pushed back: Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth
said he got a little ahead of himself in telling Johnson he could
be ready by the weekend. After working out before Tuesday's game,
Hollandsworth said he realized a more realistic return would be
Tuesday against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a little more than I thought, just a couple
of days.'' said Hollandsworth, on the disabled list with a torn
muscle on his right side. ``I have to be reasonable about it. It's
not all there yet. I have to make sure when I don't have a perfect
swing that I'm not going to hurt it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he might use injured center fielder Devon White
(groin strain) as a designated hitter during the three-game series
in Oakland this weekend, which also means the Dodgers will continue
with three healthy outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bothering him hitting,'' Johnson said. ``I have my
fingers crossed he could hit by the weekend. Maybe DH or something.
. . . I'm learning day-to-day means eight to 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Elite company: Texas right fielder Juan Gonzalez entered the
series finale with the Dodgers with 999 RBI in 1,154 career games.
Only six players in major-league history reached 1,000 RBI in their
first 1,200 games, and Gonzalez was one RBI away from being the
sixth fastest to hit that mark.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Greenberg was the quickest, driving in his 1,000th run in
his 1,026th game. He's followed by Lou Gehrig (1,079), Joe DiMaggio
(1,081), Al Simmons (1,081), Ted Williams (1,146) and Jimmie Foxx
(1,158).
</P>
<P>
   F.Y.I.: Dave Hansen started at third base in place of Adrian
Beltre. Johnson said he did it to keep Hansen sharp and make sure
Beltre wasn't tiring. . . . Three-year-old Rex Spjute (Meridian,
Idaho) sang the national anthem before the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
