<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-THREAT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DEPARTMENT'S HANDLING OF EX-WORKER'S THREAT CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Death threats allegedly made by a former
Kirkland, Wash., police employee have prompted questions about the
way the department handled the situation.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, police support officer Delano Dumo allegedly
called a colleague and said he wanted to put a gun to the back of
his training officer's head and pull the trigger, and that he
``should pull a Columbine'' at work, said Sean Riley, president of
the Kirkland Police Officers' Guild.
</P>
<P>
   Dumo, 27, resigned days later, and has since written a letter of
apology to the department, police Chief Pleas Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said his department took the alleged threat seriously and
ordered an armed officer to shadow the training officer while Dumo
was under investigation. The department determined Dumo's remarks
were offhand and lacked any criminal intent, and the matter was
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley said many department employees fault the department's
handling of the incident, which prompted few changes in security
and resulted in no written report.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were afraid for their safety,'' Riley said.
``There's no doubt in my mind a crime was committed. ... Police
officers on the street are required to take those kind of
reports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to make it go away without doing anything formal,''
said officer Mike Murray, a member of the union's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   Training officer Bob Balkema, the man targeted by the alleged
threats, said he initially was concerned and now wished the matter
would go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably did some investigating, but I don't believe it
was a thorough investigation, and I don't believe it was what they
would expect their officers to do,'' Balkema said.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo dated May 7, Riley asked Green to respond to the
questions and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions: why wasn't a report taken? Why no
internal-affairs investigation? Why weren't others notified about
the threat? Why didn't the department change the codes on locks at
the department's offices after Dumo's resignation?
</P>
<P>
   Green said no report was taken because no crime was committed,
and an internal affairs investigation would not apply to someone
who had already resigned. A card-key entry system is planned to
limit access, he said, and personnel privacy concerns limited what
staff could be told.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Capt. Joe Simon last month sent all staffers an
e-mail explaining the incident had been investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was determined that, the statements were made in an attempt
at jest, and out of frustration,'' Simon wrote, adding that the
employee was embarrassed and had apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Simon said the officer who received Dumo's alleged
threatening call took it as a joke. Another city employee reported
the call after hearing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dumo could not be reached for comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though both Green's memo and Simon's e-mail encouraged those
with concerns to come forward, no one did, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is trying to make an issue out of a non-issue,'' Simon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said department administration did not learn of the
threats _ alleged to have happened over a weekend _ for a few days,
after Dumo had already quit.
</P>
<P>
   Dumo was hired to work at the city Jail in October and was under
a one-year probation period. He ``was not meeting the performance
requirements of the job'' and knew it, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   As support staff and not sworn officers, neither Dumo nor
Balkema carried guns on the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
