<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORERS-CAREERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORER POSTS INTRODUCE OPPORTUNITIES FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ High school freshman David Ralls learned what
it takes to build a bridge _ a real bridge _ over a creek.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Bruce, a junior, tried her hand at landscape design. Later
this month, volunteers probably will put some of her ideas to work
in the courtyard of the Mattie Rhodes Art Center.
</P>
<P>
   Both students took part in Explorer Post 2967, led by Darren
Nielson, an architect at HNTB Architects Engineers Planners in
Kansas City. More than 5,000 students are wrapping up similar work
through 126 Explorer posts from Lawrence, Kan., to Warrensburg, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring, which is a part of Boy Scouts of America's Learning
for Life, brings together students and businesses throughout the
school year. Two or more times a month, the students work with
advisers who are artists, bankers, lawyers, doctors, police,
dentists, firefighters, computer designers and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The idea isn't just to get work-space and landscape designs for
Mattie Rhodes, or plans for a bridge over the creek at Osage Oaks
Arena near Buckner. Exploring helps these kids plan their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made it more realistic,'' said Bruce, 17, who is now even
more convinced she wants to be an architect. ``This is all
hands-on. This is what we wanted to do. All Darren did is he helped
us make it real.''
</P>
<P>
   She definitely plans a return to HNTB's Explorer post when it
starts up again in September.
</P>
<P>
   Ralls, 15, found that maybe he would rather be an engineer than
an architect. Next school year, he might try a different Explorer
post. But he sees potential from his work at HNTB.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be interested in getting a job there. Then, having
this Explorer post thing would be good on my record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 students in Post 2967 worked on three separate
architectural projects at HNTB. They were to present their designs
Wednesday evening to officials of HNTB, Mattie Rhodes, Osage Oaks
Arena and a local chapter of the American Society of Landscape
Architects. The society tapped the post for plans to rehabilitate
and redesign Observation Park in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited. I want to see the work these students have
done,'' said Mary Lou Jaramillo, executive director at Mattie
Rhodes, which provides counseling services and art programs for
children.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo got a preview of the students' ideas in March when
they presented three preliminary plans. Jaramillo said she and two
board members steered the students away from one of the plans and
pointed out parts of the two others they liked best.
</P>
<P>
   They particularly liked the notion of moving the art center's
entrance to the side of the building, through the courtyard. It's
not something they thought of themselves, Jaramillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so used to coming in that darn front door. It's so
narrow there's no place to greet people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce said a side entrance would bring visitors into an open
area where Mattie Rhodes' kids could display their work, as well as
hang their coats and backpacks. The students' plan also would move
the work station that was crowding the area by the side door.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring is more than 50 years old and first included girls in
1968, said Erik Lingren, who oversees the program for the Boy
Scouts of America Heart of America Council in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   He said 5,100 students were in the council's posts at the end of
1998, up 12 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring is open to any boy or girl ages 15 to 20. A
14-year-old who has completed the eighth grade also can join.
Explorers needn't have been involved in Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Lingren said the students paid between $7 and $9 for the
school-year-based program. Companies that sponsor posts donate
their employees' time, the meeting space and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Most students find out about Exploring at school. Lingren said
many area schools allowed Exploring to survey students about their
career interests. This information is forwarded to companies that
want to start an Explorer program.
</P>
<P>
   So, armed for a storm of curiosity, HNTB mailed invitations last
year to about 1,200 area students who had listed architecture
career interests, Nielson said. He said 225 showed up at the first
meeting and 90 paid the fee to participate. Competition from sports
and other activities ultimately winnowed the group to 65, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lingren currently is working with businesses and other groups
that want to sponsor posts for the coming school year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
