<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE-SLAYING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEEK PUBLIC'S HELP IN GETTING CLUES TO TRIPLE SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As they sifted through the crime scene for clues,
Seattle homicide detectives on Wednesday said they had eliminated
several family members as suspects in the slaying of a woman, her
daughter and grandaughter.
</P>
<P>
   But after 24 hours on the case, police said they had exhausted
all ``obvious leads'' and asked the public for help in the shooting
deaths of Patricia Whitfield, a 50-year-old day care owner; her
daughter, Artis ``Tizi'' Ingram, 24; and Ingram's daughter,
Champagne Younger, 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have not narrowed the focus of the investigation,''
said homicide Sgt. Cynthia Tallman. ``We're absolutely dependent
upon the community to provide us with any information, no matter
how small or unimportant it may seem to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The three victims were found Tuesday afternoon inside Whifield's
home in Seattle's Mount Baker neighborhood. Whitfield had operated
a day care center at the four-bedroom residence.
</P>
<P>
   Two possible supects emerged early in the investigation, but
quickly were dismissed. Police ruled out the father of Ingram's two
youngest children, a week-old baby and an 11-month-old baby, who
were in the house during the slaying, but were unharmed. Neighbors
said the boyfriend had been feuding with the family, but he was in
jail on a domestic-violence incident at the time of the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Also ruled out was Ingram's ex-boyfriend and father of
Champagne, whose alibi checked out; he was with relatives,
detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives also interviewed Whitfield's ex-husband, with whom
she had a history of domestic violence and had divorced in 1995.
After detectives interviewed him, they decided he was not their
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``By midnight (Tuesday), we exhausted all the obvious leads,''
said detective Steve Kilburg, who was at work at the crime scene
Wednesday. While his partner, Kevin O'Keefe, brought out sheets,
blankets and other evidence from the house, Kilburg estimated they
had spent at least 20 hours on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking friends and family for any bits of information,
any leads that would help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield's death shocked many in her close-knit community,
where she ran a day care operation in her home and was known as
``the neighborhood mom.'' Police say one of her sons hysterically
called 911 Tuesday afternoon, after finding his mother, sister and
niece dead from multiple gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives say there were no signs of forced entry, robbery or a
struggle, and that they found no evidence that points to a specific
motive. Police believe the intended target was Ingram, who had been
known to associate with gangs through one of her boyfriends, a
source said last night. But it was not clear that the slayings were
gang-related.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, neighbors were still grieving as they watched two of
Whitfield's sons enter their mother's house and come out with
diapers and clothes for a funeral Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why God would take her away,'' Arnell Wilkerson
said of Whitfield. ``It's very hard for me to believe she's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a more troubled portrait of the victims emerged
through court records and school officials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Whitfield filed for divorce from her husband of 24
years, citing a history of domestic abuse. In 1986, she said she
shot her husband in self-defense. In 1994, Whitfield entered an
Alford plea to a charge of attempted malicious harassment, which
was later dismissed. Prosecutors accused her and a companion of
harassing an interracial couple in the Central District, according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   The couple wasn't assaulted, but police were called.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield's daughter, Tizi, also had problems. She moved
frequently this year, and at one point lived in a shelter while her
daughter, Champagne, attended a school program in Everett for
homeless children. Champagne, a kindergartner, also attended John
Muir Elementary, near Whitfield's home, for about a month earlier
this year, but then transferred to Jackson Elementary in Everett
and later to Skyline Elementary in Lake Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, friends said, Whitfield worked hard to
overcome her struggles, working several jobs while rearing her
family. She loved her children and took them on trips, including
one to Louisiana so that they could be exposed to black
universities, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just a pillar of strength to everyone,'' said friend
Beulah Brooks. ``I have never known her to say `no' to anyone who
asked her for anything. She was a wonderful, generous,
inspirational person.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporter Scott Sunde contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
