<HEADLINE>
TARZAN FANS TO SWING BY FOR CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Practice that yell.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from as far afield as England and France, about 150 fans
of Tarzan creator Edgar Rice Burroughs will converge on Woodland
Hills today for the start of a three-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   They will discuss the ape man hero's many incarnations, shop for
rare Tarzan paraphernalia and watch _ a week before the rest of the
world _ Disney's new animated Tarzan movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in convention history that we've all
attended a Tarzan movie together, much less one that hasn't come
out yet,'' said organizer Scott Tracy Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, called a ``Dum Dum'' after a ceremonial
gathering of apes in the Tarzan stories, will be held at the Warner
Center Marriott in the Woodland Hills community of Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley and will be open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Those who merely wish to sit in on some of the discussions or
browse the merchandise room can do so for free. Full admission,
which includes the movie preview and a Saturday banquet, costs $70.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs bought 550 acres of property in the San Fernando
Valley in 1919, dubbing it Tarzana Ranch, a name that stuck when
the land was developed with homes years later.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
