<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9832 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-WHITESOX-H     06-10 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WHITESOX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ The Chicago White Sox may have been exactly the right
prescription to cure the ailing Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not to mention a dose of Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell continued his Windy City mastery Wednesday night,
belting three home runs and driving in six runs as the Astros tied
a club record by homering five times in rolling to a 13-4 victory
over Chicago at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   After being swept by Pittsburgh to begin a season-longest
12-game road trip, the Astros took two of three in each of the next
three series to finish the trip 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``This made things satisfying,'' manager Larry Dierker said
after his club pounded 17 hits for the second time in three nights.
``I don't think any of us thought this trip would be easy with so
many guys out of the lineup. I was hoping it wouldn't be
disastrous. After the start we had, it could have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it finished on a memorable note as Bagwell produced his
second three-homer game of the season. Coincidentally, his other
one came just down the road when he homered three times April 21 at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who has 17 multiple-homer games in his career, has six
home runs and 14 RBIs in five games this season in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice coincidence,'' said Bagwell. ``My home runs come
in bunches. I was having a tough game early. It's kind of funny
after coming back and hitting three home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox weren't in a laughing mood.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's feats were the exclamation point on a three-game
series that saw the Astros turn things around offensively. They
batted .358, scored 24 runs and had 43 hits and six home runs
against the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have double-digit hit totals in four of their last
six games.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell went 4-for-6 Wednesday, Carl Everett homered for the
second time in as many days and had three RBIs, and Tim Bogar
snapped a yearlong homer drought.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Astros had hits, six with two or more.
</P>
<P>
   The five-homer game tied the club record accomplished five times
previously, the last on Aug. 22, 1996, against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was a matter of time with this club,'' third
baseman Bill Spiers said. ``We always go through little spells
during the season. I think we came out of it good, and hopefully
we'll keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense overshadowed a strong pitching performance by Mike
Hampton (7-2), who gave up one earned run and seven hits in 6
innings. He struck out six and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   After going 1-1 in his first four starts, Hampton is 6-1 with a
2.48 ERA since April 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros actually had this one well in hand before Bagwell
chipped in, building a 4-0 lead in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   After an 0-for-3 start, Bagwell hit a three-run homer in the
sixth inning, a solo shot in the eighth and a two-run drive in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a legitimate power hitter,'' White Sox manager Jerry
Manuel said. ``His style is a little different, but once he gets it
going he is one of the dominant hitters in the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent eight batters to the plate in the first inning
to take a 2-0 lead. Craig Biggio and Spiers lead off with
consecutive singles, and Bell delivered an RBI single. Everett's
grounder to first base scored Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell hit the second of his four singles to start the third
inning, and Everett followed by sending a pitch from James Baldwin
over the fence in straightaway center field.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin (3-5) allowed seven runs and nine hits in 5 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored an unearned run in the fourth when Astros catcher
Tony Eusebio overthrew Spiers at third while attempting to throw
out Magglio Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put the game out of reach with a four-run sixth.
Bogar snapped a 275-at-bat homerless streak with a solo shot to
right. It was Bogar's first homer since April 16, 1998, against
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me 275 at-bats to regenerate my power,'' Bogar said.
``Don't expect to see another home run for another 275 at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a Biggio walk and a single by Spiers, Bagwell
unloaded a three-run shot to left off reliever Sean Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was positive to get the last two series,'' Bogar
said. ``Ending 6-6, I don't think this team is happy with that, but
we'll take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
