<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS NEED A FAST START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Sparks are eager to show they're an improved
team with the addition of two Yugoslavian national team players and
a defense designed by assistant coach and former Laker Michael
Cooper. They get their chance tonight when they open their third
WNBA season against Sacramento at 7:30 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks released three players Wednesday to reach the
11-player limit. Gone are guard Katrina Colleton, a two-year Sparks
veteran; Eugenia Rycraw, who joined the team last year and center
Tiffani Johnson. Guard Jamila Wideman (knee) and forward-center
Sandra VanEmbriqcs (hamstring) were placed on the injured reserve
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of professional sports is you have to deal with
the cards that are dealt you, and right now the people that are in
(the locker) room, including the people that are coming, we feel
are our best shot to have a very successful team,'' said Sparks
head coach Orlando Woolridge.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian point guard Gordana Grubin was scheduled to arrive
in Los Angeles on Wednesday night and is expected to make an
immediate impact. Woolridge said she could play against the
Monarchs tonight. It's unlikely 6-foot-6 Nina Bjedov, who is
arriving this afternoon, will play.
</P>
<P>
   Both were competing for their national team at the European
Championships, which concluded Sunday. Woolridge expects it will
take about a week before the pair is integrated into the team's
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   As for the remaining nine active players, Woolridge said the
team is ready to start the season. ``I feel good about where we're
at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were a disappointing 12-18 last season and went
through their third coaching change in two years when Woolridge
relieved Julie Rousseau with 10 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well together,'' center Lisa Leslie said. ``We
didn't have good team chemistry. I think right now we have very
good team chemistry, and obviously the pressure is totally off of
us because we aren't expected to do well... and I think that might
be a very good motivator for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge will stick with his starting five from the two
exhibition games, which means rookie Ukari Figgs, who led Purdue to
its first NCAA title in March, will start in her professional
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident with Ukari running the point,'' he said.
``I have to remind myself from time to time that she's a rookie.
She's showing great leadership out there. She's delivering the ball
to people when they need it. She's running the offense, she's
creating the tempo and that's one thing that we want from the
start, ball movement, player movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, who led the Sparks with 19.6 points and 10.2 rebounds
last season, finally has the post help she's needed the past two
seasons to counter the double- and triple-teams. DeLisha Milton and
Clarisse Machanguana, who were selected in the draft, and Bjedov,
once she learns the system, figure to make it tough for opponents
to key on Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   Tamecka Dixon returns to her spot as the shooting guard, and
Allison Feaster, who played only three games after fracturing her
foot in '98, starts at small forward. Both are offensive threats
from beyond the arc. Last season, Dixon shot 42 percent from
3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika, one of the most improved players on the team, is
another threat from the perimeter and should see a lot of minutes
off the bench. Penny Toler, a starter the last two seasons, will
come off the bench and play the point or shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' biggest improvement will be Cooper's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and implemented a defensive plan that is
outstanding,'' said Dixon. ``It's a very aggressive, in-your-face
defense. If we can come out strong defensively, it's going to be
tough to beat us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
