<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ STRIKES OUT AS EXPOS SWEEP UP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-EXPOS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Among his other talents, let it now be said that
Pedro Martinez also can raise the dead. He just couldn't save
himself, or ultimately, the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   With Olympic Stadium transformed from catacomb to discotheque by
the return of Martinez _ who was welcomed back Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night as
if he were Rocket Richard, Jean Beliveau, or Ken Dryden _ the Expos
fed off some of that love Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and hammered the Red
Sox, 13-1, completing a hat trick of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Playing before a Martinez-inspired crowd of 19,012 that was
bigger than the last two gatherings combined, the Expos swept the
three-game set from the Sox, outscoring Boston, 26-4.
</P>
<P>
   They sent the Sox, who were outhit, 14-5, to their fifth
straight defeat, the longest losing streak in more than a year for
the Sons of Jimy Williams. That downturn dropped them into second
place in the American League East, a half-game behind the Yankees,
after a run of 22 days in first place.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Expos and another obscure pitcher, Mike Thurman,
ended a nine-game winning streak for Martinez (11-2), who hadn't
lost since April 15 but was lifted after a yield of four runs and
six hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got to me,'' said Martinez, who struck out 10 before
parting but also gave up more earned runs Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night than he
had in any of his previous dozen starts. ``They played better
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have the ball the next day we play, but I trust
that other guys out there will do their job. I look for them to
pick us up with a good game, help us bounce back, and pick up the
team. Right now we need something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox may want to look somewhere other than the bullpen for
that pick-me-up. Wednesday night, the Expos bounced the Sox back
toward the border with an eight-run eighth inning against three
relievers _ Mark Portugal, Mark Guthrie, and John Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who opted for relief over retirement, pitched 1 1/3
innings Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and allowed five of the last seven batters
he faced to reach safely. Guthrie went double, sacrifice fly,
intentional walk, home run, and single, the home run a tape-measure
number by Expos reliever Guillermo Mota, a converted minor league
shortstop who'd never batted before in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin, who was taken deep in the opener here, gave up a home
run to the first batter he faced Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, Manny Martinez,
a defensive replacement who had one home run in 141 previous
at-bats this season. That makes it four home runs in his last five
appearances for Johnny Waz, which is one way of becoming Johnny Was
very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one person who is going to ride this out for us;
we've got to do it collectively as a team,'' said Mike Stanley,
whose bid for a tying home run in the sixth, when it was still 2-0,
went just foul, and his subsequent try for extra bases a couple of
pitches later was snatched at the wall by Rondell White's leaping
catch in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a disappointment. It's not that we took
them lightly, but we felt we were the better team. To come in here
and get swept like that, I don't think anyone thought that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our butts kicked here, and got embarrassed tonight, but
by the time we land in New York, hopefully we'll have a good offday
then get ready for the Mets. We've got to put this behind us.
There's nothing we can do about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez breezed through the first three innings, striking out
four and allowing just one base runner, Shane Andrews, who walked.
But the veneer of invincibility cracked in the fourth, when Jose
Vidro lined a double to the right-center-field gap to open the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   White bounced a ground-ball single up the middle, scoring Vidro
with the game's first run. Orlando Merced was retired on a tapper
in front of the plate, White advancing to second, and Vladimir
Guerrero, whom Martinez treats like an adopted son, pulled an
outside pitch through the left side for an RBI single to make it
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such long arms,'' Martinez said. ``Someone else
doesn't even reach that pitch. But I've seen him hit a bouncing
breaking ball into center field for a base hit. He's quick and
strong, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Since giving up three runs in the eighth inning against Tampa
Bay in his second start April 10, Martinez had not allowed as many
as two runs in an inning in his next 10 starts, a span of 77 2/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, he did it twice, as the Expos widened their
lead to 4-0 in the sixth. White bounced a one-out single and went
to third as Merced doubled into the right-field corner. Martinez
elected to give an intentional walk to Guerrero, the first he's
issued this season, but rookie catcher Michael Barrett crossed up
that strategy by lining an 0-and-2 pitch into center for a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming,'' Martinez said of Barrett's hit. ``I hung a
breaking ball. I shook off the sign about three times, I wanted to
bounce it out of the strike zone but I didn't. That was a mistake,
and he took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who reached double figures in strikeouts (10) for the
44th time in his career, ninth time this season, and 17th time with
the Sox, was lifted for Portugal at the start of the seventh. It
was just the third time in 13 starts that he has not pitched more
than six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, meanwhile, were held scoreless for 15 consecutive
innings, from the time they scored a first-inning run Tuesday
against rookie Dan Smith until they broke through in the seventh
against Thurman, a 25-year-old righthander who came into
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's game with exactly six big-league wins in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to lose to a team,'' said Martinez, who got a
standing ovation just for showing up, ``I'd rather it be this
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
