<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS' HOMER SPARKS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's not much to do but wait and find out
whether the Dodgers will hit as they should, or pitch as they
should.
</P>
<P>
   So the Dodgers are left to hope for many more instances like the
six-run fourth inning they put up against Texas, which turned into
a face-saving 7-2 Dodgers win against the Rangers on Wednesday
night in front of 46,539 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second most explosive inning for the Dodgers this
season, beaten only by the seven runs they scored in the seventh
inning nearly a month ago at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros had a three-run
homer to left-center to spark the barrage.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown (7-3) increased his team-lead
in wins by working eight innings. He allowed two runs on five hits.
Brown struck out six and walked three. He also improved his record
to 5-1 after a Dodgers loss, retiring the last 10 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time in four starts that Brown defeated
the Rangers, the team that drafted him in the first round (fourth
overall) in 1986. He pitched six full seasons for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers broke a three-game losing streak and finished the
six-game homestand 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (29-29) also moved back to the .500 mark a day after
dropping below it for the first time since April 26 when they were
9-10. Ironically, Brown won on April 27 against Milwaukee to
trigger a season-high five-game winning streak. The Dodgers also
won seven of nine games, beginning with that Brown win.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Eric Young, who homered in the ninth inning to
tie Tuesday's game, had three hits and three RBI. He was also
robbed of first-inning homer by Rangers left fielder Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   Until the offensive outburst in the fourth, the Dodgers were in
jeopardy of facing Texas starters Aaron Sele, Mike Morgan and Mark
Clark and not being in a position to win. That trio entered the
night with a combined 13-12 mark and a 6.42 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Clark rolled through the Dodgers batting order the first time
with ease, striking out four and allowing only a first-inning
single.
</P>
<P>
   The second time through was much different.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield began the assault with a one-out single. Raul
Mondesi walked before Karros hit his eighth homer of the season and
his first since May 27, to give the Dodgers a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Dave Hansen walked and Trenidad Hubbard, who had
three hits in Tuesday's loss, singled to right. Catcher Angel Pena
singled to center to score Hansen. Pena's third RBI of the season
put the Dodgers ahead 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Young singled off third baseman Todd Zeile's glove to score the
final two runs of the inning. Clark (3-5) left after the inning.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to any rally is sustaining the momentum by
shutting the opponent down the next inning, and Brown teetered on
the edge of disaster in the top of the fifth before getting one of
the game's most dangerous hitters out to end a potentially
horrendous inning.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton singled with one out in the fifth and pinch-hitter
Luis Alicea hit a grounds-rule double to put runners on second and
third. Brown got Tom Goodwin to pop up for the second out, but
walked Mark McLemore to load the bases. Rusty Greer singled to
center to break through Brown and make it a 6-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   It also brought reigning American League MVP Juan Gonzalez, who
has 16 homers and 52 RBI, to the plate. But Brown got Gonzalez to
hit into a fielder's choice ground-out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added a run in the sixth inning against reliever
John Burkett, and it was Young who came up with his second straight
two-out hit. Hubbard led off with a single and moved to second on
Brown's bunt. He scored when Young singled to right as the Dodgers
took a 7-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
