<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     06-10 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ Start spreading the news.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Knicks are for real.
</P>
<P>
   The live-on-the-edge Knicks traveled to Market Square Arena on
Wednesday night and whipped the Indiana Pacers 101-94 in Game 5 of
the Eastern Conference finals before 16,541 disappointed fans, most
of whom were busy spreading the boos when the final horn sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, up 3-2 in the best-of-seven series, are on the verge
of advancing to the NBA Finals for the first time since 1994, when
they lost to the Rockets in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just excited about getting to a point where we're
playing to move on,'' said New York coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``That's
all anybody wants to do in any kind of tournament, just try to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're playing against a great team and we're going to
have to play very well to win. But that's how we've been playing
for five games, and I don't think it's going to change now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who squeaked into the playoffs as the eighth-seeded
team, are doing it their way. Which, of course, means the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do they seem more comfortable on the road, winning two
games at Market Square Arena, but the Knicks are having to do it
without perennial All-Star center Patrick Ewing, who will miss the
rest of the playoffs with a torn left Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Van Gundy has gone with a small lineup, starting
6-5 Latrell Sprewell at forward, a move that backfired in Game 4 on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But it paid huge dividends in Wednesday night's game, with
Sprewell erupting for 29 points to lead the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's right there,'' Sprewell said. ``We know it's one
more game and we're in the Finals. We have to play as well as we
did in the fourth quarter tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to (win it Friday), but I'm not going to say we are.
But we're going to come out ready. Like I said, if we come out and
play like we did in the fourth quarter _ move the ball, find the
open guy, make shots and defend _ then we're going to put ourselves
in the position to do just that, finish this series off.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if Larry Johnson plays the way he did in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the clueless Pacers, it was Johnson (again), from the
outside (again), with the 3-pointer (again) doing all the damage
late in the game, scoring 12 of his 17 points in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who won Game 3 with an improbable four-point play,
drilled back-to-back 3-pointers in a span of 49 seconds Wednesday
night to put New York up 89-84 with 2:49 to play, and the Pacers
never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   And they have to be wondering what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the Bulls to seven games in last season's
conference finals, the Pacers thought they would be knocking on
heaven's door this season. Instead, they've been given a few
classes in the school of hard knocks.
</P>
<P>
   Or make that the school of hard Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller scored 30 points for the Pacers but got little
help.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson chipped in 16 points but hit just six of 14 shots
and had only four assists. And Rik Smits, who was saddled with foul
problems (again) in the first half, hit only four of 14 shots to
finish with eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis was the only other Pacer to show up, finishing with
12 points and a game-high 18 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad for us that some guys can talk the talk but they
can't walk it,'' said Indiana coach Larry Bird. ``Some guys didn't
show up tonight, and that's very disappointing. Disappointing for
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to be even more distressing that New York refused to
fold, despite falling behind by 14 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, Marcus Camby (21 points, 13 rebounds), Johnson (15
second-half points) and Allan Houston (19 points, 15 in the second
half) brought the Knicks back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' Camby said. ``Considering where we started
and where we are now, this is really great. We were a bunch of guys
who really didn't know each other, but now we're here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just one more game to go to the Finals; it's what
we've all dreamed about. We just have to make the best of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like they did Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   How crucial is the fifth game in the conference finals? Put it
this way _ the winner almost always moves on to the next round _
with one memorable exception.
</P>
<P>
   During this decade, 11 conference finals have been tied 2-2, and
the winner of Game 5 has gone on to win 10 of those series. The
exception was the 1994 Eastern Conference finals between the Knicks
and Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana won Game 5 at Madison Square Garden _ the night Miller
scored 25 of his 39 points in the fourth quarter _ to take a 3-2
series lead. But the Knicks took the last two games to move on to
play the Rockets in the 1994 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Pacers went up by six points moments into
the fourth quarter, but the Knicks kept plugging away until they
finally came back and took the lead at 78-77 on Johnson's nine-foot
baseline jumper with 7:10 to play.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson, who saved the Knicks with his four-point play to
end Game 3, would be the hero again for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson bombed in the first of his 3-pointers with 3:38 left to
put the Knicks up 86-82, then came back after a Smits jumper to
bury another, putting New York up 89-84 with 2:49 to play.
</P>
<P>
   The shot appeared to take the life out of the Pacers, even
though Miller dropped in a long 3-pointer with 1:59 left to pull
Indiana to within 91-87.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks managed to keep them at arm's length, running out
much of the rest of the game at the free-throw line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
