<HEADER>
A9840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-PHILLIES-NY     06-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH PHILLIES, 11-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A player lowered his voice in the New York
Yankees' clubhouse here on Wednesday and asked a question that will
gain relevance if this team retains its current mediocrity for much
longer: ``What does George think?''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, watched
Wednesday night's game from the stands at Veterans Stadium, a frown
carved into his face until his players blew open a tense contest
with eight runs in the sixth inning of an 11-5 victory. The Yankees
(33-24) snapped a three-game losing streak and moved into first
place in the American League East, a half-game ahead of Boston,
which lost its fifth consecutive game, in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Yankees' first victory against the Phillies here
since Game 2 of the 1950 World Series. Swept here in 1997, the
Yankees managed to avert another three-game sweep on Wednesday
night chiefly because Tino Martinez banged a three-run homer and
David Cone pitched five and two-thirds innings in gaining his sixth
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Their timing could not have been better, with Steinbrenner
staring them down from his seat behind the Philadelphia dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just keep playing good ball, we're going to wind up in a
good position,'' said Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner mostly has avoided reporters since Darryl
Strawberry's arrest in April, but others in the organization say
there are days when his unhappiness is profound. The Yankee players
are finally coming to grips with the fact they won't be as good as
they were in 1998 _ ``It's official,'' Paul O'Neill said Tuesday _
but there's no assurance Steinbrenner feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (6-2) has been the Yankees' best pitcher this season and
and he has great credibility with Steinbrenner. Martinez's home run
staked him to a 3-1 lead in the fourth, but in the bottom of the
fifth, Cone threw 41 pitches gave up two runs after there were two
out, forcing home the tying run by allowing a bases-loaded walk to
Scott Rolen.
</P>
<P>
   Rico Brogna smashed a line drive toward right field, a would-be
single, a two-run hit in the making but second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch reached high over his head to snag the liner.
Steinbrenner glared ominously.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Ogea the Phillies' starter, had run the bases during the
rally, and right away, he was in trouble in the top of the sixth.
Derek Jeter led off with a single and stole second, and the Yankees
were on parade: Bernie Williams singled and Martinez walked and
after a pitching change, O'Neill lined a two-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius singled and Knoblauch added his second hit of the
game. After Joe Girardi whiffed for the first out of the inning,
Cone lined a ground-rule double to left, his first regular-season
hit since he as with the Mets in 1992. (Cone later joked with
Girardi that the pitcher should have batted eighth, Girardi ninth).
</P>
<P>
   And on and on it went. In Tuesday's loss, Philadelphia sent 13
batters to the plate and scored 9 runs; on Wednesday night, the
Yankees sent 13 batters to the plate and scored 8 runs. ``It was
huge,'' said Cone.
</P>
<P>
   All of the players involved in Manager Joe Torre's lineup
changes fared well the last two days. Knoblauch has been a markedly
different player since he was shifted from the lead-off spot to the
bottom of the batting order. Often unaggressive on the bases this
season, Knoblauch extended his usual lead off first base after
reaching base three times tonight, and he broke from first
repeatedly, even stole second.
</P>
<P>
   When Cone bounced his double into the stands in the sixth
inning, Knoblauch kept running and running until the third base
coach Willie Randolph stopped him. In Monday's game, Knoblauch
slowed up on a similar play, earning Torre's anger.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch also has had several great plays on defense in the
last two days and Torre expects to restore him to the top of the
lineup in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill dropped from third to fifth in the lineup had two hits
on Tuesday and drove in two runs on Wednesday night. Martinez,
moving from the No. 5 spot to cleanup, has hit home runs in both
games and Williams has had three hits from the No. 3 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to shake things up,'' said Martinez, ``and get
everybody to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   By the seventh inning, Steinbrenner was laughing out loud,
joking with friends, and when the Phillie Phanatic approached the
Yankee owner, Steinbrenner grinned and played along. Good thing,
for the mascot's sake, the Yankees were winning big.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
