<HEADER>
A9842 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORPORATION-WEST-AZR &LR;      06-10 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATION-WEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OUSTS WEST FROM CORPORATION COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A divided Arizona Supreme Court booted Tony West from
the powerful Arizona Corporation Commission on Wednesday after
finding West illegally held a securities sales license when he was
elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's 3-2 vote will not affect any of the key utility
rulings West made during the past five months, including his swing
votes on electrical deregulation and long-distance phone service.
</P>
<P>
   West, a former two-term Republican state treasurer and 16-year
member of the Legislature, declined to comment on the Supreme
Court's action. His attorney, Tom Irvine, said the 3-2 decision
could not be appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is disappointed,'' Irvine said. ``But he's looking forward
to going back into private life.''
</P>
<P>
   West's predecessor, Renz Jennings, the only Democrat on the
three-member regulatory panel, will return from retirement on a
south Phoenix farm until Gov. Jane Hull appoints a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's appointee will serve until the November 2000 general
election, when Arizona voters will pick someone to fill out the
remaining four years of West's six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings complained about West to the Supreme Court after fellow
Democrat Paul Newman was narrowly defeated by West in the Nov. 3
general election.
</P>
<P>
   The law was discovered when West asked the commission's
securities staff in December to help him avoid any conflict between
selling securities and regulating the financial industry. When told
there was no way, West surrendered the license.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not solve West's problem, Justices Charles Jones,
Thomas Zlaket and Stanley Feldman said in a 49-page opinion:
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the election, West was a registered securities
salesperson licensed to a registered securities dealer. Both West
and the dealer were subject to regulation by the commission. Under
the plain language of the statute, he was not eligible to be
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Frederick Martone and Ruth McGregor dissented.
</P>
<P>
   ``West ran for public office and won,'' they said. ``It was not
until then that his opponent raised this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . it is so plainly unjust to remove an elected official
under these circumstances,'' Martone and McGregor said.
</P>
<P>
   But, the majority said, allowing West to serve would permit all
three commissioners to sell securities while regulating their
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises the specter of enormous conflicts,'' the majority
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Ching, attorney for Jennings, called the decision a
``historic event,'' noting that no other elected state officer had
been ousted by the Arizona Supreme Court since the state's first
governor, George W.P. Hunt, was removed temporarily in a dispute
over balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, a fellow Republican who served with West in the
Legislature, thanked him for 24 years of service as an elected
representative. Early in the election controversy, West predicted
that Hull would appoint him to the commission if he lost the court
case, but he later asked the governor not to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to name a Republican replacement as soon as
possible,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   She did not comment on speculation that possible candidates
include Pima County Supervisor Mike Boyd, former state senator and
now Pima County Superior Court Clerk Patti Noland, and former Rep.
David Schweikert, R-Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said the Supreme Court was correct in siding with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the statute was just crystal clear,'' he said. ``My
service extends until my successor qualifies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings added that ``things look pretty bad for Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings referred to an Attorney General's inquiry into alleged
securities deals West attempted to make with investment bankers
handling state funds while he was state treasurer over the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   West has repeatedly refused to discuss those dealings.
</P>
<P>
   One of those deals was revealed by ``The Arizona Republic'' on
Feb. 22, when the Supreme Court heard arguments about West's
illegal election.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said he plans to show up Thursday at the commission,
barring an unforeseen move by Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go there and do what needs to be done until she makes the
reappointment,'' Jennings said. ``I know where everything is.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes several boxes of documents taken home from his
commission office when Jennings completed his final six-year term
in January. Attorney General's investigators seized the materials
when West complained that they had been removed improperly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they'll bring them back,'' Jennings said. ``I've asked
my lawyers to ask them to return the boxes. I assume they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings will serve with two Republicans: Chairman Carl Kunasek,
whose term ends in 2000, and Jim Irvin, whose term ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, we wish Tony the best,'' Irvin said. ``Number Two, I
certainly concur with the court decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over West's election capped several years of
turmoil and personnel turnover at the commission. The high court's
decision, and the governor's appointment should add stability,
Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on whom the governor appoints,'' Irvin
added. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
