<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-1STLE     06-10 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-1STLEAD-WRITEHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS BEING SHOWN GLIMPSE OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CHANGES throughout)  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ As he was about to shoot and make a free throw to
seal Game 5, Latrell Sprewell was hit with a barrage of chants from
the less-than-tactful Market Square Arena crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choke! Choke! Choke!'' the crowd yelled, an obvious reference
to the incident that led to Sprewell's exile from pro basketball
last season.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the court, Marcus Camby had barely rejected
his sixth shot of the night when a fan began yelling, ``We know you
got paid in college,'' another tasteless reference to a Knick
player's past.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment from the crowd was understandable in some ways. So
frustrated with the aging Indiana Pacers, who never seem to clear
the last hurdle, they watched the players of the next millennium in
the Eastern Conference go by their team in a blur.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, Camby and Larry Johnson not only fought the most
diverse offensive unit in the league Wednesday night, they seized
the most important game of the Knicks' season.
</P>
<P>
   Future 101, Past 94.
</P>
<P>
   ``That young man has such a gift,'' Chris Childs said about
Camby after the lithe 7-footer pinned the Pacers against the glass
to give the Knicks a 3-2 advantage in the best-of-7-game series.
``He might not even know how good he is yet, but it's such a
pleasure to play with him. People questioned his heart, his
toughness. Marcus answered all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell did too. He jackknifed in the air, scored 29 points and
drew so much attention that someone had to be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it is right there,'' Sprewell said, referring to the
finals. ``We're going to come out ready Friday. I'd like to do it
for our fans at home. I'd like to finish Indiana off there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the between-game adjustments were made _ before Jeff Van
Gundy went back to his film room and chalkboard for Game 5 _ Reggie
Miller had made an analogy for how difficult it is to match up with
his team, all the diverse weaponry at the disposal of the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys it's like an overflowing dam,'' Miller said.''
The water is getting to the top, the dam is going to burst. And
when it does, there'll be a flood.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie finally broke through, but there was no onrushing tsunami
from the Pacers. Sprewell, Camby and Johnson fixed the leaks and
propelled the Knicks one game away from their first finals
appearance in five years.
</P>
<P>
   In a clutch performance befitting the Eastern Conference finals,
they played through unseemly actions by the crowd, a miserable
first quarter and all the distractions a playoff game might merit.
</P>
<P>
   They became the answers to every question the Pacers had posed
in Game 4, fighting the might and muscle of Indiana with their long
arms and arching jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, battling a head cold, went to the basket with a fury
and a passion unseen in Game 4. He ended with 29 points on 8-of-19
shooting, silencing his detractors (including this one), who took
issue with his adjustment as a starter in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Camby? What else can be said about this gifted player who
frustrated Rik Smits, pinned a Miller layup against the glass and
would not quit even after the game had been decided. His sixth
block came with four seconds left, a rejection of Sam Perkins along
the right baseline. Twenty-one points, 13 rebounds. Awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys played me hard and banged me,'' Camby said, ``but I
just wanted to win so bad and go up, 3-2. When we started off the
season, no one thought we would be where we are now. Just the
opportunity to go to the finals is a dream come true for most of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had been waiting for Johnson to emerge since his Game
3 miracle four-point play, and you wondered if that was possible
after his passive performance on Monday night at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he did as much as anyone on the roster to give the Knicks a
chance to end the series at home Friday, knocking down the most
crucial, back-to-back 3-pointers with less than four minutes _
daggers from the right wing that put the Knicks ahead by four and
five points.
</P>
<P>
   Miller finally broke through Wednesday night, finding his range,
his points (30) and his complete game. He went back to being the
Reggie New York knows and hates.
</P>
<P>
   But these young guns who like to run and have fun were too much
for the veteran and his graying team.
</P>
<P>
   There is a thought circulating around the league that San
Antonio's front line and overall depth will be too strong for
anyone coming out of the Eastern Conference. Well rested and
clicking as well as they have all season, the Spurs seem to have
every imaginable advantage headed into the league championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it remains to be seen if they have the heart of the Knicks,
a group of players that won't die, a team on the brink of going
where no one outside that locker room dreamed they would go; the
league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about their five-game war with Miami. If the Knicks can
somehow find a way to get out of this round, they will have dodged
the most lethal bullet in the post-season. Tim Duncan and David
Robinson are awesome in their own right, but the Spurs don't have
the backcourt to match up with Sprewell and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After weathering a gantlet in Indiana, San Antonio would be a
piece of cake. It's not over yet. But when Johnson talks about
being on a float cruising down Broadway in a couple of weeks, you
get the sense they are impossibly close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
