<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERLY LOVE, BUT ALSO LUMPS, FOR MARINER PITCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Jordan Zimmerman knew he was going to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, after the Mariners had beaten the Colorado
Rockies, the clubhouse TVs were showing the Texas Rangers' game in
Los Angeles. Jeff Zimmerman was pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants him to do bad because we're in such a rivalry
with them,'' said Jordan Zimmerman, the Mariners' left-hander. ``A
lot of guys were joking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman pitched a shutout inning that night, then
followed with two more Tuesday to run his record to 6-0. The
Rangers right-hander leads all American League relievers with a
1.15 earned-run average and only Anaheim's Troy Percival has held
batters to a lower average than Zimmerman's .116. He has thrown 39
innings, sixth in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Jordan buys a newspaper, he flips immediately to the
box scores to see if his brother pitched the night before. He's
rarely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's doing it, but I don't know how his arm's holding
up,'' said Jordan. ``He's throwing one or two innings almost every
single day. I guess the more you do it, the stronger you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jordan can relate. He has worked only 42/3 innings in
eight games since being called up from Class AA New Haven on May
16. But with John Halama solidifying his place in the rotation,
Zimmerman is the lone lefty in the M's bullpen. He figures to be
with the team when the Rangers come to town to close out the
Kingdome on June 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 family members and friends will be on hand, many coming
down from the Zimmermans' hometown of Kelowna, B.C. It will be the
first time the brothers have played against each other, and an
especially proud moment for their father, Bill, who is recovering
from lymphoma after spending five months in a coma last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Zimmerman filmed an interview with ESPN Wenesday, in a
piece to run on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   SOUVENIR ... SORT OF: Ken Cloude reached for the baseball, still
tucked in his glove in the back of his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'll do with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Tom Lampkin gave Cloude the ball after Tuesday night's
save, the first of Cloude's professional career. Cloude had been
passed over in favor of Frankie Rodriguez for the start Tuesday,
but came on for four relief innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude said his goal is to be a starting pitcher, which is the
role he prefers. But his statistics work against him. In four
outings as a starter, Cloude is 0-2 with a 14.14 earned-run average
and .441 opponents' average. In nine relief appearances, he is 3-0
with a 2.49 ERA and .205 opponents' average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, I don't have a choice,'' Cloude said.
``I've struggled starting, and I've really done nothing to show I
deserve to pitch every fifth day. But at the same time, I know I
can get guys out and make a contribution to the team. If it means
pitching in the bullpen, that's fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE OF THE GUYS: Before Wednesday night's game, each Mariner had
a flier for Thursday's annual Cystic Fibrosis Golf Tournament at
his locker. This prompted several Mariners to try their swings _
including outfielder Raul Ibanez, who got some serious ribbing for
his front-leg kick that accompanied an ugly stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But Ibanez will take the insults, and give them back. He
re-joined the team this road trip after a week-long injury rehab at
Class AAA Tacoma, which, in his words, is ``a nice play to visit,
but you don't want to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when you could be in the majors, he meant. Ibanez's roster
spot is fairly secure _ he serves an important role as an emergency
catcher and solid left-handed pinch-hitter, and he's out of
options, meaning he can't be sent to the minors without first
clearing waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners think highly of Ibanez, who likely would be
claimed. He shuttled between Tacoma and Seattle for three seasons
before '99, and he's enjoying staying in one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge difference in your state of mind,'' Ibanez
said. ``You feel a lot more comfortable up here knowing you're not
going to be going back down. You can be a part of the team, blend
in well. It's easier to have fun with the guys and mess around when
you know you're going to stay here. That's definitely nice.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Outfielder Butch Huskey wouldn't mind if the
Mariners set the all-time record for home runs in a season. ``That
would be better than the last time I was a part of history,''
Huskey said. His current distinction? Huskey is one of only three
players to make his major league debut in a no-hitter. He was
0-for-3 with three strikeouts on Sept. 8, 1993, as then-Houston
Astros pitcher Darryl Kile no-hit the New York Mets. ...
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. tried on a Shannon Sharpe jersey
given to him by the Denver Broncos tight end before Wednesday
night's game. Griffey had given Sharpe a jersey, bat and batting
gloves when the Broncos were honored at Coors Field Tuesday. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will be collecting non-perishable food items and
monetary donations for Fight Hunger Day Friday at the Kingdome.
</P>
</TEXT>
