<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TOP BLUE JAY, 4-3, IN EXTRA INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets lost Benny Agbayani to a freakish injury in
batting practice on Wednesday, but they didn't need him on
Wednesday night as they staged a stunning comeback for their fourth
consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied for three ninth-inning runs that were charged
to David Wells to force extra innings. Then Rey Ordonez lofted a
fly-ball single over a drawn-in outfield with one out in the 14th
inning to drive home the winning run early on Thursday morning in a
4-3 triumph over Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that did Mets Manager Bobby Valentine grudgingly
admit there have been more problems with Bobby Bonilla, who has
been benched since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to say he wasn't available,'' Valentine said
when asked why he did not use Bonilla on Wednesday night.
``Yesterday, he was asked to pinch-hit and he couldn't. I was told
today it was the same situation. I'm very confused.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bonilla was not talking. ``I have nothing to say,
to be honest with you. I'm not going anywhere that I know of. But
I'm not volunteering any information.''
</P>
<P>
   Most perplexing of all was General Manager Steve Phillips'
response. Before the game, Phillips was asked if having a
disgruntled Bonilla around the clubhouse could turn problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem unless it becomes a problem,'' Phillips
said. Is it a problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Phillips said then.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the same question was posed to Phillips. ``I have no
comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The night began with a ball hit by Agbayani, the Mets' budding
folk hero, ricocheting off the corner of the batting cage during
batting practice and bouncing back into Agbayani's face, leaving
him with considerable swelling under his right eye. The night ended
with the remnants of the fans at Shea Stadium cheering news of the
Knicks' victory in Indiana and then the Mets' final rally.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time it was over, Valentine who had been ejected for
arguing a catcher's interference call in the top of the 12th
inning, was peering out from the dugout entrance disguised in a
fake mustache, sunglasses and a non-Mets cap.
</P>
<P>
   The way Wells was throwing over the first eight innings, it was
debatable how much Agbayani would have helped anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells tired after carrying a shutout into the ninth. The
Mets, who were behind by 3-0, staged a dramatic rally in their
final at-bat against a pitcher they may covet. After Robin Ventura
singled home two runs with two outs, after fouling off four
consecutive pitches, not only was the shutout gone, so was Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Three pitches later, Brian McRae smacked a double off Billy Koch
into the left field corner to score pinch-runner Luis Lopez with
the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez and McRae drew walks off Thomas Davey to open the Mets'
14th, and then Roger Cedeno laid down a two-strike sacrifice bunt
against Dan Plesac. One pitch later, Ordonez launched his single to
left to score Lopez easily.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback was reminiscent of one on May 23, when the Mets
rallied for five runs in the bottom of the ninth against
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling to wipe out a 4-0 deficit. Wednesday
night's turnaround was similarly stunning, considering that Wells
had thoroughly outpitched Rick Reed, who allowed 10 hits, 2 home
runs and 3 earned runs in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was an out away from his first complete game of the season
and Reed was an out away from losing his third consecutive start.
The Mets were that close to losing for the first time since
Phillips dismissed three of Valentine's coaches late Saturday night
on the heels of a season-worst eight-game losing streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
