</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENYING FRESHMAN ELIGIBILITY FALLS SHORT OF GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gotta hand it to the NCAA. Once college basketball's governors
see the horse has left the barn, gone to the neighbor's pasture and
found a filly, raised young 'uns and won the Kentucky Derby, the
NCAA slams the door shut.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1972, the NCAA is considering making
freshmen ineligible for men's hoops. In the history of overdue
actions, this one ranks up there with today's delivery of a
baby-names book to George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Something called the Division I Working Group to Study
Basketball Issues is considering recommending that players be
barred from competition for the first year so that they can adjust
to college.
</P>
<P>
   It would be gratifying to know that the NCAA is moved to such
worthy action based on noble principles. But like most
self-satisfied bureaucracies, it is forced to act out of pure
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The graduation rate in men's basketball is 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how easy it is at most schools to graduate when the
student is a 6-foot-7 dunker who can drain the trey, the fact only
41 percent make it is altogether remarkable. Normally a mere
six-point scoring average is enough to get a C in medieval European
history.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem with the graduation rate is not that
competing freshmen become maladjusted students. The problem is that
a growing number of freshmen quit to go pro or transfer to another
school, but their departures count as a failure against the
original school's graduation count.
</P>
<P>
   For each NBA draft, the list of underclassmen leaving college
early seems to grow. This spring had a first: The lordly Duke
program, which had never been victimized by the NBA plunderers, not
only lost sophomore Elton Brand, NCAA player of the year, but a kid
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Too many high school players, full of the patronizing platitudes
of street agents, shoe-company reps and gold-digging friends and
relatives, are fooled into regarding college as a one- or two-year
stop on the way to swooping with Kobe Bryant on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   They are oblivious to the fact that 99.5 percent of the
scholarship men's basketball players in Division I in any one year
will never play a minute in the NBA. Unfortunately, the same 99.5
percent believe they will make it.
</P>
<P>
   Since there's neither an accounting nor a remedy for this
breathtaking foolishness, the NCAA has decided not to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   By barring freshmen eligibility, the NCAA tacitly adds another
significant reason for some high school kids to skip college and
try the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should not be a primary consideration,'' said Jim Delany,
Big Ten commissioner, said. ``Those players are not going to be (in
school) very long anyway. At the end of the day, that's not an NCAA
problem. That's a problem for the NBA Players Association.''
</P>
<P>
   However callous that sounds, he's right. Any rule or custom that
helps destroy the myth that athletes must go to college before
attempting professional athletics is worthy of immediate adoption.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. is virtually the only country in the world to
perpetuate this preposterous system. Throughout Europe, Latin
America and Asia, talented athletes are directed to athletic
academies and clubs, and get schooled on the side. Students, on the
other hand, are directed to college, and play sports on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Barring freshmen eligibility doesn't represent the dawn of
enlightenment in college athletics. Nor does the fact that the NCAA
sees the rule as a cheap way to improve its embarrassing graduation
rates eliminate virtue from the maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   If implemented, the plan at least filters out some kids who
would be wasting time and resources, while possibly giving others
more interested in the other benefits of college a shot at a richer
experience.
</P>
<P>
   A kid willing to sit out a year of ball gets a shot to find out
if he's college material. If he is, the incentive is greater to
pursue a degree. Obviously, there's no guarantee the kid won't quit
early, but the decision at least becomes harder.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's work is far from done, and undoubtedly will face
opposition from many coaches. So it may recommend something less
radical: Ineligibility for only the first term of the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one term is very appropriate,'' said Barbara Hedges,
the University of Washington athletic director and committee
member. ``I think that provides time to adjust to college and
campus. I just have not believed that a full year is absolutely
necessary. In basketball, unlike football, the student has time to
get used to things before the season begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said most of the committee started out with a similar
sentiment, but the full year is gaining support. Chief persuader
has been committee member Dean Smith, the retired North Carolina
coaching legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dean is very much in favor of the full year,'' she said.
``He's seen it both ways, and brought a wonderful perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   To college basketball fans who might feel cheated by missing out
on freshmen, I would recommend checking them out on the nearest NBA
team. True, it's a little more expensive, but as was learned this
season, bad basketball isn't cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 0207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS     06-10 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ASSUME CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ By the end of the night, Larry Johnson was
calling himself a 3-point shooter. ``I'm not saying I'm Allan
Houston,'' the New York forward said, ``but I can hit 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to disagree with him. You can ask Larry Bird and his
Indiana Pacers about that. They are in the Eastern Conference
finals against the Knicks, which is a matchup they wanted. But they
are on the verge of losing this best-of-seven series following
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's stunning 101-94 loss to the Knicks in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The Knicks are one game away from playing against
the Spurs for the NBA championship. They are in that position for
several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   You can point to Johnson's two wide-open 3-pointers _ less than
a minute apart in the fourth quarter _ directly in front of the
Indiana bench.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can talk about Marcus Camby's 21 points, 13 rebounds, and
6 blocked shots. ``He dominated the game tonight,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget about Latrell Sprewell's 29 points (and 13 of 14
from the line).
</P>
<P>
   And as you absorb all that, remember this about the Knicks: they
would be the first No. 8 seed in league history to play in the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   What is this?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one-game season now,'' Indiana's Reggie Miller said.
``We've got to get a win.'' If the Pacers don't win, they come back
here to be serenaded by their fans. It will be far worse than the
random boos that echoed through Market Square Arena in the final
minute Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, when it was obvious the Pacers would lose.
</P>
<P>
   Fans here had to hear how the Pacers had an advantage by working
out together during the lockout. They heard players talk about
winning the championship, especially with the retirement of Michael
Jordan. They certainly don't want to see guys named Sprewell,
Camby, and Van Gundy win the title at their expense.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is speculation until tomorrow night in New York,
when Game 6 will be played at Madison Square Garden. But the
results won't be any different if the Pacers can't find a way to
guard Johnson. The forward made the two biggest shots of the night
_ 3-pointers with 3:38 and 2:49 remaining _ to put New York ahead
for good. Camby followed Johnson's three with a layup and the New
Yorkers in the building, waving orange towels behind the team's
bench, knew they were going back to Manhattan with a 3-2 series
lead.
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly a shocker for the fans at Market Square. Late
in the fourth, the marketing department showed a clip of
``Hoosiers'' in the Hoosier State to inspire the crowd. It worked.
But the crowd didn't have to guard Johnson. For that matter,
neither did any Pacer. Actually, focusing on Johnson is the easy
part. If you dare look at the larger picture, you'll see that the
Pacers allowed the Knicks to score 36 fourth-quarter points, 1 shy
of the most the Pacers have ever allowed in one quarter in their
playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not very pleased with our defense,'' said Bird, who
looked disgusted after Johnson's second three went down. ``We
worked on playing decent defense, but it collapsed at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the night is that Miller, who had been the subject
of much analysis over his departed shot, scored 30 points. When
told that, he shrugged and said, ``I'd rather have the 12 I had in
New York and win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the irony of Johnson, too. If you polled 100 Knicks
fans before the season, 90 would have begged you to take Johnson
and his outrageous contract off the team's books. The man known as
LJ is not suddenly as beloved as Walt Frazier was in the 1970s, but
he is gaining a reputation as a clutch player.
</P>
<P>
   Making the story even crazier is that Patrick Ewing watched all
of this from the bench. He is out of the playoffs with a torn
Achilles'. And, as you can imagine, his team's run without him will
certainly stoke the ``We don't need Patrick'' cries in the
offseason. But no one is thinking about that now. The Knicks
watched the Pacers score the first 9 points of the game, then
watched a 19-4 Indiana run for a 28-14 deficit. Yet, they won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like an impossible dream two months ago,'' veteran
forward Herb Williams said. ``We've proven to be a pretty good team
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Camby's layup that made it 91-84, Miller made a three
of his own with 1:59 left. But the Pacers wouldn't get any closer
than 4 points the rest of the night. They got their points from
Miller and 18 rebounds from Dale Davis. That was irrelevant by the
end of the night. They wanted to play defense and they wanted to
win. They could do neither. They are now 48 minutes away from being
knocked out of the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
