<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1ST     06-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS RIDE SPREWELL AND CAMBY TO TAKE 3-2 SERIES LEAD OVER
PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CHANGES throughout) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There was a driving layup by Latrell Sprewell
that glanced off the rim and hung in the air like a bubble. The
ball was right there, for anyone who wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Marcus Camby cut a diagonal across the lane and
soared above the paint as if on a magic carpet ride. If he was,
there was room on it for the whole team as he took Sprewell's miss
and turned it into an emphatic dunk that provided the New York
Knicks with a lead they would embrace for the final six minutes of
their 101-94 victory over the Indiana Pacers in Game 5 of the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the drama of this tense night ended did Camby throw a
fist in the air against a background of emptying seats at a silent
Market Square Arena. Those fans remaining were in disbelief. But
the improbable has become a habit for this team. The resilient
Knicks are one victory away from advancing to the NBA finals
against the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're close,'' Camby said. ``Just to have the opportunity to
be one win from the finals, it's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 3-2 lead in this best-of-7-game series, the Knicks will
play Game 6 at Madison Square Garden on Friday night. Camby put
them in this position. He finished the night with 21 points, six
blocked shots and 13 rebounds off the bench and provided the kind
of energy that transferred to the rest of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the bounty wasn't big enough,'' coach Larry Bird said,
referring to the description coach Jeff Van Gundy used to describe
the physical play against Camby he expected from the Pacers. ``He
gets better every time we play. We want to keep a body on him but
we can't seem to find him.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Camby was everywhere. His dunk with 5 minutes 55
seconds left in the game gave the Knicks an 81-80 lead. The Knicks
then clamped down on defense and came up with a stream of big shots
_ which included back-to-back 3-pointers by Larry Johnson near the
3-minute mark _ to keep their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't of the miracle variety, but Johnson's long-range
accuracy was almost as uncanny as the ones he nailed to give the
Knicks Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a 3-point shooter,'' Johnson said.
``But I can hit them. As you can see, I can hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell fed Johnson for one of those shots. After being
invisible for most of this series, Sprewell came out of the chute
firing away. If he missed, he didn't care. He just kept coming and
thriving on the fast break on his way to 29 points. Beside him, the
previously quiet Allan Houston also caught fire in the second half
and finished with 19 points. That effort countered the Pacers'
Reggie Miller, who broke out of his shell with 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's right there for us,'' Sprewell said. ``We have to
win one more game and we're there. To do it, we have to play like
we did in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Knicks overcame a five-point deficit with 10
minutes left by shooting 10 for 15 from the field while the Pacers
were 9 for 20. Camby had four rebounds, while Johnson scored 12 of
his 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry's 3's were huge,'' Van Gundy said. ``Sometimes it comes
down to misses or makes. And we made tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, it seemed Miller was going to lead his team to
victory. The Pacers had a 14-point lead after the first quarter but
the Knicks hung in and stayed close. They were within six points
early in the fourth quarter. Houston came through and delivered a
flurry of baskets, but it was Camby who kept the chances alive with
rebounds, tips and blocked shots. This from a player who couldn't
get time on the floor early in the season, but persevered and
gained the trust of Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see where we started off, and to see where we are now, it's
a great feeling,'' Camby said. ``Everyone was writing us off. We've
come a long way to be this close to a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   That dream is so close to becoming a reality. But home court has
meant little in this series. The Pacers took Game 5 at the Garden
with a 12-point victory. Undaunted, the Knicks came right back and
weathered whatever runs the Pacers had in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played in spurts tonight,'' Mark Jackson said. ``You can't
do that. They were on a roll and kept us from doing things we
wanted to do. This is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that far. The Knicks will have the energy, emotion and drive
from their home crowd on Friday night. But they'll also need the
kind of results they got Wednesday night. Both Sprewell and Houston
clicked together and combined to score 48 points on 15 for 36
shooting and got to the free-throw line 20 times by being
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were also able to hold the Pacers to 41 percent from
the field, which allowed them to get some easy baskets in
transition off missed shots.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were in foul trouble early, they played smart and
kept their main players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Camby produced in the crunch and came up with the dunk off the
Sprewell miss that allowed the Knicks a chance to never look back.
If they work it right, they won't have to come back to Market
Square Arena again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about coming back here; it's about getting to the
finals,'' Van Gundy said. ``Obviously, you want to come out and
advance. The other team has to have something to do with it, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
