</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCKED PACERS LAMENTING ANOTHER BLOWN OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Indiana Pacers slunk out of their own gym on
Wednesday night, amazingly unnoticed by what remained of their
fans, who were preoccupied with booing the jubilant New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Just 24 hours before Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals,
the Pacers had stood in Market Square Arena after a practice and
spoke of a renewed confidence now that the series was tied and the
home-court advantage was theirs again. But on Wednesday night, that
ebullience had evaporated, sucked up by the shock of a 101-94
Knicks victory that puts them one victory from the National
Basketball Association finals. Game 6 is Friday night at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After opening a 14-point lead in the second quarter, the fizz
went out of the Pacers as quickly as a bottle of champagne bereft
of its cork. Inexplicably, they looked worn and frazzled, like a
team that in the course of the second half had aged several years _
several years too long for them to make a run at a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed right now,'' a subdued Mark Jackson said in
an utterly silent locker room. ``We had them were we wanted them.
We jumped out and played great. It's incredible how the mood swings
this deep in the playoffs. We're hurt right now, but this is far
from over. The mood right now is disappointment, but that's because
we lost, right now, the biggest game of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because we had the opportunity to take care
of business at home and we didn't do it twice. We're a team that
lives dangerously. I don't know why. I wish I knew why. We didn't
put them away when we had a chance. But it's not over. I'll be on
the plane with everyone else going back to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had as few answers for what went wrong as they did
for the Knicks' firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby confounded them all over the place and Larry
Johnson fried them with two fourth-quarter 3-pointers. While Dale
Davis had 12 points and 18 rebounds, and Reggie Miller finally
unleashed his shot for 30 points, the Pacers got little else from
anyone. They had only one assist in the critical third quarter, an
astoundingly small number for a team that passes the ball with ease
and skill.
</P>
<P>
   Their feet seemed stuck in quicksand, every movement clumsy and
ill timed. The heroes who had saved them in Game 4 virtually
disappeared. Jalen Rose had just 6 points. Chris Mullin, who
outplayed Latrell Sprewell in Game 4, had 13 points, but they were
quiet. And he was matched up frequently against Camby, who was as
energetic as the Pacers were lethargic. The Pacers gave up 36
points in the fourth quarter and let the Knicks shoot 66.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss in Game 3, Davis had lamented the lost
opportunity to put the Knicks in a 3-1 hole. Before Game 5, he was
sure the Pacers would not let such a chance slip away again.
Afterward, he dressed, shook his head when he was asked for a
theory of what went wrong. ``We just had too many breakdowns at
critical points,'' Davis said. ``We let a good opportunity go to
waste once again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We became too predictable,'' was how Rose described it. ``Any
time that happens, it's tough to win. They took it to us. They knew
the calls we were running and they did a good job of calling them
out. It was a game we felt we were going to play with intensity.
You can't excuse it, that's why we're in the losing locker room.
Now it's do or die. We've got to win with heart, with character,
the things we had throughout the season. But none of that matters
if we don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   They will have to win under the most trying circumstances. As
confident and relaxed as the Pacers seemed after Game 4, the Knicks
will surely be even more confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never lost two at home and had to go somewhere else with
our back to their wall,'' Miller said. ``But we've got to play much
better than we did tonight. For us, it's a one- game season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
