<HEADER>
A9886 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     06-10 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS OFFENSE WAKES UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The optimism permeates the Dodgers these days
because they are looking to extend on anything positive.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the Dodgers' 7-2 win against the Texas Rangers on
Wednesday at Dodger Stadium seems like any other idle win in a
frustrating two months of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet breaking a three-game losing streak gave some of the players
a different feeling than other wins this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``We needed something to happen to break the tension. Maybe tonight
was the night. I haven't said that a lot, but I'm saying that
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored six runs in the fourth inning, their
second-most productive one-inning output of the season. Eric Karros
hit a three-run homer, slumping Eric Young had three hits and three
RBI, the Dodgers got out to a big lead and Kevin Brown was
impressive and sound in beating another of his former employers.
</P>
<P>
   Those are important ingredients that some are taking stock in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win, it's big,'' said Dave Hansen, who started at third
and walked in the crucial fourth inning. ``I don't know how big,
but it's a big win for a lot of reasons. The little things that
happened are huge within the ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have had trouble scoring runs, and have rarely given
their pitchers big leads. Karros did that with his eighth homer of
the season when he hit a Mark Clark (3-5) fastball over the
left-center field fence to give the Dodgers a 3-0 lead. It was his
first homer since May 27.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the catalyst for the Dodgers offense, broke out of an
0-for-16 slump Monday, hit a game-tying homer Tuesday and went 3
for 5 in the series finale. He had seven hits and six RBI in the
three-game series with the Rangers and raised his average 19 points
to .268.
</P>
<P>
   Young also had the hit that broke the game open. Catcher Angel
Pena's RBI single put the Dodgers ahead 4-0 and Young capped the
six-run inning with a two-run single that squeezed past the glove
of Rangers third baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we needed,'' Johnson said. ``A little offense, a big
spot. I almost forgot we could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It also provided Brown with a comfortable cushion that he is
unlikely to want to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take that any time,'' Brown said after improving to 7-3.
``No doubt about it, a little breathing room was much
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed two runs on five hits in eight innings. He struck
out six and walked three in silencing one of baseball's best
lineups.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (35-23) were third in the major leagues in hitting
(.285) and fifth in runs scored (325), yet managed only a two-run
single by Rusty Greer in the fifth off Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brown retired the last 10 batters he faced and improved
his record to 5-1 after a Dodgers loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time in four starts Brown defeated the
Rangers, the team that drafted him in the first round (fourth
overall) in 1986. Brown pitched six full seasons for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any win is a good win,'' Brown said. ``I don't care if it's
Texas as in Houston or Texas as in the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   However, whether this win is a catapult won't be determined for
a while.
</P>
<P>
   What it did do was send the Dodgers (29-29) into today's off day
in a much better frame of mind and the ``comfort'' of being .500 a
day after dropping below it for the first time since April 26 when
they were 9-10. Ironically, Brown won on April 27 against Milwaukee
to trigger a season-high five-game winning streak. The Dodgers also
won seven of nine games, beginning with that Brown win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some moments where we thought we had the ball
rolling,'' Karros said. ``We haven't had that run of 10 or 15 games
in a row where we play well. Even the Florida Marlins won seven in
a row. It's been a collective lull for (us). We haven't gotten the
big hit, or made the big pitch. It's been a collective effort where
you can't really single out one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in a few weeks the Dodgers will point toward this win as
the reason for their resurgence. Of course, the chances are 50-50
that won't happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
