<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN13-CO     06-10 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GOP poll shoots GOP gun position
 &HT;    For release June 13, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could the message be any clearer to the GOP and the NRA? The
public wants something done about the misuse of guns. Note
carefully: I said misuse of guns, not banning them.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent message was delivered from within the Republican
Party in the form of what the Associated Press described as
``internal Republican polling.'' I presume that means registered
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed support in the vicinity of 80 percent for an
increase in the allowable age for handgun purchases, background
checks for gun show sales, safety devices for guns and mandatory
sentences for felons who commit crimes with guns.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this overwhelming finding, the Republicans and the
Democrats continue to spar with various forms of legislation
regarding guns, with the anti-gun forces scorching the National
Rifle Association and the pro-gun people standing behind ancient
arguments and splitting hairs.
</P>
<P>
   The public does not want hairs split. I don't believe the public
wants guns banned either, at least not most guns. The public wants
an end to this political fiasco that results in many dead people.
</P>
<P>
   What is missing in the gun argument is a sense of concession, a
sense of trying to understand each other's side.
</P>
<P>
   The internecine combat going on on Capitol Hill this past week
over varied versions of House and Senate bills, of President
Clinton posturing one way, the GOP leadership another has reached a
point where the public sits back in angry bewilderment over this
lack of comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   What the anti-gun people need to understand is that guns aren't
going to be outlawed, ever. Dilute the Second Amendment, chance
losing the First as well, and so on. Some weapons, the kind that
can mow down armies rather than elk, possibly can be banned, but
that's really not the biggest issue of the gun control war.
</P>
<P>
   Who gets the guns, how they get them and how we try to keep
track of them is the critical issue.
</P>
<P>
   What the pro-gun people need to comprehend is that their
absolutism does them ill. They've got to give a little while still
protecting their right to own guns. But to start splitting hairs
over legislation that would require waiting periods over sales at
gun shows is not what the public wants. There is just no reason _
constitutional or otherwise _ why it is OK for a maniac to buy a
gun at a gun show and not have to go through a background check,
while he would have to at a regular gun shop.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control and banning guns are two terms that are inexplicably
mixed but are hardly the same. It is similar to driver's licenses
and autos. The person using the auto needs to be checked out; drunk
driving doesn't result in the auto being banned.
</P>
<P>
   You might think the poll taken by the GOP right after the
Littleton school tragedy would influence legislators to put aside
their stupid political posturing and listen to the people who sent
them to Washington, but it hasn't; nor has it stilled the lobbying
voice of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) says Democratic Party pressure to pass
legislation as a result of the Littleton shootings is ``their
typical knee-jerk reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   So was declaring war after the attack on Pearl Harbor, Henry.
</P>
<P>
   No one is going to completely win this argument _ ever. But it
seems to me that if the Brady Bill types give in just a bit and the
NRA types pull back their troops slightly, we might be able to
agree on some things _ such as age restrictions, safety locks (that
work), mandatory sentencing and the silly nuance over background
checks that differentiate not only between gun shop and gun show
sales but within the gun show sales themselves _ the things that
poll showed so strongly.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP must have taken its poll for a reason, presumably to get
a handle on the public's pulse. What they got was the pulse of the
people within their own party. They asked for it, they got it.
</P>
<P>
   Now pay attention to it!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
