 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2548 -- June 10, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for
</P>
<P>
   availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. GREEN GOLD Throughout civilization, emeralds have been
symbols of immortality, a cure for dysentery and preservers of
chastity. Why such reverence? Because emeralds are very rare -
rarer than diamonds. The reason they are rare, says geologist Alain
Cheilletz of the Centre for Petrographic and Geochemical Research
in Nancy, France, is because 'Earth's green gold' is a mixture of
elements that don't ordinarily get a chance to mix : ``They are a
mineral that shouldn't exist at all.'' By Robert Kunzig. From
Discover magazine. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
TRYING DIFFERENT DRUGS HELPS HIGH BLOOD PRESSURE PATIENTS FIND BEST
TREATMENT High blood pressure is a major cause of heart attacks and
strokes, the world's two leading causes of death. Fortunately, in
most cases, it is possible to lower elevated blood pressure to safe
levels with medication. But finding the right drug for patients is
often difficult because different individuals can react very
differently to the same blood pressure medication. Researchers
report that patients may be able to find the drug that is best for
them if they first try out several different medications before
settling on one treatment. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet. 1,000
words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
MIDDLE EAST CONFLICT RESOLUTION MAY BE A MODEL
</P>
<P>
   FOR INDIA AND PAKISTAN As tensions between India and Pakistan
over the disputed territory of Kashmir once again boil over, world
security is threatened by the very real possibility that war will
break out between two politically unstable nuclear powers. By
Benazir Bhutto, former prime minister of Pakistan. New York Times
Op-Ed. 1,000 words.
______________________________________________________ 4. FROM
PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   A. DEBATE : GAY MARRIAGE Should gay couples be allowed to marry?
Or would gay promiscuity deal a final blow to the already
beleaguered institution of marriage? By Evan Davis and Melanie
Phillips. 3,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. ACTING IN EXILE Sarah Caudwell talks to actress Sheila
Mitchell about the different theatre cultures in Britain and
France. 1,000 words. 5. KOSOVAR SERB POLICE MUST GO, BUT SO WILL
KOSOVO The Serbs are right that their future sovereignty over
Kosovo will be put in doubt by the forced withdrawal NATO has
demanded, even though reference in the Rambouillet text providing
for a referendum after three years has been eliminated. This is
part of the wages of war. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
DRILL-LIKE MECHANISM IN SPREAD OF TUMOURS IS REVEALED A delicate
but destructive machine, a kind of molecular power drill deployed
by tumours to punch their way through the body's compartments, has
been visualized for the first time by biologists in Sweden. The
power drill exists not for the benefit of tumours, though they
exploit it, but for normal remodeling of the tough walls that
surround the body's main organs and tissues. By Nicholas Wade.
1,000 words + graphic.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
BRANDS, MONEY, FAME AND THE INTERNET The two most important
business terms of the late 1990s seem to be ``brand'' and
'Internet.'' Robert X. Cringeley, an Internet writer, explores the
relationship between ``brand,'' celebrity names, the digital era
and money. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. HRT RISK/BENEFIT ROLLERCOASTER IDENTIFIES NEW DANGER The
risk/benefit controversy surrounding hormone replacement therapy
(HRT) has taken another twist with the release of a study that
links its use to an increased risk for a type of invasive breast
cancer. 540 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. PAINKILLERS HELP EASE SIDE EFFECTS OF MS TREATMENT Multiple
sclerosis patients may benefit from taking an over-the-counter
painkiller (ibuprofen) alongside more advanced drugs commonly given
as treatment, according to a team of U.S. and Canadian researchers.
500 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. WILD MONKEY DIET Anthropologist Katharine Milton recommends
that humans take a dietary leaf from the book of the wild monkey to
avoid conditions associated with unhealthy eating habits like heart
attack and cancer. The wild fruit eaten by primates contained
higher levels of calcium, potassium and iron than levels found in
cultivated varieties. 300 words.
