<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lessons of the Never Mind War
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Far from bringing joyous crowds boiling into the streets of
alliance nations, NATO's victory in Kosovo has raised barely even a
lazy, passing huzzah. We have prevailed in the Never Mind War.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the vast public indifference to either its waging or
to its successful conclusion, the war nonetheless accomplished
important ends. Serbia has been isolated in a way _ and damaged to
a degree _ that it will be unable to excite further Balkan mischief
even if its chief mischief-maker, the regrettable Slobodan
Milosevic, clings to power. A nation led by an indicted war
criminal does not enjoy great international cachet.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic cleansing has been forbidden and defeated. NATO has
asserted, where great horrors are being written, the primacy of
human values over the political technicalities of dubious
statehood. No, governments may not devastate their own people as a
right of office.
</P>
<P>
   NATO must now shepherd a million Albanian Kosovars to devastated
communities, prepare winter quarters for them, shield Serbian
Kosovars and defang the Kosovo Liberation Army (itself a sometimes
nasty bunch and revenge-minded), crank up war-crimes investigations
and arrests, aid rebuilding and establish and police a nanny
statelet for no doubt years to come.
</P>
<P>
   As expensive as the war was, the peace will be pricier. Yet the
cost of inaction would have been higher still _ in human waste, in
a modern precedent for indulged aggression and ethnic abuse and in
the creation of a permanent regional political irritant with the
potential _ and proven willingness _ to destabilize southern and
southeastern Europe, to whatever broader damage one can only guess
and fear.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
particularly, held NATO more or less steady against its centrifugal
few and gave it new cohesion, refreshed purpose and enhanced
credibility _ even, in an especially difficult trick, involving the
conflicted and anxious Russia as a diplomatic player and
peace-minder.
</P>
<P>
   And of less importance but interestingly, Clinton once again
utterly flummoxed his constant domestic detractors. The draft
dodger proved the armchair generals wrong in their universal claim
that the air campaign could not prevail and _ the ones who went
further _ that since ground war would not be easily prosecutable,
he should therefore have done naught.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and would-be presidential Republicans have been
left stranded in various isolated positions of opposition, most
embarrassingly the House majority, which in effect voted to
surrender by refusing to vote support for NATO and then, befuddled,
authorized twice as much money for the war as the president thought
necessary. Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Heavy humanitarian and political labors lie ahead, as does a
potential pitfall: the temptation to believe that because this
bombardment worked, all we need do at the next frustration is to
pull the same trigger. For now, though, it would not be shameless
to let out a discreet cheer. Hey, team, we won.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
