<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-NOAH-WYLE-AS-STEVE-JOBS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE CORE: `ER'S' NOAH WYLE PLAYS STEVE JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Noah Wyle in
``Pirates of Silicon Valley.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Steve Jobs, the man who invented the Apple computer, is
obsessive, dictatorial, frequently irrational and often paranoid.
 &HT;    And Noah Wyle just loves him.
 &HT;    Wyle steps out of his character as ``ER's'' likable Dr. Carter
for a trip through the computer world as Jobs in Turner Network
Television's ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' airing June 20. Anthony
Michael Hall plays Jobs' archrival, Microsoft founder Bill Gates.
 &HT;    Jobs has his share of fans and his share of detractors. Count
Wyle among the former.
 &HT;    ``I'd like him if I met him,'' Wyle says after a quick lunch in
his suite at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel. ``A journalist told
me she'd interviewed Jobs and asked him if he knew about our
project, and how he felt about me playing him. She said it was the
only time he smiled.
 &HT;    ``But you have to believe that a man like that sees this as
nothing more than a distraction.''
 &HT;    The film traces Jobs' career from his childhood through a
college identity crisis to his early struggling days, and on to
fame as the founding father of Apple and of California's Silicon
Valley, before a fateful showdown with Gates for supremacy in the
personal-computer business.
 &HT;    Jobs comes across as a man of vision, with an absolute
commitment to his business and his product. But he also emerges as
a control freak who demands absolute loyalty from his staff, works
them half to death with 90-hour weeks, humiliates employees in
public and refuses to share the company's wealth with his fellow
executives.
 &HT;    ``To do what he did he had to be the way he was,'' Wyle says.
``One of the most potent testimonials I heard about him was from a
former employee who said that he had never been treated as poorly
as he was by Steven _ he'd never been belittled or berated or had
his humanity questioned more.
 &HT;    ``But he also never had had a time when he had done better
work.''
 &HT;    Besides, Wyle relishes the chance to flex muscles he doesn't use
much as ``that nice Dr. Carter.'' But the actor knows that it is
the success of ``ER'' that has made everything else in his career
possible. He makes a point of putting the show first on his
priorities list, and in fact almost turned the chance to play Jobs
for that reason.
 &HT;    ``But as soon as I saw a picture of Jobs and saw that we bore a
more than passing resemblance to each other, and I realized the
dynamic, charismatic, conflicted character that he was, I jumped at
the chance,'' he says.
 &HT;    With George Clooney out of ``ER'' and Wyle signed for an
additional three years, he finds himself suddenly the mainstay of
one of television's most popular series. No one is more surprised
than the 27-year-old actor himself.
 &HT;    ``I didn't have much interest in working in television,'' he
says, ``so it's a wonderful irony _ the one thing I didn't want to
do has given me everything I've ever wanted.''
 &HT;    It's certainly a gratifying development for a young man who not
so long ago was most remarkable as the only boy in his class at The
Thacher School in Ojai, Calif., who decided not to go on to
college.
 &HT;    ``Not the most popular decision, I can tell you,'' he says with
a laugh.
 &HT;    Instead, he headed for Los Angeles and the enticing but unlikely
prospects of an acting career. After initially running into a
series of dead ends, he found a job as a busboy at a hotel
restaurant, a job he quit on the day he signed for his first movie,
``Crooked Hearts'' (1991).
 &HT;    ``The maitre d' left me on the payroll for another four or five
years,'' he recalls, ``just in case I needed my job back.''
 &HT;    Three years later he was cast in ``ER,'' and not long afterward
his picture was on the walls of teen-agers' bedrooms all over the
country.
 &HT;    His emergence as a sex symbol still bemuses Wyle, who values his
privacy _ especially now, when he's planning his wedding to
30-year-old Tracy Warbin, a makeup artist he met on the set of
``The Myth of Fingerprints'' (l997).
 &HT;    ``I would like to make it as private as possible,'' he says.
``It's sad, but it's the reality that the first call we made in
planning the wedding was to a security person. I have `ER' to thank
for that.
 &HT;    ``It's ridiculous to complain about it after reaping so many of
the benefits,'' he adds. ``Nonetheless, there are still moments
when your vulnerability is down and you think, `Why does that have
to be the byproduct of success?'''
 &HT;    Among the more welcome of those byproducts is the ranch estate
he and Warbin call home. Formerly the property of John and Bo
Derek, it's located in the rolling hills of the Santa Ynez Valley,
120 miles north of Los Angeles, and is the most obvious testimony
to the literally millions of dollars the show has brought him.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he says, he's not extravagant. Other than ensuring
his mother's comfortable retirement and buying the ranch _ ``it was
a good investment,'' he insists _ he's put his money into blue-chip
stocks and conservative investments.
 &HT;    ``Any actor in my shoes would be smart to be smart with money,''
he says, ``and not believe million-dollar checks will come every
year.''
 &HT;    He credits Clooney for a lot of his financial savvy.
 &HT;    ``He's a blueprint for me, a very smart businessman who knows
the industry well,'' the actor says. ``I get advice from him very
often.''
 &HT;    Wyle hopes that his next three years on the series will be a
learning process in studio politics and production.
 &HT;    ``Hopefully I'll walk away having brought a few things to
fruition,'' he says, ``as well as earning a nice chunk of change.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, he likes what the ``ER'' writers have in mind
for Dr. Carter.
 &HT;    ``He's interested in going into the community, to the people who
don't necessarily make it into the emergency room, and in
practicing triage medicine in the streets. Have stethoscope, will
travel,'' Wyle says. ``And there was a sort of big-brother
relationship starting between him and a kid from the streets on a
scholarship, with Carter as mentor. I like that.
 &HT;    ``Taking doctors out of the hospital to show their personal
lives can mean that the further we leave the hospital behind, the
more it becomes a nighttime soap,'' he acknowledges. ``So anytime
we find a story line that involves the personal a bit but is still
steeped in medicine, it's always the way to go.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,''
consult the TNT Website at tnt.turner.com/tntoriginals. For more on
``ER,'' see the NBC site at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
