<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX     06-10 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharon Stone and I make a gossip column
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGODOCHES, Texas _ Andy Warhol said we'd all have 15 minutes
of fame. Looks like I've received mine, so it's all downhill from
here. To steal columnist Dave Barry's line, I'm not making any of
this up. This is all gospel truth, and I have the newspaper clip to
prove it.
</P>
<P>
   A while back I wrote a column about a recent visit I made to
Palm Beach, Fla. for a Cox newspaper editor's meeting. I walked
around the island for a few days, took notes, and made some
observations about a small town whose residents by-and-large have
more money than God, love little white dogs and are fond of talking
incessantly on cell phones while lounging by the swimming pool.
Let's say I poked gentle fun at these folks, whose lifestyle is,
well, a bit different than mine and 99.9 percent of the people in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Daily News, which is owned by the same folks that
own this newspaper, published the column with an editor's note
apologizing for my backwoods attitude. It was all done in fun and
good humor. I realized this would not endear me to some people in
Palm Beach, though in truth the only reaction I received after it
ran were two e-mails from ex-residents who said they enjoyed the
column _ and both of them mentioned they had mothers still living
in Palm Beach who owned little white dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The editor of The Palm Beach Daily News, who has enjoyed calling
me Brutus, as in ``et tu Brutus,'' since the column ran, last week
sent me a clipping from The New York Post. A gossip columnist there
took offense to my column and saw fit to remark upon it.
</P>
<P>
   A little background. The New York Post is a tabloid newspaper,
the kind with screaming headlines, such as ``Six Killed In Bloody
Enchilada Battle.'' It revels in scandal, murder, mayhem and
corruption. That's why it's one of my favorite newspapers, though
it seems doubtful now that any future career move of mine will
involve a transfer to the Big Apple, not that I am looking.
</P>
<P>
   The column, called ``Neal Travis' New York,'' leads off with
sultry actress Sharon Stone's spokesperson denying that promoters
are using a double for her when she takes off her clothes, which
she seems to do quite often in films. I remember a movie a few
years back when it quickly became obvious that Ms. Stone was not
fond of underwear. I remember thinking that she best be careful.
Think how embarrassed her mother would be if she was in a car
wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The last item in the gossip column concerns the piece I wrote
about Palm Beach. It calls my name, as we say in East Texas, and
speculates about whether one of the Cox family members, who owns a
chateau in Palm Beach, ever saw the column written by one of her
``pesky'' newspaper editors. That's what the writer called me:
pesky.
</P>
<P>
   His sage advice: ``Never let the hired help hang out anywhere
near your private domain.''
</P>
<P>
   I can say with total confidence that this is the only time my
name and Sharon Stone's will be mentioned in the same big-city
gossip column. Me and Sharon, we're tight.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Travis, who seems inexplicably defensive about a town
1,500 miles or more from where he lives, is worried that my
``diatribe'' and ``nasty column,'' as he put it, will hurt the
social standing of another Cox family member who still lives in
Palm Beach and recently had an art show. I'm thinking everything is
going to be OK. Newspaper people, apparently everywhere but New
York, have a sense of humor. At least that's what I'm counting on.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, I was most offended by his calling our fine little
Palm Beach paper a rag. Coming from The New York Post, that's like
being called ugly by a frog. As for me, in the words of Ben
Bradlee, portrayed magnificently by Jason Robards in ``All the
President's Men,'' which, coincidentally, I was watching while
writing this column in a Palm Beach hotel room that cost more daily
than my monthly electric bill here behind the Pine Curtain: I stand
by my story.
</P>
<P>
   But I appreciate the plug in The New York Post. If Sharon calls
Mr. Travis to complain about her mention in his column, I hope he
tells her to look me up some time. Maybe we can go underwear
shopping together at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel. His
e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
