A0065 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN11-COX     06-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perry receives mostly favorable reviews this session
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lt. Gov. Rick Perry got fairly high marks for
his first session following Democrat Bob Bullock as presiding
officer of the Texas Senate. As might be expected, his fellow
Republicans were more lavish in their praise than were some of the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came in as a rookie, and you followed an icon,'' said Sen.
Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant) on the final night of the session
May 31. ``You mastered this job. You kept the Senate together at a
lot of times when it could have fallen apart. ... You had a good
session, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eliot Shapleigh (D-El Paso) had similar kind words.
``Managing 30 bucking broncos in the shadow of an icon isn't an
easy task,'' Shapleigh said in an interview. ``He moved the agenda
with very few errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, with glibness and a quick sense of humor, seemed quickly
in control from the Senate dais. However, in contrast to the
one-man rule often exercised by his predecessor, he acted more as a
referee than as someone deciding issues for the Senate. Even
Democrats gave him credit for stepping in and helping close deals
on some issues.
</P>
<P>
   But he had nowhere near as ambitious an agenda as the omnivorous
Bullock, who pushed big issues like school finance and water, among
others. Perry's own personal concerns, in fact, seemed limited
largely to requiring parental notification of abortions, which
passed, and allowing school vouchers, which the Democrats kept from
reaching the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Parental notification was dear to Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential campaign. Perry, who knows he wouldn't have been
elected lieutenant governor had it not been for Bush's coattails,
was only too happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   Bush paid lip service to vouchers but didn't push it. Perry did
_ causing some Democratic senators to note that it seemed a payback
to San Antonio multimillionaire James Leininger and other voucher
supporters for pumping more than $1 million into Perry's campaign
last year for TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's chewing out of some senators of both parties over their
reluctance to support some of Perry's pet issues cost him some
points, some senators said. One Democrat complained Perry's
decision to have standing five-member subcommittees to which bills
were directly referred meant the seven-member full committee had to
vote on issues without having been involved in public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of that makes much difference in the long run
remains to be seen. Several senators _ and probably Perry, too,
though he doesn't admit it _ think he may be a very short-term
presiding officer.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is elected president in 2000, Perry would move into the
Governor's Mansion. If Bush fails to take over the White House, the
general speculation is he would not seek another term as governor
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That could set the stage for a face-off for the GOP
gubernatorial nomination between Perry and U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, who has indicated an interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hutchison presumably will have just been re-elected to the
Senate in 2000 and have just renewed her name identification and
organization, some speculate Perry wouldn't take her on. In fact,
there has even been talk that Perry might stay out of that race,
let Hutchison become governor, and then she would appoint him to
her vacant Senate seat. He had talked before the 1996 election
about possibly running for the Senate if a vacancy occurred.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Perry has defied conventional wisdom before _
beginning with his switch to the Republican Party in 1989, for what
most thought was a very remote chance to unseat Democratic
Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower. But Perry did, and a decade
later, he's one election away _ though it's Bush's, not his _ from
becoming governor.
</P>
<P>
   And so on ... Some senators actually breathed easier with the
absence of the all-knowing Bullock and his unquenchable thirst for
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock had an unerring political antenna,'' said one
Democrat. ``He knew what was going on in your office before you
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the session, Bullock gave each senator a set of
longhorns on a swivel base. More than one senator would talk into
the longhorns, only half-joking that they were a camouflaged
antenna _ hooked to a transmitter that went straight to Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
