r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFETRAVEL-OVERSEAS11     06-10 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFETRAVEL-OVERSEAS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safe travel: To go or not to go
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Palestinian ``intifada,'' or
uprising, was underway in Israel. But I was still surprised to walk
into the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem in 1988 and find only
a monk.
</P>
<P>
   The usual crowds of tourists and pilgrims had been scared away
by the nightly news showing bombed city buses and streets patrolled
by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   On my way out, I passed a lone British tourist. We stopped to
talk. ``A war is always the best time to travel,'' he said,
smiling, with no apparent sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to sound gruesome, but I have enjoyed a blessed
lack of tourists and increased graciousness from locals after ugly
well-publicized incidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris during a series of metro bombings, I felt even safer
than usual because of increased security. Who's going to rob me
with soldiers in fatigues nearby?
</P>
<P>
   Something awful happens and tourists naturally run the other
way. After all, who wants to think about safety when you're trying
to relax and have fun? Americans are especially cautious. Tensions
erupt in the Middle East and travelers cancel plans to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's a war in Europe. Is it safe to go to Italy?
We're seeing stealth bombers and F-16s flying out of Aviano on the
nightly news. Should we go to Greece?
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Middle East and Africa?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department Web site (http://travel.state.gov) is
getting 90,000 hits a day since NATO attacks began, double the
usual number.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous callers have sought guidance from the State
Department's hotline (202-647-5225) on whether they should go to
Serbia or countries nearby, or to countries that support or oppose
NATO action.
</P>
<P>
   At present, only four European countries have State Department
warnings, which means American citizens should not travel there:
Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia-Montenegro and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
   These countries have State Department ``public announcements,''
which means you should heed the State Department's information and
then decide whether to go: Greece, Croatia, former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia, Moldova, Kyrgyz Republic and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, Americans are safer from terrorists in Europe
than they are from terrifying drivers on U.S. roads. The trick to
staying safe, if you judge by the numbers, is to vacation in
Croatia and stay off our highways.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, seven private American citizens (nongovernment
employees) died from terrorist attacks worldwide, according to the
Bureau of Diplomatic Security at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the total number of U.S. casualties from terrorism
was 23, all killed in the bombing of the embassy in Kenya. Of
those, 12 were private citizens. On Florida roads, for example,
more than 2,000 people were killed in 1997, according to statistics
compiled by the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But for those going overseas, there are plenty of safety
precautions to consider, some of which go against the conventional
wisdom of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Most people think it's safer to travel with a group. But this
has proven deadly in Egypt and Uganda, where groups of tourists
were targeted and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Is there safety in numbers? ``There's no such thing as being
absolutely safe even in this country,'' says State Department
spokeswoman Nyda Budig. ``Hopefully, well-organized groups won't
take them to countries where there are warnings.''
</P>
<P>
   How about visiting U.S. embassies? The rule of thumb used to be
to stop by and get the latest safety information. But after the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya and the demonstrations at U.S.
embassies worldwide by Serb sympathizers, it might be more prudent
to call.
</P>
<P>
   One recently retired U.S. Embassy employee told me that friends
and associates of embassy workers now ask to meet in restaurants,
not at the embassies.
</P>
<P>
   And forget about wearing your New York Yankees cap. Contrary to
popular belief here in the States, not everybody out there likes
us. It's always best to keep a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Stay away from demonstrations. Resist the temptation to watch,
and quickly walk the other way. You never know when they might turn
ugly. Since the beginning of NATO air strikes in Serbia, there have
been almost daily demonstrations at NATO-member embassies around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Buy health insurance, particularly a policy that includes
medical evacuation. And call the State Department's hotline about
the countries you're thinking about visiting.
</P>
<P>
   When you arrive at your destination, read newspapers, watch the
local TV news, take a shortwave radio if you're in a developing
country, and talk to fellow travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, try to relax.
</P>
<P>
   --Athens, Greece
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers marching in a daily ceremony are entertainment, not
cause for alarm. The U.S. State Department emphasizes that it is
not warning U.S. citizens against going to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   But a bomb placed at the Intercontinental Hotel in Athens killed
one person in April, and there were two failed bombing attempts,
one at the U.S. Consulate General in Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
   You might avoid the U.S. Embassy. Since the beginning of NATO
air strikes in Serbia, there have been almost daily demonstrations
in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   --Venice, Italy
</P>
<P>
   Gondola rides in Venice have always been a popular tourist
attraction. Now, war planes flying out of Aviano Air Base are
drawing crowds, too. Sightseers gather outside the base to watch
fleets of NATO planes flying round-the-clock sorties to the
Balkans. As a result, officials have built higher walls to shield
the tents housing new troops.
</P>
<P>
   It's pickpockets, not terrorists, that you need to watch out for
in Italy, according to U.S. State Department Consular Information.
</P>
<P>
   --Jerusalem, Israel
</P>
<P>
   Hassidic men pray at the Western Wall. Many tourists are making
religious pilgrimages here for the millennium. Travelers can call
the State Department for a brochure on safety in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   --Amboseli, Kenya: There are no State Department warnings
against travel to Kenya, though last year's embassy bombings are
sure to make tourists wary.
</P>
<P>
   5 TIPS FOR SAFE TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   Safety in numbers used to be the conventional wisdom, but this
has proven deadly in the Middle East and Africa, where tourist
groups were targeted and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Reconsider visiting U.S. embassies. After the bombing of the
U.S. Embassy in Kenya and the demonstrations at U.S. embassies
worldwide, it might be more prudent to call.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about wearing your New York Yankees cap. It's always best
to keep a low profile and not broadcast being American.
</P>
<P>
   Buy health insurance, particularly a policy that includes
medical evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Before you leave home, call the U.S. State Department hot line,
(202) 647-5225, about the countries you are visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
