<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANTS-NOISE11-C     06-10 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-NOISE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All the buzz at restaurants
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a Sunday night at Pappadeaux Seafood Kitchen, and
things are running at full cry. In the bar, blenders whipping up
margaritas and pina coladas barely make an impression over the buzz
of the crowd. The loudspeaker crackles with intermittent
announcements that tables are ready. In the dining room, the
chatter of hundreds of patrons fueled with swamp things and other
high-octane drinks bounces off the tin ceiling, colliding with a
Cajun soundtrack, clattering plates and the occasional shrieks of
children.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to hear the waiter, sometimes hard to hear your
companion across the table. Yet Pappadeaux, one of the most popular
restaurants in Gwinnett County, probably isn't the noisiest
restaurant in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the atmosphere creates entertainment and the people
enjoy that,'' says Cris Reed, guest relations manager for the
Texas-based Pappas Restaurants, which owns Pappadeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not noise, it's just people enjoying themselves and the
music.''
</P>
<P>
   If noise indicates enjoyment, diners should be having the time
of their lives. Restaurants are getting louder, often by design,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when diners were asked about food, cleanliness, service and
other attributes in a National Restaurant Association survey, they
said they were least satisfied with noise levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real fine line between too noisy ... and not noisy
enough _ read dead, not lively, not exciting,'' says John
Imbergamo, a Denver restaurant consultant. ``Finding that fine line
is what restaurateurs are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Karen Robbins of Decatur celebrated their fifth
anniversary Friday at the Food Business, which ranked loudest in a
small Journal-Constitution spot check of noise levels at metro
Atlanta restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leaning over toward Karen just so we could hear each
other,'' said Steve, 31, an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the downtown Decatur eatery ``the Neyland Stadium of
Atlanta restaurants,'' referring to the University of Tennessee
football venue renowned for its crowd noise. But, he adds, the good
food makes up for the overly loud ambience.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, noise has become an issue,'' says Atlanta
restaurant designer Bill Johnson of the Johnson Studio, architects
for the Cheesecake Factory, Seeger's, Rio Bravo Grill and many
other restaurants in Atlanta and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Banging plates, background music and large parties have always
helped pump up the volume at restaurants. But as design styles have
changed, Johnson says, restaurants have gotten louder. Popular,
low-maintenance building materials such as wood, tile, plaster,
metal and concrete give a hip, industrial look _ and often an
industrial-strength sonic blast.
</P>
<P>
   Open floor plans, uncarpeted floors and ceilings without
sound-absorbing material bounce conversations across the room.
Factor in baby boomers who seem to be growing less tolerant of loud
settings, and you get complaints about clamor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's my age, but I tend to be looking for a quieter
environment these days,'' says Tim Zagat, publisher of the New
York-based Zagat restaurant guides. ``The funny thing is, it's a
two-edged sword. A lot of people don't think a restaurant is
exciting unless it's noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurateurs would agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's really noisy it's probably busy and popular, and I
wouldn't change anything,'' says Pano Karatassos, president of the
Buckhead Life Restaurant Group, which owns Pano's and Paul's, the
Buckhead Diner, the Atlanta Fish Market and other dining spots.
</P>
<P>
   Karatassos remembers when noisy restaurants were unheard of in
Atlanta. In 1991, when the company opened Pricci, an Italian
restaurant in Buckhead, Karatassos worried about how loud it was.
He considered hiring sound engineers to improve the acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would take business away,'' Karatassos says.
``But very quickly people got used to it. There's always going to
be somebody who might want to be in a more quiet room, but we can
accommodate that.''
</P>
<P>
   As co-owner of Bacchanalia and Floataway Cafe, Anne Quatrano
oversees restaurants that fall on opposite ends of the decibel
scale. Bacchanalia, in Buckhead, drew complaints about noise when
it opened. In response, its wooden floors were covered with carpet
and the restaurant now has a reputation as a quiet, intimate dining
room. This summer, Quatrano plans to tone things down at Floataway,
near Emory University. The restaurant's industrial-chic design
blends well with its home in a converted warehouse, but it's caused
a problem with acoustics, she says. The aluminum chairs and high
ceilings will stay, but the concrete floors will be carpeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest criticism I get from people here at Floataway is
that it's noisy,'' Quatrano says. ``It's a mix. Some people like a
place that sounds like a lot's going on, and certainly we attract a
younger crowd here as a result of it than we do at Bacchanalia.''
</P>
<P>
   Count 27-year-old Dana Young, a sales representative from
Atlanta, among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come here for intimate conversation,'' Young says.
``The tables are too close together for that. I usually come with
several friends and we're the ones making the noise. I don't even
notice the noise from the other tables.''
</P>
<P>
   Big groups keep noise levels high. At Fratelli di Napoli, a
family-style restaurant in Buckhead, owner Tony LaRocco installed
some soundproofing materials several years ago in response to
complaints. But large parties still keep the restaurant buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to have just a fun, energetic dinner, it's a good
place to come,'' LaRocco says. ``If you're looking for a place
where you're sitting across the table holding hands and you can
hear a fork drop, it's not the place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Food Business, host Paul Powell said the restaurant plans
to provide some noise abatement by installing carpet and other
sound-absorbing materials.
</P>
<P>
   Because noise levels have become such an issue, Johnson often
arranges for an acoustic consultant to check out restaurant designs
before construction begins. Fixing problems after a restaurant
opens can be costly.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Smith, president of the acoustic consultants Ballentine
Walker Smith of Kennesaw, estimates the average cost of carpeting
and adding sound-absorbing material in the tens of thousands _ and
that's without tearing out walls and major renovations. Many of
those who call for advice wind up forgoing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I tell them what they're going to have to do it depresses
them,'' Smith says, ``because it involves reconfiguring the way the
restaurant is laid out, and they can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   For diners, the best solution is matching a restaurant to the
mood. Increasingly, restaurant reviews include information on
noise. Some dining reviews indicate noise levels, as do restaurant
guides.
</P>
<P>
   Some loud restaurants do have quieter tables that can be
reserved. And visiting during off-peak hours should tone down the
volume too.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Staff writer Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
