<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARMADILLO-FOOD (San Francisco) _ Armadillos are in San
Francisco, and that could pose a problem: It's the leprosy thing.
They are turning up in Chinatown food stores, waiting for an
adventurous gourmet to take out his or her wallet and surprise the
family come dinner time. City health officials have learned what
every Texas school kid already knows: Armadillos, like humans, can
contract leprosy. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ Saying ``only I can decide
whether to arm or disarm my police officers,'' San Francisco Police
Chief Fred Lau said he intends to stick to his guns and continue to
allow cops to carry weapons on campuses during non-emergencies
despite the school board's gun ban. By ANITA WADHWANI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FTC-E-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _ Hoping to protect consumers,
the Federal Trade Commission and global regulators are studying new
electronic commerce rules to cover the millions of merchants
worldwide with Web sites. An FTC survey of 200 corporate Web sites,
released Wednesday, shows that most fail to disclose key consumer
information and legal guidelines. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ADS (San Francisco) _ Fed up with advertising banners
crowding your screen while surfing the Web? Wish they would all
just go away? Thanks to numerous versions of ad-blocking software
that are relatively inexpensive, and often free, you can live a
banner-free lifestyle. By BOBBY McGILL.
</P>
