<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0104 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-GILLOM-TI     06-10 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-GILLOM-TIMMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMMS, GILLOM FOCUSED ON LANDING TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Pilates and protein.
</P>
<P>
   Could these off-season conditioning regimens practiced by the
Mercury's two senior citizens be the magic bullets to bring down
the two-time WNBA champion Houston Comets and finally deliver a
professional basketball title to Phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, they are the age-defiers of choice for
Michele Timms and Jennifer Gillom in their push for the
championship ring that slipped from their grasp some nine months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Up one game and 12 points in a best-of-three series with 7:24
remaining, the Mercury lost to Houston in overtime, 74-69, then
lost again, 80-71, in the deciding Game 3. The heartbreaking finish
left both the league's second-best player, Gillom, and the
underachieving Timms to take a long, hard look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way from that second game up until say a month ago,
that game has not gotten out of my mind,'' said Gillom, runner-up
as WNBA Most Valuable Player behind repeat winner Cynthia Cooper of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like if I had played a little bit better (she was sick
to her stomach after going 3 for 15 from the field in the overtime
game), we could have won it. I'll never forget it because we were
too close, and that was our opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gillom, Timms could not even find individual solace.
Although her assist/turnover ratio improved (2.29, compared with
1.71), her other important statistics plunged dramatically _
scoring (from 12.1 per game to 6.9); steals (from 2.6 to 1.3). Her
shooting percentages from the field, line and three-point range all
dropped off as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a bad season, but it wasn't anywhere near how I'd
been playing the year before,'' Timms said. ``I'm trying to
recapture that form, I guess, and even take it to the next level,
and that is being hopefully a little bit smarter in my game.''
</P>
<P>
   With new two-year contracts that will take Gillom to age 36 and
Timms to 35, the Mercury's veteran leaders are not looking
elsewhere for a savior to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   If Edna Campbell and Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil live up to their
American Basketball League credentials, great. If 6-foot-8 Maria
Stepanova blossoms at age 20, even better.
</P>
<P>
   But if Timms and Gillom have to hoist the Mercury on their backs
for the 32-game season that begins Saturday, they're determined to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're getting down to the finals (of their careers),
and if we want to do this, this is our year to do it,'' Gillom
said. ``It's not going to get any easier for us. We know the time
is now. I think she (Timms) is as focused as I am right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Timms' off-season focus was on regaining the step or more that
was missing in '98. For Gillom, it was a high-protein diet and
weight-training program that shed 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Timms, who believed she took too much time off after 1997,
played in the Australian WNBL and hooked up with Mark McGrath,
strength and conditioning coach at the Victorian Institute of
Sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really concerned because I was the heaviest I've been
the last two years and just sluggish and slow,'' Timms said.
</P>
<P>
   Through McGrath, she was introduced to Joseph Pilates, the
hip-again German boxer whose conditioning program developed in the
1920s has busted out of the ballet studio to be embraced by
Hollywood (Jodie Foster, Madonna, Vanessa Williams, Sharon Stone).
</P>
<P>
   Timms is blending the Pilates concept, designed to lengthen and
strengthen muscles, with sprinter resistance workouts.
</P>
<P>
   While backup point guard Kristi Harrower clings to an elastic
band connected to her belt, Timms sprints down the court, dragging
Harrower with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'll take it off, and you just fly,'' said Timms, who put
up 18 points on Charlotte standout Dawn Staley in the Mercury's
first preseason game. ``It's all about letting your mind and your
body know you can turn your legs over.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Graf, the Mercury and Australian National Team assistant
coach, said, ``She's much more the player she was in '97. In fact,
I think she's better. From the signs I see, her body's back close
to what it was, she's got confidence, she's much more on top of
just her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmsy's really at peace with herself and is saying, `I'm
going to maximize the end of my career.' I think that's exciting
for us because she's a great leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet no Mercury leads more by example than Gillom, who, following
the season of her life (20.8 ppg, 7.3 rpg), bypassed the
rubber-chicken circuit for a rigorous off-season of diet, knee
surgery and weights.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 Gillom shed 20 pounds to 175, her lightest since
she was a senior at Lafayette High School in Oxford, Miss., in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom said she used a protein diet similar to the one advocated
by Dr. Robert Atkins in his bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I ever saw fast results from a diet,''
she said. ``That's when I decided, `Hey, this may be it for me,'
and kept with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of her beloved pasta and bread, Gillom opts for
eggs and bacon at breakfast, salad with chicken at lunch and hot
vegetables with meat at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That might not help to sell ``Mercury Madness in the Kitchen,''
a cookbook in which Gillom's contribution is Pasta Carbonara, but
it has even those who know her looking twice to make sure it's her.
</P>
<P>
   She said at a recent commercial shoot in New York, ``I was
sitting in the chair doing my makeup and Rebecca (Lobo) comes in
and says, `Where's Jennifer? She's supposed to be here.' I thought
she was just joking around, but she was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of things are just like, wow, it must make that big
of a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew if I lost the weight, I had to try to keep myself
strong, so I started going in the weight room a lot more than I
have in the past. I feel strong. I'm still getting used to the new
body, especially on my fadeaway. Sometimes I can feel myself fading
too much because I'm used to the weight holding me in a certain
position.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first preseason game, Gillom suffered the worst shooting
(2 for 16) of her WNBA career and scratched out six points. Nine
days later, she was 12 for 18 for 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   Able to jump somewhat higher because of the weight loss and
arthroscopic left-knee surgery after a half-season in Turkey,
Gillom hopes for another improvement in her rebounding average and
perhaps an increase in the six double-doubles she logged in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Coach/General Manager Cheryl Miller, her Hall of Fame
playing career cut short more than a decade ago by bad knees, can
relate to the urgency felt by the first two players allocated to
the franchise in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like looking at your window and that window
gradually getting smaller and smaller,'' Miller said. ``They know
physically what it takes to get where we need to get. For them to
commit like they did was huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it just has to transcend to leading this team, and that's
where I'm hoping they take that next step. You can be better
physically and as a ballplayer, but you need to make everyone else
around you better. It's the little things that will make us better
that I need both Michele and Jennifer to do consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, like Timms, thinks playing a season or two beyond 2000
is possible, but the unpredictability of anything beyond next year
makes winning now mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   In a season in which other teams are catching up to the Mercury
in depth and Phoenix is without starting forward Michelle Griffiths
(on maternity leave), the road just as easily could turn the other
way.
</P>
<P>
   Without wins in its final three regular-season games in 1997 and
the last four in '98, the Mercury would be a two-time also-ran. The
margin of success is that thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get better than what I was last year,'' Gillom
said. ``I've never settled for what I've done last year. It was a
great season, but I thought this was something to even get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get a ring out of this some kind of way. I'm not
going to stop until I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Timms, whose ultimate goal is to win an Olympic gold medal
in Sydney before her countrymen. She has bronze medals from the
1996 Olympics and the '98 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last two years I wasn't happy with, and I didn't want to go
out on such a bad note,'' she said. ``I want to go out on top, not
as though she should have retired a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it was looking like. You're hearing the
whispers of what people are saying about you, I guess. I'd be very
disappointed if I went through my WNBA career without winning a
championship. It wouldn't sit right with me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
