<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-PREVIEW-A     06-10 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER'S CHALLENGE: TRIM ROSTER TO 11 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sleepless for 24 hours, Cheryl Miller expected to end
the angst and cut her Mercury roster to 11 after practice Tuesday.
She couldn't make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling the trigger isn't getting easier for the third-year
coach/general manager, especially given the exponential rise in
talent since 1997, when the agonizing was over a developmental
player or two.
</P>
<P>
   Now some starters' jobs are on the line as Phoenix grasps for
the combination that will earn the rings it fell just short of
claiming last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question we're going to have to let go of people
who have been in this system,'' Miller said. ``I wish there was
some other way. I hate the WNBA for not going to a 12-player
roster'' _ a union initiative that was not included in the new
four-year collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   With the camp debut of 6-foot-5 Marlies Askamp on Tuesday and
expected arrival of 6-8 Maria Stepanova today, the Mercury roster
is at 14. If fourth-round draft pick Amanda Wilson and free-agent
center MerleLynn Lange-Harris are among today's cuts and no one
goes on the injured list, Miller will be down to one decision.
</P>
<P>
   Since Michelle Griffiths, a starter at power forward last year,
is sitting out the season while pregnant, all the returning post
players (Jennifer Gillom, Toni Foster and the European centers) are
safe.
</P>
<P>
   So are Australian point guards Michele Timms and Kristi Harrower
and the top three drafts picks _ Edna Campbell, Clarissa
Davis-Wrightsil and Lisa Harrison, all with American Basketball
League experience.
</P>
<P>
   By elimination, that leaves a pair of two-year starters, Bridget
Pettis and Umeki Webb, and 1998 reserve Andrea Kuklova for two
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Pettis, the Mercury's emotional leader and second-leading scorer
(690 cumulative points) is expendable only if all doubts are
removed about Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   But how can they be when the 5-8 shooting guard scored just four
points in one exhibition game and missed the other, plus a good
share of practice time, while protecting a left foot from a
possible fracture?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, Bridget looks great,'' Miller said.
``So that's comforting to know that we can go in either direction
(Campbell or Pettis) and not miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pettis is in, the choice is between Webb, the 5-10 small
forward who is losing her starting job to the 6-1 Davis-Wrightsil,
and the 6-foot Kuklova.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't beat yourself up over it,'' Miller said. ``Once it's
done, it's done. And it's like anything _ if you're going to do
something, do it with conviction. And that's what I've got to live
with.''
</P>
<P>
   And then get on with the job of finishing among the top three of
a Western Conference that most believe to be appreciably stronger
than the East, and of overtaking the two-time WNBA champion Houston
Comets in the West playoffs for another title shot.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and Davis-Wrightsil, who has been protecting her foot
to avoid a ruptured plantar fascia, sat out the second exhibition
game. Much is expected from both in strengthening a perimeter that
put too much of a burden on Gillom, the league MVP runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   For the slimmed-down Gillom to be free for a full-time move to
power forward, Askamp or the 20-year-old Stepanova must emerge as a
starting center.
</P>
<P>
   Germany flopped to 12th at the European Championships, but
Askamp played big (18 points per game, tournament-high 12 rebounds
per game). The 28-year-old reported in the best shape of her WNBA
career and was immediately inserted into the Mercury's revamped
transition offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury opens at Sacramento on Saturday, then is home
against the Monarchs on Monday and against Cleveland on June 19
before embarking on a team-record seven-game road trip that
continues through July 3.
</P>
<P>
   If it comes through that stretch with a winning record, Phoenix
will be poised to finish strong, playing 14 of its final 22 games
at America West Arena. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
