<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999: THE YEAR OF THE DUNK?  
 TEAMS GEAR UP AS SEASON NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA Year 3 slogan makers settled for We Got Game, perhaps
because Summer Slam is under some pro wrestling copyright.
</P>
<P>
   But won't this certainly be the season when dunks _ we'll even
settle for just one _ come to U.S. women's professional basketball?
</P>
<P>
   A combined four-plus seasons between the WNBA and now-defunct
American Basketball League have produced a miss by Lisa Leslie in
the nationally televised WNBA debut and nothing since, except
Sylvia Crawley's blindfolded contest jam at the 1998 ABL All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 Crawley was not one of the 35 ABL players chosen in
the 50-player WNBA draft last month, but there are plenty of other
new candidates to palm the smaller WNBA ball and deposit it where
no woman in America has since the University of North Carolina's
Charlotte Smith in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 6 feet tall, is a third-round draft pick of the Charlotte
Sting, while 6-7 Kara Wolters, third in the 1998 ABL dunk contest,
was a third-round choice of the two-time WNBA champion Houston
Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dreaming about it (dunking),'' said Sacramento's 6-4
Yolanda Griffith, another ABL crossover and the second overall pick
in the draft. ``I can throw the ball down, and this ball is small.
I'm going for it if we're winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The tallest players in the WNBA are returnees: 7-2 Margo Dydek
of the Utah Starzz and the Mercury's 6-8 Maria Stepanova. Both dunk
in warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Starzz Coach Frank Layden now has a full season to cajole Dydek,
who thinks dunking is impolite, into making history. Large Marge
was the leading scorer (19.3 points) at the just-completed European
Championships as she and new Starzz guard Krystyna Lara took host
Poland to a title.
</P>
<P>
   Stepanova, a reserve for European bronze-medalist Russia, should
significantly better her playing time (6.5-minute average) with
Jennifer Gillom sliding to power forward. She has the mobility to
slam in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The point of who slams first or most is an aside to who wins
last, which common sense again says will be Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But the Comets have issues, beginning with the duel between
Sonja Henning and Jennifer Rizzoti to replace point guard Kim
Perrot, under treatment for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry also will be an issue with the arrival of 1998 No. 1
draft pick Polina Tzekova of Bulgaria, who missed all of last
season because of her mother's poor health. Now this year's No. 1
pick, Russian forward Natalia Zasulskaya, faces the same family
crisis, and her availability is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that everybody else has
closed the gap on us talentwise,'' Comets Coach/General Manager Van
Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   But if not Houston, with two-time league MVP Cynthia Cooper and
MVP-in-waiting Sheryl Swoopes, then who? Even picking 10th, the
runner-up Mercury came up with two new starters from the draft to
make the deepest team in the league more so, despite the maternity
absence of Michelle Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   An expanded playoff format prevents a Houston-Phoenix finals
rematch. Each conference champion earns a bye while the second- and
third-place finishers in each conference meet in one-game
quarterfinals. A best-of-three series then determines each
conference champion and the league champion.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the 32 regular-season games are against conference
opponents. Eight teams begin play Thursday, with the Mercury
starting Saturday at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The addition not only of ABL talent but of Chamique Holdsclaw,
arguably the most heralded collegian since Cheryl Miller, has teams
as down as 3-27 Washington talking playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we have a vision,'' former ABL MVP McCray said.
``Last year, we weren't so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of the Utah Starzz and Sacramento Monarchs,
neither of whom has managed more than 10 wins in each of the first
two seasons. And of the underachieving Los Angeles Sparks, who are
on their third coach, Orlando Woolridge, and have entrusted their
point guard position to rookie Ukari Figgs. At least Figgs, out of
NCAA champion Purdue, is familiar with the league's new hand-check
rule, which is consistent with how American women's college
basketball is called.
</P>
<P>
   Also new this year is the league's first All-Star Game, July 14
in New York, and expansion teams in Minnesota and Orlando. Next
year, the roster of teams grows to 16 with the addition of Portland
and Seattle in the Western Conference and Indianapolis and Miami in
the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you have a league and not have us in it?'' Indiana
Pacers President Donnie Walsh modestly declared Monday. ``This
legitimizes the WNBA.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA President Val Ackerman might remind Walsh that the league
bettered 1.6 million in regular-season attendance last year and
expects to maintain a 10,000-plus per-game average even with
expansion to Minnesota and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, Phoenix, New York and Washington averaged 12,600 to
15,900, with Cleveland and Detroit cracking the 10,000 barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana and company will have a ways to go with ABL leftovers
and inexperienced collegians to catch up with their brethren next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've proven beyond a doubt the existence of an
audience for women's professional basketball,'' Ackerman said. ``We
have found a different fan base than the NBA. The fan support we've
had has been truly amazing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
