<SLUG> BC-TV-MTV-REAL-WORLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOSE OF REALITY A SHOT IN THE ARM FOR MTV'S `REAL WORLD' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new season of ``The Real World premieres'' Tuesday on MTV, and
if the first episode is any indicator, expect this cast to bring
back the ``reality'' that made the show's early seasons so
captivating.
</P>
<P>
   When the dysfunctional docu-soap debuted in 1992, its concept
was simple: Pick seven strangers to live together and have their
lives taped to find out what happens when people stop being polite
and start getting real.
</P>
<P>
   A mostly Gen X audience tuned in weekly to see what the
roommates _ Julie, Eric, Heather, Kevin, Norman, Andre and Becky _
were up to in their Manhattan loft. Was Julie still a virgin? Could
model/actor wannabe Eric keep his shirt on? Would Kevin be angry,
again?
</P>
<P>
   It was new. It was fresh. And, except for Eric, we rarely felt
like cast members were posing for the cameras. Reality-based
programming was becoming a part of our TV culture, and we liked it.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Real World'' has never been as ``real'' as its debut
season. Because producers must cast from a pool of people who grew
up watching the show, it got harder to find those capable of
keeping it real. Remember the revolting Puck of the 1994 San
Francisco cast? His every action was contrived.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the concept remained simple. We long for the days when
cohabitation was all MTV asked of the roommates. In 1996, the Miami
cast struggled to start a business. We struggled to stay awake.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these flaws, we remain fans (ratings have increased 73
percent since the show's debut) because sparks of reality continue
to fly each season. Nothing has been more real than the life and
death of Pedro Zamora, an HIV-positive AIDS educator from the 1994
season in San Francisco. He died from AIDS-related complications
just days after the last episode aired.
</P>
<P>
   The seasons that followed _ London, Miami, Boston, Seattle _ had
their high, and low, points, but it always felt like the roommates
were too aware of the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle cast certainly had its ``real'' moments, including
Stephen slapping Irene. But it looks like the new season, set in
Hawaii, will bring the series back to its original glory.
</P>
<P>
   The cast, ranging in age from 19 to 22, seems oblivious to the
cameras. Today's young people have spent their formative years in
front of one lens or another _ at ATMs, in department stores, at
work _ and can watch others' lives unfold on the Internet. Perhaps
they've been desensitized to cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour season opener airs Tuesday night. More than 23,000
auditioned for the Hawaii season, but only seven made it. Let's
meet them:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ruthie,  &LR; 21, Hawaiian native, Rutgers University student,
bisexual with a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   In the first episode, Ruthie skinny-dips, drinks nonstop and
passes out in a bar. Two roommates take her home, where she has a
seizure, then is rushed to the hospital with alcohol poisoning. The
roommates hold an intervention, and producers, who say Ruthie hid
her alcoholism during the screening process, allow her to take a
30-day leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Kaia,  &LR; 22, African-American studies major at the University
of California-Berkeley, vegan, feminist.
</P>
<P>
   Kaia spends much of the season topless and announces in the
first episode: ``I really, really like looking at myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Teck,  &LR; 22, Illinois native, wannabe filmmaker, ladies' man.
</P>
<P>
   Teck is Ruthie's skinny-dipping partner in the first episode but
said during a recent interview: ``I didn't do it for shock
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Ruthie, Teck and Kaia, MTV had to increase its
blurring budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent thousands of dollars blurring the nudity,'' said
supervising producer Matt Kunitz. ``We figured if they are this
comfortable being nude, then we don't want to stifle that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amaya, 21, UCLA grad, sunny blonde, has issues with her body.
</P>
<P>
   Amaya takes care of the drunken Ruthie and cringes at her
skinny-dipping roommates. Will she be the den mother? She also
falls for Colin, giving the show its first serious intra-cast
romance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Colin, 19, Sports broadcasting major at Berkeley, reject
turned cast member.
</P>
<P>
   Colin falls for Amaya. Asked just how ``real'' the coverage of
their romance will be, he says, ``I was pretty open with everything
I did,'' but ``there isn't any tape of me doing the monkey dance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt, 22, Political science major at UCLA, wannabe script
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Could Matt be the most forgettable roommate? It looks like it in
the first episode
</P>
<P>
   _ Justin, 21, Child prodigy, gay activist, Harvard University
law student and Houston native.
</P>
<P>
   Justin doesn't last the season. Tune in to find out why, since
he isn't talking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz had this to say about the departure: ``He came into this
project with a different maturity level than your average cast
member. He may have come in thinking he would have more control
over the process. But you really just have to be yourself. It was
difficult for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like he just got sick of it. How real is that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
