A0136 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV13-C     06-10 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: FAST-FORWARDING THROUGH HISTORY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 13
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic presidential nominee Hillary Rodham(cq)
said today, ``I shall go to Kosovo'' in a bid to extract U.S.
forces from the Balkan quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Rodham's pledge to visit the shaky cease-fire lines as her first
presidential act was promptly assailed as ``an empty gesture'' by
Vice President Elizabeth Dole, the Republican choice to succeed
President George W. Bush in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting from her Internet site, people-first.com, Rodham
cited what she termed ``the long litany of Bush blunders that have
compelled our brave women and men to forgo their role as
peacekeepers to fight a ground war against the Eastern Orthodox
Axis on behalf of the Islamic Brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing her intention to visit a divided Kosovo if
elected, Rodham retraced what historians regard as a possible
turning point in the 1952 U.S. presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual victor, Dwight Eisenhower, had said ``I shall go to
Korea'' in criticizing another unpopular war. After taking office,
Eisenhower secretly told the North Koreans and Chinese that he was
prepared to use nuclear weapons and carry the war to China if peace
were not quickly achieved.
</P>
<P>
   An armistice was promptly signed. The fact that some 40,000 U.S.
troops remain on Korean soil, some 55 years after that cease-fire,
has not emerged as an issue in the 2008 elections.
</P>
<P>
   As she readied her White House run after winning a second Senate
term from New York, Rodham has increasingly turned her attention to
foreign affairs. Her opponent in the 2006 Democratic primary, Rep.
Andrew Cuomo, D-N.Y., a former Cabinet member in the Clinton
administration, has endorsed the Dole-Bush candidacy as ``my
personal moral choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo had sought to make an issue of Rodham's scandal-driven
divorce from former President Bill Clinton, now a wealthy Internet
attorney. But the press corps, reporting under the newly mandatory
Universal Polling Guidelines, frustrated Cuomo's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As a hundred million Americans prepare to vote in November on
the Internet, it is all but certain that Rodham has been
``inoculated'' against the issue of the now six-year-old divorce
proceedings. In a similar sense, Vice President Dole is seen as
having been ``inoculated'' against the ``Viagra hoax'' scandal that
once engulfed former Sen. Bob Dole, her 85-year-old husband and the
Second Spouse.
</P>
<P>
   But surveys suggest that both major party candidates face
political problems within a restive electorate in the wake of the
sporadic fighting in the Balkans that Clinton triggered in 1999 and
which Bush has not been able to halt. The prolonged hostilities
sparked the Turko-Greek-Cypriot War of 2004 that finally ruptured
the NATO alliance and revived the Cold War with the masters of the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is known to be weighing an exploratory mission to Moscow by
his trouble-shooting brother Jeb, the former Florida governor and
Dole's current running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The third-party tag team of Jesse Ventura and Jesse Jackson,
seeking to mount what they call ``a co-presidency'' in 2009, have
denounced both the projected Rodham and Bush trips as ``just more
messin' around.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
