<SLUG> BC-RED-VIOLIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A PERFECT SCORE   FOR `THE RED VIOLIN' 
(FOR USE BY NYTIMES NEWS SERVICE CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spanning five countries, four languages and more
than 300 years of history and cultural upheaval, ``The Red Violin''
certainly gets high marks for ambition, not to mention cinematic
form.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's interconnected stories _ held together by the
musical instrument of the title _ too often lack the kind of detail
and humanity needed to give the movie the resonance for which it
strives. In the end, this really is a just a movie about a violin,
and the inherent impersonality weighs a bit too heavily for it to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and co-written by Canada's Francois Girard, ``The Red
Violin'' feels like a natural extension of his 1994 cult favorite
``Thirty-Two Short Films About Glenn Gould.'' This time, though,
Girard and co-writer Don McKellar (who has a small role in the
movie) have chosen to profile a musical instrument instead of a
musician. It's an intriguing concept for a biography, since people
(save for biblical times) tend to expire after several decades,
while an object can live on for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The violin dates back to 1681, when it was made by a master
craftsman as a gift for his unborn son. (How it acquired its
unusual color is a mystery explained near the film's conclusion.)
The instrument then passes through the hands of several owners who
treat it, alternately, as a muse, a surrogate parent and a symbol
of cultural depravity.
</P>
<P>
   All this is foretold by the violin maker's housekeeper, who also
specializes in tarot card readings. Before each of the movie's five
main stories, Girard returns to a newly upturned tarot card that
predicts what is to come next. In a small way, this framing device
spoils the stories that follow, since it spells out their emotional
outcomes _ anger, infirmity, fear, rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Girard uses a second connecting device as well, that of a
modern-day auction of the red violin. (Samuel L. Jackson is the
segment's featured actor.) It's here that Girard's technical
proficiency shines best, as the movie repeatedly returns to the
auction house, each time revealing a new detail from a different
vantage point.
</P>
<P>
   All this structural complexity is interesting and, at times,
engaging. But the film's disparate stories aren't always fully
formed and often feel like one-note genre pieces. There's a costume
drama, a bodice-ripper, a political thriller.
</P>
<P>
   The stories have their moments and fine performances _ the
second segment about a lovably vain music master and his 6-year-old
child prodigy works best _ but in the end, it feels like Girard is
more interested in form than he is in storytelling. And the form is
hardly original. This sort of construction has been done before and
to better effect in Joseph Mankiewicz's ``A Letter to Three Wives''
and ``Tales of Manhattan'' (which followed a fancy tail coat).
</P>
<P>
   The movie's deficiencies come to a head during its final scenes,
which fail to tie up the story, mostly because Girard doesn't
supply the necessary details. Thus, rather than being a
transcendent statement about love and mortality, ``The Red Violin''
comes off resembling a performer who knows all about technique but
lacks the soul to bring it off. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
