<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0159 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTINPOWERS-REVIEW-L     06-10 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTINPOWERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY SPOOF SPUTTERS IN SECOND GO-AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are enough really funny gags in ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' to justify its existence.
</P>
<P>
   But just barely. This sequel to Mike Myers' '60s spy movie spoof
goes to heroic lengths to pump some clever new humor into what was,
even the first time out, a one-joke concept. It works sporadically,
but the strain shows.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who co-wrote the screenplay with Michael McCullers,
spreads the net of pop-culture references here to include riffs on
``The Jerry Springer Show,'' Viagra consciousness and even that
perplexing Elvis Costello-Burt Bacharach collaboration. But the
vigorous satire, even coupled with a kind of gross-out ingenuity
rivaling that of ``Something About Mary,'' can't counterbalance the
sequel's long mirthless stretches.
</P>
<P>
   Myers made the not-exactly-astute decision to focus this film's
attention more on the mincing Dr. Evil than on the prancing Powers.
And while he takes the villain to behavioral lengths that must have
been fun for Myers to play, they're not nearly as enjoyable to
watch as Austin when his mojo's working.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it? Austin's loss of mojo _ which can
politely be described as the unlikely love machine's life force _
is the movie's main plot point.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, British secret agent Powers was cryogenically
frozen in the late '60s and thawed out in the less swinging '90s.
So was his lifelong, equally incompetent foe, Dr. Evil. Unable to
conquer the brave new premillennial world, Evil returns to the '60s
in a time machine, where he has the iced Austin's biological
Gatorade extracted.
</P>
<P>
   Back (or is that forward?) in 1999, Austin suddenly feels a
certain something missing. So he has to go back 30 years, too,
where he hooks up with the CIA's beautiful and ultra-willing
Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham, who may not be a natural comic
but was made to wear go-go boots and crocheted dresses). Despite
Austin's uncharacteristic timidity, she gives her all to helping
him regain his juice and stop Dr. Evil's latest, ludicrous scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the master-villain-in-his-own-mind would likely succeed
anyway. He's too distracted by his own dysfunctional dilemmas to
dominate the planet. These include the disdain of his unloved son
Scott (Seth Green, funny like before), disagreeable henchmen (Rob
Lowe does an uncanny imitation of Robert Wagner as the younger
version of Number Two) and his infatuation with a one-eighth-sized
clone of himself that he dotingly dubs Mini-Me (Verne Troyer,
uncannily mimicking Myers' mannerisms).
</P>
<P>
   The psychocomedy that grows out of all this is amusing the first
couple of times, but less so as it drags on through the film.
</P>
<P>
   Myers also takes on a third persona as another Evil operative, a
grotesquely obese Scotsman whose name cannot be printed in a family
newspaper. He's the source of most of the film's disgusting humor,
and the fat suit is a pretty impressive special-effects job from
the Stan Winston Studios.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's overall look is also a treat, brimming with
retro-mod references from Rusty Smith's bright, sightgag-strewn
production design to Deena Appel's goofy-yet-flattering British
Invasion costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Roach, who also directed the original ``Austin Powers:
International Man of Mystery,'' brings more of the same off-rhythm
that one had to ``Spy's'' shaggy comedy (not to mention some of the
same bits). Islands of high hilarity dot an often tedious sea in
which Myers rows strenuously without always getting anywhere. Good
times can be had with ``Spy,'' but a reliable humor mojo would have
made it a more shagaliciously satisfying experience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
