<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARMLESS-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-10 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARMLESS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN, WOMEN AND SEX GET SUPERFICIAL TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The gimmick that's supposed to make ``Just a
Little Harmless Sex'' stand out from the run of cheap romantic
comedies is that its male characters were written by a man and its
female characters were written by a woman. Not a bad idea, but one
nonetheless crucially dependent on the writers being clever,
regardless of their gender.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Mills, a former assistant director, and Marti Noxon, a
co-producer on TV's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' don't exactly
display sparkling wit in their script for this low-budget ensemble
comedy. Not much insight, either; the basic deal here is that men
are ruled by their urges, women are only slightly more repressed,
but true love is what they both really need to live happily ever
after.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is on three young adults of each persuasion, all of
them generic types. Alan (Robert Mailhouse) is unfulfillingly
married to Laura (Alison Eastwood). We first see him in a strip
club with his buddies, the divorced and vocally sex-obsessed Danny
(Jonathan Silverman) and the quietly sex-obsessed bachelor Brent
(William Ragsdale). With that beginning, we really can't feel too
much sympathy for the guy when, after being arrested for giving a
beautiful girl with car trouble a lift, he honestly claims not to
have known she was a hooker.
</P>
<P>
   Laura deals with her apparently ruined marriage by getting drunk
with her pals _ Danny's promiscuous ex Terrianne (Jessica Lundy)
and cute-but-doesn't-know-it Ally (``Father of the Bride's''
Kimberly Williams) _ then going out to the same pickup bar the guys
are hopping in and out of.
</P>
<P>
   You won't believe what complications ensue!
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe you will. Mousey Ally, who says things like, ``I
never did nubile _ I went straight from awkward to gawky,'' has too
much to drink and does an impromptu striptease. Danny, who says
things like, ``We cannot help it, it's biological'' in regard to
male infidelity, endeavors to kiss and make up with Terrianne in
the men's room. Brent becomes infatuated with Laura's worldly
mother, most probably because she's played by Lauren Hutton.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough by-the-numbers dumb misunderstandings,
inappropriate clinches and just-missings of significant others to
make an episode of ``Friends'' seem like ``Shakespeare in Love'' by
comparison. Little about the playing or staging salvages the
superficial material.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Rick Rosenthal, has done some fine television
work, including the pilot episodes for such noteworthy series as
``The Practice'' and ``Life Goes On.'' He also made a good, tough
prison feature with Sean Penn, ``Bad Boys,'' in 1983, but since
then his theatrical output has been pretty shaky. This outing is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal doesn't show any particular flair for comic timing or
sensitivity to the serious emotional contradictions ``Harmless''
hints at here. He also made the rather curious decision to turn the
film's cinematography over to Bruce Surtees, a fine interpreter of
Clint Eastwood's darker visions but not necessarily the right guy
for glib comedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Just a Little Harmless Sex'' lives up to the
harmless part of its title. But ``Just a Little Forgettable Sex''
would be just as apt a label. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
