<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-LADN &LR;      06-10 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE MYERS' SPY POWERS HIS WAY INTO POP CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
( EDS:  Note use of italics throughout)  
BY GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Mike Myers never planned to make an ``Austin
Powers'' sequel. He figured the first movie, 1997's ``Austin
Powers: International Man of Mystery,'' made a little money, earned
him a few critical kudos and steered his career back on track after
disappointments like the ``Wayne's World'' sequel and ``So I
Married an Axe Murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the movie came out on video and Myers' plans changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just took on this kind of weird life of its own,'' Myers
says. ``I heard through somebody, and I don't know if this is true,
that when King Hussein (the late ruler of Jordan) was sick at the
Mayo Clinic, he would watch `Austin Powers,' and it would revive
his spirits. And supposedly, he went to the Pentagon in some sort
of high-level defense capacity and stormed in and announced,
`Gentlemen, I want 20 F-16s and one (BEGIN ITALICS)meeelion!(END
ITALICS) dollars.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that mind-blowing story,'' Myers says, shaking
his head, ``I knew we had made it into the pop-culture lexicon.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. Just a sampling of the film's catchphrases _ (BEGIN
ITALICS)``Yeah, baby!'' ``Oh, behave!'' ``Do I make you
randy?''(END ITALICS) _ indicates just how much the swinging secret
agent has infiltrated our consciousness. And with the sequel,
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' arriving in theaters
today, the number of bad Austin Powers imitations is only going to
multiply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie is loaded with conversation pieces, and that's a big
part of its success,'' says Paul Dergarabedian, president of the
box-office tracking firm Exhibitor Relations Co. ``If you haven't
seen the movie, you won't get what everybody's talking about. `Star
Wars' was like that, and it's the same thing with `Austin Powers.'
It's part of our culture now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is rather remarkable, given the movie's humble origins.
Myers' wife, writer Robin Ruzan, knew he was onto something one
night when she heard her husband splashing around in the bathroom,
bellowing, ``Yeah, baby! Do I make you horny, baby?'' It all came
from Dusty Springfield's version of ``The Look of Love,'' the
sensual Burt Bacharach song that to Myers evokes images of ``lust,
libido, mojo, James Bond and all that other swinging stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Baby.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, 36, then wrote a movie that paid humorous homage to all
the things his late father loved _ Peter Sellers movies, ``Our Man
Flint,'' ``Beyond the Fringe,'' Monty Python, ``The Goon Show'' _
and convinced New Line Cinema to put up a few million dollars to
make it. Test screenings were, as they say, inconclusive, and there
were many at the studio who believed audiences just wouldn't get
all the English humor and phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some hand-wringing and maybe deservedly so,'' says
Jay Roach, the USC film school graduate who has directed both
movies. ``More or less, we were making that first movie for
ourselves and our friends. We figured it would reach a Monty
Python-sized audience, which, in this country, isn't all that
big.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie opened in May 1997, made $9 million in its first week
and held on to rake in a respectable gross of $54 million _ or
about what ``The Phantom Menace'' made in two days. But ``Austin
Powers'' received a second life on video, selling more than 3
million copies and earning $47 million in rental revenue. The film
remained one of Billboard's top rentals well into this year,
whetting the public's appetite for the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of layers to Mike's comedy, and it's not that
easy to take it all in in just one viewing,'' says ``Powers''
producer John Lyons. ``You get the physical, broad stuff when you
first see it. But then there are these subtle things going on in
the background, along with verbal and pop-culture components.
Bottom line, though, it's a producer's dream. People like to watch
it again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   And that leads to the smashing forecasts for ``The Spy Who
Shagged Me.'' Basically, the sequel flips the plot. This time,
Austin must travel from the 1990s back to the psychedelic '60s so
he can recover his ``mojo'' _ the very quality that makes him so
shagadelic _ from nemesis Dr. Evil. Myers again plays both parts as
well as a third _ a corpulent Scotsman named Fat Bastard.
</P>
<P>
   The humor, never subtle to begin with, is even more outrageous
this time around. (The title alone is raising a small ruckus in
England, where shag does (BEGIN ITALICS)not(END ITALICS) refer to a
loose-knit type of carpet.) Bathroom jokes abound, and there's
plenty of screen time for a pint-sized Dr. Evil clone, Mini-Me,
played by a 28-inch-tall actor. Heather Graham replaces Elizabeth
Hurley (who does turn up for a cameo) as Austin's sexy sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin has always been a superspy with a 13-year-old
mentality,'' Roach says.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Myers: ``People just want to have a good time right now.
We're at the end of the second millennium, and it's like a
pop-cultural appetizer tray where people want to sample a little
bit of this and a little bit of that, but mostly, I think people
really want to enjoy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Myers also maintains that the ``Austin Powers'' movies
contain a message, albeit one disguised like a Flintstones vitamin.
(``They don't need to know that it's good for them,'' Myers quips.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Myers, the central question of the first movie was:
Will Austin find love despite his outmoded sexual mores? Move
forward to ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' where the core issue is:
Will Austin find love despite his lack of belief in love due to a
broken heart and a rekindling of his old swinger ways?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a whole lot in common, but Austin and I are
believers in true love,'' the unfailingly polite and sincere Myers
says.
</P>
<P>
   Such reads may be a tad deep for a series that strives to find
as many uses for the word ``shag'' as possible. More likely,
audiences connect with Austin because, for a guy with bad teeth,
(shag-)carpet chest hair and a wardrobe that would be the envy of
Little Lord Fauntleroy, he's completely and infectiously confident.
And pretty funny, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin is like a breath of fresh air,'' says Myers' friend Rob
Lowe, who has a small part in the new movie. ``People respond to
his enthusiasm and his love of life. He's a little _ how shall I
put it? _ dense, but he charges forward with this insanely positive
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Graham: ``I'd shag him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too late for that, though. Austin belongs to the world now.
HBO has an Austin Powers animated series in the works. His likeness
is selling a host of beverages _ Starbucks coffee, Heineken beer,
milk (BEGIN ITALICS)(smashing moustache, baby!(END ITALICS) _ and
is also featured on those ubiquitous Virgin ``Shaglantic'' Airlines
billboards. And, of course, there's the usual array of trinkets _
key chains, T-shirts, watches, action figures, books _ and the
not-so-usual (embossed martini glasses).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, everyone is already asking for (yet) another sequel.
Myers is non-committal, saying he never makes plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if my heart is in it, and Jay's around, then I'm sure it
would be fun,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Roach seems to already be sketching the plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think about it,'' the director says. ``I
always have to cut certain things from the movie, which is painful,
but then I think, `Well, OK. Maybe we can use it in the next one.'
We've got a lot of that stuff, so, basically, we could start
tomorrow _ even without a script.''
</P>
<P>
   To which, fans will no doubt say: Yeah, baby! Yeah! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
