<HEADER>
A0211 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LIMBO-TEX     06-10 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIMBO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ACTING IS GREAT, BUT `LIMBO' LEAVES YOU HANGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director John Sayles, the first of the indie film heroes,
knows what to do with actresses. He gives Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio one of the best parts of her career in his newest
film, ``Limbo.'' She plays Donna, a down-on-her-luck lounge singer
who drags her teen-age daughter, Noelle (Dallas native Vanessa
Martinez), with her whenever she feels the need to relocate. This
time, it's to a small Alaska town, called Port Henry, given its
full natural glory by cinematographer Haskell Wexler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' is not just Donna's story, even though Mastrantonio's
performance dominates the film. The entire town is in a state of
limbo, caught between circumstances. Joe (David Strathairn) carries
his dislocation around with him, like a cloud of bad luck hanging
over his head. He's moved from one job to another because an
accident on one of his fishing trips has shaken his confidence.
He's been distant and slightly lost ever since. All that remains is
his fundamental decency. It's a quality that both Donna and Noelle
fall for.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to not respond to Sayles' ambitions _ at least for me.
He has a deep-set interest in how people's work defines them, and
how being stripped of vocational definition can rob them of
something integral to their beings. (He once said no one eats or
makes love eight hours a day, but most of us do spend that much
time at work. The only thing we spend as much time at is sleep.)
</P>
<P>
   Being so deprived can leave anyone in a state of limbo, even
though some try to fight it, as does Leo Burmester. He plays
Harmon, an angry ex-fisherman who now works at a canning factory.
When Sayles finds the right actors, like Burmester, ``Limbo''
springs to life. Mastrantonio, with her stubborn vivacity, sends
real experience through the film. (She also does a fine job singing
in her performance scenes.) The young Martinez comes through
beautifully. Hypersensitive and willful, she matches up physically
and psychologically with Mastrantonio. She's part of a new wave of
distinctive and watchable young actresses who are making the future
of film exciting to behold _ especially when the two find
themselves trapped with Joe on an uninhabited island after a
boating tragedy that involves Joe's brother (Casey Siemaszko).
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Sayles has become more confident and willing to
take risks himself. ``Limbo'' contains a scene that has now become
his signature: He moves the camera through a big event, shifting
the film's focus from one character to another, giving us a sense
of what's going with each person. It's a way to use his limited
financial resources, as well as to stretch and give his films a
cinematic import.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few times we get a rush of filmmaking energy
from him, because ``Limbo'' has that fixed, literary quality that
can sometimes make his films dreary. The allegories are worked out
in an almost mechanical manner. This can makes Sayles' storytelling
less than engaging, as is the case here. The rigidity is
oppressive, and ``Limbo'' is hard to enjoy because of it; even the
ending lends itself to the title, and audiences may be left
unsatisfied, no matter how much of an affinity they may have for
Sayles' work.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Limbo''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Sayles
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: David Strathairn, Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio
</P>
<P>
   Length: 126 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and brief violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
