</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WARMONGER DOES SOMETHING RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Before I go back to blasting him about the war
against Yugoslavia, I want to thank President Clinton for a couple
of recent moves. They reminded me of why I twice voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   1. The long overdue but wily appointment of James Hormel as
ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 months, a handful of reactionary, homophobic Senate
Republicans used a nasty little procedural trick to keep Hormel's
nomination from coming to the Senate floor for a vote. The
president trumped their trick with one of his own: the chief
executive's right to make appointments while Congress is in recess.
</P>
<P>
   The ultra-conservatives used their trick _ called a ``hold'' _
because they knew it was the only way to keep the 66-year-old San
Francisco philanthropist from being confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Since October 1997, when Clinton nominated Hormel, the votes
have been there. The Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved
the nomination 16-2. A majority of senators supported his
appointment, including Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. And the Luxembourg
government said he was most officially welcome.
</P>
<P>
   None of those people, it seems, gives a rat's bum about the fact
that Hormel is a comfortably out-of-the-closet gay man. The
ultra-conservatives _ led by Sens. James Inhofe, R-Okla., and Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., who created the hold _ care a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott cares, too _ enough to aid and
abet the hold for 18 months instead of acting like a man and
allowing a full Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, Lott, R-Miss., says he believes that
homosexuality is not only a sin but a curable disease like
kleptomania or alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Other than being gay, everything about Hormel screams,
``Traditional U.S. diplomatic corps!''
</P>
<P>
   He's male, rich, white, elegant, educated, cosmopolitan and
comes from a fine old family. He's a father, served as the dean of
the University of Chicago Law School and as a U.S. delegate to the
United Nations Human Rights Commission in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Like many ambassadors, Hormel is a generous donor to his
favorite political party and drops big bucks on charity ($500,000
to the San Francisco Public Library alone).
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton did his end-run around the vacationing Congress,
Inhofe whined like a child that the Hormel appointment ``shows
President Clinton's utter contempt of the Senate and its values.''
A week later he retreated to the shallowest end of the baby pool
and vowed to hold up every Clinton nomination because the president
had ``forfeited the presumption of any cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator, the man beat you at your own game. Grow up.
</P>
<P>
   2. Kudo II goes to Clinton for holding the first-ever White
House conference on mental illness and for pledging $7.3 million
for a National Institute of Mental Health study of mental illness
and a national training program for teachers to recognize and help
disturbed children.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even better, the president informed managers of nearly 300
health plans used by federal employees that they must cover mental
illness and substance abuse. He urged private employers to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tipper Gore headlined the conference and spoke about her
own struggle with clinical depression, some cynics dismissed the
mental illness action program as an administration ploy to make
Vice President Al Gore a more attractive presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, so what? For the first time in history a
president has insisted that we stop stigmatizing the tens of
millions of Americans who suffer from mental illness, and he has
put some substantial money where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if Clinton called the conference to make his dog
Buddy look good; $7.3 million is $7.3 million. Besides, as
manipulative political posturing goes, I'll take a conference on
mental illness over the bombing of Serbia any day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
