<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BESIEGED-TEX     06-10 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BESIEGED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LUSH LOOK AT A LOVE BEYOND WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Besieged,'' director Bernardo Bertolucci proves himself
one of film's reigning sensualists. There's so much visual and
aural texture here that you realize it's more than 10 minutes into
the picture before we hear either of the protagonists speak.
</P>
<P>
   One of those protagonists is Shandurai (Thandie Newton), whose
schoolteacher husband is arrested by the militia of their small
African country. Before we know it, she's in Italy, where she's
studying to be a doctor and working as a housekeeper for a British
recluse/pianist named Mr. Kinsky (David Thewlis), who she thinks is
rich.
</P>
<P>
   Baroque and swooningly romantic, ``Besieged'' plays at a high
emotional pitch. The music in the film spells out Shandurai's
emotional states. This motif could be condescending in the wrong
hands, since Shandurai screams at Kinsky, ``I don't understand your
music,'' as he toys at a classical composition. But it's clear this
music means something to Shandurai. It's a constant part of her
life, her soul, and it helps to ease some of her feelings of
alienation in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' has an extraordinary suppleness and visual
richness. After the torpor of his last movie, ``Stealing Beauty,''
Bertolucci is awake and focused here. He's helped by having an
actress up to the demands the movie makes of her. At times,
Shandurai is painfully, desperately alone; as played by Newton, her
feelings are always erupting to the surface. Those who recoiled
during Newton's no-holds-barred performance as the title spirit in
``Beloved'' may re-experience some of that discomfort here.
</P>
<P>
   Newton is not afraid of looking foolish, and sometimes she looks
just so. That bravery also helps her succeed at depicting a full,
potent brew of drama that a Bertolucci movie hasn't offered in some
time. (Bertolucci gains by falling for Newton. She deserves a
director who knows how to use her gifts, as her talent has shone
through in roles in which she's barely been used.)
</P>
<P>
   Thewlis, who looks like a combination of Alan Rickman and Pete
Townshend of the Who _ most specifically in his slim-lipped cruelty
_ suffers exquisitely here. Kinsky sells off his possessions,
including his prized piano, to help finance a legal defense for
Shandurai's husband. He wilts in the room whenever he beholds
Newton's ripe beauty, and who can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bertolucci's days of plumbing new depths in the medium are
behind him. Yet there's a radiance, a sureness of touch coupled
with his astonishing taste and style, that makes ``Besieged'' a
unique pleasure. It glows.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Besieged''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bernardo Bertolucci
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Thandie Newton, David Thewlis
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations, and brief nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
