<P>
   CLINTON-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ President Clinton's most
enduring legacy in foreign affairs may his willingness to intervene
in the internal affairs of sovereign nations to combat humanitarian
disaster. A News Analysis. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ With Thursday's the first
successful intercept of a ballistic missile by the $4 billion THAAD
anti-missile system, defense contractor Lockheed-Martin Inc. is
under intense financial pressure to do it again by July 16. If the
anti-missile system doesn't score a second successful intercept by
the deadline, the firm will owe the Pentagon $20 million in
penalties. Lockheed has already paid the Pentagon $15 million after
a failed test in March. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Washington) _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, says the
flow of illegal immigrants into the United States will worsen
unless President Clinton increases the number of Border Patrol
agents along the Southwest Border. He also called on the Clinton
administration to remove illegal aliens already in the United
States. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
