<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HARMLESSSEX-TEX     06-10 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HARMLESSSEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A LITTLE CHARMLESS MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, movie reviewers have consciences (well, some
of us do), and a negative reaction to a film like ``Just a Little
Harmless Sex'' can induce pangs of guilt. Here's a little movie
that's apparently well-meaning, modestly budgeted, cast with
familiar faces but bereft of ``stars,'' and devoid of the
calculation that goes into a crowd-pleasing confection like
``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking on a film like this feels kind of like bullying, but the
truth is that ``Just a Little Harmles Sex'' is just a little
needless movie. The acting is OK at best, the direction static
despite some nifty camera movements, courtesy of veteran
cinematographer Bruce Surtees. The main villain, though, is the
screenplay, which is yet another hackneyed variation on the battle
of the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   The set-up: Alan (Robert Mailhouse), having left his buddies
behind at the topless bar, comes to the aid of a stranded woman on
a rainy night. Turns out she's a hooker, because in the sexist
world of movies, all stranded women on rainy nights are either
hookers or victims. Alan can't resist a little sexual favor from
her, and naturally this doesn't go over too well with his wife,
Laura (Alison Eastwood), who dumps Alan and cuts his face out of
all their family pictures.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Alan and Laura kind of choose teams. On Alan's team
are Danny (Jonathan Silverman), a male-pig sort who's working out
his anger over his own divorce, and Brent (William Ragsdale), whose
main purpose in the movie seems to be to give the male team as many
players as the female team. On Laura's team is Danny's ex,
Terrianne (Jessica Lundy), who's apparently so loose that she has
slept with every guy in town even though she can't reach a climax;
and Allison (Kimberly Williams of the ``Father of the Bride''
movies, virtually unrecognizable in a boyish haircut), who's shy
and demure _ except, of course, when she drinks.
</P>
<P>
   This examination of male-female relationships was co-written by
Marti Noxon, who handled the female characters, and Roger Mills,
who provides the male perspective. Their not-too-surprising
insights: Men just can't help themselves when it comes to sex;
women like sex, too! Just because the movie's not calculated
doesn't mean it's not contrived; didn't anyone learn from the
awkwardness of 1991's similarly constructed ``He Said, She Said''
that such a forced screenwriting collaboration is better in theory
than it is in practice?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, but then it's apparent that the people involved here
haven't really learned much of anything, or at least haven't paid
attention to a decade's worth of TV, where shows such as
``Seinfeld,'' ``Friends'' and even ``Melrose Place'' have addressed
sexual politics in much more deft and entertaining ways.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly surprising when you consider all the TV
vets involved, from Lundy (as entertainingly flinty here as she was
in the short-lived sitcom ``Hope &AMP; Gloria'') to Silverman (not
quite as irritating here as he was in the sitcom bomb ``The Single
Guy'') to Noxon, who works with much more incisive material as
co-producer of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie suffers from having such bland leads as Mailhouse and
Eastwood, and from a playlike structure that populates its few sets
with dozens of extras but barely a dozen speaking parts.
Actress-models Lauren Hutton and Rachel Hunter, along with
musicians Nuno Bettencourt and Tito Larriva, help flesh things out,
but to little avail. ``Just a Little Harmless Sex'' feels like what
it is, a personal film developed among friends. But that doesn't
mean you or your friends should see it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Just a Little Harmless Sex''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rick Rosenthal
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Robert Mailhouse, Alison Eastwood, Jonathan Silverman
</P>
<P>
   Length: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, sexual dialogue and situations, and strong
language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
