<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-CLASH-LADN &LR;      06-10 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIO'S SOCIAL COMEDY TAPS INTO BORDER ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The ``all-American monster,'' as Richard Montoya
calls it, wears the bland, baby-faced expression of Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, there are the two Columbine High School seniors,
staring out from the 15th anniversary flier that Montoya and the
other two members of the Latino comedy troupe Culture Clash are
using to promote their 15th anniversary tour.
</P>
<P>
   Less familiar are the flier's two other faces, those of Montoya
and Herbert Siguenza as they appeared in their own high school
yearbooks. Culture Clash's third member, Ric Salinas, declined to
include his face in the flier, having been the random victim of a
shooting himself several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he is represented by an acerbic message: ``Violent people,
guns &AMP; the NRA Suck!''
</P>
<P>
   A touch of gallows humor, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But Culture Clash believes that America currently is in the
midst of a cultural war, being fought with live ammunition. That,
they say, is where theater comes in. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was talking to each other in Littleton, Colo.,''
Montoya explains. ``That is the antithesis of what Culture Clash
and what good theater ought to be doing, is provoking discussion,
provoking dialogue. Because the Littleton, Colorados of the world
are going to start popping up more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   After several years of performing throughout the United States,
the aggressively non-politically correct L.A.-based trio is popping
up in its hometown this week for a five-week engagement of
``Culture Clash in Bordertown'' at the Actors' Gang in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Originally commissioned by the San Diego Repertory Theatre,
where it was produced last June, the piece is a series of
identity-switching skits about the various borders _ economic,
political, sociological and even cosmic _ that divide citizens of
that gaping !ital!frontera!off! encompassing San Diego and its
Latinate twin, Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Based on weeks of firsthand observation and more than 100
interviews the trio conducted with residents on both sides of the
fence, ``Bordertown'' weighs in on a number of thorny issues
including ethnic tensions, anti-gay discrimination within the U.S.
armed services, xenophobic performing killer whales and the
ultimate flight from reality's border undertaken by the Heaven's
Gate cult.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Culture Clash stocks its comic arsenal with
vaudeville, commedia dell'arte techniques and a sardonically hip
sensibility that American Theatre magazine likened to ``the Marx
Brothers meet the Rolling Stones.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of the more painful themes in ``Bordertown'' will be
all-too-familiar to Angelenos, Montoya suggests there may be an
additional ``subtext'' beneath the show's jocular facade.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last five years, thanks to people like Gov. Pete
Wilson, (they) have kept us so obsessively focused on the border
and the `brown tide' that comes from the south,'' he says. ``While
we were so focused on that, militias got armed to the teeth and the
all-American monster next door was building pipe bombs. Now, I've
never heard of an illegal immigrant blowing up a federal building.
We've got the monster and the terror right in our back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: It's a war zone out there, folks.
</P>
<P>
   However, Montoya stresses, we're all implicated in this
conflagration, not just the Dylan Klebolds and Eric Harrises
lurking among us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here pointing the finger and saying, `Those are
white suburbanites.' We're saying that when Culture Clash goes to
new cities like Detroit or New York or Lawrence, Kan., instead of
everybody rushing us to the inner-city school to go talk to
inner-city schoolkids, people better start getting us out to the
white suburban high schools too. And we better be prepared to try
to make sense to these kids out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bordertown'' may come as a bit of a surprise to those who
haven't seen Culture Clash in a while. Founded in 1984, on Cinco de
Mayo, the group initially favored a broad style of physical comedy
that in some ways echoed the stand-up-comic heyday of the
mid-Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   But, partly because Culture Club was ``never were really
embraced'' by mainstream comedy clubs, Montoya says, the troupe
began gravitating toward university campuses and legitimate
theaters, honing its acting chops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Culture Clash material also assimilated modern playwrights like
Bertolt Brecht and Dario Fo, the scathing monologues of Lenny Bruce
and the timeless comic insights of the classic Greek dramatist
Aristophanes.
</P>
<P>
   Culture Clash began developing more ambitious pieces such as
``The Mission'' (1990), whose definitive moment is a sequence in
which Father Junipero Serra literally beats religion into some
hapless Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mission'' paved the way for the group's 1994 breakthrough
work, ``Radio Mambo,'' about the frothing ethnic and cultural
jambalaya that is the city of Miami. It was later performed at
L.A.'s Tamarind Theatre, where it won Theatre L.A.'s Ovation award
for ensemble performance.
</P>
<P>
   Culture Clash's growing reputation has taken it to Lincoln
Center, the Kennedy Center, off-Broadway, the Mark Taper Forum and
the La Jolla Playhouse _ where it recently did a version of
Aristophanes' ``The Birds'' _ among other venues.
</P>
<P>
   Its production of ``A Bowl of Beings'' premiered on PBS' ``Great
Performances'' in 1992, and the group has been seen, individually
and/or collectively, in such feature films as ``Encino Man,''
``Falling Down,'' ``Mi Vida Loca'' and ``Star Maps.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that under their belts, it was time to reconnect with
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Bordertown,' the subject matter is a lot closer to us.
It's about Southern California, it's about the border, it's about
Mexicans,'' says Siguenza. ``I think it's a little funner than
`Radio Mambo,' it has some glimpses of, like, our older styles here
and there, a little broader here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing here (at Actors' Gang) was totally strategic,''
Siguenza goes on. ``We've got to be honest. It's kind of in the
middle of the city. When you play the LATC, you get no Westsiders.
They're not going to cross Vermont (Avenue). So it's totally
strategic. We said, `We've got to be in the middle of the city
where we get Eastsiders and Westsiders.'''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Montoya, ``And people from the Valley, for God's sake!''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Angelenos are able to see their own reflections in the
mirror of San Diego-Tijuana, Culture Clash appears to have crossed
a border of its own. As the trio closes in on middle age _ Siguenza
is 40, Salinas and Montoya both 38 _ their focus has shifted
steadily away from pratfalls to a more sobering perspective on
life.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas, who nearly died of a shotgun blast to the chest while
trying to break up a fight between two kids eight years ago, thinks
that incident, in particular, cast a shadow of mortality and
seriousness over the group's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, I think our work has always been pretty full of
life-and-death situations,'' he observes. ``So here in Los Angeles,
with this piece, `Bordertown,' you're going to see that it is going
to be funny, but we're really saying some heavy stuff.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
