</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-YANKEES (Washington) _ As the World Champions visit the
White House Thursday, Hillary Clinton is proudly describing
herself, a native of Chicago, as a life-long Yankee fan. Some,
however, including her potential rival for the New York Senate,
Mayor Rudy Giuliani, beg to differ. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court, by a 6 to 3 vote,
upholds a lower court ruling that a Chicago city anti-loitering law
is unconstitutional. The law said that a person could not hang
around on the street with a known gang member if the police said to
move on. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION (Washington) _ The Christian Coalition loses
its tax exempt status, a blow to a once powerful lobbying group
already waning in influence. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES (Washington) _ The major airlines, trying to stave off
``passenger rights'' bills, say they will voluntarily adopt reforms
like providing food, water and toilets to passengers stranded on
snowbound airplanes; they also promise to tell customers about
known delays and cancellations, return misrouted luggage faster,
raise payments for lost luggage, and give customers who phone for
tickets a better chance at getting the lowest-cost fares. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan reports its economy grew by a
surprisingly robust 1.9 percent in the first three months of the
year, largely because of increased public spending. The increase in
gross domestic product is the first since the summer of 1997 and
baffles some economists, who doubt that the nation has actually
emerged from its longest recession since World War II. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ECON (London) _ The Bank of England cuts its benchmark
interest rate by a surprise quarter percentage point to 5 percent,
the lowest level since October 1977. By Alan Cowell
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the Dow industrial average was
down 135 points, or 1 percent. By Robert Hershey.
</P>
