<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES UNFAZED AD-BLOCKING SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fed up with advertising banners crowding your
screen while surfing the Web? Thanks to numerous versions of
ad-blocking software that are relatively inexpensive, and often
free, you can live a banner-free lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to a security guard at the front gate, ``ad blockers''
ward off any unwelcome ad intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   The software monitors block strings that indicate the nature of
what is being transmitted to your browser. Once identified as an
advertisement, the software instructs the browser not to download
it to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   According to Anne Marshall, product marketing manager for the
Seattle-based software company WRQ Inc., by preventing the often
image-heavy ads from downloading, Web users experience much faster
download times. ``Users should experience downloads that are up to
six times faster,'' said Marshall, whose company makes and markets
AtGuard ad-blocking software.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ad-blocking technology doesn't seem to unravel Internet
businesses, where banner advertising revenue is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   According to Drew Ianni, an advertising analyst at the New
York-based consulting firm Jupiter Communications, this year's
on-line advertising expenditures will top $3 billion. That will
continue to grow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to release our 2003 projection, and that will
probably call for it to eclipse $10 billion,'' Ianni said.
</P>
<P>
   David Sims, editorial director of Web Review.Com, a publication
that relies on advertising to stay in business, said losing
advertising dollars due to ad blockers is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ad-blocking software is really not very high on our radar
screen,'' Sims said from his office in Sebastopol, Calif. ``It
certainly doesn't keep us up at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims describes a ``covenant'' between Web users and Web content
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of users understand the deal. We spend our time and
effort to create content. Part of the reason we show up is to get
paid, and the way we get paid is selling ad space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Charlene Li, senior analyst with Forrester
Research, a consulting firm based in Cambridge, Mass., ad blockers
are of little worry because they are rarely used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people use it or even care about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett, founder and president of Junkbusters Inc., a New
Jersey company that distributes free ad-blocking software from its
Web site (www.junkbusters.com), acknowledges that few Web surfers
use the software. He said his product and products like it would
not hurt advertising revenue ``that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts do not track use of ad-blocking software, but
the companies producing it report that sales are doing well.
``Interest has definitely been on the rise,'' Marshall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
