</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARROGANCE-AIDS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG MEDICAL WORKER PLANS A CULTURALLY SENSITIVE AIDS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Color photo of Sarah Stewart with a young Haitian orphan is
available.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALISON ARCHER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As American colleges release thousands of graduates this spring
to seek promising careers in business or go on to further study,
one of the nation's brightest is passing up medical school to
enlist in the fight against a deadly and badly misunderstood
disease in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Stewart, a 22-year-old Fulbright Scholar, Truman Scholar
and USA Today Academic All-American, is heading for Africa to mount
a unique attack on the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Her focus is Namibia, a small country situated at the
southeastern tip of the continent where, if the current rate of HIV
infection persists, one-quarter of the population will be wiped out
by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering a record 26 percent infection rate, Namibia's campaign
against AIDS has been hindered by a lack of healthcare education,
facilities and media technology to promote awareness.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of an $18,414 Joanna Jackson Goldman Memorial
Prize, Stewart will conduct an HIV and AIDS education and research
project. It will focus on exploration of the indigenous culture and
modification of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's first taste of medical missionary service was in
Port-au-Prince, Haiti, two years ago. It was quite a change from
the comfortable neighborhood where she grew up in Peoria, Ill., and
her four years on the campus of Miami University in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls that one day in 1997, as she walked the streets of
Port au Prince, she heard a soft voice whisper, ``Anmwe. M'ap
mouri,'' which in Haitian Creole means, ``Help. I'm dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The plea came from an abandoned little girl lying in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her tiny hands groped over her body, scratching the scabies
that infested the sores under her armpits, legs and groin,''
Stewart says. ``Her ribs were clearly visible, bulging through her
translucent brown skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made no sound as I picked her up to take her with us.''
The child died a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw dying people lying in the dirt, singing spirituals and
hoping to die,'' Stewart says.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that trip, as she rocked children with sad eyes,
wounded spirits and stomachs distended by hunger, at the
Missionaries of Charity Orphanage, that she decided to work for
change in international healthcare attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   She sees the arrogance of western culture as a major hurdle in
promoting health reforms in third world countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The root of the healthcare problems in the international world
is (our) attitude that if something is different, it's wrong. We've
got to overcome that,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Dr. Martin Bosman, a Namibian professor
visiting Miami University, Stewart will focus on the eight local
tribes' understanding of the country's history, leaders, practices
and resources. She plans to use case studies and questionnaires to
form a culturally sensitive program that will be embraced by the
community.
</P>
<P>
   During the year-long project, which begins in August, she will
study local cultures to isolate the problems that make their region
home to three-fifths of the world's AIDS population.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's unique approach to the Namibia project, stemming from
her mission work with the sick and poverty-stricken in Haiti and
India, began under the direction of Dr. John Caroll, an
emergency-room doctor at St. Francis Hospital in Peoria.
</P>
<P>
   In Stewart's first experience with Third World healthcare, she
brought six Haitian children to the U.S. for life-saving surgery,
after lobbying for visas, raising money for airfare, and locating
U.S. doctors to donate surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the children received open-heart surgery. Two
hydrocephalic babies, with a deadly condition of fluid collecting
on the brain, underwent surgery, and one blind boy received a
cornea transplant, restoring his sight.
</P>
<P>
   These are stories of success, but Stewart also tells stories of
tragedy and death.
</P>
<P>
   She held a 5-pound, 8-month-old girl, Alice, in her arms as the
baby died, so she wouldn't be alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly, I began to accept my limitations, and realize that,
sometimes, my job was to comfort, not to cure,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer of 1998, Stewart continued her work in
Radjkar, India, where she helped local residents of the small rural
village learn proper sanitation techniques for their hospital,
which allowed cows to pass through the operating room and had not
been cleaned in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many people in the world, this kind of suffering seems
insurmountable. People deem their efforts as futile and use the
justification 'life just isn't fair.'
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the medical work I have rendered in Haiti, India and
the U.S. has convinced me that by being privileged to be a citizen
of this country and obtain an education, I have not only the
ability, but the responsibility to help others who are not as
privileged,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Though these problems seem far removed from the United States,
Stewart points out that Haiti is only a 90-minute plane ride from
the U.S. and that a child dies there every five minutes from
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Upon her return to the United States, Stewart plans to pursue
both a medical degree and master's degree in international public
health at either Harvard University or John Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to follow her passion of global healthcare reform as a
doctor with the World Health Organization, where she will use
hands-on experiences drawn from countries to develop policies,
allocate funds for research and reform, and enact public health
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
