surprisingly robust 1.9 percent in the first three months of the
year, largely because of increased public spending. The increase in
gross domestic product is the first since the summer of 1997 and
baffles some economists, who doubt that the nation has actually
emerged from its longest recession since World War II. By Stephanie
Strom.
