<P>
   Y2K: Yes, you're sick of reading about Y2K by now, and so, it
seems, are a lot of people _ which could spell big trouble by the
time the public actually starts paying attention again this fall,
experts say. A new survey shows that experts still expect we could
have big problems. Finn Bullers.
</P>
<P>
   DAD: Jackson County's first fathering class graduates today.
About a year ago, County officials decided to help a few so-called
deadbeat dads instead of jailing them. It worked. The program
ordered men into programs such as drug treatment, job placement and
fatherhood training. The Fathering Project had 45 men, but few
worked full-time, paid child support or visited their children. Now
30 of the men have jobs, 26 pay child support and 31 visit their
children. Prosecutor Bob Beaird said the approach can help children
and prevent crime. Erica Thesing. 15. Photos, graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HART: Following the investigation into wrestler Owen Hart's
death. Checking with the WWF for comment and trying to reach the
stunt coordinator. Christine Vendel. 10.
</P>
<P>
   NOONE: Three months ago, Patricia Noone, 61, was found dead in
woods across the street from her KCK home. She had died of
hypothermia, but her body had some bruises. The coroner ruled the
death accidental, but detectives considered it suspicious. Last
week, they got a a tip which turned the case into a homicide. A man
has been charged with murder, and his girlfriend _ Patricia Noone's
daughter _ has been charged with aiding a felon. Anne Lamoy. 20.
Photo
</P>
<P>
   SHEP (business) _ Community of the Good Shepherd, a charity that
runs group homes for developmentally disabled men, took a hit years
back when a former director stole more than a quarter-million
dollars. The organization's efforts to clean up its act and win
back public trust resulted in a successful $170,000 fund-raising
program last year, which led the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development to nominate the organization for a national
award. By Gene Meyer. Photo
</P>
<P>
   LISA (business) _ When national consumer advocate Lisa Carlson's
husband died in 1981, local authorities in Vermont had trouble
coping with her insistence that she would be handling the details
herself. ``When they asked which funeral home I was using,'' she
said, ``I told them to bring the body back to the house. They were
flabbergasted.'' But they finally did as Carlson requested, she
said, because the law allowed it _ and still does in many states.
Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   ACENT (business) _ American Century purchases 5 percent in
another alternative investing company. By Mark Davis
</P>
