<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-POWERS-TEX     06-10 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-POWERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAG ME, BABY: TOILET HUMOR AND SEXUAL INNUENDO ARE THE `POWERS'
THAT BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was so much fun about the original ``Austin Powers'' is how
much of a surprise it was. An affectionate surprise, as it was full
of the obsessions of its creator and star, Mike Myers, that we'd
already glimpsed. For all of the enjoyment it provided, it wasn't
much of a movie; it was an extended sketch. And a lot of its appeal
came directly from Myers' boyish need to please, which surfaced in
his character. Unlike the cigarette-wielding super-spies ``Powers''
parodied, the International Man of Mystery just wanted to be liked.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' Dr. Evil (also
played by Myers) escapes from that orbiting Big Boy statue and goes
into the past to steal away Powers' mojo. ``His libido,'' Dr. Evil
trills mournfully, sounding even more like ``Saturday Night
Live's'' ruthlessly hip honcho, Lorne Michaels, this time around.
By doing so, Powers will be more useless, if that's possible. So
Powers sprints into the past _ 1969, for obvious reasons _ to
defeat his nemesis and get his mojo back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powers'' works as a media satire _ it's an amusing idea,
bringing in the professionally shallow Rob Lowe to play a younger
version of the equally professionally shallow, but more likable,
Robert Wagner (Dr. Evil's right-hand man). This time around,
though, the satire has a price tag hanging off of it. Jokes about
Starbucks, Chili's and Heineken are more product placement than
they are funny. And a lot of ``Spy'' feels like just a rehash, and
a barely heated one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some very choice bits, giving Myers a chance to
pilfer from the pop culture of the past 30 years _ bits from ``The
Exorcist,'' and even the king of shameless, Jerry Springer, show
up. Myers gives Dr. Evil a small clone of himself, Mini-me, as a
son figure, to replace his whiny slacker offspring Scott (Seth
Green). And Dr. Evil has picked up a hilarious addiction to dated
hip-hop culture, including a musical number that almost
single-handedly redeems the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Myers trots out another of his loves _ Scottish hooligan culture
_ and combines it with the hugely fat and openly disgusting Mr.
Creosote from ``Monty Python'' for the villain Fat B------, a
character that functions as a collection of gross-out jokes. The
toilet humor that could be shaken off in the first movie just about
gets its own subplot here.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Spy,'' Powers still wants to be liked. And the movie is
still essentially a lengthy sketch, which means at some points,
it's tiresome, like the last half-hour of ``Saturday Night Live.''
It also means there's so little going on that a talented actress
like Heather Graham is wasted, because there's nothing for her to
play. A glamorous nonactress, like Elizabeth Hurley, who briefly
reprises her role from the first ``Powers,'' is far better off
because she doesn't try to play anything.
</P>
<P>
   There is some funny stuff here, although if Myers has an
original thought in his head, he doesn't use it in this picture. To
keep yourself from getting bored, you can sit and tick off the
sources that Myers and director Jay Roach have so lovingly ripped
off. ``(Spy'' is mostly lifted from the James Bond epic ``You Only
Live Twice,'' which many aficionados consider to be the best Bond
movie.)
</P>
<P>
   It's still funny to watch this sprite in wolf's clothing _ Myers
is like a kid chasing all the cute girls around the classroom. And
they're going for it. But Powers' vocal shtick _ ``Yeah, baby'' and
``Behave'' _ has worn out its welcome, if only because everyone in
the theater imitates it every time Powers opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The role of sequels is to reassure, and when the sequel is
reprising a lightweight piece of material in the first place, it
seems even more limited. The ``Austin Powers'' movies have become
this generation's ``Pink Panther'' films. And let's not forget, the
endless repetition of those films turned into an industry.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jay Roach
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Mike Myers, Mike Myers, Mike Myers and Heather Graham
</P>
<P>
   Length: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG-13 _ PG-13 for toilet humor and wall-to-wall sexual
innuendo
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7032. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
