<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      06-10 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX JOKES? GROOVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If you're wondering where all the 15-year-old boys
are, they're chuckling their butts off at ``Austin Powers: The Spy
Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   This comic sequel to Mike Myers' surprise 1997 winner hits all
the high spots _ or low spots, depending on your taste in tasteless
humor _ of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Myers and crew provide an endless string of sex jokes, potty
jokes, then back to the sex jokes again.
</P>
<P>
   The story? Well, there's no story in a spoof like this. Or as
Myers points out: If you try to follow the runaround they use
instead of a plot, you'll end up cross-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers is a takeoff on James Bond, with Myers as the
British super-agent with the bad teeth and the groovy libido.
</P>
<P>
   His mission: to bed babes. In between, he doesn't mind saving
the world from Dr. Evil (also played by Myers).
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' Dr. Evil goes back in time to
steal Austin Powers' mojo. Austin then goes back in time to stop
him. There are threats to destroy the world and, even more
diabolical, deplete Austin's sex drive. Heather Graham runs along
changing her modish clothes as Austin's new sidekick, Felicity
Shagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just me, but I don't buy Graham (``Boogie Nights'')
as babelicious. She's sexy from a distance or while dancing, but
something goes wrong when director Jay Roach stops her for
close-ups. Maybe her head's too big for her body, or her body is
too small for her head.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter much because Roach, who also directed the
original ``Austin Powers,'' doesn't stop long before it's back to
the sex jokes and the potty jokes, including a couple of gross-outs
gross enough to gross out the previously ungrossable.
</P>
<P>
   The sequel is funnier than the original because it has more
silliness, more smut and more ``yeah-babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers owes much of his wink-wink sex humor to the British clown,
Benny Hill, with whom most of ``Austin Powers''' audience will not
be familiar. In recycling dirty jokes, Myers goes so far back for
old gags that they're as good as new to most teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of spoof humor creates a treadmill effect. Every gag
is like every other gag, and the movie runs along at a zippy pace
without ever actually getting anywhere. But Myers knows his
audience, and he caters to their amusements with enough chuckle and
snicker material to fill a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Myers also triples up as Dr. Evil's hit man, Fat Bastard, in a
remarkable exhibit of gross-out body costuming.
</P>
<P>
   The film packs in a large number of familiar faces in cameos,
including Elvis Costello, Woody Harrelson, Tim Robbins and Willie
Nelson. Except for Jerry Springer, Roach doesn't use the cameos to
any great cameo effect.
</P>
<P>
   Myers gets away with the title gag, using an English slang that
if he used the American equivalent, he wouldn't get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Will they retitle the movie when it opens in England? They've
already agreed to do that in other, more restrictive countries. My
favorite so far is Indonesia, where the title now is the translated
equivalent of ``The Spy Who Made Me Feel Good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' also gets away with a
PG-13 rating. It has more than enough profanity and raunchy humor
for an R. 3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Fenster can be reached at bob.fenster(at)pni.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
