<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTOR-REBELLION-NYTS     06-10 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-REBELLION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS ON THE PICKET LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Health Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Like many doctors, Dr. Byron Thomashow, a pulmonary specialist,
is fed up with managed care. He's tired of justifying the need for
clinical procedures to ill-informed HMO personnel. He's weary of
fighting endless battles in order to treat his patients. And he's
frustrated by loss of the autonomy he once enjoyed to make his own
medical decisions.
 &HT;    But unlike many of his colleagues, he's fighting back. In fact,
he's given up on managed care altogether, electing to withdraw from
the web of HMOs and health insurers that have come to dominate our
healthcare system.
 &HT;    ``I just couldn't stand it,'' he explains. ``The thought of
being put on hold by people who don't know a quarter of what you
are doing to get permission for patients to go to the bathroom''
was simply too much to take.
 &HT;    Dr. Barney Softness, a New York pediatrician, is another rebel.
When his HMO suggested that he fire his registered nurses to reduce
costs, he did something few doctors have dared to do: he fired his
HMO instead. He says he just wants ``to give the kind of care that
I think people deserve.''
 &HT;    The two mutinous physicians are not alone. Across America, state
insurance commissioners are reporting a veritable revolt by doctors
against their HMOs, and medical society officials say that more and
more practitioners are severing their ties with managed care
altogether. A recent headline in The New York Times heralded this
trend, citing a growing rebellion by doctors like Thomashow and
Softness.
 &HT;    Of course, much of the dispute revolves around the reduced fees
that insurers are paying physicians for their services.
Nonetheless, despite a glut of physicians in many specialties,
doctors' incomes have continued to rise, unencumbered by the laws
of supply and demand. For this reason, some critics have described
the controversy as much ado about money. But it is also about
something much more fundamental -- the sudden encroachment of
``outsiders'' into the practice of medicine.
 &HT;    For the first time in history, insurers are telling physicians
how to practice their profession, and the medical community is up
in arms. As an early participant in managed care, I am no stranger
to this phenomenon, and I've seen what it is like to lose your
autonomy as a doctor. It is not a pretty sight.
 &HT;    As a salaried physician at an HMO, I experienced firsthand the
sense of helplessness and outrage that can result when a third
party comes between you and your patients, preventing you from
caring for them the way you were trained. Indeed, after years of
advanced training and education, I felt something I'd never felt
before in my life as a doctor: the inability to have my medical
decisions carried out.
 &HT;    As any doctor can tell you, this is a dreadful feeling. It goes
to the very heart of medical practice. Moreover, it challenges some
of the basic assumptions about what it means to be a physician.
From the outset of their training, doctors are taught that they
alone bear ultimate responsibility for the fate of their patients,
and therefore they alone must have the final say -- in conjunction
with their patients -- regarding clinical decisions. They may
consult with other health professionals before reaching a
conclusion, but in the end, they must make the final call.
 &HT;    This may seem a bit autocratic to some, but because lives are at
stake, it's a necessarily authoritarian regime. When dealing with
life-and-death decisions, you can't have a committee bickering over
strategy.
 &HT;    On the other hand, medicine cannot afford to operate in a
vacuum. When dealing with one-seventh of the U.S. economy, you just
can't leave the decision to physicians alone. This is how we
arrived at the current economic crisis in the first place. The
medical community, unconstrained by managed care, continued to
inflate medical spending until it consumed a whopping 14 percent of
the nation's economic output.
 &HT;    This voracious appetite for dollars obviously couldn't be
sustained, and the need to control runaway costs eventually set the
stage for managed care. The result was the current revolution in
health care, in which the laws of economics finally held sway over
the canons of medicine. Economic pressures steadily chipped away at
the hegemony of the medical profession, and managed care ultimately
did what no other force had ever done: it turned doctors into
``employees'' on a massive scale.
 &HT;    Now, the revolution has led to another first: physicians are
clamoring to join unions as never before. Courted by everyone from
the American Federation of Teachers to the International
Association of Machinists, doctors are beginning to unionize across
the country. And they are being welcomed with open arms.
 &HT;    The Service Employees International Union, the nation's
fastest-growing labor coalition, pledged in March to spend $1
million this year to organize the nation's 600,000 doctors. Even
the United Food and Commercial Workers union has gotten into the
act, seeking to expand its base by enrolling doctors disaffected
with managed care. This could lead to some intriguing alliances, in
which doctors could find themselves walking the picket lines
alongside supermarket workers.
 &HT;    Though there is already some precedent for the concept of a
physicians' guild, unionization still raises some troubling ethical
questions for the healing profession. Perhaps the most important
issue involves organized labor's right to strike. Could doctors
actually go on strike, denying care to their patients? If so, who
would treat their patients while they walked the picket line? And
how would they reconcile withholding care with the obligations of
the Hippocratic oath?
 &HT;    These are difficult questions, but they'll have to be addressed
as we move into the next phase of the managed care revolution. In
the meantime, one thing is certain: the revolution will continue.
As insurers press on with their onslaught, doctors will persist in
the struggle, fighting a rear-guard action in the hope of regaining
some control over their fate in the new healthcare economy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1999 Stephen L. Cohen
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stephen L. Cohen, M.D., is a medical journalist based in New
York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
