<HEADER>
A0257 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERS-SOUNDTRACK-TEX     06-10 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERS-SOUNDTRACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `POWERS' THAT BE DON'T CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody, and I mean nobody, is looking forward to the second
Austin Powers movie, ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' more than I am.
</P>
<P>
   I plan to be there the day it opens, first showing, popcorn and
soft drink in hand, ready to settle in, laugh at Austin's teeth
(again!) and hear him purr ``Yeah, baby!'' (again!) and swoon over
Heather Graham _ ready to, well, have at least as good a time as I
had with the first one.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe the music on this 12-cut soundtrack will work within
the context of scenes in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Sure hope so, 'cause it sure doesn't work on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with the ``Powers'' soundtrack are the same that
have vexed numerous soundtracks in the past _ (a) Weak original
songs, and (b) Weak cover versions of good old songs.
</P>
<P>
   In the former category we have ``Alright'' by The Lucy Nation, a
really boring bit of modern radio rock, and in the latter we have,
well, where do we start? Lenny Kravitz's version of ``American
Woman'' is fair, but come on, it's ``American Woman,'' one of the
most overplayed songs in rock history. There's only so much Kravitz
can do.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, things go downhill fast: R.E.M.'s ``Draggin' the
Line'' is lame, Melanie G.'s take on Cameo's classic ``Word Up'' is
completely anemic, and Big Blue Missile's butchering of ``Time of
the Season'' is, frankly, horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Letting modern artists update classic rock tunes is hardly ever
a really good idea, however good a marketing ploy it may seem to be
_ but in this case it sinks the CD like an anvil tied around a
gangster's foot.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't help matters that the live version of the Who
doing their classic ``My Generation'' is thin and stiff, or that
the Elvis Costello/Burt Bacharach cover of Bacharach and Hal
David's ``I'll Never Fall in Love Again'' is good for its kitsch
factor and not a whole lot else.
</P>
<P>
   A shame, too, as there is some good stuff here. The opener,
Madonna's ``Beautiful Stranger,'' is a great summer song and will
deservedly be a hit, and Dr. Evil's take on Will Smith's ``Just the
Two of Us'' (in this case, a paean to Mini-Me) is cute _ but only
just. Also fairly interesting is the Flaming Lips' ``Buggin''' _
although it's hardly the best thing these guys have ever done. And
the remix of Quincy Jones' ``Soul Bossa Nova'' is a pleasant, campy
final touch.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a final touch on, really, a lot of mediocre material.
Four memorable songs out of 12 is not a good batting average. This
soundtrack might be an indication that this Powers film isn't as
good as the first. Or maybe the CD's just a stand-alone
disappointment. I'm really hoping it's the latter.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Various artists
</P>
<P>
   Label: Maverick Records
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
