<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING INTO THE JUNETEENTH ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late, lamented comedian Jimmy Durante had an expression that
fits what's happening to that long-standing Texas tradition called
Juneteenth.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with instances of people imitating him or responding
to some funny line of his, Durante would grumble: ``Everybody wants
to get into de act.''
</P>
<P>
   So it seems with the June 19 observances that most
African-Americans in Texas have considered their own peculiar
institution.
</P>
<P>
   But for several years now, Juneteenth celebrations have been
flowering in places like Buffalo, N.Y., Los Angeles, Washington,
D.C., Kansas City, Mo., and Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that. Still, I believed that the real thing only happened
in Texas cities and towns. I doubted that anywhere else in the
nation went about the business of celebrating the anniversary of
the announcement of the Emancipation Proclamation in Texas in the
way that African-Americans in Fort Worth, Port Arthur, Beaumont and
Houston do it.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my astonishment when I came across a wire story
indicating the big way that folks underscore June 19 in the City by
the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Something about Juneteenth and the San Francisco I know from
movies, songs and brief visits just didn't seem to go together.
Therefore, I called to make certain that the wire story was telling
about the same Golden-Gated, cable-carred, Nobb-Hilled,
Fisherman's-Wharfed place where Tony Bennett left his heart and
Rice-A-Roni supposedly originated.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it was the same windy, chilly place. And according
to publicist Sandra Varner, Juneteenth is no
semi-holiday-come-lately to that cosmopolitan metropolis. According
to Varner, it's been going on there with varying degrees of
emphasis for the past 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   That would make the San Francisco observance about as old as the
revived Juneteenth observance in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the celebration really began 134 years ago, when Gen.
Gordon Granger landed in Galveston and put the word on the
grapevine that two years earlier, President Abraham Lincoln had
issued the Emancipation Proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``You slaves can tell your masters to take their
nonpaying jobs and shove them.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas African-Americans used to take a lot of ribbing about
getting the news so late. But that was before CNN and the Internet.
Union troops did not reach Texas to spread the news until 1865
because no major Civil War battles were fought in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it wasn't the slaves' fault that they didn't find out
they were free until they did. When they did hear, they celebrated.
And in Texas and parts of Louisiana, they have celebrated that
hallelujah day every year from that day until now.
</P>
<P>
   However, the intensity of those celebrations waned in the 1950s
and early 1960s, when many African-Americans became so committed to
integration and assimilation that they downplayed their history and
heritage to try to blend into the dominant culture.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of the black pride movement in the late '60s,
Juneteenth came back to the fore as a public observance in places
like Fort Worth. And it apparently was about that time that the
tradition was started in San Francisco by African-Americans who had
moved there from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Varner said the observance is flourishing more than ever in San
Francisco because of the support it is receiving from Mayor Willie
Brown, a native Texan. She said that Brown is committed to
elevating Juneteenth to a level comparable to all of the city's
other big festivals.
</P>
<P>
   That shows in some of the activities planned for the observance.
Among them are:
</P>
<P>
   _A talent show similar those traditionally staged at Fort
Worth's Renaissance Center. That June 12 event will be hosted by TV
and movie star Tamala Jones.
</P>
<P>
   _The first annual National Black Invitational Rodeo on June 18
at Golden Gate Park. The event will be hosted by actors Glynn
Turman and Reginald Dorsey.
</P>
<P>
   _A film festival on June 18-19 that will honor pioneer
African-American filmmaker Melvin Van Peebles. The annual event
will be named after Van Peebles.
</P>
<P>
   _A free gospel concert featuring gospel singer Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. So Fort Worth and Houston Juneteenth coordinators
will have their work cut out to top San Francisco's Juneteenth and
probably those several other non-Texas cities around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Durante was right. Everybody wants to get into the act.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
