<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT11-COX     06-10 1761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, June 11, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOZOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ With NATO airstrikes
suspended, peacekeeping forces began flooding into Macedonia as a
prelude to moving into Kosovo to enforce compliance with a peace
deal there. As Serb troops began withdrawing from the embattled
province, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic went on national
television to proclaim victory. Story will wrap in all major
developments. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ You would think that
refugees and peacekeepers would be excited that they will soon be
moving into Kosovo. But among ethnic Albanian refugees, the mood
here is surprisingly subdued. They are extremely apprehensive over
whether it's safe to return and at the notion of what they will
find in their abandoned villages. And members of the U.S. 82nd
Airborne Division aren't overly eager. Many of them express concern
that they are moving into a dangerous situation. And they are
chafing at playing the role of peacekeeper after having been
trained in the art of war. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With Photo of refugees who will be quoted in the story.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA _ KUKES, Albania _ Refugees here are just
learning that they won't be returning very soon to their homes
inside Kosovo. Their fellow refugees in Macedonia will be first
back, and some of the refugees in Albania may not be able to return
until next year. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AIRWAR _ WASHINGTON _ After 78 days, nearly 35,000
sorties and more than 20,000 bombs, the U.S.-led NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia were suspended on Thursday without a single
combat fatality for the allies. There has never been an air
campaign like it, said Defense Secretary William Cohen, who called
the campaign ``an extraordinary achievement in the history of air
warfare.'' Pilots flew high and let lasers, satellites and infrared
scanners guide 2,000-pound bombs to their targets miles away.
Despite advances in tactics and technology that put this air war a
full generation ahead of what was seen during the Gulf War,
Operation Allied Force was dogged by two of the oldest variables in
the history of battle: weather and terrain. And it ended without
solving the debate over whether wars can be won from the air alone.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS _ WASHINGTON _ Two days before Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas makes his presidential campaign debut, the two top national
Democratic Party officials, Joe Andrews and Gov. Roy Romer of
Colorado, unloaded on the frontrunning GOP candidate. At a
breakfast with reporters, they sought to tie Bush to Republicans in
Congress who are blocking spending bills and gun control
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories. (Shepard,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION _ WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service
has ruled that the Christian Coalition is not entitled to
tax-exempt status, forcing the once-vaunted political powerhouse to
split into two entities in changes that will leave it
``dramatically reshaped.'' (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means
Committee ends two days of hearings on a Social Security reform
proposal offered by its leaders. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ED-FUNDS _ WASHINGTON - Lively exchanges likely when Catholic
and NEA witnesses are among those testifying before a House
committee that is considering tighter lids on funding over the next
five years for Title I, which is supposed to supply educational
help for schools with low-income children. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ WASHINGTON _ Cisco Systems, a leading network
hardware company, releases what it calls the most comprehensive
study of the Internet's impact on the economy. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-KILLING _ MEXICO CITY _ At first Paco Stanley's murder
was seen as the most glaring example yet of vicious, random crime
in this metropolis. Television anchors and fans of the famous comic
wept, assuming Stanley was an innocent victim of an assault on a
Mexico City street Monday. Political opponents of the city's mayor
saw a chance to weaken his presidential aspirations, wasting no
time in attacking him for failing to stem crime. But now it appears
that Stanley's killing could spotlight the pervasiveness of drugs
in Mexico -- their use and trafficking -- rather than street crime.
Police reports confirmed that Sanchez had cocaine in his body and a
stash of the drug in his car, where he was killed execution-style.
Unconfirmed allegations are flying that he consorted with one of
Mexico's most notorious cocaine traffickers and that he may have
owed $300,000 on a drug shipment. The killing has also made a
mockery of Stanley's employer, TeleAzteca, a network that had been
sponsoring a ``Say no to drugs'' campaign. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-TROOPS _ MIAMI _ Nearly five years after the United States
invaded Haiti to restore democracy, the U.S. House of Reps. is
expected to vote Wednesday on whether to end the permanent U.S.
military presence there. A growing number of lawmakers are
demanding the withdrawal of the remaining 500-member U.S. Support
Group in light of a rapidly deteriorating security situation in
Haiti that has left even military leaders concerned about the
safety of U.S. troops. The House will be voting on an amendment
proposed by Rep. Porter Goss (R-Fla.) and Rep. Ben Gilman (R-N.Y.)
(Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WICCA-BOYCOTT _ Pentagon responds to Christian right's
anti-Wicca boycott of the Army. Folks there told us Wednesday they
were too busy dealing with media questions about Kosovo to decide
what to say about Christians and witches. They promised to talk to
us Thursday. Story will include other fallout as it happens.
(Perkes, Austin American-Statesman). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS _ ATLANTA _ In the days before their annual meeting in
Atlanta, Southern Baptists plan to blitz the city with evangelism,
door-to-door and in revival-style worship. This comes at a time
when the denomination recently admitted losing members for the
first time in decades. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-RAISING _ Members of Gateway Baptist Church in Dawson
County, Ga., have spent three years meeting in a school. All that
changes next week (June 7) when they and members of a special
Baptist ministry, Builders for Christ, build a structure for the
faith community. In the tradition of an Amish barn raising, the
facility will rise quickly, in just four days, according to
Gateway's pastor, the Rev. Ray Rhodes Jr. Everyone will help out _
parents, children, builders from West Virgnia, South Carolina,
North Carolina and Georgia. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MISS-GOV _ Gov. Kirk Fordice, whose love life has been the talk
of Mississippi ever since he was spotted holding hands with a woman
in a restaurant while his wife was out of town, said Thursday he is
getting divorced and will marry his junior high school sweetheart.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-SUITS _ A profile of Bill Marler, the lawyer who
specializes in E. coli cases, and is handling all the White Water
litigation, plus an update on where the litigation stands. Marler
is speculating this will be the first E. coli case to go to trial
(all the others have been settled for huge sums), because White
Water's liability is a little less clear than that of meat
manufacturers and Jack in the Box. (Guthrie/Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHGALLERY _ Out in the Hill Country, they're getting ready for
Friday's opening of the Bush Gallery at the National Museum of the
Pacific War. The former president's story is one of dozens of
wartime accounts told through photos and artifacts. Organizers say
the museum is the only one in the country dedicated to the Pacific
War. The governor's dad will be in Fredericksburg for Friday's
opening. (Kelley, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   PLANE _ After crash-landing her plane in Sylvia Graham's front
yard, the student pilot knocks on the door and asks to use the
phone to call 911. And, also, could she please have a towel because
she's bleeding. The student pilot was treated at the hospital for
minor injuries. The plane is badly damaged. Graham, who was reading
the paper with her husband when they heard a loud noise they
thought was thunder, didn't get to see the plane in her yard at
2111 Lake Bass Circle. They were evacuated. (Coyle, Palm Beach
Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
