<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-SHAME-BOS &LR;      06-10 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-SHAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOLS TAP THE POWER OF SHAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ A decade of reform efforts, cash rewards, and
threats of state takeovers didn't improve test scores at the Van
Zandt-Guinn Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Shame did.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Texas began labeling every public school with one
of four ratings, from low-performing to exemplary, based largely on
state test scores. Then, they launched a campaign to publicize
them. Soonparents, teachers, students, and neighbors near Van
Zandt-Guinn saw the tiny school flashed on the local nightly news
with a red F.
</P>
<P>
   The shame factor worked. Staff volunteered to tutor students,
students held pep rallies to boost enthusiasm for learning, and
parents brainstormed at community meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Van Zandt-Guinn has among the highest test scores in the
state, despite a student population that is 100 percent poor. It
seems everyone, from a 45-year-old neighbor with no children to a
nearby store clerk, knows the school is ``recognized,'' the state's
second-highest rating.
</P>
<P>
   Now, other states are starting to recognize the role that public
embarrassment can play in public education. Massachusetts plans to
start assigning schools similar ratings next year based on the
Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System, or MCAS. And if
Texas is any indicator, publicizing those scores may prove to be
the most powerful motivator local public school reform has ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a system of reality. ... It says this is where we are
and this is where we need to be,'' said David P. Driscoll,
Massachusetts education commissioner. ``Sometimes motivation is a
pat on the back and sometimes it is fear.''
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts teachers, already feeling a strong dose of
public humiliation after half of the candidates who took a new
teacher test last year failed, say the ratings will only make
teachers feel more disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the dunce cap was put in the closet a long time
ago,'' said Steve Gorrie, head of the Massachusetts Teachers
Association, the state's largest teachers' union. ``Teachers, like
students, respond far better to support than naming, shaming, and
pointing fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas education officials agree that shame alone does not change
schools. But they were able to turn teachers' frustrations in
low-performing schools into action and _ along with money, staff
training, and even teacher firings _ to boost scores on the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills, or TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has poured money and effort into schools since reform
began in 1984. Tactics included lowering class sizes to 22 in
kindergarten to fourth-grade. The movement gathered steam and in
1994 the state began grading schools and letting communities know
exactly how their schools stacked up.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently _ and most remarkably _ the reform movement has
meant every single one of the state's 250,000 teachers, some of the
most poorly paid in the country, will get a $3,000 raise this
September.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also has curbed social promotion of students and
strengthened teacher candidates. Those efforts have trickled down
to local districts such as Fort Worth, and individual schools, such
as Van Zandt-Guinn.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous that Van Zandt-Guinn's test scores, although improving,
weren't rising fast enough, Fort Worth School Superintendent Thomas
S. Tocco transferred all the teachers out of the school four years
ago. Principal Constance Goines hand-picked new teachers, keeping
only four of the original 14. Tocco insisted on 18 extra days for
teacher training and Van Zandt-Guinn's school year was extended to
200 days.
</P>
<P>
   Students began spending a minimum of 2 1/2 hours a day on
writing. An hour was set aside for math and every student received
an additional two periods of the subject a week from a specialized
math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Van Zandt-Guinn, named after two prominent local families, is in
an impoverished southeast section of Fort Worth, a block from
Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   Boarded-up or dilapidated single-family homes line wide,
pothole-filled streets near the school; a bail bondsman's office is
two blocks away. All 280 students in the almost all-minority school
are on a free- or reduced-price-lunch program. Most of the students
walk to the school, created in 1979 when two schools merged. Many
parents were taught in those earlier schools.
</P>
<P>
   While the school was largely once ignored by residents, it is
now noticed _ and celebrated. Neighbor Marie Hapatale, 22, says she
will continue to rent in the area to ensure that her 2-year-old
attends school there. Others also say they are staying because of
the stellar school, despite the ability to move to better sections
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is very strong pressure,'' said Goines. ``You feel like
everyone knows what you are. It's in the newspapers and it's public
record. The kids know it, the parents and everyone else knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Tocco's leadership, Fort Worth's other schools also have
improved: Forty-six of the district's 114 schools were projected to
be low-performing last year. Only one was.
</P>
<P>
   Texas boasts similar results, and Massachusetts _ which is
mimicking many Texas reform efforts _ hopes to see similar rises in
test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread fears of major failures plagued Texas when it began a
graduation test in 1988, but the news has largely been good: In
1994, some 5 percent of Texas seniors didn't pass the test; this
year, only 2 percent failed. Starting in two years, Massachusetts
seniors will have to pass the MCAS to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   And Texas will not allow any school to make excuses for bad
scores because of students' race or socio-economic background.
Ratings are largely based on the lowest-performing ethnic or
socio-economic group in a school. Massachusetts will rate schools
on their overall scores as well as their ability to raise scores of
all students.
</P>
<P>
   And while teachers in both states say they are resigned to
standardized testing, they still worry they cannot teach as
creatively with such singular emphasis on the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate it, we call is TASS-Mania,'' said Annette Cootes,
spokeswoman for the Texas State Teachers Association. ``It is too
high-stakes, it is all anyone focuses on. We drill, we drill, we
drill.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at Van Zandt-Guinn, everything is about the test.
</P>
<P>
   Every bulletin board in the school offers TAAS advice: ``Slam
dunk the TAAS'' reads one. Posters are tacked in every room showing
students as young as first grade that words like ``sum'' and
``add'' both mean put together.
</P>
<P>
   Students who are expected to take longer on the untimed TAAS are
put in a separate room so they don't feel pressure to finish when
their classmate do.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, after fifth-grade teacher Mourine Kirk spent the
period before lunch going over decimals _ an item bound to appear
on the test the following week _ her students nervously shifted
from foot to foot and predicted their outcome on the test. They
take several practice tests so they know their anticipated score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous, I'm not going to pass,'' said Laquana Phillips,
11, shaking her head sadly. She said she needs more than 10 points
to pass math, her weakest subject.
</P>
<P>
   Her classmate Amber Sherman frets over the stress on her and
even her teachers. ``You don't want people thinking you go to a bad
school,'' Amber said.
</P>
<P>
   While some Texas educators continue to cringe at the amount of
pressure on children to perform well on the TAAS, some community
leaders say the rating system gives a tangible measure of schools
that was missing in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very important benchmarks,'' said Floyd R. Davis Jr.,
president and CEO of United Community Centers Inc., which provides
social services to residents around Fort Worth. A community center
he oversees is six blocks from Van Zandt-Guinn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis said he understands why some teachers, parents, and
students dislike the pressure of the test. Those teachers and
students often say they feel the reputation of the entire community
is hinged on how well their school performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' Goines said. ``It's like a report card. Everyone can
understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
