<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-10 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB IS WINNING THE TALENT WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's possible that CNN financial news anchorman Lou Dobbs will
rescind his decision to quit the network. He has resigned (or
threatened to resign) on numerous occasions. Some believe that his
most recent resignation is just another gambit to extract more
concessions from CNN management.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more likely that Dobbs really has decided to leave and
move on to the next thing. The next thing is an Internet venture
called Space.com. Dobbs has long been, as he says, ``a space nut,''
and joining Space.com offers him the opportunity to make his
avocation his livelihood. It also offers him the chance to make a
great deal more money than CNN would ever be willing to pay him
(and they pay him a ton).
</P>
<P>
   One ordinarily wouldn't think of Dobbs as a cutting-edge kind of
guy, but he's emblematic of an important shift in the employment
game. Simply put, talent is going to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, there was great concern that the most talented
business school graduates were eschewing careers in manufacturing
and management to become consultants and financial services
professionals. Now, talented business school graduates are
eschewing consulting and financial services to join Internet
enterprises. This brain drain is causing something close to panic
at ``traditional'' companies. It will likely accelerate as Internet
technology advances and improves.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what's happening is financial. Consider the case of two
Wall Street Journal employees. One stayed and is now a senior
editor. He probably makes $125,000 a year and has some options to
buy Dow Jones stock. Including benefits and travel and
entertainment expenses, his current annual compensation package
comes to roughly $180,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, you say, but it's nothing when compared to the
compensation package earned by David Kansas, a former Wall Street
Journal employee who now edits TheStreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas earns the same salary (give or take) as his former
colleague, gets similar benefits, but owns stock in TheStreet.com
that, at current prices, is worth roughly $5 million. Given the
choice between these two career paths, talent will go where Kansas
went.
</P>
<P>
   Talented people everywhere are doing just that. Wednesday, The
Wall Street Journal (of all places) published a front-page article
describing how one top manager after another has left The Walt
Disney Company to join recently established or newly established
Internet ventures. The advertising business has had to increase
salaries dramatically and create Internet marketing companies to
keep key employees down on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these inducements, creative talent is leaving in
droves. The consulting and accounting businesses are finding it
much harder to recruit new hires. Young hotshots look at a 15-year
path to partnership as a kind of careerist's Death March when
compared to the possibilities, real or imagined, of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just about money. Another piece of this migration
is demographic. Hotshots in their 20s and 30s look at traditional
companies and see squadrons of baby-boom white men occupying all
the best jobs. Many of these good old boys are on their second
marriages, with new families, so they'll be working into their 70s.
Moving up the organizational chart under these circumstances isn't
just difficult, it's impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies, on the other hand, are run by talented
people in their 20s and 30s. The organizational chart has lots of
good jobs and empty boxes waiting to be filled. There's more than
enough opportunity. If anything, there's too much to do.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to the third great attraction of Internet employment;
failure is expected. Bright young people know that they can go to
an Internet start-up, fail, and yet still get picked up on waivers
by some other Internet start-up. Internet culture considers failure
a necessary qualification for moving up. You can't be any good
unless you've taken a big chance on something that didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   This is not how traditional companies think, to say the least.
People who participate in corporate failures at traditional
companies are usually consigned to some nonexistent square on the
organizational chart. Failure leads to exile and an abrupt end to
one's career path. This is why so many traditional companies
engender such odious office politics. The game is about avoiding
blame and not taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a game highly intelligent, highly motivated, highly
creative people are interested in playing. They'd much rather go
for it and see what happens. In the world of the Internet, they can
and they're not penalized for trying. They're only penalized if
they don't try.
</P>
<P>
   When Lou Dobbs, the consummate inside player, dispenses with the
old model, the rules of the game really have changed. The talent
war is being won by the Web. The challenge for traditional
companies will be to reverse this trend. It isn't just about money.
It's about changing corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
