<P>
   CASSETT-EXHIBIT (Washington) _ ``Women should be someone and not
something,'' the American artist Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) once
wrote, emphatically underlining her words. And she dedicated a long
career to fleshing out this conviction through art. Her efforts
come across with a quiet, though sometimes surprisingly passionate
force in ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman,'' a succinct survey of her
paintings and prints at the National Gallery of Art in Washington.
The show, which has appeared in Chicago and Boston, is the first
comprehensive look at Cassatt's work in nearly 30 years. And it
marks yet another step in evaluating an artist who was herself a
someone _ indeed, several someones _ to be reckoned with. By
Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   PLANET-EARTH (New York) _ Over more than a century, scientists
and explorers from the American Museum of Natural History have
searched the world and returned with arresting examples of life in
all its diversity: dinosaurs from Montana to Mongolia, birds and
butterflies, artifacts of exotic cultures from here to the South
Sea. For the last four years, their quest has been to collect the
stuff of Earth itself and bring it back for a new exhibition
illustrating the planet's 4.5 billion-year history. Now the
collections have been studied, winnowed and arranged for display in
the museum's newest permanent exhibit, the Gottesman Hall of Planet
Earth, which opens Saturday. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   TANGO-MANIA (New York) _ The Argentine tango is not unlike
chess. It is serious; it takes discipline; it must be studied hard
to be done well. It is elegant and formal, passionate and intimate.
It is about power and vulnerability. It is both a dance and a
metaphor. And to its captives, it can become a magnificent
obsession. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
