<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TOURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURS LET YOU STOP AND SMELL THE FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   June is the month of wine and roses _ and garden tours and
courses and lectures. There are so many good things to do and see
that there's almost no time to smell the roses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best of June are the open house and garden tours
because perennial beds are at their peak and roses are at their
absolute zenith, especially in the grand gardens managed by
professional horticulturists.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, I like even better the garden tours put on by
local garden clubs because I can see what serious gardeners, who
are just plain people like me, can do in their own back yards.
There are always new, tasteful ideas, and I have absolute
admiration for the level of work put into these gardens.
</P>
<P>
   So what is more rare than a day in June, snooping around in
private gardens that you wouldn't be invited to otherwise? Actually
not so rare, because you can spend every weekend on one tour or
another, but it's still a treat not to be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Massachusetts Federation of Garden Clubs have
these tours for June, and many months of preparation and hard work
have gone into the big day.
</P>
<P>
   June 11-12, Hanover Garden Club tour, ``Blooms Beyond the Garden
Gate.'' For tickets call 781-843-4366.
</P>
<P>
   June 12, Acton and Stow, ``Rhapsody in Bloom'' with music and
lunch, 978-486-0540.
</P>
<P>
   June 12, Lexington, always an interesting tour. Call
978-369-2835.
</P>
<P>
   June 12-13, Marshfield, ``Festival of Flowers.'' Call
781-834-6135.
</P>
<P>
   June 15-16, Duxbury, ``Artist in the Garden.'' Call
781-934-0824.
</P>
<P>
   June 16, Hingham, Historical Society 75th Annual House Tour.
Call 781-749-1815.
</P>
<P>
   June 26, Brockton, Garden Tour. Call 508-584-2570.
</P>
<P>
   June 27, Belmont, ``Down the Garden Path,'' a tour of 11 special
historic gardens. Call 617-484-4817.
</P>
<P>
   Boston will host another rare treat, a special event for very
serious gardeners. The American Horticultural Society is holding
its annual conference in Boston from Wednesday to Saturday at the
Fairmont Copley Plaza Hotel. Promoting excellence in horticulture
is the aim of this national society headquartered in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   With a theme of ``Celebrating You, The American Gardener,'' the
speakers cover the who's who in American horticulture. The
conference program has cutting edge talks and panels plus giving
awards, including to our own Weston Nurseries, Michael Van
Valkenburgh, Joseph Hudak, and Mayor Thomas Menino of Boston (for
his Broom to Bloom urban beautification program). Four afternoons
of garden tours will cover the best of everything floral around
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The whole event is pricey but good. One-day afternoon tours are
$80-$100 each, and the Saturday flower arranging workshop costs
$25. For more information, call 800-768-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Our own venerable institutions all have superb garden walks,
summer lectures, courses, and hands-on training programs. There's
just no excuse to sit at home and mope about the unfinished
maintenance in one's garden when it's so easy to go to someone
else's garden. They usually have just as many unfinished chores as
you do.)
</P>
<P>
   Some good places for programs, walks, and talks include:
</P>
<P>
   --Massachusetts Horticultural Society Elm Bank in Dover.
Programs all summer plus on June 19 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. you
might enjoy all the marvellous products from our local farms at the
Massachusetts Market Place, produced along with the state
Department of Food and Agriculture. Also included are hayrides,
free pH testing of soil samples, plants for sale, the trial
gardens, and children's activities. Call 617-536-9280, ext. 324.
</P>
</TEXT>
