<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGES OF PARENTING AN ONLY CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting in the family room of their Andover, Mass., home a few
weeks ago, Daniel Morocco and Toby Lazerton listened intently as
their daughter ran through editing changes for her sixth-grade
social studies project on England. Suddenly Lazerton got up and
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me that there was too much intensity in the room with
two adults tending to one child's project,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that two parents should never focus on one child at the
same time; it's just that in the Morocco-Lazerton household,
12-year-old Jaime Morocco is the only child. Having Mom and Dad
both attend to her at once is the norm, not the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Jaime to feel like she's under a microscope,''
says her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lazerton's sensitivity is typical of a kind of sixth sense many
parents of only children develop out of necessity, not just for
their child but also for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenting an only is high-pressure parenting,'' says
psychologist Carl Pickhardt of Austin, Texas. ``Because it is the
first and last child all in one, you tend to be harder on yourself:
If you have only one child, you only have one time to get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, some of that pressure seeps down to the child.
</P>
<P>
   All children, at least through elementary school, want to please
their parents. ``For the only child,'' Pickhardt says, ``that
desire is even greater, because the triangle in the family creates
a stronger attachment.'' Pickhardt is the author of ``Keys to
Parenting the Only Child'' (Barons Educational Series, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   That the attachment is so strong is both good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   It can mean, for instance, that a child is more likely to seek
out parents' views on issues, thus minimizing peers' risky
influence. But it can also mean that a child is so able to take the
parents' perspective that she withholds information to protect
them, rather than withholding to protect herself as most children
do, says University of Texas psychologist Toni Falbo, who has been
researching only children since 1970. That that dynamic exists at
all is a pressure for a child, she says.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that parents walk a thin line, with many falling
victim to one extreme or the other. In the past, for instance, when
less was known about the connectedness that only-child status
confers, parents were likely to be overly indulgent and protective.
Now, Falbo says, with more awareness of that extreme, and with more
mothers pursuing careers and having only one child by choice, the
pendulum is swinging the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about parents who are too uninvolved,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco walks the line with exquisite awareness. As a youngster,
he had the double whammy of being an only child and having no
cousins his age. ``I was the focus of my parents and also of aunts
and uncles. I was always under the gun,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He works hard for his daughter not to feel that way and suspects
his parenting is a more conscious process than it is for other
parents of just one child. On the other hand, he probably speaks
for them when he says, ``I worry that I might make a mistake ...
that would cause us to lose the closeness we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Parental dilemmas
</P>
<P>
   The nature of that closeness can affect many aspects of life in
a single-child family:
</P>
<P>
   --Disciplining. Not seeing a sibling also being punished, not
having anyone to commiserate with about how mean Mom and Dad are,
and feeling very connected combine to make an only child take our
disapproval more to heart than other children, says parent educator
Marcy Tannenbaum-Fox, who leads workshops on one-child families at
Families First in Cambridge. Add to that the parental tendency to
overlook infractions, just because it's easy to do so when there's
only one child, and the result is that our anger, when it does
come, can be all the more upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   Tannenbaum-Fox reminds parents that an only child, like everyone
else, needs discipline. ``Don't let any guilt you may have about
only having one child get in the way of appropriate
limit-setting,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --Giving responsibility. It's also sometimes easier not to
insist that a child pull her weight at home; after all, with only
one child's mess to clean up, it's not a big deal to do it
yourself. In fact, it is a big deal. An only child who isn't
expected to contribute to the family is more likely to feel
entitled, says social psychologist and researcher Susan Newman. A
child who feels more powerful than her place in the family warrants
not only doesn't feel good about herself but also can end up
driving a wedge between her parents, because she is adept at
manipulating them.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's antidote: ``Think big. Establish chores and
responsibilities just as you would in a family with more children,
even if it makes it harder on you,'' she says. Newman is the author
of ``Parenting an Only Child: The Joys and Challenges of Raising
Your One and Only'' (Doubleday).
</P>
<P>
   --Sharing. Selfishness is an issue that pushes the button of
almost every parent of an only, a holdover from the stereotype of
the selfish only child. Newman reminds parents that selfishness is
a developmental issue, especially in the preschool and teen years,
and can have nothing to do with only-child status. Nonetheless,
because an only child doesn't have siblings to share with, she
urges parents to model sharing behavior at all ages, from
toddlerhood _ ``One bite for you, one bite for me'' _ to teens:
``You can borrow this sweater if you want.''
</P>
<P>
   --Dealing with conflict. Because an only child tends to be
emotionally closely aligned with her parents and doesn't have
siblings to fight with, she may find conflict intimidating.
Pickhardt says that may be why the onset of adolescent behavior,
when children and parents are at each other's throat, is typically
delayed for only children. ``They don't feel the need to make the
break as badly as other children. The loss of closeness and
prospect of conflict is as scary to the child as to the parent,''
he says. When it does come, though, it can be worse than in other
families. ``It's not that the only child pushes harder for
independence, but that the members of the triangle are so tightly
interwoven, the push is more deeply felt,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of conflict can also make a child less willing to extend
herself in friendship. ``Friendships by definition include
conflict, which an only may shy away from,'' says Tannenbaum-Fox.
She is quick to point out, however, that personality and
developmental stage contribute to this as well.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving well alone
</P>
<P>
   When children are young, parents should facilitate playdates,
and at all ages we should model conflict resolution. But by school
age, when friendships become more important as well as trickier to
negotiate, we should cool it.
</P>
<P>
   She says there's a tendency for parents of an only child to rush
in to fix problems, an irony that is often lost on the parents:
``This is the child who needs the hands-on experience the most, and
here we are reducing opportunity for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickhardt tells parents not to worry so much about a child who
wants to spend time alone. It's not just that these children come
to enjoy peace and quiet, but also that they enjoy their own
company. ``If the choice is having a great time with yourself or
going off with friends where you may or may not have a great time,
there will be times when they will choose to be alone, and that's
OK,'' he says. Tannenbaum-Fox says that even an only child who
likes being in the social thick of things tends not to get bored
the minute she's alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as a child has some playmates, don't assume that
because she spends time alone, she's unhappy,'' says
Tannenbaum-Fox. ``Accept that your only may have fewer friends, but
that the friends she has are likely to be more loyal and more
intense.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb that guides Newman's advice (as well as her
parenting of her son, Andrew, who is 17) is that it's not good to
do everything you can or be all things to your child, whether it's
a question of picking up a toddler every time he falls down or
buying something he wants just because you can.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Morocco says she has never felt that her parents give her
too much or too little of anything, including themselves. ``Maybe I
get more help with my homework,'' she says, ``but mostly, I just
think the three of us are a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Highly recommended: ``The Movie Mom's Guide to
Family Movies,'' by Nell Minow (Avon Books). Includes movies for
children of all ages, with summaries and discussion points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
