<HEADLINE>
WASHING SODA CLEANS WITHOUT PHOSPHATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You wrote recently that to clean a garbage disposal, you
should pour in some washing soda, then two trays of ice cubes, and
run the disposal. It sounds like a good idea, but for the life of
me, I cannot find washing soda. What is it, and where can I get it?
</P>
<P>
   BILL M., Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Washing soda is concentrated sal soda (sodium carbonate), a
phosphate-free laundry booster found in the detergent section of
supermarkets. Directions for cleaning plumbing traps and lines are
on the box of the Arm &AMP; Hammer product, called Arm &AMP; Hammer super
washing soda detergent booster. Other manufacturers also make it.
Washing soda is an effective heavy-duty cleaning alternative to
solvents.
</P>
<P>
   It is more caustic than baking soda (sodium bicarbonate), but if
after all this legwork (whew!) you can't find it, baking soda might
be nearly as effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking at a house I would like to buy. It has 1,300
square feet of living space and electric heat. The owner said he
spends $1,100 for heat and hot water a year. I am skeptical of that
figure, but if I bought the house I would install hot-water heat
fired by gas. I learned that this would cost $6,500 to $9,500 to
install. Is that something reasonable to expect?
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY KRUMSHAK, Boston
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I too am suspicious of that electric heating and hot water
yearly cost. The cost of a new system and boiler sounds reasonable,
although you could put in a hot-air system and gas furnace for
somewhat less. A nonelectric heating system and hot water heating
could save you half of that $1,100. The savings would pay for the
new system in 12 years (low side) or 18 years (high side). Payoff
would be faster if you put in a less expensive hot-air system and
furnace. These payoff times are beyond the 10-year limit used to
gauge economic feasibility, but if you like the house and location,
it is worth doing. And maybe you can get the owner to knock off
something from the price because of this need to replace the
expensive electric heat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The addition to my house has a roof with a 15-degree pitch,
asphalt shingles, and two roof windows set at 30 degrees. My
problem is noise from rain. The roof is well insulated. How can I
lessen that drumming on the roof and roof windows?
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM ROBERTS, Rockland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing can be done about the roof itself because the rain is
impact noise, and to stop impact noise you have to put on a softer
surface. Can't you just see putting Astroturf on your roof? I don't
think the roof is as much of a culprit as the roof windows, which
act as a drum, echoing and reverberating every drop that falls.
</P>
<P>
   Try installing a Window Quilt at the ceiling line. You could
make it translucent, but you would have to open it for air. Window
quilts are secured tightly to the window frame and can help quite a
bit. They are sold in home goods and other stores. But don't expect
library silence. Or, you could set up a thin piece of wood,
insulated on the inside with 1-inch rigid foam insulation, that
could be screwed or fastened to the bottom of the opening. It might
be a little awkward to put up and down, but if it works, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am thinking of replacing my fir gutters with aluminum
gutters, and I'd like a heavy-duty gutter. How do I know I'm
getting a heavy-duty one? I'd like to hang them myself. Is that
practical? How much would the sections have to overlap?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD STEPHAN, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Thickness of gutters is described by gauge. Roofers and
gutter installers can show you heavy-duty ones; the handyman's
roofer recently suggested a heavy-duty gutter in a certain place,
heavy enough to lean a ladder against. I haven't checked it out
with the ladder yet; I trust my roofer. It might be a little
tougher to get a heavy-duty gutter at a store.
</P>
<P>
   You certainly can do it yourself. There are a few rules to
follow. For starters, the sections generally do not overlap; they
butt end to end, secured with a fastener and mastic.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a gutter should slope about 116 inch per foot.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the gutter should be in the right position for water to
drip into the center, not too near the front edge and not too near
the back edge. To determine that position, lay a board on the roof
so that it overhangs by a foot or two. The front edge of the gutter
should be within half an inch of this board.
</P>
<P>
   You can hang the gutter with strap hangers, hangers that fit
into the gutter itself, or with a spike and ferrule. The spike goes
through the gutter right at the top, into the fascia, preferably
into the end of a rafter. The ferrule fits inside the gutter so the
spike doesn't squeeze the gutter out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A radiator leak wet a part of my carpet and backing. The leak
is fixed, but the carpet is exuding a chemical smell. How can I get
rid of that smell?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN PAUPLIS, Wayland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let the carpet and the pad dry out thoroughly; you may have
to lift the rug to get at the pad. Putting a fan on the rug will
hasten drying. Lots of ventilation will, too. If that does not
improve things, you can have the carpet cleaned. Another
possibility is to cut out the pad that got wet and substitute a new
piece of pad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
