r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BESIEGED-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      06-10 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESIEGED-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE, SPACES ARE EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Bernardo Bertolucci makes two kinds of movies: those,
like ``The Last Emperor'' and ``Little Buddha,'' which are readily
accessible to American audiences, and those, like ``The Sheltering
Sky'' and ``The Conformist,'' where you must find your way into the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci's new drama, ``Besieged,'' is one of the latter. If
you want to gain a sense of this film, you must meet it half way if
not three-quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' opens in Africa with a series of images that look
like an anti-travelogue: pictures of an unhappy people and a
threatening military.
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-minute wander, the film moves to Rome, where
Shandurai (Thandie Newton) studies at the university while working
as a maid to a reclusive pianist, Mr. Kinsky (David Thewlis).
</P>
<P>
   For another 15 minutes, we are taken through scenes from their
daily lives, again almost without dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Then Kinsky suddenly announces that he's in love and wants
Shandurai to marry him, knowing practically nothing about her or
her African culture.
</P>
<P>
   That might be Bertolucci's point, that Europe and Africa are
separated by a cultural divide wider than the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, their behavior turns even more inexplicable, when
Shandurai learns that her long-suffering husband is to be released
from an African prison and will join her in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Besieged'' is an impressionistic film conveyed with a
minimum of talking, plot or explanation, there is not much else to
fill the spaces left by the silence of speech and story. Even
Bertolucci the artist cannot make much of repeated scenes of people
entering a metro or walking down a city street.
</P>
<P>
   The African music is the film's most attractive element, but
even that is explored in a minimal fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have a cultivated taste for European cinema, you may
find Bertolucci's tolerance for his own laxity a bit too
dispiriting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' is predominantly in English, with subtitles when it
is not. The film is rated R for brief nudity and sex. 2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Fenster can be reached at bob.fenster(at)pni.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1452EDT &QL; 
