r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-10 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TRAGEDY STRIKES, RECALL LIFE'S BLESSINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've had a lot of drama in our lives during the past few weeks.
I've spun the emotional wheel of fortune and landed on grief, fear
and joy.
</P>
<P>
   My only prize was the sunrise of each new day, which brought
with it the vague promise of another chance at happiness.
</P>
<P>
   First, my father-in-law, Andy, had a stroke. His body had
already been ravaged by a previous stroke, hypertension, failing
kidneys and diabetes. He lapsed into a coma and was placed on life
support. At 65, this is not the retirement one anticipates.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, my mother was involved in a terrible car
accident. Her car was hit at an intersection, and it didn't stop
spinning until it wrapped around a pole like a yo-yo in fate's
palm.
</P>
<P>
   A frantic phone call from my sister at 8 a.m. catapulted me from
my office to a hospital in Fort Worth, where my mother lay in the
emergency room, battered and bruised, and, remarkably, alive.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting how these things all happen in rapid
succession. We seem to become human dominoes, waiting for disaster
to topple us. My sister was supposed to get married the weekend
after my mother's accident. Two days later, as a matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   Andy was removed from life support on the day of my mother's
accident. We waited and anticipated. They put a ``Do Not
Resuscitate'' sign on Andy's door.
</P>
<P>
   It felt as if they had put that same sign on the rest of our
lives. But I smiled anyway. I later smiled at my mother's bedside
as she vowed to walk down the aisle at the wedding. I kept smiling
for my family as we sat at the hospital in San Antonio praying and
hoping for Andy's doctors to say they had made a mistake and he'd
be all right. I smiled for my friends as they voiced their concern
and compassion. I smiled, smiled, smiled.
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of a cane and my two sons, Mom did walk down that
aisle as scheduled. A few days later, Andy's soul walked away from
his paralyzed body to what I believe is a better place.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on our way back from Andy's funeral, a big truck slammed
into the back of our vehicle. Can you believe it? Do you ever have
periods like this in your life? Don't you just want to scream,
``That's enough! I've had all I can take. Give me a break!''
</P>
<P>
   As I sat there on the side of the highway, waiting for the state
troopers, I thought about everything that had happened. Then I
thought about everything that could have happened. And do you know
what I did then?
</P>
<P>
   I picked myself up, hugged my frightened family and I smiled,
smiled, smiled.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
