u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS &LR;      06-10 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY MAGAZINES BARE IT, AND GRIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it's June, it must be time for a parade of pulchritude on
the covers of America's city magazines. This month's Boston
magazine features an exceedingly fit model in a tiny two-piece suit
advertising ``Summer Pleasures.'' Chicago magazine's summer issue
is graced by bikini-clad Gabrielle Reece, the statuesque volleyball
star. The cover girl for San Diego Magazine is Playboy's Miss July
1998 Lisa Dergan striking a come-hither pose in one of the season's
``hot summer swimsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   For the slick city mags, long accused of showcasing perky
``bimbos'' on their covers, it seems that nothing sells like skin.
Well not exactly, say those who understand the magazines' typically
upscale 40-something audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dowden, director of the City and Regional Magazine
Association, said his group recently solicited examples of best-
and worst-selling covers. The sure-fire winners are such city mag
chestnuts as top restaurants, top doctors, and best buys. In other
words, it's the service journalism, not the hot model, that really
sells. In fact, skimpy swimsuit models are usually there to dress
up a service story on ``the best weekend getaways,'' says Dowden,
at least half-seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston magazine, editor Craig Unger has downplayed sexy
covers; the June 1998 ``Summer Pleasures'' issue featured only the
head of a female model. The current cover, he says, ``is one of the
rare times we went for a professional model. We specifically sought
a model who's athletic.'' The model (the exotic-sounding Olanna) is
supposed to connect the reader to such strenuous fun as hiking and
sea kayaking. ``Our history has been that actual words matter more
than the image,'' says Unger. But he's already fielded a dozen
complaints that the midriff-baring Olanna is too skinny.
</P>
<P>
   On Chicago's cover, the 6-foot-3-inch Reece is not simply eye
candy, explains editor Richard Babcock. She's part of the summer
``User's Guide,'' because she actually instructs readers on how to
spike a volleyball. ``There are endless ways to convey good
feelings about the summer season and someone in a swimsuit is one
way,'' he says, presumably with a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, where it's summer half the year, Los
Angeles magazine did its sun-and-fun issue in May and cut right to
the chase in the June edition. ``The Sex Issue!'' features a
provocative cover shot of actress Calista Flockhart perched atop a
naked man and includes stories on lap dance parties and
partner-swapping bacchanals.
</P>
<P>
   Editor-in-chief Spencer Beck says the winning formula is to
``get a big star and get a huge service'' cover. (He obviously
considers sex a form of service journalism.) ``I'm a strong
believer that sex sells,'' he declares. ``This is the first (sex
issue) and I'm gonna do it every year because you cannot find the
magazine'' on the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   So where must one live to escape the city magazines' fascination
with the flesh? How about the City of Brotherly Love where new
Philadelphia magazine editor Stephen Fried tried a counterintuitive
twist. The June ``Great Summer Drives'' cover is pure family
values, with an illustration of dad, mom, junior, and Rover off
road-tripping in the red Mustang. ``We wanted to do something
differently,'' Fried says. ``I think our readers appreciate strong
service and they want the magazine to be interesting and
surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philly may not be a bikini-free zone after all since Fried
is planning a sand-and-sea issue for July. Asked about the cover,
he offers a hint: ``It could involve twins.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a time when former Cincinnati Enquirer reporter Mike
Gallagher squeals on his confidential informant and fired CNN
producer April Oliver sues a confidential source, it's actually
refreshing to hear a judge order two reporters to jail for keeping
mum about the people who fed them crucial information.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in former 1996 Olympic bombing suspect
Richard Jewell's long-running libel suit against the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. In response to Judge John Mather's June 3
order that reporters Kathy Scruggs and Ron Martz be jailed for
failing to reveal law enforcement sources who provided information
about the Jewell investigation, the defendants' attorney Peter
Canfield filed a notice of appeal with the state Court of Appeals
effectively staying their sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Canfield argues that the reporters should not have to reveal
sources because their stories were accurate and because the court
has not examined the viability of Jewell's claims. ``The trial
judge has never looked at the merits of this lawsuit,'' says
Canfield. ``The order puts the cart before the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his clients are actually prepared to sit behind bars if
the appeal fails, Canfield says, ``I don't think it really serves
our interest to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to instill pride and stability in local journalism, about
two dozen of the Connecticut-based Thomson newspaper chain's mostly
small-market papers are recruiting and training citizens with no
journalism experience to become reporters. (Thomson senior vice
president for reader and product development Terry Quinn estimates
they'll start at an average salary in the high teens.)
</P>
<P>
   The fond hope is that the grass-roots recruits will already be
engaged in civic life. ``We do not feel the current journalism
school system services the smaller community newspapers,'' says
Quinn, noting that ambitious young reporters rarely make an
``emotional investment'' to smaller papers. ``One of the areas
we're preaching is bringing more passion to our communities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
