<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO IQ: PRIMER ON INITIAL OFFERINGS BREAKS DOWN RISKS,
OPPORTUNITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you love roller-coaster investing, consider the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Buying stock in a company's initial public offering is not for
the weak-hearted, financial writer Tom Taulli says. But the
potential to make money is astronomical.
</P>
<P>
   Consider amazon.com, the online bookstore that is the No. 1
distributor of books in the world. The initial offering price of
its IPO was $18. A few years later, it reached a high of $208 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the story of Amgen, a drug maker, whose IPO started
out in 1983 at $1.50 per share. The stock now sells for $70.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, Home Depot and Southwest Bankcorp. of Texas are also
examples of successful IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a dangerous downside to these little gems. Some
IPOs soar 50 percent on their first day, and then proceed on a wild
death spiral downward, wiping out investors' money. Other IPOs
never seem to get off the ground, and then sizzle and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing in IPOs can be a wild ride,'' admits Taulli, who
writes about such investing for ``Barron's'' and other print media,
appears on CNN and CNBC and writes columns for online investment
publications such as ``Microsoft Investor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taulli adds that some sense of order can be brought to the
risky investment through patience and research. He shares his
expertise on the subject in ``Investing In IPOs'' (Bloomberg Press,
264 pages, $).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact that IPOs make one of the best places in the
financial markets to find huge gainers,'' he writes. ``There's
enormous upside if you can manage to pick the winners at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you're still nervous about looking into such investments
to diversify your portfolio, consider this: ``Chances are that you
have already participated in the IPO market and don't realize it,''
Taulli writes.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that mutual funds are the biggest purchasers of
IPOs. Fidelity's mutual funds, for example, make up 10 percent of
the IPO market share in the United States, Taulli explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you own mutual funds, you likely own IPOs,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you go about picking the golden winners from the
dismal losers? One key is to stay informed.
</P>
<P>
   Taulli recommends print publications such as The Wall Street
Journal and Barron's to get you familiar with what IPOs are coming
up. Online services such as The Internet Stock Report and
Thestreet.com and databases such as Bloomberg Financial Markets and
IPO Central will provide you with the latest filings,
registrations, pricing and aftermarket performance.
</P>
<P>
   The first place Taulli says he goes to investigate an IPO is the
Electronic Data Gathering Analysis and Retrieval online database of
financial filings developed by the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, EDGAR has every company's prospectus, which
holds ``most of the specifics you need to evaluate an IPO,'' Taulli
writes. The documents have become more reader-friendly recently
with new SEC rules calling for ``plain English'' in drafting a
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Taulli provides an analysis of all the information sources, and
then breaks down the major industries with the hottest IPOs, namely
technology, biotech, finance and retail. He also devotes a chapter
to foreign IPOs, IPO mutual funds and online or virtual IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the basic primer descriptions for a novice investor,
Taulli provides insight for those with more financial savvy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while discussing risk factors of IPOs, he notes
that if more than 50 percent of the proceeds for an IPO are
earmarked for outstanding debts, which would be noted in the
prospectus, ``chances are that the company has dismal growth
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Taulli writes that an IPO stock offering below $5 per
share is considered a ``penny stock'' and labeled ``extremely
risky.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Streetwise Motivating &AMP; Rewarding Employees: New and Better
Ways to Inspire Your People''
</P>
<P>
   By Alexander Hiam
</P>
<P>
   Adams Media Corp., $17.95
</P>
<P>
   ``However good your people are, they could be a lot better,''
begins this book by trainer and consultant Alexander Hiam. But
rather than completely revamping a company, Hiam says, his methods
work by ``transforming the daily interactions with your people in
small but powerful ways.'' This tome offers many interesting ideas
on increasing productivity in thoughtful ways.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Rescued By Personal Computers''
</P>
<P>
   By Kris Jamsa
</P>
<P>
   Jamsa Press, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   This is an ideal primer for beginners or those who want to
expand their computer skills. It is broken into 15-minute lessons
teaching a specific skill: e-mail retrieving and sending, surfing
the Web, learning basic software programs. From unpacking your
personal computer to chatting online around the world on the Web,
this book can tell you what to do with simple, easy-to-follow
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Single Best Investment: Achieve Lasting Wealth with Low
Risk, Steady Growth Stocks''
</P>
<P>
   By Lowell Miller
</P>
<P>
   Adams Media Corp., $21.95
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: There are 8,000 mutual funds today, compared with
less than 1,000 in 1975, and there are more than 20,000 domestic
stocks, compared with 6,000 just 20 years ago. That alone can make
individual investors pull out their hair. Lowell Miller says he has
evaluated it all in the 25 years he has been an investment adviser,
and his best advice is this: Find a select group of stocks in
steady, moderate growth companies with consistent returns, minimal
risk and little price fluctuation _ and you'll make the best return
possible.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
