<HEADLINE>
CATCH UP WITH FLYING SAUCER FLOWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I obtain seeds of flying saucer morning glories?
</P>
<P>
   _A.T.F., Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: One mail-order retailer that sells them is the Jung Seed
Catalog. You can order two 50-seed packets for $3.10 plus $3.50
shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 297-3123 or write to J.W. Jung Seed Co.,
335 S. High St., Randolph, WI 53957-0001. The company also has a
World Wide Web site at www.jungseed.com.
</P>
<P>
   Flying saucers are a variety of morning glory with white and
blue flowers introduced by Darold Decker in 1960. They bloom from
early to late summer and should be planted in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to country singer Marty Stuart?
</P>
<P>
   _G.C., Haltom City, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Letters can be sent in care of the official Marty Stuart Fan
Club, Box 24180, Nashville, TN 37202.
</P>
<P>
   The same address is used to join the club, which costs $12 per
year. Members receive a quarterly newsletter, color photo and
special opportunities to attend autograph sessions.
</P>
<P>
   On June 15, Stuart is releasing his 11th album, ``The Pilgrim.''
The two-album project is described as a ``concept album,'' and it
tells a tragic love story about a man Stuart knew when he was
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   More information on ``Pilgrim'' and Stuart's current tour
schedule is available from his official World Wide Web site,
www.martyparty.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I subscribed to Country Wood Projects, a magazine published
by Harris Publications. The magazine stopped coming, but I know I
have issues due. Are they still in publication?
</P>
<P>
   _E.D.J., Saginaw, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Country Wood Projects was canceled in 1996, and subscribers
were sent a refund for undelivered issues, according to a Harris
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries about refunds should be sent to Circulation
Department, 1115 Broadway, New York, NY 10010.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
