<HEADLINE>
REMEMBRANCE OF THONGS PAST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many people have experienced deja vu, being certain that
something is unknown and yet perceiving it as familiar. Is there an
opposite of deja vu? When you know for sure you've been there, done
that, seen something, met somebody before but you can't remember
anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning the bookshelves I found dozens of books I'm positive
I've read but can't remember reading. I just re-read Muriel Spark's
``The Ballad of Peckham Rye.'' How could I forget such a wonderful
novel?
</P>
<P>
   When reverse deja vu happens with people the results are not as
happy. You run into someone you're sure you know and she yammers on
about the most intimate details of your life while you stand there
thinking: Who is this person? And how does she know I no longer
have a gallbladder? This sort of thing isn't strictly a function of
aging. Something similar used to happen in school. I'd study like
mad, then sit down for the exam and find I'd forgotten everything.
Maybe it's nothing mysterious, just simple stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it may be, it's too bad it can't be utilized
selectively because I'd like to forget some of the hideous things
I've eaten lately. You never know when you'll find yourself trapped
in a desperate eating situation. In an airport. In a hospital
cafeteria. At the FleetCenter. Held captive on a highway most
people will eat anything, which is how I found myself at Hot Dog
City on the Mass. Pike, ordering a dog with the works. Talk about
desperate eating. I'd like to forget the taste, the texture, the
aftermath. But I can't.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many people, I worry too much about what I eat. We've
all been conditioned. Just about every food comes with nutritional
particulars, even if the food in question isn't remotely
nutritious. What sort of nutritional information could possibly
pertain to a bag of taco chips? Except maybe a warning: ``Eating
these may be hazardous to your hips.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday's newspaper arrived with a free sample of Wow!
potato chips, a new product made with the miracle fatless fat
substitute Olestra. The only miraculous thing about Olestra is that
anybody is willing to eat it. Small print on the bag warned that
Olestra ``may cause abdominal cramping and loose stools.'' Maybe
that's why they named it Wow! But please, spare us the details.
Couldn't they just put a line on the bag that reads, ``Eating these
may make you sick,'' and leave it at that?
</P>
<P>
   Men's Fitness appears in my mailbox every month, for reasons
that are not entirely clear. Not that I'm complaining, because it's
a big, lovable hunk of a magazine, and I read it avidly for the
insights it provides into the male psyche. Many of the stories are
all but identical to the stories you'll find in women's magazines,
but couched in different terms, to wit: ``Before you start cutting
calories, cut the crap out of your diet.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd never see that sort of language in a woman's magazine,
which is too bad. That no-nonsense advice might come in handy next
time I'm tempted by Hot Dog City.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletin: This is Ergonomics For Everyday Living Week,
proclaimed by Cynthia Dunning Michels of Longwood, Fla., creator of
the first ergonomically engineered underwear for men, ETU Original
Briefs. Ergonomics, in case you're wondering, are design factors
intended to maximize comfort, function, and safety. Maybe Michels
will give some thought to ergonomically engineered underwear for
women. Tuesday's Wall Street Journal had a lengthy report on the
growing popularity of thong underwear in post-Monica America. (I
guess that's why they call the Journal ``The Daily Diary of the
American Dream.'') The thong may be sexy, but it's definitely not
ergonomically sound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
