A0299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-10 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT ADVENTURE: 40 YEARS TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 11 at night.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing in the bedroom, stripping off my clothes as fast
as I could. In my rush, I kicked off my shoes, pulled off my shirt,
and dropped my slacks on the floor. Behind me, my husband was
unbuckling his belt. He tore off his watch, stepped out of his
pants, and soon was as naked as I was. I'd already turned on the
shower, and as I stepped into the warm water, Jack was right behind
me, holding a bottle of Bloody Mary mix.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way for a couple who's just celebrated their 40th
anniversary to behave? Can passion, with all its youthful urgency,
survive so many years of child-raising, house maintenance, and
bodily wear and tear? Are Jack and I an exception to the rule that
the original blazing fires of love eventually settle into a quiet
congenial glow?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that our dog, instead of doing what she'd been put
outside to do, had decided to pursue a passing skunk, with
predictable results. Pandora was drooling skunk spray from her
mouth, emitting an odor that was permeating every inch of our
house. With each jerk of misery, she wiped a thin film of spray on
our walls, a door jamb, a chair. With every moment wasted, drops of
spray fell on our floors, seeping into the rugs. For two people
prepared to go to bed after a long day, it was so awful that we
found ourselves laughing as we slathered the chastened dog with Dr.
Bronner's pure Castile soap and spicy tomato juice.
</P>
<P>
   With 30 people arriving the next day for what would be a
skunk-scented celebration in honor of my son-in-law's having
completed his PhD, we had a choice.
</P>
<P>
   It was either laugh or shoot ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while most of us were outside during the party, the dog
got up on our dining room table for the first time in her life and
ate a cake designed to feed 30, then topped it off with three dozen
cookies. The vet had no suggestions other than to keep a close eye
on her and see what happened. Because our house has an open floor
plan, and because the dog barked incessantly when we tied her
outside on her run, see it we did. For three days, the dog ejected
various disgusting substances out of both orifices at all hours of
the day and night in every conceivable undesirable location in our
house.
</P>
<P>
   I never thought about coping with daily disasters when I married
Jack. You know how it is: a head full of daydreams. I anticipated
romance, admiration, and fun. I looked forward to conversations,
shared interests, and exciting adventures. And there has been some
element of each of those in our 40 years together.
</P>
<P>
   But when you hear the dog retching at the foot of your bed as
you lie warm and relaxed under the covers at 4 a.m., there is
nothing more conducive to loving feelings than hearing your husband
say in a voice that is wonderfully calm and unperturbed, ``I'll get
it this time, hon.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first 24 hours, we went through every towel in the house.
Jack took charge of washing them. The dog messed on a small
Oriental carpet in the wee hours of the morning. Jack cleaned it
and hung it outside to air. I felt not only gratitude but a melting
of all resentments and an upwelling of overwhelming affection.
</P>
<P>
   I probably wouldn't have said this 20 years ago, but if Prince
Charming himself had ridden up on his horse to rescue me, I would
have sent him away. What fantasy can compare to having a person by
your side who assumes an equal share of the unpleasant realities of
daily life?
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years, let me offer a definition of romance, apart from
the usual flowers and candy. Let a man cheerfully clear the table
and smile when helping make the bed. Have him get a kick out of
coaching his son's T-ball team or look forward to reading a story
to his daughter at bedtime. A woman's heart begins to flutter when
the man beside her is also unpacking the groceries.
</P>
<P>
   A woman's soul embraces the man who has taken the day off from
work to accompany her to a routine but distressing medical
procedure. There is nothing more soul-stirring than turning to
another who is also reaching out to you.
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years, love may no longer rage like a bonfire, but the
heat generated by glances of understanding and frequent gestures of
support can keep one warm for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
