<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITERATE-RELIGION-NYT     06-10 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERATE-RELIGION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUBTLE, POWERFUL LINK BETWEEN EDUCATION AND RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It has become a rite of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Every graduation season, some community tests the limits of
church-state relations by sponsoring school prayer or allowing a
sectarian graduation sermon to be preached.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated court rulings that the state cannot promote
religion in public education, school-prayer advocates continue to
argue their case.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect many Americans find this tiresome -- either because
they agree with the Supreme Court or recognize that the
school-prayer rulings will not be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the argument misses the point. Throughout American
history, there exists a more subtle -- and often more powerful --
relationship between education and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with European settlement, Americans have prized
literacy. The earliest cultural impulses for education were
religious ones. The Puritans, who envisioned Massachusetts as a
``Bible Commonwealth,'' believed that God's people had to be able
to read God's book. To that end, they brought books across the
ocean, started printing houses, established libraries, and founded
Harvard College.
</P>
<P>
   In 1647, they passed the ``old deluder Satan'' law that
established universal education to teach children to read the
Scriptures lest they fall prey to the wiles of the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   By 1700, 95 percent of the men (and 60 percent of the women) in
New England could read. Although literacy rates were lower in other
regions, evidence exists that a majority of American colonists
could read the King James Bible and other simple texts.
</P>
<P>
   Reading was considered a spiritual exercise. If individuals
could read the Bible for themselves, they could interpret scripture
and make common-sense choices regarding truth.
</P>
<P>
   As the colonies formed a new nation, denominations heeded the
call to create an educated citizenry. Before the Civil War,
Protestants alone founded 130 colleges. At these institutions, as
with schools of every level, the Bible formed the core of the
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Although some schools, such as the University of Virginia, were
established on secular principles, most early American education
was a religious enterprise. Perhaps because of the close link
between literacy and faith, American religious beliefs have been
substantially shaped by scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   Not every culture sees reading this way. Some depend on oral
tradition or ritual to teach religious values. Although Americans
can be oddly anti-intellectual, we remain a bookish lot when it
comes to faith.
</P>
<P>
   However, the relationship between religion and reading has
changed over time. Literacy no longer focuses solely on the Bible.
That does not mean, however, that education is a strictly secular
enterprise. If one employs a broader definition of ``scripture,''
teaching can be seen as still fundamentally a spiritual vocation.
</P>
<P>
   Even early in American history, not every colonist was a
literate Christian. Before the Europeans, native religions
understood myth and nature as sacred texts.
</P>
<P>
   And the Europeans themselves did not prove uniformly orthodox in
their interpretation of the Bible. Although some hewed closely to
traditional Christianity, others departed so radically that they
wrote their own scriptures. Some adopted other religion's sacred
texts.
</P>
<P>
   Still others were never Christian at all. Jews, Buddhists and
Hindus bought their own holy books to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite claims to the contrary, the United States was never a
purely biblical culture. Many sacred texts shaped American
religious experience. The Bible often stood predominate but never
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the link between reading and faith, most successful
American religions have emphasized holy books. Traditional world
religions teach their books such as the Koran or Bhagavad Gita.
Home-grown faiths wrote their own sacred texts. Where would
Mormonism be without the Book of Mormon? Or Christian Science
without ``Science and Health''? Newer religions often base their
claims on divinely inspired texts.
</P>
<P>
   Even political documents, such as the Declaration of
Independence, take on quasi-scriptural status. American religion --
traditional, new, or civil -- is book religion.
</P>
<P>
   To recognize that religion birthed much of American education,
and that education itself is broadly religious, does not violate
the separation of church and state. Although Protestants
established this relationship in America, nearly every religion
here now depends on sacred scripture to form faith. Education
reflects the pluralism -- rather than the particularity -- of
American religion.
</P>
<P>
   Educators, by teaching reading, interpretation and critical
theory, enable people to evaluate competing religious claims.
Teachers are doorkeepers to a wide variety of faiths, ethical
systems, and moral claims.
</P>
<P>
   The state need not ``permit'' religion in the public schools. It
is already there -- in all its confusing and glorious American
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   And schools, as has always been the case, have a profoundly
religious vocation: To teach, as in the words of the ``old deluder
Satan'' law, ``That Learning may not be buried in the graves of our
fore-fathers in Church and Commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0302 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITERATE-RELIGION-NYT     06-10 0988
