<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-GREER-2TAKES-B     06-10 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GREER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL GERMAINE, DASHING AND INCONSISTENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BELLA ENGLISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Germaine Greer is sprawled out on the king-size bed
at the Pierre Hotel, all 6 feet of her. She has good legs and she
knows it, showing them off to maximum advantage in a short black
dress, black tights, and black pumps. The photographer has asked
her to do this and that, and she obliges him quite politely. Here
she is, leaning back and laughing uproariously, legs up
revealingly. There she is, lying down in beach-blanket pose.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there, since she once sat for a close-up shot of her
privates for a porn rag she helped found in the 1960s. (``That
issue is unobtainable anywhere in the world,'' she sniffs. ``The
idea was that all the editors would expose themselves as ruthlessly
as we exposed others. But the men didn't do it.'')
</P>
<P>
   But back to June of 1999. Would she consider going next door to
Barney's and posing at the cosmetics counter, where all those
trendy young men make up all those gorgeous young women in the
latest colors?
</P>
<P>
   Not bloody likely. ``Do you know the thing about being 60?'' she
asks, sitting straight up on the bed, eyes flashing. ``They don't
even want to put makeup on you.'' She launches into a story about
going to Bloomingdale's the day before. ``This woman was squirting
perfume all over people. I was all ready to say no thank you when
she turns away from me and goes toward a young woman. I'm
invisible. I could come in glittering with diamonds from head to
foot and they would go over to the younger girls who don't know if
they have $12 to put together. I'm invisible,'' she repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine Greer is anything but. Thirty years after ``The Female
Eunuch'' created an international sensation with its frank analysis
of the bleak condition of women, she has written its sequel, a book
she vowed she would never write. In ``The Whole Woman,'' Greer
maintains that things are bleaker than ever for women. The book has
stirred controversy on both sides of the Atlantic: in England,
where Greer lives, and in America, where she is now on book tour.
</P>
<P>
   British reviewers have wondered, to quote one headline, whether
``Germaine is germane.'' American feminists have berated her for
being sloppy, anti-male, and contradictory. Camille Paglia called
the book ``exasperatingly disjointed and scattershot.'' The New
York Times ended its review with: `` `The Whole Woman' is a
castrated book.''
</P>
<P>
   A major complaint about Greer is that she is inconsistent, a
trait she displays consistently during a recent interview in her
hotel room. One minute she is saying she doesn't read her reviews:
``I can't. They'd do me in.'' The next minute, she's dismissing
Camille Paglia as ``an odd girl'' because of Paglia's negative
review of her book. ``She used to be on my side. I've defended her
on untenable grounds because I thought she was an original
feminist. She liked me,'' she adds acidly, ``when she thought no
one else liked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's her current love interest. This is a man for whom
she made a compilation tape before she flew to the States, so that
he would have something to remember her by. This is the woman who
declared that she gave up sex a long time ago, who proclaimed
publicly that ``no sex is better than bad sex.'' (Penises, she
claims, are overrated.) And this is the very same woman who was
married for three weeks in 1968, during which time she says she
cheated on her husband seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Of love, she says, ``I gave it my best shot. I spent the best
years of my life waiting for the phone to ring.''
</P>
<P>
   This country-Western lament, from one of the world's leading
feminists?
</P>
<P>
   She continues: ``I gave up on the whole business of sex 10 or 12
years ago. The first year was very hard. I got used to a life
without love. I found all the people I had neglected and all the
causes I'd neglected and I felt really happy and centered in my
life. I knew the one thing I had to worry about was falling in
love. I also knew that some day, I would turn a corner and there he
would be.''
</P>
<P>
   He _ whoever he is _ was indeed around the corner. ``Was he
worth it?'' she asks. ``Yes. Was he an embarrassment? Yes. Was he
someone else's? Yes. Was he manipulative? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, what happened to him? ``He's still out of jail,'' she says
impishly. ``I've ended it.'' A minute later, she adds: ``No, I'm
not sure it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   In her introduction to ``The Whole Woman,'' Greer asserts that
she wrote the book because in the 30 years since ``The Female
Eunuch,'' women's lives have become fuller but tougher. ``When `The
Female Eunuch' was written our daughters were not cutting or
starving themselves. . . . It's time to get angry again.''
</P>
<P>
   There are people who would probably swear in a court of law that
Greer has never stopped being angry. Still, she's hardly a
humorless feminist. She can be downright hilarious, but God forbid
she aim her mordant humor at you. After one writer annoyed her,
Greer, referring to the columnist's lip-stained logo, stated that
``lipstick must rot the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the secretary of state is not spared: Madeleine Albright,
she opines, should stay away from short skirts, especially when
seated on couches next to heads of state. ``There are certain
things I cannot take,'' she says. ``She's always wearing these
short skirts and she's so grossly fat. She must spend more time
eating than thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask her what she'd do differently in her life and she pauses
before stating, seriously: ``I wouldn't have bunions.''
</P>
<P>
   In person and in her book, she shows little patience with
feminists of both her generation and the next. It was bad enough
that her colleagues started asserting that feminism had gone too
far. Then the young ones got uppity. ``When the lifestyle feminists
chimed in that feminism had gone just far enough in giving them the
right to `have it all,' i.e., money, sex, and fashion, it would
have been inexcusable to remain silent,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining silent is one thing Greer has never been accused of.
In her new book, she takes on everything from men (``to be male is
to be a kind of idiot savant, full of queer obsessions about
fetishistic activities and fantasy goals . . . '') to high heels
(``the high-heeled shoe itself is a marvelously contradictory item;
it brings a woman to a man's height but makes sure she cannot keep
up with him'').
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
