<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MCBRIDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
THE `EVOLUTION' OF MARTINA McBRIDE  
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martina McBride's latest album, ``Evolution,'' opens with a tape
of the singer at age 7 belting out Little Jimmy Dickens' Grand Ole
Opry favorite ``I'm Little But I'm Loud.'' The recording was made
on a cassette recorder at a 4-H Club convention in Manhattan, Kan.,
not far from the farm where McBride grew up in tiny Sharon, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put that on there because it was really representative of
what I did when I was a kid,'' McBride said. ``I'd go around, and
my dad would play guitar and I would sing. It's just this little
piece of history that somehow has survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 years later, McBride is still little at 5-foot-4 and
barely 100 pounds. She's still loud, too.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who's heard her hits _ such as ``Independence Day''
and ``A Broken Wing'' _ can attest, McBride can hold her own with
the most powerful female country singers in Nashville, from Patty
Loveless and Wynonna Judd to Trisha Yearwood and Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   McBride was calling from the Money Pit studio in Nashville,
Tenn., where she was finishing the follow-up to ``Evolution.'' The
album is due in September, even though ``Evolution'' is still
hovering around the country Top 10 nearly two years after its
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have to give credit to the songs,'' said McBride of
the album's remarkable staying power. ``Every song that we've put
out has been a hit. We've released six singles off the album.
That's pretty unusual, especially for country music. So I'm also
going to have to credit the record company for sticking with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But give the credit to McBride, too, and her co-producer, Paul
Worley, for finding those songs. They listened to more than 1,000
submissions to pick the dozen or so gems on the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we have more artists than we've ever had, so the
demand for great songs has gone up,'' she said. ``But they're out
there. You just have to take the time to really search for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I set my standards pretty high when it comes to recording
material. In the past, I've put out some things that haven't
worked. With this album, I feel like I've finally been accepted at
radio. The good songs have gotten through. That doesn't always
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride's career has been distinguished by her refusal to cut
the dumb little ditties that clutter too many Nashville releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the audience credit for their intelligence,'' she said.
``I think an audience wants to be entertained and doesn't want to
always have to think about something heavy. At the same time, I
think they want to hear intelligent lyrics. You need a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the new album won't be a radical departure from
``Evolution,'' but it will represent a slightly more raw sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite as layered, not quite as textured, not quite so
produced, which is something I wanted to go for,'' said McBride,
who takes an active role in all aspects of the production of her
albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut with a smaller band. We keep trying to add little
instrumental overdubs and they just don't fit. It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride and her husband, sound engineer John McBride, moved to
Nashville in 1990 after working with Top 40 cover bands in Kansas.
John soon landed a job mixing sound for a young up-and-coming
country singer named Garth Brooks, and Martina tagged along on tour
selling T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   With the 1992 release of her debut album, ``The Time Has Come,''
McBride graduated to opening shows for Brooks. But it wasn't until
her 1993 album, ``The Way That I Am,'' that her career really took
off.
</P>
<P>
   The album included the hit ``Independence Day,'' a powerful song
about domestic violence as seen through the eyes of a young girl.
The video for the song was voted video of the year by the Country
Music Association _ the first time a female artist had won that
award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way That I Am'' was eventually certified platinum, as was
1995's ``Wild Angels.'' Prior to the release of Evolution, McBride
recorded ``Valentine,'' a duet with pop pianist Jim Brickman that
became a No. 1 adult contemporary hit. She also sang a hit country
duet with RCA label mate Clint Black called ``Still Holding On.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the single ``Broken Wing'' that really sent folks
into the record stores with money in hand. Like ``Independence
Day,'' the song is about a woman in an abusive relationship. But
this time, the story has a happier ending; rather than burn down
the house, she departs through an open window.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that song has a lot of symbolism,'' McBride said. ``The
window is symbolic for her flying away to freedom. I think what
it's saying is that even though this man tries to break her spirit,
he can't break her spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The McBrides have two daughters: Delaney, 4, and Emma, 14
months. Both travel with mom and dad on the tour bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a little family out there,'' McBride said. ``It's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Delaney about to enter school, McBride has scaled back
her tour schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really easy to tour with a little baby, but 4-year-olds
kind of start missing home. She misses her things, and her bike,
and her yard, and her preschool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always make your decisions based around the kids. Anyway,
that's how it is for me as a mother. When I was pregnant, I was
like, `I don't know how this is all gonna work.' And then once you
have the baby, you realize that, well, everything else just has to
fit around this.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride is proud to be part of the generation of female artists
that has finally leveled the playing field between men and women in
country music. While she's been outspoken about the shortcomings of
Nashville's factory approach to making country music, she's managed
to carve an independent space within that system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very satisfied with the music that I've made, and I
feel happy that it has been accepted. I've been able to get away
with making music that is original and thoughtful and production
that isn't typical at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest insult to country music is when someone puts a
steel guitar on there because they think they have to make it
`country.' That's kind of token. Put it on because that's what you
feel in your heart, not to try to fit a certain format.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Evolution'' contains a hidden last track. McBride overheard
daughter Delaney, then 2, singing ``Broken Wing'' in the kitchen
and turned on the tape recorder. Like her mom, she's little, but
she's loud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
