<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-GREER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-10 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GREER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... keep up with him'').  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The book has been most loudly criticized for its sections on
women's health. Legalized abortion, Greer writes, has enriched male
doctors and lawyers, while Pap smears, mammograms, and fertility
treatments are forms of female torture with few benefits. And then
there's the chapter on mutilation, in which she condemns plastic
surgery and episiotomies as butchery while offering a defense of
the African tradition of female circumcision: ``One man's
beautification is another man's mutilation.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the whole woman _ a creature who does not rely upon a man
for social status, doesn't have to be gorgeous, and can age with
stature _ Greer is still on the lookout. She mostly has found
``fractured lives,'' including, she says, her own. The closest she
came on her quest was the aboriginal women in the Northern
Territories and the Osage Indians in Oklahoma, whom she met while
teaching at the University of Tulsa from 1979 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Those women, Greer says, are ``strong and cunning'' because
they've had to be. ``But do women become great when men fail? Is
that the price of them becoming great? If so, it's sort of a
mournful grandeur. We don't really want our men to fail. Men who
fail are dangerous. Our prisons are full of them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the recent rash of school shootings _ almost all of
them by boys _ Greer notes that ``we have to look after the boys.
Boys are crazy and girls are sane. I think men are weird. The XY
chromosome is damaged. It's a faulty chromosome.'' Men, she adds,
are ``either geniuses or dolts, and we love them either way.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this sort of comment that has led reviewers to label her
anti-male, a label that makes her bristle. ``This is not a
vitriolic attack on men,'' she says. ``The word `weird' is not a
bad word. I just despair of ever understanding them.''
</P>
<P>
   British writers have at times offered up the observation that if
she'd only had children, Greer wouldn't be so angry. ``I'd be
angrier,'' she snaps. ``I teach other people's children. I'm with
them all the time. They are my life.'' Her highest-achieving
students at Warwick University, in England, she says, all have
eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also know how they are being done over by guys,'' she says.
``I know how little they settle for in a relationship. If one of
these children were mine, I'd be murderous.''
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, Greer observes, ``I've been ripped off by men
all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The next moment, contradiction strikes: ``I think I've been
really well-treated by men.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who underwent surgery in a futile attempt to conceive,
says that if she were a mother, she would ``eat my child alive,''
she would love it so much.
</P>
<P>
   Did she ever consider adoption? No way, not since she read a
book about a woman who had lost her child to adoption. ``You don't
adopt the child,'' she lectures, ``you adopt the mother and
child.''
</P>
<P>
   When people have asked what she wants for Christmas, she has
been known to respond: ``a mother and child.'' This search for
surrogate motherhood led her to yet another one of her periodic
public imbroglios. A few years ago, she wrote a column that ran in
a newspaper for the homeless in which she offered to shelter a
down-and-outer, preferably a pregnant woman or a mother and child.
Tabloid journalists disguised as homeless people turned up at her
door looking for the inside story on life with Britain's most
famous feminist.
</P>
<P>
   One fellow showed up and stayed for three days, then left
without so much as a goodbye, later writing an expose on her home,
with details on how he'd burrowed through her dresser drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Did Greer feel foolish? ``Well, it was rainy and he was on
crutches,'' she explains, then adds wryly: ``I did notice that his
boots were new.''
</P>
<P>
   Might her obsession with motherhood have anything to do with her
own mother, with whom she has a rocky relationship? Peggy Greer
lives in Australia, where she raised two daughters and a son. ``I
had a mad, daft mother,'' says Greer. ``Her family lived in a crack
in the Alps for 1,000 years and they all intermarried. These people
all got sent to Australia, and that's who I'm descended from.''
</P>
<P>
   When she last made the 12,000-mile trip to Australia, her mother
refused to see her. It is rumored that she has never read any of
her daughter's books. Greer once said that her mother had spent 70
years ``lying on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   So Greer concludes that it may be a good thing she hasn't had
children, given her family tree. (Her deceased father was no
better, she says.) But she remains close to her sister and brother,
who live in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Greer lives in an old stone house on 3 acres in the
English countryside with eight geese, two goslings, two dogs, and
``one cat who is my husband.'' She is quite fond of her 13
godchildren and loves to cook for guests who drop in. At this point
in the interview, she shoos away the photographer, telling him not
to shoot her ``double chin.''
</P>
<P>
   She then grabs the slack skin and bunches it to the back of her
neck, giving herself an instant face lift. Is she ever tempted?
Hardly. Cosmetic surgery is one of her pet peeves. ``I just saw a
woman in Barney's whose implants were too big. They looked as
though they would leap off her chest and fly across the room,'' she
guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   Back to that food she loves to serve. She grows much of it
herself and is forever devoted to ``anyone who hoovers it up.'' But
she cautions women against getting into a habit of cooking for men.
``You realize you've just started digging a long ditch,'' she says.
``You're poaching asparagus and all he wants is a Big Mac. Let the
bugger have a Big Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads her _ heaven knows exactly how _ into a discourse on
men and their ``postorgasmic chill.'' Just when a woman is feeling
cuddly and emotional, she says, a man wants to get up for a smoke
or a shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finest time in your life was when you went to sleep in
someone's arms and woke up in the same position eight hours
later.'' She sighs wistfully. ``Sleeping in someone's arms is the
prize.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Greer is not enamored of American feminists. She
believes they stood by Bill Clinton above and beyond the call of
duty during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. ``English feminists were
not minded to give Clinton an easy ride,'' she says. ``They saw an
emotionally abused young woman. He should not have allowed himself
to be drawn into her fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she fancy Hillary. ``I don't know why American
feminists let her appear as an icon. The only thing she's ever done
was marry this man.'' But, Greer is reminded, she is _ or was _ a
prominent attorney. ``She's a crook,'' Greer states flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Greer was giving a lecture at Oxford in which
she stated that white-collar women should consider having
blue-collar partners so that they wouldn't be in competition with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   A young man in the audience raised his hand. ``You said,''
mimics Greer, attempting a Southern drawl, ``that white-collar
women should have relationships with blue-collar guys. But would a
white-collar boy from Arkansas stand a chance with a lady like
you?''
</P>
<P>
   The man asking the question was a young Rhodes scholar named
Bill Clinton. ``I think I said to him, `Are you coming on to me?' I
was amazed,'' Greer says.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to discern the real Germaine Greer. Is she the
feminist warning of male oppression in the new millennium, or is
she the woman sitting around waiting for the phone to ring?
</P>
</TEXT>
