<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROKE TREATMENT BENEFITS ASSESSED;  
 DRUG HALTS CAUSE OF BLINDNESS IN MICE;  
 GENETIC LINK FOUND TO CORONARY SPASMS;  
 CANCER MAY INITIATE DISORDERS OF BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The benefits for stroke patients of quick treatment with
clot-busting drugs _ a greater chance of avoiding disability _ last
for at least a year afterward, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The report in the New England Journal of Medicine is a followup
to a study published in 1995 showing that stroke patients who
received the drug, tissue plasminogen activator, or t-PA, were at
least 30 percent more likely than patients given a placebo to have
minimal or no disability three months after the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   T-PA and similar drugs dissolve clots that obstruct blood
vessels to the brain. Treatment has to be quick: The benefits were
limited to people who got the drug within three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The question was whether the good results would hold up over a
longer period. The report, from a number of collaborating medical
centers, said that the improved outcomes were sustained at six
months and 12 months after the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Drug halts cause of blindness in mice &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Johns Hopkins Medical Institutions are expressing
enthusiasm about a new drug that, in mice, completely halts the
abnormal growth of blood vessels in the eye that causes diabetic
retinopathy and age-related macular degeneration, two common
blinding diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been searching for a way of stopping the growth
of blood vessels in or beneath the retina, the light-sensitive
layer at the back of the eye. The abnormal vessels often leak fluid
or blood and progressively destroy vision.
</P>
<P>
   The new drug, made by Novartis Ltd. Pharmaceuticals and labeled
PKC 412, blocks chemicals that foster angiogenesis, or the growth
of new blood vessels, said the scientists, headed by Dr. Peter A.
Campochiaro, a professor of ophthalmology and neuroscience at Johns
Hopkins. The results are published in the June issue of the
American Journal of Pathology.
</P>
<P>
   While results in mice do not necessarily predict the
effectiveness of a treatment in humans, Campochiaro said in a
statement, ``This is the first drug I've seen that has a
knock-your-socks-off kind of effect,'' adding that previously
studied drugs were only about 50 percent effective.
</P>
<P>
   Human trials of the drug could begin next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Genetic link found to coronary spasms &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coronary spasms _ contractions in blood vessels that can cause
chest pain or heart attacks _ are more likely to occur in some
people than others: for example, they're more common in Japanese
people.
</P>
<P>
   Until now there had been no explanation for this imbalance. This
week, Japanese researchers said they have found three gene
mutations that seem to predispose individuals to coronary spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the journal Circulation, the scientists from
Kumamoto and Kyoto universities said that they found the mutations
in 30 percent of patients who had coronary spasms, but only in 7
percent of 161 people without them.
</P>
<P>
   The mutations affect a gene that helps regulate the production
of nitric oxide in the blood vessels of the heart, the coronary
arteries. Nitric oxide is an important chemical messenger that
signals blood vessels to relax and allow blood to flow more freely.
The finding could lead to new drug treatments for people who are
genetically predisposed to the spasms, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cancer may initiate disorders of brain &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People with cancer sometimes suffer from brain and nerve
disorders caused when their immune system erroneously attacks the
brain while attempting to combat the cancer. The cancer may go
unnoticed for a long time as the cause of the brain problem.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are reporting in the New England Journal of Medicine
that testicular tumors are particularly prone to causing a brain
disorder that can manifest itself as depression, seizures, and
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, from Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center,
said they identified antibodies in the blood of 12 patients showing
that the immune system was attacking both the tumor and the brain,
and they say these antibodies could be used to diagnose suspected
cases of the disorder, called paraneoplastic limbic encephalitis.
</P>
</TEXT>
