<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMOR REFLECTS FEARS AND OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I had to pay a nickel for every e-mail message I send, I'd
have to hock my computer and yours too. Yet just such a fate awaits
us all, if bill 602P is enacted into law.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to slap a nickel tax on each of the roughly 2
billion e-mail messages sent daily in the US. The money would go to
the Postal Service to make up for falling postage stamp revenue.
</P>
<P>
   I've gotten about 25 cents worth of e-mails concerning this
dreadful piece of legislation from worried readers who should
replace the batteries in their baloney detectors. For bill 602P is
a hoax. The Postal Service has no plan to tax the Internet. You can
look it up on their Web site--www.usps.gov. So many people have
called to complain that the Post Office has published a denial on
its home page.
</P>
<P>
   I won't mock those who fell for the prank; indeed, I understand
their panic. Never mind the seductive wonders of the Web. Good old
e-mail is still the Internet's most useful feature, especially
because it costs virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the popularity of e-mail poses a challenge for delivery
companies. The Postal Service handled 101 billion pieces of
first-class mail last year, and made a tidy profit. But mail volume
is growing at a snail's pace, largely thanks to competition from
e-mail. It's not just a threat to first-class letters, either.
United Parcel Service ships 1.8 million airmail packages a day,
many of them documents, at rates of $7.50 and up. Much of this
material could be delivered by e-mail instead, draining millions in
UPS revenues.
</P>
<P>
   UPS isn't watching idly as a lucrative piece of their market
disappears. Instead the firm is pioneering a new market, selling
premium-quality e-mail at a premium price.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't swap Yankee insults on a Boston Red Sox electronic
mailing list at $2.50 a pop. But you might pay that much to send
critical business documents with guaranteed delivery. Thousands of
people are doing it through a UPS service called Document Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It's a clever concept that targets e-mail's chief flaws. For one
thing, e-mail is wildly insecure. Messages routinely pass through a
dozen or more computer systems, with the possibility of
interception at every point. You can protect yourself by using
encryption software to hide your message from snoops. But for this
to work, the recipient must have the same type of encryption
software. Otherwise, he won't be able to read the message either.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how do you know if an e-mail arrived? Internet e-mail
won't tell you when your message is received. That's often critical
information in a business transaction or legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Document Exchange solves these problems with the help of the
World Wide Web. Documents aren't directly mailed to recipients.
Instead, you get an e-mail with a Web address inside. Go to this
Web page and you find a hyperlink to the document, which is stored
on a UPS computer. Click the link and the document streams onto
your own hard drive. There's no fussing with encryption; UPS takes
care of that automatically. And the UPS computer knows when the
recipient picks up the document, and sends a notice to the sender.
</P>
<P>
   There are other advantages to this method. For example, paper
documents come to your office or home, but the electronic versions
are available through any Internet-connected computer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But would anybody pay $2.50 for this service, with extra
surcharges for files larger than 1.44 megabytes? UPS marketing
manager Paul Vassallo tells me that since they introduced the
product a year ago, it's gotten thousands of users and is turning a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Gupta, managing director of interactive marketing at
rival FedEx, says there's no future in this business, that some
company will eventually start offering the same service for free.
But the Postal Service doesn't think so. It's testing its own
premium e-mail product called Post Electronic Courier Service.
Which means there's a smidgeon of truth in the bill 602P hoax, and
the Postal Service may soon start charging for e-mail after all.
</P>
<P>
   You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
