<HEADLINE>
A RUMBLING RECOLLECTION OF HOT-ROD CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of them were the boys that mothers did not want their
daughters bringing home. After &UR;  &LR; all, they were mechanically
inclined and probably took shop, had grease under their nails, an
itch for speed, and an eye for life on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Hot-rodders they called them and in the social pecking order
they were just a notch above gnarly bikers on their chopped up
Harleys and Indians. Never mind that many of them were mechanical
and design whizzes who would grow up to be engineers and
illustrators and writers and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s New England hot rod culture was a religion unto
itself, and a surprising one at that, given that most people think
California, and racing at Santa Ana or out near Edwards Air Force
Base, or Bonneville when they think of hot rods and racing. They
don't think of airport runways in Orange, Mass., or Sanford, Maine,
or Newington, N.H., and many other runways where National Hot Rod
Association races were held around New England.
</P>
<P>
   It was a culture of channeled cars, mechanical ingenuity and
inventiveness and it endures down to this day as hot rod clubs,
cruise nights, and individuals who remember keep its essence alive.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with the publication of ``Cool Cars, Square Roll Bars''
- subtitled ``Photos and Recollections of Fifties Hot Rodding in
New England - the New England branch of the religion has a bible.
</P>
<P>
   Written by brothers Arnold and Bernard Shuman, hot rodders who
went on to become, respectively, an automotive journalist and then
public relations guru for Mercedes Benz, and an illustrator, the
book provides a rumbling ramble, in words and photos, through 1950s
hot rodding.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this is two books in one. The first, in columns of
words spilling down the left-hand pages, tells the story of 1950s
hot rodding. There are personal reminiscences, minutes from old
club meetings, interviews and news clippings.
</P>
<P>
   You read about the Bannister brothers, Ralph and Fran, and other
afficiandos of hot, channeled cars: Carroll Sleeper, Marvin
Rifchin, Skip LaJoie, Jack Hartney, Jack Crosby, Eleanor ``Ma''
Shagbotham, and the Sharrigan brothers, Shag and Mudd.
</P>
<P>
   And you read about the clubs all over New England: Rollin' Rims,
Cam Snappers, Drag-Lynx, Push Rods, Rockers, Cam Twisters, Gear
Eaters, Hot Heads, Piston Manglers, No-Mads, and Ty-Rods.
</P>
<P>
   And of the Ty-Rods, who had to reorganize in 1952-53 over a bad
image the club had built up, you read, ``They behaved like the
crazed teenage car junkies in the B movies shown at drive-ins.
Correctly costumed, right down to the cigarette pack rolled in the
T-shirt sleeve and engineer boots ... racing the five miles to
Sunshine Dairy ... they would posture, ogle the young girls ... and
eventually be thrown out by the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Readio, a Ty-Rod since 1978, acknowledges the old image but
points to that early `50s reorganization that kept the club alive.
It will hold its annual Ty-Rods' Old Timers Reunion this Sept. 13
at the Hudson, Mass., Elks Lodge. And, says Readio, the appearance
of ``Cool Cars...'' ``will help bring some of the intimacy back.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because, in addition to the written history contained in
the book, the photographic history is astounding.
</P>
<P>
   There are pictures of old club membership cards and emblems;
pictures of club members standing in groups; pictures of members
then and now.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly there are pictures of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Cars racing on airport runways or at New England Dragway.
</P>
<P>
   Cars built by young men who'd had glimpses of low-slung European
sports cars and decided they could make older American cars -
notably 1932-34 Fords - look much like that.
</P>
<P>
   Channel the cars to lower the bodies, add cycle fenders to cover
open wheels and, hopefully, find the grill from a newer pickup
truck and, voila, an American roadster.
</P>
<P>
   You can just imagine club members gathering with copies of this
book, looking up names, pouring over the pictures of cars they
owned or remember having belonged to others.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Pete Seferian's Olds V8 roadster with only three exhaust
pipes per side; or Dick Kelly's Chevy-powered '33 Ford coupe known
as ``The Merger;'' or Jerry Sheehan streaking down the strip at
Sanford, protected by a ``rollbar'' that the authors say he now
confesses was really just a piece of waterpipe he had bent around a
floor support in the basement; and Fran Bannister's distinctive `32
Ford roadster with its `39 Ford pickup truck grille.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people in the book are gone, and so are many of the
cars. But as always, there are stories about what remains, or what
is rumored to remain. The book, with all its fine photos and
stories, and in the hands of hot rodders around New England, will
only fuel more stories.
</P>
<P>
   Stories like the tale of the Bannister roadster, which five
years ago, as Bannister lay dying, was strewn in pieces in
Haverhill.
</P>
<P>
   Bannister asked Tom Caruso, of Tommy Caruso's Specialized
Automotive in Tyngsboro, to please buy the car and restore it
himself - or at least make sure it went into the the hands of
someone who would do so. Two years later, Caruso got the car and
sold it to Larry Hook, a Rhode Islander hot rodder, who is having
the roadster meticulously restored, one bit of tangible history
restored, even as ``Cool Cars...'' continues to preserve the
memory, if not the metal, of those hot rod days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Cool Cars, Square Roll Bars...'' is available from
Hammershop Press, 6 Huckleberry Lane, Sharon, MA. 02067. Tel.
781-784-8724.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Royal Ford's email address is Ford(at)Globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
