<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERRY-GARCIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TAKES A LOOK AT `CAPTAIN TRIPS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's been nearly four years since Jerry Garcia
left this mortal plane for parts unknown. For many, Garcia's death
from a heart attack as he lay in a California rehab facility,
trying once again to kick his heroin habit, left a void yet to be
filled.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are a rabid fan or not, ``Garcia: An American Life''
(Viking; $34.95), by Blair Jackson, is a fascinating look at one of
the more complex and influential personalities to emerge from the
'60's maelstrom, a musician that Bob Dylan claimed ``had no
equal.'' The book is due to be released this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Deadheads will eat it up. There is enough detail about the
evolution of particular songs and the construction of the various
albums to fill a library. Add in meticulous set-lists from various
memorable concerts from the band's decades of touring _ and the
evaluation of particular nights' performances _ and it makes it
easier to figure out which Dead tapes the discriminating listener
might want to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still plenty here for the non-obsessed. By focusing
on one person, ``Garcia'' also serves as a detailed look into the
evolution of American culture, using Garcia and the band's
experiences to weave through the anything-goes exploration of the
'60's all the way through the ugly realities of addiction, failed
relationships, isolation and death.
</P>
<P>
   And man, do a lot of people die in this book. They don't call
them the Dead for nothing, apparently. The band loses more keyboard
players than Spinal Tap loses drummers. Enough, in fact, that when
pianist Bruce Hornsby was approached to join the group, he was
jokingly _ perhaps _ asked if his insurance was paid up.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Garcia's road to oblivion that makes for the most
compelling reading, even if you know the ending. The same attitude
that passes for fun early in the band's career _ liberal drug
ingestion in the name of ``mind expansion'' _ contributes to his
downward spiral, as the Dead entourage is always reluctant _ with a
few notable exceptions _ to call their ``Captain Trips'' on his
descent into junkiedom.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Dead was such a money-making corporation,
especially toward the end, and that scores of people's livelihoods
were linked to the band's touring schedule, it's easier to
understand this look-the-other-way attitude, even if it did
eventually kill the goose that laid the golden eggs.
</P>
<P>
   For all its tales of drug use and deterioration, however,
``Garcia'' manges to avoid the pratfalls of becoming a tawdry
snort-and-tell book. This is due largely to the author's extensive
interviewing, which adds depth to a story that most people only
know on the surface. Jackson was able to interview more than 100
people, with access to much of Garcia's family, friends, band
mates. He also claims to have had more personal interviews with
Garcia than any other journalist, though who knows who was keeping
count? Garcia died Aug. 9, 1995, in Forest Knolls, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a pastiche of anecdotes that are sometimes
remembered slightly differently by those involved, which adds to
the air of truthfulness of the book.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting section is the beginning, chronicling
Garcia's emergence as a folkie, bluegrass-type picker who was swept
up in the confluence of the Beats and the evolving hippies.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kesey's Merry Pranksters play a prominent role in the birth
of the new counterculture, with the Dead serving as the house band
for the Pranksters' famous Acid Tests.
</P>
<P>
   It is from this tripping, free-form atmosphere that the
essential Grateful Dead live concert experience is born, as the
band learns to noodle endlessly before maybe coming across a nugget
from which to take off on one of their extended jams. When it
works, it's otherworldly _ when it doesn't, it's some of the worst
stuff since the invention on the musical instrument. And that,
without much change, remained the basic Dead concert experience.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Mickey Hart explained that the band was never in the
music business, they were in the transportation business. And in
truth, they were, largely because Garcia's musical acumen in so
many diverse stylings allowed them to explore territories more
often the realm of jazzmen like Ornette Coleman and John Coltrane.
But few who saw Garcia during his several junked-up phases will
forget his vacant stare, his lifeless shoe-gazing and his total
inability to transport anyone to the next song, let alone the next
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, he was often bored. But then again, so are a lot
of people who toil on the clock in thankless jobs every day _ and
nobody is paying $35 to watch them work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garcia'' seems a fair biography, though clearly told from a
fan's perspective. Still, Jackson doesn't let his admiration for
the man and the band get in the way of an honest accounting, which
is all a reader can ask for.
</P>
</TEXT>
