<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NEWENGLAND-BOS &LR;      06-10 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHARM OF NORTHERN EXPOSURE   GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something special about getaway golf in northern New
England. The season is painfully short. Nevertheless, it is as
magnificent as it is brief.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike heading to Cape Cod, which demands that one travel over a
pair of often jammed bridges, there are many roads to the more than
200 golf destinations north of the Massachusetts border. The pace
on those roads is unlike that of Cape Cod in the summer as well. It
isn't stop-and-go Route 6 or bumper-to-bumper Route 28. The prelude
to the first tee at a northern New England course often is clear
highways and winding rural roads along stone-filled streams,
punctuated by the occasional covered bridge.
</P>
<P>
   You can make a day trip to some of this region's courses.
However, the best way to savor these rounds is with an overnight
expedition. Then, the only agenda after walking off the 18th green
is inspecting a picturesque sunset at your rental cottage and
listening to the Red Sox game from faraway Fenway via a portable
radio.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of golf runs the gamut, from championship tracts
like Sugarloaf in Maine's Carrabasset Valley to nine-hole
mom-and-pop operations. Conditions vary, too, from well-manicured
to hardscrabble.
</P>
<P>
   The region is steep in golf tradition. Golf has been played in
the northern woods since the 19th century. Scottish weavers brought
their native game to Skowhegan, Maine, in the 1880s, playing on a
rudimentary course that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kebo Valley, nestled in Bar Harbor, exists today. It
opened in 1888, and is the eighth-oldest course in America. H.C.
Leeds, the first champion at The Country Club in Brookline and
designer of the Myopia Hunt Club course in South Hamilton, turned
Kebo Valley into a first-class golf destination at the turn of the
century. Millionaires and heads of state have graced the course.
One hole is even called the Taft Hole after the 27th president of
the United States, who once took 26 strokes on the par-4 17th,
which measures only 349 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's golfing genealogy traces back to the earliest stages
of the game in America. In fact, the Dorset (Vt.) Field Club claims
golf was played there in 1886, a year before the Apple Tree Gang
came into existence at St. Andrews-on-the-Yonkers in New York. But
there is no written proof to further the claim. In New Hampshire,
golf was played as early as 1894 in New London by vacationing
Bostonians. Beaver Meadow, a course in West Concord, was the first
club established in New Hampshire in 1897. Now it is a
municipally-owned course.
</P>
<P>
   Maine has far more courses than New Hampshire or Vermont and
offers a great variety. The late Gene Sarazen, who spent many
summers in northern New England, thought Maine could become the
golfing Scotland of America because of the geographic similarities.
It never happened, but there are many jewels.
</P>
<P>
   If Sugarloaf were closer to civilization it would be the
people's choice as the best course in New England. Because it is
four hours from Boston, it remains a secret. Relatively few have
played it, but those who have rave about its beauty. There are no
weak holes on this Robert Trent Jones Jr. design. It is the only
course in northern New England worthy of a four-hour car ride. The
signature holes are the 10th and 11th, where the tees are 120 feet
above the landing area, offering dramatic views of the Presidential
mountain range.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best way to make the trip to Sugarloaf is by breaking
up the long commute with golfing stopovers. On the way up, visit
Belgrade Lakes GC, just a few minutes out of Augusta. This is a new
course, the first effort in America by English architect Clive
Clark, and is destined to become one of the top tracts in the Pine
Tree State. It is unique for several reasons. It is walker
friendly. In fact, there are some 400 caddies registered at the
club. Also, it is cheaper to take a caddie than a cart. Another
nice thing about Belgrade Lakes is the tee times. They are spaced
15 minutes apart during the week and 12 minutes apart during the
weekend. ``There are no problems because of slow play,'' said
general manager Kyle Reed.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home, visit Dunegrass Golf Club in Old Orchard Beach.
It is worth the stop. If you ever played some of the great courses
at Myrtle Beach, S.C., such as Marsh Harbor, Oyster Bay, the
Heritage, or the Pearl, you will notice a similarity. The same
architect, Dan Maples, designed them. Dunegrass is Maples's only
work in New England. Another reason this trip is worthwhile is the
greens, some of the best you ever will roll a putt on.
</P>
<P>
   A must before any foray into Maine's backwoods is a copy of
TravelGolfMaine, a fee publication that gives an in-depth look at
the region. Its internet address is www.travelgolfmaine.com.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that all the best courses in northern New England
involve long rides, such as a trip to the Balsams Resort in
Dixville Notch, N.H. The Panoramic course is one of Donald Ross's
best efforts in that area. The master architect left his imprint in
the region, and it is surprising that the marketing geniuses at the
great resorts haven't created a Donald Ross Trail, a chain of
courses and stopovers for Ross aficionados. Besides the Panoramic
course at Balsams, you can tee it up at several Ross creations.
Visit Mount Washington CC and stay at the grand hotel. Then you
could head to Bethlehem and play his Maplewood course, a half-flat
and half-hilly tract with one truly memorable hole, the 16th, a
634-yard par-6. You could finish the trip with a visit to Lake
Sunapee, a Ross course that recently has been restored.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire courses vary, much like its landscape. There are
the mountaintop layouts, like the Balsams, as well as the flatter
courses of the Merrimack Valley. One enjoyable place is the Country
Club of New Hampshire in North Sutton, just minutes off of I-89. It
is the site of this week's New England Senior Open and offers
stay-and-play packages. In the 1970s it was selected among the top
75 public courses in America, and in recent years its owners, the
Friel family, have revitalized it.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see a historic landmark, play Windham Country
Club. This Bill Flynn course just north of the Massachusetts border
is a terrific layout offering challenging shots on all 18 holes.
But when you tee it up on the par-3 sixth, the huge boulder behind
the green is a record-holder, the largest free-standing boulder in
the Western Hemisphere. It's called Butterfield Rock because there
was a hermit who years ago made the area beneath the rock his home.
Windham is close enough to Boston to be a great sneakaway day trip.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont golf is different from that in New Hampshire or Maine.
It is more pastoral. The only downside is that Red Sox fans will be
a minority because New Yorkers invade the Green Mountains every
July and August. Despite that, there are several places worthy of a
visit. There are the staples, such as Stratton Mountain, former
host of the LPGA McCall's Classic, a 27-hole facility with a
neighboring golf school that ranks with the best in the world.
Vermont is also the home of the Mount Snow Golf School, and for
many years Mount Snow was the site of the New England Open.
</P>
<P>
   There is Woodstock, also a Jones creation that plays in a valley
along a brook. The brook comes into play on 11 holes. Woodstock Inn
guests get a discount. Another interesting course is Rutland CC,
built it 1902 by George Low. He is not to be confused with his son
of the same name who played on the PGA Tour and was a renowned
putter. Low Sr. was runner-up in the 1899 US Open and worked for
many years as the head professional at Baltusrol. Later Wayne
Stiles and John van Kleek, underrated architects of the 1920s,
remodeled the existing course and added a second nine.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to stay and play at one resort that best will offer
the Green Mountain experience, it is the Equinox in Manchester. It
has been a stop for presidents and the rich from the days before
there was a golf course. The course was designed by Walter Travis
in the 1920s and was restored in 1991 by Rees Jones and renamed
Gleneagles. If there is one hole you will remember it is the par-4
(and aptly numbered) 13th. Locals call it ``the Volcano Hole''
because it is straight up and has caused the eruption of scores and
tempers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-RECOVERY-BO     06-10 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lost and Found is a serious disaster recovery tool for Windows.
Like other data recovery tools, Lost And Found can find files after
they have been accidentally deleted or removed from the Windows
``recycler.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lost and Found can also recover files after a hard disk has
been scrambled by a computer virus, after somebody has reinstalled
a computer's operating system, or even after a hardware failure. No
office or serious home user should be without it.
</P>
<P>
   Data recovery programs used to be extremely popular back in the
early 1990s. Way back then, computers were less reliable, computer
users were less skilled, and there were so many bugs in the DOS
that computers routinely lost the contents of their floppy disks or
hard drives for no apparent reason. Back in the early '90s, many
computer users I knew would purchase a copy of Norton Disk Doctor
or Mace Utilities as a kind of insurance policy. Then, when
disaster inevitably struck, they were ready.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few years, most data recovery tools have
evolved in a way that hasn't been entirely helpful: the programs
have gotten bigger and more powerful, but have lost their original
vision. For example, today Norton Utilities is a huge system that
includes a virus checker, a disk optimizer, and a program
``uninstaller.'' For data recovery, Norton can back up your
computer or make a ``rescue'' disk that has critical files and
information. If something later goes wrong with your computer, the
theory goes, you can use the ``rescue'' disk to make your computer
right. The problem with Norton Utilities is that you need to
purchase the program and install it before disaster strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Lost and Found takes a fundamentally different approach. Instead
of coming on a CD-ROM, Lost and Found comes on a floppy disk. If
something goes wrong with your computer's hard disk and you need
the data, just turn off your computer, insert the Lost and Found
floppy, and reboot. No installation is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Lost and Found comes with its own copy of DOS and a very
sophisticated program that will analyze your computer's hard drive,
help you find the data you are looking for, and write it to a set
of floppy disks. You then take these floppies to another computer
and run a special program that restores the data onto the good
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lost and Found can recover against many virus attacks
(including the dreaded Chernobyl virus), the main use of this
program is for recovering data after hardware failure. The
program's authors have worked closely with disk-drive manufacturers
to learn how to access the information on a hard drive at a very
low level. As a result, Lost and Found can frequently read disk
blocks that are inaccessible from Windows itself _ as well as from
other recovery programs.
</P>
<P>
   I found Lost and Found to be remarkably easy to use. The program
is also safe to use, since it doesn't modify the data on the hard
drive in any way: if you are not successful recovering your data
with one approach, you can try another without fear of permanently
altering the data on your disk. (Of course, since Lost and Found
doesn't repair your disk, you may still need a program such as
Norton Disk Doctor if you want to try to get your computer working
again without reformatting the hard disk and reloading your
operating system.)
</P>
<P>
   Recently acquired by PowerQuest (http://www.powerquest.com/),
Lost and Found is a relatively new product. But Lost and Found's
technology is based on a disk recovery product that has been used
for many years by both major corporations, such as Dell and
Microsoft, as well as disk drive recovery centers such as Driver
Savers (http://www.drivesavers.com/), On Track
(http://www.ontrack.com/), and Atlanta Computer Resource
(http://www.atl-datarecovery.com/). In fact, PowerQuest believes it
is these services, rather than simple utility programs such as
Norton, that are the real competitors for its program.
</P>
<P>
   Data recovery centers typically use a combination of software
and hardware to get data back after a disaster. Because of this
combination, they can do a much better job than software-only
systems such as Lost and Found. Using a center also costs a lot
more money _ hundred or even thousands of dollars, as opposed to
$60.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lost and Found, PowerQuest also sells a more
advanced data recovery program called Search and Rescue. Besides
copying to floppies, Search and Rescue can also send the recovered
data to a networked file server, and it includes advanced search
features for scanning through lots of data very quickly. Search and
Rescue is priced at $150, but there are steep discounts for
businesses that want to purchase multiple copies for recovering
more than one machine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the applications for Search and Rescue has been law
enforcement. Cops and investigators equipped with this technology
have been able to execute search warrants on computers and recover
files after they have been deleted and allegedly ``destroyed'' by
suspects. According to the company, data recovered using these
programs has been invaluable in obtaining numerous convictions,
including several cases involving child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons these programs can be successful in
recovering data that has been intentionally destroyed is that the
Microsoft Windows ``format'' program doesn't actually erase the
computer's hard drive. Instead, the computer reads every block on
the hard disk to figure out which ones are good and which ones are
bad, but the only sectors that it writes are those for the
computer's root directory. All of the information is still left in
place.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, if you care about data security you might still
want to purchase a program such as Norton Utilities or Nuts and
Bolts. Both include data destruction programs that will repeatedly
overwrite unused blocks of your computer's hard drive. Once you've
run one of these programs, a data recovery program such as Lost and
Found is all but useless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at
plugged-in(at)simson.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
