<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-10 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOGNIZING A STAR IN A GROWTH INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Landscape architect Joseph Hudak quips that he's been wondering
if the medal he's getting from the American Horticul-
</P>
<P>
   tural Society on Friday is the kind ``made of chocolate with a
foil wrapper.'' If it is, this is a sweet week for Boston's flower
power elite.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 18 years since the AHS, a national organization of
26,000 avid amateur gardeners and professional horticulturalists,
last came to Boston for its annual conference. Medals and national
recognition are being showered on the gathered stars of Boston's
garden scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak, well-known as a teacher and the author of five garden
books, will receive the society's 1999 Meritorious Service Award.
He will lecture on ``Gardening from One Millennium to the Next!''
</P>
<P>
   Both Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino and Michael Van Valkenburgh,
professor of landscape architecture at Harvard, are receiving
awards. Menino is getting the AHS 1999 Urban Beautification Award
for his ``Broom to Bloom'' program, intended to beautify the city
and its 15 neighborhoods by using public-private partnerships to
encourage green space adoptions and flower plantings.
</P>
<P>
   The AHS Communication Award will be presented Saturday to
Frances Tenenbaum of Cambridge, Mass., an editor at Houghton
Mifflin. By championing the reissuing of New Hampshire poet Celia
Thaxter's 1894 ``An Island Garden,'' with its important
Impressionistic watercolors by Childe Hassam, as well as other
gardening classics, Tenenbaum ``helped give Americans back their
horticultural history,'' in the words of Garden Book Club founder
Pam Lord.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hudak's imprint
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For half a century, beginning with his 25-year tenure at the
fabled Olmsted Associates of Brookline, Mass., the nation's oldest
landscape design firm and now a National Historic Site, Hudak has
been making an imprint with good planting and design. He consulted
on the AHS headquarters master plan at River Farm in Alexandria,
Va. (once owned by George Washington). Hudak also landscaped the
former Prides Crossing farm of past AHS president Nathaniel ``Nat''
Dane and his wife, Arabella, who chairs one of this year's AHS
awards committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect Joe tremendously,'' says Arabella Dane. ``He's
great in so many different dimensions. He's such a good teacher
that he brings out the best in everyone. And he sure knows his
plant material. I have all his books, and they're all marked up
because I've used them so much. They're great teaching tools.''
</P>
<P>
   These include the classic ``Gardening with Perennials Month by
Month,'' published by Timber Press, which has had a 25-year shelf
life, with revisions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hudak has been only slightly less ubiquitous than the
PJM rhododendron. He's a life member, board member, or trustee
emeritus of just about every major local horticultural
organization.
</P>
<P>
   As a teacher, he's well known among students who took his plant
identification and design courses at Harvard and Radcliffe between
1963 and 1983. He continues to teach throughout the region for the
National Council of State Garden Clubs' Landscape Design School and
other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A mecca
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who belong to horticultural organizations, all roads
eventually lead to Hudak's dead-end street in Weston, Mass., where
his home sits on a densely planted oasis amid a neighborhood of
unprepossessing lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Many landscape architects open their own yards to such tours
occasionally. But few gardens have been as tramped through as
Hudak's, thanks to his many affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, 1,500 visitors strolled through. ``That's 3,000
feet!'' Hudak exclaims. The Westwood Historical Society Garden Tour
attracted 550 people in May. The Tower Hill Garden Tour brought 600
in June. And in July, 100 members of the Perennial Plant
Association rode buses out from their national conference in
downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had thousands. Every garden club. It's a lot of work.
The fussiness! You have to get everything just right. It's not like
you're hosting visiting dental hygienists. Gardeners know.''
</P>
<P>
   At 72, Hudak says he is not planning on retirement anytime soon.
His current projects include a new book, ``Design for Gardens,''
coming out next spring, a new edition of ``Shrubs in the
Landscape,'' coming out in 2001, and next year's ``Festival of
Flowers,'' the 25th anniversary celebration of the annual
International Design Symposium he helped found.
</P>
<P>
   For his 70th birthday, friends and clients donated a silver
trophy in his name to the Spring Flower Show of the Massachusetts
Horticultural Society. Though it's presented annually, the Hudak
trophy goes to an outstanding exhibit of herbaceous perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical approach
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hudak seems unimpressed by the current building and landscaping
frenzy. ``It's hard to say if this is the most affluent period I've
seen. There's always money around. But this is a splendiferous
period for people spending money. I hope the market stays up so
everyone gets paid!''
</P>
<P>
   Hudak may be insulated from the ups and downs of the stock
market more than most in his profession. Like the proverbial family
lawyer, he has been engaged for generations within some families.
It's not unknown for longtime clients to send him as a kind of
housewarming gift to consult with their grown children after a new
home purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak's landscaping style is traditional, with an emphasis on
common sense. But whereas many landscape architects work with a few
dozen tried-and-true (and ho-hum?) plant varieties, Hudak's palette
is huge, and his practical knowledge of what will grow well here _
and what won't _ is unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   It is plants, after all, that excite him. From the time his
grandmother introduced him to gardening as a child in Pennsylvania,
``plants were always my life. I don't know why. I wanted to be a
hybridizer like Luther Burbank,'' he says with his trademark
``Ho-HO!'' hoot of laughter. ``That is, till I learned it took 20
years to find out if an ear of corn you bred did what you wanted it
to!''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when landscape design is breaking out of the
century-old Colonial Revival mold, Hudak remains a traditionalist.
Sun-drenched California minimalism and swimming pools with
``infinity edges'' that flow to the horizon are not for him.
``Contemporary is not the mood of New England. You see swimming
pools and ornamental grasses and great lawns in Architectural
Digest. But here people need variety, because we have too much of
the sameness of winter five months a year.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hudak sometimes tries to talk clients out of swimming
pools. Too much upkeep for too few swimmable months. ``I tell them
it's easier to just join the country club.''
</P>
<P>
   Landscape guru
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One change he has contributed to is people's greatly increased
knowledge and sophistication about landscapes. ``It's because they
travel and they see things. Even on TV. Look at all the cable
shows!''
</P>
<P>
   The pastel garden is fading as people become more appreciative
of interesting foliage and brilliant color, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round textural layering from many plant types with colorful
foliage plays an important role in Hudak's own 1-acre garden, which
begins as a narrow path at his front door that widens as it circles
around the house. Very carefully selected plants with leaves and
flowers of yellow come first: yellow barberry, a 24-foot-tall
euonymus alata compacta (``compact is a relative term'') with
yellow flowers, yellow azaleas, rare Japanese maples, Scotch broom,
a mysteriously variegated drumondii Norway maple, and many
different yellow-needled chamaecyparis.
</P>
<P>
   Then come the red plants, as the grass sward opens into a large,
tree-lined lawn dubbed ``the polo field.'' Here most of the floral
fireworks are displayed, as well as a zipper scar of new sod where
disruptive sewer work was done.
</P>
<P>
   The circle is completed with the quiet coda of another woodland
path, this time lovingly furnished with blue plants, such as select
hostas.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak seems relieved that the sewer work allowed him to beg off
on most garden tours this year. Except for the American Society of
Landscape Architects. They're having their national conference in
Boston in September. That means the grass has time to knit and
heal, and so the ASLA will be coming through. Ho-HO!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
