<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0393 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-VOUCHERS-COUR     06-10 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-VOUCHERS-COURT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHERS AN ISSUE FOR THE SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Many states are passing laws that allow parents to use public
funds to send their children to religious schools. Some courts are
declaring this trend constitutional, while others are not.
Ultimately, the Supreme Court will probably have to make a
decision.
 &HT;    Certainly, the most important advance has been in Florida, which
recently approved the first statewide school voucher plan in the
country. It is actually a small part of a much larger plan to
improve Florida schools by a unique route. Each school is to be
graded between an A and an F. Schools that improve are rewarded
