or parochial school.
 &HT;    In the first year, only four schools are failing. But within two
years as many as 200 schools with 156,000 students could be
eligible for vouchers.
 &HT;    Gov. Jeb Bush says the goal is to ''see that children learn a
year's worth of knowledge in a year's worth of time.''
 &HT;    The law provides $645 million added funding to reward improved
performance. There are rising standards of what schools are to
deliver.
 &HT;    But if a school is flunking, students will get ''opportunity
scholarships'' to get out, giving them and their parents a choice
that exists only for the affluent today.
 &HT;    The only other public voucher programs in America involve
limited numbers of poor children -- 6,000 in Milwaukee who get
$4,400 to go to the school of their choice and 4,200 students in
Cleveland.
 &HT;    Americans United for Separation of Church and State fought both
programs because they would ''directly pay religious schools for
