<HEADER>
A0410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-TROOPS-0611-COX     06-10 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-TROOPS-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE VOTES TO PULL U.S. TROOPS OUT OF TROUBLED HAITI BY
YEAR-END
 &HT;    450&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even as it debates the future of peacekeeping forces in
Kosovo, the House has voted to end another U.S. military presence
-- this one in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   The measure that would pull U.S. troops from Haiti by Dec. 31,
approved late Wednesday, comes amid a rapidly deteriorating
security situation in Haiti that has prompted growing concerns over
the safety of U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our troops have been fired on in Haiti,'' said Rep. Porter
Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the House Intelligence Committee and a
key sponsor of the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haiti is a failure and is indicative of the administration's
foreign policy, which isn't very good,'' he added. ``Haiti is just
about as miserable a situation as there is anywhere on the globe
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials expressed disappointment with
the vote Thursday, saying it undercuts the president's ability to
deploy troops abroad for non-combat purposes.
</P>
<P>
   They said that continued gains in Haiti would require a
sustained U.S. commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. military presence has been an important contributor
to security in Haiti,'' a State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 227-198 to approve the amendment to the defense
spending bill, which would replace the permanent force with
``periodic, noncontinuous'' troop deployments. It also would
require the president to report to Congress when ordering such
deployments.
</P>
<P>
   After passage in the House, the bill will go to a House-Senate
conference committee for coordination with a Senate defense bill
passed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Many senators have been calling for an end to the American
military presence in Haiti, including Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who
chairs the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Those increased calls for a troop withdrawal come on the heels
of a Cox Newspapers series in March that reviewed U.S. policy in
Haiti and found that little had been accomplished after spending
more than $2 billion on aid to the tiny island nation since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Gen. Charles Wilhelm, who leads the U.S. Southern
Command, testified before Congress that troops had been unable to
create stability in Haiti and that he feared for the troops'
safety. He recommended the permanent U.S. presence be ended.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent 20,000 troops to Haiti in 1994 to oust a
brutal military regime and restore Jean-Bertrand Aristide as
president. Today about 500 U.S. troops remain in Haiti to build
schools and perform other humanitarian tasks at a cost of $22
million a year. But about 175 of these troops do nothing but
protect the others.
</P>
<P>
   Political violence has intensified over the last few months,
presumably related to the power vacuum sparked when President Rene
Preval shut down Parliament on Jan. 11 in a controversial move to
end a political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Cox Newspapers reported that dozens of U.S. soldiers
in Port-au-Prince had twice been sprayed with a flurry of bullets
on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a jeep being used by civilian employees of the U.S.
support group was seized and torched by protesters in downtown
Port-au-Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
