<HEADER>
A0417 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY11-COX     06-10 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOPE BRIGHTENS FOR SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM
 &HT;    270&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hope for a solution to Social Security's financial
problems brightened slightly during a congressional hearing
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the House Ways and Means Committee agreed to hold a
closed-door meeting to seek ``common ground'' for reform, although
they expressed concern over the willingness of President Clinton
and the GOP leadership to join them if a plan emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Without reform, Social Security will not be able to pay full
benefits after 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning the second day of a two-day hearing on Social Security
reform, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the committee chairman, offered
an impassioned plea for action this year. He warned that reform
will be almost impossible once the 2000 election season begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The options are before us now,'' Archer said. ``Now is the
time to choose. Now is the best opportunity we will ever have. ...
The American people expect this of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the panel's ranking Democrat,
said he welcomed the prospect of negotiating in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``An executive session ... is the only way to see how much we
can accomplish as a committee ... to find out not how far apart we
are, but how close we may be,'' Rangel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made a giant step forward, because I think a lot
of Democrats and Republicans would just as soon this didn't come
up.'' he said. Rangel expressed concern that Republican leaders may
be unwilling to push a Social Security reform plan this year.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, however, noted a letter issued Wednesday by House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., expressing a desire for a
bipartisan solution.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how Social Security may be reformed is still very much
in doubt. Clinton has proposed using 62 percent of the projected
federal surplus to reduce the national debt, and earmark those
savings for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous bills would use a portion of the payroll tax to create
individual retirement accounts that would offset reductions in
Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Archer and Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., have offered a bill to
use the federal budget surplus to finance individual retirement
accounts that would help pay for benefits. That bill has not been
endorsed by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw noted that under their plan Social Security benefits _
including cost-of-living-adjustments _ would not be changed and
taxes would not be raised.
</P>
<P>
   At an earlier breakfast with reporters, Shaw noted that his bill
has been attacked by the far right for not going far enough to
replace the current program with individual accounts, while
Democratic proposals to set up some private accounts have been
criticized by the far left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: are we going to end up as road kill?'' Shaw
said. ``Republicans will be justifiably criticized if we don't move
a bill; the Democrats will be justifiably criticized if they kill a
bill'' without offering a viable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
