<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASSATT-EXHIBIT-2TAKE     06-10 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSATT-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY CASSATT: FORCEFUL SPIRIT IN AN AGE OF INNOCENCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Penn., Mass., Ill.)  (fb) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Women should be someone and not something,'' the
American artist Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) once wrote, emphatically
underlining her words. And she dedicated a long career to fleshing
out this conviction through art.
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts come across with a quiet, though sometimes
surprisingly passionate force in ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman,'' a
succinct survey of her paintings and prints at the National Gallery
of Art in Washington. The show, which has appeared in Chicago and
Boston, is the first comprehensive look at Cassatt's work in nearly
30 years. And it marks yet another step in evaluating an artist who
was herself a someone _ indeed, several someones _ to be reckoned
with.
</P>
<P>
   The first book on Cassatt, published in 1913 in France where she
spent most of her adult life, carried the subtitle ``painter of
children and mothers.'' The label was accurate _ the world depicted
in Cassatt's art is, with rare exceptions, a world without men _
but it also clouded her name with perfumed associations of ``lady
painter.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminist scholarship of the past quarter century has done much
to disperse that cloud and reveal a more reality-based view of the
artist. And what has emerged is a haute bourgeoise heroine, admired
for embodying particular qualities that the late 20th century finds
admirable.
</P>
<P>
   As an artist, Cassatt was a focused professional. As a woman,
she broke vocational ground. Politically, her thinking was
progressive, in a moderate, class-bound way. She was witty,
intelligent, with no obvious signs of disruptive personal quirks.
She has even come to feel like a contemporary, which means like a
desirable dinner partner: urbane, unsentimental, reticent without
being shy.
</P>
<P>
   This view of her is, in its turn, now being inflected and
refined, but the central facts of her biography are firm. Born in
Pittsburgh to a patrician Pennsylvania family, she studied painting
in Philadelphia, then in Europe. After she settled in Paris in
1874, her sister and parents moved, lock, stock and barrel, to join
her there.
</P>
<P>
   From the very start, she had an appetite for forward-looking
styles, as the Manet-inspired paintings on Spanish themes that open
the Washington show suggest. And when she encountered the work of
Edgar Degas and the Impressionists in Paris, she knew at once that
this was the art for her.
</P>
<P>
   She soon became an insider in the Impressionist circle, both as
an artist and an advocate. Socially well connected on both sides of
the Atlantic, she served for years as adviser to a fledging
generation of American collectors, steering them toward the best
new French art, and helping to shape future American museum
collections.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she kept a certain distance from her Parisian
peers. As a genteel, unmarried woman, cafes and dance halls were
off-limits to her, and the urban demimonde was an inappropriate
subject for art. So she painted what she knew: the carefully
controlled public universe of theater matinees and drives in the
park, the intimate realm of the drawing room and the garden.
</P>
<P>
   It is that vital, if circumscribed life that dominates the first
half of the exhibition. Most of her early Paris paintings are set
in the theater. Cassatt never depicts women onstage or backstage,
or for that matter anywhere outside the precincts of the private
box. Yet within that sequestered environment, figures like that
seen in ``Woman in a Loge'' (1878) can have an extravagant dramatic
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The painting's subject, with her iridescent pink dress and
auburn-gold hair, is a high-color confection set against a mirrored
wall in which the theater itself is reflected. A Degas or a Monet
might have turned her into a scintillating blur of shadow and
light. Cassatt doesn't do so. She maintains the figure's physical
integrity, confining virtuosic brushwork to interior passages of
the dress.
</P>
<P>
   In Cassatt's hands the woman, once thought to be Cassatt's older
sister, Lydia, is a distinctive personality. She has the blooming,
unguarded, slightly gauche charm of one of Henry James' American
heiresses, those smart young women who've never been told not to
show their teeth when they smiled, who don't notice or care that
their corsages are a bit bedraggled, who feel at home wherever they
land.
</P>
<P>
   Home is, in fact, another setting for many of Cassatt's
paintings from this time. In the picture ``Tea,'' a hostess and her
guest are concluding a visit in a fashionably color-coordinated
parlor; the stripes in the wallpaper look like soft, protective
bars. In her great, innovative series of Japanese-inspired color
prints, Cassatt turns the minutiae of domestic routine _ writing a
letter, being fitted for a dress _ into a secular Book of Hours.
</P>
<P>
   She often depicts women reading. In one painting, her
bespectacled mother concentrates on Le Figaro; in another, a sitter
in an 18th-century-style dress is absorbed in a magazine. Here, as
elsewhere, women pose for her, but their lives don't stop when they
do. Maybe that's why there is so little eye contact in her
paintings. Her subjects are too busy with thoughts and activities
of their own to care that they are being observed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A decisive shift in locale from theater to home is apparent in
the late 1870s. Cassatt's career was going well after her
much-noticed public debut in the 1879 Impressionist exhibition. But
Lydia had been diagnosed with kidney disease; Cassatt was devoting
most of her time to her sister and tenderly recording her decline.
</P>
<P>
   These portraits of Lydia, which have been grouped together by
the curator of the show in Washington, Nicolai Cikovsky Jr., are
often set outdoors, in a garden or park. In one of them, Lydia sits
on a bench crocheting. Her sallow face is protected by a lace
bonnet as frilly as a christening gown, but she stares anxiously at
her hands, as if she had just pricked her finger.
</P>
<P>
   In the painting ``Autumn,'' her face is again closely, almost
clinically observed, though her body is wrapped in a vivacious
foliage-colored shawl, a little miracle of free-form hatching in
which Cassatt demonstrates her Impressionist credentials. And in an
oil sketch done not long before her death in 1882, Lydia sits at a
distance from us, dressed in white, her features undefined, as if
she were merging with the parkland around her.
</P>
<P>
   After this period, Cassatt's attitudetoward art gradually
changed; she seemed to want more from it, or at least something
new. All along she had been a funny sort of French Impressionist,
often barely one at all. Degas was a central influence on her work,
and a friend for over 40 years. But she always referred to herself
as an American artist, and that's really what she was.
</P>
<P>
   Her figures, no matter what kind of painterly fireworks are
exploding around them, are as materially solid and specific as any
of John Singleton Copley's colonial portraits. Cassatt was a modern
painter the way Winslow Homer or Thomas Eakins (another
Philadelphian and born the same year) were modern painters, a
realist for whom realism came to imply something psychologically,
even spiritually expansive.
</P>
<P>
   All of this grows increasingly evident in her work from the late
1880s onward. Like many women of the era, she became interested in
spiritualism, with its quasi-scientific belief in a network of
concrete links between nature, people _ especially women and
children _ and the divine. And the figures in her paintings became
both more precisely defined and more emblematic.
</P>
<P>
   This trend was exemplified in the mural, now lost or destroyed,
that she created on commission for the Woman's Building at the
World's Columbian Exhibition in Chicago in 1893. Titled ``Modern
Woman,'' it was executed in a crisp, realist style, though its
central scene of nine female figures of various ages gathered in an
orchard and ritualistically harvesting the Fruits of Knowledge was
almost purely allegorical.
</P>
<P>
   Cassatt's mother died in 1895, and the artist was devastated.
Around that time, she turned her full attention to maternal images,
producing some of her most original work. A few images stick to a
symbolic mode. ``The Family,'' with its trio of mother, child and
mesmerized adolescent girl, echoes Italian Renaissance icons of the
mystical marriage of Saint Catherine. But other paintings project a
peculiarly claustrophobic, fleshy heat.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a women wears a rose-patterned dress that looks
blood-spattered; her drowsy, heavy child touches her face in a
chin-chucking gesture that has ancient erotic implications. In the
color print ``The Kiss,'' mother and baby are locked in a clinch
like lovers. In the 1896 ``Maternal Caress,'' a fat-cheeked infant
grasps a woman's face with ferocious concentration, as if about to
devour her.
</P>
<P>
   In a late painting, ``The Mirror'' (circa 1905), near the end of
the exhibition, many strands come together. Here the mother,
dressed in shades of yellow with a huge sunflower corsage, is as
exaggeratedly decorative a presence as the young woman in the
theater loge was 25 years earlier. She supports a nude,
post-toddler-age child on her lap. Together they hold up and
contemplate a small hand mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The vignette isn't simple. The sunflower is an emblem of
fecundity. The mirror (there was one behind the woman in the loge
too) is a time-honored symbol of vanity and vanitas, self-love and
loss. And the mother, with watchful detachment, seems to be
imparting a lesson to her child, whose reflected face looks
directly but tentatively out at us as if to say, ``I am a someone,
and so are you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassatt learned this lesson in self-regard, one suspects, many
times in her life, and in ways that have yet to be fully explored
and appreciated. And it is that sense of continuing discovery _
both hers and ours _ that draw us back to her deceptively
undemonstrative art. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman'' remains at the National Gallery
of Art, Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue, NW, Washington,
through Sept. 6. The exhibition was organized by the Art Institute
of Chicago in collaboration with the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston,
and the National Gallery of Art. The show is sponsored by Aetna.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
