<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAHAM PROPOSES PREVENTIVE CARE COVERAGE UNDER MEDICARE
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill to expand Medicare coverage of preventive
health care was introduced Thursday by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's plan would expand Medicare coverage to three new areas:
annual screenings for hypertension and glaucoma, counseling for
tobacco cessation and hormone replacement therapy to reduce
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Graham would provide Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs for conditions related to those preventive
areas. Currently, Medicare does not cover outpatient prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   To keep Medicare's preventive benefits current, Graham
recommended a process that would require Congress to vote every
five years on a package of preventive benefit reforms that would be
recommended by the Institute of Medicine, part of the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's bill also would earmark $100 million for research by
the National Institute of Aging on delaying the onset of
age-related impairments and $25 million for research related to
increasing the use and delivery of preventive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Graham estimated his bill would cost up to $6 billion over five
years. He said that could be paid out of any money the federal
government might receive as a result of its planned suit against
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Graham said, Medicare ought to be reformed by
looking first at what benefits should be provided rather than at
how to finance the program.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
