<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton will address the
nation from the Oval Office after a heady day marked by a subdued
sense of victory. ``We face challenges and risks in bringing home
the refugees and restoring stability,'' he says in earlier remarks.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ President Clinton's most
enduring legacy in foreign affairs may be his willingness to
intervene in the internal affairs of sovereign nations to combat
humanitarian disaster. A News Analysis. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ As U.S. peacekeepers prepare to
enter Kosovo, House Republicans consider a proposal to block funds
for the mission. Democratic lawmakers blast the timing, saying it
is a horrible signal to U.S. troops and the Yugoslav leadership. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ With the first successful
intercept of a ballistic missile by the $4 billion THAAD
anti-missile system, defense contractor Lockheed-Martin Corp. is
under intense financial pressure to do it again by July 16. If the
anti-missile system doesn't score a second successful intercept by
the deadline, the company will owe the Pentagon $20 million in
penalties. Lockheed has already paid the Pentagon $15 million for a
failed test in March. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION (Washington) _ The Internal Revenue Service
has ruled that the Christian Coalition is not entitled to
tax-exempt status, forcing the once-vaunted political powerhouse to
split into two entities and to be ``dramatically reshaped,''
officials close to the group say. The Texas branch will be renamed
the Christian Coalition of America, and will be limited to
non-partisan voter education. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-BUSH (Washington) _ Democratic National Committee Chairman
Roy Romer criticizes Texas Gov. George W. Bush for being weak on
Kosovo and other issues and says he brings oil and baseball _ the
Republican governor's former businesses _ to the national political
arena. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Washington) _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, says the
flow of illegal immigrants into the United States will worsen
unless President Clinton increases the number of Border Patrol
agents along the Southwest border. He also calls on the Clinton
administration to remove illegal aliens already in the United
States. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-LOITERING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes down a
Chicago anti-loitering law targeted at breaking the grip of street
gangs on inner-city neighborhoods. In a 6-3 decision, the court
rules that the 1992 law violates the rights of those arrested
because it does not give them adequate notice of what was
forbidden. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-US (Brussels, Belgium) _ Yugoslavia begins to withdraw
its forces from Kosovo amid a NATO halt to air raids, while the
United Nations moves to authorize the peace plan that will pave the
way for a 50,000-troop peace force in the province. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COCAINE-TRIAL (New Braunfels, Texas) _ A Texas jury, deciding in
a precedent-setting verdict that cocaine is a deadly weapon,
convicts a man of giving it to his teen-age daughter. Jurors
returned the verdict in less than an hour and sentenced Johnny
Rodriguez, 43, of New Braunfels, to 60 years in prison and a
$10,000 fine. By ROGER CROTEAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Is it in the genes? As he prepared
to take his presidential campaign outside of Texas for the first
time, Gov. George W. Bush tied himself into a no-new-taxes knot
just like the one that brought down his father. He blew the
possibility of making ``compassionate conservatism'' look like a
creative new deal, not just another rigid, stingy GOP approach to
governing. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-LIMA (Houston) _ With a little more than a month to go until
the All-Star Game, Houston Astros' pitcher Jose Lima has emerged as
the clear leader to be the National League starting pitcher for the
July 13 game in Boston. Lima, who leads the NL with 10 victories,
has a chance this weekend to further impress the manager who will
make the All-Star selections when Bruce Bochy and the San Diego
Padres come to town Friday for a three-game weekend series at the
Dome. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
