<HEADLINE>
(ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, JUNE 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEON HAS LOST ITS `HI' PROFILE t   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Neon hit the ground running in 1994, its cheerful face
bearing the promise of fun times in a serious world.
</P>
<P>
   A youthful car designed for young people, the Dodge and Plymouth
Neon was another solid hit for Chrysler, which was awash in kudos
for everything from groundbreaking cab-forward sedans to
ground-pounding Viper sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   As well as being attractive to look at, the diminutive Neon
proved to be relatively roomy inside and drove with spunk. It was
noisy, though, and some complained about its rough ride and darty
road manners.
</P>
<P>
   And Neon never fulfilled its promise to be a reliable member of
the family, suffering from a number of shortcomings in build
quality and durability, and earning low grades in ``Consumer
Report''s' reliability ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Neon's star has been fading in comparison with
such miniscule stalwarts as Honda Civic, still the undisputed
segment leader; Chevrolet Cavalier; Ford Escort; VW Golf; and
Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Neon has been redesigned fore and aft to eliminate some
problems. Gone is the noise and roughness, and, hopefully, the
spotty repair record. But also gone is much of the charm and
character that made the Neon such a standout among subcompacts.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler has traded in Neon's quirky attitude for a shot of
refinement, a homogenizing process that certainly has improved the
little critter, but at the cost of its perky originality. It's
longer, wider and more substantial in nearly every way, but the
styling is fairly generic, easily mistaken for Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Its placidly bland face is very unlike the animated friendliness
of the previous version, and unlikely to be seen going ``Hi'' on
any billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once inside and headed down the road, it's easy to
forget that style and personality have been sacrificed for a more
grown-up car. Neon is no longer just kid stuff designed to attract
young people into buying their first vehicle from Chrysler (and
presumably becoming lifelong customers) but a fully formed small
car meant for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is much improved, more supple and refined, but still
with the quick steering that make the old model so much fun to rip
into the turns. The engine is still somewhat boomy, but not too bad
and definitely improved.
</P>
<P>
   The tester was equipped with a five-speed, which in my humble
opinion is the way to go in a small car with a four-cylinder
engine. Shifting felt smooth and direct, and acceleration is brisk.
The engine revs up to a high 6,500 redline, but just gets noisy and
hostile when pushed up there and obviously prefers to be shifted
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The previously optional 150-horsepower engine seems to have
disappeared, but I'll wager that it comes back.
</P>
<P>
   The model designations and optional equipment are a complex
matter that takes some figuring. All I know is that our ES test car
included upgrades such as a nicer interior, a tachometer, fog
lamps, 15-inch wheels instead of 14, and some other convenience and
cosmetic upgrades, part of a $2,635 package. A combination package
of anti-lock brakes and traction control cost $740, and aluminum
wheels added another $355.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the Neon still exhibits the jewel-like quality of its
former self, our red ES test car looking quite snappy in the
driveway and standing out in traffic. The body is rattle-free and
feels tight as a drum.
</P>
<P>
   The body style looks somewhat like a smaller Dodge Stratus from
the side, with well-integrated full-frame doors and a nicely shaped
roof line. The front end looks nice, just not very distinctive, and
the rear has the sculpted, concave look of some of Chrysler's
bigger sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, there's no coupe, for those who prefer a sportier small
car. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   The interior does feel roomy, and the dashboard is functional
and interesting to look at, with a sharp-looking instrument panel
and trendy white-faced gauges.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is something about this interior that is
decidedly weird, and that's the windows. For front passengers,
they're standard electric windows, but in the back, they're manual
crank windows. This is a configuration that I've never seen before,
and which I find bizarre and mystifying.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure somebody at Chrysler had this bright idea to save a few
bucks on each car, but it's a classic case of penny-wise and
pound-foolish. No one is going to favor this setup.
</P>
<P>
   But all told, Neon has grown up, turning into a nice, all-around
car, competing well in this high-volume segment, and offering some
decent accommodations at a budget price.
</P>
<P>
   But it has gone from distinctive to mainstream. Something lost,
something gained. Just don't expect it to say ``Hi.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dodge Neon ES &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: &QL; 
Five-passenger, four-door sedan, front-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: &QL; 
$12,390. &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$16,080. &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
2-liter in-line four, 132 horsepower at 5,600 rpm, 130 pound-feet
of torque at 4,600 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: &QL; 
Five-speed stick. &QL; 
Curb weight: &QL; 
2,564 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: &QL; 
105 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
28 city, 35 highway. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
Sporty ride. Solid feel. Upgraded aura. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
Personality loss. Weird window setup. Generic styling. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
