<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITNESSES TELL CONGRESS TO KEEP TITLE I FOR POOR CHILDREN
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government's biggest educational
program for poor children should be continued despite its
shortcomings, a wide array of witnesses told Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Title I'' because it is the first program in the
Elementary and Secondary Education Act, the $8 billion-a-year
program will expire unless the act is renewed within the next 15
months. More than 45,000 public and private schools with high
numbers of poor children use Title I funds for programs that range
from extra tutoring to computer-based instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be reauthorized; the only question is what can be done
to improve it,'' said Chairman William Goodling, R-Pa., after his
House Committee on Education and the Workforce heard testimony from
skeptical state officials and enthusiastic representatives of
public-school teacher unions and the U.S. Catholic bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Title I has been a colossal failure,'' testified Roan
Garcia-Quintana, director of Title I programs for the Georgia
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discernible difference could be found (by a massive study
in 1997) between children who received Title I services and
children of equivalent backgrounds who did not participate in the
program,'' Garcia-Quintana said. ``But I don't want Congress to
dump Title I. I want them to overhaul it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association, was
less downbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvement has been insufficient, but it's there,'' said
Chase, who cited other studies and contended that changes made in
1994 will continue to increase the program's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NEA opposes any efforts to alter significantly the
structure or direction of Title I,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses cold-shouldered many of the Clinton
administration's suggestions for imposing new, detailed
requirements on schools that accept Title I funds.
</P>
<P>
   States should be able to spend Title I funds any way they want
as long as they can show that they are improving the academic
performance of disadvantaged children, said Garcia-Quintana and
Cheri Pierson Yecke, Virginia's deputy secretary of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to step forward and accept the responsibility
for improving student achievement,'' Yecke said. ``All we ask is
the flexibility to use our funds as we see fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, vice president of the American Federation of
Teachers, and Chase liked Clinton's suggestion for tougher
standards for new teachers. But they were leery of his proposal
that the federal government require two years of college for any
aide whose duties include such instructional activity as one-on-one
tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   While about one-third of aides want to go on to become teachers,
two-thirds aren't interested in education other than vocational
training for their current job, Weingarten said.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying on behalf of the Catholic bishops, John Clark said,
``We also believe that the existing law addresses instructional
aides in an adequate fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   As the witnesses filed out of the hearing room, Goodling said,
``I thought some of them should have been a little more forthcoming
in talking about the failures of Title I. There have been a lot of
failures.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
