<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE YET NOT JAPANESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 15, when most Americans were preoccupied with taxes,
more than 400 citizens of Nagoya, Japan, were lining up to be the
first to enter their city's new museum, the Nagoya/Boston Museum of
Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   In a novel arrangement, Nagoya has built a contemporary,
flexible museum space and is paying the Boston museum each year to
borrow works of art that curators of the two museums choose to show
for limited periods.
</P>
<P>
   One might have guessed the Japanese were lining up to see the
Boston museum's collection of Impressionists, which filled one
floor of the Nagoya museum, or its superb collection of
antiquities, also on loan.
</P>
<P>
   But many were on their way to study an early 17th-century
Japanese screen that had been in Boston for a century and would be
on loan only until early June.
</P>
<P>
   The six-panel screen, ``European King and Members of his
Court,'' was shown in its own room. The figures portrayed are
Western nobles in elaborate court dress in brilliant oranges and
reds.
</P>
<P>
   The men have beards and curly hair but their faces do not look
totally Western. The details are convincingly painted, but the work
looks odd; for one thing, none of the figures relate to each other.
They look like a parade of paper dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This screen is highly unusual because it depicts Westerners
and was done under the influence of Western painting,'' said Anne
Nishimura Morse, associate curator of Asiatic art at the Boston
museum. ``But it was painted by Japanese. And they were not using
standard Japanese techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese painters may have copied the figures from books
brought to Japan from Europe, Mrs. Morse explained, adding that by
the 1580s, the Jesuits had founded a painting school in Japan.
Jesuit missionaries arrived in Japan as early as 1549, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The screen shown in Nagoya is an example of Nanban, a work of
art created by Japanese that either imitates a Western form, like a
trunk, or is decorated with Western subject matter, like European
sailors. ``Nanban'' means ``southern barbarians,'' because
foreigners approached Japan from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Nanban art is a collecting specialty all its own. There are
museums of Nanban art in both Osaka and Kobe, Japan, and New York
City dealers like Leighton Longhi and Naga Antiques, which
specialize in Japanese art and antiques, usually have several
examples for sale at any given time. Nanban art even has its own
section in the catalog of Christie's London sale of ``Japanese Art
and Design,'' scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the Christie's sale is a huge lacquer chest with
elaborate shell inlay depicting rabbits, deer, turtles and an ox in
panels bordered in metal studwork.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hinton, director of the Japanese department at Christie's
London, said that the studs had no purpose. In copying a leather
trunk from Portugal, the Japanese put studs in the spots where they
would have anchored the leather pieces on the original trunk. The
trunk is a good example of how the Japanese borrowed a form, then
used their own materials and artistry. The piece is estimated to
sell for $65,000 to $81,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another lot consists of five tea bowls and saucers from the Edo
period designed with gold lacquer on a black ground. Again, the
saucers show a strong European influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Note the wide flat rim,'' Hinton said. ``It's not Japanese.
Sets like this from the 1680s are comparatively rare, though some
have been found in the inventories of English country houses like
Burghley House in Lincolnshire.'' Its estimate is $3,300 to $4,800.
</P>
<P>
   Nanban art reveals how Japanese artists reacted to Westerners on
first contact.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike China, which had periodic influxes of Islamic peoples for
2000 years, Japan was relatively isolated until the 1500s. It had
never been defeated at war and was not at all threatened by the
first Portuguese traders who arrived in 1541.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese were fascinated by foreign things,'' Longhi, the
New York dealer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Portuguese and then the Dutch established trading ties.
Then Portuguese missionaries arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Christianity spread very rapidly in Japan, according to Shinichi
Tani, a professor who contributed to a catalog for a Nanban art
show at the Japan Society in 1972. By 1582 the number of Japanese
that had embraced Christianity had risen to 150,000, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese banned the practice of the Christian faith in 1613.
Nonetheless, the professor wrote, ``interest in European culture
was enhanced, and to some extent European manners and customs were
gradually absorbed into the life of the rulers, the local feudal
lords and the well-to-do. Thus a body of artists was gradually
created who expressed themselves in a European manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanban art appears in various media. The best examples are
folding Japanese screens that depict Portuguese galleons in detail.
Often the foreign ship is shown entering a Japanese port, with
welcoming dignitaries on shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese captains are usually tall and have long noses and
scraggly beards, and the crew typically includes a few African
sailors. The missionaries wear habits. Frequently the foreigners
have pale blue eyes and seem to be looking toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large quantities of these screens were made in the late 16th
century, when they became popular among the merchant class,'' said
James Marinaccio, of Naga Antiques in Manhattan. ``It was a time of
prosperity, and the merchants were furnishing their mansions.''
</P>
<P>
   Longhi said that Nanban screens were now fairly rare. He is
selling one that shows Japanese people greeting a black Portuguese
sailing ship docked at a Japanese port. On shore are an odd-looking
elephant and a tiger, neither of which was painted from life; they
look like Booth cartoons. There are Christian priests on the boat
and on shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese exaggerated the physiognomy of Western people
because they weren't used to their pointed noses and long chins,''
Longhi said. ``They had to translate the idea that they were
foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese were also taken with Western dress, he said. ``Part
of the exoticism is in the Westerners' outfits,'' he said. ``The
Japanese adopted Western pantaloons in the early 17th century just
as they have American blue jeans in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   The screen is in excellent condition. Its price is $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   People have long speculated about why the Japanese embraced the
West so quickly in the 1860s, after Admiral Perry sailed in.
Perhaps they had never stopped thinking about Westerners, even
after the Tokagawa regime closed the borders in 1639.
</P>
<P>
   As Longhi said, ``Once you put ideas in someone's head, you
can't stop ideas by edict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
