<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG BOY'S BATTLE WITH AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most beautiful sights you'll see on television this
month is the face of Travis Jeffries. All the joy of youth, and
some of the wisdom of age, glows from his 200-watt eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Travis, who was born with AIDS, lives in the Highbridge section
of the Bronx. In 1995, when Travis was 7, the filmmaker Richard
Kotuk began compiling his portrait, never knowing if this child
would survive. But the loving attention of his family, principally
his heroic grandmother, and of his unflinching medical team never
flagged.
</P>
<P>
   Travis thrives today. Kotuk died last year, shortly after
completing the hourlong documentary called simply ``Travis.'' It is
to be broadcast Friday night on WNET, Channel 13, as the first
installment of ``Reel New York,'' an eight-week series of films by
independent artists working in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis'' manages to distill this plague to the dimensions of
one life. And it demonstrates the power of that one life to affect
a hundred others.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with Travis looking right into the camera and
saying: ``I'm gonna die. I'm gonna die.'' And a moment later: ``I
don't wanna die. D'you?'' If that doesn't get your attention, flip
back to the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Travis himself, there are two other major figures in the
film. One is his grandmother, Geneva Jeffries, who has 11 children,
33 grandchildren and 7 great-grandchildren. She has spent a
lifetime as a domestic, tending to other families' needs. Now she
tends to Travis, after winning his custody from his mother, her
daughter Samantha, a drug abuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hurting feeling, to see your child in misery,'' Mrs.
Jeffries says during one of Travis' setbacks. But she adds: ``You
want me to be sorry for myself? I'm not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   She speaks directly to Kotuk, the narrator and off-screen
interviewer and the film's other big presence. Although unseen, he
frames people with his questions. When he asks Travis, who
understands that he inherited his disease, if he is angry at his
mother, the boy replies seriously: ``Why should I be mad at Mommy?
It's not her fault.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a boy who has taken more than 275 different drugs,
some of which prevented him from eating solid food for most of his
life. When the film ends with a scene of Travis, feeling well at
last, happily chomping his lunch in a restaurant, that moment is a
monument to hope.
</P>
<P>
   A postscript added last month reports that Samantha has
completed a rehabilitation program and has started a job, Mrs.
Jeffries has terminal cancer, and other family members are caring
for Travis. You may be moved to pray for them all. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDDIE IZZARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Dress to Kill' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Saturday night at 11:30 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you notice about the British comic Eddie Izzard
_ after you notice that he's wearing high heels, blue nail polish
and lots of plum-colored lipstick _ is how smart he is. His
interests range from ancient history to society's latest offenses,
and his mind leaps from one to another in an
extreme-of-consciousness monologue.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes he can hopscotch among topics including Pol
Pot, squirrels, gun control, ``Scooby Doo,'' perjury and the
Austro-Hungarian Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Izzard calls himself an ``executive transvestite,'' as opposed
to the weirdo kind. Many New Yorkers, executives and weirdos alike,
are still chuckling over his March 1998 visit with his
two-and-a-half-hour one-man show, ``Dress to Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO's version, edited to 90 minutes, was taped in San Francisco
in September. He can be a bit offensive here and there. Mostly he's
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Grappling with the concept of original sin, he wonders what sort
is original? ``I poked a badger with a spoon.'' That's an original
sin, he declares, then decides that the penance for it must be
``say three Hail Marys and two Hello Dollys.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzard enjoys chiding Americans' ignorance. They don't remember
their own national anthem: ``The words are a bit fuzzy in the
middle.'' Nor do they remember their own national history. After
mentioning General Lafayette, he slyly admonishes: ``You don't know
who he is, do you? What is it? The Spanish-American War? The French
Banana War? What?''
</P>
<P>
   It's Izzard's war on pretense. Pretense loses. Viewers win. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REEL NEW YORK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Channel 13, New York, Friday night at 10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Richard Kotuk and Jean Tsien; produced and directed
by Kotuk. Produced for the Independent Television Service and
presented by Channel 13/WNET New York. Michelle Materre, curatorial
consultant; Garrison Botts, series producer. &QL;
</P>
