<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: MARY PICKFORD; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Pickford, Power Broker
</P>
<P>
   She was ``America's sweetheart,'' all right, but under those
golden curls Mary Pickford, often cast as the tragic waif, had one
of the hardest heads in Hollywood. ``By 1914 or 1915, she was
pulling the strings, making the rules,'' said Elaina Archer, the
manager of the Mary Pickford Library in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With Dennis Doros of Milestone Films, a New York distributor,
Ms. Archer helped choose six Pickford films for video release, five
of them for the first time on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known of these is ``Stella Maris'' (1918), in
which Pickford plays Unity Blake, a homely and much abused servant,
and Stella Maris, a gloriously radiant rich girl who, because she
is paralyzed, has been so sheltered from the woes of the world that
she reaches young womanhood unaware of things like war and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Pickford was acquainted with the latter condition,
having at the age of 8 or so become a principal provider for a
theatrical family that was virtually destitute. In those days,
Pickford, who was born Gladys Louise Smith in 1893, developed a
kindly but tough Irish personality that, as ``adorable'' as she
was, found expression in roles as provider and aggressive champion
of the downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   An example is ``Tess of the Storm Country'' (1922), one of the
six Milestone films, in which Pickford battles for the rights of a
group of squatters threatened by the rich man on the hill. ``Tess
is parallel to Mary as a person,'' Ms. Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sparrows'' (1926), another Milestone release, she is Mama
Mollie, the oldest of a group of exploited children whom she leads
to freedom through the swamps. Two other films, ``Daddy-Long-Legs''
(1919) and ``My Best Girl'' (1927) cast her as, respectively, the
oldest child in an orphanage and a lowly shop clerk who falls for
the boss' son. ``Amarilly of Clothes-Line Alley'' (1918), the sixth
film, is set in an Irish tenement neighborhood in San Francisco and
celebrates Pickford's Irish roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was buying rights to the stories and hiring women to write
them,'' Ms. Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   As Little Mary in 1909, Pickford made $40 a week at the Biograph
Co. By 1916 she was making $10,000 a week. Later it was a million
dollars a year. In 1919, at age 26, she began United Artists with
Charlie Chaplin, D.W. Griffith and her husband, Douglas Fairbanks.
By then she had long chosen her own films and roles. ``There came a
point when Mary became powerful enough to hire her own directors,
casts, crews, everyone,'' Ms. Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually her career dried up in the 1930s when she turned 40,
in those days the death knell for a woman on screen, and didn't
fare that well in the talkies. She always drove a hard bargain.
Samuel Goldwyn said it took longer to negotiate a Pickford contract
than to make one of her films. ``She was generous,'' Ms. Archer
said, ``but she came from a hard background and she wasn't going to
be pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are $29.95 each or $124.95 for the set. Information:
(800) 603-1104.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa''
</P>
<P>
   As Kate Mundy, one of five unmarried sisters in a remote Irish
village in 1936, Meryl Streep turns even the simple act of peering
out a window into a haunting expression of loneliness. Without much
overarching action, Pat O'Connor's film, based on the play by Brian
Friel, becomes a collection of personal sea changes and splendidly
realized small moments among the women (Catherine McCormack, Kathy
Burke, Brid Brennan and Sophie Thompson are the other sisters).
Returning from his missionary's post in Africa, their brother,
Father Jack (Michael Gambon), offers a wider perspective, as does
Gerry (Rhys Ifans), the youngest sister Christina's boyfriend. As
he did in ``Circle of Friends,'' O'Connor, Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times, ``creates a quintessentially Irish
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 92 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG. Release date: June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy of the State''
</P>
<P>
   Unwittingly stuck with a videotape showing the murder of a
congressman, the straight-shooting lawyer Robert Clayton Dean (Will
Smith) runs for his life. Seems the killing is tied to a scheme
hatched by a National Security Agency higher-up (Jon Voight) to
wire the entire country for surveillance. As it stands already, the
agency has Dean wired right down to his trousers, which he has to
get rid off at high speed if he's to shed his pursuers. With its
snazzy equipment and wild chases, Tony Scott's film keeps ``the
story moving faster than the speed of scrutiny'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $107.77. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Faculty''
</P>
<P>
   An alien being takes over Herrington High School, turning its
faculty and student body into murderous zombies (which in most
cases is a distinct improvement). Only a small group of students,
all of them either very cool or very nerdy, are left to battle the
thing long enough to stab it to death with a syringe. Josh Hartnett
is the coolest as Zeke, who peddles condoms but has a feel for
science. Anyway, the performances are the thing in a sly if
mediocre sci-fi horror film that, like Frankenstein, ``plunders the
crypts of cinema for its body parts'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Dimension. $106.77. 102 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theory of Flight''
</P>
<P>
   Dying of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's disease),
the feisty Jane (Helena Bonham Carter) talks dirty and spends her
spare time watching hard-core pornography. Eager to lose her
virginity, she gets the help of Richard (Kenneth Branagh), a failed
painter who builds primitive flying machines. Richard, though,
never is more than an allegorical construction in a film that
``might be described as a disease-of-the-week movie with comic and
mythic pretensions'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $104.16. 99 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``FROM EARTH TO THE MOON.'' The 12-hour mini-series tracing the
Apollo project has been on DVD since November, and now is available
on videotape. Tom Hanks conceived the show, wrote part of it and
acted in one segment. And quite a show it is, having been nominated
for 17 Emmy Awards. 1998. HBO $89.92, six cassettes. 720 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``UN AIR DE FAMILLE.'' A wishfully jolly family birthday party
gradually turns acidic in Cedric Klapisch's film, which began as a
play and won Cesars (French Oscars) for its writers, Agnes Jaoui
and Jean-Pierre Bacri, and two of its actors, Jean-Pierre Darrousin
and Catherine Frot. Gathered in the family's restaurant, six
relatives, ruled over by a proper and quite awful bourgeois mother
(Claire Maurier), spar drolly at first but grow steadily more
contentious during an encounter that eventually levels everybody in
sight. Klapisch's film expertly frees the one-set play from visual
claustrophobia and has the same cast that performed the work
onstage, which is why, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``they work so artfully as an ensemble and so evidently know their
characters inside out.'' 1998. Fox Lorber. 105 minutes. French with
English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``BEHIND THE SCENES.'' Jazz percussionist and composer Max Roach
and photographer Carrie Mae Weems explain their art to children
(adults are welcome) in the PBS series. 1999. First Run Features.
$14.95 each. 30 minutes each. Information: (800) 488-6652. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
