<SLUG> BC-SEX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUST A LITTLE HARMLESS SEX': FALLOUT WHEN MARS AND VENUS COLLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who can't get enough of the romantic and sexual
travails of 20- and 30-somethings in the customary half-hour
television sitcom format, the super-size version has arrived under
the title ``Just a Little Harmless Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   It is well cast, well acted and thoroughly inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   But it has a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two-thirds of the film, according to its publicity,
the buddy talk was written by a man and the girl talk by a woman.
When the sexes finally come together for the finale, the writers _
Roger Mills and Marti Noxon _ collaborated.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rick Rosenthal, whose credits include ``Bad Boys''
and ``Russkies,'' this prosaic romantic comedy hangs off a sexual
misadventure involving Alan (Robert Mailhouse), as he is driving
home to his wife in a downpour after a night at a topless bar with
his buddies, Danny (Jonathan Silverman) and Brent (William
Ragsdale).
</P>
<P>
   Spying a young woman drenched beside her disabled sports car, he
gives her a lift and she promptly gives him oral sex. In a moment
they are surrounded by police cars. The damsel in distress turns
out to be a prostitute. Alan's wife, Laura (Alison Eastwood, Clint
Eastwood's daughter), is informed of his arrest and asked to post
bail, and Alan's marriage is fractured.
</P>
<P>
   Most of ``Just a Little Harmless Sex'' cuts back and forth
between the remorseful Alan and his friends and Laura and her
friends discussing this crisis and exchanging confidences,
including their own problems with relationships and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Danny, an opportunistic lawyer, is angrily separated from his
wife, the nonorgasmic Terrianne (Jessica Lundy), who is one of
Laura's friends and who is convinced he cheated on her. Brent, a
sportswriter, has no girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Terrianne, Laura's best friend is the seemingly mousy
Allison (Kimberly Williams) who turns out to be nothing of the sort
once she sheds her eyeglasses, dons black, has a few drinks and
starts dancing at the HiJinx, the club where everybody eventually
winds up.
</P>
<P>
   And on the fringes of all the angst is Laura's mother, Elaine
(Lauren Hutton), playing a latter-day Mrs. Robinson as she dazzles
all the overgrown adolescent males with her knowing, indulgent
smiles; her overwhelming self-confidence and her unabashed
flirtatiousness.
</P>
<P>
   But on the big screen, ``Just a Little Harmless Sex'' looks like
just a little more television.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JUST A LITTLE HARMLESS SEX'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Rick Rosenthal; written by Marti Noxon
and Roger Mills; director of photography, Bruce Surtees; edited by
James Austin Surtees; music by Tito Larriva; production designer,
Amy Danger; released by Phaedra Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 98 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: The film is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes bare breasts, sexually
suggestive dancing, simulated sex, frank sexual discussions and
coarse language.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Alison Eastwood (Laura), Lauren Hutton (Elaine), Kimberly
Williams (Allison), Jonathan Silverman (Danny), Jessica Lundy
(Terrianne), William Ragsdale (Brent) and Robert Mailhouse (Alan).
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
