<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHIEF DEFIES GUN RULE AT SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANITA WADHWANI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco police chief defied a school
board vote to restrict the authority of police officers to carry
weapons on school campuses, saying that only he will decide whether
to ``arm or disarm'' officers.
</P>
<P>
   The rule was part of the ``Safe Schools'' package approved by
the San Francisco Unified School District board Tuesday night. The
measure also requires school staff members to contact
administrators before calling the police when there is a problem
with a student, unless the pupil has broken the law or poses a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau, with the backing of Mayor Willie Brown,
said Wednesday he asked the city attorney to look into the legality
of the school district resolution.
</P>
<P>
   School board members and civil rights activists, meanwhile,
stood their ground, saying the policy was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been unfairly portrayed as something that limits
police presence on campus and endangers students,'' said Renee
Saucedo, a lawyer with La Raza Centro Legal, which supported the
school board measure. ``But if you read the resolution, it becomes
clear that the reason for it is to protect the civil rights of
students.''
</P>
<P>
   La Raza Centro Legal, a San Francisco public interest law firm,
began advocating such a measure when it started seeing clients as
young as 12 who said they were hauled before police officers in
their schools over routine disciplinary matters. The students,
Saucedo alleged, were disproportionately black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Steve Phillips, who proposed the resolution,
said: ``The issue is systemic. If we disproportionately
discriminate against African-American children in our schools, then
that would extend to police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the purpose of the gun restriction was ``to set up
guidelines so that staff don't call the police in situations where
their presence is just not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lau said his department's 50-year-old school programs are
popular with students, teachers and the police and have earned
national recognition. Posting officers at many campuses in the city
is just one aspect of the Police Department's campus programs.
</P>
<P>
   Officers also take students on fishing and camping trips, among
other activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our officers describe these jobs as being a family and
community responsibility,'' Lau said. ``If there are any
allegations of mistreatment of students, then they have not been
brought to my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau pledged to move forward with plans to place more additional
officers in high schools. The mayor included money for the
personnel in the city budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety of our schools is paramount,'' said Ron Vincent, a
spokesman for the mayor. ``We stand firmly behind the San Francisco
Police Department on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Teachers Association did not take a formal
position on the resolution. However, the union's local president,
Ken Mitchell, voiced concern that the new reporting procedures
might conflict with the California Education Code mandate that
teachers report all violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support any effort to create safe environments for teachers
and students, but teachers must be able to report violent incidents
to police,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. James Dudley of the Police Department's juvenile division
had urged the school board not to vote on the measure until the
police had a chance to review it.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote on the ``Safe Schools'' measure, Dudley
criticized the decision, saying it would keep officers in the dark
about potential acts of violence or troubled youths. He also said
the district didn't have the authority to govern police practices
on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they refuse to have us on campus with guns, I don't know
who that will benefit,'' Dudley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     06-10 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: `MAGNOLIA' SECRECY; RARE HOLLYWOOD EPIC; HOPE FROM
`STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look Who's Not Talking
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ April Grace is understandably thrilled at getting
the biggest break in her acting career, a part opposite Tom Cruise
in the movie ``Magnolia,'' and she expresses delight at being able
to talk with a reporter about her breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   What part does she play? ``I'm not supposed to say that,'' Ms.
Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what kind of character is it? ``I can't really answer
that, either,'' she said, smiling awkwardly, ``other than to say
she's a really intense woman.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so what was it like working with Cruise?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask the studio,'' said Ms. Grace, clearly eager
to share but feeling constrained. ``But I can tell you it was a
great experience. It was a great group of people to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Some filmmakers court publicity with a maddening persistence,
and then there are those whose movies seem like shadows of rumors.
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' directed by Stanley Kubrick and starring Cruise
and Nicole Kidman, is one such film. Another is ``Magnolia,''
written and directed by Paul Thomas Anderson, whose last film was
``Boogie Nights,'' about a group of kindly pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia,'' which is being produced by New Line, is scheduled
for release at Christmas, but don't tell anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been obsessively secretive about the movie _ in
part, people who know him say, because he felt his last movie was
misrepresented in the press before its release _ and Ms. Grace, 32,
who has made appearances in the film ``Playing by Heart'' and on
television in ``Chicago Hope'' and ``NYPD Blue,'' has had to take
an oath of silence, along with everyone else. She is an exuberant
woman, and the effort is an obvious strain, but she plays the part.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch, at which she nibbled about three leaves of a caesar
salad, she spoke energetically about the difficulties of being a
black actress in Hollywood, about her love of singing, about the
tendency of directors to cast her as a crack addict and about
growing up in Florida, but passed when the subject of her movie
came up. She had company.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kingsley, Cruise's publicity agent, said: ``He's just not
talking about it. This is an unbilled performance. He just wanted
to work with the director.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumble Ward, Anderson's public relations agent, commented: ``All
I can tell you is it's an ensemble piece set in present-day San
Fernando Valley. We can't say anything further because it's so
complicated. He's not talking about the movie yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But some intensive sleuthing produced the following. The movie
is a fragmentary drama about several different relationships, a
group of loose threads that eventually pull together. Cruise's
relationship with Ms. Grace's character, named Guinevere, is
dissected slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also stars William H. Macy, Julianne Moore, Jason
Robards, John C. Reilly, Philip Baker Hall and Felicity Huffman,
among others. Anderson wrote the script and directed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grace did let out one slip. Of Anderson, she said, ``He's a
wonderful director to work for.''
</P>
<P>
   A Violin's Story
</P>
<P>
   Epic films are not exactly the order of the day in Hollywood,
where the focus tends to be, with few exceptions, on teen flicks
(``Austin Powers''), scatological humor for younger audiences
(``Austin Powers'') and the wizardry of special effects (``Star
Wars'').
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason, anyway, why ``The Red Violin'' stands out.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opens in New York and Los Angeles on Friday,
spans three centuries and three continents. It is filled with
passion and drama, thievery, an early death, greed, suspense,
injustice, betrayal and more passion and drama. There are gypsies,
Maoists, monks and millionaires. It is, in short, one of the most
ambitious movies to come out this year, so it is understandable
that it took five years for its director, Francois Girard, to make.
</P>
<P>
   All that for what the 36-year-old Girard described as a
metaphor. ``It's about a very central human obsession,'' he said.
``We are all trying to leave some proof or some traces of our
presence here.''
</P>
<P>
   In more ways than one. The movie appears to be an effort by
Girard, who made ``Thirty-Two Short Films About Glenn Gould,'' to
leave a mark as a filmmaker with a sweeping vision. And the story
itself is about immortality, of a sort.
</P>
<P>
   Girard, who was also the co-author of ``The Red Violin,'' said
the film took root from a conversation he had with a friend in
London in 1994, he said. They discussed the idea of how an object
travels through time and came up with the notion of a story with a
nonlinear chronology. ``Fragmented time and space, those are the
prerogative of the filmmaker,'' Girard said.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows the journey of a famous violin through its
history, telling the story of the enduring love that inspired the
creation of the violin by Nicolo Bussotti (Carlo Cecchi) in
17th-century Italy. He intends the violin to be a gift for his
soon-to-be-born son. When the child and his wife die during the
birth, he imbues the instrument with his grief and aspirations, and
these qualities then infect the lives of each of the instrument's
later owners.
</P>
<P>
   In contemporary Montreal, the violin is up for auction, and a
dogged researcher, Charles Morritz (Samuel L. Jackson), explores
its history and past owners. The movie is a dramatization of what
he discovers, as the violin journeys from Italy to an Austrian
monastery, to London in 1893, via some gypsies, to China in the
thrall of Mao's Cultural Revolution, where it is almost destroyed
before being rescued by Xiang Pei (Sylvia Chang).
</P>
<P>
   Once the Cultural Revolution has passed, the violin is sent to
Montreal to be auctioned, with heirs of all its previous owners
present to try to buy it back. But now it has infected Jackson's
character with its passion, and a new adventure begins just as the
movie ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I identify with Charles Morritz,'' Girard said. ``He's the man
through whom I'm looking at the violin and all the things it
represents.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's about how can love survive.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for Weirdness
</P>
<P>
   The runaway success of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace'' has been particularly good news for Rob Burman. It is not
just that the latest installment in the Star Wars series is
breaking box office records but that this is the first time in a
while that a major special-effects-driven movie has done so
spectacularly well, particularly one with characters that look so
odd.
</P>
<P>
   Odd is good for Burman because he and Sticks and Stones, the
company he runs with his wife, specialize in unusual makeup design,
and they are struggling with a recession in movie production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that we're coming up on the second worst year
in our history, and we've been doing this for more than 20 years''
Burman said. ``It can't last forever, I'm sure, but I would say out
of 35 competitors in Los Angeles, three have jobs right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that his own company had ballooned to about 22
employees at its peak several years ago and that it is now down to
just him and his wife. The American economy may be booming, but
Hollywood is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   To get inflated costs under control, most studios are cutting
back on the number of movies they produce and on the overall
budgets. Walt Disney Co., for instance, has said it is cutting as
much as $600 million from its annual moviemaking budgets.
</P>
<P>
   This is having a pronounced impact, particularly on the
thousands of little companies that provide services from catering
to makeup. Jack Kyser, an economist with the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp., said that California state figures show
employment in the movie industry in Los Angeles has declined from a
peak of 142,500 in February 1998 to 127,200 as of April 1999, the
latest period for which figures are available, and that the decline
is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very pronounced slowdown and it just goes on,''
Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there were 637 feature movies initiated in Los
Angeles County in 1997 and 510 last year. This year he estimates
there will be about 480 based on current trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole production cost structure has gotten out of hand,
and this is the response,'' Kyser said. ``Our feeling is you'll see
another employment slowdown this year and very likely in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the slowdown is more pronounced than the official
figures show because many small companies provide services that do
not show up in the state data.
</P>
<P>
   Burman said he hoped that the success of ``Star Wars'' will
encourage more big budget pictures with creatures and the like,
requiring elaborate makeup. ``No more of these romantic comedy
clones, please,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
