<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANET-EARTH-ART-NYT &LR;      06-10 1928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANET-EARTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAPING EARTH: AN EXHIBIT 4.5 BILLION YEARS IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over more than a century, scientists and explorers
from the American Museum of Natural History have searched the world
and returned with arresting examples of life in all its diversity:
dinosaurs from Montana to Mongolia, birds and butterflies,
artifacts of exotic cultures from here to the South Sea. For the
last four years, their quest has been to collect the stuff of Earth
itself and bring it back for a new exhibition illustrating the
planet's 4.5 billion-year history.
</P>
<P>
   On 28 acquisition expeditions, museum teams collected 82 tons of
rock and ore, ranging from granite and sandstone to gold and
platinum. The oldest, a zircon crystal from Australia, is nearly
4.3 billion years old. The youngest, a chunk of sulfur, was picked
up the same day it solidified in an Indonesian volcano. The rarest
and most intriguing to scientists are sulfide chimneys that rise
from volcanic vents on the sea floor, where some of the first forms
of life may have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Now the collections have been studied, winnowed and arranged for
display in the museum's newest permanent exhibit, the Gottesman
Hall of Planet Earth, which opens Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Showing off the exhibit, museum president Ellen Futter declared
that this was a ``never-before assembled global array'' of
specimens integrated with ``the most innovative multimedia
technology ever created for a museum hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone expecting to find the usual drab pieces of rock under
glass should be pleasantly surprised. Huge slabs of stone, highly
polished and touchable, draw attention to the ingrained beauty and
surging dynamism of geology. Video and other graphics offer crisp
explanations. A result is an awakening to the motions and changes
of the restless world underlying and supporting life.
</P>
<P>
   The intent, said Ms. Futter, was ``to convey both the majesty of
earth and its dynamic, seething innards that yield such cataclysmic
explosions as earthquakes, volcanoes, tornadoes, hurricanes and the
like, while also presenting the latest, still emerging theories of
the origins of life on earth and the possibilities of life
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   To this end, as Dr. Edmond Mathez, a geologist and the chief
curator of the hall, explained, the exhibit is organized around
five fundamental questions: How has earth evolved? Why are there
ocean basins, continents and mountains? How do scientists read
rocks? What causes climate and climate change? Why is earth
habitable?
</P>
<P>
   In the center of it all, for rest, contemplation and
perspective, is a 30-seat granite amphitheater where visitors can
look up at an enormous earth globe. It appears to be rotating
slowly as a projection system inside the globe shows the planet's
surface as seen from space. Stay for 12 minutes and see the
familiar landscapes change. The clouds disperse, then continental
vegetation disappears and finally all the blue water of the oceans
drains away. The bare, rugged earth stands revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Off to one side is the ``Earth Event Wall.'' This is an
electronic bulletin board bearing news of recent storms,
earthquakes and volcanic eruptions, illustrated with television and
computer-generated animation. The display is to be updated
regularly, providing expert interpretations of how these events
illustrate the world's geologic forces.
</P>
<P>
   At the north end of the hall is another focal point, a large
video screen exploding with scenes of rampaging lava, rivers
overflowing and glaciers carving terrain. The experience can be
visceral. As the sounds of an earthquake fill the hall, those
sitting on nearby benches feel the rumble. From one bench it is
possible to see the consequences in the face of a crystalline rock.
Its layers are offset more than a foot by the slippage of a fault
during a major quake.
</P>
<P>
   Children and not a few grown-ups will enjoy stamping their feet
and seeing the tremor, their own ``earthquake,'' recorded as a
jagged spike on a seismograph.
</P>
<P>
   On display also is one of the world's best records of climate
change, an ice core from Greenland. The ice is a 115,000-year
archive of atmospheric gases, dust and other chemicals from the
time the snow first fell. A chart shows the effects in the ice of
the eruption of Vesuvius in A.D. 79 and the Clean Air Act in the
United States, beginning in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the rock specimens can be viewed as a natural art form
as well as a lesson in geology. The rippling folds exposed in one
rock cutaway are a graceful show of how seemingly brittle material
can flow, given enough time and heat. The rock is in easy, tempting
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can touch,'' Mathez said. ``This is a very tactile hall.''
</P>
<P>
   One approaches a polished specimen of banded iron from Ontario,
2.7 billion years old, with the same impulse. Fingers run over the
dark red streaks of jasper. Helpful labels explain the deeper
meaning. When single-celled organisms began supplying oxygen to
earth's atmosphere, iron and silica minerals emerged out of the
ocean. The red bands in the rock stopped forming once the
atmosphere and ocean were saturated with free oxygen. Here, then,
were rocks telling of this fateful transition in an evolving earth.
</P>
<P>
   Another display brings together two sandstones that were, so to
speak, separated after birth. They were deposited at the same time
near each other, but then the spreading Atlantic Ocean came between
them, one rock residing in Scotland and the other ending up near
Monticello, N.Y. It was a striking illustration of continental
drift through the shifting of crustal plates, the process known as
plate tectonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The present is the key to the past,'' said James Hutton, the
18th-century Scotsman who was among the first to recognize the
principles of modern geology. His contributions are acknowledged
and explained in one corner of the hall.
</P>
<P>
   The museum advertises that the rock specimens and 11 full-scale
models of classic outcroppings were gathered from 25 countries. But
geologists take special pride in some tall heaps of rock,
resembling smelting slag, that they sent a robotic vehicle to the
bottom of the Pacific Ocean to collect.
</P>
<P>
   These are the sulfide chimneys, also known as black smokers
because they are formed as dark, mineral-laden hot water billows
from vents in the sea floor. The museum said these are the first
such chimneys ever collected while they were still hot and teeming
with strange life. An expedition by the museum and the University
of Washington brought them to the surface last summer off the coast
of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   It is the microbial and other forms of life found thriving on
the chimneys that especially intrigue scientists. These organisms
flourish in the absence of sunlight, living on chemicals at
crushing pressures. Scientists theorize that early life on earth
could have arisen at such places, and life on other planets just
might exist in similarly harsh environments.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the stark columns of dark rock, Mathez said,
``This is where the biosphere and geosphere meet in a profound
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Planet Earth was developed with the financial
support of David S. and Ruth L. Gottesman and was designed by Ralph
Appelbaum Associates. It is the first half of the Rose Center for
Earth and Space, designed by Polshek Partnership Architects. A new
planetarium and hall devoted to cosmology is scheduled to open
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   For the American Museum of Natural History, today the world,
next year the universe.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Outcroppings of Films, Lectures and Tours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special activities are planned this weekend to celebrate the
opening Saturday of the David S. and Ruth L. Gottesman Hall of
Planet Earth at the American Museum of Natural History, Central
Park West at 79th Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth, Wind and Cinema,'' a series of films and videos, begins
Friday night at 7 and runs through Sunday; some of the filmmakers
will speak after the screenings. Admission for Friday night's
screenings is $4 a program, but is free Saturday and Sunday. Events
Saturday begin at 11 a.m. with a free outdoor celebration featuring
the ``eruption'' of a 10-foot volcano, followed by performances of
jazz, Dixieland, rock and Latin music, and magic and puppet shows
and juggling demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Unless noted, admission to all events is included in museum
admission: $8; $4.50 for children ages 2 to 12; $6 for students and
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Museum hours: Sundays through Thursdays, 10 a.m. to 5:45 p.m.;
Fridays and Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 8:45 p.m. Information: (212)
769-5100. Tickets: (212) 769-5200. Tour and lecture information:
(212) 769-5304. Here is a sampling of weekend events:
</P>
<P>
   Films
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM 1, with ``Rain'' (1929), a silent film directed by Joris
Ivens and Mannus Franken, and ``A Tale of the Wind'' (1988, French
with English subtitles), directed by Ivens and Marceline Loridan,
Friday night at 7.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM 2, with ``Frozen Heart'' (1998), by Stig Andersen and
Kenny Sanders, Friday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   FLEISCHER SUPERMAN CARTOONS (1942), featuring ``The Electric
Earthquake,'' ``The Arctic Giant'' and ``Volcano,'' Saturday at
11:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``JOURNEY TO THE CENTER OF THE EARTH'' (1959), by Henry Levin,
Saturday at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``EVEREST _ DEATH ZONE'' (1998), by David Breashears and Liesl
Clark, Saturday at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``STROMBOLI'' (1950, English with some Italian), by Roberto
Rossellini, Saturday at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``UMBRELLAS'' (1996), by Henry Corra, Grahame Weinbren and
Albert Maysles, Saturday at 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``MAN FALLING IN LAVA'' (1999), by Max Rosenthal, and ``THE DAY
THE EARTH MOVED'' (1997, Japanese with English subtitles), by
Toshio Goto, Sunday at 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``WILD RIVER'' (1960), by Elia Kazan, Sunday at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lectures
</P>
<P>
   ``BLACK SMOKER EXPEDITION,'' lecture by Edmond A. Mathez, chief
curator of the Gottesman Hall of Planet Earth, with screening of
the ``Nova'' film ``Volcanoes of the Deep.'' June 22 at 7 p.m.
Admission: $12; $10 for students, the elderly and museum members.
</P>
<P>
   ``PLANET EARTH VIDEO SERIES AND HALL VIEWING,'' Monday lectures
by Dr. Rosamond Kinzler, co-curator of the Gottesman Hall of Planet
Earth. Mondays through June 28, 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANTARCTIC GEOLOGY AND FOSSILS,'' a lecture by Scott G. Borg,
program director at the National Science Foundation. Wednesday
night at 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANTARCTIC METEORITES: SIFTING THE SANDS OF THE SOLAR SYSTEM,''
lecture by Ralph P. Harvey, assistant professor at Case Western
Reserve University. June 23 at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``GLACIOLOGY AND CLIMATE,'' lecture by Paul A. Mayewski, a
professor at the University of New Hampshire. June 30 at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``LIFE AT THE POLE,'' lecture by Helleary D. Everist, deputy
director at the National Science Foundation. July 7 at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tours
</P>
<P>
   ``ON THE TRAIL OF THE MANHATTAN SCHIST,'' a look at the Earth's
geological processes through an examination of rocks in Central
Park. July 8 at 5 and 7 p.m.. Fee: $12; $10 for students, the
elderly and museum members.
</P>
<P>
   ``BUILDING _ STONE GEOLOGY,'' an examination of the museum's
building stones followed by a discussion of mountain building, lost
seas and extinct animals. July 15 at 5 and 7 p.m. Fee: $12; $10 for
students, the elderly and museum members. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
