<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels) _ Lede-all: NATO General Secretary Javier
Solana announces bombing halt. Story will bring together aspects of
Serb troop withdrawals from Kosovo and NATO troop movements into
Yugoslavia. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton to address the
nation from the Oval office at 8 p.m. ET regarding the end of NATO
bombing and the agreement between NATO and Yugoslavia. By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ United Nations Security Council
takes up, and is expected to pass, Kosovo resolution. By Judith
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ U.S. and Russian representatives begin
to hash out the Russian role in the peacekeeping force in
Yugoslavia. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ The scene as Yugoslav
civilians weep, tremble and flee as Serb troops pull out. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan reports its economy grew by a
surprisingly robust 1.9 percent in the first three months of the
year, largely because of increased public spending. The increase in
gross domestic product is the first since the summer of 1997 and
baffles some economists, who doubt that the nation has actually
emerged from its longest recession since World War II. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
