   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NRA-WOES (Washington) _ After years of struggling with debt,
rebellions within its ranks and declining membership and revenues,
the National Rifle Association now finds itself under attack on
many fronts, from Congress to the courts. Despite its internal
woes, the NRA has been lavishing large campaign contributions on
its lawmaker allies at the federal and state levels.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS (Undated) _ A roaring economy, a demographic
boom, an increasingly sophisticated admission industry and the
widespread acceptance of the link between higher education and
personal success have raised the stakes for acceptance to the
nation's better colleges, and there is every indication that the
trend will intensify every year for the next 10. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES (Washington) _ The major airlines, trying to stave off
``passenger rights'' bills, say they will voluntarily adopt reforms
like providing food, water and toilets to passengers stranded on
snowbound airplanes; they also promise to tell customers about
known delays and cancellations, return misrouted luggage faster,
raise payments for lost luggage, and give customers who phone for
tickets a better chance at getting the lowest-cost fares. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
