<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-BARRY-SONNENFELD     06-10 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-BARRY-SONNENFELD-DIRECTS-WILD-WILD-WEST-ART-ADV21-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WALK ON THE WILD WILD SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Barry
Sonnenfeld directing Will Smith in a scene from ``Wild Wild
West.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Knife Guy. Helmet Head. Shovel Guy. Spike Head.
 &HT;    Barry Sonnenfeld couldn't believe the movie call sheet on the
wall.
 &HT;    ``I looked at it and thought, `What poor, pathetic guy has to
direct a movie with guys like that?''' Sonnenfeld says, laughing.
``Then I realized it was me.''
 &HT;    Sonnenfeld may feel pathetic, but he isn't poor _ having
pocketed substantial paydays for two ``Addams Family'' pictures and
a little something called ``Men in Black'' a couple of years ago.
And, as those titles would suggest, he's no stranger to the
outlandish, the weird or even the altogether ooky, either.
 &HT;    Shovel Guy and Spike Head couldn't be in better hands.
 &HT;    And their film, ``Wild Wild West,'' isn't looking bad itself.
Opening on June 30, the film reteams Sonnenfeld with ``MiB'' star
Will Smith for the big-screen, $100 million version of the
ultra-cool-for-its-day Robert Conrad television series of the same
name.
 &HT;    For those who may not have caught the show in reruns _ and it's
hard to find _ Smith stars as 19th-century secret agent James West,
while Kevin Kline plays Artemus Gordon, West's reluctant partner
and a master of disguise. Kenneth Branagh hams it up as the
villainous Dr. Arliss Loveless, with Salma Hayek adding heat as the
mysterious entertainer, Rita Escobar.
 &HT;    So what's up with Spike Head and his buddies?
 &HT;    ``I'm very comfortable with comedy and visual FX,'' Sonnenfeld
explains, ``but late in the game we decided we wanted to shoot a
sequence with Will in the belly of this 80-foot-tall mechanical
tarantula, a fight sequence with a bunch of Dr. Loveless's
henchmen.
 &HT;    ``I never thought I could pull off a big fight that involves a
certain amount of martial arts and a certain amount of people
slugging each other, with Will beating these four guys,'' the
director admits. ``I was afraid I wouldn't be able to, tonally,
make a big slugfest fit in with the rest of the movie.
 &HT;    ``Working with Will, we created a sequence that has tremendous
energy and fighting and chains and kicking and leaping but that,
tonally, is also incredibly funny and keeping within the context of
the character we created for Will,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``I never thought I'd be able to pull it out. It was a huge
challenge for me.''
 &HT;    Actually, the whole film seems pretty challenging. After all,
the television show on which it's based _ think James Bond meets
``Gunsmoke'' _ ended 30 years ago. A hot property it's not. And
it's not as if there's an obvious audience for your basic
sci-fi/spy/Western action/comedy/drama,
 &HT;    So why why ``West?''
 &HT;    ``Two reasons,'' Sonnenfeld booms by telephone from a Los
Angeles editing bay, where he's racing to complete ``West'' in time
for its opening.
 &HT;    ``Growing up, `Wild Wild West' was my favorite television
show,'' he recalls. ``I watched it, along with `Man from
U.N.C.L.E,' almost every week with my dad. For me, ``Wild Wild
West' was the perfect show. It had Bond and it had women with
cleavage, in dresses, who looked sexy.
 &HT;    ``Then I was at Sony one day talking to them about the marketing
of `Men in Black' and Will's partner, James Lasseter, came up to me
and said, `There's a ``Wild Wild West'' script floating around.
What would you think of doing it with Will?'''
 &HT;    Sonnenfeld chuckles at the memory.
 &HT;    ``I love working with Will,'' he says, ``and what he did for me
as it relates to `Wild Wild West' was to take something that had
been on television and flip it, twist it and make it feel quirky
and different from just a feature version of the show.
 &HT;    ``I got to do my favorite show with my favorite actor.''
 &HT;    OK, but what what is this thing? A comedy? A sci-fi epic? An
action/adventure?
 &HT;    The director thinks it's a ... well, actually, even he's not
sure.
 &HT;    ``The first time I showed it to Kevin, he and I were on an
airplane together,'' the 46-year-old Sonnenfeld says. ``I had a
cassette of the film in a very rough state. We got done watching
it, and Kevin said, `I've never seen a movie like this before.'
 &HT;    ``It's very hard to categorize,'' he says. ``It's sci-fi, sort
of. It's Jules Verne-like, in that we made sure that all the sci-fi
elements could exist in 1869.
 &HT;    ``That was a very cool challenge for (production designer) Bo
Welch and myself,'' he says excitedly. ``For this 80-foot, walking
tarantula, we desperately tried to make it look like it was burning
coal and leaking oil and was state-of-the-art for 1869. The idea
was to make it all seem as if you're watching a sci-fi film from
100 years ago.
 &HT;    ``The film is also funny,'' he adds, ``but sometimes comedy can
be the enemy of action _ and it's also full of action, which can
often be the enemy of comedy.
 &HT;    ``I hope _ I pray _ that somehow we've pulled off this synthesis
of genres.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Wild Wild West,'' consult the
film's official Website at www.wildwildwest.net. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
