<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0611-C     06-10 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: This story will be updated after President Clinton's speech
at 8 p.m. EDT.
 &HT;    CLINTON: FINISH THE JOB, BUILD THE PEACE IN KOSOVO, BALKANS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0611.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Grasping victory in one hand and fresh risks in the
other, President Clinton said Thursday that ``inhumanity'' was
defeated in Kosovo but additional costs must be borne to secure the
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past four months, we have seen some of the worst
inhumanity in our lifetime,'' Clinton said, referring to atrocities
and terror inflicted upon ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a moment of hope,'' Clinton told reporters at the
White House, less than two hours after U.S. and allied pilots
suspended air strikes against Yugoslavia after 78 days of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to finish the job,'' he said, ``and build the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracing the country for years of peacekeeping operations
involving thousands of U.S. troops, Clinton declined to set a date
certain for bringing American forces home from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put a timetable on it,'' Clinton said.
``We will define our objectives and proceed to implement them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear, though, that he expects Europe to bear the
lion's share of the costs of helping to rebuild the war-shattered
Balkans and knitting the region back into the fabric of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect that most of the money would come through
Europe, because most of the costs of this campaign, the air
campaign, have been borne by the United States,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't quarrel with that; we had the capacity, and we did
what we should have done,'' said Clinton. ``But I don't want us to
get into a haggling situation either,'' over how much countries
should pony up for Balkans reconstruction aid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Balkans recovery would be impeded so long as Serb
leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, remains in
power in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how Serbia can participate in that unless they
have a leadership that is committed to a multi-ethnic,
multi-religious democracy and to genuine democracy and human
rights,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The message was clear: Serbia, Yugoslavia's main republic, can
expect little assistance beyond basic humanitarian aid from the
United States and Europe until Milosevic leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Serb troops, police and paramilitary thugs
have forced more than a million ethnic Albanians to flee their
homes in Kosovo, Clinton said the U.S. peacekeeping commitment
there is open ended.
</P>
<P>
   That approach differed sharply from Clinton's pledge in December
1995 that U.S. peacekeepers would remain in Bosnia for only one
year. There are still 6,200 U.S. troops in Bosnia, part of a larger
NATO peacekeeping force there of some 31,000. There are no plans to
remove the force.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 U.S. troops are staging to deploy into Kosovo as part
of a larger NATO force expected to crest near 50,000 forces.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
