<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-10 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME': FAB, FUNNY, BUT SLIGHTLY
FADED
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may come a time when even Austin Powers tires of the words
``Oh, behave,'' but it isn't here yet. The sequel with the fab
title ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' is several love
beads short of its predecessor, but some of that was bound to
happen once Austin's novelty dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an oversupply of bathroom jokes and scattered scenes
that play like outtakes, this is still a crafty, intermittently
hilarious comedy that deserves its place alongside Bill, Ted,
Wayne, Garth, Ace, Mary and the Waterboy in the Smart-Stupid Hall
of Fame. Mike Myers' neo-Sellers multiple-personality act
guarantees that.
</P>
<P>
   In a cheerful hit-or-miss laugh-in that plays like ``The Three
Faces of Mike,'' Myers slips back into party mode as the happily
delusional nerd and hedonist of the title. He grins gamely once
again as the man who made bad teeth adorable and restored the word
``shag'' to its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   Myers wrote the screenplay with Michael McCullers for a
candy-colored, amiably slapdash film directed by Jay Roach.
</P>
<P>
   Even the credit sequence shows that this franchise's sense of
fun hasn't faded. Wearing nothing but his dead-animal chest pelt
while scampering through a hotel, Austin shields himself with
enough metaphorical edibles (two hams covering his posterior,
phallic anything, etc.) to recapture the first film's giddiness
immediately. It doesn't hurt that the very first thing on screen
here is a poke at ``Star Wars,'' with a couple of others waiting in
the wings.
</P>
<P>
   The new film nominally centers on the possible destruction of
Washington and a plot to steal Austin's mojo. (That term, as
loosely defined here, is whatever makes one sway when Marvin Gaye
sings ``Let's Get It On.'') But the real stealing comes from
Austin's nemesis and alter ego, Dr. Evil, who emerges again as
Myers' most inspired creation. If Austin is lovable for his wishful
studliness (``I put the  &UR; grrrr &LR;  in swinger, baby''), and for not
having any idea how nutty it is, Dr. Evil is an even more
recognizable bundle of neuroses. He's the peevish but endearing
villain who shows how easy it is to think like a large impatient
baby, whether bossing his underlings or plotting to rule the world.
</P>
<P>
   After the newlywed Austin is alarmed to find that his bride
(Elizabeth Hurley, in a brief, delicious cameo) can be made to
speak Spanish with a remote control, he reverts to his
man-of-the-world mode and winds up with Heather Graham's Felicity
Shagwell as his new companion. In hot pants or a macrame dress, Ms.
Graham also makes terrific eye candy, but she doesn't share Ms.
Hurley's quick-witted air of being in on the joke.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity, Austin and the 1969 Carnaby Street setting for much of
the film are essentially one-note inventions. (Incidentally, at 95
minutes, the film still has enough water-treading time for Burt
Bacharach and Elvis Costello to do a musical number in its swinging
London locale.)
</P>
<P>
   But the film's Dr. Evil scenes have more to work with. While
Seth Green plays an even funnier version of Dr. Evil's surly
teen-age son than he did the first time (the two turn up on a ``My
Father Is Evil, and He Wants to Take Over the World'' segment for
Jerry Springer), ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' also provides an added
element of sibling rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   It gives Dr. Evil a new favorite in the form of a tiny,
worshipful clone named Mini-Me (Verne J. Troyer) who wordlessly
mimics every Evil gesture, even that smirky way of making mock
quotation marks with his fingers. Dr. Evil, whose tantrums often
leave him hilariously tongue tied (``You're the Diet Coke of Evil!
Just one calorie! Not evil enough!''), naturally prefers the
slavish copy to the offspring who talks back.
</P>
<P>
   Uncanny as Myers can be while squaring off against himself in
Austin vs. Evil confrontations, he becomes even more so in the
id-like third persona of a drooling, loutish Scotsman. Pumped up to
Jabba the Hutt proportions by the Stan Winston Studio, this
scatological slob plays as perhaps a nightmarish overreaction to
too many viewings of ``Trainspotting,'' or just a gross-out gambit
to win the hearts of teen-age boys. Though Myers shows his
versatility from behind the blubber, the film's wit is not
heightened by the joke about the Scotsman's stool sample.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' mostly does a good job of paring down
and improving the first film's minor characters. Frau Farbissina
(Mindy Sterling), whose Yiddish name is perfect for her sourpuss
demeanor, is magically transformed into Dr. Evil's love slave
midway through the story. (``I can't let my feelings for you
interfere with my taking over the world,'' he tells her solemnly.
``You know that.'') The character named Mustafa (Will Ferrell)
remains accident prone.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Evil's sidekick No. 2 is again played by Robert Wagner
in present-day scenes, but he spends much of the film being Rob
Lowe in 1969. Lowe's deadpan impersonation of Wagner is one of the
film's sly little pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more sure-fire comic routines here, at least for the
film's target audience, is one in silhouette that has Austin and
Felicity horrifying onlookers with, among other things, a gerbil
and an umbrella. And presuming that nothing delights the true
Austin Powers fan more than a penis joke, the film has special fun
with synonyms. Cameo appearances by Woody Harrelson and Willie
Nelson come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jay Roach; written by Mike Myers and Michael
McCullers; director of photography, Ueli Steiger; edited by John
Poll and Debra Neil-Fisher; music by George S. Clinton; production
designer, Rusty Smith; produced by Suzanne Todd, Jennifer Todd,
Demi Moore, Eric McLeod, John Lyons and Myers; released by New Line
Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' is rated PG-13
(Parents strongly cautioned). It includes every dopey
double-entendre it can think of.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Mike Myers (Austin Power/Dr. Evil), Heather Graham
(Felicity Shagwell), Michael York (Basil Exposition), Robert Wagner
(No.r 2), Seth Green (Scott Evil), Mindy Sterling (Frau
Farbissina), Will Ferrell (Mustafa), Rob Lowe (Young No. 2), Gia
Carides (Robin Swallows), Verne J. Troyer (Mini-Me), Woody
Harrelson (Himself), Willie Nelson (Himself) and Elizabeth Hurley
(Vanessa).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
