<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-10 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOAB IS MY WASHPOT': A REBELLIOUS YOUNG WEED, AND HOW HE GREW
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(fb) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his best-selling first novel, ``The Liar'' (1993), Stephen
Fry created an antic portrait of a feckless schoolboy named Adrian
Healey who is described, quite admiringly it must be said, as ``a
fraud, a charlatan and a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar self-portrait emerges in Fry's enormously entertaining
new autobiography, ``Moab Is My Washpot,'' which chronicles the
first 20 years of his life, from his childhood in rural England
through his departure for Cambridge University in 1977. One
schoolmaster describes him as ``feckless, fickle, flamboyant and
evasive.'' Another says, ``for colossal nerve, for sheer, ruddy
cheek, I have never met anyone to match you.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Stephen, we quickly learn, is brilliant, bookish and
rebellious, the sort of teen-ager who can complete the London Times
crossword puzzle faster than most adults, likes to memorize the
Guinness Book of Records for fun and routinely torments his
teachers with willfully smart-aleck questions. He also happens to
be a compulsive thief whose penchant for pilfering candy and pocket
money gives way to a wild spending spree fueled by stolen credit
cards. The prank will land the 18-year-old Fry in jail and
temporarily derail his academic career.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fry points out that ``the story of a sensitive young
weed struggling to grow up in the robust thicket of an English
public school'' was ``done to death, in the earlier part of this
century in novels, memoirs and autobiographies,'' his own account
of his schoolboy travails is so engaging, so idiosyncratic, so
larky, as he might say, that the reader never for a moment feels a
sense of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   In fact ``Washpot'' bears about the same resemblance to the
conventional memoir as ``Tristram Shandy'' does to the traditional
novel: Fry does not merely employ digressions as a narrative
technique; he positively revels in them as a minor art form.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he sounds like a chatty talk show guest, discussing
the future of the monarchy (he thinks it's worth keeping, because
without it ``Britain would suddenly have no absurd minor blemish to
blame for its failures'') and the seniority system in English
public schools (``No one in life, not the wartiest old dame in
Arles, not the wrinkledest, stoopingest Cossack, not the
pony-tailedest, venerablest old Mandarin in China, not Methuselah
himself, will ever be older than a group of seniors at school'').
At other times he plays the philosopher, musing about the
relationship between sex and love and explicating E.M. Forster's
observation that the English suffer from ``undeveloped hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the dominant voice in this book _ as in Fry's novels
(``The Liar,'' ``The Hippopotamus'') and acting performances
(``Peter's Friends,'' ``Jeeves and Wooster'') _ is comic, by turns
insolent and witty, ribald and pugnacious, but Fry also
demonstrates his ability to write earnestly about the
transgressions of his youth and his youthful crushes. Indeed much
of the narrative tension in this memoir springs from the contrast
between the two Frys who appear in its pages _ the young Fry (or
``small Fry,'' as he might put it), who seemed to bounce from one
misadventure to another, like a ricocheting ball in a pinball
machine; and the older Fry, who shakes his head in chagrin and
bemusement at his earlier self.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many American memoirists, Fry does not psychoanalyze
himself or his parents, nor does he blame the things that happened
to him as a boy (being shipped off to boarding school at the age of
8, being beaten by teachers and violated by a schoolmate) for his
later run-ins with the law. His reminiscences are animated not by
anger or indignation, but by a genial sense of regret, his
portraits informed by an elegiac if irreverent nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   He draws a lovely, gently shaded portrait of his childhood in
rural England, conjuring up a world of badminton lawns, old family
retainers and crumbling Victorian houses with dubious plumbing (the
bottom of the water tank ``had been alive with bright red
nematodes''). He describes his mother as being ``more cheerful than
Pickwick, Pollyanna and Mrs. Tiggywinkle on a sunny day in
Happyville''; his father, as possessing a Sherlock Holmes-like
mind, combining ``dreamy abstraction with ruthless logic and an
infinite capacity for taking pains.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the young Fry, he comes across as a painfully
self-conscious boy, an outsider by virtue of his physical
awkwardness and self-loathing as well as his Jewishness and
homosexuality, a skinny, underdeveloped boy who was terrified of
showering with the other boys after sports, who was terrified of
having to sing in music class. All this ``wretched 13-year-old''
had, he writes now, was ``his anger, his fury, his verbal
arrogance, his pride,'' and so he learned to use words as a means
of saving himself ``from bullying, mockery and rejection.''
</P>
<P>
   Fry's account of his progression through a series of boarding
schools, his sad-funny reminiscences of his discovery of love, his
memories of childhood humiliations (having his dead mole upstaged
by a live donkey during a classroom show-and-tell presentation) and
childhood triumphs (stealing some sweets from a drawer in the
headmaster's study), his rapturous discovery of literature and his
more tentative discovery of sex, all combine to make an engagingly
rueful memoir and to whet the reader's appetite for the sequel that
will presumably bring the author's life up to date.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``MOAB IS MY WASHPOT'
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Fry.
</P>
<P>
   366 pages. Random House. $24
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
