<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-LOITERING-HNS &LR;      06-10 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-LOITERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TELLS ANTI-LOITERING LAW TO MOVE ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court on Thursday struck down a
Chicago anti-loitering law targeted at breaking the grip of street
gangs on inner-city neighborhoods, ruling that the ordinance failed
to explain to those arrested what they were doing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 law, which resulted in more than 45,000 arrests in the
three years it was enforced, permitted police to arrest not only
suspected gang members, but also anyone else who, standing with
``no apparent purpose'' on a public street near a gang member,
defied a police order to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to imagine how a Chicagoan standing in a
public place with a group of people would know if he or she had an
`apparent purpose,''' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M.
Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, Kennedy and Breyer wrote separate opinions explaining
their views.
</P>
<P>
   The court's 6-3 ruling was consistent with several Supreme Court
decisions from the 1970s that ended or severely curtailed vagrancy
and loitering laws that were once common in American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court's rejection of the Chicago ordinance, law
enforcement and municipal government associations said the
differing opinions of the justices left open the possibility that a
less vague law could pass constitutional scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State Solicitor Edward B. ``Ned' Foley, who helped write a
friend-of-court brief for the city of Chicago, pointed out that
O'Connor's opinion ``laid out a blueprint'' that would allow a
different version of the law to be found constitutional. He added
that Breyer agreed with that blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want loitering laws to be more defined, and that's a
whole different ballgame than saying they shouldn't exist,'' Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, O'Connor said a better definition for the term
``loiter'' might be lingering in one spot ``with no apparent
purpose other than to establish control over identifiable areas, to
intimidate others from entering those areas, or to conceal illegal
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Chicago defined loitering as ``remaining in any one
place with no apparent purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois Supreme Court struck down the law in 1997, calling
it an ``arbitrary restriction on personal liberties'' and ruling
that it gave police officers too much discretion in deciding
whether there had been a violation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court affirms the state
court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said the court recognized the ``serious and difficult''
problems faced by Chicago citizens in their fight against street
gangs but believed that the city had gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this instance, the city has enacted an ordinance that
affords too much discretion to the police and too little notice to
citizens who wish to use the public streets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the court's only Chicago native, said the law allowed
police to tell people to move on without asking why they were
standing around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It matters not whether the reason that a gang member and his
father, for example, might loiter near Wrigley Field is to rob an
unsuspecting fan or just to get a glimpse of Sammy Sosa leaving the
ballpark,'' he said, referring to the Chicago Cubs' homerun hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In either, if their purpose is not apparent to a nearby police
officer, she (the officer) may _ indeed, she `shall' _ order them
to disperse.''
</P>
<P>
   In unusually strong words, Justice Antonin Scalia disagreed with
the majority opinion, calling it ``simply wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Chicago have decided that depriving themselves
of the freedom to `hang out' with a gang member is necessary to
eliminate pervasive gang crime and intimidation _ and that the
elimination of the one is worth the deprivation of the other,''
said Scalia, who was joined by Chief Justice William Rehnquist and
Justice Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, 31 states, the National League of
Cities, U.S. Mayors Conference and National Governors Association
sided with Chicago and urged the court to reinstate the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The law's opponents included the NAACP and other civil rights
groups, the National Law Center on Homelessness and Poverty and the
National Black Police Association.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
