<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCAINE-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      06-10 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCAINE-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN GETS 60 YEARS FOR GIVING DAUGHTER COCAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ A Texas jury, deciding in a
precedent-setting verdict that cocaine is a deadly weapon,
convicted a man late Wednesday of giving the narcotic to his
teen-age daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors in Comal County returned the verdict in less than an
hour and sentenced Johnny Rodriguez, 43, of New Braunfels, to 60
years in prison and ordered him to pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was announced, Rodriguez's sister, Margaret
Cabell, sent the daughter sobbing from the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you are happy ... sending your father to prison,''
Cabell called after her.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old daughter testified that her father gave her
cocaine when she was 14. The testimony was key to the case.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time Texas prosecutors have sought a finding
that cocaine is a deadly weapon _ a decision they expect to be
appealed. If it's upheld, the case could mean enhanced penalties in
other drug trials.
</P>
<P>
   Use of a deadly weapon in the commission of a crime carries
stiffer penalties in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Comal County District Attorney Dib
Waldrip told jurors in this community northwest of San Antonio:
``We have an opportunity today to close a loophole in the law and
at the same time close the manhole cover on the sewer of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldrip said that to find that cocaine was a deadly weapon,
jurors only had to agree that the drug ``in the manner of its use
is capable of causing death or serious bodily injury.''
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, the daughter said her father gave her cocaine
20 to 30 times between January and September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt secure because I was around him, and he was my dad, so
I did it,'' she said. ``At first I liked it, because my dad gave it
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She appeared to carefully avoid making eye contact with her
father during her testimony. She stayed calm nearly the entire
time, only choking a couple times, especially when she told the
jury she still loves her father.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Brent Free characterized Rodriguez's daughter as
a liar who used drugs, who was suspended from school and who was
kicked out of a drug rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   Free said the girl made up the story at the prompting of
Rodriguez's former wife, the girl's mother, to get back at him for
not paying child support.
</P>
<P>
   Free also said common sense would lead to the conclusion that
cocaine wasn't a deadly weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere delivery of a controlled substance is not the use of
a deadly weapon,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   By ruling that a deadly weapon was used, the jury ensured that
Rodriguez will have to serve at least half his sentence before
being eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Without that finding, he would have to serve one-quarter of his
sentence, and possibly less if he received credit for good behavior
while in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
