<HEADER>
A0559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-10 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CRITICS RECOMMEND :
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word `star' in parens should be replaced by the symbol.) 
(dw) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. The word ``star'' denotes a highly recommended film
or series. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``BESIEGED,'' starring Thandie Newton and David Thewlis.
Directed by Bernardo Bertolucci (R, 92 minutes). Like all
Bertolucci films, this love story of an expatriate African woman
(Ms. Newton), fleeing an oppressive military regime, and the
reclusive British pianist ( Thewlis) for whom she works as a
housekeeper in Rome is a visual jewel. Based on a short story by
James Lasdun, ``Besieged'' is a film of few words and powerful
images _ especially of a military coup in a poor African country.
The love is sealed through an extraordinary act of self-sacrifice
and a deepening appreciation of each other's tastes in music. If
this elliptical movie leaves too much unsaid, it has strong
understated performances by its two stars (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB,'' with Ibrahim Ferrer,
Compay Segundo and Ry Cooder. Directed by Wim Wenders (not rated,
106 minutes). When the American guitarist and producer Ry Cooder
assembled a group of all-but-forgotten Cuban musicians to record an
album, no one expected that the record would become a phenomenon,
selling more than a million copies worldwide and revitalizing the
Cuban music scene. Wenders' ebullient documentary follows the group
on tour from Amsterdam to New York and includes interviews with the
group's main members. The music pulsates, and the pictures of
Havana compare the city's grand but faded architecture with the
musicians' weatherbeaten faces (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``ELECTION,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Matthew Broderick and Reese
Witherspoon. Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the
acerbically funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic
satire of the American electoral process in a high school setting.
Its leading candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms.
Witherspoon, has a mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from
Connie Chung and Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless
good-guy teacher who thinks this wicked little front-runner needs
to be stopped. And Chris Klein plays Tracy's reluctant opponent in
a style best described as early Keanu. With a lovely ear for
hypocritical conversation, the screenplay specializes in keeping
all the characters a few beats off what they actually mean (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) &UR;  &LR; ``ENTRAPMENT,'' starring Sean Connery and Catherine
Zeta-Jones. Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy
caper summons the days when being a thief was the profession of
choice among debonair movie heroes. Heroines: As the great-looking
insurance investigator who is supposedly investigating Connery's
glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones makes a smashing gymnast
and heist expert in her own right. No need to believe the
outlandish details of the story; there's enough verve and charisma
to the stars to make the escapade easy on the eyes. The action
sequence, in which the stars hang off the side of the world's
largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper. Here's a nice
bonus: Nobody gets killed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``ETERNITY AND A DAY,'' &UR;  &LR;  starring Bruno Ganz. Directed
by Theo Angelopoulos (not rated, 132 minutes). Winner of the Palme
d'Or at last year's Cannes International Film Festival, this
dreamy, lulling film is the haunting poetic valedictory of a man
spending his last day on earth. As his memory leads him across the
landscape of his life, Ganz's soulful Greek writer drifts through
his past as he seeks his life's meaning. The film's visual style is
less magnificently grandiose than the director's ``Ulysses' Gaze,''
but it roams from mood to mood with a fluid, liberating assurance.
It's a style that's both trance-inducing and filled with
unutterable emotion (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``LIMBO,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio and
David Strathairn. Directed by John Sayles (R, 126 minutes). Part
survivalist drama, part satirical portrait of contemporary Alaska,
Sayles' powerful new film is almost as vast as the great outdoors
it contemplates. Ms. Mastrantonio, as a well-traveled folk-rock
singer working Alaskan lounges, and Strathairn, as the brooding
local fisherman with whom she becomes involved, make one of the
most compelling adult couples to be seen in an American film in
quite some time. When they find themselves castaways along with her
teen-age daughter on a remote Alaskan island, the movie becomes
both a suspense thriller and a sorrowful meditation on survivalism,
civilization and the ties that bind. Though marred by an abrupt
ending and glaring literary devices, ``Limbo'' is eminently
worthwhile (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE LOSS OF SEXUAL INNOCENCE,'' starring Julian Sands,
Femi Ogunbanjo and Hanne Klintoe. Written and directed by Mike
Figgis (R, 101 minutes). Figgis' visually ravishing cinematic tone
poem retells the Adam and Eve story (Adam is black and Eve is
white), interspersing it with semi-autobiographical reveries of the
director's early childhood in Kenya and his teen-age and adult
years in northern England. The strands are drawn together in a
final scene of violence and betrayal set at a film shoot in Tunisia
and reminiscent of Antonioni's film ``The Passenger.'' The film is
moody verging on melancholy, the storytelling elliptical, its view
of eroticism menacing rather than joyful. Though marred by
pretentious symbolism and an overall vagueness, this film has many
spellbinding moments (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MATRIX,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Keanu Reeves and Laurence Fishburne.
Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120 minutes). The
time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will be all but
incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the film borrows
unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with a big debt
to ``The X-Files'' in the paranoia department. But the storytelling
is intricately bizarre and the special effects are indeed special,
notably when it comes to midair martial arts with a gravity-defying
gusto. And Reeves shows that you can look like a Prada model while
behaving like an action hero. One of the main stars here is Bill
Pope, the cinematographer. He and the Wachowskis provide a
couch-potato epiphany; while the characters seem to be performing
marvelous feats, they're often lying stock-still in the grip of
virtual reality (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
