<P>
   POWERS-SOUNDTRACK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Nobody, and I mean nobody, is looking forward to the
second Austin Powers movie, ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' more than I
am. I plan to be there the day it opens, first showing, popcorn and
soft drink in hand, ready to settle in, laugh at Austin's teeth
(again!) and hear him purr ``Yeah, baby!'' (again!) and swoon over
Heather Graham _ ready to, well, have at least as good a time as I
had with the first one. And maybe the music on this 12-cut
soundtrack will work within the context of scenes in the movie.
Sure hope so, 'cause it sure doesn't work on its own. By DAVE
FERMAN. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LIMBO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Writer-director John Sayles, the first of the indie
film heroes, knows what to do with actresses. He gives Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio one of the best parts of her career in his
newest film, ``Limbo.'' She plays Donna, a down-on-her-luck lounge
singer who drags her teen-age daughter, Noelle (Vanessa Martinez),
with her whenever she feels the need to relocate. This time, it's
to a small Alaska town, called Port Henry, given its full natural
glory by cinematographer Haskell Wexler. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story
has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
