NYT-06-10-99 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     06-10 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Undated:: virtual reality (Maslin).  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Kevin Kline and
Michelle Pfeiffer. Directed by Michael Hoffman (PG-13, 115
minutes). This is potluck Shakespeare, with a wildly uneven range
of performances and no clear style holding them together. Rather
than wonder why the actors are wrestling with bicycles in
19th-century Tuscany (a setting used much less enchantingly than it
might have been), it's best to focus on the most comfortably
Shakespearean performances and not wonder what Ms. Flockhart is
doing here. Kline makes a perfect Bottom, Everett slinks
seductively through Oberon's role and Ms. Pfeiffer makes an
appropriately gorgeous fairy queen. The younger cast members are
largely used as window dressing for the Leo-Does-Romeo set
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MUMMY,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes). More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent
spoof (very loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror
classic), overloaded with cheesy special effects, suggests an
unwieldy hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and
Costello Meet the Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.'' The
intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that
carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the Foreign Legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed
English librarian) and Hannah (as her twitty older brother). It's
all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve swarming
scarabs that burrow under the skin and do awful ``Alien''-like
things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``NOTTING HILL,'' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant.
Directed by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic
notion here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts
might be out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to
bring her together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome echoes
of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright, winsome
romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters themselves,
inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's burdens of being
world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' &UR;  &LR;  starring Joseph Fiennes and
Gwyneth Paltrow. Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty,
sexy and merrily literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever
premise that only gets better as the film unfolds. The screenplay,
originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard
into razor-sharp dialogue, dares to imagine whatever it likes about
the link between Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad
yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile, this
tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an Elizabethan theater
fraught with the same backbiting and conniving we enjoy today and
has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo and Juliet,''
glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous
duo, and she gives the first great, fully realized starring
performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,'' &UR;  &LR; starring
Liam Neeson. Directed by George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes).
Stripped of hype and breathless expectations, Lucas' first
installment offers a happy surprise: it's up to snuff. It sustains
the gee-whiz spirit of the series and offers a swashbuckling
extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions that are even more
plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of ``Jurassic Park.''
While the human stars here are indeed reduced to playing action
figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and hordes of
crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in Lucas is
given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier and
scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Dame
Maggie) who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously
relish chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted
from a chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of
English expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War
II. Dame Maggie, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of
the pack, nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are
shattered when the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves
carted off to another city where they are held under house arrest.
Cher is her usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving
wealthy American heiress and art collector who befriends the group
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (star) ``THE WINSLOW BOY,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca
Pidgeon and Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G,
110 minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's
trial that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down
to its essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played
with unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it
works as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family
of a cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the
consequences of that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography
is beautifully lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch
acting style sets the film's tone and gives her suffragist
character a sharp edge (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``MAD MASQUERADE: VALENTINO, FAIRBANKS, BARRYMORE AND CHANEY IN
THE JAZZ AGE.'' It's back to the jazz age, silent films, piano
accompaniments and stars like Rudolph Valentino, Douglas Fairbanks,
John Barrymore and Lon Chaney in this series, which begins tomorrow
at the American Museum of the Moving Image. Billed as a
retro-retrospective, the series, which runs through June 27,
examines the evolution of the screen image of these stars by means
of a dozen movies that span the years from 1915 to 1928. Among them
are ``The Lamb'' (1915), starring Fairbanks, which opens the series
at 2 p.m. Saturday, followed at 4:30 by ``Dr. Jekyll and Hyde''
(1920), starring Barrymore. Other films in the series include ``The
Sheik'' (1921), with Valentino; ``He Who Gets Slapped'' (1924) and
``Phantom of the Opera'' (1925), both with Chaney, and ``The Three
Musketeers'' (1921) and ``The Thief of Bagdad'' (1924), both with
Fairbanks. The series is based on ``The Mad Masquerade: Stardom and
Masculinity in the Jazz Age,'' by the film historian Gaylyn
Studlar, who will introduce ``The Lamb.'' Admission: $8.50 for
adults; $5.50 for those over 65 and students with ID; $4.50 for
children from 5 to 18, and free to children under 4. Information:
(718) 784-0077.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-COMMERCE11-COX     06-10 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET ECONOMY BEATS EXPECTATIONS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The booming domestic Internet economy now rivals or
exceeds the revenues of such veteran sectors as autos, energy
utilities and telecommunications, a major academic study concluded
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study estimates that the Internet economy grew by 174
percent a year between 1995 and 1998 to reach $301 billion, at the
same time that the nation's gross domestic product was expanding at
a compounded annual rate of 2.8 percent to reach $7.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers concluded that the U.S. domestic Internet
economy ``by itself is one of the major economies in the world.''
If it were a nation, it would rank just behind Switzerland and
ahead of Argentina in terms of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than a decade we've done what other industries have
done in 100 years,'' said John Chambers, chief executive officer of
Cisco Systems Inc., a major provider of Internet routing equipment
that sponsored the path-breaking University of Texas survey.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas researchers said they compiled their results by
observing 3,100 U.S. companies that generate all or part of their
revenues from Internet products or services.
</P>
<P>
   As defined by the researchers, the Internet economy is made up
of companies that directly generate all or some part of their
revenues from Internet-related products and services, such as
Cisco, Dell Computer and IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   To this group, they added both pure Internet sellers such as
Amazon.com and eToys.com, and also measured the cyberspace business
of such traditional firms as L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   The team found that electronic commerce, the most readily
visible component of the Internet economy, generated $102 billion
of revenue in the United States in 1998. It also estimated that the
average revenue per Internet employee was $250,000 last year,
against an overall U.S. average of $160,000 for non-Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The $301 billion overall value placed on the Internet economy
contrasts favorably with autos (at $350 billion),
telecommunications ($270 billion) and utilities ($223 billion) but
still does not come close to rivaling the banking sector at $7.9
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Commerce Department said it will begin
tracking annual consumer sales across the Internet. But the figures
from last year's activity will not be available until mid-2000.
Earlier studies placed current Internet sales at about 1 per cent
of all retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   With the promise of continued financing from Cisco, the research
team plans to create a quarterly index of the Internet economy and
to expand their survey to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers said he had been trotting around the globe lately in an
effort to show top government and business leaders how the Internet
is rapidly transforming their own economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've recently met with (British Prime Minister) Tony Blair and
(Chinese President) Jiang Zemin,'' Chambers noted. ``Four years
ago, when I traveled abroad, I'd consider myself fortunate if I
could get a few minutes with a company's chief information
officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Cisco's fortunes have risen to a current market
capitalization of some $175 billion, placing it as the fastest
growing firm ever to be listed on the Nasdaq exchange. Such
reserves proved more than ample to underwrite the work Andrew
Whinston and Anitesh Burua, two senior professors from the
University of Texas Graduate School of Business, who came here from
Austin to present their findings.
</P>
<P>
   The complete University of Texas study appears on line at
http://www.internetindicators.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1711EDT &QL; 
