<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-TEAMS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TEAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR STRANGLEHOLD: EIGHT TEAMS DOMINATING RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CAR-NASCAR-KENSETH) 
(mk) 
 BY PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ask the people who promote NASCAR, most will tell you
this has been a competitive Winston Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   They can quote stats like nine different winners in 13 events,
35 different cars that have led laps, and a margin of victory that
averages out to just over a second in most races.
</P>
<P>
   But numbers don't always tell the whole story. While the numbers
imply that most races turn into heated battles, that is not always
the case.
</P>
<P>
   If there is competition, it is a competition among the few,
especially when it comes to winning.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, and over the last three in particular,
eight teams and drivers have dominated Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And while there is evidence that some, like Rusty Wallace, Dale
Earnhardt and Terry Labonte, are slipping, for the most part, these
eight teams rule.
</P>
<P>
   They are the cars driven by Jeff Burton, Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon,
Dale Jarrett, Bobby Labonte, Terry Labonte, Mark Martin and
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has won the Winston Cup three times, 1995, '97 and '98;
Terry Labonte won in 1996; and Jarrett is leading this year.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, seven of the eight are in the top eight in points.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, five of the eight finished in the top eight. In 1996,
six of the eight were in the top eight in points and in 1997 and
1998 seven of the eight were in the top eight, with Wallace ninth
in '97 and Terry Labonte ninth in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the last three years, when Burton came of age
after joining Jack Roush's multicar team in 1996, this group has
had a stranglehold on Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, these eight drivers have won 12 of the 13
races.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, they won 30 of 33, and in 1996, they won 27 of 32.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the group itself, over the last three years there
has been a dominant clique of four _ Gordon, Burton, Jarrett and
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   That group has won eight of the 13 races so far, and between
them, the foursome has won 57 of 78 races since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, still a tigerish competitor at 40, says you could break
it down even more this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just coincidence that it's been more competitive,''
Martin said. ``Gordon has had problems in a number of races he
could have won and didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burton won three and could have won more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could easily have been the Jeff Gordon and Jeff Burton
show, but it hasn't, and that's good for the sport,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, another veteran who has not been quite as strong as he
once was but who still seems determined to battle with the best,
says it's difficult to jump into Winston Cup and become a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting a team is nothing,'' Wallace said. ``Getting a team
and buying equipment is one thing, but your key thing is the engine
deal and your driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only drivers that are consistently successful are the
drivers that know how to tell their crew chiefs what to do with
their car and guide them along.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said Gordon has ``this unbelievable communication'' with
his crew chief, Ray Evernham. ``Gordon could just blink his eye and
Evernham knows what he means,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of relationship I used to have with Jimmy
Makar when I first started and now I feel I'm pretty close to that
with my guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing the relationship between the driver and the crew
chief, along with the chassis guy, is the toughest thing in the
world,'' Wallace declared.
</P>
<P>
   Makar is now Bobby Labonte's crew chief and supervising a
two-car team that features Labonte and Tony Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a rookie, Stewart is one of a few drivers who may
succeed in breaking the stranglehold of the elite eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a very capable effort from Stewart and Bobby
Labonte,'' Martin said, ``but it's still pretty much like any other
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COREA-RECORD-REVIEW-N     06-10 0255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COREA-RECORD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHANGE': A NEW BAND INVIGORATES CHICK COREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no question that Chick Corea's recently formed band,
Origin, has invigorated him. There's so much and so many different
kinds of jazz writing on ``Change'' (Stretch/Concord), his new
album that it sounds like a competitive young band leader angling
for his first precious shot of attention, rather than a figure who
has been well known for 30 years and weathered one conceptual
overhaul after another.
</P>
<P>
   Origin _ a New York crew including the saxophonists Steve Wilson
and Bob Sheppard, the bassist Avishai Cohen, the trombonist Steve
Davis and the drummer Jeff Ballard _ is precise, relentlessly
playful with melody and rhythmically alert as it negotiates the
tango, flamenco, blues and splintered-melody mazes. (One number,
``L.A. Scenes,'' sounds like a cross between Eric Dolphy and
particularly evocative crime-film soundtrack music.) The structure
of many of the arrangements is staggered: A quiet, pedaled solo
piano passage segues into a saxophone-trombone duet that leads to a
line for double-bass and bass clarinet.
</P>
<P>
   A result is that the tunes create their own forward motion,
never stalling in the round-robin soloing that bedevils so much
mainstream jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Corea gets his say, though, especially in the trio ballad
``Compassion,'' and in uptempo pieces his fluid, skating lines skid
to a shuddering stop on dark chords. It's smart, exacting music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-KENSETH-NY     06-10 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-KENSETH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENSETH READIES FOR WINSTON MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CAR-NASCAR-TEAMS) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth has made his choice. Now, he can only hope it's the
right one.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, 27, has announced he will move from the Busch Series to
Winston Cup next year in a car owned by Jack Roush and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Almost up to the final minute, General Motors worked hard to
keep Kenseth, now in a Chevy, from defecting to Roush and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, three Winston Cup car owners, including
Richard Childress and Joe Gibbs, made a run at Kenseth in an effort
to lure him away from Roush.
</P>
<P>
   But in part because Martin has become a mentor to him, Kenseth
stuck to his earlier commitment.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt Kenseth will succeed in Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Some say he is, potentially, a better driver than his good
friend Dale Earnhardt Jr., who will also move full time to Winston
Cup in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. Kenseth will make the jump without the
kind of scrutiny, or the kind of pressure, that will fall on Little
E.
</P>
<P>
   That should help.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he made the right decision by joining Roush, though,
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, it can be argued that Roush owns the top Ford
multicar team. It can also be argued that he owns the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Roush runs five cars, with at least one, driven by
Kevin Lepage, in danger of losing its sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the five Roush cars, two, driven by Martin and
Jeff Burton under the charge of Buddy Parrott, run extremely well,
while the other three don't perform at all.
</P>
<P>
   Because Martin is Roush's top driver and because he has a stake
in the Kenseth operation, one would think Kenseth will get the kind
of help he needs to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no guarantees. While in theory, the five Roush
entries all have equal access to parts and information, clearly,
they do not work together.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Coca-Cola 600 recently, Burton made the
following comment while talking about rivals Bobby Labonte and Tony
Stewart:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have helped that team become better by being an
example of how a two-car team can operate,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, plans are for Kenseth to be housed with one of
Roush's other cars, not Martin and Burton.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps his association with Martin will ensure that he will
not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   That will be critical, because by itself, doing well in the
Busch Series has not guaranteed success at the Winston Cup level,
and unless Kenseth gets the best Roush has to offer he is going to
struggle, no matter how much potential he has.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOAH-THEATER-REVIEW-N     06-10 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOAH-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SERMON IN THE SLUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Logorrhea isn't just a word in a spelling bee.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the term that describes the condition that reduces
the preachy and artistically questionable ``Noah's Archives'' to
sludge.
</P>
<P>
   Playing through June 26 at the Ohio Theater in SoHo, this
sophomoric play by Stephen Spoonamore is an enterprise of Ransom
Productions, whose publicity describes it as a nonprofit theater
company that uses corporate money to finance consciousness-raising
theatrical productions and turns over the proceeds to active
grass-roots organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In this case the beneficiary is said to be Riverkeeper, an
organization devoted to protecting the ecological integrity of the
Hudson River watershed by tracking down and stopping polluters.
</P>
<P>
   With a pedigree like that, little wonder that ``Noah's
Archives,'' directed by Darcy Marta, plays like a clumsy
infomercial whose underlying message is ``Be good to planet
Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially the play is a story of the second coming of Noah's
Ark. A flood that sweeps away the 20th-century characters for more
than three years aboard an ark with Noah, his son Shem and a
menagerie of 36,341 species of unseen creatures serves as the
medium for telling audiences to cast aside selfish concerns and
preserve the environment.
</P>
<P>
   This long-winded sermon, which taps the talents of actors who
deserve better but never invests its ideas with genuine drama or
intellectual conflict, begins in a Canal Street bar on a rainy
night.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the gathering storm comes a motley crowd, including Shem
and his shaggy father, as well as a group of young women and men,
all without dates. Through the first act these characters deliver
what might be construed as philosophical stand-up comedy routines
about their sex lives, if wit or humor graced the monologues.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally Shem reveals himself as a man with a past and
relates the history of Canal Street (a canal filled in with old
arks, he says), and at the end of the first act, as the storm
gathers intensity and the characters pair off, the bar is swept
away on the rising waters.
</P>
<P>
   In the second act, with all the women pregnant, the war between
the sexes still raging and the bar-as-ark adrift and leaking
dangerously, Shem is still expounding on ecological perils and now
trying as well to read God's mind.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, a three-piece band furnishes interludes of
lively music.
</P>
<P>
   Like the band on ``Titanic,'' these musicians can't save
``Noah's Archives'' from sinking.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NOAH'S ARCHIVES'  &QL; 
By Stephen Spoonamore; directed by Darcy Marta; sets by Andy
Warfel; lighting by Robert Williams; costumes by Moira L.
Shaughnessy; sound by Eric DeArmon; production stage manager,
Jemima Godsall. Presented by Ransom Productions and Cold
Productions. At the Ohio Theater.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Tim Moore (Noah), Lydia Fiore (Bartender and Nebekenezer),
William Peden (Shem), Caroline Strong (Buns, Captain Steel and
Judith), Lisa Thayer (Nips and Sarah), Lou Carbonneau (A-Train and
Adam), Gregory Norman Cruz (Numbers and Cane) and Tracy Christian
(Giggles and Eve).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
