<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOREDOMS-MUSIC-REVIEW     06-10 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOREDOMS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOREDOMS: PROFUNDITY VIA REPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Boredoms, from Osaka, Japan, were
semi-demi-famous in the early 1990s for playing miniatures _
writhing, howling, spasmic, cartoon art-punk built on split-second
timing. But even the most outre rock band in the world has become
more patient with age: It's now after continuity and profundity,
and the Boredoms have figured out that repetition is the quickest
route to the profound in popular music.
</P>
<P>
   The band's remarkable set at the South Street Seaport Atrium on
Wednesday night, part of the Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival, operated
like gospel music at its most urgent: It set up a short chant over
a sea of rhythm, repeating it endlessly, bringing the energy level
up higher and higher until you thought it had to stop or mutate.
But the chant continued. And continued. And continued.
</P>
<P>
   The set began with organ tones, and the drummer Yoshimi chanted
a phrase, sitting between two other drummers (one with the standard
drums replaced by congas and bongos); the singer Yamantaka Eye
answered her. Suddenly, all three drummers hit their cymbals
together and began to pound out a two-beat rhythm in lock step; the
pieces rocked back and forth between two chords, with the bassist
and guitarist seesawing their parts.
</P>
<P>
   Eye used to flail his rail-thin body around in a kind of parody
of martial arts movement; on Wednesday, under a long tangle of
dreadlocks, he stayed in one place and shook. He raised his eyes
prayerfully to the ceiling and then lowered them back to the crowd,
positioned next to a table of electronic effects to modulate his
voice, and chanted short-syllable words swathed in echo. The first
mesmerizing piece lasted 40 minutes; later moments had similarity
to the Grateful Dead's ``Space'' concert interludes and the
chugging bliss of German art-rock from the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   These were simple formulas similar to what is heard on the
band's most recent album, ``Super Ae'' (Birdman), and the band put
everything into making it work.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding the Boredoms was an off-the-cuff improvised set by
John Zorn on saxophone, Fred Frith on guitar, Bill Laswell on bass
and Dave Lombardo on drums. The first three are old friends, hubs
of the early '80s experimental-music scene that made the Knitting
Factory (and thus the Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival) possible;
Lombardo, the former drummer from the death-metal band Slayer,
should have been the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   But their first encounter as a quartet was completely functional
_ even warm and touching in places, in a funny way _ and Lombardo
was much of the reason why.
</P>
<P>
   He set the tone, playing stomps festooned with galloping
double-bass drum palpitations, and even, at one point, the rhythm
from James Brown's ``Cold Sweat''; the others fell into natural
patterns around him. Frith tapped his guitar strings with
paintbrushes and tiny chains; Zorn howled and blasted through the
alto saxophone, and Laswell played giant, greasy, fuzzy bass lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
