<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGMA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     06-10 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGMA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGMA: A BAND CLEARLY FROM EARTH (MORE PRECISELY, FRANCE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The progressive rock of the 1970s was a magnificent
paradox: meticulously ordered music that carried out some of rock's
most off-the-wall impulses. It threw together romantic pop and
modernist dissonance, complex structures and stretches of
improvisation, ethereal reveries and earthy stomps, all in
arbitrary proportions that showed off musicians' memories as much
as they served the songs. Magma, a French band that played its
first New York concert since 1973 at Wetlands on Tuesday night,
took those attributes to its own extreme.
</P>
<P>
   While progressive rock bands were always inventing fantasy
worlds and science-fiction legends, Magma also came up with a new
language, Kobaian, to depict a myth that placed Earth and Kobaia in
the midst of interplanetary strife. It made a handy framework for
music with epic ambitions; Wednesday's 90-minute set included four
songs. The music, first recorded by Magma in the early '70s, was
still recognizably from Earth, and Europe in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The current group includes two of Magma's core members from the
'70s, Christian Vander on drums and his wife, Stella Vander, on
vocals and keyboard. Vander, Magma's leader and songwriter, had
classical piano training and jazz inclinations; outside Magma,
which broke up for the first time in 1977, he has made jazz and
jazz-rock albums.
</P>
<P>
   At Wetlands, each song was a suite with recurring movements,
near-symphonic crescendos, speed-fingered melody lines and plenty
of idiom hopping. When Vander sang, in a robust baritone, his
melodies started as a kind of operatic recitative and turned into a
babble like scat singing. There were bombastic fuzz-toned marches,
brisk trio jazz passages (with Emmanuel Borghi on electric piano),
virtuosic dialogues between instruments and voices, and long,
circuitous buildups that started with airy vocal harmonies and
added the muscularity of a rock band.
</P>
<P>
   The music glimmered, crunched, sprinted and exulted, drawing
power from the possibility that at any moment it could take another
tangent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
