<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-GUNS-ADS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER BANS CERTAIN GUN ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NRA-WOES) 
(mk) 
 By PAUL POWER JR.   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ From 9 mm pistols complete with 15-round clips
to a weapon called a .223-caliber Bushmaster, classified
advertising sections in newspapers have been a fertile hunting
ground for gun seekers.
</P>
<P>
   But no more for The Ledger in Lakeland.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a moral dilemma in providing a forum for such sales,
Ledger publisher Don Whitworth said the newspaper would no longer
accept advertisements for assault weapons and handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have a right to bear arms,'' said Whitworth, who
goes on quail hunts three or four times a year. ``I also believe in
responsible gun ownership. But I'm opposed to a free market for
weapons such as cheap Saturday night specials or assault weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ledger's gun advertising policy is thought to be one of the
first of its kind in the state, said Dick Shelton, executive
director of the Florida Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, nine newspapers that responded to a 1997 survey said
they had restrictions on classified advertising for guns. The
survey was conducted by Editor &AMP; Publisher magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In Lakeland, handgun and assault weapon advertising will be
banned as a result of a series of events, Whitworth said.
</P>
<P>
   _ A fatal shooting in the newspaper's lobby in the early 1980s
in which an employee was killed by a man who then shot himself. At
the time, Whitworth ended up assisting medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   _ The killing of a 4-year-old and three Tampa area law
enforcement officers in a daylong shooting rampage last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida voters' deciding last November to authorize more
police background checks at gun shows and flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The high school carnage caused by students with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The new advertisement policy was slammed by some gun defenders
and cheered by others. Some said the policy doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the next time I am looking for a gun I'll buy another
newspaper,'' said Michael Baxter, owner of Sunshine Taxidermy in
Lakeland, which preserves fish, hogs, deer and other prey. Baxter
said he depends on a gun, a Rottweiler and an alarm system to
protect his business from burglars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend the publisher for the decision,'' said criminology
expert Risdon Slate, an associate professor at Florida Southern
College in Lakeland. ``I don't think that newspapers should be
facilitating that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Slate said that the media should refuse to identify juveniles
who commit horrible crimes, such as the mass slaughter in
Littleton, Col. ``I don't think these people should have their
names in the newspaper,'' said Slate. Cut back on the opportunity
to become famous for dastardly acts, he said, and crime might be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   State voters last year approved a constitutional revision giving
counties the right to require that all gun sales _ not just those
by dealers _ be subject to background checks. Several counties in
Florida have adopted such requirements, although Polk, where
Lakeland is located, has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laws have been passed to ensure that only responsible
individuals can purchase weapons,'' said Whitworth. ``Well, I
happen to agree with those laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ledger doesn't want to be a party to the sale of certain
weapons where the buyer might otherwise be unable to obtain a
weapon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to help anyone beat the system,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth said the policy would not necessarily ban all ads for
gun shows, which are popular in Polk County. But he said if the ad
included the availability of a .44 magnum, it would not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   He did not estimate the amount of revenue potentially lost
because of the decision but said it was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
