<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-10 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETURN WITH HONOR': TRUE TALES OF HEROISM FROM VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Return With Honor,'' Freida Lee Mock and Terry Sanders'
gripping documentary film about U.S. pilots shot down over North
Vietnam, signifies a major shift in the screen image of the Vietnam
veteran. Until recently, that image, formed by dozens of Hollywood
films steeped in anti-war angst, tended to portray the Vietnam
veteran as a tormented lost soul, the permanently damaged survivor
of a nihilistic hell too terrible to be put into words.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pendulum has swung. In the era of ``Saving Private
Ryan'' (Tom Hanks is credited as ``presenting'' ``Return With
Honor'') and Tom Brokaw's book, ``The Greatest Generation,'' a
traditional image of American heroism has recrystallized in the
popular imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Return With Honor,'' more than 20 veteran airmen describe
their captivity in precise, detailed and remarkably calm
reminiscences that make that hell seem absolutely real. The lessons
they've learned, far from being nihilistic, are lessons in
physical, emotional and spiritual self-preservation and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   How they survived with such apparent equanimity is a testament
to their training (many are graduates of the U.S. Air Force
Academy), unwavering patriotism, powerful sense of brotherhood and
native ingenuity. Everyone who speaks in the film (including the
half-dozen loyal wives who waited for as long as eight and a half
years for their husbands' return) emerges burnished with glory.
</P>
<P>
   The heroism they share is of a classic American sort: stoic,
dutiful, utterly lacking in grandiosity, but deeply emotional
beneath a dignified surface. When tears come, they flash suddenly
in the eyes and the voice begins to break. An instant later,
emotional control is restored.
</P>
<P>
   The stories they tell are inspiring, sometimes astounding, and
most importantly, true.
</P>
<P>
   There is Comdr. Jeremiah Denton, a prisoner of war for more than
seven years who foiled his captors by blinking the word ``torture''
in Morse code when placed before newsmen and told to make a
``confession.'' There is Lt. Comdr. Richard Stratton who, when put
in front of news cameras, embarrassed the North Vietnamese by
pretending to be a brainwashed North Vietnamese version of ``The
Manchurian Candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is Seaman Douglas Hegdahl, who mastered a memory technique
that enabled him, when released and debriefed, to reel off the
names of all 268 American prisoners of war. And there is Lt. John
McGrath, a self-taught artist who kept himself sane by drawing on
the wall with his own pus and blood.
</P>
<P>
   The movie visits the prison in Hanoi where many of the pilots
were held, a grim medieval fortress with meat hooks on the ceiling
and rusted iron shackles on the floor. We hear about an
excruciating torture nicknamed ``the Vietnamese rope trick,'' in
which prisoners were tightly bound with ropes that cut off the
circulation to their limbs and dislocated their shoulders. Once
prisoners were ``broken'' during interrogations, they were asked to
divulge information they usually didn't have and were forced to
invent.
</P>
<P>
   But after the death of Ho Chi Minh in 1969, the use of torture
was largely suspended and prison conditions improved somewhat.
Although the prisoners were isolated from one another, they
developed a communications code (based on dividing 25 of the 26
letters of the alphabet into five rows) and methodically tapping on
the walls of their cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return With Honor'' has two happy endings. The first, about
halfway through the film, follows a group of liberated pilots to
the plane carrying them home. Then the movie doubles back to tell
more war stories. The second and final happy ending shows the
actual reunions of several aviators and their families in San
Francisco in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews are accompanied by vintage newsreels and scenes
from North Vietnamese archives, including one of American prisoners
paraded through the streets of Hanoi and pelted with abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In remembering the American anti-war movement, ``Return With
Honor'' treads gingerly. The issue of whether or not the Vietnam
war should have been waged at all is barely addressed. But we do
learn that television coverage of antiwar demonstrations was shown
by the North Vietnamese to the prisoners to try to demoralize them.
Whatever emotions these scenes may have stirred is not mentioned
except for a certain confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Unabashedly patriotic but without flagrant flag-waving, ``Return
With Honor'' is a celebration of courage.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RETURN WITH HONOR'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Freida Lee Mock and Terry Sanders;
written by Ms. Mock, Sanders and Christine Z. Wiser; directors of
photography, Eddie Marritz and Sanders; edited by Greg Byers; music
by Charles Bernstein; released by Ocean Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Everett Alvarez, Jim Stockdale, Jeremiah Denton, Robbie
Risner, John McCain, Richard Stratton, John McGrath, Douglas
Hegdahl and others.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
