<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANCY-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXUBERANT AMERICANA THAT'S NOT ALL-AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Wednesday, Christopher Wheeldon made his debut in
``Fancy Free'' at New York City Ballet, and Jose Manuel Carreno
appeared for the first time in ``Push Comes to Shove'' at American
Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   These major debuts in major companies performing the same night
at Lincoln Center could well lead one to ponder the meaning of a
word like Americana. In the 1930s and early '40s, when nationalism
in the arts was at its peak, the term was associated with a
glorification of the open frontier. Nation building was the task
and opportunity beckoned in many dance works, especially if they
had scores by Aaron Copland (``Billy the Kid,'' ``Rodeo'' and
``Appalachian Spring'').
</P>
<P>
   In 1944 Jerome Robbins broke with this pattern. He was concerned
not with the American myth but American reality. ``Fancy Free,'' to
music by Leonard Bernstein, showed three sailors meeting three
young women in New York during World War II. But it was not only
Robbins' content that was peculiarly American. It was also the
style and execution of his choreography, ballet that had a
vernacular flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Twyla Tharp was very much in this line of descent when she
created ``Push Comes to Shove'' for Ballet Theater in 1976.
Although plotless, the piece is American in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, you don't have to be American to dance these works.
Wheeldon is British and Carreno is Cuban. Unsurprisingly, Wheeldon
was given the lyrical solo of the middle sailor in ``Fancy Free.''
His youthful exuberance, mischievous demeanor and ability to
sustain an innocent look made him a natural for the poetic gob
flanked by two streetwise friends.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gold was superb and precise in his bravura as the tipsy
fellow, and Damian Woetzel danced almost too well. He needs to tone
down his overall aggressiveness in the role and to dispense with
the bump-and-grind pelvis in his rhumba. On the other hand, his
lusty pursuit of Pascale van Kipnis in the ballroom duet had a fine
live-for-the-moment passion. Ms. van Kipnis matched him on her own
ground. Deanna McBrearty was too bland as the big-city girl with
the red bag while Aura Dixon was a shade too bold in a cameo role.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening at the Metropolitan Opera House, Carreno
looked at ease in Mikhail Baryshnikov's original role in ``Push,''
capturing its staccato dynamics but also adding a flush luxuriance
to the style.
</P>
<P>
   Carreno was very funny here, as were Giuseppe Picone and Irina
Dvorovenko, with Ashley Tuttle and Yan Chen as the other soloists.
The ballet's emphasis has changed. There are fewer mock bows, and
there is no longer the sensational virtuosity once offered by
Baryshnikov and his immediate successors in the role, Danilo
Radojevic, Kirk Peterson and Gil Boggs. Boggs gave his farewell
performance earlier in the evening in ``Airs.'' His versatility and
excellence will be remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
