<HEADER>
A0612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-0611-C     06-10 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO RESETTLING TO TAKE MONTHS, REFUGEES ANXIOUS TO FIND
HOMES, FAMILIES
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ With a Yugoslav troop withdrawal from Kosovo
beginning Thursday, ethnic Albanian refugees here were cautious
about a return to a land of minefields and destroyed villages. But,
patience will be hard for young Riza Rudaj.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, the 15-year-old saw Serb police drag his father from
the driver's seat of a tractor in the exodus from southern Kosovo.
He has not seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have any time to speak to us at all . . . If I tried
to speak to him I could have been killed,'' Rudaj said near the
squalid tenement where he has stayed for five weeks. ``It seems
like five years have passed here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rudaj, sporting a University of Nevada-Las Vegas T-shirt and
a vest decorated with pictures of the rock band Metallica, knows he
must wait. His Kosovo might not be safe yet and his return will be
part of a massive and complicated months-long resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   With NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia suspended and Serb-led
Yugoslav troops beating a path out of the war-torn province under
the military technical agreement that requires their withdrawal,
U.N. officials were trying to figure out how and when to reverse a
humanitarian effort that is even now still under construction.
</P>
<P>
   No refugees came into Albania from Kosovo Thursday, but
construction continued at refugee camps to take care of a shelter
shortage. About 125 refugees were transferred from Kukes, just over
the border from Kosovo, to reunite with families hours away in
southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The first step to any resettlement will start with a major
military operation. A 5,000-man ``battle group'' with tanks and
artillery was headed north through Albania Thursday. The troops
should enter southwestern Kosovo by Sunday, after comparable forces
from other NATO countries, including the United States, have
entered from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Military planners said the NATO troops will enter step-by-step
on the heels of the Serb withdrawal. The Serbs have 11 days to
leave the province entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not interested in leaving any sort of vacuum, so as
soon as Serb troops leave, we will enter,'' said Col. Helge
Erikson, spokesman for the NATO force in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Troops will be followed by aid workers, who will begin assessing
the living conditions and prospects for return. As they try to
avoid Serb-planted landmines, they will give top priority to
finding people hiding in the mountains who may be facing severe
malnutrition. Also, the U.N. estimates that half the houses in
Kosovo are damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Returnees from Albania pose special problems. First, it has the
most refugees, nearly half a million. Second, the crumbling roads
through Albania's mountain passes make any mass movement slow. That
is one reason the first NATO troop movements into Kosovo will come
from neighboring Macedonia, which has easier terrain and better
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Colville, spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR), said about half the refugees may have to wait
until as late as next year for their return.
</P>
<P>
   He said some recent international refugee movements have been
larger in sheer numbers, but Kosovo ``is shaping up to be one of
the most complex, logistically.''
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at helping the refugees understand and be patient, the
United Nations is preparing a massive leaflet and information
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most seem to understand, at least for now, that landmines,
possible booby-traps, damaged water systems and roads, could make
for a slow return. Most have heard that their homes have been
looted or burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only when the U.N. tells us to go back we will go back,''
said 80-year-old Azem Basha, a refugee from north of Prizren in
Kosovo province. But, he hopes it will be soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go back to my land. Even if there is nothing
there, I will set up a tent . . . and live in that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
