<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-10 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ain't Nothin' But a Flap
</P>
<P>
   If only the television show had been this interesting ...
</P>
<P>
   Broadway was positively atwitter this week with talk of lawyers,
sales and suspicious speeches, a drama that many spectators agreed
far surpassed the suspense generated Sunday by the Tony Awards
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list was the saga of ``It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues,'' which continued to prove that for sure-fire success,
nothing beats a protest. After its production number was cut from
the Tony show on CBS, the revue made headlines citywide and had its
biggest week at the box office, taking in more than $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy ``has certainly brought us a great deal of
attention and sympathy,'' said Eric Krebs, the lead producer. ``But
I think it would be wrong to consider that this makes everything
OK''
</P>
<P>
   As for possible legal remedies, the show has retained a lawyer,
Bert Fields, and Krebs said discussions continued for some sort of
compensation from Tony Awards Productions, the partnership of the
two organizations that run the awards, the League of American
Theaters and Producers and the American Theater Wing. The
production company has already agreed to pay the ``Blues''
producers for the cost of rehearsing and transporting the cast for
the Tony broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one Tony official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said several efforts were being made to help ``Blues,''
including asking Rosie O'Donnell to talk it up on her television
show. A number from the musical was on David Letterman's CBS show
on Wednesday. Other options being pursued include additional
appearances on CBS as well as at a performance on Sunday for
President Clinton at Ford's Theater in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure is what they want,'' the official said. ``And we're
trying to make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For the musicals that did appear, there were immediate benefits:
``Fosse'' took in about $250,000 on Monday, and ``Annie Get Your
Gun'' sold nearly $200,000 worth of tickets. That represented large
increases for both shows.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the complaints about the handling of the show were
crystallized in a letter sent by director Harold Prince to several
high-ranking members of the wing and the league. Saying that the
broadcast was generally handled like ``an entertainment on the
Carnival Cruise Line,'' Prince also upbraided Tony officials for
scheduling a lifetime achievement award for actress Uta Hagen
before the broadcast began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is downright insulting to relegate one of our
greatest actresses to a segment off camera,'' Prince wrote. He also
suggested the entire broadcast should be on PBS, which carried its
first hour, rather than CBS.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't appear likely. The Tonys have a contract with CBS
through 2004, and Tony officials say this year's broadcast had not
put that in jeopardy. As for Ms. Hagen, Keith Sherman, a spokesman
for the Tonys, said that a recap of her award was to have been
included in the CBS portion, but that the segment was cut because
of time.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Sherman declined to comment on Prince's letter,
although Prince said the Tony administrators had responded
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere wags were positing ``X-Files''-style conspiracies
around the fact that David Richenthal, lead producer of ``Death of
a Salesman,'' somehow had his speech for the telecast on a
prompter! What did this mean? Did Richenthal know in advance that
his show had won? Was the fix in?
</P>
<P>
   No, Richenthal said, although a global consortium of
gossip-famished alien hybrids might not believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The prompter incident was more mundane, Richenthal said. While
sitting in the Gershwin Theater studying his speech before the
broadcast, he said, he was approached by a television technician
who asked if he wanted the text on a prompter. He said sure, and
voila, it was done.
</P>
<P>
   But in explaining his computerized cue cards, Richenthal offered
one slightly cryptic prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' he intoned, ``in future years, this will become a
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sale, Again
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore Theater is back on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the landmark theater at 261 W. 47th St. was
supposed to be sold by the Nederlander Organization to a developer,
Joseph Moinian, who said he planned to build a 43-story hotel on
the site of the theater and five adjacent buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But in late April, said Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for the
Nederlanders, Moinian failed to arrive at a meeting arranged to
close the deal and defaulted on a $1 million deposit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the contract it was stated that time was of the essence,''
Rubenstein said. ``Not only didn't he deliver the check, he didn't
even show.''
</P>
<P>
   Moinian, however, has sued the Nederlanders in state Supreme
Court in Manhattan, arguing that the organization improperly
terminated the contract and kept the deposit, said Menachem J.
Kastner, Moinian's lawyer. The lawsuit seeks $35 million in damages
and enforcement of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein called the suit frivolous and said the theater and
the five other buildings were still for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The 948-seat theater, built in 1925, was once the home of
productions of the musical ``Hair'' and ``Barefoot in the Park.''
But it has sat empty and decaying for more than a decade. The
interior, with neoclassical detail and an unusual horseshoe-shaped
auditorium, was designated as a landmark in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Woody Harrelson is confirmed for a November revival of ``The
Rainmaker,'' by N. Richard Nash, produced by the Roundabout Theater
Co. Scott Ellis directs.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the department of now it can be told: ``Epic Proportions,''
a comedy by Larry Coen and David Crane, will be the next tenant of
the Helen Hayes Theater, soon to be vacated by ``Night Must Fall.''
Kristin Chenoweth, a Tony winner in ``You're a Good Man, Charlie
Brown,'' will star.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corin Redgrave will read from ``The British on Broadway,'' a
book by Elizabeth Sharland about the English influence on early New
York theater, on Monday at the Barnes &AMP; Noble store on 66th Street
and Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
