<SLUG> BC-HARTFORD-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE A ROMAN GALLERY REMODELS, CARAVAGGIO VISITS HARTFORD
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN.: Conn.)  (fb) 
 By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever their inconvenience to the local public, museum
renovations are great for the circulation of masterpieces. They
enable people who live elsewhere to see works that might otherwise
elude them. Right now, for instance, because the Capitoline Picture
Gallery in Rome _ part of the oldest public museum in the world _
is refurbishing several of its rooms, museumgoers on this side of
the Atlantic can view one of its greatest masterpieces, the
sensual, much debated ``St. John the Baptist'' (1600) by
Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio (1573-1610).
</P>
<P>
   Never before exhibited outside of Rome, the Caravaggio appears
along with 20 other Renaissance and Baroque works in an all-star
show called ``Caravaggio's `St. John' and Masterpieces From the
Capitoline Museum in Rome,'' at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford,
Conn. Caravaggio's illustrious colleagues in the show include
Pietro da Cortona, Domenichino, Dosso Dossi, Il Guercino, Lorenzo
Lotto, Guido Reni, Veronese and Simon Vouet.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is part of a continuing Caravaggio saga for the
Atheneum, which has developed a special relationship with the
museums of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Hartford, ``Caravaggio and His Italian Followers:
From the Collections of the National Gallery of Ancient Art in
Rome'' celebrated the Atheneum's return to Italy of a painting by
the 16th-century Mannerist Jacopo Zucchi. The painting had been
bought in Paris in 1965, but it was later discovered that the work
had been looted from the Italian Embassy in Berlin at the close of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Atheneum is rich in early Italian art, including a
Caravaggio, ``The Ecstasy of St. Francis'' (1595). Acquired in
1943, it was the first work by this artist to enter a museum in the
United States. (In 1930, the Atheneum was the first museum in the
United States to present a show of Italian Baroque paintings.)
</P>
<P>
   And it just so happens that the Atheneum owns a work _ done in
1749 by Giovanni Paolo Panini _ depicting the enormous collection
of Cardinal Gonzaga (1690-1756), who founded the Capitoline Picture
Gallery. In the current show, the slightly exaggerated Panini view
of the palatial Gonzaga galleries, whose walls are plastered with
masterpieces, is next to a portrait of the cardinal himself, a man
of a girth to match his collection. The portrait, which belongs to
the Capitoline, was done in the mid-1740s by Pierre Subleyras.
</P>
<P>
   The show's centerpiece is the challenging Caravaggio, ``St. John
the Baptist,'' painted around 1600 and hung in the Capitoline
Picture Gallery since 1750. Painted with the sharp contrasts of
light and dark that characterize the artist's work, it depicts a
naked youth embracing a ram while turning a slyly smiling face to
the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some naughty innuendo here, but scholarly debate
has focused on whether the traditional identification of the
subject as John the Baptist is correct. One reason is the fact that
John's traditional attribute is a lamb, not a ram.
</P>
<P>
   A recent proposal, however, suggests that the subject is really
Isaac, who, about to be sacrificed by his own father, Abraham, is
saved by God and happily greets the ram that will be killed in his
stead. The semireclining pose of the youth, incidentally, is
derived from a similar one of a boy in Michelangelo's epic for the
Sistine Chapel ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a small assemblage, occupying only two galleries,
the show has a number of other paintings _ selected from the
Capitoline collections by Peter C. Sutton, director of the
Wadsworth, and Eric Zafran, curator of its European paintings _
that will stop you in your tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Domenichino's operatic ``Sybil'' (1622) is a high-flown Baroque
fantasy, with an abundance of florid drapery, that shows the Sybil
wearing a sultan's turban, her chubby wide-eyed face with bee-stung
lips turned up as if in search of cues. Stripped of finery and
posed a little differently, she would bear a distinct resemblance
to Guido Reni's ``St. Sebastian'' (1615), whose chubby, wide-eyed
face is resolutely heavenward as arrows pierce his naked torso.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's ``Annunciation'' (1528) is an exquisite rendering of
one of the most hackneyed subjects in art history, a grand,
columned interior with the Virgin kneeling in prayer as a princely
Archangel Gabriel arrives on jumbo wings to make his startling
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Of the secular paintings in the show, an undated, unfinished one
thought to be a self-portrait by Velazquez ranks high for its
fierce, almost belligerent intensity of expression. Two other
likenesses, besides Subleyras' unsparing fleshscape of Cardinal
Gonzaga, are compelling.
</P>
<P>
   One is Lorenzo Lotto's ``Portrait of a Crossbowman'' (1551-52),
a dark, slightly menacing rendition of an earringed sportsman
holding a crossbow meant for business. The other is Bartolomeo
Passerotti's ``Portrait of a Man With a Dog'' (1585), an endearing
view of a handsome young man in a high velvet hat and lace ruff who
looks earnestly at the viewer as he clasps to his chest a
tan-spotted setter.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked are two charming small Roman landscapes by
the Dutch-born Gaspar Van Wittel, both done around 1680. Unlike the
romanticized landscape fantasies common to Italian art of the 17th
century, these are unidealized documentaries seen through a
northern European eye, an approach important in setting the style
of modern landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``View of the Temple of Vesta'' shows an old pagan temple
converted to a church in a run-down neighborhood. ``View of the
Broken Bridge'' depicts the ruin of a rebuilt bridge dating back to
the second century A.D., with the busy banks of the Tiber in the
foreground.
</P>
<P>
   As a kind of lagniappe to the Capitoline show, the Atheneum has
put up some Baroque examples from its own collection, including
works by Vouet, Reni, Claude Lorrain, Bernardo Strozzi, Salvatore
Rosa, Jusepe de Ribera and others that fortunately managed to make
their way to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   A word about the Capitoline Picture Gallery, whose fine
collection of paintings dates from the 14th to the 17th centuries,
with the emphasis on 17th-century Italian examples. It stands on
Capitoline Hill as part of an older museum complex in the
Michelangelo-designed Piazza del Campidoglio, dominated by a bronze
equestrian statue of Marcus Aurelius dating from Imperial days.
</P>
<P>
   The Picture Gallery was opened in 1749 through the joint efforts
of Pope Benedict XIV and Cardinal Gonzaga, his shrewd,
hard-bargaining Secretary of State, a collector and patron of the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1748 and 1750, bent on preventing the dispersal of paintings
to foreign collections, and giving Roman art students the
opportunity to study works of the past, Gonzaga secured for the
Picture Gallery significant parts of two big Roman collections,
those of the Sachetti and Pio families.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the gallery, which now belongs to the city of Rome,
has seen its holdings vastly expanded, by gifts and purchases, not
only of paintings but also of porcelains, tapestries and furniture.
The gallery continues to make acquisitions: the Subleyras portrait
of Cardinal Gonzaga came in 1995 from a private collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
