<P>
   CALIFORNIA-INS-JOBS. The Immigration and Naturalization Service,
trying to reduce a nearly two-year backlog in immigration cases,
will hire 35 workers for its San Francisco office, the agency
announced. (150 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-REACT-DELEGATION. Colorado's Republican lawmakers in
Congress on Thursday downplayed the significance of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's decision to submit to NATO demands,
insisting the agreement is neither a victory for the United States
nor a vindication of President Clinton's policies. (500 words.) By
Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-WILDERNESS-UDALL. Rep. Mark Udall, a Boulder Democrat,
introduced legislation on Thursday that would create a 6,000-acre
buffer zone of federally owned land around Rocky Flats and
strengthen wilderness protections in Rocky Mountain National Park
and Arapaho National Forest. The bills -- the first ever offered by
Udall, a freshman member of Congress -- would affect lands outside
his congressional district, but Colorado Republicans don't seem to
mind. (500 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-MEDICARE-GRAHAM. Sen. Bob Graham thinks prevention is
some of the best medicine. That's why Graham, R-Fla., on Thursday
introduced a measure to expand Medicare coverage with a group of
benefits aimed at preventing certain ailments that affect seniors.
(300 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-HEALTH-COLLINS. As a result of cuts that stem from the
Medicare Interim Payment System, home health care agencies cannot
provide the amount and quality of services elderly Americans need,
according to Sen. Collins. (400 words.) By Sara Kugler
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SNOWE-CONTRACEPTION. Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, offered
legislation with Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., Thursday that would
require health insurance companies to pay for female prescription
contraceptives and consultations under their prescription benefit
plan. (500 words.) By Tiffany Lynch
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA-DEFENSE-MONEY. Tucked away within the $265 billion
defense spending bill passed by the Senate Tuesday is about $26
million earmarked for military projects scattered throughout
Nevada. (450 words.) By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA-WOMEN-CONTRACEPTION. Women are being short-changed by
health insurance companies who refuse to pay for female birth
control, Sen. Harry Reid told about 50 people at a news conference
Thursday. (500 words.) By Tiffany Lynch
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-KOSOVO-REACT. Rio Grande Valley lawmakers talk about the
end of the conflict in Kosovo, and the role of the United States in
the peace plan (400 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-FUTURE-CAR. The Aluminum Cow was victorious in
Washington when the University of Wisconsin-Madison ``FutureCar''
team won the Department of Energy award for its hybrid electric
vehicle. (500 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
