<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANNIBAL-THE-CANNIBAL     06-10 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANNIBAL-THE-CANNIBAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 `HANNIBAL the CANNIBAL' RETURNS  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``On a related subject, Signore Pazzi, I must confess to you:
I'm giving serious thought to eating your wife.'' _ Hannibal Lecter
speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years after he last appeared in print and eight years
after his movie alter ego told Clarice Starling, ``I'm having an
old friend for dinner,'' Dr. Hannibal Lecter finally comes out of
hiding as 1 million copies of ``Hannibal'' are hitting bookstores
nationwide in what the publishing industry is saying is the closest
thing they'll ever have to a ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``Hannibal the Cannibal'' have waited more than a decade
for the reclusive Thomas Harris to finally produce a sequel to
``The Silence of the Lambs,'' and they'll be lining up to find out
what's been going on with one of the most popular villains in
modern American fiction.
</P>
<P>
   If you like to dine on literary mayhem, you will not be
disappointed. This 484-page excursion into lunacy drips with blood
and entrails and is almost gleefully gross, as life on the run has
left the devilish Dr. Lecter with quite the appetite.
</P>
<P>
   He's so hungry he could eat a corpse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hannibal'' picks up seven years after FBI Special Agent
Clarice Starling forged a slightly erotic and deeply disturbing
bond with Dr. Hannibal ``the Cannibal'' Lecter _ a relationship
that provided young Starling with the information she needed to
find the infamous serial killer Jame Gumb.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the splashy bust was the worst thing possible for a
female agent trying to launch a career in the macho FBI. Starling
has spent the last seven years on one dangerous, low-rent stakeout
after another _ and when she kills five people in a botched drug
raid caught by television news cameras, she's practically forced
off the job. Not even her soon-to-retire, burned-out mentor Jack
Crawford (Scott Glenn in the movie) can do much to help.
</P>
<P>
   As for Starling's old friend Dr. Lecter, he's the subject of
much speculation on the Internet and he's become something of a
cult hero _ his annotated and signed copy of Alexandre Dumas'
``Dictionary of Cuisine'' has been auctioned to a private collector
for $16,000 _ but the authorities aren't even close to catching
him.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Verger, on the other hand, is moving in for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   Verger, one of Dr. Lecter's earliest victims, remains alive
despite having one lidless eye, no nose or lips and a paralyzed
body. Living on a respirator in a specially designed room on his
compound in Maryland, Verger's mind is even more grotesque than his
hideous physical appearance. Drawing on his connections within the
U.S. government and his limitless supply of funds, Verger is
hatching a plan to kidnap Lecter and feed him slowly to a team of
specially bred wild boars, if you can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   While the character of Verger is a vividly drawn architect of
pure evil, he's also close to being comically absurd. Harris aims
high with his depictions of horror and his explorations into the
chambers of Lecter's mind _ he's like Stephen King with advanced
degrees in history and fine arts _ but he veers dangerously close
to self-parody with the scenes involving the killing pigs, and he's
sure to have some readers howling with anger and/or retching with
disgust over a dinner scene featuring a guest whose skull is
unscrewed so Hannibal can scoop out some appetizers for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   There are also nice moments of intentional humor, as when the
sophisticated Dr. Lecter must wear a Toronto Maple Leafs warmup
suit and sit in coach class in order to blend in with a crass tour
group. Faced with the prospect of an in-flight dinner, Lecter is
mortified. Here is a man who has dined on a census taker's liver
and a nurse's tongue, among other delicacies, but ``there are
limits: he cannot eat this airline swill.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say ``Hannibal'' is pure camp. Partially because
we cannot help but hear the voices of the great team of Anthony
Hopkins and Jodie Foster from the movie, Hannibal and Clarice
remain a compelling, star-crossed couple who share a connection of
almost elegant tenderness _ not to mention childhood scars that are
more alike than any outsider would imagine. Their connection is
strange, sweet and sick.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Hannibal'' is by no means a horror classic. While
Harris delivers some chilling moments, I can't imagine that most
readers will be satisfied with the ultimate fates of Starling and
Lecter. We might have been better off had the two parted for good
with ``Silence,'' reuniting only in our imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``NBC Nightly News with Tom Brokaw,''
``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah''
and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
