<P>
   This is not to say ``Hannibal'' is pure camp. Partially because
we cannot help but hear the voices of the great team of Anthony
Hopkins and Jodie Foster from the movie, Hannibal and Clarice
remain a compelling, star-crossed couple who share a connection of
almost elegant tenderness _ not to mention childhood scars that are
more alike than any outsider would imagine. Their connection is
strange, sweet and sick.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Hannibal'' is by no means a horror classic. While
Harris delivers some chilling moments, I can't imagine that most
readers will be satisfied with the ultimate fates of Starling and
Lecter. We might have been better off had the two parted for good
with ``Silence,'' reuniting only in our imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``NBC Nightly News with Tom Brokaw,''
``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah''
and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
