<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-2000-$ADV13-HNS &LR;      06-10 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE STARTS PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN TRAILING REPUBLICAN CHALLENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore will be far from Washington's corridors of
power, his natural stomping ground, when he announces the start of
his official presidential campaign Wednesday at the Smith County
courthouse in Carthage, Tenn,
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to avoid the label of Beltway insider and trying to put
some subtle distance between the Clinton administration and his own
presidential campaign, Gore chose to make his announcement in
Carthage where his late father, Sen. Albert Gore Sr., D-Tenn., ran
a 250-acre farm and where his mother Pauline Gore still lives.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, the younger Gore wistfully recalls spending summers
there hosing down hog manure and plowing a steep hillside behind a
mule team.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that Gore was born and raised in Washington
where he resided in a posh hotel, attended an elite private school
and developed his reputation as a wooden, somewhat gaffe-prone
speaker, partial to blue suits and other Washington trappings.
</P>
<P>
   By this measure, Gore at this stage is competing less with
fellow Democratic contender Bill Bradley and the Republicans than
with himself. But his supporters hope that Gore's Tennessee
campaign initiation on Wednesday _ followed by quick visits to
Iowa, New Hampshire, New York, Los Angeles and Seattle _ will help
wipe the slate clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is well known by American public but he's not known
well,'' said Mark Mellman, a Washington-based pollster and
political consultant who backs Gore. ``He needs to fill out the
picture and tell people who he is, what he's done and what he
intends to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore starts his campaign for the Democratic nomination in 2000
at a significant disadvantage. While he is comfortably ahead of
Bradley, most polls put him at least 10 percentage points behind
the Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Gore also
trails former American Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign is waiting in the wings and Gore's
announcement trip could prove to be a key juncture for the former
senator from New Jersey. ``The only shot Bradley has is if Gore
fails to connect to people,'' said one Democrat who has advised
Bradley. ``If he does, that's it; Gore's the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Baker, a political science professor at Rutgers University,
said that polls have only limited value this far away from the
November 2000 election. ``Rumors of (Gore's) demise are
premature,'' he said, recalling how President Bush also struggled
as a vice president early in the 1988 election, but went on to
cream Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Against the negatives, Baker said, Gore can boast of eight years
of high-level governmental experience as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways he redefined and revitalized the office, moving it
away from its traditional status as political bone yard, according
to Baker. ``Gore is not a potted palm,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Gore has spiced up his speaking style,
sometimes adopting the cadences of a Baptist preacher to articulate
his contrast of Republicans and Democrats. (``We say legislate.
They say investigate.'')
</P>
<P>
   And he attempted to cut through the political thicket last month
in Iowa by laying out his education plan, a program that calls for
smaller high schools, tough discipline, standards for teachers and
_ a long-time Gore theme _ connecting classrooms and libraries to
``the information superhighway.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also reached out into Republican territory, telling a
Salvation Army meeting in Atlanta last month that he supports
federal grants to so-called faith-based organizations that work on
homelessness, drug addiction, youth violence and other social ills.
</P>
<P>
   And he is winning the all-important money chase. In the first
three months of the year, Gore's campaign led all other
presidential hopefuls by raising $8.9 million. Bush followed in
second place with $7.6 million over the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, Gore is likely to be dogged by
memories of some recent verbal gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, his remark in a CNN interview in March that he
``took the initiative in creating the Internet'' won him headlines
and derisive Republican press releases.
</P>
<P>
   A similar reaction has greeted Gore's emphasis on his down-home
Tennessee links and the downplaying of his privileged Washington
D.C. upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore emerged unscathed from the various congressional
probes of how President Clinton and Democrats financed the 1996
election, some of embarrassing episodes might come back to haunt
him, such as his 1996 visit to the Hsi Lai Temple in Hacienda
Heights, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhist monks and nuns there were straw donors for campaign
contributions illegally funneled from the temple, but Gore
contended that he was unaware of any wrongdoing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Gore's defense of making 52 campaign fundraising
phone calls from his White House office despite federal law
prohibiting political fundraising on government property.
</P>
<P>
   At a now-famous 1997 press conference, Gore used the phrase ``no
controlling legal authority'' seven times in insisting to reporters
that there was no law that made such calls illegal.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of whether Gore can overcome the
negative side of Clinton's legacy _ everything from the Whitewater
real estate imbroglio to questionable fundraising to the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's closely associated with Clinton and he seems to be
carrying Clinton's negative baggage,'' said George Edwards III,
director of the Center for Presidential Studies at Texas A&AMP;M. ``It
has nothing to do with personality. People just might not want a
third Clinton term.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign earlier this year seemed dogged by disgruntled
Democrats complaining anonymously that the effort to get Gore into
the White House was marked by lethargy and lack of focus.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton took a few whacks at Gore, telling the
New York Times that he, too, was concerned about the campaign and
had urged Gore to loosen up and enjoy himself on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   To tighten up his organization, Gore gave his campaign's reins
to former Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the onetime Democratic House
whip still known as a shrewd political operative and expert
fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been heartened by the early Gore miscues, but
they do not see the 2000 election as a GOP romp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we nominate a strong candidate, coalesce around the
candidate and don't destroy each other, we can win,'' said Whit
Ayres, an Atlanta-based Republican pollster. ``But it's not a cake
walk.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
