<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRATS11-COX     06-10 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATIC PARTY LEADERS ATTACK BUSH'S RECORD, TIES TO CONGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leaders of the Democratic National Committee
assaulted the record of George W. Bush with unusual ferocity
Thursday and sought to link the Texas governor with the Republican
leaders of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The attack prompted a suggestion from the Bush's presidential
campaign that Democrats are ``pushing the panic button'' over his
commanding lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   DNC co-chairs Roy Romer and Joe Andrews spoke at a breakfast
with reporters just two days before Bush's much-anticipated first
trip to Iowa and New Hampshire as a prospective candidate for the
2000 Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   They frequently drew comparisons with Vice President Al Gore,
contending that Gore's extensive experience, personal integrity and
commitment to successful economic policies made him a better choice
for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Romer characterized Bush's cautious support for the NATO-led
bombing in Kosovo to ``hiding in the bushes'' at the Alamo. Andrews
compared the well-financed Bush campaign to the Titanic, ready to
``hit the iceberg'' of public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In their comments and in a a 13-page review of his career they
distributed, they belittled the record Bush has compiled during his
five years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Romer credited Bush with cutting taxes and improving education
in the Lone Star state. But he said nearly every governor could
make the same claim as a result of a national economy strengthened
by the economic policies of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is in a a group of 30 to 40 governors that have
done fairly well in handling good times,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   The party leaders also sought to link Bush to the Republican
leadership in Congress, which has been in disarray over budget
priorities, education and gun control legislation in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``has been anointed by the establishment'' of the
Republican Party, and the GOP's budget priorities reflect a
``reckless public policy,'' Romer said, citing a proposed cut in
Head Start funding that would result in 50,000 children cut from
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Republican candidate for president cannot avoid some
responsibility for what that party is doing,'' he added. That is
especially true for Bush, he said, because 114 Republican House
members have endorsed his presidential bid, an unprecedented number
at such an early stage in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   They include Majority Leader Dick Armey and Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, fellow Texans whose conservative views do not fit
comfortably into the governor's mold of ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer said Bush should be forced to explain to voters how he
would get his ``compadres from Texas'' to abandon the GOP's current
budget and to line up behind spending that ``the rest of America
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Beckwith, chief spokesman for the Bush presidential
campaign, said the attack suggested that Democrats ``long to return
to the Newt Gingrich days when they could raise money by making him
into a bogeyman on every issue that came up.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Democrats ``have to realize they've got to deal
with George Bush now, not with some congressional fright mask that
they manage to create.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that with Bush continuing to lead Gore in polls by
substantial margins, ``there is a whiff of desperation in the air
at the DNC'' for ``such big guns to be out attacking'' Bush at this
stage of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to think that they're pushing the panic button very,
very early,'' Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
