<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-10 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is it in the genes?
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the water?
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared for his first campaign swing outside of Texas,
Gov. George W. Bush tied himself this week into the same
no-new-taxes knot that politically strangled his father.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't necessary and it wasn't wise.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to ``oppose and veto any increase in individual or
corporate marginal income tax rates or individual or corporate
income tax hikes.'' Unless he has adopted President Clinton's style
of splitting legal hairs, this seems to rule out taxes that are
often paraded as something else, such as user fees, gasoline taxes
and tobacco fines.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Bush do this? He's so far ahead in the presidential
polls he could have survived the pressure on him from tax-cut
radicals demanding he take the rigid pledge already made by his
less popular rivals. So far, they need him more than he needs them.
He can write his own script; he doesn't have to take orders or play
copy-cat.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, the first primary state, loves low taxes.
Genuflecting to that sentiment is expected of GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, New Hampshire isn't the nation. In poll after poll,
voters put issues that require government activism, such as better
education and protection of Social Security, ahead of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   So far the primaries are not Bush's biggest problem. No
Republican contender comes within a mile of him.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, his problem will be the general election in
November 2000, facing Vice President Al Gore. (Trust me: it won't
be ex-Sen. Bill Bradley).
</P>
<P>
   Bush beats Gore in the trial heats at the moment, but a savvy
sitting vice president is no patsy. And with Monica gone and the
Kosovo war crisis fading, Gore may well wriggle clear of the worst
Clinton administration baggage and advance his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush is playing it safe by hewing to GOP tax cut
orthodoxy, voters don't yet know much about him. He has forfeited
an opportunity to project an image of a truly independent, new
breed Republican who could overcome the partisan polarization in
Washington and keep the country moving. Sadly and suddenly, he
looks like the same old scorpion out of the same old bottle.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to governing than being a skinflint and lowering
taxes, as Bush knows.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he has been getting at with his emphasis on
``compassionate conservatism.'' A president is not just a stingy
national bookkeeper. He is supposed to help government better serve
its people, which means backing policies and projects that cost
money and must be paid for somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Texas Sen. Phil Gramm crowed after a government
shutdown following the 1995 budget stalemate that nobody would miss
the bureaucrats? Well, it turned out people did miss them and the
services they provided. His GOP presidential candidacy evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Democratic presidential nominee Walter Mondale
carried only one state in 1984 after admitting he would hike taxes,
no politician has dared to confess favoring that means of
revenue-raising. But to go so far in the other direction as to
eliminate in advance a potential financial tool that may later be
required to keep the budget balanced or perpetuate badly needed
programs is equally foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, the younger Bush indicated he had learned a
lesson from his father's bad experience. During the 1988 GOP
convention President Bush had vowed, ``Read my lips: No new
taxes.'' But two years later, he was forced to break that promise
to reach a budget agreement with the Democratic-controlled Congress
aimed at stimulating the economy and fending off a recession that
threatened his re-election. The president lost to Bill Clinton four
years later at least in part because his opponents mocked him for
that reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his father's big mistake was in making the promise
or in breaking it, George W. Bush replied, ``I think making it, for
certain. Once he made it and broke it, it cost him a lot of
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But now George W. has voluntarily walked into the same verbal
trap. He has needlessly limited his operational options. After all,
a little user fee here and a tobacco tax there are not going to
drive voters screaming into the hills.
</P>
<P>
   And the trap comes with a new catch. Why should voters believe
he'll stick to his promise when his father couldn't do so? There's
an old saying: Fool me once, shame on you. Fool me twice, shame on
me.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cutting ideologues who persuaded Bush to do this contend
that he won't be caught in the same bind as his father because
times have changed. The nation is prosperous, the federal budget
has a surplus and tax-cutting Republicans control Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So what? The economic and political conditions that prevail
today may be gone tomorrow. Prosperity can wane. The GOP can lose
control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   No, Bush has taken a reckless, unprovoked risk. And since he has
matched the other GOP candidates in a no-new-taxes pledge, the
primary campaign issues will inevitably move to stickier areas.
</P>
<P>
   How to divide the federal pie without increased revenues? How to
boost military spending without touching Social Security and
slam-dunking the federal budget? Whose favorite domestic program is
to go?
</P>
<P>
   The fun has only begun.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
