<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-ADVISOR     06-10 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(jt)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories on Kosovo
for Friday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels) _ NATO suspended the bombing of Yugoslavia
Thursday afternoon, after confirming that Serbian troops had begun
withdrawing from Kosovo hours earlier. The halt after 78 days set
the stage for a United Nations Security Council resolution that
permits 50,000 international peacekeepers to move in on Friday to
help a million and a half ethnic Albanian refugees try to go home.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton to address the
nation from the Oval office at 8 p.m. ET regarding the end of NATO
bombing and the agreement between NATO and Yugoslavia. By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ United Nations Security Council
takes up, and is expected to pass, Kosovo resolution. By Judith
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FORCE (Skopje, Yugoslavia) _ NATO Thursday night abrubtly
scrubbed plans for a dawn entry into Kosovo by British
paratroopers, putting its peacekeeping operation on at least a
24-hour hold. The plan, which had been kept secret, was quietly
cancelled tonight, as was a technical and logistical briefing that
had been scheduled earlier in the day, at which NATO officers had
said they would outline the deployment of the various forces,
predominantly British, French, Italian and American at this point,
and their schedule for entering Kosovo behind the departing Serb
forces. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ U.S. and Russian representatives begin
to hash out the Russian role in the peacekeeping force in
Yugoslavia. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ As the long army convoy
roared out of Kosovo Thursday, beginning a defeated Serbia's
painful retreat from its historical heartland, a military policeman
in his black beret snapped a salute to each passing vehicle, tears
streaming down his face. Small knots of Serbs gathered quietly on
Podujevo's streetcorners in the wearying sun as the long column
moved past. Soldiers rode in military trucks and civilian busses,
and in passenger cars of every kind. Trucks full of stretchers
moved past, then portable kitchens and armored personnel carriers.
The Serbs stood shocked, pale and still, as if their blood was
draining into the gutter. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ There were shouts of joy in
the refugee camps last night as Kosovar Albanians crowded around
radios to hear the news of peace in the Balkans. But on Thursday
morning after, most said that they were too frightened for now to
rush back across the border and would wait for assurances from NATO
and humanitarian agencies that Kosovo was safe. Some said they
expected to remain in the camps for as long as two more months,
even though many are only an hour's drive from home. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In another attack by Republicans
on President Clinton's policies, the House debates measures that
would bar funds for peacekeepers in Kosovo. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ President Slobodan Milosevic spoke
to his people Thursday in a televised address, wishing them a happy
peace and calling the servicemen who died heroes, who gave their
lives in the struggle for freedom and dignity. ''The aggression is
over. Happy peace to us all,'' he said, standing stiffly in his
trademark blue suit by the fireplace of a state room in the White
Palace. It was his first speech to the public since last October
and the first time he has attempted to justify the conflict with
NATO to the people of Serbia. By Carlotta Gill.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-TROOPS (Petrovic, Macedonia) _ More than 3,000
American ground troops poured into dusty, makeshift camps near the
airport here Thursday, as the United States scrambled to amass its
contribution to a peacekeeping operation in Kosovo fraught with
risks and uncertain support back home. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
