<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-900&AMP;ADD     06-10 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS IN HEAVILY ALBANIAN CITY FEAR REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODUJEVO, Yugoslavia _ As the long army convoy roared out of
Kosovo Thursday, beginning a defeated Serbia's painful retreat from
its historical heartland, a military policeman in his black beret
snapped a salute to each passing vehicle, tears streaming down his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Small knots of Serbs gathered quietly on Podujevo's street
corners in the wearying sun as the long column moved past. Soldiers
rode in military trucks and civilian buses, and in passenger cars
of every kind. Trucks full of stretchers moved past, then portable
kitchens and armored personnel carriers. The Serbs stood shocked,
pale and still, as if their blood was draining into the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all we have,'' one man said quietly. ``There's no one
here now to defend us. Now they'll try to cut my throat any way
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   He fears revenge from the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army, he
said, gesturing toward this city's burned and looted streets.
Podujevo was 95 percent Albanian before this passionate and
murderous war of expulsion, threat and panic began. Most of this
city's 1,500 or so Serbs have already left, and Vukasin Zivaljevic
was planning to leave Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got until the evening to pack my stuff and get out,'' he
said, beginning to shake. ``Because tonight I think the KLA will
come back to town.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the municipal building, Srbislav Bisercic, head of
the Podujevo administration, tried to persuade Serbs to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's futile,'' he told a foreign reporter. ``I told you months
ago what would happen, that all the Serbs here would leave. It's
easy for the Serbs in Pristina or Srbica or Kosovo Polje or
Gnjilane to stay; it's like Serbia for them. It's very difficult to
be a Serb in Podujevo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bisercic, a competent and imposing man, is furious that the
arrangements between NATO and Yugoslavia have left a vacuum that is
sucking the Serbs out of Podujevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav army and police are leaving and where are the
troops of the United Nations?'' he asked. ``They should be here now
to protect and guarantee the security and free movement of both the
Serbs and the Albanians. Of course there is panic among the people
now. They're terrified, they're afraid of revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milenkovic, the head of the local chapter of the
Yugoslav Red Cross, had the first drink of his life on Thursday.
``For 53 years I haven't drunk a drop,'' he said, spilling some
raki, the local plum brandy, from his shaking hands. He downed it
quickly, then Bisercic poured him another.
</P>
<P>
   Milenkovic has worked for the Red Cross for nine years, and
before a foreigner, he began to plead his case. ``Of course the big
majority of the help is for the Albanians, because they are the
majority here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just Wednesday, he said, he helped city officials bring 205
Albanians, mostly women and children, into town from the burned-out
village of Metohija, where they were living out in the open and
unable to get enough supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Albanians return us one part of the good, we local
Serbs will be fine,'' Milenkovic said. ``But one part of the
Albanians prepare a real revenge, and everyone knows it. It doesn't
matter who is guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who, then, is responsible for the devastation of the
Albanian areas of Podujevo, Milenkovic insisted: ``Outsiders.'' He
said plaintively: ``We were scared ourselves of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bisercic said that local Serbs did not do the damage, but did
not deny that it was an organized rampage to drive the Albanians
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy is the policy,'' he said finally, throwing up his
hands. ``And policy is like a prostitute, and it doesn't have a
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall of his office, Bisercic has a calendar from the
Socialist Party of Serbia, the ruling party of President Slobodan
Milosevic. Sparkling young people ride a jeep on a beach, looking
like an ad for the Gap. It is a surreal touch in this dingy office,
where the bulky, ancient police radio is silent and cigarette ash
dusts everything, and where Bisercic knows that his power _ and
that of his president _ is quickly slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we Serbs will start to speak English,'' he suddenly said,
laughing bitterly. But Bisercic, who has always packed a pistol,
says he will stay in Podujevo no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Vuceta Djordjevic, 52, is in a hurry. He wants to pack his house
and his family and go, by Friday at the latest. He lives in a small
mixed village two miles from here called Perane, and he will move
his wife, three children and six grandchildren to Kursumlija,
outside Kosovo, where he has relatives.
</P>
<P>
   If he can, he says, he'll take his pigs and cattle, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born here, and my father and my grandfather,''
Djordjevic said, wringing his scarred farmer's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians are gone from Perane, their homes and stables
burned and trashed, and Djordjevic, who says he did nothing bad to
anyone, is afraid to be home when they return _ or more precisely,
when the fighters of the KLA return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm afraid of the KLA coming down from the forest,''
he said. ``The KLA used to dig their trenches on my land. Now we
have no army and no police and no guards, and who will guarantee my
safety? The international forces are not here to guarantee
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Djordjevic, like Milenkovic, will go but says he wants to come
back. ``Where else have I to live?'' he asks. ``I have no other
house. The graves of my parents are here, and of my grandparents.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night in Pristina, as the news spread about the
coming withdrawal of the Yugoslav army, people shot thousands of
rounds of ammunition into the air.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, at the Corzo cafe, where many Albanians
also take a morning espresso, the song on the sound system pleaded:
``Stay! Don't run away. Please! Just for one more day. Don't be
walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   A young Yugoslav soldier, Stevan Lazarevic, said he mostly felt
sad _ at the loss of friends, at the stupidity of the war. ``No one
here feels defeated,'' he said. ``But there is a lot of anger at
Belgrade, at people who can't live without elevators and water for
more than a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   He was awaiting orders, but he would go home to Nis, he said.
And he was proud of his service, and of his comrades.
</P>
<P>
   A former soldier, Sasa, who served seven months last year in
Kosovo and now works for a Western news agency, said he was
relieved to be alive. But he was also completely depressed, he
said. ``It's not just the loss of Kosovo, which no foreigner can
really understand. It's all the death and pain. I saw 250 dead
civilians with my own eyes, killed by NATO bombs, and it will be
offensive to hear NATO come in and talk of humanism and morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the roads, stretching beyond the destroyed homes and shops
and farms, the meadows blaze with lavender and red flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The red flowers are known as ``bozur,'' and are said to
represent the Serbian blood that has flowed in the defense of
Kosovo. ``This whole land is watered with blood, Serb and
Albanian,'' said a mobilized soldier, hitching a ride, glad to have
survived this latest bloodletting and sure that it will not be the
last.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gazimestan monument on Thursday, on Kosovo Polje, ``the
field of blackbirds,'' where the Serbs lost to the Turks and
founded their national myth, weeds are growing between the tan
stones. The Serbian restaurant there is destroyed, its windows
gaping.
</P>
<P>
   This is where, in 1989, a gray party secretary from the capital
of Belgrade, Slobodan Milosevic, catapulted to power when he
promised thousands of anxious Serbs that ``no one will beat you
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a visitor stepped carefully, looking for land
mines. On the monument, stuck into an iron Serbian sword, lay one
bozur flower, faded to a pale orange by the sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
