<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-11LIMBO-COX     06-10 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-11LIMBO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The wait in 'Limbo' saved by the acting
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are good reasons why mainstream audiences
don't clamor to see a John Sayles movie. He's drawn to commercially
inert subject matter, from rankled labor unions to obscure Irish
folklore, on which he heaps sociopolitical freight that causes
old-fashioned entertainment to wheeze and buckle. Moviegoers, bless
their souls, know a chore when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   What the masses risk missing are films of singular, if raw,
compassion and often cutting social insight. For all his noble
pretensions, Sayles' films are finally about people and place. In
works as varied as ``Matewan,'' ``Passion Fish'' and ``Lone Star,''
he alights on universal truths and reveals stuff about us we aren't
always prepared to embrace in the relaxing gloom of the movie
house.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as engaging as Sayles' films are, they always feel slightly
lumpy, forced, attenuated. Like Paul Schrader _ another
intellectual striving for artistic grace _ Sayles' boldfaced themes
don't always dovetail with his narrative ambitions. He has yet to
make a perfect picture.
</P>
<P>
   His new drama, ``Limbo,'' is far from perfect, but it pulls you
in with its storytelling risks and bumps, its unpredictable arc,
its maddeningly rough edges. The story, frankly, is a mess, and
Sayles throws structure and consistency of tone to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Limbo'' is vintage Sayles, a ponderous thematic cue
to the condition of the main characters' fissured lives. Set in
contemporary Juneau, Alaska, the story starts wide, encompassing an
Altmanesque menagerie of chattering characters. The scope slowly
tapers, until the third act, where we're left in the intimate
company of single-mother Donna (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio), her
teen-age daughter Noelle (Vanessa Martinez), and Joe Gastineau
(David Strathairn). In a dramatic snap that feels misplaced here,
the trio has been marooned on a small, uninhabited island in the
Alaskan wilderness, and this is where they will stay until the
final, perplexing frame.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles has made two movies here and pushed them into an uneasy
marriage of social critique and domestic rumblings. The switch is
jarring but oddly compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles has real feeling for regional flavors, and he begins
``Limbo'' exerting this knack (with fine help from veteran
cinematographer Haskell Wexler). Right off, he places Alaska's
mushrooming tourist industry in his editorial cross hairs and
illustrates how traditional Alaskan vocations, like fishing and
lumber, are being blotted out. Sayles' instinct for platitudes, and
his ineptitude at irony, blare in these scenes. In condescending
tones we hear about the Disney-fication of the region _ including
tin-eared quips at the expense of geriatric cruise-ship passengers
_ and we're even subjected to a stop-the-action-dead jeremiad from
a disgruntled fishery worker.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles' rote soapbox liberalism abruptly gives way to the story
of frazzled bar singer Donna; her petulant daughter, who's had
enough of her mother's flaky love life; and the man who quietly
enters their lives. If not for the commanding performance of
Mastrantonio as the good but distracted mother and newcomer
Martinez's fiercely persuasive turn as Noelle, this slice of the
story would languish in domestic banality. The actors make it
consistently fresh and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Strathairn's Joe is haunted by a fishing accident he was a part
of 25 years ago, in which two men were killed. He has shriveled
into himself, tiptoeing life's sidelines _ drifting in limbo. He is
painfully reticent, his rugged face a mask of melancholy and shame.
He looks halfway between a brood and a beaten-dog flinch. It's a
great and affecting performance.
</P>
<P>
   When the three of them become stranded for a long time in the
freezing woods, courtesy of twists I'll leave alone, they are given
the time and enforced intimacy with which to unpack and sort their
tangled problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lengthy stretch of the movie, and it feels tacked on,
like pants that don't fit. Several interludes showing Noelle
reading aloud from a diary she finds in a derelict forest dwelling
simply don't work and reveal Sayles' schematic writing and a
tone-deafness for hard emotional truths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo's'' rash ending will annoy some people as much as it
leaves others (myself included) in a state of liberated expectation
_ something few movies would trust to leave with an audience. It
doesn't so much show its ending as it does deposit it.
</P>
<P>
   The end works because the key plot strands have been resolved;
the characters have changed. Any other conclusion would have been
pat or, worse, overwrought. Its sheer unorthodoxy, much like the
whole of the film, is its own payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo''
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, David Strathairn, Vanessa
Martinez, Kris Kristofferson
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Sayles
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: John Sayles
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for language, intense drama and adult themes
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 2 hours, 6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
