<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAYLES11-COX     06-10 1668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAYLES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horror scripts finance Sayles' own ideas
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ During ``QTIII,'' the film festival thrown here
by Quentin Tarantino in February, Tarantino screened the 1980
B-horror curiosity ``Alligator.'' The movie, dreadful but harmless,
was a fatuous genre piece whose thin camp patina quickly curdled
into I-get-the-joke tedium. With predictable hyperbole, Tarantino
championed the virtues of ``Alligator,'' not the least of which was
the witty, fist-tight script by John Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time in his career, under contract to B-movie
impresario Roger Corman, one could argue Sayles harbored a perverse
penchant for flesh-snarfing beasts. Besides ``Alligators,'' he
wrote the 1978 ``Jaws'' spoof ``Piranha'' and 1980's werewolf orgy
``The Howling.'' Of course, as the active quintessence of American
independent filmmaking, Sayles has gone on to write and direct (and
edit and act in) such respectable adult fare as ``Matewan,''
``Passion Fish'' and ``Lone Star.''
</P>
<P>
   (Although this didn't stop him from hiring out his writing
talents for ``Mimic,'' Guillermo Del Toro's 1997 shriek-fest about
_ chomp, gulp _ mutant cockroaches that prey on humans.)
</P>
<P>
   Paychecks from the horror movies (blood money?) have enabled
Sayles to finance his own films, beginning with the $40,000 ``Big
Chill'' precursor ``The Return of the Secaucus Seven'' in 1980.
Films quivering with an earnest social consciousness followed,
including ``The Brother From Another Planet,'' ``Eight Men Out,''
``City of Hope'' and last year's somewhat lugubrious ``Men With
Guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with a well-developed sense of social justice and
political rectitude, Sayles consistently demonstrates a probing
interest in the ethnography of disparate cultural regions. His
films have perceptively painted the social textures and human
dynamics of the American inner city, Irish coast, Mexican border,
Deep South and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Limbo,'' Sayles' 12th film as writer-director, Alaska is
the latest frontier the filmmaker charts. The film, an existential
drama about three people trapped in the Alaskan wilds, begins as a
pointed commentary on the region's shift from a trove of natural
resources to a tawdry tourist playground. Opening today, the film
stars Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio and Sayles' regulars David
Strathairn and Kris Kristofferson.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles got the idea when he and his producer/life partner Maggie
Renzi visited Alaska 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's less than a million people in Alaska, yet it's our
largest state,'' says Sayles about what drew him there. ``It's
still a place where most of the people I meet were not born there.
They came there and they're doing something or being something that
never would have been possible in the lower 48. ... It's changing
very rapidly, and a lot of the first third of the movie deals with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   At 48, the sometime novelist remains one of Hollywood's most
sought-after script doctors. In 1995, he lost an arbitration fight
with the Writer's Guild of America to receive screen credit for his
rewrite of ``Apollo 13''; Texas scribes William Broyles Jr. and Al
Reinert got credit. He also takes small roles in others' films,
including Jonathan Demme's ``Something Wild'' and Spike Lee's
``Malcolm X.'' This mercenary work allows Sayles to make his own
movies, on which he demands, and enjoys, the right to final cut.
</P>
<P>
   We recently spoke with Sayles by phone from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Unlike some of your recent films, ``Limbo'' seems more
concerned with existential quandaries, as opposed to social and
political issues.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah. I think of it as a movie about the concept of risk. For
me what limbo represents, going on the Catholic version I was given
growing up, is that it's infinite, there's no end to it, and it's
between heaven and hell. I think a lot of people live in these
kinds of personal limbos, where it's not hell, it's not that awful,
but the fear of falling into some kind of hell, the fear of
failure, is so great that they don't get themselves out of a bad
marriage or a job they hate. In order to get out of that kind of
limbo, you do have to risk. Real risk is when you don't know how
it's going to turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the Alaskan setting provide ample opportunity for social
and economic commentary?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think it's unavoidable. If you talk about a place you
have to show what the place is like and what's happening to it.
It's a good metaphor for what's happening to the characters. Here's
a place that even 15 years ago an awful lot of the jobs were all
men. An awful lot of the jobs were jobs that called for physical
risk. You were a lumberjack or a commercial fisherman or you worked
on the oil pipeline. More and more, those jobs are being phased-out
or the risk is being regulated out of them and the jobs are in the
tourist industry, where you're selling the illusion of risk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You do considerable research for your films; ``Lone Star''
and ``Men With Guns'' come to mind. Did you do much on the Alaskan
way of life?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'll have an idea for something and I'll know something about
the place, so I'll read about it and whatever. In the last several
movies I've gone to the place just before I've written the script.
I have the story in my head so I'm able to go there almost as a
reporter with a shopping list of facts and conversations I want to
have with local people. The last thing I do is when we get to the
place with a written screenplay and the budget, I'll select various
people in the community and show them the script and ask them if
there's anything that strikes them as being totally inaccurate. We
get a lot of good information from people. Sometimes it's something
that just affects the art director or the costume person. For
instance, I originally had (David Strathairn's character) being a
purse seiner (a type of fisherman), which requires a bigger boat.
And local people said if he's just getting back into fishing and
he's throwing this thing back together really quickly, it's much
more likely he'd be a gill-netter, which is much simpler. That kind
of stuff is very useful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it a great visual feast out there?
</P>
<P>
   A: I keep saying it's the only movie where I've had to yell
``cut'' because there were whales breaching in the background,
upstaging our actors. It's a place where you can truly turn 360
degrees and not see anything man-made. And we were only 40 miles
out of the capital city. You can take a 10-minute walk from
downtown Juneau and be attacked by a bear. Nature is that close to
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your films are sometimes criticized for being preachy and
didactic. ``Limbo'' seems to steer away from heavy pamphleteering.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, but you know, that's just b.s., so ... (Laughs.) It
doesn't steer away from it, it's just harder for someone to say
that about the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Critics have their opinions, but what in your own words
interests you as a storyteller and filmmaker?
</P>
<P>
   A: I really have never thought of what I've done as a career.
I've just done one movie at a time. I'm certainly interested in
community and the fact that in the United States we really don't
live in a traditional society. It's always been a place where
people are more mobile, where people tend not to do the same thing
their fathers and grandfathers did for a living. We're a young
country and most of our history has been since the time of mass
communications. So I find that people find and build communities
that aren't necessarily based on geography. You live in a big city
and you don't know the people in your apartment building, but you
may be into poetry and you know every place where people read
poetry. That's your community.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it still hard to get a film made?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it is. We've been very lucky with the last couple.
With ``Lone Star'' I was working as a writer for Castle Rock and
they asked if I had anything I wanted to direct, and I said no, but
that I could in a couple of weeks. In the case of ``Limbo,'' we
just went to Sony and said, ``Here's a screenplay, here's a budget,
are you interested?'' In the case of something much less commercial
like ``Men With Guns'' I just started making that with my own
money, and luckily the producers were able to find investors to
take me off the hook. I've made 12 movies now, so people have a
track record to look at. That both helps us and hurts us. We've
never made anybody $100 million. On the other hand, our movies have
come in on budget and some people have really liked them and
they've been pretty much what the screenplay said they were going
to be, so you know what you're getting into as an investor.
</P>
<P>
   The Sayles file
</P>
<P>
   Born: Sept. 28, 1950, in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Early career: Works in a factory in East Boston while writing
short stories, one of which evolves into the 1975 novel, ``Pride of
the Bimbos.'' Sayles' other novels include ``Union Dues'' (1977)
and ``Los Gusanos'' (1991), as well as the short story collection
``The Anarchists Convention'' (1979).
</P>
<P>
   Film career break: Roger Corman hires Sayles as screenwriter in
the late '70s. He pens ``Piranha,'' the first of almost 30 scripts
he will work on over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: Oscar nominee for best screenplay for ``Passion Fish''
(1992) and ``Lone Star'' (1996). Received a MacArthur Foundation
Fellowship ``genius'' grant in 1983, for which he was given a
tax-free income of $32,000 a year for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director filmography:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Limbo'' (1999)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Men With Guns'' (1997)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Lone Star'' (1996)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Secret of Roan Inish'' (1994)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Passion Fish'' (1992)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``City of Hope'' (1991)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Eight Men Out'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Matewan'' (1987)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Brother From Another Planet'' (1984)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Baby, It's You'' (1983)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Lianna'' (1983)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Return of the Secaucus Seven'' (1980)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
