<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0696 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FENGSHUI-AZR &LR;      06-10 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENGSHUI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANCIENT CHINESE ART OF PLACEMENT  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, MAY 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
By JAIMEE ROSE  
c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Do you know where your trash cans are?
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the sink,'' ``my neighbor's back yard'' and ``duh'' are
not viable answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My love corner,'' ``my career area'' and ``my wealth
quadrant'' are.
</P>
<P>
   According to feng shui, an ancient Chinese art of placement and
decorating that divides the home into nine areas that represent
aspects of life, the location of unsightly junk cans could be the
culprit behind caustic spouses or cooled creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Simply said, wherever there's clutter in the home, there's
clutter in one's life. Thus, according to feng shui masters, a
trash can in the creativity area is writer's block explained.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we reveal how to make the house a home shui home.
</P>
<P>
   First, a quick lesson in the basics.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui (pronounced fung shway) has been around for 3,000
years. As with any age-old idea, it has branched out and been
interpreted many different ways, resulting in a number of
``schools'' of thought. For our purposes, we will use the intuitive
school.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui is based on the flow of ``chi,'' or energy. When chi
is allowed to flow freely through the home, it creates a healthy,
happy atmosphere for inhabitants. When chi is blocked by unpleasing
or messy objects, it cuts the good vibes.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a little karma-crazy? Take it from Scottsdale's Karen
Way, doctor of sociology turned feng shui master: This stuff works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a self-fulfilling prophecy,'' she says. ``What
we surround ourselves with reflects who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the trash-can-placement issue.
</P>
<P>
   Way suggests placing items in areas symbolically. If the goal is
to feel more unified with a spouse, hang art selected together in
the marriage corner. If better health is a priority, place a
vibrant plant in that area. If making a good name for oneself is
needed, purge the fame and reputation quadrant of all trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   The quadrants of feng shui that represent aspects of the human
experience are mapped on an octagon shape called the bagua map,
which is to be laid over the floor plan of the home to determine
which areas fall into these categories.
</P>
<P>
   The bagua and feng shui can be applied to gardens, office
cubicles and even cars, but today, home is where our heart is.
</P>
<P>
   Because Arizona homes are about as likely to be shaped like a
stop sign as they are to be made out of anything other than stucco,
Way has supplied a square bagua, courtesy of the Western School of
Feng Shui in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The squares each are associated with a certain color, and the
five anchoring squares have been assigned one of feng shui's five
foremost materials: earth, water, wood, fire and metal.
</P>
<P>
   Those designations have been around for three millennia, so Way
isn't sure how they came about. But most of them tend to echo the
feelings that are ideal in those areas of life.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to have all of the materials and colors balanced,
leading to a balanced life, but if you're seeking to enhance a
certain area, a little more of the recommended color or material
would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui has been experiencing a revival as of late. It now has
its own magazine, its own section in the bookstore, and a rash of
Internet sites dedicated to the ancient art.
</P>
<P>
   Way believes feng shui's new forest of followers sought it out
because the '80s were about excess and the '90s are about
clutter-free simplicity, which is at the heart of feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   And now, a step-by-step, square-by-square guide to making the
home karma-compatible:
</P>
<P>
   - We'll start with the entrance quadrant, which contains the
career, knowledge/self-cultivation, and helpful people/travel
squares. Align this side of the map with the front of your house,
or the side facing the street. If your front door happens to be on
the side, that's OK. You will just enter into a different area.
</P>
<P>
   The center quadrant often contains the garage. As Way says,
``there's nowhere to hide from feng shui eyes,'' so keep it clean.
And don't be afraid to hang pictures on the walls. She's seen it
done.
</P>
<P>
   The front, center square signifies the career. Pay extra
attention to this square if you're starting a new job, want a new
job or are looking for volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   Obstacles, such as protruding furniture in this area, are bad.
They symbolize obstacles in the career path. Water, such as from a
miniature fountain, is the chief element in this area and is good.
It equals the flow of success. Make sure it flows toward the house
and not away from it. The key colors in this area are appropriately
powerful: black, navy blue, anything dark in tone. Think power
suit.
</P>
<P>
   - Moving clockwise, we come to the knowledge/self-cultivation
area. Enhance this section if you are in school, counseling, or
want a more peaceful mind or lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Do's in this segment are books, tapes or any other study
materials. This segment is associated with mountains, and blacks,
blues and greens. Think of those mountainous ``success'' posters
embraced by self-help gurus. They're great wall decorations for
this area.
</P>
<P>
   - Health/family is next. If your in-laws are making you nuts,
your health could use a boost, or sports are on the agenda, pay
extra attention here. Put up a few photos of the in-laws in
question. Healthy plants, according to Way, will help you feel
better, as will fresh flowers of all colors. Wood, not
surprisingly, is the key element. Blues and greens are the colors.
Family pictures should occupy the walls. Fountain Hills resident
Sharon Braverman's key family members are her dogs, whose furry
mugs are framed in this area.
</P>
<P>
   - Moving on, we stop in wealth/prosperity. If you need more of
this (and who doesn't?), listen up. Items that ``call the chi,'' or
get the energy flow really excited, are appropriate here, Way says.
Examples of chi enhancers are wind chimes, windsocks and flags.
</P>
<P>
   Display valuable possessions, such as antiques or art here _
even better if they're blue, purple or red. Water flow is key here,
too; it symbolizes cash flow. A pretty ``prosperity bowl'' is
another idea _ fill it with 20- and 100-dollar bills. It is
believed that if you have money in your presence, you'll have money
in your wallet.
</P>
<P>
   - Fame/reputation follows wealth. Here's a good place for a
trophy case, things relating to fire such as candles or bright
lights, and reds. Think of the bright lights of Broadway. If you've
got a fave celeb, display his or her mug here.
</P>
<P>
   - Next comes love/marriage, Way's specialty. Focus here if you
want to improve relationships with others or your personal self or
start a new relationship. She says posters or pictures of that
special someone should go here. If he or she doesn't exist, cut out
Mr. Right from a magazine. This is all about self-affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Pairs of things are good _ doves, hearts, dolphins or other
symbols of love. Colors should range in the Valentine's Day
spectrum _ pinks, red, white, peach. Honeymoon mementos should be
located here.
</P>
<P>
   If equality among partners is an issue, make sure each partner
has his or her own night stand, and make sure they're the same
size.
</P>
<P>
   - First came love, paired with marriage, now we've come to the
baby in the baby carriage, or the children/creativity square,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Writer's block sufferers, pay at tention. Baby-hungry couples,
read on. This area should be attended to. Posters, paintings or
collages of or by children are good for the walls here. Art that
stimulates creative juices is another option. White and pastels _
think nursery _ are the colors. Metal _ think creativity conducting
_ is the material; use it in furniture or picture frames.
</P>
<P>
   - Travel/helpful people is next. If mentors are needed or a
vacation is coming up, this should be an area of emphasis. Statues
of angels or other famous helpers are good decorations. Travel
posters are good. Gray, white and black are the colors. Religious
books would be intelligently located here.
</P>
<P>
   - Last is the center square. Way has been called to
consultations by people who feel ``scattered,'' and she often finds
that the reason is an unstable center. Ground it with the earth
element, which is key here. Yellows and earth tones are
appropriate; a display of pretty pottery also could be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Try to make the center a peaceful place. Sometimes, the center
of a home is occupied by an intersection of rooms. This can be hard
to stabilize, but be sure to know where the center is and keep it
clear of clutter. If you have a floor that is tiled, you're set in
this area, as tile generally is made of earth or clay.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Way recommends hanging a desert landscape painting on
one of the intersecting walls, or trying some earth-colored chi
enhancers. Just be sure to recognize it, keep it organized, and try
to incorporate earth elements.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the end of our feng shui tour.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, as you take your own home tour, to strive for
balance of all of the elements _ earth, water, wind, fire and
metal. This will keep the chi flowing and your good karma going.
Emphasize things you like, but don't leave out others.
</P>
<P>
   If your house overall lacks the element of fire, including
candles or red tones, you'll lack energy. Too much energy? Cool it
off by adding water.
</P>
<P>
   Balanced feng shui leads to a balanced life, according to Way,
but she stresses this:
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get from A to Z without working the letters in
between. I cannot guarantee that feng shui will bring husbands
back, make (people) rich, or make a fabulous career fall onto their
laps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can guarantee is that feng shui can make their homes a
haven _ a springboard from which they can make positive changes in
their lives and create the results they want.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for those dumpsters, well, the neighbor's yard?
(Kidding.) Try one with a lid, keep it emptied, and place it in an
inconspicuous place located in one of the squares that you've got
going strong. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
