<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GETREAL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Get Real' tells truth with humor
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``I came late to sex,'' says Steven Carter (Ben
Silverstone) in Simon Shore's infectious film ``Get Real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nearly 10,'' he tells us, and as we watch the opening
shots of a young Steven swinging on the playground, we get a
familiar montage of images that has become cinematic shorthand for
kids learning about sexual intercourse: squirming students in
health class, hilariously brief conversations between parents and
their children, and bungled explanations whispered between
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its familiarity, ``Get Real'' is an insightful,
often original film about coming-of-age and coming out in
contemporary middle-class Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A queer John Hughes movie'' is how one savvy viewer described
the film. ``Get Real'' has all the appeal of Hughes' comical high
school scenarios, but with a gay main character and a better
ending. Also, Patrick Wilde's script subtly addresses class issues
that are either overdramatized or often completely absent in most
movies set in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Although he may have come late to sex, Steven realized he was
gay at the tender age of 11. His perceptiveness is all the more
poignant when we see him sitting nervously on a park bench hoping
to ``meet'' someone outside the men's bathroom. When he actually
does make contact, it turns out to be with the sexually confused
school stud (Brad Gorton).
</P>
<P>
   Balancing out Steven's low-key sense of humor is his
over-the-top next-door neighbor and best friend, Linda (Charlotte
Brittain), who would be perfect for the next John Waters movie.
Linda is a refreshingly secure, zaftig young woman who enjoys
dressing up: Camryn Manheim for the junior set. Linda nearly makes
the movie, and when matched with the engaging Steven, ``Get Real''
becomes that rare thing, a high school movie with characters you
actually like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' is also the title of an essay that Steven writes as
a member of the school magazine. Without revealing his identity,
Steven details what it's like to be a gay teen-ager in the 1990s,
particularly difficult in a culture renowned for its stiff upper
lip. This essay represents Steven's reality more accurately than
the article he submits for a newspaper competition in which each
entrant must explain what it means to be a contemporary teen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' languishes during the bits of business needed to
flesh out the larger story, and it uses a rather workmanlike
approach to deal with miscellaneous supporting characters. But the
film's finest moment is its climactic outing, set appropriately
enough in the school auditorium. The scene is reminiscent of the
revelatory sequence in ``In &AMP; Out,'' when Kevin Kline's character
reveals his sexual orientation to a salivating audience ready for
full disclosure. In keeping with the tone of ``In &AMP; Out,'' Kline's
unveiling is played for laughs, but in ``Get Real,'' the more
realistic response to Steven's admission reverberates profoundly.
</P>
<P>
   The final scenes of ``Get Real'' are a vicarious thrill for
anyone who's ever suffered through high school's indignities. What
makes the conclusion so satisfying, though, is Steven's triumph in
making a private battle public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real''
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Ben Silverstone, Brad Gorton, Charlotte Brittain
</P>
<P>
   Director: Simon Shore
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: Patrick Wilde
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for nudity, sexual situations, strong language
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
