<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-AUSTIN11-COX     06-10 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AUSTIN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Powers' on best behavior
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mike Myers knows how to milk a joke till it's
chapped. It's a trick he learned in his years at ``Saturday Night
Live,'' where even the lamest gags are stretched, wrung, diced and
cannibalized. And their poor corpses aren't buried. They're turned
into movies.
</P>
<P>
   Myers milks hard in ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,''
the tonic, joyously crude sequel to 1997's hit James Bond spoof
``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery,'' which introduced
us to the era-hopping British secret agent.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for him, that's part of the joke _ to watch Myers and his
motley screenmates ride funny bits until they sputter into the
comic ether. The embarrassed characters just stand there, looking
around like dogs who've wet the carpet, letting out limp, residual
chuckles. Then, as if nothing happened, they troop on to the next
set-up.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the snaggle-toothed agent may dissent, but ``The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' surpasses its predecessor. Overstuffed with wink-nods
and iconoclastic glee (see the pasting Starbucks takes), the new
movie contains more self-reflexive moments like the above. It also
is looser and more wackily ambitious. The writing is savvier and
the jokes funnier, even if the phallic visual puns and fecal
enthusiasm bludgeon instead of tickle. Myers' vanity affair seems
to profit from co-writer Michael McCullers, a former ``SNL''
scribe. Jay Roach returns to direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shagged'' starts where the first ``Austin Powers'' left off _
in Powers' heavily trafficked bedroom, naturally. It's 1999 and
Powers, a trollish figure who's all fur and epileptic twitches, is
basking in postcoital fumes with token babe-heroine Vanessa
Kensington (Elizabeth Hurley). When she exposes that she isn't what
she seems by literally blowing up yet another spy-flick cliche,
Powers turns to us, beams those donkey teeth and exclaims, ``That
means I'm single again!''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for him and us, except that his nemesis, Dr.
Evil (also played by Myers), is responsible for this turn of
events. Which means Dr. Evil is no longer drifting through space in
his Bob's Big Boy vessel and has returned to Earth to vaporize the
joint. Better yet, Dr. Evil has contrived a time machine, in which
he travels back to 1969 to steal Powers' ``mojo'' _ the key to the
spy's unquenchable libido.
</P>
<P>
   British intelligence, led by Basil Exposition (Michael York,
dignity in tact), one-ups Evil with a time-traveling Volkswagen
Bug. To foil the bald baddie, Powers takes it for a spin, right
back to his own swinging '60s. He lands in his London pad, a garish
den of Warholian decadence, where ``Laugh-In'' go-go girls writhe
to Steppenwolf and the Guess Who.
</P>
<P>
   Here Powers hooks up with CIA operative and walking
double-entendre Felicity Shagwell, played by a game but underused
Heather Graham, whose tiny head can hardly contain her blank,
Keane-painting orbs.
</P>
<P>
   Myers gives equal screen time to Dr. Evil, who looks like Uncle
Fester carved from wax. He's a bizarre invention, feyly fellating a
manicured pinky while gurgling baby-talk. Myers also provides him
two hilarious henchman _ an obese Scottish spy named Fat Bastard
(played by Myers, amazingly) and a botched one-eighth-size Dr. Evil
clone, whom he calls Mini-Me (Texas actor Verne Troyer).
</P>
<P>
   ``Shagged'' is great, rude fun, splashed in Blow-Pop colors. I
didn't find the slight comedy half as gut-busting as some
spectators at a preview show (I've never rocked in my chair,
slapped my thigh and made ostrich noises before), but it did
provide an amusing buzz for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, some of these merry young men were busy connecting
the synaptic dots between the rash of satirical allusions and nods
to the first movie, which go well beyond Myers' creative vocabulary
(``shagadelic,'' etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Like the ``Airplane!'' series, ``Powers'' is scorched-earth
parody. The crossfire hits an encyclopedia of pop culture: ``Star
Wars,'' Willie Nelson, ``The Exorcist,'' ``The Island of Dr.
Moreau,'' the Chili's baby-back ribs jingle, ``The Great Santini''
and Chaplin's ``The Great Dictator'' (ingeniously melded in one
scene), all-purpose punchline Jerry Springer, and, of course, the
entire James Bond canon _ from Ursula Andress' white bikini in
``Dr. No'' to the climactic space sequence in ``Moonraker.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this jungle of jokes, the comedy breathes. And
``Powers'' fans can rejoice: From the way this one ends, there's
gonna be a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Mike Myers, Heather Graham, Michael York, Robert
Wagner
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jay Roach
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters: Mike Myers, Michael McCullers
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: PG-13 for sexual innuendo, crude humor, language
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
