<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC WISHES SERBS A ``HAPPY PEACE'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic spoke to his
people on Thursday in a televised address, wishing them a happy
peace and calling the servicemen who died heroes who gave their
lives for freedom and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aggression is over, happy peace to us all,'' he said
standing stiffly in his trademark blue suit by the fireplace of a
state room in the White Palace. It was his first speech to the
public since October and the only time he has personally addressed
the people of Serbia on the conflict with NATO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also gave the first exact figures of Serbian troop fatalities
in the 11 weeks of bombing _ 462 army soldiers and 114 members of
the police forces. ``We shall never be able to repay them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has spoken of much higher casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The president also praised ordinary people for their part. ``The
entire people participated in this war, from babies in hospitals to
intensive-care patients, to soldiers in air-defense positions and
soldiers on the border,'' he said. ``The people are the hero of
this war. This may be the shortest way to sum up this war.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly aware of the growing internal criticism that he put the
country through an ordeal for nothing, Milosevic did not claim
victory. But his speech was a careful presentation of successes of
the people, not of the government or leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never gave up Kosovo,'' he said, sticking to the pledge
often repeated at rallies over the last year. Territorial integrity
and sovereignty are guaranteed, and the United Nations' involvement
is assured, he added.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed responsibility for bringing the United Nations to the
world stage as the foremost organization of world power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have defended the only multiethnic society left over as a
remnant of former Yugoslavia,'' Milosevic said. ``This is another
great achievement of our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He made no mention of NATO troops' arriving in Kosovo, but
promised his people that those forces would serve peace regardless
of their origin, a stark change from the usual government
vilification of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward to the enormous job of reconstructing the
country, Milosevic examined the extraordinary unity that rallied
the Serbian people. ``Never before have our people been so
united,'' he said, ``and never in our history did we have less
cowards who fled the country to await the war's end abroad in
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   That may have been a criticism of the leader of the Democratic
Party, Zoran Djindjic, who spent much of the war in Montenegro
after have received death threats here.
</P>
<P>
   Growing animated, Milosevic said: ``We shall begin rebuilding
our bridges immediately, our factories, our roads. The work ahead
will require great mobilization. I wish all citizens of Yugoslavia
much joy and success in reconstruction of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   As the people of Belgrade relaxed in the sunshine and admitted
their relief that the war was over, Milosevic's political rivals
were calling news conferences and issuing statements, agitating for
change.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Svilanovic, leader of the Civic Alliance, the most liberal
democratic opposition party, if one of the smallest, called for the
federal Assembly to convene to discuss Milosevic's responsibility
for this ``tragic war'' and hold a vote of no confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Former Deputy Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic called for broad
changes in the government and for the expulsion of anti-West
elements. Draskovic, who is widely thought to be negotiating to
return to the government, is trying to oust the extreme
nationalists of the Radical Party from the government coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The radicals' leader, Vojislav Seselj, has threatened to leave
the government when foreign troops enter Kosovo. He is apparently
negotiating with the government. Thursday he said that his party
would make a decision on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
