<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave will subside in the Carolinas on Friday as a push
of ocean-cooled air from the Northeast arrives. Low clouds and
drizzle will persist along the shore where onshore breezes will be
brisk, especially from Cape Hatteras to central Delaware. A large
disturbance south of Cape Cod will progress toward the Middle
Atlantic coast perhaps leading to duller weather this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A ridge of high pressure stretching from the Grand Banks to
eastern Pennsylvania will provide very pleasant conditions along
the Northeast coast with low humidity, abundant sunshine and an
active sea breeze. Farther inland, the return circulation around
the high will direct very warm and more humid air from the Ohio
Valley along the west slopes of the Appalachians into the St.
Lawrence Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Thundershowers will drench many parts of northern Florida,
Georgia and Alabama as a weak disturbance progresses slowly
northwestward. Tropical air will cover the southern Plains, lower
Mississippi and Ohio Valleys. Thunderstorms will develop in a few
places.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with a cooler air mass will be active with several
clusters of thunderstorms from Kansas to Wisconsin. Showers will
linger over the western Dakotas and northeastern Rockies. Some
sunshine will be seen in the eastern Dakotas and northern
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure in Washington state will promote sunny skies and a
significant warming trend for the West. Light onshore winds will
keep patches of fog along the Pacific coast. The Southwest will
return to seasonal heat.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Back-door Front
</P>
<P>
   After temperatures flirted with 100 degrees at Boston on Monday,
readings floundered in the 60s on Thursday in the wake of a
back-door cold front, a moniker bestowed on cold fronts which move
southwestward along the Atlantic seaboard. Such a direction is
contrary to the east-southeast movement of most cold fronts (hence
the name ``back-door''). The chill behind a back-door front is
enhanced as winds from the northeast pass over cool Atlantic
waters. Some New Englanders ascribe the name ``sea turn'' to
back-door fronts, for the chilly ocean winds that follow in its
wake. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
