<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS &LR;      06-10 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS RENEW CALLS FOR MORE BORDER AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Kenedy County is CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers on a House immigration panel called on
the Clinton administration to step up efforts to hire more Border
Patrol agents amid testimony Thursday from ranchers who said the
daily influx of illegal immigrants is causing an increase in
vandalism and burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on Immigration and Claims, said the problems would
only ``worsen with grave consequences'' without more agents and
more deportations of illegal residents.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said more Border Patrol agents
are needed but said it was ``preposterous'' to assert that illegal
immigration had significantly worsened in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no crisis in immigration,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Vance, who lives about a mile north of the U.S.-Mexico
border in Douglas, Ariz., said that until about five years ago he
would see an occasional person entering the United States from
Mexico. Now, he said, he sees dozens of people crossing the
unguarded border near his ranch each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been burglarized, had a truck stolen and property
vandalized,'' Vance told a subcommittee hearing attended by Smith
and Lee. ``The area along the Mexican border has become a no-man's
land where lawlessness prevails.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this situation cannot continue,'' Smith said. He and
other lawmakers from Texas and California have criticized the
Clinton administration in recent weeks for failing to achieve a net
gain of 1,000 Border Patrol agents this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress passed a law mandating the net addition of
1,000 new Border Patrol agents each year through 2001. The idea was
to double the force from 5,000 to 10,000 over five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Immigration and Naturalization Service _ which oversees
the Border Patrol _ is only expected to achieve a net gain of 200
to 400 agents this budget year. The INS plans to hire between 1,000
and 1,200 agents but is expected to lose 800 agents through
attrition. The 1999 budget year ends Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has about 8,000 Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials have acknowledged that the problems described
by ranchers and other people living near the border exist and noted
that they have increased the overall number of Border Patrol
officers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Chulick, an INS spokeswoman, said in an interview that
the agency has had problems recruiting and retaining personnel
because of strong economy and the relatively low $23,000 starting
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin Armstrong, a rancher in Kenedy County, Texas, also spoke
of an increase in the flow of illegal immigrants through his
county, which is on the Gulf Coast, and of an increase vandalism
and burglary attributed to the illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was concerned about the welfare of the illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toll on illegals themselves is appalling,'' he said,
telling the panel that the body of a 44-year-old Mexican woman was
found near his ranch earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he said, ``six illegals were run over and killed
while sleeping on the rails adjacent to our pasture and in March,
12 illegal aliens were severely injured, one of them permanently
paralyzed, when the Suburban they were being smuggled in turned
over and crashed through our ranch fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS estimates that there are about 5 million people live in
the United States illegally, with about 2 million living in
California and 700,000 in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some 275,000 people illegally enter the United States each year.
About 40 percent of them enter the United States at border
checkpoints with temporary visas but remain here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hearing devolved into an immigrant-bashing session when an
auto mechanic from South Central Los Angeles testified that his
``American culture was being phased out.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Anderson, the mechanic, complained that illegal immigrants
from Mexico have taken over his once largely African-American
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have chickens, goats, laundry hung out in front and corn
growing in the front yard,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith cut Anderson's testimony short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be very cautious about a using a broad brush'' to
describe immigration, Lee said. ``All of us came from somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee recently introduced legislation that would raise the
starting salary of agents from about $23,000 to $33,000 annually.
Similar legislation is pending the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate Appropriations subcommittee for
Commerce, Justice and State Departments approved an additional $83
million to hire 1,000 new Border Patrol agents next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said the money could also be
used to provide bonuses to attract new agents and reward
experienced ones.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
