<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      06-10 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, June 11, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Roy Greene  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA (Undated) _ NATO suspends its punishing 78-day
bombing campaign as Serb troops began their pullout from Kosovo. By
Mary Leonard. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Appearing on state television,
Slobodan Milosevic applauds the successful ``defense of the
fatherland in the struggle for freedom and dignity'' and suggests
Yugoslavia won the war. By Kevin Cullen. 1100
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The Russian army, gearing up for
peacekeeping duty in the Balkans, is looking for a few good men.
Promises payments of $1,000 a month in the economically strapped
country are a powerful lure. By David Filipov. 1200 words
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-REFUGEES (Morina, Albania) _ For now, most refugees say
they will stay put in the camps and send a male head of household
to check conditions in Kosovo. By Susan Milligan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-BUTHELEZI (Johannesburg) _ In a move to solidify his
political power, Thabo Mbeki is expected to name as deputy
president a man branded as a thug and killer by the Truth and
Reconciliation Commision. By Kurt Shillinger. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   POWERS-CARNABY (London) _ On Carnaby Street, the epitome of
swinging London in the '60s, Austin Powers rules. Like the
fictional British secret agent, mod never went out of style here.
By Peggy Hernandez. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ With Oval Office remarks hailing
the West's victory against barbarity in the Balkans, the master of
the comeback appears to have done it again. By David Shribman. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DNA-SHAPE (Undated) _ Shedding light on a 20-year mystery,
scientists discover that zig-zag, left-handed DNA molecules grab a
critical enzyme that ``edits'' the DNA and fine-tunes the resulting
gene product. Experts say the finding opens up new biotechology
possibilities. By Richard Knox. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-REPORT CARD (Cambridge, Mass.) _ At Harvard Medical
School's commencement, Surgeon General David Satcher releases an
optimistic progress report on the government's ``Healthy People
2000'' goals. But he says Americans are drifting further from
targets on obesity and in other key areas. By Karen Hsu.
</P>
<P>
   CONN.-SLAYINGS (East Hartford) _ A 32-year-old woman allegedly
stabs her husband to death then sets a fire that kills her and two
of her four children. By Ellen O'Brien. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
