   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-VIRUS (San Francisco) _ Computer researchers on
Thursday reported a malicious computer program that spreads through
the Internet, attacking Microsoft's electronic mail programs and
destroying documents created with either of two Microsoft programs,
Word or PowerPoint. The program, a form of computer attack known as
a worm, has been detected in Europe and the United States. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court, by a 6-3 vote, upholds
a lower court ruling that a Chicago city anti-loitering law is
unconstitutional. The law said that a person could not hang around
on the street with a known gang member if the police said to move
on. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels) _ NATO suspended the bombing of Yugoslavia
Thursday afternoon, after confirming that Serbian troops had begun
withdrawing from Kosovo hours earlier. The halt after 78 days set
the stage for a United Nations Security Council resolution that
permits 50,000 international peacekeepers to move in on Friday to
help a million and a half ethnic Albanian refugees try to go home.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton to address the
nation from the Oval office at 8 p.m. ET regarding the end of NATO
bombing and the agreement between NATO and Yugoslavia. By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ As the long army convoy
roared out of Kosovo Thursday, beginning a defeated Serbia's
painful retreat from its historical heartland, a military policeman
in his black beret snapped a salute to each passing vehicle, tears
streaming down his face. Small knots of Serbs gathered quietly on
Podujevo's streetcorners in the wearying sun as the long column
moved past. Soldiers rode in military trucks and civilian busses,
and in passenger cars of every kind. Trucks full of stretchers
moved past, then portable kitchens and armored personnel carriers.
The Serbs stood shocked, pale and still, as if their blood was
draining into the gutter. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-HAMM-PROFILE (Undated) _ Mia Hamm is considered the world's
best female soccer player, a woman born in 1972, the year of Title
IX, the federal law aimed at prohibiting discrimination against
athletes on the basis of gender. And now, at 27, Hamm represents
for many the full realization of sports opportunity for women. At
15, she became the youngest player ever to join the national soccer
team, and in winning a world championship and an Olympic gold medal
in recent years, she has scored 109 career goals, more than any
other man or woman ever to play the game. She has, as well, reached
an uncommon level of celebrity and corporate appeal. By Jere
Longman.
</P>
