<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE AIDE SAYS FOREIGN INVESTORS' WORRIES DRIVE UP RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Argentina's undersecretary of finance said here
Thursday that foreign investors still seemed to be uncomfortable
about Latin America, leaving interest rates ``unusually high'' in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, he argued that Argentina could weather a
rise in short-term interest rates by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In the Treasury market, bond prices fell and long-term interest
rates moved higher after Japan reported surprisingly strong
economic growth in the first quarter, leading some investors to
worry that a revival of global growth would ignite inflation in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   With many investors already expecting the Fed to raise the
overnight lending rate between banks at the end of the month, the
yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.06 percent
Thursday, the highest in more than a year, from 6.02 percent
Wednesday; the price, which moves in the opposite direction, fell
14/32, to 88 30/32.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Commerce Department is scheduled to release its
retail sales report for May. If the report is strong, as some
forecasters expect, it might help drive interest rates higher
because it will be another sign that the economy is not slowing
enough to curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to money managers at a bond conference held by
J.P. Morgan Securities in New York, Miguel Alberto Kiguel, the
Argentine undersecretary of finance, noted that the spreads between
interest rates on Latin American debt and those on comparable U.S.
Treasuries ``are higher than historical levels.'' And, he said,
that spread reflected ``a level of discomfort about the region that
does not fit with the fundamentals of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged being asked tough questions by foreign
investors, including ``What other shock might come?'' Kiguel did
not make any predictions, but did say, ``My concern is, when will
the international situation improve and help Argentina?''
</P>
<P>
   He said that these spreads had begun to widen again recently
after the Fed said in mid-May that it was leaning toward raising
rates if inflation barometers continued to rise and the economy did
not slow down. ``The Fed is making them more nervous,'' Kiguel said
of investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to bond indexes kept by J.P. Morgan, the spread
between Latin American bonds and comparable U.S. Treasuries is now
8.74 percentage points, up from 7.65 before the Fed said it had
shifted its bias toward a rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, the spread is up to 7.59 percentage points, from
6.60, according to the index, while the spread in Brazil has jumped
to 10.41 percentage points, from 9.20 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, a jump in U.S. interest rates has been bad for
emerging markets because it raises a country's cost of borrowing
and can drive foreign investors away. Flows of foreign capital into
Argentina have been a key engine of the nation's economic cycle, he
said, ``so what happens to interest rates in the region will be
critical.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a rate increase that slows U.S. economic growth
will also curb growth in Latin America as Americans buy fewer of
the region's exports.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Kiguel expressed these concerns, he said that a rate
increase by the Fed _ seemingly expected by most analysts when its
policy makers meet June 29 and 30 _ would not have a significant
negative effect.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he argued, if it was clear that the Fed would raise
rates only a half-point in two steps _ and the U.S. economy began
to show signs of slowing _ then the spread between Argentine and
Treasury rates should narrow more than enough to offset the rate
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Daza, the managing director for emerging markets at
J.P. Morgan Securities, forecast continuing volatility in those
markets as investors await the Fed's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daza said, ``when the threat of inflation is
eliminated,'' he is predicting an emerging-markets rally. In three
months, he expects the spread in the Morgan index to narrow to 9
percentage points, and to just 6.5 percentage points in 12 months.
The spread is now 11.33 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Kiguel said that Argentina still needed to raise $2.1 billion
from global debt markets this year.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Argentina should have no problem doing this,
``even in a rough environment.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
