<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSFUL ANTI-MISSILE TEST PUTS PRESSURE ON DEFENSE CONTRACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Thursday's first successful intercept of an
incoming ballistic missile, defense contractor Lockheed-Martin
Corp. is under intense pressure to repeat the results in three
upcoming tests that carry $60 million worth of penalties for
failure.
</P>
<P>
   The giant defense firm must achieve a total of three successful
tests of its $4 billion THAAD anti-missile system.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed has until July 16 to make a second intercept using the
Theater High-Altitude Area Defense system; failure means the firm
would owe the Pentagon $20 million in penalties, according to Bob
Hunt, an Army spokesman in Huntsville, Ala., where the THAAD system
is managed.
</P>
<P>
   The firm must score a third success at knocking a missile from
the sky with a THAAD missile by Oct. 16, or the Pentagon will
collect another $20 million. The company then gets until Jan. 16 to
score a third hit or lose $20 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed-Martin has already paid the Pentagon $15 million for
failing to achieve a successful test in March.
</P>
<P>
   The successful hit took place at 7:19 a.m. EDT Thursday over the
White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico. According to the Pentagon,
a modified Minuteman II target missile was launched to simulate an
Iraqi Scud ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   As THAAD ground-based radars tracked the weapon across the sky,
a THAAD missile was fired 120 miles to the south. Seven minutes
later it struck and destroyed the Minuteman II in a fiery blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The success comes after a checkered history. Since the test
program began in 1995, the weapon has failed to intercept targets
on all six previous tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has a lot riding on THAAD, which is being developed as
the military's primary weapon for protecting troops from theater
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon, THAAD ``will give U.S. forces the
best chance to shoot down incoming missiles far enough out so that
post-intercept debris will not harm our troops _ a vital
consideration if a missile carries a weapon of mass destruction.''
The Army intends to field the weapon by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The major difference between THAAD and the Patriot missile,
which intercepted Iraqi Scuds in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, is that
THAAD is designed to intercept incoming missiles at greater
altitudes and ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot missiles were used to knock down Scuds at much lower
altitudes and didn't actually ram the missiles but instead
detonated close by. THAAD is designed to destroy the incoming
missile by colliding with it.
</P>
<P>
   THAAD also differs from the National Missile Defense program,
dubbed ``Star Wars,'' that would provide an umbrella defense for
the entire United States against intercontinental ballistic
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the THAAD program assert that the program is too
costly and ultimately won't work in actual battlefield conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army is a long way away from proving reliability,'' said
Brian Hughes, a defense analyst with Taxpayers for Common Sense, a
private Washington, D.C., group that styles itself an independent
watchdog on government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``One success every $4 billion is not acceptable. If THAAD is
not consistently successful, we believe it should be terminated,''
Hughes added.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cirincione, a defense analyst with the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace, a non-partisan think tank here, said it
was ``shocking'' that the Army has had only one success in over
four years of test flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much does it add to our capability if it now can hit
Scuds, the types of missiles that we encountered eight years ago in
the Gulf War?'' Cirincione asked.
</P>
<P>
   THAAD champions, meanwhile, hailed Thursday's results.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Brig. Gen. Richard Davis, a senior official with the
Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, called the test
``a major milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., one of the most outspoken congressional
advocates for missile defense, said the test demonstrated that
THAAD ``is a capable system that will be effective in protecting
our troops overseas from the threat of missile attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said the previous test failures were ``an inevitable
part'' of developing a new complex weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the conservative activist running for the Republican
presidential nomination in 2000, praised the program, calling it
``an important step forward in the drive to give the American
people a defense against missile attack.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
