<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THAI-COMPANY-RECOVERY     06-10 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAI-COMPANY-RECOVERY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN TRIES TO LEAD THAI COMPANY BACK FROM BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ For Robert B. Mollerstuen, the Asian
economic crisis hit home on a sultry Sunday evening in July 1997,
three weeks after Thailand let its currency plunge in value and set
off a panic from Singapore to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing on his day off, Mollerstuen was called with some
jolting news: his boss, the Thai founder of Alphatec Electronics,
had quit abruptly, suspected of siphoning money out of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Alphatec's directors asked Mollerstuen to take over. The next
day, he arrived at company headquarters here to find finance
executives shredding documents. Mollerstuen barricaded them in a
conference room and later dismissed the whole department.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mollerstuen, an American who is a veteran of the computer
industry, is still at the helm of Alphatec. It has been a
white-water ride. The company tumbled into insolvency soon after
that Sunday and is the first company to have been resuscitated
under Thailand's newly strengthened bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Alphatec climbs back on its feet after a bankruptcy
reorganization, it could become a model for other companies
paralyzed by debt, a devalued currency, and the collapse of
Thailand's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Alphatec, decisions were made: whether you shut it down,
whether you keep operating it,'' said Amaret Sila-On, the chairman
of Thailand's Financial Sector Restructuring Authority. ``Something
had to be done. People have to force this to happen because the
owners will not do it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mollerstuen, 63, is clearly proud to play a part in Thailand's
revival. But his deeply lined face attests to the ravages of the
last two years. To save one of Thailand's pioneering technology
companies, Mollerstuen had to battle balky creditors, fearful
customers, and shareholders whose anger prompted him at one point
to hire bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very difficult experience for me because my
credibility was on the line,'' said Mollerstuen, who had been a
senior executive at Alphatec in its heady growth and descent into
financial turmoil. ``The thing I was naive about was business
practices in Thailand.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mollerstuen is not the only outsider who failed to see the
unfolding financial disaster in Thailand. Alphatec, which packages
and tests computer chips for semiconductor manufacturers, was one
of the highest fliers during Thailand's high-flying boom years.
</P>
<P>
   When this corporate Icarus crashed to earth, the wreckage
exposed a host of festering problems that contributed to the
nation's economic fall.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, analysts say, the pace of restructuring among large,
debt-ridden Thai companies has picked up. Though Alphatec is the
first to go through an American-style bankruptcy, major companies
like Thai Petrochemical Industry have negotiated deals with their
banks to stretch out or write off debts. All told, Thai companies
have overhauled about 20 percent of their estimated $21 billion in
short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's progress in cleaning up its corporate sector has made
the country a quiet success story among recession-racked Asian
countries. While South Korea struggles to tame its stubborn
conglomerates and Indonesia drifts in an ocean of red ink, Thailand
seems to be getting back on course.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``In Thailand, the balance of power is shifting from the debtors
to the creditors in the recovery of bad loans,'' said Roy Ramos, a
banking analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Such a development is crucially important to Thailand's
recovery, analysts say, because it could persuade foreign investors
to begin pouring money back into the country. Although Thailand has
won praise from the International Monetary Fund for its reform
efforts, outside investors remain dubious.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand attracted $628 million in foreign direct investment in
the first quarter of 1999, down from $2.3 billion in the first
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories like that of Alphatec Electronics help explain
why investors are so gun-shy. Founded in 1989 by a Thai
entrepreneur, Charn Uswachoke, Alphatec initially sought to fill a
typical niche for a technology company in an emerging market: it
packaged and tested integrated circuits for chip manufacturers like
Philips, AMD and Cypress Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   Charn, however, was eager to vault Alphatec up the technology
food chain. An ambitious ethnic Chinese entrepreneur, Charn viewed
his company as an engine that could propel Thailand into the ranks
of high-tech Asian heavyweights like Taiwan and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he announced plans to build Thailand's first wafer
factory. With Thai banks eager to hand out money, he quickly lined
up more than $300 million from 26 creditors for the $1 billion
project.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with just a chip factory, Charn began assembling an
empire. His ventures, which grew to include satellite and
telecommunications companies, were to be arrayed in a 2,000-acre
technology park near the Bangkok airport, called Alpha Technopolis.
It was modeled on the vast Hsinchu complex in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Mollerstuen said, Alphatec's cash demands were
``horrendous.'' That coincided with a slump in the global
semiconductor market, which hammered Alphatec's core packaging
business.
</P>
<P>
   Things went from bad to worse as the Thai economy buckled in the
summer of 1997. Banks stopped lending, Alphatec's loans dried up,
and construction of the Technopolis ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, according to outside auditors, Alphatec
executives transferred money from the publicly listed company to
Charn's privately held companies. In an audit carried out for
Alphatec's banks by PricewaterhouseCoopers in July 1997, the firm
reported that more than $300 million was missing.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers filed a civil suit on behalf of creditors
against Charn to recover the money, as well as a suit against
Alphatec's former auditors, KPMG. In addition, the Thai police
began investigating Charn on criminal charges, and he was
blacklisted by the Thai Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the flurry of legal action, executives at
PricewaterhouseCoopers said that the purported siphoning of money
from Alphatec was far from unusual for family-controlled companies
in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   As Jonathan Sisson, a partner at PricewaterhouseCoopers who runs
the Alphatec case, put it, ``In Thailand, it is often difficult to
figure out where the family interests end and the corporate
interests begin.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Charn, 55, denies that he improperly removed any
money from the publicly listed company. In a telephone interview,
he said Alphatec was a victim of Thailand's imploding economy. He
also notes that no one has successfully brought civil or criminal
charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one who tried to keep the company alive for many
years,'' Charn said. ``When the crisis came, people, especially in
Thailand, didn't know how to handle it. It got worse and worse
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for Alphatec's debts, the conditions for
financial chicanery were certainly ripe. The company's board
consisted of people with close ties to Charn and his family. By the
time the bankers on the board began agitating, Alphatec was already
suffocating under $378 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   When Alphatec's directors put Mollerstuen in charge, the future
looked grim. Cypress Semiconductor had canceled a crucial contract.
And the company could not meet its debt payments. In 1998, Alphatec
reported losses of $48 million on revenue of $36 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Mollerstuen was sure the company was worth salvaging. Aside
from Cypress, its other customers were loyal. And he believed when
the semiconductor market rebounded, Thailand's advantages as a
low-cost labor center would make Alphatec solidly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was, Thailand did not yet have an effective
procedure for overhauling an insolvent company. Mollerstuen's bid
to install PricewaterhouseCoopers as the new auditor was voted down
by Alphatec's shareholders, more than half of them controlled by
Charn. The company's initial proposal to write down 90 percent of
its debts was vetoed by the banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't get from here to there,'' Mollerstuen said. It
was during this period that he hired bodyguards, he said, after
hearing rumors that angry shareholders might attack him.
</P>
<P>
   Alphatec got a break in April 1998 when Thailand amended its
bankruptcy laws. Now the company could submit a rehabilitation plan
and if it was accepted by the creditors, it could be adopted
without shareholder approval. The creditors threw Alphatec into
bankruptcy in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers was appointed to draw up the plan, and
the French bank Credit Agricole was retained to search for
investors. At the end of 1998, it found two: AIG Investment, the
arm of insurance giant American International Group, and Investor
AB, the Swedish holding company controlled by the Wallenburg
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of unsolicited advice that I was crazy for looking
at this company,'' said Alexander West, the president of Investor
Asia. ``The good thing was that banks had decided to fire Charn and
the finance department.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, Investor and AIG agreed to put $40 million in fresh
equity into the company. PricewaterhouseCoopers devised a plan to
spin off most of Alphatec's debts into a shell company and create a
new Alphatec with only $30 million in debt. Faced with the prospect
of recovering only 5 percent of their loans if the company
liquidated, the banks gulped and went along.
</P>
<P>
   Alphatec's backers took some steps considered unorthodox in
Asia. Borrowing an idea from leveraged buyouts in the United
States, they required Mollerstuen and other top managers to put up
personal assets as collateral against the performance of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure they believe in the company, and this is
the way we test their conviction,'' said Timothy C. Chang, the
executive director of AIG Investment (Asia) in Hong Kong. ``It
takes a management ethos that is different from traditional Thai
family management.''
</P>
<P>
   Alphatec's investors recognized that retaining Mollerstuen
raised a red flag, since he had been a deputy to Charn. But
Mollerstuen said he knew nothing about the finances of Charn's
companies _ an explanation that was accepted by both
PricewaterhouseCoopers and the investors.
</P>
<P>
   What made Mollerstuen valuable was his ties to Alphatec's
customers and his experience in Thailand, Singapore, Brazil and the
United States. Mollerstuen said that if Alphatec could rebuild its
relationships, the company might be profitable enough in three to
five years to contemplate a stock offering in Asia or even on the
Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   After the turmoil of the last two years, however, Mollerstuen
seems reluctant to make predictions. An affable but visibly tired
man, he confided that his journey through the Asian crisis had
exacted a high personal cost. But he saw himself as having little
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I turned and walked away from this company,'' Mollerstuen
said, rubbing his eyes, ``people would have said: `Ah, he's part of
it. He's as guilty as the next guy.' I didn't want that to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
