<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXACT-THEATER-REVIEW-     06-10 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXACT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EZ-PASS WOULD HAVE HELPED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ireland)   By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of plays seem to be set in bars this season: ``The Weir,''
with its charming Irish storytellers; ``The Iceman Cometh,'' with
its motley assortment of the down-and-out, and now, several blocks
from Broadway, ``Exact Change.'' This three-character play by David
Epstein is a mixed bag, awkward at first but coming together near
the end, not particularly deep but consistently well written.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that the men in ``Exact Change'' may not be that
smart is that they've opened a bar in a Muslim neighborhood.
Business, understandably, hasn't been that brisk. Now Rickie
(Charles Stransky, looking like a cross between Vincent Gardenia
and a young Steve Allen) has lost the trio's money by investing it
in soybean futures. It isn't the local bank that is going to be
upset with them; it's a guy named Caravelli who presides over his
loan shark operation at a suede desk.
</P>
<P>
   The men spend most of Act I discussing their business problems.
In Act II, they have taken action to solve things and failed
miserably. Why on earth they decided to kidnap a dentist for a
modest ransom we don't know, but they lost him while stopped at a
toll booth, which accounts for the title, and now they're pretty
much doomed.
</P>
<P>
   The friends, who were in Vietnam together, deal with just about
everything that comes their way by talking about it, often with
memorable lines, like ``Hitler didn't drive'' and ``When have you
ever seen a picture of the Pope with a drink in his hand?'' and
``Did you ever light a sock?'' (All of these make sense at the
time.) Epstein has been compared to David Mamet, but this is more
because of his characters and his tone than his use of language,
which is just a touch too aware of itself but shows a lot of
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Pierson is the standout as Richie, the brightest of the
bunch. Stransky is fine, as is Ken Ryan as Eddie, even if he often
seems a lot like Art Carney as Ed Norton trying to sell Kramden on
his latest brilliant plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exact Change,'' directed by Jacques Levy, continues at the
Medicine Show Theater in Clinton through June 19.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`EXACT CHANGE'  &QL; 
By David Epstein; directed by Jacques Levy, sets by Ray Recht;
costumes by Tina Firestone, lighting by Chris Dallos; production
stage manager, James Beaumont. Presented by Teejay Productions. At
the Medicine Show Theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Charles Stransky (Rickie Merola), Ken Ryan (Eddie Bompkee)
and Geoff Pierson (Richie Botts).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
