<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0745 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-H     06-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION TO REORGANIZE AFTER IRS RULING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Denied tax-exempt status by the government, the
Christian Coalition announced Thursday that it is splitting into
two separate groups and anointing its Texas operation as the
``principal vehicle'' for its national operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition of Texas, which is headquartered in
Bedford, near Fort Worth, and is exempt from paying sales taxes,
will be renamed the Christian Coalition of America.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization was prompted by an Internal Revenue Service
ruling that the Christian Coalition, a Virginia-based group founded
by religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, was not entitled to a tax
exemption as a religious organization.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS ruling, issued in late 1998 and kept under wraps until
this week, is the latest blow to the coalition, a force in the
Republican Party that has been wrestling with the departure of
several top officials, a decline in fund-raising and lethargy in
most of its state chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the reorganization will enable the Christian
Coalition to remain active in U.S. politics. ``Christian Coalition
of America will continue to be a force in American politics and
will remain a prominent fixture on the political landscape as the
nation's number one pro-family, pro-life organization,'' said
Robertson, whose failed bid for the Republican presidential
nomination in 1988 gave birth to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Russell, a spokesman for the coalition's national office,
added, ``The organization has been dramatically reshaped but its
mission statement remains intact, and it will continue to do the
things it has been doing since it formed, which is recruit
pro-family activists, draw people to the polls in record numbers
for elections and educate.''
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring calls for formation of a new for-profit
organization to be called Christian Coalition International, which
will endorse candidates and funnel money to political causes and
candidates. The Texas chapter will continue most of the
organization's current operations, including distribution of voter
guides before elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to affect anything,'' said Chuck Anderson, a
spokesman and political organizer for the Christian Coalition of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition opponent criticized the restructuring, calling it a
blatant move to get around the IRS ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of disgraceful shell-game you find in a
second-rate carnival in the middle of nowhere,'' said Barry Lynn,
director of Americans United for Separation of Church and State. He
said his group would challenge the newly restructured coalition's
tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Coalition is a hardball political machine that
is masquerading as a religious group,'' Lynn said. ``This
organization has been operating as little more than an appendage of
the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, when it raised and spent more than $26 million on
political activities, the Christian Coalition's influence has
slipped. The organization is credited with help pulling off the
Republican Party's winning control of both houses of Congress in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, the Christian Coalition boasted 3 million members,
mostly from Robertson's list of 1988 campaign supporters. Robertson
recently announced that the organization would mobilize 1.5 million
conservative voters in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, the coalition has gone through a
staff exodus. Executive director Ralph Reed left in 1997 and more
recently resigned from the board and is working with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential campaign. Reed's replacements, unable
to get along with Robertson, have not lasted long.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition President Don Hodel quit in February, and executive
director Randy Tate was demoted to the organization's Washington
lobbying office early this month. National field director Dave
Welch left in March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
