<P>
   AIRPORT-NOMINATION (Los Angeles) _ Mayor Richard Riordan is
expected to announce his nomination of Lydia Kennard to replace
Jack Driscoll as head of the city's Department of Airports,
overseeing Los Angeles International as well as airports at Van
Nuys, Ontario and Palmdale. By Rick Orlov. (Will move on the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAGTEAM-FAMILIES (Los Angeles) _ As the 24-hour workday expands,
split-shift families are taking the toll, according to a new study.
When men work nights and have been married less than five years,
odds of divorce are six times greater than normal according to the
study. When it's the women who work night, divorce odds are three
times greater, says Harriet B. Presser of the department of
sociology at the University of Maryland in College Park. By Steve
Carney. (Will move on the ``a'' nation and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   PROSTITUTION-RING (Los Angeles) _ Jody ``Babydoll'' Gibson,
accused of running one of the largest prostitute rings in Los
Angeles, has been arrested in Van Nuys. The apparent heir to Heidi
Fleiss' dominance of the Los Angeles flesh trade is accused of
pimping 34 women in Southern California and six in Europe in a
sophisticated operation including an Internet site that drew
clients from as far away as New York. By Browne. (Will move on the
``a'' nation and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY-OPENING (Los Angeles) _ A mega-budget production makes
its debut Saturday in Hollywood. It's a new, 4.6 mile segment of
the MTA's Metro Red Line subway with five new stations, ending with
the station at Hollywood and Vine. But the beleaguered MTA, ordered
by a federal court to spend hundreds of millions of dollars to
improve bus service, was targeted anew Thursday by two state
senators who are introducing legislation to prohibit the transit
agency from spending more money for rail or other nonbus projects
until it allocates funds to comply with the court's order on buses.
By Douglas Haberman. (Will move on the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TARZAN-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Folks go ape over the 38th
Annual Dum Dum convention honoring Tarzan creator Edgar Rice
Burroughs in Woodland Hills. Also on the agenda - a dealers' forum,
rare memorabilia, tours of local sites and honors for celebrity
guests who have contributed to the Burroughs legacy. By Troy
Anderson. (Will move on the ``a'' nation and ``n'' California news
files.)
