<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR RAKING IN CAMPAIGN CONTRIBUTIONS AT RECORD RATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush is collecting campaign
contributions at a record pace in a high-stakes bid to become the
first presidential candidate in history who successfully ignores
federal spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The all-out drive for cash slips into high gear Friday, the day
before the Texas Republican's first presidential campaign swing.
While more than 100 reporters gather in Austin for Bush's initial
outing to Iowa and New Hampshire, the governor will ditch his media
entourage for the day to raise money in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The private fund-raisers in Chicago and St. Louis are the first
in a series of at least two dozen similar events across the country
in June. By the end of the month, Bush advisers expect his campaign
donations to top $15 million _ about $2 million more than
Republican Bob Dole, the previous record-holder, had at the same
point in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only the beginning. Bush's fund-raising goals call
for him to have about $32 million by the end of the year. And,
although a final decision is months away, Bush may turn down
federal matching funds and try to raise $50 million on his own to
carry him to the Republican nominating convention in late July
2000.
</P>
<P>
   To put that figure in perspective, Dole and President Clinton
together raised $59 million in 1996. Turning down federal matching
money would let Bush ignore overall and state-by-state spending
limits in the battle for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from $32 million to $50 million is a significant move.
Each additional dollar gets more difficult to raise,'' said Don
Evans, the campaign's finance chairman. ``Nobody's ever tried it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reformers worry that Bush's decision could effectively
end the federal matching system by setting a new standard for
presidential candidates. The matching system, first used in 1976,
relies on the lure of federal dollars to get candidates to rein in
campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the potential of just devastating the whole public
financing system in the primaries,'' said Paul Hendrie of the
Center for Responsive Politics, an organization that tries to
highlight special interest influence in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates who tried to play outside the system fell short
of their goals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, another Texas Republican, former Gov. John Connally,
turned down federal money so that he could spend unlimited amounts
in the early primary states. He spent nearly $12 million before his
campaign collapsed, leaving him with a single convention delegate.
</P>
<P>
   A few millionaire candidates, most notably Ross Perot and Steve
Forbes, have ignored the federal limits by tapping their personal
fortunes, but to no avail. Forbes intends to ignore the limits
again in Campaign 2000 even though he is accepting donations this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush may yet decide to go the conventional route, his
fast pace is causing problems for his GOP rivals. Former Vice
President Dan Quayle recently complained that Bush's operation is a
``big sucking machine'' that is vacuuming up dollars from
Republican supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and Elizabeth Dole have
also encountered fund-raising difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a Midland oilman and one of Bush's closest friends, said
the governor's early fund-raising success was the political
equivalent of picking ``easy low-lying fruit'' from donors who
needed little prompting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, more than 200 Bush supporters agreed to become
campaign ``pioneers'' by raising $100,000 from friends and
associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were anxious to write a $1,000 check without
even a phone call,'' Evans said. ``You want to raise as much as you
can as fast as you can. You raise it early and spend it late.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said Bush and his advisers will make a decision on whether
to take federal money in the fall, when they are better able to
assess their finances. Candidates who agree to spending limits will
receive nearly $16.8 million, with the first payments scheduled for
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving Bush more flexibility in the early primary
states, turning down the money would let him continue to raise and
spend money well into next year. In 1996, the federal limits forced
candidate Bob Dole to scale back his campaign after the expensive
early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly anticipate a very competitive primary. It would
be nice to have the luxury to continue to raise money (next year),
but it's just too early to make that call,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
