<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-TROOPS-AR     06-10 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-TROOPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TROOPS FUNNEL INTO MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROVEC, Macedonia _ More than 3,000 American ground troops
poured into dusty, makeshift camps near the airport here Thursday,
as the United States scrambled to amass its contribution to a
peacekeeping operation in Kosovo fraught with risks and uncertain
support back home.
</P>
<P>
   The American buildup began before dawn, only hours after
Yugoslav generals accepted NATO's demands for an international
force in Kosovo, as the first of nearly 2,000 troops from the 26th
Marine Expeditionary Force stormed a beach southwest of the Greek
port of Thessaloniki, greeted by protesters and banners opposing
NATO's attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As the Marines boarded buses and trucks and began a six-hour
drive north, some 1,400 Army soldiers arrived along with tanks,
artillery batteries and 11 Apache helicopter gunships that the
Clinton administration sent to Albania, but then declined to use in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally getting something done,'' Spc. Jeremiah Siejo, a
machine-gunner with the 82nd Airborne Division, said as he climbed
from a Chinook helicopter with his platoon, which had spent the
last two months outside Albania's capital, Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few hundred Americans stationed in Macedonia
when the day began, but by dark nearly half of the 7,000 troops the
United States has pledged to the NATO force in Kosovo, known as
KFOR, had arrived, set up camps near the airport here and begun
preparations for moving into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The American force is not expected to join NATO's first push
into Kosovo, but rather will follow British troops who, NATO
officials said, will clear a corridor on the main road between
Macedonia and Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the Marines from the 26th Expeditionary Force, the
Americans will ultimately patrol a sector in southeast Kosovo,
maintaining a headquarters in Gnjilane, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the war itself, the new commitment of American troops in
the Balkans _ on top of more than 6,000 still in Bosnia, 3 1/2
years after the civil war there ended _ has generated opposition in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Republicans in Congress revived an effort to block
financing for the American force, President Clinton said Thursday
that he would not impose a limit on the force's duration, as he did
when he sent 20,000 Americans to Bosnia and pledged to bring them
home in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put a timetable on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO suspended its air war Thursday, preparations for the
peacekeeping mission could be seen all over northern Macedonia.
British and Italian troops took up positions near the border post
at Blace, which is expected to be the main overland route into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The road into the Macedonian military base near the airport at
Petrovec, which holds troops from several NATO allies, was clogged
at times with fuel trucks, armored troop carriers and other
vehicles coming going in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, wave after wave of helicopters _ including Army Black
Hawks and Chinooks _ thudded to and from a corner of the base
occupied by the fast-growing American force, ferrying soldiers from
the force in Albania while stirring up terrific storms of dust.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 Apaches, kept out of combat in the air war, will provide
air cover to the American forces as they move in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a period of time when we make sure the
peacekeeping force is the most powerful force in the area,'' Col.
Jeffrey Schloesser, commander of the helicopter squadrons, said
when asked why the Apaches, a powerful weapon against armored
forces, would be needed in a peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   The troops themselves sounded eager to begin the operation.
``However they can use us, we'd like to be a part of it,'' said
Chief Warrant Officer 3rd Class Eric E. Rings, one of the Apache
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's deployment came after several false starts that
mirrored the on-again, off-again progress in five days of talks
between NATO and Yugoslav generals over the details of the end to
the war. Greece's government, wary of anti-NATO protests in a
country with religious ties to Yugoslavia's Serbs, had denied the
Marines permission to land until an agreement was reached. Only
then did the orders come to move in.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. B. John Craddock, the Army commander of the American
forces involved in the mission, said in an interview Thursday that
the troops would encounter any number of obstacles once they
entered Kosovo. Even if the Yugoslav forces withdraw as promised,
the NATO peacekeepers would encounter mines laid by Yugoslav forces
and Kosovo's rebels, the destruction of roads and bridges by NATO
aircraft and, very likely, thousands of refugees who have spent the
war hiding in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the terms of the agreement, if complied with, I would
expect to find nothing,'' he said, when asked what obstacles he
expected to face. ``However, it's not a perfect world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
