<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-HAMM-PROFILE-2TAK     06-10 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HAMM-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOCCER STAR MIA HAMM FACES THE PRESSURE OF BEING THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time Mia Hamm steps on or off a soccer field, the young
girls are waiting. They are wearing her No. 9 jersey. Their hair is
pulled back into a replica of her ponytail. The cumulative effect
is of nesting dolls, each one opening to reveal another inside that
is smaller but identical.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is considered the world's best female soccer player, a
woman born in 1972, the year of Title IX, the federal law aimed at
prohibiting discrimination against athletes on the basis of gender.
And now, at 27, Hamm represents for many the full realization of
sports opportunity for women. At 15, she became the youngest player
ever to join the national soccer team, and in winning a world
championship and an Olympic gold medal in recent years, she has
scored 109 career goals, more than any other man or woman ever to
play the game.
</P>
<P>
   She has, as well, reached an uncommon level of celebrity and
corporate appeal. People magazine voted her one of its 50 most
beautiful people. Nike named a building in her honor at its
headquarters. She appears in a commercial with Michael Jordan,
challenging him in basketball, soccer, track and fencing, and
flipping him over her hip in a judo maneuver while the music
asserts, ``Anything you can do, I can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   And starting next week, Hamm will headline the largest sporting
event ever held for women, the Women's World Cup, a 16-team
tournament which begins at Giants Stadium on June 19 and that will
be played in stadiums across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The games will provide the biggest stage yet for the woman who
is a sports role model for 7.5 million girls who play soccer in the
United States. Girls, ranging in ages from 10 to 17, wait for her
after practices and games in adoring flocks, shrieking her name in
a way familiar to anyone who saw the Beatles on the old Ed Sullivan
Hour.
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny promises to be intense, for athletes are rarely
asked to carry the enormous burden of opportunity Hamm is being
shouldered with this summer. She is being counted on not only to
lead the favored American team, but to help fill stadiums, to lend
a name and a face to an emerging game, to be the spark that could
possibly ignite a professional soccer league for women in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If Hamm fails, or her team loses early, the Women's World Cup
could become a diminished athletic and commercial affair. And a
women's pro league, now a longshot proposition looking for a star
to hook onto, may have trouble becoming more than a proposal in a
boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it is important for soccer that Mia plays well,'' said
Leonardo Cuellar, coach of the Mexican women's team. ``I don't want
to add pressure, but it's always important, when fans have
expectations about seeing a player excel in a world class event,
for that to happen. She's charismatic, very humble. Those are the
attributes of Pele and some of the best stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the pressure to dominate on the soccer field can feel
to Hamm like knotted muscle. Hamm did not finish among the top
scorers in previous major tournaments _ the 1991 World Cup, the
1995 World Cup, the 1996 Summer Olympics. The burden was
particularly evident earlier this year when Hamm did not score a
goal for eight consecutive games. Twice during that drought, the
Americans lost to China, the team the United States defeated for
the 1996 Olympic gold medal and its chief rival.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm seemed reluctant to challenge defenders one on one,
according to the American coach, Tony DiCicco. No one is better at
this aspect of the women's game that is part croquet, part ballet,
part bullfight. At her best, Hamm seems to release and retrieve the
ball as if it were a yo-yo. But now she was hesitant. For the first
time in her career, she made as much news when she didn't score as
when she did. Doubt seeped into her game like sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line between setting standards that keep you
getting better and being hypercritical to the point that it
undermines your confidence,'' DiCicco said. ``She's always flirted
with that line. She's not only a soccer icon, but she's an icon for
women's athletics. That's a huge responsibility. It's a very
vulnerable place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls who wait for her hold out their hands for her to slap,
or they ask her to sign their jerseys, or thrust soccer balls
toward her. In return, she offers high-fives, an autograph, a
smile, a nod, an affirming gesture that they can aspire to be
everything she has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for young girls to have female athletes
they can identify with,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   While she accepts that she is a pioneer, she is a reluctant
celebrity. She wears the role awkwardly, like donning a fur coat in
the dead of summer. Having grown up in a military family with three
sisters and two brothers, there is a reserve about her, almost a
sense of rank, as if she should succeed at a high level but that
she should not stand out from the others.
</P>
<P>
   She is a scorer who is a selfless passer, a forward who is as
economical with her words as she is explosive with her feet, a
female athlete as effortless and guarded as Joe DiMaggio. Even her
handshake is noncommittal, as if it might reveal too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men grow up knowing that if they are the best they are going
to be famous,'' said David Bober, who is Hamm's agent. ``Mia didn't
sign up for soccer to be a famous sports icon. It's an
adjustment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is actually more forthcoming discussing her failures than
her successes. The mantle of ``best player in the world'' is
subjective, she says. Failure is objective. It can be taken apart,
examined, repaired. She says that confidence, like fitness, must be
cultivated daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone tried to tell me that Michael Jordan doesn't have
confidence problems, but he is probably very selective who he
shares it with,'' Hamm said. ``I don't think a lot of athletes walk
around thinking they're the best. If they do, it's probably to hide
some weaknesses they have.''
</P>
<P>
   During the scoring drought, Hamm heard and read that she wasn't
playing her best, and by repetition, the supposition of a slump
became fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to listen but it does get to you,'' Hamm said. ``I
was putting too much pressure on myself. I wasn't enjoying what I
was doing. I was so worried about, `All right team, jump on my
back, I'm going to carry you through all this.'''
</P>
<P>
   She consulted friends, like Nomar Garciaparra, the shortstop for
the Boston Red Sox, who told Hamm, ``Go out and enjoy the game and
don't worry about all that other stuff.'' Eventually, she scored
again, and with five goals in her last five matches leading to the
World Cup, her personal fog cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia takes the burden really seriously on herself,'' said
Tiffeny Milbrett, who plays forward alongside Hamm. ``She needs to
realize she's not alone. The team will be fine. She will pull off
the spectacular play just by being on the field. All she needs to
do is play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm was born in Selma, Ala., and lived a road-map childhood in
Texas, California, Virginia and Italy, where her father, an Air
Force colonel, was passionately drawn to soccer. When Mia was five,
her family adopted an eight-year-old boy named Garrett, whose legs
and arms seemed wondrously suited to propelling a ball off a bat,
through a hoop, into a net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garrett was an influence on me on any form of athletics,''
Hamm said. ``When he'd go play pickup football or baseball, I was
always right behind him. He always picked me for his teams.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 14, the national soccer team wanted her,
too. Anson Dorrance, who coached the team then, got an excited call
about her from a coaching friend in Texas. Skeptical, Dorrance went
to watch her play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team kicks off, a girl passes the ball to the right about
30 yards and I see this skinny brunette take off like she had been
shot out of a cannon,'' Dorrance said.
</P>
<P>
   He walked around the field and approached his coaching friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that Mia Hamm?'' Dorrance asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got something here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hamm was only 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a potential genius, you don't want to crush
their spirit and shatter their confidence if they don't succeed,''
Dorrance said. ``I decided we couldn't wait. The rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Hamm became the youngest player, male or female, ever to
join the national team. She then followed Dorrance to North
Carolina, where she won four national championships and met her
husband, Christian Corry, a Marine pilot. With Hamm, the Americans
won the initial Women's World Cup in 1991, and later the gold medal
at the 1996 Summer Olympics. But her success has been tempered by
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Hamm contracted a rare blood disorder. Mia raised
$50,000 for his care through a benefit soccer game. But in April of
1997, at the age of 28, her brother died.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm absorbed the hurt, and she has played on, scoring more
goals, raising expectations. But some close to her believe she has
been pulled too thin, playing and promoting the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us might be asking her to do too much,'' Dorrance said.
``I have a great fear it will burn her out, on the field, off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Reticent off the field, her style of play is dynamically suited
to spreading the sport to a wider audience. A fiercer countenance
emerges, cheeks hollow and jaws clinched in exertion, her ponytail
fanning out behind as she sprints 40 yards to finish a fastbreak or
carves a defender with a deft two-step and makes an inexorable
charge toward the goal. The passion of her game is most evident in
the celebrative convulsion when she scores, the tendons in her neck
flared, her mouth an open scream, her arms cocked at the elbow and
fists closed as if she has just lifted some enormous weight.
</P>
<P>
   She has a dancer's feet, a felon's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her acceleration is so visceral,'' Dorrance said. ``When she
gets the ball you hold your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Her athleticism is such that, during a desperate moment of the
1995 Women's World Cup, the Americans made her a goalkeeper.
Someone brought a football to a recent practice, and Hamm expertly
knocked in field goals from 35 yards. As a 7th-grader in Wichita
Falls, Texas, she played end and cornerback on a boy's football
team. ``Even in pads she was fast,'' said her father, Bill Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   With her teammates, Hamm can be funny, outgoing, a master of
accents, someone who gives as good as she gets. When midfielder
Julie Foudy, in a moment of introspection, said that she wanted to
retire from soccer to do something that ``makes a difference,''
Hamm dabbed at fake tears and burst into a mock Bette Midler
number, singing, ``Did you know that you're my hero?''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she mind sticking pins in her own public image. On the
box of Soccer Barbie, which she endorses, Hamm is pictured with a
doll's freeze-dried smile and eternity-proof makeup. ``You can't
tell which one is the Barbie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In filming the Gatorade commercial with Jordan, cameras began
rolling in the unscripted judo sequence, and Hamm moved confidently
toward Jordan and flung him to the mat. He played along, said
Bober, Hamm's agent, ``but he waved his finger and said, `That
better not make the final cut.'''
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras will be rolling for real in the coming weeks, and
there will be no play acting. Everyone will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``All sports lacking a profile really have to push one or two of
the best athletes who have a number of qualities in and out of the
game,'' said Julie Murray, captain of the Australian women's team.
``Sometimes it can be daunting, standing up and making speeches
when all you want to do is play. But I know it is better for the
sport and for the people who will follow in Mia's shoes. Girls who
are 13, 14, 15, are looking at her. The sport is better off doing
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
