<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIAL-FUTURE-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNING YOUR FINANCIAL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By the editors of Hispanic magazine 
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    It seems like everyone is ready to offer financial advice these
days _ from your Tio Pepe to your local newspaper to your bank
teller. Too bad much of it can seem garbled.
 &HT;    Money magazine recently advised investing in high-technology
companies, proclaiming ``Everyone's getting rich: Get your share!''
on its front cover. About a year earlier (before the stock market's
subsequent surge to record levels), its front cover had read,
``Sell Stocks Now!'' and warned of a possible market collapse.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, the large stock brokerages warn about the dangers of
on-line investing, even as a growing number of individual investors
are getting richer that way.
 &HT;    On-line stock trading firms warn about the greediness and
general untrustworthiness of commissioned stockbrokers, not
bothering to mention that some investors may need professional
advice when it comes to the often complicated fields of investing,
retirement planning and insurance.
 &HT;    Given all the contradictory messages and hype, what's the
average person to do?
 &HT;    The following financial experts were asked four questions that
touch on issues that concern new investors, young professionals,
baby boomers and families with children. The result is a financial
planning primer that answers some very basic questions.
 &HT;    
 THE PANEL  
 &HT;     LOUIS BARAJAS.  Barajas is a certified financial planner and
head of Louis Barajas &AMP; Associates Financial Advisors in Los
Angeles, Calif.
 &HT;     LILIA MOJICA.  Mojica is assistant vice president of business
development for Union Bank of California in San Diego, Calif.
 &HT;     ROBERT G. FERNANDEZ.  Fernandez is a vice president and
financial consultant with Salomon Smith Barney in Austin, Texas.
 &HT;     ELIZABETH S. GONZALES.  Gonzales is an insurance agent and
registered investment representative at New York Life Insurance
Company /NYLife Securities in Austin, Texas.
 &HT;     PEDRO U. DIAZ.  Diaz is an investment adviser and the vice
President 0f Capital Anal ysts, Inc., in Miami, Fla.
 &HT;    
 Q&AMP;A  
 &HT;    1. How much money does a person really need to start building a
financial portfolio?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Barajas: To start building a financial portfolio, all it takes
is the first dollar saved. It's not until you decide to save money
that you will see financial changes. Who cares if there are
investments paying 20 percent or 3 percent if you have nothing
saved?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mojica: First and foremost, because of the state of the economy,
everyone should be concerned about securing his or her own
financial future. As far as how much money someone needs to start
building a financial portfolio, everyone's situation is different;
therefore, the amounts may vary. As long as you are consistent, you
can start a savings account with as little as $5 and a serious
financial portfolio with about $500,000.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fernandez: There is no specific amount needed to really get your
financial portfolio started, but of course, the more money the
better. The point is just getting started. There are some
investment programs, like mutual funds, that one can invest in with
as little as $25 to start.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gonzales: There is only one way to eat an elephant, and that's
one bite at a time. Most banks will allow you to open a savings
account with as little as $100. Mainstay Funds, which are offered
through New York Life, which I represent, allow investors to open
an account with as little as $100 and a $50 monthly bank draft.
There really is no excuse for not saving.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Diaz: What I tell my clients is that it's not so important how
much you start with, but how soon you start. When investing, your
best allies are time, the power of compound interest, and the rule
of 72. The rule of 72 states that to determine how fast your money
will double, divide 72 by your annual return. For example, if
you're getting a 12 percent return on your investments, you will
double your money in six years (72 divided by 12 equals six).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    2. What Is the single best tip you would offer a young person
just getting his or her professional life arted?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Barajas: The single best tip for a young professional is to get
him or her to understand why he or she should start saving early.
The why is more important than the how. The how is easy, but
understanding the why takes more thought. However, once you know
the why, you will reach your financial goals without a problem. The
next best tip is to take 10 percent of your hard-earned income and
save it through your company pension plan. Pay yourself first!
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mojica: My best tip for young professionals is: Save
consistently and minimize consumer debt.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fernandez: For the young person just getting started, the best
financial advice would be to take advantage of your employer's
benefit plans like 401(k), retirement plans, employee stock
purchase plans, etc. This is usually the best and cheapest way to
start saving and building net worth.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gonzales: Start your financial plan now! It's never too early.
The sooner you start, the less you'll have to put away later and
the more you will accumulate in the end.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Diaz: The first thing a young person should do is enroll in his
or her company's 401(k) plan and save the maximum allowed under the
plan. (Besides the tax benefits), most companies match employee
contributions anywhere between 1 to 6 percent. That's free money.
If the company you work for does not offer any retirement plan,
start your own IRA or Roth IRA. If you own your business, start a
Simplified Employee Pension (SEP) plan.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    3. What are steps baby boomers can take to plan for the future?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Barajas: Baby boomers have a number of options. A.) If possible,
save up to 10 percent of your income for financial independence
through a retirement program (pre-tax). B.) Save 10 percent Of Your
income for current financial needs (so you won't have to rely on
debt). C.) Protect your family with enough life (buy ``term''
only), disability and health insurance.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mojica: Good advice to baby boomers includes: A.) Obtain
objective, qualified, professional financial advice. B.) Clearly
understand your goals, objectives and risk tolerance level.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fernandez: Baby boomers should sign up for the plans offered by
their employers, set up a financial plan with reasonable goals and
start as soon as possible to take advantage of the power of
compound interest.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gonzales: If you're a baby boomer and haven't started a serious,
systematic savings plan for retirement, you have a lot of catching
up to do. Start by taking advantage of any qualified pension plan
that may be available to you. Pension plans allow you to save for
retirement on a tax-deferred basis while you receive tax deductions
for your contributions. Contribution limits vary from $2,000 to
$30,000 a year, depending on the type of plan.
 &HT;    Second, take advantage of the Roth IRA. So long as your earned
income is less than $95,000 as a single person (or $150,000 if
you're a married couple), you can contribute up to $2,000 of your
after-tax income to your Roth IRA. This type of IRA grows tax-free:
You don't pay tax on your gains so long as you leave the money in
the account for at least five years. Two thousand dollars a year
may not seem like much, but over the years your Roth savings will
add up.
 &HT;    Lastly, get permanent life insurance. The cost of term-life
insurance rises as we age and can become cost prohibitive for some.
If you get permanent coverage now, you'll have time to get it paid
off before you retire, freeing up money for your retirement.
 &HT;    A good option is to get a variable universal life insurance
policy, which allows you to maintain your life-insurance coverage
while you invest in mutual funds. The growth in this life insurance
policy grows tax-deferred and the death benefit is paid directly to
your beneficiary, who doesn't have to pay income tax on his or her
windfall.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Diaz: If you were born between 1946 and 1963 and have not
started saving for retirement, you should immediately determine how
much risk you're willing to take with your investment portfolio and
how you want to diversify your investments (probably with the help
of a financial consultant). You should then open an IRA or Roth IRA
account and fund it according to your plan.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    4. What are some of the best ways families with children can
save for college expenses?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Barajas: For ways to save for college expenses, it depends on
the age of the child. If the child has more than five years to go
before starting college, a portfolio of growth mutual funds (U.S.
and international) is the best place to start investing. If the
child has less than five years to go before starting college, a
portfolio of balanced mutual funds, short term bonds, and money
market funds is ideal.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mojica: If sending your children to college is a priority, then
discipline is the key. Even if you only save a minimal amount per
child, the important thing is that it's done consistently. It will
help alleviate the problem of goiing into debt. It will also
provide the child with some understanding of the responsibility of
being a parent and hopefully allow him or her to appreciate the
privilege of receiving an education. There are also certain types
of loans, such as 401(k)s, which, if used for educational purposes,
can be obtained at minimal interest rates and may be withdrawn
without penalty. You should always consult a qualified tax
professional.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fernandez: Some of the best ways to save for college expenses
are as follows: Set up a Uniform Gift to Minors Act (UGMA) account
for the child and add to the account regularly. This will put the
money in the children's name. Also look at the Educational IRA as a
means of saving. Parents also can withdraw from their own IRA for
educational expenses.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gonzales: For college funding, you might consider making a gift
to your child or grandchild under the UGMA. After establishing a
UGMA account in a child's name, the first $650 in unearned income
deposited each year in the account is tax-free. The next $650 is
taxed at the child's tax rate, which is usually lower than that of
the parents or grandparents. Some restrictions apply when the child
is over the age of 14 and with unearned income amounts of $1,300 or
more.
 &HT;    You may also borrow money against the accumulated value of your
workplace's 401(k) plan when college rolls around. However,
remember that it's still a loan that must be paid back. I bought a
whole life insurance policy on each of my grandsons when they were
born. I realized their policies would only grow enough by their
college years to cover one year of college. But I also was locking
in their insurability at an early age and accumulating on a
tax-deferred basis; they will never have to pay a higher
life-insurance premium than what I paid at their birth.
 &HT;    The new Educational IRA allows for a $500 annual contribution.
However, with the rising costs of college tuition, I don't believe
this is enough, even if you start the plan at birth.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Diaz: The safest way to save for your children's education is to
buy zero-coupon bonds issued by the U.S. Treasury. These are bonds
that can be purchased at a discount to their value upon maturity.
For example, if you bought your newborn a $1,000 bond that matures
when the child reaches 18, you would pay approximately $350 now and
receive $1000 in 18 years. If you could tolerate more risk, you
could buy some stocks or mutual funds, and wait to see what growth
the stocks would return.
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
