A0770 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEECH-MARIN-PROFILE-     06-10 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEECH-MARIN-PROFILE-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEECH-TOSO! 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By VALERIE MENARD 
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    When Richard ``Cheech'' Marin shaved off his mustache in 1995,
he not only looked younger, he was transformed.
 &HT;    The actor/comedian's new look wasn't just what the role in
``From Dusk Till Dawn'' demanded, it marked the beginning of yet
another surge in his career. This would include a string of popular
films (``Tin Cup,'' ``The Great White Hype''), a children's record
(``My Name is Cheech, the School Bus Driver''), and a co-starring
role on the hit TV show ``Nash Bridges.''
 &HT;    In 1999, Marin has transformed his image yet again. The mustache
is back, but this time it's to promote a new line of hot sauces.
 &HT;    Marin, 42, says he always wanted to produce his own line of hot
sauces and so he found a specialty food company to help develop the
concept.
 &HT;    Figueroa Brothers, makers of Melinda's hot sauces, won the
opportunity to work with Marin. According to David Figueroa,
president of the company, he and his brother, Greg, were introduced
to Marin through artist Alan Aldridge.
 &HT;    The Hispanic-owned company had worked with the House of Blues,
with which Aldridge was associated, to create a line of hot sauces
for that restaurant chain as well as for Joe's Crab Shack.
 &HT;    The company put together different combinations, and after
several taste tests with Marin, three flavors were born: Gnarly
Garlic, Smokin' Chipotle and Mojo Mango.
 &HT;    ``These are not salsas,'' Marin clarifies. ``They're more in the
family of hot sauces, like Tabasco, and are designed to complement
any dish.''
 &HT;    Marin's favorite, Mojo Mango, combines mangos with habanero
chiles and works very well with fish, he says.
 &HT;    If Marin's latest venture elicits surprise from some, that
merely points to how little the public knows about the man _
despite the fact that he made up half of one of the most popular
comedy duos of the '70s, Cheech and Chong.
 &HT;    ``I've cooked all my life,'' Cheech says. ``My dad taught me.''
 &HT;    Oscar Marin, a member of the Los Angeles Police Department,
didn't enforce gender stereotypes on his son.
 &HT;    ``I remember cooking breakfast on weekends _ pancakes and
sausage, eggs and bacon, the typical breakfast stuff,'' he says.
 &HT;    That early training would come in handy later. In 1968 he left
California State University at Northridge _ just eight credits shy
of earning an English degree _ for Canada, where he worked as a
hotel chef and met Tommy Chong.
 &HT;    Twenty-seven years after the release of the first Cheech and
Chong comedy album, Marin has moved on. With every success, he has
developed a reputation for being the nicest guy in Hollywood.
 &HT;    He prefers to use his celebrity to help a cause. He has been
known to take his own car to an event, passing on an offered
limousine.
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, he plans to set aside a portion of the profits
from the sale of the hot sauces to a Latino charity. preferably one
that encourages self-help.
 &HT;    ``I'd much rather set aside funds like this than just throw
money at a cause. I'm a real believer in the parable that says,
`Give a starving man food, and you feed him for a day. Teach him
how to fish, and you feed him for life.''
 &HT;    Each time Latino consumers purchase a Cheech sauce, they will be
giving back to their community, consciously or unconsciously, he
says.
 &HT;    This is only part of Marin's extracurricular agenda. He's become
an avid golfer _ another fact he believes few people know about
him.
 &HT;    With a handicap of 15, he describes his skill level as
``studying to he an amateur.'' When he can, Marin participates in
celebrity golf tournaments that raise funds for different Youth
programs.
 &HT;    These efforts have earned him the 1999 NCLR/Kraft ALMA Community
Service Award. He plans to donate the $10,000 cash award to the
National Hispanic Scholarship Fund.
 &HT;    But that's not all. Marin is developing a project that's even
closer to his heart. Committed to preserving the Cultural legacy of
Latinos in the United States, Marin is the owner of one of the
largest personal collections of Chicano art. He's been approached
for years by friends and fans to organize an exhibit of his
collection.
 &HT;    He's chosen the new millennium to do just that. He plans to put
together a retrospective of Chicano art using pieces from his own
collection as well from others.
 &HT;    The exhibit will tour the country throughout the year and will
incorporate a multimedia interactive component that will encompass
the history of Latinos in all art disciplines from dancers to
comedians.
 &HT;    Marin also will continue playing the character of Joe Dominguez
in ``Nash Bridges,'' which was renewed for another season.
 &HT;    ``This has been the best season. We're having fun, getting paid
and living in San Francisco. What could be better?'' he asks.
 &HT;    (The Cheech sauces are available on-line at www.thecheech.com or
by calling toll-free, 877-424-3324.)
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Valerie Menard is a senior editor at Hispanic magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
