A0771 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPREME-COURT-DECISIO     06-10 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-DECISION:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC LEGAL DECISION STILL IMPACTS NATIVE-AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    The Santa Clara Pueblo vs. Martinez decision has impacted many
Indian people since the U.S. Supreme Court handed it down more than
20 years ago.
 &HT;    The court ruled that the Indian Civil Rights Act does not
subject tribes to the jurisdiction of federal courts in civil
actions for the injunctive or remedial relief. Plainly, the court
decided that federal agencies should not interfere with the
internal policies of an Indian nation.
 &HT;    The Martinez case originated on the Santa Clara Pueblo in
northern New Mexico. It involved a Pueblo woman married to a Navajo
mn. Mrs. Martinez attempted to get her half-Navajo children
enrolled in the tribe but discovered that a tribal ordinance only
allowed male members of the tribe married to nonmembers the right
to enroll their children. Women married to nonmembers could not
enroll their children.
 &HT;    Martinez and her children sued the Pueblo and its governor in
federal district court contending that the membership ordinance
violated the equal protection and due process provisions of the
Indian Civil Rights Act.
 &HT;    The Supreme Court's opinion reaffirmed the theory that Indian
tribes possess immunity from suit traditionally enjoyed by
sovereigns and that a waiver of sovereign immunity cannot be
implied but must be unequivocally expressed.
 &HT;    The court's opinion goes, ``First, is the plaintiff one of a
class for whose benefit the statute was enacted: second, is there
any indication of the legislative intent, explicit or implicit,
either to create or deny such a remedy? Third, is it consistent
with the underlying purposes of the legislative scheme to imply
such a remedy? Fourth, is the cause of action one traditionally
relegated to tribal law in an area basically of concern to tribes
so that it would be inappropriate to infer a cause of action based
solely on federal law?
 &HT;    The court concluded that ``Tribal courts have repeatedly been
recognized as appropriate forums for the exclusive adjudication of
disputes affecting important personal and property interests of
both Indians and non-Indians and the tribal forums are available.''
 &HT;    What the court intended, simply put, was to allow the Indian
nations to settle internal matters involving personal and property
interests within their own court system.
 &HT;    Most outside observers would believe that excluding Indian women
on Santa Clara from enrolling their children if they had a
nonmember father as outlandishly unconstitutional, but the court
recognized the sovereign right of the tribe to live within the
framework of its own culture and traditions.
 &HT;    Since that decision in the 1970s, several government agencies
have used it to duck controversial issues arising on many Indian
reservations. When confronted with these choices, they often allude
to the Martinez decision and wash their hands of the matter saying
they do not want to intrude upon tribal internal matters.
 &HT;    Some tribal leaders have used the Martinez decision to declare
open warfare upon political rivals. Given the freedom to act
independently without fear of interference by the Bureau of Indian
Affairs or the Interior Department gives a lot of elbowroom to
unscrupulous politicians.
 &HT;    Too often, decisions made by tribal courts can violate the civil
rights of tribal members and many times these decisions are made
for political reasons and have little to do with protecting the
tribe's right to make decisions on internal matters.
 &HT;    As in the larger society, laws enacted can be used for good or
evil. The Santa Clara Pueblo vs. Martinez decision strengthened
tribal governments in many ways but it also left the door open for
political skullduggery.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
