A0772 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALABAMA-1999:CONTRERA     06-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-1999:CONTRERAS-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 1959 ALABAMA IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican-American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    The best argument for term limits for politicians is an
83-year-old Democrat county tax assessor in Madison County, Ala.
 &HT;    The man just might be liable as a criminal for denying American
citizens their civil rights, by denying them legal tax benefits
that any Alabama homeowner is entitled to as long as the homeowner
swears that his application is true and correct.
 &HT;    Kevin Sack of the New York Times has brought to our attention
that Mr. Wayland H. Cooley, the elected county tax assessor for
almost six four-year terms, has denied American citizens their
rightful home tax exemptions because they don't speak English.
 &HT;    Cooley claims that the Alabama Constitution has English as the
official language of Alabama, thus, he cannot accept the oaths of
those who do not speak English. Not being able to give an oath
would thus render the application untrue. Madison County, where 3.8
percent of 272,000 residents are Hispanic or Asian, is the only
county in Alabama that does not allow interpreters to assist
applicants for tax exemptions. By the way, Alabama civil and
criminal courts can accept Spanish with interpreters.
 &HT;    A lawsuit has been filed by Dominican immigrants Julio and
Carmen de Paula Telleria, 71 and 59 respectively, who came to the
United States in the 1960s and became citizens in 1982 under a law
that didn't require they speak English. They retired from their New
York and New Jersey jobs in 1995 and bought their Alabama house for
$54,000.
 &HT;    They went to Cooley's office in 1996 with their English speaking
son to claim their tax exemptions. He turned them down and when
informed they were U.S. citizens allegedly said that it doesn't
matter.
 &HT;    Cooley is wrong. He is wrong because the Alabama Attorney
General, Bill Pryor, says so in a formal opinion declaring that the
English-language provision in the Alabama Constitution does not
prevent someone from receiving their tax exemptions, as the
exemptions accrue to the property not to an oath.
 &HT;    Cooley has violated the United States Constitution's call for
equal protection and due process of law. The Southern Poverty Law
Center of Montgomery has filed the lawsuit. It has surveyed the
entire state of Alabama and finds that Cooley is the only tax
assessor in the state who refuses to accept any language but
English.
 &HT;    What is Cooley doing here?
 &HT;    There are two previous cases in which Cooley denied property tax
exemptions to a native of Mexico. His comments to an FBI analyst
who offered to act as interpreter are instructive. Mary Catherine
Graham says, ``He said that he had to watch out for people who were
trying to come in from all over the world and skin us on taxes.''
 &HT;    Cooley told a real estate agent who volunteered as an
interpreter that ``They're coming over here and taking what's
ours.''
 &HT;    What we have here, is a case of all foreigners looking alike, a
touch of xenophobia and, perhaps, a case of dementia. This is not
to speak ill of an 83-year-old, but certainly we would have few
Cooleys around if there were term limits for all political offices.
 &HT;    We have the English-only conundrum here and that is a phony
issue that appeals to people like Cooley, but didn't appeal to the
founders of the country. We then have the issue of whether a State
constitution can override the U.S. Constitution. The issue of
whether a county official can violate the ``equal protection'' and
``due process'' and be immune, as Cooley claims, from taking legal
responsibility is involved here, as well. And, Cooley is going to
learn that a naturalized citizen cannot be denied anything a
native-born citizen can receive.
 &HT;    Cooley claims that he gives all English-speaking citizens what
they are entitled to, thus he has violated no law. But, again, the
State Attorney General has issued a formal ruling that tax
exemptions cannot be denied on the basis of language, despite the
language provision of the Alabama Constitution. What Cooley doesn't
claim is that he is a racist, but he is. He hasn't claimed that he
is a xenophobe and hates immigrants, but he is and does.
 &HT;    Is he alone in Alabama? Or is Alabama a hotbed of xenophobes and
haters of foreigners? It looks like he's pretty much alone. The
Asian population is growing in Alabama, as is the Hispanic
population. Prior to this situation, there haven't been too many
problems of note for immigrants in Alabama.
 &HT;    We can only hope that the lawsuit will put Cooley in his place
and send a signal to everyone else that neither Cooley nor anyone
else can discriminate on any basis as a public official. We can
also hope that Cooley takes the hint and retires from office. We
can further hope that if he runs for reelection, the good people of
a fairly sophisticated space city will retire him from office.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
