<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0775 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERS-CARNABY-BOS &LR;      06-10 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERS-CARNABY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE AUSTIN POWERS, STREET STILL SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PEGGY HERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Perry Brooks is groovy, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks sports a moptop, an orange wide-collared shirt open at
the neck, and brown polyester pants that hug his slim hips, flaring
just so over mock croc ankle boots. And he has a mood ring that is
tinting a pale blue. Very mod.
</P>
<P>
   The only person cooler is Austin Powers, the foppish British
secret agent featured in the 1997 film, ``Austin Powers,
International Man of Mystery.'' On Carnaby Street, the epitome of
swinging London in the 1960s, Austin rules _ or is at least
emulated by 20-somethings such as Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff I can relate to in Austin Powers
because I'm heavily into the '60s and swinging London,'' said
Brooks, who works at Sherry's, a '60s store on the street.
</P>
<P>
   So news that the ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' is
finally hitting the screens in the United States _ although not in
the United Kingdom until this summer _ was greeted warmly along the
street, which set fashion standards in the '60s with its
psychedelic colors, garish designs, and outrageously short
hemlines. Because, on Carnaby Street, a half-mile swath in central
London, mod never went out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows about mods and everyone has blokes who were, or
have been mods,'' said Phil Meynell, 19, at Face, another retro
shop off Carnaby Street. ``It's totally cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnaby Street, Abbey Road, Portabello Road, St. John's Wood.
These were the haunts of young Mick Jagger, Twiggy, the Beatles,
Marianne Faithful, The Who, The Yardbirds, and Petula Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Abbey Road, for one, remains unscathed by time, except for fresh
graffiti on the nearby fence of the Beatles' former recording
studio. Carnaby Street, however, was defined by its commercialism.
That element still exists.
</P>
<P>
   A walk down the pedestrian thoroughfare is like being on an
Austin Powers's set: Hendrix and Morrison posters abound, the Union
Jack flies at nearly every shop, and buyers can pick up plastic
breasts, plastic blowup chairs or mushroom-shaped ceiling lamps.
The clientele is young, and business has never been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a lot of cravats and velvet suits,'' said Helen
Robinson of Pop Boutique. ``We just get a lot of people who follow
'60s fashions and they like to look here, especially on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all young people,'' she says, then slightly wrinkles
her young nose. ``Not 40-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, baby boomers and older generations this side of the pond
seem to be ignoring comic Mike Meyers and his movie persona, Austin
Powers. Commentary in British press _ which enthusiastically
embraces nearly every popular topic _ has barely scratched the
Austin Powers surface. When they do, it is to decry a return to
that ``vulgar'' era.
</P>
<P>
   But younger, cooler Britannia says Austin Powers is all in fun.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers ``has got a really good sense of humor. Even though
Austin is making fun of the English, he's also looking at their
ability to laugh at themselves,'' said Lewis Wharton, 24, who
sports a mild mod look with a shag haircut and retro eye wear.
``He's not a bad guy to have stereotype the English.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Britons embrace Meyers for several reasons: They enjoyed
his performance in ``Wayne's World,'' his parents are British
(although he is Canadian), and he did a stint long ago on British
children's television in a show called ``Wide Awake Club.'' But it
is Austin Powers and the '60s they never knew that they have
embraced the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie was hilarious,'' Brooks said. ``It draws a lot of
obvious references from the '60s, but it was very amusing. I even
thought the teeth thing was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Underneath all of his shagadelic bravado, Austin Powers owns
plaque-encrusted, yellow, crooked teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the movie, I thought: `What was that all about?' ''
recalled Wharton. ``My (American) girlfriend had to tell me: You
English don't know you've got bad teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meynell disagreed. Mike Meyers ``has got it quite right,''
he said. Then he smiled wide and flashed crooked, yellow teeth.
``We all have bad teeth over here. We don't care!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
