<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0776 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PREDATORS-SPI &LR;      06-10 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PREDATORS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BEST TO QUIETLY AVOID THE TBS MOVIE, `SILENT PREDATORS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every now and then, critics need to sharpen their claws, which
apparently is why movies like Sunday's ``Silent Predators'' on TBS
Superstation are made.
</P>
<P>
   It's a marvelous public service. But trust me. Unless you're a
critic you don't have to see this movie, because you've already
seen it. And you know how it ends. It is cinematic schlock of the
first order, featuring acting and writing so pedestrian it could be
arrested for jaywalking.
</P>
<P>
   As a horror-genre flick aimed at viewers who like to be shocked,
``Silent Predators'' has some grab-the-sofa moments, thanks mainly
to well-timed music (by Michael Tavera). It's about killer snakes
in California, none of whom works in the film industry. The premise
is the same as in all the ``Jaws'' movies, the only difference
being that it's land-based, so the advertising slogan would be
altered slightly to something like: ``Just when you thought it was
safe to go into the crawl space beneath your house ... ''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the original script for ``Silent Predators'' is
nearly 20 years old. Horror-meister John Carpenter (``Halloween'')
intended it as a feature film, but it went the way of many grand
cinematic schemes and never got made. (Possibly because it was so
much like the ``Jaws'' oeuvre?) Anyway, TBS chose it for its
original-movie lineup, but whatever tweaking it received from
co-writers William Gilmore and Matt Dorff won't win it any prizes.
Example:
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Ever been to a herpetologist?''
</P>
<P>
   Gal: ``Excuse me?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``A snake scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   Gal: ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``There's always a first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the film, one of the characters actually says, ``Better
safe than sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hamlin is our hero, Vic Rondelli, the new fire chief in
the pleasant San Diego suburb of San Catalano. Shannon Sturges is
our heroine/woman in distress, Mandy Stratford, who works for the
bad guy but likes the good guy. Jack Scalia is our bad guy, Max
Farrington, a slimy real estate developer who knows he's not the
only snake in town but doesn't want to address the problem because
it'll ruin his business.
</P>
<P>
   The snakes are hybrids: a combination of the Western diamondback
rattlesnake and a much more lethal tropical variety. And therein
lies another problem: The film is called ``Silent Predators,'' but
these big honkin' reptiles _ an expert estimates there may be as
many as 35,000 bearing down on San Catalano _ are rattlers, and
they're not exactly quiet when disturbed by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Silent predators indeed. It's as if a maraca convention is
meeting in them thar hills. Was anyone at TBS paying attention?
</P>
<P>
   The best performance in this loser is Scalia's. Though
completely one-dimensional, his Farrington is relatively plausible:
greedy, opportunistic, self-centered. But with a thin script and a
hackneyed story, Hamlin and Sturges travel a path so worn that they
can't muster much support. They'd have been better off saying less
and giving the snakes more screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Silent Predators. Two-hour cable-TV movie about a small
California community infested with killer rattlesnakes. Starring
Harry Hamlin, Shannon Sturges and Jack Scalia. Sunday on TBS
Superstation. Repeats Wednesday and June 19. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
