<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHES TO ASHES TO BOMBS BURSTING IN AIR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   That fireworks display Wednesday night over San Francisco Bay
was put on by the Neptune Society, which was inaugurating its
fireworks display service for cremains.
</P>
<P>
   The ashes are packed into the fireworks and set off from a boat,
in a display the society says celebrates ``a life well lived.'' The
fireworks are visible from the shore.
</P>
<P>
   The service, which costs $3,200, is available for clients
cremated by the society or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A COUNTERPUNCH IS THROWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago,  &UR; John Updike &LR;  wrote about  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; 's ``A
Man in Full'' in the New York Review of Books, &LR;  and described the
book as ``entertainment, not literature.''
</P>
<P>
   This week in London, Wolfe told the Telegraph, ``In my country,
there are 273 million people. And not one of them is waiting for
the next John Updike novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN APRIL LOVES BECOME AUTUMN LEAVINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pat Boone &LR;  has founded the Gold Label, a record company for
artists more than 45 years old. Each of the performers has to have
earned at least two gold records.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream has been to have a roster of legendary artists who
have been overlooked and neglected by record companies,'' he told
New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Boone has already signed  &UR; Sha Na Na &LR;  and  &UR; Jack Jones, &LR;  and is
talking with  &UR; Eddie Fisher &LR;  and  &UR; Steve Lawrence &LR; . A representative
of the company told the magazine that contracts for  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Goulet &LR;  and the  &UR; Mills Brothers &LR;  are in the works, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PETA ADS REJECTED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A series of billboards in which People for the Ethical Treatment
of Animals linked meat-eating with impotence has been rejected in
cattle-raising states (Texas, Nebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma and
Colorado), says PETA.
</P>
<P>
   Meat-eating causes fat and cholesterol, which clog the arteries,
the group claims, and thus leads to impotence.
</P>
<P>
   The organization says it will try to convey the message in ads
posted inside bar and restaurant bathroom stalls.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. PETA released this week a 15-second TV commercial starring
 &UR; Linda McCartney &LR; , who died a year ago. The ad opposes National
Fishing Week, June 5 to June 13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPARE AND CONTRAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On his way into the Washington Square Bar &AMP; Grill the other day,
 &UR; Jim Schock &LR;  overheard two gentlemen in conversation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine's smaller than yours,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the other, ``mine is smaller, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hold them side by side and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Schock said he couldn't resist eavesdropping further. The gents
were discussing their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rolling Stone reports on the World Music Awards recently in
Monaco, co-hosted by  &UR; Pamela Anderson Lee &LR;  and  &UR; Damon Wayans &LR; .
Commenting on his co-host's recent breast implant removal surgery,
Wayans said, ``If they were bigger before, I don't know how she
stood up. She must have had a kickstand or something.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A comparison of the Napa Valley to the Hamptons in Sunday's
New York Times reveals that  &UR; Tom Waits &LR;  is going to sing ``Here
Comes the Bride'' when  &UR; Sofia Coppola &LR;  marries director  &UR; Spike &LR; 
 &UR; Jonze &LR;  at the Coppolas' place in Rutherford this summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Everybody in New York has ``Run, Hillary, Run'' bumper
stickers on their cars, reports  &UR; Baird Jones &LR; . Democrats have them
on their rear bumpers; Republicans on the front.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regarding Paris in Las Vegas:  &UR; Bonnie Jones &LR;  reports that on a
recent trip she was unable to find pate anywhere in Las Vegas, but
did locate the ``largest Krispy Kreme doughnuts factory store in
the West.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dennis Bradley &LR; , a recent graduate of Duke University's Fuqua
School of Business, is still watching over the place: That
``Oprah'' quote cited in Personals and attributed to  &UR; Ted Turner &LR; 
by People magazine was actually said by a student speaker,  &UR; Craig &LR; 
 &UR; Crawford &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me that he gained 30 pounds, and I was so
excited. It was like, `Oh good, at least he put on weight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Faye Resnick, friend of Nicole Brown Simpson, describing the
depth of her negative feelings about O.J. Simpson, in People
magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
