<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-0611     06-10 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFUGEES AND U.S. TROOPS BOTH LOOK WITH SKEPTICISM AT THE
JOURNEY TO KOSOVO
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia As Ismet Blakgori's extended family of
refugees languished in the shade of their tent flap in Thursday's
breathless heat, they listened to the radio, talked now and then,
and didn't even think much about prospects of returning to their
Kosovo neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the news they said we would be going home soon, but we
don't trust it,'' said 50-year-old Blakgori, who was stretched out
on a blanket until a grandbaby landed in his arms. ``We THINK this
time might be different, but we still don't trust it.''
</P>
<P>
   On another outskirt of town, paratroops of the elite 82nd
Airborne Division were idling outside their own hot tents at Camp
Able Sentry Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And like the refugees at the Stankovec camp, many of them were
considerably less than euphoric over the deal NATO finally clinched
with Yugoslavia on Wednesday night to stop the latest of the ugly
Balkan conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Some troops sitting on gravel outside their olive drab tents
likewise voiced skepticism about what lies ahead as they try to
secure Kosovo so families like the Blakgoris can return safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not too happy, to tell you the truth,'' said Sgt. John
Newland, 27, of Fayetteville, N.C. ``Most of the guys are going to
BS you and say they are proud to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Newland, among a group that had shed flak jackets and
helmets in favor of their brown T-shirts and camouflage pants, said
these troops of the 82nd Airborne Division didn't sign up for
service as the world's policemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting ourselves in a nutroll,'' he said. ``It's like
Bosnia. They make a plan to get out, but it is not possible to get
out because without you the fighting is going to start all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly some Kosovar Albanian refugees and some newly-arrived
U.S. soldiers are enthusiastic about the prospects of how the
coming weeks will unfold. But voices in both camps spoke with
arresting hesitation and worry, if not downright pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   At another tent in the Stankovec refugee camp, two women and
nine children hanging around in the desultory afternoon were
perplexed about what to do if the deal works and they are sent
home.
</P>
<P>
   Naile and Bahnie Zhieqi, who married brothers now working in
Italy, enjoy a vastly better situation than the thousands of women
whose husbands were separated from them and now are missing.
</P>
<P>
   But the pair is still fearful and uncertain of how to proceed in
this culture where women are not so used to being either
decision-makers or breadwinners. A complication is that their homes
in Podjevo were burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have our husbands. We don't have our houses. How will
we survive?'' said Naile Zhieqi, 31, who has three children.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Camp Able Sentry, Spec. Christopher Miller, 21, of
Elizabethton (CQ), Tenn., wasn't so worried about survival, but he
did express concerns not so dissimilar to Zhieqi's about readiness.
He said American soldiers were never trained for this kind of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a trying experience,'' said Miller, who pointed to
the problem of target recognition now that this mission is not
simply about shooting enemy soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previously when one of us saw a Serb soldier, we could regard
him as an enemy contact,'' he said. ``Now we have to wonder whether
it is just a soldier who has gotten lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The physical hazards of Kosovo sometimes were troubling to both
refugees and troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hope to be back this year, because they destroyed
everything. We don't have a home any more. We don't have a place to
sleep,'' said Haxhi Ibrahimi, 52, of Pushkosova, a village outside
of the Kosovo capital of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in a half-hour conversation, Ibrahimi spoke of the
mines both refugees and military think are planted around Kosovo.
He also feared the retreating Serbs left booby traps in the homes
or barns or wells of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   To the military, such dangers are simply a way of life. What
does raise some concern is how efficiently the troops _ as
peacekeepers _ will be able to defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty stupid we are coming down here,'' said Spc.
Nathan Poppenga, 20, of Centerville, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``We train for hostile situations. And when we get deployed, we
spend all our time peace keeping,'' he said. ``Basically, we have
to wait for them to shoot. By then it may be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Blakgori tent, a cavernous structure housing 13
people, Ismet's brother Idriz was clad in shorts and was virtually
wearing the radio he never put down as he talked about the
prospects of the peace pact working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are happy, some are skeptical. We don't trust
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about the family's two years of bad experiences that
he said began after another brother was beaten by Serbian police
and died. Others of the family were arrested and harassed, but none
treated so badly as that brother who was arrested and fatally
beaten a day after he held a ceremony in his school room in honor
of Albanian national day.
</P>
<P>
   Those bad times are enough to make them wary of returning, and
now the three surviving brothers from Pristina, their parents and
children, have heard that everything was stolen from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a hint of hope crept into the bleak commentary of
brother Ismet Blakgari
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NATO troops are there and clear the mines, then we will
go,'' he said. ``It's better in my house, even if I have nothing,
than it is here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
