<HEADER>
A0784 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SHOWGIRLS-REVIEW-S     06-10 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOWGIRLS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING CHANNEL EXPLORES THE WORLD OF SHOWGIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's 6 feet tall in her stocking feet, and pushing 10 feet in
her work clothes.
</P>
<P>
   High heels and feathery headdresses do that to a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Vanderliet is the (set ital)vedette(end ital) _ the star _
of the high-strutting stage show at the Lido in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the world's most glamorous jobs. But outside the
famous nightclub, she says, ``I'm a Northern California girl. I
come from the Bay Area and I love the outdoors. I like to put my
jeans on. I'm just a down-to-earth kind of girl without a lot of
makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderliet, who grew up in Orinda, Calif., and once studied
ballet in San Francisco, has been at the Lido for a decade. She's
not only its lead dancer but, at 39, its oldest.
</P>
<P>
   She's also one of the featured personalities in a cable TV
documentary to be televised Sunday. Narrated by Anjelica Huston,
the film by Agnieszka Piotrowska is called ``Showgirl Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest eyebrow-raiser from The Learning Channel, the
cable channel that promises ``adventures for your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous mind adventures on the channel that now simply calls
itself TLC have included documentaries about swimsuits (``History
of the Bathing Suit: Nothing to Hide'') and lingerie (``Next to
Nothing: The History of Lingerie'').
</P>
<P>
   Are we feeling adventurous yet?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watches might wonder what sorts of adventures went
into editing the film for TV.
</P>
<P>
   TLC seems to be majoring in physical education but not in
anatomy. Bare breasts have been blurred in the film, and in many
shots nipples have been magically eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showgirl Stories'' runs the gamut from hip-grinding lap
dancers to stage stars such as Vanderliet. It's a lavish production
with some serious intent and, at least, a few light points to make
about fleeting beauty.
</P>
<P>
   But at two hours, the film is too long and sometimes meanders
its way without good effect through the stories of showgirls in
London, Paris, New York, Las Vegas and the Mojave Desert, home to
an exotic dancer museum.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to meet a few of the surviving Ziegfeld Girls
and to hear about wealthy admirers showering them, way back when,
with roses, diamonds and hundred-dollar bills for their cab fares.
</P>
<P>
   But I could have done without a tour of a showgirl's suburban
Las Vegas house. (``Me and my ex-husband, we bought it together ...
This is the TV room, as I call it. As you can see, I love pink.'')
</P>
<P>
   Vanderliet, a University of California at Irvine graduate who
made her way to Paris via Reno and Lake Tahoe revues, stands out as
one of the more sensible performers in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Good sense seems to be a lifelong trait. On a recent visit to
San Francisco, she said in an interview that although she devotedly
took ballet classes, she knew since childhood that she wouldn't
dance ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew when I was a little kid,'' she said. ``You know,
you look in the mirror every day when you take a ballet class. You
look and you expect perfection. I knew what perfection was, and I
didn't see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go to New York and pursue New York City
Ballet or ABT (American Ballet Theatre). I grew too tall. I didn't
want to suffer. I knew I wouldn't be a diva, a prima ballerina. It
wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   But what was wrong for the ballet stage was altogether right for
the international troupe at the Lido. The minimum height for a Lido
dancer is 5 feet 9 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The film captures a pensive Vanderliet talking about her
decision not to marry during her stage career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally have chosen to be alone and lonely than to be
with someone else and lonely,'' she says, and the comment sounds
sage in the context of Piotrowska's film.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco interview, Vanderliet said she's wrestling
with the knowledge that age is closing in on her showgirl career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed to say it: I'm pushing 40,'' she said. ``Most
people finish long before this. I'm preparing myself now mentally
for that, because you can't do it forever.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her future possibilities include returning to the Bay
Area as a dance teacher and maybe taking a stab at a new career in
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the crossroads right now,'' she said. ``I wish I could
give you a straightforward answer. I'm trying to make a decision
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
