<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-AUSTIN-COX     06-10 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AUSTIN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   `Austin Powers': It's still a gas, baby
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE CRITIC
</P>
<P>
   Chaos hits Carnaby Street when our favorite dentally impaired
British superspy has his mojo, and much of his new movie, stolen by
Dr. Evil. But because Mike Myers plays both the good guy and the
bad guy (and a third character to boot), he has only himself to
blame for the scene-stealing in ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   In this follow-up to 1997's surprise hit, Myers keeps the faith
with Austin fans, delivering a gas of a sequel. The flick gives us
a new curvy love interest, Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham),
while bringing back Seth Green as Dr. Evil's sullen son Scott and
Robert Wagner and Mindy Sterling as henchpersons Number 2 and Frau
Farbissina. We also get Rob Lowe doing a perfect Wagner imitation
as Younger Number 2 and tiny Verne Troyer as Dr. Evil's clone,
Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   As shaggy as it is shagadelic, ``Spy'' is really just an excuse
to take comic aim at pop institutions, from ``Star Wars'' to
Starbucks, with ``The Jerry Springer Show'' thrown in as a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The movie zaps us back and forth between 1999 and 1969, but
don't worry about plot; screenwriters Myers and Michael McCullers
barely do. Instead, revel in the movie's gleeful bad taste. That
includes toilet humor involving a greasy, flatulent, kilt-wearing,
obese Scotsman (Myers in a body suit); a genital-biting battle
between Austin and Mini-Me; and a scatological shadow play that
climaxes with a gerbil joke. The gags this time out are more body
humor than boudoir. In other words, kids will love it.
</P>
<P>
   The movie doesn't always hit its targets. When Dr. Evil commands
son Scott to ``zip it,'' the ensuing shtick goes on too long. So
does his riff on '90s catch phrases (``Don't go there,
girlfriend''), which bewilders the U.S. president of 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The prez is played by Tim Robbins, one of many cameos. Willie
Nelson and Woody Harrelson also appear, lending their first names
to a riotously juvenile running gag about Dr. Evil's phallic-shaped
space shuttle. Elvis Costello and Burt Bacharach also turn up to
sing ``I'll Never Fall in Love Again.''
</P>
<P>
   These celebrity visits underscore the charm of ``The Spy Who
Shagged Me.'' It's a pop-art party where the host is happy to do
anything to keep the guests laughing _ whether that means wearing
rotten teeth and a chest pelt or running around in a bikini. Last
summer we had ``There's Something About Mary.'' This year, ``Austin
Powers'' meets our need for undiluted silliness. And best of all,
at 95 minutes, it doesn't waste any time giving us our fix. And
that, indeed, is groovy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy
</P>
<P>
   Who Shagged Me''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mike Myers and Heather Graham. Rated PG-13 for sexual
innuendo and crude humor. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The sequel's a gas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0786 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BESEIGED-COX     06-10 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BESEIGED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    l
 &HT;    Exquisite, if you're really in the mood
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Thandie Newton was ``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's ``Besieged.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to move to a new letter of the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Made for Italian television by Oscar-winning director Bernardo
Bertolucci (``The Last Emperor''), ``Besieged'' is an art film for
the MTV Generation. Most of the story is conveyed through image and
music; in fact, the two leads don't really talk to each other until
a half hour into the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Newton plays Shandurai, a proud, beautiful African woman who has
moved to Rome after her husband was arrested by her country's
repressive government. David Thewlis plays her employer, Kinsky, a
reclusive, music-loving Englishman who has inherited a huge villa
in Rome filled with antiquities. While she mops and cooks
downstairs (no mere maid, she's also studying pre-med), he mopes
and composes upstairs. Then, out of the blue, he makes a startling
confession: He's in love with her and would do anything to earn her
love in return. Shocked, perhaps even frightened, she snaps
angrily, ``You get my husband out of
</P>
<P>
   jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the villa is becoming noticeably less stuffed with,
well, stuff. Shandurai slowly realizes Kinsky is as good as his
word. He's selling his art, his tapestries, even his beloved piano
to finance his rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the film has a fairy-tale Beauty-and-the-Beast
quality. Kinsky may be ardent, but his eccentricity has made him
remote and unfamiliar with human contact. His gestures of love are
as strained as a schoolboy's (a love note consists of a sheet of
music with a question mark on it). A more successful gambit is the
way he begins to work African rhythms into his white European male
repertoire. Yet, while there is a culture-clash component, theirs
is not just an opposites-attract love story. Rather, the two are
surprisingly similar _ both isolated exiles, wary of, yet aching
for, connection.
</P>
<P>
   The film is full of exquisite touches, but the bottom line is,
``Besieged'' is a movie you have to be in the mood for. Otherwise,
it comes off as a bit overblown and solemn/silly. If you're not
caught up by Bertolucci's mastery of nuanced sight and sound, you
may find yourself thinking, gee, Thewlis really does look better
with a beard (as in ``Naked,'' his breakthrough film). Or wondering
about the incredibly gifted Newton, whose career is almost a case
study in the limited opportunities available to actors of color.
She's wonderful here. She's wonderful in just about everything she
does. But she's already done the smart-servant-loved-by-the-master
bit (in ``Jefferson in Paris'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' is more bothersome than bad _ a congruence of
top-flight talent from which you somehow expect more than swooning
camera shots and operatic emotional shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Thandie Newton and David Thewlis. Directed by Bernardo
Bertolucci. Rated R for brief nudity. 1 hour, 34 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: MTV meets the art-house movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LIMBO-COX     06-10 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LIMBO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An unsettling, intriguing `Limbo'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By all rights, John Sayles' career should be in limbo. Only a
filmmaker independent to the point of near-insanity would follow a
commercial breakthrough like ``Lone Star'' with something as
doggedly uncommercial as ``Men With Guns'' (Central American
politics? Subtitles? )
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Limbo'' is the title of his new work, a movie that
evinces Sayles' ornery, goes-his-own-way streak in spades. It's as
if he started out to make one picture _ a tender, middle-aged
romance told against the backdrop of encroaching tourism in Alaska
_ and then got interested in something entirely different: an
unsettling metaphysical survival tale.
</P>
<P>
   The setup is Sayles at his satirical best. Welcome to Alaska,
land of azure skies, cathedral-sized icebergs and omnipresent
``floating nursing homes'' (read, cruise ships). Tourism is on a
rampage, turning the state into a giant theme park. One developer
cautions another to avoid cutting down trees along the coastline:
``Heavy machinery they can see in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In semi-bustling Port Henry (a thinly disguised Juneau), Joe
(David Strathairn) meets Donna (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio). He's
a former fisherman, landlocked since a fatal accident 25 years
earlier. She's a been-around lounge singer (actually, quite a good
one) with a sullenly sensitive teenage daughter (Vanessa Martinez).
</P>
<P>
   They come together tentatively, two people accustomed to the
kind of personal limbo where lives are shaped by ``unforeseen
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot's unforeseen circumstance turns up as Joe's shady
half-brother (Casey Siemaszko). He needs a favor, a favor that will
take the characters _ and the film _ in an unexpected direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' can't honestly be called a successful movie. The parts
simply don't add up to a satisfying whole. But it's always a
thematically intriguing and inherently honorable work, right down
to the true-to-its-title denouement. Sayles' pungent character
observations and knowing dialogue make it worth a look, as do the
two leads. Strathairn, a Sayles regular, has the delicate, soulful
masculinity of a latter-day Gary Cooper, while Mastrantonio invests
her character's nervous optimism with a kind of wayward courage.
</P>
<P>
   The same wayward courage, it might be said, that it takes to
make a movie like ``Limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Strathairn and Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
Directed by John Sayles. Rated R for language. 2 hours, 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Even a mixed-up John Sayles movie is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
