<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRWAR-0611-CO     06-10 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRWAR-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO AIR CAMPAIGN HISTORIC ACHIEVEMENT, BUT SUCCESS REMAINS
QUESTIONABLE
 &HT;    650&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There has never been an air campaign quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   Over 78 days, NATO warplanes flew 35,000 sorties, dropped 23,000
bombs, destroyed 1,500 targets and shattered the backbone of a
central European military force, all without losing a single U.S.
or allied pilot in combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an extraordinary achievement in the history of air
warfare, to be sure,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said
Thursday. Just hours earlier, NATO suspended its attacks against
Yugoslav military forces as they retreated from Kosovo, winding up
what Cohen called ``the most precise application of air power in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of its high-tech weaponry and success, the air campaign
was dogged by two of the oldest variables in the history of battle:
weather and terrain.
</P>
<P>
   During the early weeks of the air war, there were nights when
more than half of NATO's strike planes were forced to return to
base without dropping their bombs, because heavy cloud cover or fog
prevented them from using their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks after that, Serbs were able to hunker down inside
Kosovo, hiding tanks and heavy weaponry inside barns, alongside
churches or beneath foliage, frustrating NATO pilots. In several
instances, the strategy appears to have resulted in strikes that
caused civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the campaign settle the argument over whether air power
alone can win a war without the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't end the debate,'' said former Pentagon official
David Ochmanek, an expert on air power for RAND, a research
organization based in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   That's because NATO pilots had little success finding and
destroying concentrated groups of Serb troops in the field until
the last two weeks of the campaign, when Kosovo Liberation Army
rebels on the ground were able to force their opponents to mass and
move out into the open for battle.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign did go further than any other in history, Ochmanek
said, in demonstrating the extent to which modern air power can
isolate and grind away at a military force dispersed in the field _
to prepare the battlefield, in other words, for the successful
deployment of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air power was able to substantially place at risk the Yugoslav
army in Kosovo, and that, to me, was always the key to this,'' said
Ochmanek, who served as assistant secretary of defense for strategy
during the first two years of the Clinton presidency. ``The
viability of our strategy turned on being able to create in Kosovo
the conditions under which a ground force could be mounted.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in six months, U.S. Air Force and Navy pilots have
spearheaded bombing campaigns aimed at bringing intransigent
leaders to heel over issues the White House has defined as
important, if not vital, American interests.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day Desert Fox campaign last December used high-tech
air strikes to both punish Iraqi President Saddam Hussein for
impeding United Nations weapons inspections and to set back his
efforts to build or store weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Allied Force, the NATO campaign that was suspended
Thursday, coerced Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, to begin pulling 40,000 troops and police out of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   If the campaigns demonstrated the might of American air power,
though, they have also underscored its limits.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein and Milosevic may have paid a price for their conduct,
but they both remain in office, where they could well outlast their
antagonist, President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The outside world knows little about Hussein's weapons program
now, or about the extent to which December's bombings set those
efforts back.
</P>
<P>
   And the success of Operation Allied Force will forever be marred
by its tragic inability to stop the commission of atrocities on the
ground by Serb troops, police and paramilitary thugs that forced an
estimated 1.5 million ethnic Albanians to flee their homes in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In both Desert Fox and Allied Force, U.S. pilots relied heavily
on technologies and tactics that have advanced greatly in the
decade since the Gulf War ushered in the dawn of precision air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon didn't give the percentage of NATO bombs that
struck their targets during the 11-week campaign. Preliminary
battle damage assessments, however, suggest that the ratio will
prove to be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Of an estimated 23,000 bombs dropped, Cohen said the Pentagon
has confirmed just 20 instances in which munitions missed their
targets and caused unintended civilian deaths or destruction.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only measure of misses. The Pentagon has shown
footage of some bombs falling wide of the mark into forests or
fields, and even some instances in which pilots diverted bombs at
the last minute to avert the possibility of civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government, moreover, claims that some 1,500
civilians were killed by NATO strikes and four times as many others
were wounded. While that number is impossible to refute or confirm
with confidence, it would, if true, imply far more misses than the
Pentagon has admitted.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Without question, though, a large number of NATO's bombs landed
within a few feet of the bull's eye.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes destroyed or damaged beyond use roughly 500 fixed
targets _ refineries, airfields, military headquarters, ammunition
dumps, troop barracks, radio and television facilities among them.
Many of those required dozens of bombs to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Pentagon claimed Thursday that the strikes
destroyed or left inoperable 800 tanks, armored personnel carriers,
artillery pieces or mortars in the field in Kosovo, not to mention
scores of military trucks and cars and more than 200 military
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness stemmed from a combination of new technologies
and evolving tactics employed on a scale never before seen in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize the threat from the several hundred surface-to-air
missiles fired at them, NATO pilots flew high _ at altitudes
topping 15,000 feet during the first several weeks of the campaign
_ and dropped bombs that used lasers, satellite signals and
infra-red sensors to help direct them to targets several miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a revolution,'' said Ochmanek. ``Back in the 70s and
80s we were all about going low and going fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-altitude strikes helped protect pilots. Two U.S.
warplanes _ an F-16 and an F-117 stealth fighter _ were lost during
the campaign, but the pilots of both were rescued by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   Critics allege, however, that reducing the risk to pilots
increased the threat to civilians on the ground: both from Serb
forces and from errant NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
