<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-GANGS-HNS &LR;      06-10 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GANGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES STRIKE DOWN CHICAGO ORDINANCE AIMED AT GANGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided Supreme Court on Thursday limited the
ways in which cities can fight the scourge of gang violence,
striking down as unconstitutional a Chicago ordinance that allowed
police to disperse people congregating on street corners with a
suspected gang member.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 decision, the high court said the city's Gang
Congregation Ordinance violated the constitution's requirement that
criminal laws be clear. The justices assailed the Chicago statute
as vague, saying it gave police unbridled authority to order
loiterers to separate while providing city dwellers with no warning
of what behavior would constitute an illegal act.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago enacted the controversial ordinance in 1992 amid
outcries from city residents who said the presence of neighborhood
gangs had made them terrified to leave their homes. Police issued
more than 89,000 dispersal orders and arrested more than 42,000
people between August 1992 and December 1995, when an Illinois
court ruled the law unconstitutional, according to testimony in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union, which brought the case on
behalf of people arrested under the law, praised the court's
decision in Chicago vs. Morales. The ACLU said the law hit minority
youngsters especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are grateful that the justices of the Supreme Court
understand what escaped the political leaders of Chicago: namely,
that it is not a criminal activity simply to be a young man of
color gathered with friends on the streets of Chicago,'' said
Harvey Grossman, legal director of the ACLU of Illinois, who argued
the case before the high court. ``The Chicago ordinance is, sadly,
exemplary of what happens when politicians seek to appear tough on
crime, ignoring the basic rights of individual citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston criminal defense attorney Edward Mallett also hailed the
decision as providing ``great comfort to the American people'' that
they can peacefully assemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we might be upset that such laws can find a majority
in city councils,'' added Mallett, a senior vice president of the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``We have no such
laws in Texas that I'm aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Ruda, a Washington attorney who represents states
and municipalities, said the high court's decision preserves the
ability of cities to enact valid anti-gang ordinances so long as
the laws are more narrowly written to address gang violence. He
noted that, in this case, many justices wrote separate opinions
that either supported the Chicago ordinance or advised the city to
narrow its law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ordinance, people who failed to comply with an
officer's order to disperse were jailed for up to six months, fined
$500 and ordered to perform up to 120 hours of community service.
The law defined a loiterer as a person standing with a suspected
gang member ``in any one place with no apparent purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the court's majority,
said that ambiguous definition made potential criminals out of
innocent people who had no way of knowing that they were doing
anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to imagine how any citizen of the city of
Chicago standing in a public place with a group of people would
know if he or she had an `apparent purpose,''' Stevens wrote. ``If
she were talking to another person, would she have an apparent
purpose? If she were checking her watch and looking expectantly
down the street would she have an apparent purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens also expressed disdain for the law in saying that it
could have made criminals out of Chicago Cubs fans who were merely
standing together outside Wrigley Field to catch a glimpse of
slugger Sammy Sosa. Joining Stevens' opinion were justices Sandra
Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Justice Antonin Scalia took the unusual and highly
symbolic step of reading portions of his dissent from the bench, a
move reserved by justices who have the most profound disagreement
with the Court. Scalia, agreeing with arguments made by attorneys
for Chicago, said the city's ordinance was a constitutionally
reasonable method to keep thugs off residential streets.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia acknowledged that the ordinance imposed ``minor
limitations'' on the right of innocent people to congregate but
called the restriction ``a small price to pay for liberation of
their streets.'' He equated the anti-loitering ordinance to traffic
laws that restrict the freedom of people to drive fast but are not
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Chicago have decided that depriving themselves
of the freedom to `hang out' with a gang member is necessary to
eliminate pervasive gang crime and intimidation _ and that the
elimination of the one is worth the deprivation of the other, ''
Scalia wrote. ``This court has no business second-guessing either
the degree of necessity or the fairness of the trade (off).''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate dissent, Justice Clarence Thomas assailed the
court for striking down what he called the city's reasonable and
legitimate effort to keep its streets safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``By invalidating Chicago's ordinance, I fear that the court has
unnecessarily sentenced law-abiding citizens to lives of terror and
misery,'' Thomas wrote. ``Gangs fill the daily lives of many of our
poorest and most vulnerable citizens with a terror that the court
does not give sufficient consideration, often relegating them to
the status of prisoners in their own homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia and Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist joined Thomas'
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
