<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS11-COX     06-10 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists to show faith in evangelism
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the doorbell rings this weekend when you're not
expecting company, chances are it's a Southern Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 Southern Baptist churches in metro Atlanta will be
coordinating door-to-door canvassing Saturday through Wednesday as
part of an evangelism effort linked to the Southern Baptist
Convention meeting here next week.
</P>
<P>
   Some 700 teen-agers from across the country, known as
Frontliners, will participate, as will about 140 college and
university students. As many as 1,000 people will come in early for
the Southern Baptist Convention, which convenes Tuesday at the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate knocking on 50,000 doors through the metro
area,'' said Don Smith, associate for event evangelism for the
North American Mission Board of the 15 million-member Southern
Baptist Convention. Baptists will be visiting houses from Douglas
to Gwinnett and Forsyth to Henry counties asking questions about
church participation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, about 20 churches are hosting block parties for
their communities. Musicians, puppeteers and magicians will perform
on the streets in inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Teens from Peachtree City's Braelinn Baptist Churchwill wash
cars for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bible times, one way to serve was to wash people's feet,''
said the Rev. Barry Odom, the church's community pastor. ``We're
going to wash people's cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica Snelling, 18, will be out with the sponges and hoses. ``We
use practical ways to help out the community,'' she said. ``People
respond more to God's love when they see actions behind it and it's
not just words.''
</P>
<P>
   To put some large-scale action behind their evangelism, the
Baptists are hosting two mega-parties Saturday at Centennial
Olympic Park, one for families and one geared to teens.
</P>
<P>
   Family Fest '99 is a free carnival with rides, games, mimes,
magicians and stage shows taking place from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. at
the park. At 7:30 p.m. youth are invited to the ``Gettin' Free''
concert, featuring contemporary Christian groups Third Day and
Smalltown Poets.
</P>
<P>
   The evangelism blitz is known as Crossover Atlanta, a name
meaning both the proselytizing sweep over Atlanta and the cross of
Jesus over the city. Southern Baptists began Crossover activities
in their convention cities in 1989, Smith said. About 14,000 people
have made professions of the Christian faith as a result, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Baptists got national attention for evangelism in
Mormon-heavy Salt Lake City, heartland of the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints. Although Georgia is known as Bible
Belt country, there is room for work here, according to Joel
Harrison, director of missions for the Atlanta Baptist Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical challenge that we have in Atlanta is the
perception that Atlanta is not a mission field,'' he said. ``But
they don't realize the statistic that approximately 60 percent of
the people in the metro area are unchurched.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
