<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-SHOOK11-COX     06-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-SHOOK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The E. coli outbreak: One year later
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jordan Shook's long, yellow hair bounces like holiday
curling ribbons down her back, just as it did last June.
</P>
<P>
   Her little-girl teeth are white and straight, even if the tooth
fairy has claimed one. And when Jordan smiles at her mommy, it
still melts Judy Shook's heart.
</P>
<P>
   But the real trick is to even get a look at Jordan today, almost
a year after she contracted E. coli last June 12 at White Water
Park in Cobb County. The outbreak sickened 25 other children,
killing 2 1/2-year-old McCall Akin in July.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, now 5, spends most of her time in hiding in her pink
bedroom in Cartersville, or in doctors' offices hiding from nurses
and others who would stick her with a needle. She is scared of most
people, especially men, after having seen 62 doctors, mostly male,
and countless nurses and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   The once outgoing child uses her long hair as a veil to hide
from visitors. She darts out of her bedroom into the living room
only once every few minutes, then just as quickly runs back inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just say the word E. coli, and it makes me sick,'' Judy
Shook said as she talked about the effect of the infection on
Jordan and the other children. ``I feel like some of her innocence
has been taken away so senselessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is the sickest surviving child of last summer's outbreak
of E. coli 0157:H7, a deadly bacteria that health officials believe
was transmitted when an infected child visited a children's wading
pool at White Water Park. The germ can cause severe diarrhea in
mild cases, but some children get much sicker and, like Jordan,
develop a life-threatening kidney and blood disorder called
hemolytic uremic syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's parents, James and Judy Shook, said they feel blessed
for her life, despite the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to hold her and kiss her all the time and tell her
how much I love her,'' Judy Shook said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan may never get a clean bill of health. The Shooks are
uncertain whether their only child can go to kindergarten in the
fall. They feel happy when Jordan will agree to go to a church ice
cream social.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jordan's ever swimming again, Judy decided to hide a
sprinkler she bought for the garden hose; she had hoped to use it
to reintroduce Jordan to a bathing suit and water, but then decided
the child wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a stroke and seizures, undergoing dialysis,
physical therapy, occupational therapy and having been poked and
probed over nearly her entire body, Jordan is afraid someone will
hurt her. She also is afraid she's going to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can get real emotional,'' said her mother. ``And it's
hard. You see her little mouth pucker up and she says, `Am I going
to die, Mommy?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan undergoes occupational therapy once a week and physical
therapy once a month. She has regained most of the use of her left
side, which had been partly paralyzed from the stroke. She is not
on any medications.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors as far away as Dallas and Seattle have examined her and
are studying the functioning of her kidneys, brain and nervous
system for a prognosis, which the Shooks hope to receive next week.
</P>
<P>
   Of equal concern now is Jordan's emotional well-being, her
mother said. The Shooks and Jordan's doctors don't know how much of
her fear may be due to brain injury or from trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first come home, you think your life is going to be
normal,'' Judy said. ``And then you realize `normal' won't be in
your vocabulary anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When visitors stayed for a few hours at her Cartersville home
last week, Jordan asked three times, ``Mommy, I'm not going to have
to have any more blood tests, am I?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan spent 52 days in Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center
last summer. She underwent dialysis for almost two weeks. When she
was released from the hospital, she received daily physical therapy
for months. By winter, the therapy became weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors called Jordan a miracle because of her recovery. She
was nearly as sick as McCall Akin.
</P>
<P>
   Andy and Marisa Akin, McCall's parents, stayed fast by her
bedside, just as the Shooks did with Jordan. For days and nights
that seemed endless, both couples watched their little girls go
downhill, hooked up to machines and spliced with wires and tubes to
keep them tethered to life.
</P>
<P>
   They camped out in the waiting room of Scottish Rite's intensive
care unit, often unable to sleep or shower for fear they would miss
a moment of their daughters' lives, or miss being there when their
daughters needed them.
</P>
<P>
   Last July 22, doctors took McCall off life support machines. She
died that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Shook said she will never forget Marisa Akin's coming into
Jordan's room to give McCall's balloons to Jordan before she left
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just stood there and said, `You are so lucky.' And I will
never forget that. Marisa will never have the chance to be with her
little girl ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's death has been one of the hardest things to talk to
Jordan about, Judy Shook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell her that they just got a nasty germ, and that God
decided it was time for the other little girl to come home to
heaven. And she tells me, `I'm glad that God wasn't ready for me to
go, cause I want to stay with my mommy and daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
