<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LOTTERY11-COX     06-10 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LOTTERY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia lottery sales soon may set record
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Lottery Corp. could soon achieve a
national record with sixth straight years of revenue growth,
surpassing the $2 billion mark in annual ticket sales with help
from a successful new instant ticket game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lottery's contribution to state education is
expected to soar above $640 million for the fiscal year ending June
30 from $555 million a year ago, lottery CEO Rebecca Paul said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The strong performance comes after many state officials had
assumed the lottery had reached its peak _ even before competing
lotteries open next door in Alabama and South Carolina. A year ago,
Georgia ticket sales were virtually flat and lottery contributions
to the state fell slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned,'' said Rep. Newt Hudson (D-Rochelle),
chairman of the House Industry Committee that oversees the lottery.
``That's why I'm so pleased with this rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   After selling $1.74 billion in tickets last year, Paul said, the
lottery will sell $2 billion for the year ending June 30 ``unless
the sky falls.'' Paul said Georgia and Texas were the only U.S.
lotteries that achieved rising sales during their first five years.
Texas slumped in year six.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's sales have grown this year because of The Big Game,
Cash 3 and a popular new star: the $2 instant ticket game Jumbo
Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   With annual sales approaching $300 million, Jumbo Bucks is the
most popular instant game ever in Georgia because prizes total 69.9
percent of ticket prices. On average, lottery games pay back about
53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said the Jumbo Bucks payout is supplemented with money from
the lottery's unclaimed prize fund, which amounts to about $25
million a year. The game started in 1995 but was discontinued
briefly before taking off this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gained a great deal of momentum in the last six to
eight months,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its high payout ratio and popularity with players,
Jumbo Bucks may jeopardize the lottery's ability to return 35
percent of all ticket sales to the state for education. State law
requires that return to be ``as near as practical'' to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time last year, the lottery dipped below 35
percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lottery Chairman Wyck Knox attributed the failure to
unusually high payouts on Cash 3, the lottery's most popular
fixed-odds game. Cash 3 payouts have continued to run higher than
expected this year, but Paul and Knox said it was too early to tell
whether the lottery would reach the 35 percent standard this year.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said he was less concerned about achieving a 35 percent
payout than with maximizing dollars paid to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Most lottery employees receive bonuses based on lottery sales,
but Paul and a few senior officials receive bonuses tied to
payments to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said Paul's base pay was raised to $200,000 earlier this
year. ``Of course, our board will want to reward her for an
excellent year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
