A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-RDP-COX     06-10 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RDP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Running Time' needs a script
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aspiring filmmakers might love ``Running Time,'' a 70-minute,
black-and-white crime caper flick. It's composed of several long
takes that create the illusion that the movie is unfolding in a
single camera shot. It's a cool experiment. But as a movie _ you
know, something that gives you interesting characters, sharp
dialogue, plausibility and thrills _ it tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Campbell plays a bank robber leaving jail after five years
and then immediately jumping into another heist with some pals.
Things don't go as planned, resulting in some shootouts, chases and
an unexpected reunion with Campbell's high school girlfriend (Anita
Barone), now a hooker.
</P>
<P>
   That the yuppieish Campbell and the powder-puffy Barone don't
remotely seem like a crook or a hooker is only one distraction in
``Running Time.'' It doesn't help that writer-director Josh Becker
wants us to believe Campbell and Barone don't recognize each other,
even when they're face to face having quickie sex in the brightly
lit back of a truck. The movie's worst fumble is the long robbery
scene, which has Campbell and his main partner in crime (Jeremy
Roberts) wearing surgical masks that barely hide their faces,
shouting incriminating details about each other in a roomful of
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Becker obviously took a lot of time to figure out the
photographic logistics for his flick. Too bad he didn't take the
same amount of time writing a believable script. Or hiring someone
else to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running Time''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Campbell. Unrated, but contains profanity,
bloodshed and discreet simulated sex.
</P>
<P>
   One hour, 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A fun filmmaking stunt, but not much of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   `Elephant' plus IMAX equals BIG
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   If you like your elephants big, how about five stories tall?
``Africa's Elephant Kingdom,'' the new IMAX film at Fernbank Museum
of Natural History, delivers some eye-poppingly large pachyderms.
When one of these angry mamas comes charging at the screen to
protect her territory, don't be surprised if you feel like ducking
under your seat.
</P>
<P>
   The first IMAX movie from Discovery Channel Pictures,
``Kingdom'' follows a family of elephants as they survive drought
in Kenya. The flick is narrated by Avery Brooks, who plays the role
of a male ``bull.'' This viewpoint takes some getting used to, and
it never works especially well.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, it doesn't get in the way of the movie's mixture of
facts and spectacle. We learn that elephant clans are matriarchal.
The bulls tend to be loners who come around only when the mating
itch hits them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Everest,'' the pinnacle of IMAX movies, ``Africa's
Elephant Kingdom'' isn't visually astounding. But it has its share
of lovely images, including a massive storm whirling across the
plain. It strikes a pleasant balance: a film that's informative for
young people but won't have grown-ups looking at their watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa's Elephant Kingdom''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   An IMAX film. Unrated. 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An informative and lovely visit with pachyderms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
