u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      06-10 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE OF RUSSIAN TROOPS REMAINS AN OBSTACLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Western nations are considering new command
arrangements to ease Russia's concerns about participating into a
NATO-led peacekeeping force in Kosovo, allied officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With allied peacekeepers poised to enter Kosovo, the role of
Russian troops has emerged as one of the last major hurdles to a
durable peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Russian generals are scheduled to take up the issue on
Friday, and the matter is also receiving top-level attention.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called President Boris Yeltsin on Thursday to
encourage a settlement, and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott discussed the matter with Russia's prime minister, Sergei
Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the two sides are faced with a contradiction.
Allied officials insist that Kosovar refugees will not come back
unless they are protected by an effective peacekeeping force that
is commanded by a NATO general.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the Russians a sector of their own to control, NATO
officials add, would discourage the refugees from returning to that
part of Kosovo and lead to a de facto partition.
</P>
<P>
   But putting Russian troops under the control of a NATO general
is out of the question to most Russian politicians, who have
bitterly condemned the allied airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist sentiment against the alliance is running so high
that on Thursday the Communist-dominated Parliament urged in a
lopsided vote that Victor Chernomyrdin be stripped of his post as
Russia's special envoy to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   One simple way to resolve the issue would be to leave the
Russians out of the peacekeeping force. From a military
perspective, the Russian soldiers are not essential.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, however, NATO wants Russian troops to be deployed,
largely to prevent a further deterioration in Russian-Western
relations. So NATO officials are struggling to devise a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Under one approach, Russian troops would support NATO forces in
their area but would not be under their direct command.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Russian troops would be under the overall
supervision of the top NATO general in Kosovo, a less rigid command
structure that is designed to mollify the Russians while upholding
the alliance's principal of unity of command.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Moscow might accept such an arrangement.
But it is just one of a host of issues that remain to be settled.
</P>
<P>
   Money is likely to be a big issue. Citing Russia's financial
crisis and its cash-strapped military, Stepashin has publicly
proposed that the international community pay the cost of
stationing Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said that Russian officials have yet to formally ask for
funds. He declined to say Thursday whether Western nations might be
willing to provide them.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it clear how many troops Russia might send. Russia's
defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, initially talked about providing
up to 10,000 troops. But on Thursday the Defense Ministry talked
about dispatching 2,500 paratroopers, a deployment that could take
seven days or more.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of NATO, the Russians have so far refused
to go along with the kind of command structure they agreed to in
Bosnia, where Moscow has 1300 Russian peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   Formally, the Russian troops in Bosnia report to the Russian
general staff. But the Russian troops are deployed in an American
sector and as a practical matter are under the day-to-day
supervision of a two-star U.S. general.
</P>
<P>
   Given its strident criticism of NATO's air attacks, the Kremlin
appears to believe that replicating the Bosnia command arrangement
in Kosovo would make it vulnerable to charges that it is
cooperating too closely with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The military talks Friday will bring together Gen. Robert
Foglesong, a representative of the U.S. joint chiefs of staff, with
Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov, the chief of the international division
of the Russian Defense Ministry and a vociferous critic of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a solution ``will take a combination of political will
and very tough serious work on the part of military experts,''
Talbott said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an especially important challenge for Talbott. He was
one of the architects of the strategy to include the Russians in a
Balkan settlement. On the other hand, Talbott warned Thursday that
the Kosovo settlement could falter if the peacekeeping arrangements
were flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get this wrong, KFOR is not going to work,'' Talbott
said, referring to the NATO-led peacekeeping force. ``Unity of
command is absolutely crucial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
