u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-KILLING-0611-C     06-10 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KILLING-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN COMIC'S KILLING FOCUSES ON HIS DRUG USE RATHER THAN
COMMON CRIME
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ At first Paco Stanley's murder on a Mexico City
street was seen as the most glaring example yet of random crime
plaguing this troubled metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Television anchors sobbed and fans of the famous television
comic mourned, all assuming that Stanley was the innocent victim of
a vicious assault by gunmen Monday in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents of the city's mayor, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
also jumped on the bandwagon, anxious to weaken Cardenas'
presidential aspirations by blaming the mayor for failing to stem
the city's crime wave.
</P>
<P>
   But now it appears that Stanley's killing was not random, and he
may not have been so innocent. Instead of common crime, his death
is spotlighting another crisis in Mexican justice: the
pervasiveness of drugs in Mexican society and, possibly, the
brazenness of powerful drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   After his funeral Tuesday, Mexico City authorities announced
that Stanley, 56, died with cocaine in his body, half a gram of the
drug in his pocket and a special grinding kit consumers use to
reduce rocks to powder.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also said Stanley had lesions in his nose of the
type that habitual users develop.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City authorities have not announced they believe that
Stanley's killing is directly connected to drugs, but reports
suggest that narcotics are a primary line of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley was killed when gunmen fired a hail of bullets into his
head while he sat in his parked car outside a restaurant in Mexico
City's exclusive San Angel neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen escaped after the mobster-style execution, which
killed a bystander.
</P>
<P>
   A news report in Mexico's El Universal newspaper Wednesday cited
unnamed investigative sources who say Stanley was a pool-playing
buddy of the late Amado Carrillo Fuentes, the head of Mexico's
Juarez cocaine-smuggling cartel. Carrillo Fuentes died during
plastic surgery in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican public, by now accustomed to politicians being
linked to drugs, isn't having trouble accepting that the comic --
who hosted a popular morning show -- could have been mixed up with
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cruel to say it, but I can't understand how a man of his
importance could be killed in such a manner if he didn't have
something to do with drug traffickers or some other mafia,'' said
Irais Yanez, a 30-year-old Mexico City nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who really believed the city was a den of
injustice. But now that passions have fallen and after what
(authorities) have said, there are those of us who smell a rat,''
Yanez added.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's Reforma newspaper cited sources speculating that
Stanley was killed because he was late in paying a $300,000 debt on
a cocaine shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Reforma also said Stanley was implicated in trafficking by the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration. But in a statement, the DEA
strongly denied ever investigating Stanley and accused the
newspaper of ``making up'' information.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Duran Chavez, a Mexico City federal legislator and
representing Mexico's dominant Revolutionary Institutional Party,
said it could be true that a high-paid entertainer like Stanley
used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the simple fact that a citizen, a politician, an artist, a
student . . . uses drugs, doesn't mean that they are drug
traffickers,'' Duran Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Initially, it appeared that the biggest political casualty after
Stanley's killing would be Cardenas, predicted to be the leftist
opposition candidate for Mexico's presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the tables have turned. Emotional television coverage that
targeted Cardenas is now under attack. After the killing, TV Azteca
owner Ricardo Salinas Pliego -- Stanley's employer -- took over the
airwaves to personally put Cardenas under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we pay taxes? Why do we have elections? Why have
government if there is no authority?'' Salinas Pliego said.
</P>
<P>
   Now TV Azteca faces charges of hypocrisy since it is sponsoring
a public service campaign ``Live without Drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In a message to the press, the network said, ``if it's proved
that Stanley consumed these type of products, it only serves to
strengthen the need for the efforts of programs like Live without
Drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
