<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-GOV11-COX     06-10 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-GOV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miss. governor to divorce, then marry junior high sweetheart
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mississippi Gov. Kirk Fordice has become so brazen in
his extramarital activities, he makes President Clinton seem
subtle.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in his two terms as governor, Fordice on
Thursday announced he will divorce Pat, his wife of 44 years. But
he won't be single long: He also announced he will marry his junior
high school sweetheart, Memphis, Tenn., widow Ann G. Creson, whom
it is widely rumored he has been dating for many years.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, released by his attorney, James Becker, comes
after reports by WLBT-TV in Jackson, Miss., that Fordice vacationed
in Paris with Creson last week. In one report, which has been
replayed as often as O.J. Simpson driving his white Bronco on a Los
Angeles freeway, Fordice walks toward the reporter, wagging his
finger and saying, ``You invade my privacy this way, six months
from now, I'll whip your ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Fordice finishes his second term in six months. State law
prevents a third term. He plans to work for former Vice President
Dan Quayle's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sid Salter, a statewide columnist and publisher of the Scott
County Times, was the first person to report on the Fordices'
marital problems six years ago. He said Thursday that Fordice's
indiscretions are now so blatant, he's lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the point when the governor announces a divorce and stops
lying, it retreats into a private matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice has gained enemies on both sides of the aisle in the
Legislature by issuing a flurry of vetoes each session. The list of
opponents is growing longer as his personal behavior becomes more
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even hard-core Republican backers are falling off him in
droves,'' Salter said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Ken Stribling, a Republican and longtime Fordice
critic, said this was ``the last straw'' for his colleagues who
still supported the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he remembering that anything he does reflects on the
Republican Party and on the state of Mississippi?'' he said. ``This
is a class issue: If there is something wrong in your marriage, you
should handle it with class.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fordice's bad relationship with the Legislature has
been a newsmaker, it seems now that his legacy will be his cheating
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Friedeman, a newspaper columnist, radio talk-show host and
theologian, used to be a Fordice supporter. This week, he has been
calling for the governor's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very disappointed,'' he said. ``I want to say,
`Governor Fordice, you ran on a God and country ticket, you talked
about faith and families, and it's obvious you're not walking the
walk. It's time to leave.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stribling says he does not think Fordice should resign but he
does think he should stop being seen in public with Creson until
his divorce is final.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since he was elected the state's first
Republican governor since Reconstruction, Fordice on several
occasions has made public _ on purpose or inadvertently _ his
marital troubles. In 1993, he announced he and his wife had
``irreconcilable marital differences'' and hinted at divorce. His
wife immediately issued her own statement that said she had no
intention of getting a divorce. They reconciled publicly a week
later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, on Election Day, Fordice was driving alone on
Interstate 55 from Memphis to Jackson, Miss., when his Jeep
Cherokee veered off the road, flipped and caught fire. The crash
was called a mystery by the state troopers; meanwhile, rumors began
to fly that he was having lunch in Memphis with a middle-aged
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice claimed to have no memory of the entire day. Later, he
went on record calling President Clinton a liar for not being
truthful about his affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
He called for Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fordice bought a house in suburban Jackson that his
wife knew nothing about. ``I know it is not for me,'' Pat Fordice
recently told a Jackson television station.
</P>
<P>
   Becker said the Fordices are working out a property settlement
``in connection with an irreconcilable differences divorce.'' Both
Fordices still live in the governor's mansion, according to the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a show of respect for the first lady, he needs to go ahead
and move out now from the governor's mansion,'' Stribling said.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice may be feeling the heat of the criticism being heaped on
him. Perhaps that's why he was pictured on the front page of
Thursday's Jackson Clarion-Ledger with three trusted friends: His
beloved labrador retriever, a bodyguard, and a pistol strapped to
his waist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
