<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-REPORT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS' HEALTH IMPROVING OVERALL 
</HEADLINE>
 CARD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year since 1979, the federal government has issued a
report card on how healthy Americans are. This year, the nation got
its best report card in the last two decades: Americans are eating
more fruits and vegetables, have healthier hearts, and are dying
less frequently from breast and colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   However, US Surgeon General David Satcher said that child
obesity is at an epidemic level, and the huge disparities between
the health of whites and minorities is stalling progress toward the
nation's goals.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Medical School's commencement Thursday, Satcher
released a progress review on the government's Healthy People 2000
goals, a blueprint of more than 300 health objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The Healthy People initiative, first launched in 1979 under
former surgeon general Julius Richmond, has been reformulated each
decade to provide a yearly review of Americans' health progress.
</P>
<P>
   Six months shy of the year 2000 goal, many of the target areas
are on track or have been reached, including those for nutrition,
maternal and child health, heart disease, and mental health.
</P>
<P>
   Goals have been met for 15 percent of the objectives: Infant
mortality has dropped throughout the 1990s and the death rate for
children ages 1 to 4 has declined by 26 percent, surpassing the
government's objective. For adolescents and young adults, ages 15
to 24, death rates have declined enough to meet the government's
2000 goal of 85 deaths per 100,000. Since the inception of the
initiative 20 years ago, the mortality rate for this age group has
dropped 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol-related motor vehicle crash deaths and suicides are
down. However, heavy drinking among high school seniors has
increased recently and there has been little reduction among
college drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer death rates for adults ages 25 to 64 are below the year
2000 target, due in part to the drop in breast and colorectal
cancers and a slowing of lung cancer fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Among older adults, life expectancy rates are up, reflecting a
continuing decline in heart disease and stroke-related fatalities.
But as Americans live longer, more people over age 70 have trouble
performing critical functions, such as dressing, bathing or even
getting out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   In several key areas, Americans are drifting further from the
government's healthy target _ most notably when it comes to weight
and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of work to do,'' Satcher said. ``For 20
percent of the objectives, we are moving in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases of and complications from diabetes are on the rise. Rates
for deaths resulting from falls and motor vehicle crashes have
increased during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the rise in obese children is that many states
have cut physical education in the schools, Satcher said. ``We are
paying a tremendous price.''
</P>
<P>
   Children are also watching more TV, playing video games, and
working on computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be OK, if they still went outside to play,''
Satcher said. In addition, children emulate their parents and other
adults, who are leading sedentary lives and spending less time
organizing activities for children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Violence and unsafe neighborhoods are also a cause of less
activity among children and adults because they do not feel safe
going outside, Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   During his commencement speech, Satcher hinted at some of the
nation's goals for 2010, which he said he would release in January
2000. He said one goal will be to eliminate racial and ethnic
disparities in health by 2010, especially in six areas where there
have been documented differences: infant mortality, child and adult
immunization, coronary heart disease, diabetes and cancer
screening, and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Satcher said two strategies to close the gap are a
balanced-community health system, including uniform access, and a
balanced research agenda, one that reflects racial and ethnic
health disparities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
