<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS ACKNOWLEDGE THE TRANSFORMATION OF THE KNICKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Reggie Miller was at the podium and talking
somberly after the Pacers had crumbled to lose Game 5 to the Knicks
when some startling words slipped out of his mouth: when the Knicks
get out and running, Miller said, it is hard to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   With this admission, it appeared, the transformation of the
Knicks was complete. This Eastern Conference final matchup has been
turned on its head in Game 5, with the new-look greyhound Knicks
making the Pacers, thought by most to be the heirs apparent to
Chicago in the East, seem old and ragged, as if the time for their
ascension had come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like as the game went along, the more fatigued we
looked,'' Coach Larry Bird said. ``We didn't get much accomplished.
We battled and played hard, but we didn't make a lot of plays. They
made all the plays down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, that was the role of the plodding, physical Knicks,
who were eaten up not only by Miller but, more critically, by the
athletic Dale and Antonio Davis, the Indiana forwards.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, when the Knicks spread the floor to take
advantage of their superior athleticism, the Pacers could not keep
up and were taken out of their own game. When Marcus Camby, who was
occasionally guarded by Chris Mullin of all people, soared to the
basket, no Pacer went with him. Bird had talked of the need to put
a body on Camby. The Davises had little luck and Mullin's was the
wrong body entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The efficiency of the Knicks was staggering and, for the Pacers,
stultifying. They seemed mentally and physically out of the game
for much of the second half, outrun by the Knicks, but also, more
surprisingly for a veteran team that has had its lineup intact
since Bird arrived, outthought.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led on fast-break points, 18-2. They scored on 10 of
their last 11 possessions. But more shocking was that the desperate
and wheezing Pacers abandoned the type of fundamental, old-school,
half-court basketball that has taken them to four of the last eight
Eastern Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   During a span of nearly 27 minutes from midway through the
second quarter to when there were just four minutes left in the
game, the Pacers had one assist. That's one assist from a team with
Mark Jackson at point guard. The result: after the spectacular
first quarter, when the Pacers opened a 14-point lead on 10-of-18
shooting, they shot 23 of 61 (.377) the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   No one, save Miller, ever seemed to have any energy.
</P>
<P>
   Bird said he thought this team _ celebrated last season for
pushing the Chicago Bulls to the brink of elimination _ perhaps did
not have the heart of a champion after all. When the Pacers went up
by 14 to start the second quarter, they seemed to become
complacent, unable to find the killer instinct to put the Knicks
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't press them when we had them down,'' Dale Davis said.
``We had breakdowns in offense and defense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION11     06-10 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS ruling leads Christian Coalition to restructure
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Christian Coalition announced a major
reorganization Thursday following reports that the Internal Revenue
Service has ruled that the group is too partisan to be exempt from
federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition spokesman Mike Russell would not comment on the IRS
ruling, first reported by the St. Petersburg Times. The newspaper
said the IRS issued its denial last year, but kept its decision
quiet pending an appeal. The coalition received word recently that
it would lose the appeal, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the coalition was pulling its application to be
granted tax status given to nonpartisan groups, a category reserved
for educating voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years of fruitless negotiations with the IRS, the
Christian Coalition board of directors has decided to withdraw its
application for tax-exempt status, and create two new separate
organizations,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition of Virginia will be renamed Christian
Coalition International, and it will operate as a for-profit
corporation. As such, it may endorse candidates, form a political
action committee and contribute to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition of Texas, an existing tax-exempt
organization, will change its name to Christian Coalition of
America and focus on nonprofit ``voter education,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come as the Christian Coalition is struggling to
regain the influence and fund-raising power it enjoyed in the late
1980s and early 1990s. Founder Pat Robertson predicted the group
would ``continue to be a force in American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But the group has keen competition from the Family Research
Council and other religious-based organizations that appeal to the
same social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's critics welcomed the outcome of the
announcement, whether the result of an IRS ruling or a voluntary
decision to change course.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a decade we have urged the IRS to recognize the Christian
Coalition's clear partisan nature,'' said Carole Shields, president
of the liberal People for the American Way. ``We welcome this clear
signal that everyone has to play by the rules, even Pat
Robertson.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's opponents and many Democratic candidates have
fiercely criticized voter guides that the coalition has distributed
to churches before elections.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates have complained that the guides distorted their
positions and were thinly disguised promotional materials for
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
