<SLUG> BC-YUGO-BELGRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SUGGESTS YUGOSLAVIA WON THE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ His army is retreating from Kosovo. Thousands of his
citizens are dead. He has been indicted as a war criminal. And his
country has been bombed so much that it could take 30 years and
perhaps $100 billion to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic spoke of
a successful ``defense of the fatherland in the struggle for
freedom and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on state television for the first time since he dared
NATO to bomb him 78 days ago, Milosevic suggested his nation had
won the war because Yugoslavia retains sovereignty over Kosovo. He
did not tell his audience that the Western allies had never wanted
independence for Kosovo, or that the future of Kosovo is largely
out of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   His government said at least 2,000 civilians died, and he
asserted that 462 soldiers and 114 police officers were killed.
But, after losing his fourth war in 10 years, he said the nation
had never been more united.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are the heroes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's rare televised address and the reaction of ordinary
people show the huge gap between government rhetoric and reality in
a society where the news media is state-controlled. If it is, as
Politika, the newspaper that backs Milosevic, declared, a ``great
victory,'' many people here had trouble pointing to the evidence of
it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, after the official media announced an end to
the war, there were celebrations on the streets of the Yugoslav
capital. Soldiers and police fired their guns. Young couples kissed
in Republic Square. Motorists honked their horns.
</P>
<P>
   But for a city of 2 million, it was not much. The Yugoslav Army
is known here as the VJ, but this was no VJ day. Thursday, people
went about their business, not savoring the moment as much as
contemplating the future. Many were subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a victory. It is a capitulation,'' said Bozo
Koprivica, 46, a writer. ``It is a capitulation not of the army,
but of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Koprivica said this was a ``virtual war.'' News censorship kept
ordinary people from seeing how many people really died. While
deaths of civilians were emphasized for propaganda purposes, deaths
of soldiers and police were suppressed. Only their families and
friends will know, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Koprivica nor his friend, Bozidar Djurovic, 43, a stage
director, felt much like celebrating Wednesday night. If anything,
they felt less celebratory Thursday afternoon, as news spread that
NATO had officially suspended its air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the feeling we're smiling with one eye and crying
with the other,'' said Djurovic. ``We're happy because people are
not going to be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he celebrated, Djurovic managed a tired smile and said,
``No, I slept for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Sleep sometimes brings nightmares, and that, according to young
people, especially, is what awaits Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   At 18 years of age, fresh from high school, Dusan and Milja are
Serbia's future. Both are going on to university, he to study
biochemistry, Milja to study physics. But both say that most of
their friends want to leave Serbia as soon as they can. This war
convinced many of them there is no future here. They spoke on the
condition that their last names were not used.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to celebrate,'' said Dusan, standing in a
pedestrian mall. ``There are so many people dead. They say 2,000
civilians died, but it's many more. Some say 10,000 soldiers, I say
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Milja said even those who believe the country won by standing up
to the world's most powerful military alliance will begin to
question that assessment in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is destroyed,'' she said. ``It will be a very long
winter. People are not going to have heat. The water and
electricity systems are destroyed. The entire region is unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are people here who believe Milosevic when he says
that the country won the war. Ruzica Minic, 40, a housewife who was
buying vegetables at a downtown market said, ``Of course this is a
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We succeeded in defending our land, and Kosovo remains inside
Yugoslavia,'' she said. While many grumble that the government that
got them into conflict with Europe and the United States should go,
Minic is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has defended the country, so why should we
change it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dragana Stamenkovic, 33, who was selling cheese and salami at
the market, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory because we got to keep Kosovo. Nobody can
take Kosovo from us,'' she said. ``Our country is destroyed, but we
will try to rebuild as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say whether the widespread skepticism and
cynicism here will grow into a demand for political change. The
Americans and Europeans have been adamant that they will not pay to
rebuild Serbia unless Milosevic is removed and the country becomes
truly democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This war will not produce a healthy movement of the people,''
said Koprivica. ``If this government stays, we'll go backwards.
There will be no progress or prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Milja, the newly graduated high school student, said she found
it hard to concentrate on politics. She said she had friends killed
in the war, both civilians and soldiers. Her friend Sanja
Milenkovic, 16, was killed when NATO bombed a bridge south of
Belgrade two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanja was in a special school,'' she said. ``A lot of the
students go on to MIT, Harvard, Yale. Sanja wanted to be a
scientist. But now she is dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
