<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TEAM EFFORT INCLUDES THE COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Around the witching hour Friday night, it just might
be appropriate for Dave Checketts to burst into a press conference
and blurt, ``Jeff Van Gundy, you're a gosh-dang good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happened before, where a sports executive had to eat crow
in public. I once witnessed the legendary Branch Rickey making nice
to Johnny Keane, the baseball manager he had schemed to dismiss. In
sports, all things come around.
</P>
<P>
   If momentum and energy and sudden surging youth have anything to
do with it _ the roar of underground trains, the honking of taxis,
the bellowing of rich and petulant fans _ then Friday night could
be the time for Checketts to say something nice about Van Gundy.
Long overdue, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   These improbable Marcus-come-lately Knicks could very well oust
the Pacers from their preordained place in the National Basketball
Association finals. The Knicks are on a roll _ from essentially
nowhere, Lower Dysfunction _with an oddness not seen in these parts
in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: New York winners in recent years were
supposed to be good. The Stanley Cup Rangers, Devils and Islanders.
The World Series Yanks. The Holzman Knicks. The Mookie Mets. Even
the Seaver Mets, you could see that team coming on, months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But if these 12 characters in search of an identity should get
past Indiana on Friday night, they would be New York's most
surprising finalists since the Jets won Super Bowl III in 1969.
Before that, you go back to 1951 when a baseball team called the
New York Giants won a playoff with a man named Bobby Thomson. . . .
Ah, ask your grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   These Knicks could get buried Friday night and Sunday. Or they
could get clobbered by the tall and fresh San Antonio Spurs in the
finals, the way those ancient Giants were outclassed by the Yankees
in 1951. Doesn't matter. The Giants are still remembered for their
Miracle of Coogan's Bluff and Leo Durocher is still the Dandy
Little Manager. Forever.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these Knicks, under Jeff Van Gundy, have shown us a
surprisingly good time this past month. Allan Houston's
follow-the-bouncing-ball shot to beat Miami. Knicks fans filling up
the arena in Atlanta. Three shocking victories over Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   All of New York has been analyzing these characters since their
erratic wobble toward a 21-21 record late in the season, when
Checketts sacked Ernie Grunfeld, who assembled this lot.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they appeared to be certified numbskulls, egotists,
individualists, and they still are, some of them. But they have
stunned a cohesive, logical, talented team, with Patrick Ewing in a
suit, with Latrell Sprewell and Houston still making it up as they
go along, without a point guard who can equal Indiana's Mark
Jackson out of Queens and Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't have anything to do with the coach, could it? Van
Gundy, the son of a coaching lifer, came into this job with his own
tactics. He withheld time from Marcus Camby, who was playing soft.
He started Kurt Thomas because somebody had to give up some early
fouls. He turned Sprewell into an unwilling sixth man because he
envisioned the chaos Sprewell could cause in the opponent's second
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to revise his thinking because of Ewing's absence, Van
Gundy started Sprewell in the fourth game. I did not agree with
that, because it left the Knicks without their normal jolt of
adrenaline midway through the first and third quarters. But now Van
Gundy is 1-1 by listening to his own head. Sounds like gosh-dang
coaching, to me.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Checketts has been smoked out interviewing a
replacement for Van Gundy. It reminds me of 1964, when
beetle-browed Branch Rickey, the eminence grise of the Cardinals,
politicked all summer to replace Keane, the kind and grizzled lifer
from the St. Louis system, with the vain and notorious Durocher.
</P>
<P>
   To everybody's surprise, the Phillies collapsed and the
Cardinals roared into first place in the final week. One night
after a game, while Keane was talking with reporters, Rickey
materialized from a back door, like Banquo's Ghost, startling the
small assemblage with a hearty, ``Johnny Keane, you're a gosh-dang
good manager!'' (A religious man, Rickey did indeed say
``gosh-dang.'' I was there.)
</P>
<P>
   After the Cardinals won the World Series, Keane left for the
Yankees. I am not saying Van Gundy will do anything that impetuous.
I do hope Checketts does not have anything in writing with Phil
Jackson. Regardless of what comes down, Van Gundy's Knicks have
entertained New York _ and have made money for whoever owns the
Garden at this moment. It's time for Checketts to polish up his
``gosh-dang good coach'' speech. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
