<HEADLINE>
ANTI-VIRUS EXPERTS SCAMBLE TO COMBAT MALICIOUS COMPUTER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Pa.)  (Eds: Skedded on NYTNS front page as COMPUTER-VIRUS) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Computer researchers Thursday reported a
malicious computer program that is spreading rapidly through the
Internet, attacking Microsoft's e-mail programs and destroying
documents created by popular Microsoft software programs, including
Word, Powerpoint, Excel and other applications.
</P>
<P>
   A number of large corporations, including Boeing, A.T.&AMP;T. and
General Electric, said they had computers infected by the program
and moved to limit the damage, in some cases by shutting down their
e-mail systems. Employees of Microsoft, Intel and the anti-virus
software maker Symantec said they had also been hit.
</P>
<P>
   The program, a form of computer attack known as a worm, shows up
an an e-mail attachment. It held the potential to be far more
dangerous than the Melissa computer virus, which spread rapidly in
March as a sort of e-mail chain letter but was not designed to
destroy files.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is known as a worm rather than a virus because
it able to transmit itself through the Internet under its own
power. In contrast viruses spread by hitchhiking by attaching to
documents, programs or disks.
</P>
<P>
   The program, began spreading Wednesday in Europe and the United
States. Several anti-virus software companies said they believed
that the program had originated in Israel, because the first sample
had been discovered in that country.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T's headquarters in Basking Ridge, N.J., the company
intercom broadcast an alert at lunch time warning employees that
the program was spreading and a spokesman said he believed that
several hundred computers had been infected within the building.
</P>
<P>
   At the Intel Corp., the program was first discovered during the
day at the company's development facility in Israel and computer
administrators severed networks linking the company to Europe and
the United States to halt the spread of the program, according to
an internal company memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone and past, it's a great tornado that zoomed through
and left,'' said Pam Wickham, a spokeswoman at General Electric.
She said the company had been warned on Wednesday and that
anti-virus software had been quickly distributed, minimizing the
impact.
</P>
<P>
   The worm e-mail is particularly dangerous, anti-virus experts
said, because it contains the message: ``I received your e-mail and
I shall send you a reply ASAP. Till then, take a look at the
attached zipped docs. Bye.''
</P>
<P>
   One employee at an e-commerce firm said two of her colleagues
encountered the virus Thursday morning, with one employee losing
all files on his hard drive. The attachment apparently came from an
employee of Microsoft, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The worm is transmitted by Microsoft e-mail programs and uses
those programs' features to spread itself to other computer users
who have sent e-mail messages from the infected machine.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said they were aware of the attack and were
gathering information on it. During a day a number of anti-virus
companies updated their programs and posted scanning utilities to
their web sites to fend off the attack.
</P>
<P>
   However, anti-virus experts said that the program was difficult
to detect and that the best defense was for computer users to
resist opening electronic mail attachments from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The program which comes in an innocuous file identified as
zip_files.exe is an example of a kind of attack known as a Trojan
Horse because it fools computer users into executing a malicious
program by opening the attached mail document.
</P>
<P>
   The program then creates another file named explore.exe that is
launched every time the infected computer is restarted.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of ``social engineering'' relies on the gullability of
computer users who are lulled into believing that the program has
actually been sent as a reply from the person who they recently
sent an electronic mail message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Explore worm is even worse because you get it from someone
you know,'' said David Chess, a research staff member at the Watson
Research Laboratory in Hawthorne, N.Y. ``People are going to be
lulled into to thinking it is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the worm establishes itself on a computer, it
systematically searches for documents created by the three programs
that are part of the Microsoft Office Suite, Word, Excel and
Powerpoint as well as some programmers' files and erases them.
</P>
<P>
   Word is the world's most widely used word processing software
and Excel is the most widely used spreadsheet program. PowerPoint
is software for creating graphical business presentations on a
computer screen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, experts at anti-virus firms said the new program
represented a disturbing trend in the virus underground which
appears to be developing more lethal programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few weeks we've begun to see attempts by virus
writers to combine the rapidly spread capability of the Melissa
program with a more destructive payload,'' said Wes Wasson,
director of security product marketing at Network Associates, a
Silicon Valley software developer. He said he expected to see a
number of copycat programs in the future as virus writers attempt
to mimick the Explore program.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates has recently established ``risk assessment''
guidelines for gauging the danger of new malicious programs and
</P>
<P>
   Wasson said the company had assigned the Explore worm a ``high''
rating, its most threatening category because of its destructive
ability.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is known as a worm rather than a virus because
it able to transmit itself through the Internet under its own
power.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``worm'' was coined by science fiction author John
Brunner in his novel Shockwave Rider. In the novel, worms were
programs created by a rebel group that helped destroy an oppressive
computer network.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new Explore worm does not have the ability to
spread as quickly as the Melissa virus, it still has the capability
to quickly proliferate because an infected machine attempts to
infect any other computer that it receives mail from, computer
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worm has the ability to create a ping pong effect,'' said
Wasson.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie
Mellon University in Pittsburgh said Thursday that they were still
assessing the situation and had not decided whether they would
release an alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to understand the scope of the problem a
little better,'' said Shawn Hernan, a CERT security expert. He said
that by late in the afternoon on Thursday the security organization
had received only ten reports of worm infections, however, he said
that the program had spread rapidly at the afflicted organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a number of virus experts said they were puzzled by the
recent destructive bent within the virus writing community. Many of
the programs in the past have been written as a form of cybernetic
graffiti and are annoying but do not do physical damage.
</P>
<P>
   However, a program such as the Explore worm has the power to
destroy years of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what these people who write these programs are
thinking,'' said Chess, the IBM researcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
