<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS REALIZE A QUICK RETURN IS UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Ylkie Drvishaj has waited six years to see her
husband, a Kosovar Albanian who fled to Germany to avoid getting
drafted into the Yugoslav Army. She has waited two months in a
refugee camp here for a peace agreement. She was waiting hours in
the hot sun Thursday to call her husband at a free telephone bank.
</P>
<P>
   And now, she is ready to wait even longer before she ventures
back into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go to Kosovo, and to go as fast as we can,'' said
the 30-year-old Drvishaj, clutching a 6-year-old son who can't
remember his father, who left when the boy was an infant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I won't believe it's happening until I see my brothers''
in the Kosovo Liberation Army, ``to see if it's real,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Trust is in short supply in the Balkans, and the lack of faith
is especially pronounced among ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   No one trusts Milosevic. Most trust NATO and the office of the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, which is desperately trying to
persuade the masses not to rush to the border all at once.
</P>
<P>
   There are two who appear to enjoy the absolute trust of the
Albanians: President Clinton and the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Clinton guarantees it, and he says I can go back, we will
go,'' said Esmer Rashiti, 40. ``But only if Clinton says to go.''
</P>
<P>
   For hours after the signing of the peace deal was announced on
Wednesday, there was celebratory shooting and cheering on the
streets of Kukes, a refugee collection point, and in the town of
Kruma, a virtual KLA base on the Albanian-Kosovar border.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after, the reverberations of bombs and unfriendly fire
began. In the northern town of Bajrum Curri, loud thumps and slight
tremors from bombing could be heard for hours late Wednesday night.
It was unclear whether the sounds were from a NATO attack on the
Kosovo side, or a Serb attack on the Albanian side.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, four villages near Kruma were shelled by the
Serbs, said an official with the Organization on Security and
Cooperation in Europe who was there.
</P>
<P>
   Bajrum Curri was shelled Thursday, said a KLA volunteer soldier
who had come from western Europe. He was caught in the attack as he
drove from the town to Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This war is not over,'' the soldier said. ``Don't believe
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bajrum Curri, a skeleton OSCE crew had been put on alert to
watch for last-minute attacks from either the Serbs or Albanians
seeking to use up their artillery before heading home or to settle
old scores in the last hours of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the Serbs do _ they do as much damage as they can
at the last moment,'' said Ales Biber, an OSCE staffer in Kruma.
</P>
<P>
   What is waiting for the refugees back home may be even worse.
The entire province must be cleared of an unknown number of mines _
a huge task. Homes may be booby-trapped, and water may have been
deliberately poisoned. The nightmarish picture has aid
organizations scrambling to persuade refugees to stay put _ at
least until the situation can be assessed and deemed safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to get as many people as possible back in as
quickly as possible,'' said Rupert Colville, spokesman for the UN
commissioner. But ``it would be pretty disastrous if they tried to
rush the border too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of 5,000 German soldiers headed north Thursday
night to Kukes; the troops may head into Kosovo as early as Sunday,
said Albania Force spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Helge Eriksen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow a vacuum,'' Eriksen said. ``As soon as they
(Serbs) leave, we have to enter.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugee aid groups _ having just succeeded in getting the bulk
of the refugees to move away from northern Albania to camps in the
south _ are now faced with trying to keep nearly half a million
Kosovars from heading back north too soon.
</P>
<P>
   There is no chance that everyone will be resettled by the end of
the year, meaning that camps here must be winterized to accommodate
those who must wait it out here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want people going back and living under a scrap of
plastic in a Balkan winter,'' Colville said.
</P>
</TEXT>
