<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, June 11. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286. 
 
BUSH (Phoenix) - Two weeks ago Congressman Matt Salmon made a
pilgrimage to Austin Texas, where he sipped tea with Texas Gov.
George Bush and asked the presidential candidate a simple question:
Would the front-runner make a stand in the state of Arizona? Bush,
in an attempt to put to rest rumors that he was ceding the state to
John McCain, said yes. By KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the ``A''
category. 
 
MORTGAGE (Phoenix) - Home buyers got bad news Wednesday when
mortgage rates hit their highest level in nearly two years. The
average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages climbed to
7.51 percent from 7.41 a week ago, and the highest since September
1997, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. By
CATHERINE REAGOR. Story will move in the ``F'' category. 
 
AUSTIN-MOVIE (Phoenix) PHOENIX - If you're wondering where all the
15-year-old boys are, they're chuckling their butts off at ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' This comic sequel to Mike Myers'
surprise 1997 winner hits all the high spots _ or low spots,
depending on your taste in tasteless humor _ of the original. Myers
and crew provide an endless string of sex jokes, potty jokes, then
back to the sex jokes again. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the
``E'' category. 
 
BESIEGED-MOVIE (Phoenix) - Director Bernardo Bertolucci makes two
kinds of movies: those, like ``The Last Emperor'' and ``Little
Buddha,'' which are readily accessible to American audiences, and
those, like ``The Sheltering Sky'' and ``The Conformist,'' where
you must find your way into the film.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bertolucci's new drama, ``Besieged,'' is one of the latter. If
you want to gain a sense of this film, you must meet it half way if
not three-quarters. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOVIES-ALTERNATIVES (Phoenix) - There is a lack of good
alternatives to R-rated movies for teens, and many of the
alternatives are flops at the box office. Why? These R-rated movies
are marketed to teens. The movie's success depends on this market.
And even if they stayed home from the movie and watched the WB
instead, they'd still see sex and violence. Even teen magazines are
chock full of ads for sex. We'll also mention that parents take
their kids to the r-rated movies, anyway. Call that the moral
decline of America. By JAIMEE ROSE. Story will move in the ``A''
and ``E'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - The 2000 Neon has been redesigned fore and
aft to eliminate some problems. Gone is the noise and roughness,
and, hopefully, the spotty repair record. But also gone is much of
the charm and character that made the Neon such a standout among
subcompacts. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category.
Embargoed for Saturday, June 12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FENGSHUI (Phoenix) - How to make your house a fengshui home. An
guide to the ancient art of Chinese placement for dummies. By
JAIMEE ROSE. Story moved in the ``L'' category. Embargoed for
Saturday, May 12.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
