<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-HAVANA-COX     06-10 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HAVANA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smith wrests much from steamy Cuban locale
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 13. DOM NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Very early in Martin Cruz Smith's new novel, his hero, Arkady
Renko, is about to commit suicide. Renko, the melancholy Russian
investigator of three previous Smith procedural thrillers starting
with ``Gorky Park,'' is despondent over the death of his beloved
wife, Irina. He's been summoned to Havana to identify the corpse of
an old friend and is just about to inject an air bubble into his
own vein when a Cuban bursts into his room, trying to murder him.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting without thinking, Renko kills the Cuban in
self-defense, then spends the rest of the book unraveling the links
between his dead Russian friend and his would-be Cuban killer. But
that moment _ a man stopping his own suicide to defend himself _ is
so very Russian it sounds like the punch line to one of the dark
jokes that are told in the crumbling former empire today.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you had to do was wait,'' the Russian tells the dying
assassin. Renko is both passive and aggressive, but not
passive-aggressive in the way we use that term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Havana Bay'' is really not so much about the state of a
Russian's soul as it is about the state of Cuba's soul, and really
not even so much about that as about the way the two play off each
other.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful idea _ seeing the beautiful, proud, desperate
city of Havana through the eyes of a Russian, seeing as how the
Cubans now hate the Russians more than anybody on earth. For years,
Cuba was essentially a Soviet colony, and the Soviets ruled with
contempt. After the collapse of the Soviet Union, Cuba was
abandoned and now makes much of its income off tourists who come
for the cigars, the rum and the blatant underage prostitution,
which the government grotesquely winks at.
</P>
<P>
   There is a plot, full of players and double-crosses and
McGuffins, giving Renko reason to move from Point A to Point B, but
it hardly matters, and when he gets to the end, it matters even
less.
</P>
<P>
   But the plot does give Renko the opportunity for several edgy
encounters, leading to an unusual symbiotic relationship, with
Ofelia Osorio, a Cuban detective who distrusts the Russian, as
opposed to outright loathing him like the rest of her countrymen.
The scenes of Ofelia at home, worrying about her two young
daughters, whether they have enough to eat and whether they'll
soon, of economic necessity, join the hot-pantsed girls who prowl
the boulevard along the sea wall for fat, rich European tourists,
have a fierce maternalism that is heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Details such as those of Ofelia's home life make ``Havana Bay''
worth attention: The way people, even in private conversations,
never refer to Castro by name but instead pull their thumb and
forefinger along their chin, indicating a beard _ a gesture of
paranoia, respect and superstition. The constant blaring of salsa
music from tinny radios, the fin-heavy Caddies from the '50s that
still roam the streets (so preferred over the flimsy Russian
Ladas), the intensity of the local folk religion Santeria, the way
in which the country's revolutionary zeal is crumbling faster than
its apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Elmore Leonard also ventured to Havana for his novel
``Cuba Libre,'' but it was the Havana of a century ago, at the time
of the Spanish-American War. Reading ``Havana Bay,'' one wishes
that a writer of Leonard's gifts had used the Havana of today as a
setting. Smith may not have done right by his narrative, but the
sheer observational powers he brings to bear, coupled with his
strangely endearing detective hero Renko, make ``Havana Bay'' a
trip worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer covers television for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   -- FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Havana Bay. By Martin Cruz Smith. Random House. $24.95. 329
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Give that man a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
