<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0834 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS13-COX     06-10 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comma et al. are markers on road of life
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, JUNE 13. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many of us, the Iowa Test of Basic Skills has become the bar
exam of life. You can be a good parent or a bad parent, a grouch
whose glass is forever half empty, a spineless pushover or a
watchful monitor of minutely calibrated behavioral limits. But what
really concentrates the mind is that array of numbers reporting how
one's child did in the early heats of the rat race.
</P>
<P>
   I opened the white envelope addressed to ``Parent of ...'' with
clammy hands, not knowing its contents but wondering, ``Well, what
was it this time?''
</P>
<P>
   The array of numbers, the bar graphs, the showy jargon lifted
from statistics _ what a relief, for once, to see it all. And amid
this impressive tangle of data one particularly amusing nugget of
information only a writer could appreciate. They're testing the
kiddies on their punctuation now, although even there they cannot
resist the urge to complicate what would seem clear enough. One of
the categories is called ``Terminal Punctuation,'' which I take to
mean periods, question marks and the like. Somehow that word
``terminal'' conjures up images even grimmer than the perils of
middle school.
</P>
<P>
   But it was something else that caught my eye. Once one gets past
intimations of mortality there is a subcategory called, simply,
``Comma.'' And there I read that my child, whose attention to
punctuation had always struck me as blissfully insouciant, is
something of a master. He not only knows how to use a comma, but he
knows how to use it better than just about everyone his age.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this came to me as a complete surprise _ a shock, in fact.
So much so that it raised grave doubts about a test I would like to
take at face value: I have seen those commas, and ``masterful'' is
not the first word that comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Ramifications of a little black dot
</P>
<P>
   Periodically there come in one's life Rubicons that must be
crossed. Punctuation is one of these, terminal or otherwise. Anyone
who begins a sentence and ends it with a little black dot knows the
uncertainty of getting from here to there. Punctuation marks do
more than help us along our way, like the four-way stops or the
cattle-crossing sign; they are triggers of emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   And for writers they are fetishes of a sort, things to be
fretted and worried about. Punctuation, a man named Paul Robinson
wrote once in The New Republic, ``is naturally attractive for all
with the character strictures of the sort Freud dubbed anal, and I
readily confess to belonging to that sect. We anal folk keep neat
houses, are always on time, and know all the do's and don'ts,
including those of punctuation.''
</P>
<P>
   Speak for yourself, Robinson. I'm never on time, my house not as
neat as it could be (too many newspapers, too many magazines, too
many books, too many kids, too little time), and there are don'ts
I've too often done and do's I don't do enough. But about
punctuation I'm punctilious.
</P>
<P>
   The late Lewis Thomas, an oncologist better known as an
essayist, wrote playfully once of the stops and pauses of prose and
of the indicators of tone _ the foolish exclamation mark (it should
be expelled from the language), the question mark, quotation marks
(usually misused or overused). My kid's no master of the comma,
much less the complex sentence. But Lewis Thomas was one of the
masters of English prose in our day. He was, among other things,
fond of the staid old mark you don't see much anymore, one that's
not a period and not a comma:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost always a greater pleasure to come across a
semicolon than a period. The period tells you that that is that; if
you didn't get all the meaning you wanted or expected, anyway you
got all the writer intended to parcel out and now you have to move
along. But with the semicolon there you get a pleasant feeling of
expectancy; there is more to come; read on; it will get clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   Parenthetical paean
</P>
<P>
   In the same essay Thomas happens to mention something
parenthetically, and then something else parenthetically within
that, and again and again until a sentence that began simply enough
ends with )))))))))))).
</P>
<P>
   And you never thought punctuation could be so much fun (put away
that exclamation mark). But gold-star exactitude and fluency are
not the same. You can learn to write mechanically and never make a
grammatical error, but you won't necessarily write well. The
pleasure of all those silly marks is that they shape what we say by
modulating how we say it. Russell Baker called punctuation a kind
of body language of our written word, helping readers hear us the
way we want to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly used, the comma can be lovely, and the dash diverting.
The question mark serves of necessity, while the semicolon,
appreciated only by its friends, gathers dust. And loveliest of
all, of course, is the one a reader might give up hope of ever
seeing, the one that says we are finished, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
