<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0835 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-DOCTORS-$A     06-10 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-DOCTORS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FAMILY DOCTOR HAS A BLURRED FACE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DIANE BARNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was, family doctors were there for you through thick and
thin. They immunized your children, prescribed antibiotics for your
strep throat and visited you in the hospital after your
appendectomy. It was not unusual for such relationships to last 20
years or more.
</P>
<P>
   But these days a ``health care provider'' often has the shelf
life of a sneeze droplet, because of managed care, health industry
mergers and the insurance business. My recent struggle to be
reimbursed $87.83 from a clinic led me to examine this surreal
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating the thousands of insurance plans _ each with its own
deductibles, ``co-payments'' and ``allowed amounts'' _ can tax
anyone's strength. Although health maintenance organizations
control the amount of care a consumer receives and insurers dictate
the financial parameters, doctors can pick and choose the health
care plans and insurers they accept.
</P>
<P>
   I know first-hand the absurdities of the doctor-insurer-patient
relationship. Several years ago, I began work as a registered
nurse. My job offered health insurance, but, as is often the case,
it didn't kick in for three months. Unfortunately, the only
significant medical problem I've ever had _ a neurological
condition involving an eye _ developed during that time.
</P>
<P>
   I went to an ophthalmologist, who referred me to a neurologist.
While I was willing to pay his $200 fee up front, he kindly waived
it and suggested a CT scan. ``How worried are you about these
symptoms?'' he asked. ``Not very,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking more of the $1,000 cost of the scan than of my eye, I
deferred the procedure, and the problem cleared up on its own. But
the irony of working in health care yet lacking insurance did not
escape me.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, I married, switched to part-time work and
obtained coverage through my husband's employer. My family doctor,
however, did not accept his insurer. A friend recommended another
doctor. But my search would continue after just one visit, when,
with only a glance at my records and no discussion with me, that
doctor decided that I should have estrogen therapy.
</P>
<P>
   I was just getting used to Doctor No. 3 when he left to teach
family-practice residents at a hospital. His replacement was a
young woman I liked. Unfortunately, she moved to another city after
a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor No. 5 had been my husband's physician for 10 years. A
clerk in her group practice told me that her clinic accepted our
insurance. That turned out to be incorrect; the group had recently
dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   My husband was not affected by that decision, because he had
just qualified for Medicare, but I had a hefty bill for an office
visit. The office manager suggested that I pay with a credit card
and then file a claim even though my doctor was a
``nonparticipating provider'' _ in the hope that the plan would
cover part of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   During my battle to straighten out the mess, I could feel my
blood pressure rise and my heart race every time I gathered my
paperwork and picked up the phone. And (italics)I'm(end italics)
healthy; I can't imagine arguing with insurers while recuperating
from surgery, say, or undergoing chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   So where does the $87.83 come in? In pursuing my claim, I
learned that even a ``nonparticipating provider'' could not bill me
more than 115 percent of the amount allowed by my insurer for a
given procedure. My bill from No. 5 had exceeded that ceiling by
$87.83, and I was determined to get it back. So I began another
round of copying documents and firing off letters to billing
supervisors. I would love to charge for my time and annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of calling, writing letters and being passed
from office manager to billing supervisor to refund supervisor, I
finally received a check. My efforts had stopped just short of
contacting the state insurance commission.
</P>
<P>
   My new doctor is No. 6 in as many years. Well, he is really No.
3, the one who left to teach. I realized that he was seeing
patients again when his name appeared on my insurer's list of
``providers.'' But such lists can soon become out of date, as
providers or groups of providers end their relationship with an
insurer.
</P>
<P>
   I called the clinic of Doctor No. 6 to make sure that he still
accepted my insurance. The clinic couldn't tell me, because it
contracts its billing to another company.
</P>
<P>
   That contractor has since confirmed in writing that my insurer
is on the list, so I feel safe _ for this week, anyway _ and ready
again to brave the shifting sands of managed care. Of course, my
doctor's group practice could decide to drop my insurer. Such
decisions are made at the corporate level, and doctors don't
necessarily like them any more than patients do.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems that doctors, too, are pawns in the insurance game.
They are losing not only their autonomy, but also, in the parlance
of managed care, their titles. I'm waiting for the day when a
receptionist announces: ``Primary care provider Smith is not in,
but P.C.P. Jones will see you as soon as his staff examines your
insurance coverage.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diane Barnet is the author of ``What You Need to Know About
Hospitals'' (Crossing Press, 1998). Submit your account of
struggling or succeeding as a worker, consumer, investor or
entrepreneur to My Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229
West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036, or by e-mail to
mymoney(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
