<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-BUSH-HNS &LR;      06-10 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ASSAIL BUSH'S LEADERSHIP ABILITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Texas Gov. George W. Bush embarks on his first
presidential campaign tour, Democratic leaders Thursday criticized
his leadership abilities and suggested he could be tarred by the
actions of congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the leadership issue there is much to be desired,'' said
Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
``He would not be a candidate if he did not have his father's
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer, who along with the DNC's national chairman Joe Andrews,
devoted a large part of a breakfast meeting with reporters to what
they believed were the GOP front-runner's vulnerabilities. Their
comments suggest that they not only believe Bush will be the likely
Republican nominee, but they need to try and quickly slow his
political momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Saturday begins a tour of the key primary states of Iowa
and New Hampshire, and he will attend a number of fund-raisers
elsewhere Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that he is not only leading a large field of
Republican candidates but is also ahead of the Democrat's top
candidate, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman David Beckwith dismissed the attacks, saying
``there is a whiff of desperation already in the air at the DNC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to peck away at him in every which way. They
think these little peashooter attacks are going to undermine him,''
Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said Bush had failed to show leadership on a number of key
issues. He criticized Bush for delaying for several days after the
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia began to comment on it. He also said the
governor was remiss for not supporting a hate-crime bill that was
killed in the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   And he particularly singled out Bush's position on gun control,
including his endorsement of a measure requiring instant background
checks at guns shows after a state legislative committee had killed
the bill. Lawmakers said that even though Bush said he backed the
measure he did not lobby for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans generally oppose hate-crime legislation and gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said Bush's positioning on that gun-control measure was
``like being at the Alamo, being out in the bushes waiting until
the fight is over and then coming out and saying, `Hey, I was
really there for you guys after all.'''
</P>
<P>
   Romer predicted that the gun-control measure would continue to
prove troublesome for Bush as the House considers a GOP-sponsored
gun-control measure, which Democrats charge is considerably weaker
than one passed by the Senate several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said that Bush could not distance himself from Republican
congressional leaders because he had received the support of a
majority of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also made it clear they will try to link Bush with
two conservative House firebrands from Texas, House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, R-Irving, and House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Bush's relationship with Armey and DeLay was
``very good.'' And he added that the Texas governor was ``proud of
the record of the Republican Congress since 1995 in eliminating the
deficit, reforming welfare and reducing the growth of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer and Jacobs insisted that the vice president's record in
government would stack up favorably to Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask candidates what they have been doing in the last 25
years,'' said Romer. ``Bush brings five years, plus baseball plus
oil drilling to the table. Gore brings 25 years of very intense
focus on public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governorship, which Bush first won in 1994, is Bush's
first elective office. Gore was first elected to Congress in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said Republicans have criticized Gore's advocacy of
environmental positions and ridiculed his book ``Earth in the
Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic chair countered, ``At least he has an idea.
He is intellectually curious. He is willing to step out and say we
got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith, however, said it was odd for the Democrats to be
questioning Bush's qualifications when they backed a presidential
candidate in 1992 who was governor of a state ``one tenth the size
of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
