<HEADLINE>
THE COST OF RECHARGING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Calif.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)After 15 years of working in sales and marketing for
a Fortune 100 company, I need to make a change. I will most likely
seek a position in a similar field, but first I need a break from
the pressure. I have all but decided to quit my job and take a
two-month respite. But if I do so, how much more difficult will it
be to find another job? And how can I improve my chances?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Even in a strong economy, getting a new job is easier when
you already have one. Proving that a resignation was entirely
voluntary can be tough; some old-school employers still view any
gap in your employment record as a warning flag, said Edward D.
Hendricks, a management consultant in Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dropping out of the rat race, consider moving into
the slow lane. Many companies grant sabbaticals. You might try
finding part-time consulting work, suggested Ruth J. Luban, a
career counselor in Laguna Beach, Calif. In some cases, she added,
you can even work as a consultant to the very company that you're
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   If consulting seems too daunting, think about going back to
school, Hendricks said. Pick a topic or two that captures your
interest and has practical applications in your field. Consider
courses in Web design, for example, or in information technology
advances. ``Look for something that a new prospective employer
would see as valuable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still too much pressure? You could try developing your own
informal (and low-key) learning regimen. Many of us have stacks of
new computer software or industry-related reading that we'd like to
go through, Ms. Luban said. Catching up on changes in your field _
and related fields _ can improve your prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drawbacks of an extended break, it can put you in a
much better frame of mind for job-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burnout so erodes your energy and self-concept that you're
only 50 percent available to go out and sell yourself,'' Ms. Luban
said. By recharging and rediscovering your passion for your work,
you can make a much better impression than if you go to interviews
when you're ``fried and tired,'' as she put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing with burnout is that it does not go away by
itself,'' she said. And it will only get worse if you jump directly
into another high-impact job.
</P>
<P>
   When you start looking for a new position, don't be defensive
about taking a break. ``De-emphasize the time out,'' Ms. Luban
said. ``Go in really pushing that you're the right person for the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   If _ or, more likely, when _ an interviewer raises the issue,
``lead with a positive, pro-active spin and explain the reasons why
your time off was so productive,'' she said. Especially in today's
tight labor market, many employers may be more interested in your
abilities and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the right skill set,'' she said, ``you're going to
land somewhere fairly soon.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y.
10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
