<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titanic wake was no bonus for `Ship of Gold'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sinking of the Titanic was the biggest sea disaster of the
20th century, but some six decades earlier, another sinking shocked
the nation. In 1857, the SS Central America was bound for New York
from Panama with 600 passengers and 21 tons of gold from California
when it sank in a hurricane off the South Carolina coast. The 149
survivors' personal accounts of the horror of the storm and the
bravery of Capt. William Herndon were more dramatic than any
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the kind of story that Seattle writer Gary Kinder
thought would make a compelling book. ``I have to feel the story
before I can write about it,'' says Kinder, 52, a Seattle lawyer
who changed careers after reading Tom Wolfe's comments on the ``new
journalism'' in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a good story soon turned into a great one.
While researching the shipwreck for a book in 1987, Kinder heard
about a Columbus, Ohio, group that had filed a claim for salvage
rights. Tommy Thompson and his crew planned to retrieve the riches
from nearly two miles beneath the ocean's surface using a specially
designed robot. Hesitant at first, Thompson finally agreed to let
Kinder accompany him on the greatest treasure hunt of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving in historic details with Thompson's recovery efforts,
Kinder wrote the spellbinding best seller ``Ship of Gold in the
Deep Blue Sea'' (Vintage, $14 paperback). The book sold more than
150,000 copies in hardback and Warner Bros. recently bought film
rights for seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   Originally scheduled for publication in 1995, the book was
delayed until 1997 because of Thompson's legal battles over rights
to the treasure. When it finally was published, ``Ship of Gold''
came out in the wake of the ``Titanic'' frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think `Titanic' helped my book, but I think it hurt
it,'' says Kinder, who was in Atlanta for a book tour this week.
``By that time, four or five books about Titanic were out. The two
stories had nothing in common. Director James Cameron had to
fabricate a love story, while we didn't. If we had come out before
`Titanic,' we could have gotten even more attention.''
</P>
<P>
   CLIMBING HIGHER: Armchair adventurers apparently can't get
enough of true outdoor sagas such as ``The Perfect Storm'' and
``Into Thin Air.'' Now, with the discovery last month of the body
of explorer George Mallory on the slopes of Mount Everest, more
books about mountaineering are in the pipeline. Some believe that
Mallory, who disappeared during a 1924 expedition with his partner
Andrew Irvine, may have reached the summit 29 years before Sir
Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay. Larry Johnson and Jochen
Hemmleb, who found Mallory's remains, will tell the story of their
expedition this fall in ``Ghosts of Everest: The Search for Mallory
and Irvine.'' Rights to a BBC and Nova documentary have already
been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, National Geographic Books plans an October
publication of ``The Last Climb: The Legendary Everest Expeditions
of George Mallory'' by David Breashears and Audrey Salkeld.
Breashears is the author of the recently published ``High Exposure:
An Enduring Passion for Everest and Unforgiving Places.''
</P>
<P>
   RICKY, RICKY, RICKY: Less than three months after Ricky Martin
sparked a fan frenzy at the Grammy Awards, the Latin singing
sensation has become the idol of screaming teenage girls. So it's
no surprise that publishers have rushed to press with four
biographies for young fans. In stores this week are ``Ricky Martin:
A Scrapbook in Words and Pictures'' (Dell, $7.95) and ``Ricky
Martin: An Unauthorized Biography'' (St. Martin's, $4.99) by Elina
Furman. Coming in July are ``Ricky Martin: Rockin' the House!''
(Pocket, $4.99) by Nancy Krulik and ``Ricky Martin: Livin' La Vida
Loca'' (HarperEntertainment, $5.99) by Letisha Marrero. Needless to
say, all the books are packed with photographs.
</P>
<P>
   OUT THE DOOR: Bring in a best-selling author and what thanks do
you get? In Dell president Carole Baron's case, it's a pink slip _
after 18 years of nurturing such authors as Thomas Harris, Elmore
Leonard, Nicholas Evans and Danielle Steel. Baron's ouster, a
result of ``restructuring'' at parent company Random House, comes
just as Harris' blockbuster ``Hannibal'' hits stores.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Email: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
