<HEADLINE>
WOMAN STABS HUSBAND, DIES IN FIRE WITH 2 CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND JOANNA MASSEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HARTFORD, Conn. _ Kelly Silk struggled against depression
in the pale yellow house with red shutters.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the 32-year-old mother of four, who
attempted suicide a year ago, battled the disease for years before
slashing her sleeping husband to death with a kitchen knife
Thursday morning. She then set a fire in the split-level ranch that
killed two of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Silk and her husband Charles, 39, were discovered dead by
firefighters who responded to the 1:15 a.m. blaze at the couple's
home on Passaro Drive, a cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   Two Silk children, ages 3 and 2, were barely breathing when
firefighters found them in their smoke-filled bedroom. They died
shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The family's baby, 6-month-old Joshua, was severely burned and
in serious condition Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kelly Silk's eldest child, 9-year-old Jessica, who
managed to run for help after she was stabbed by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were awakened by a voice crying for help,'' the Rev. Chad
Trigge, a neighbor and the Silk's pastor told WHDH-TV Channel 7,
describing how Jessica Silk came to his door. ``It was Jessica,
whose hair was ablaze, and as soon as I doused the flames, I
realized that she was quite bloody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica may have awakened to hear her parents fighting and then
walked into their bedroom, police said. She was stabbed several
times in the back and legs and seriously wounded, but she was able
to run from the family home and knock on Trigge's door.
</P>
<P>
   Church members gathered to mourn last night at the Truth Baptist
Church in South Windsor, where Trigge is pastor and where Kelly and
Charles Silk met. Several woman who knew Kelly Silk said that they
were aware their friend was depressed, but that she sought relief
by attending prayer meetings and celebrating her children's
milestones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew she was depressed,'' said Cathy Amadusun. ``But
nobody expected anything like this. Nothing at all like this.''
Church member Leon F. Madore said he never saw a hint of depression
in Kelly Silk, who was a single parent, raising Jessica alone, when
she met her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're loving parents,'' Madore said. ``The kids really loved
their folks. The church community is mortified and shocked by
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Madore said Jessica and her brother will not have to worry about
finding a loving home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will all be here for her. In our church, when one grieves,
we all grieve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   East Hartford Police Commander Mark Sirois said Kelly Silk had
attempted suicide a little over a year ago by combining the
antidepressant drug Prozac with other prescription drugs. Sirois
confirmed that she was hospitalized at the time, but said he could
not release any other details related to her health care or
hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Silk, 39, died from multiple stab wounds, police said.
His body was found in the home's master bedroom, and the severely
burned body of his wife was in the hallway. Jennifer, 3, and Jonah,
2, likely were overcome by smoke inhalation, said Assistant Fire
Chief Brian Rykowski.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua was in full cardiac arrest in his crib, in the same room
where his father was killed, when firefighters found him.
</P>
<P>
   Because there were so many ambulances already in use, a
firefighter held the infant in a police cruiser that rushed to the
nearest emergency room, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was listed in serious condition in the burn center at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, according to a hospital
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica was taken to the Connecticut Children's Medical Center,
where she was in serious condition following surgery for multiple
wounds, hospital spokesman Chris Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   East Hartford Police said Kelly Silk's attempted suicide in May
1998 was the only domestic dispute or call for service from the
Passaro Drive home while the Silks lived there.
</P>
<P>
   State and local police and fire investigators were working to
determine whether there was anything that sent Kelly Silk into a
rage. They said they could not be sure how the fire was set, only
that it was apparently started upstairs, in one of the bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smoke was billowing out of the windows when they arrived
on scene,'' Rykowsky said. ``They would find one person, drag them
out, and know they had to go in after the others. The neighbors
knew there were small, young children in there somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Kelly and Charles Silk and their two young
children were taken to the Connecticut state medical examiner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether she planned to die in the fire, or
wanted to escape and couldn't,'' Rykowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have three homicides and an arson. Do we have a
suicide? We can't be sure yet. It's an awful scenario no matter
what we find.''
</P>
</TEXT>
