<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0847 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-OUTFORGOOD-COX     06-10 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-OUTFORGOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Out for Good' ably traces gay rights drive
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, JUNE 13. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's true that ``history gets thicker as it approaches recent
times,'' as English historian A.J.P. Taylor once remarked, there
are few better illustrations than ``Out for Good: The Struggle to
Build a Gay Rights Movement in the United States.'' In the 30 years
since the patrons at New York's Stonewall Inn fought back against
police harassment _ a pivotal encounter known ever since simply as
``Stonewall'' _ the campaign for gay rights has inspired a steady
flow of histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out for Good,'' by Dudley Clendinen, former features editor at
The Atlanta Journal-Consti-
</P>
<P>
   tution and now an editorial writer for The New York Times, and
Adam Nagourney, a Times reporter, stakes its claim as the first
comprehensive history of the gay rights movement _ a sweeping
statement that sets a prodigious task. After careful consideration,
it seems a valid boast. Many before have chronicled the same
events, but with a microcosmic focus. In 1993's ``Stonewall,''
Martin Duberman invested the movement as a whole with a sense of
personal warmth by tracking the lives of several participants and
bystanders at that seminal moment in New York in the summer of '69.
Others have taken a regional tack: James T. Sears compiled early
Southeastern gay experiences in ``Lonely Hunters'' (1997); Will
Fellows did the same for the Midwest in ``Farm Boys'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   In ``Out for Good,'' the authors focus on a handful of cities,
but the places chosen represent a respectable range of sizes,
regions and temperaments: Atlanta, Los Angeles, New York, Chicago,
Minneapolis/St. Paul, Boston, Austin, New Orleans, Seattle, Miami,
Washington and San Francisco. The protagonists in these tales are
much less familiar than those recounted before in books; some in
fact have never been written about.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Franklin Kameny, the first openly gay candidate for
federal office, is an early indicator of the quality storytelling
to come: He has ``the confidence of an intellectual autocrat, the
manner of a snapping turtle, a voice like a foghorn, and the habit
of expressing himself in thunderous bursts of precise and formal
language. He talked in italics and exclamation points, and he
cultivated the self-righteous arrogance of a visionary who knew his
cause was just when no one else did.'' A Harvard-trained
astronomer, Kameny was dismissed from his government job after
being arrested in Washington's Lafayette Park in 1957. (Late one
evening in the park, he saw an arrest in progress and stopped to
watch, before being spotted by the police and placed under ``arrest
for investigation'' himself. The authors describe this as ``a
procedure used by the morals squad in those years to hold, question
and pressure someone they suspected of homosexuality.'') In 1971,
he ran for the newly created office of delegate to Congress from
the District of Columbia. Ultimately he lost, but ``the votes were
not the measure of the campaign,'' Clendinen and Nagourney write.
``It was the change made in public consciousness, and in the
political organization of the gay community in Washington and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might quibble with the authors' decision to begin their
story with the Stonewall riots, the importance of which many gay
activists and historians have debated in recent years. The fact
remains, though, that Stonewall was a powerful symbol and a
rallying point for the struggles of the early 1970s, and it lingers
in the yearly gay pride celebrations that commemorate that June
night each year in cities all over the world. The authors don't
ignore the work of the pre-Stonewall activists, but much of the
work of pioneers such as Harry Hay, founder of the Mattachine
Society, and Phyllis Lyon and Del Martin of the Daughters of
Bilitis, is well-documented elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   With the detailed clarity that comes with meticulous research
and a little distance, the authors recount the many highs and lows
of the gay rights movement, from Anita Bryant's successful late
'70s campaign against a gay rights ordinance in Florida to Bowers
v. Hardwick _ which pitted Georgia Attorney General Mike Bowers
against Michael Hardwick, an Atlanta bartender arrested under the
state's sodomy law _ to the devastating toll that AIDS wrought on
the early generations of activists.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the AIDS crisis was felt not just in the deaths of
some of the movement's leading lights, but in the response to
governmental and medical reactions to the disease. ``No other
movement has been so reshaped by a plague,'' Clendinen and
Nagourney write.
</P>
<P>
   The founding of the AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power (ACT-UP) was
a galvanizing moment in gay activism. On March 10, 1987, at the New
York City Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center, a group was
born that ``would be hip, stylish, informed and sexy activism,''
and that ``defied type.'' ACT-UP wasn't alone, though. Without
accounts such as ``Out for Good,'' many of the other important
players might be left to languish in the footnotes. Few people
would recognize the contributions of organizations such as the
Lavender Hill Mob and the unnamed collective organized by Avram
Finkelstein and others that was responsible for the now familiar
slogan ``Silence  &QC;  Death.'' As Clendinen and Nagourney write, ``The
Lavender Hill Mob would lend to ACT-UP much of its tactical
armament, but (Finkelstein's) collective would impart an artistic
and marketing sensibility, which would prove equally distinctive to
this new activism.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Randy Shilts' excellent history of the early years of the
AIDS crisis, ``And the Band Played On'' (1987), the mountainous
cast of characters in ``Out for Good'' can be overwhelming. But the
authors never allow the many disparate threads of the story to
become tangled into outright incomprehensibility. Dashes of humor
and a simple, straightforward style make the book a pleasure to
read, with none of the dry, academic prose that plagues so much
historical reportage. What Clendinen and Nagourney have created is
an invaluable document, impressively researched, remarkably
well-written and groundbreaking in its scope.
</P>
<P>
   -- NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   Out for Good: The Struggle to Build a Gay Rights Movement in the
United States. By Dudley Clendinen and Adam Nagourney. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $30. 716 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
