<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0848 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-$ADV13-NYT &LR;      06-10 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BLUE IS YOUR COLLAR?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DEBORAH STEAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her mid-30s and in mid-career, Solange de Santis, a business
reporter with an Ivy League education and a crisp white-collar
upbringing, became an auto worker.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. de Santis writes in her engaging account of that
year-and-a-half stint, ``Life on the Line: One Woman's Tale of
Work, Sweat and Survival'' (Doubleday, $24.95), it wasn't a hard
decision.
</P>
<P>
   She was bored with journalism to the point of mischief: To amuse
herself, she had begun to sneak hidden baseball references into her
bond-market articles. Besides, she wanted, for once, to write a
business article from the inside out and from the bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   She found that story in the early 1990s _ in Ontario, where she
had been freelancing after jobs at Reuters and The Toronto Globe
and Mail, and where General Motors was warning workers about an
impending shutdown of its Scarborough van plant.
</P>
<P>
   The project would also satisfy her longtime curiosity about
factory work. She said she found herself ``weirdly attracted to
blue-collar life,'' and, at 5 feet 4 inches tall, to the physical
challenge it posed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Santis's aim was to be at the plant to chronicle the 18
months or so leading up to that closing. She also wanted ``to step
over the line between white collar and blue collar,'' a line, she
reminds us, that is widening.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the narrative of the shutdown doesn't have much
drive. It meanders a bit, and there is little drama in the plant
closing. Ms. de Santis's co-workers, counseled by outplacement
professionals and wearily adept at calibrating the available buyout
deals, seniority privileges and union benefits, are more or less
prepared by the time the last van rolls off the line in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the author, who is known at the plant as ``Sally,'' take us
over the collar line with grace and authority. And with conviction:
She winds up marrying a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life on the Line'' doesn't pretend to be a woman's version of
``Rivet-head,'' the boozy, funny, testosterone-saturated
best-selling memoir by Ben Hamper, a GM worker in Michigan. Ms. de
Santis describes herself as a ``visitor,'' aiming to make a mosaic
from the bits of life she sees in her corner of the 2,700-employee
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Well, visitors can bring not just passion, but their own special
perspective, as Keith Thomas points out in ``The Oxford Book of
Work'' (Oxford University Press, $35), to be published in America
this fall. Thomas notes that analytic observers have always been
drawn to labor arenas, often successfully capturing the life around
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in many ways the advantage is with those who go
in and do it for a bit,'' he said in a recent interview about the
writers he has included in his collection. ``It's fresh and new to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He includes in this genre Polly Toynbee, a British journalist
who took a job in a cake factory (``A Working Life,'' 1971) and
David Linhart, a French academician and radical who signed on at a
Citroen plant (``The Assembly Line,'' translated in 1981).
</P>
<P>
   The writing of Ms. de Santis is indeed fresh as she is initiated
into the world of hard work. And she offers a terrific newcomer's
account of how shocking it can be to mind and body.
</P>
<P>
   Her first job, at $16 an hour, is to wrestle fiberglass
insulation into engine compartments, add a vent and tighten three
screws. In passages that are bone-achingly visceral, she describes
how, to keep pace with each moving van shell, she has to walk
backwards, fling herself against it, jam in the insulation and
tighten the screws through layers of fabric, plastic and metal. The
work is exhausting. It is impossible to keep up. The half-hour
lunch break is scant respite. Time crawls.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-workers are helpful enough, but they can't stop the
fatigue, the heat, the tiny glass insulation needles that cling to
her nose, the clang of robots, the Led Zeppelin blasting out of
boom boxes. After her first shift, she sits in her car and cries
with exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arms were sore, my chest bone was bruised,'' she writes.
``I had figured assembly-line work would be hard, but a small piece
of my yuppie mind had conceived it as sort of an extended session
at the health club.'' A co-worker tells her that men, too, cry on
their first day.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, and satisfyingly, Ms. de Santis gains the strength
to wield her power tools like a pro. The fatigue is always there,
and she occasionally finds herself gripped by irrational anger and
by a desire to quench her thirst _ and boredom _ in a time-honored
way: swigging beer in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The author also introduces us to her co-workers, but the list of
characters is a bit difficult to keep straight. The best drawn are
Lance, her immediate supervisor, and Maria, a 50-something woman
made frail by breast-cancer treatments who nonetheless reports for
a full shift most days. The author's husband-to-be, Cam, turns up
near the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life on the Line'' also portrays casual sexism at the factory,
which is 85 percent male (pinups and the occasional suggestive
leer, along with vulgarisms hardly shocking to a newsroom veteran
like Ms. de Santis). And it chronicles workers' cynicism toward
both GM and the Canadian auto workers' union as the plant's last
days tick away.
</P>
<P>
   But what sticks is the rhythm and the punishment of the line. At
book's end, when Ms. de Santis and her co-workers read an article
quoting a professor who says the Scarborough line crews are
``probably overpaid in relation to their job skills,'' you may be
as enraged as they are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
