s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PHYSICAL-THERAPIS     06-10 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PHYSICAL-THERAPISTS-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PHYSICAL THERAPISTS, A SUDDEN DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Mich., Ind., N.J., N.Y., Va.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
growth in physical therapists is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC QUINONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his first year in the physical therapy program at Thomas
Jefferson University in Philadelphia, Tony Woods saw advanced
students receiving multiple job offers _ sometimes months before
graduation. Woods, a former carpenter, was feeling good about
trying a career change.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he is close to earning his master's degree
but recruiters have not come calling. ``No responses on anything so
far,'' he said, ``and I've probably put a couple of dozen feelers
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods's plight exemplifies a rather sudden shift in physical
therapy. For years it was a booming field desperate for skilled
practitioners, but now it faces a slowdown caused by its own
growing pains, the growth of managed care and, especially, Medicare
cutbacks that took effect in January. Years of undersupply have
given away to rising unemployment, reduced work hours and salaries,
and a tighter job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortfall has literally evaporated,'' said William
Quillen, director of the physical therapy program at Indiana
University in Indianapolis. ``There's just not the hot, hot job
market there was two or three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the number of physical therapy programs at
colleges and universities nationwide soared 75 percent, to 208,
with graduates in fierce demand to treat an aging, fitness-obsessed
population. And thousands of foreign therapists arrived to fill
vacancies at hospitals, rehabilitation centers and nursing homes
and with home health-care agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Full-time therapists typically earn $55,000 a year, and some
make more than $100,000. But the ranks of full-timers are thinning
even as more graduates enter the field each year.
</P>
<P>
   Therapists assign some responsibility to managed-care companies'
cost controls, but they say the new Medicare spending caps are most
to blame. Under a provision of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act that
took effect this year, Medicare beneficiaries are now limited to
$1,500 a year for physical therapy, though the head of a federal
advisory panel recently recommended eliminating that cap.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have meant that many patients get less care than
they used to and that new graduates must look longer and harder for
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I actually got accepted to Jefferson, everybody was
telling me what a great field it was,'' said Woods, 46. But now he
is facing $50,000 in loans, which he must start paying off later
this year, and job prospects appear dim in the area around
Philadelphia, where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   As he works in his final two clinical rotations, Woods and his
wife, Cynthia, a management training consultant, have begun to
consider leaving the Northeast, a saturated market for physical
therapists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two children, so that's a big issue,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Jennifer Sonn, who graduated from Thomas Jefferson
in 1996, had three offers before she even finished school. She
chose Presbyterian Medical Center in Philadelphia, which offered
her a signing bonus 10 months before she graduated.
</P>
<P>
   She left the hospital last summer and now works for the Visiting
Nurses Association, a nonprofit home health-care agency in
Runnemede, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is doing well, experienced therapists are not exempt
from effects of the tightened job market. Mrs. Sonn said that of a
dozen of her friends from Thomas Jefferson, three have been laid
off and two have taken pay cuts of up to $5,000 in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Weinstein, a veteran therapist who practices in New York
City, said managed care restrictions have cut his revenues by 35
percent in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The American Physical Therapy Association, in Alexandria, Va.,
which represents about 49,000 of the nation's 116,000 or so
licensed therapists, confirmed last month that the Medicare cuts
have led to a sharp rise in unemployment and to cuts in therapists'
working hours.
</P>
<P>
   The group reported that 20 percent of 6,000 therapists surveyed
in April said their hours had been reduced, compared with 13
percent in October 1998. It also said that while unemployment among
therapists working in nursing homes and home health care remained
low, it had more than doubled, to 3 percent in April from 1.2
percent in October. There was virtually no unemployment in those
fields just three years ago, Alexis Waters, the group's
spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The association has not compiled industrywide unemployment
figures this year. But even before the new law, a 1997 study
commissioned by the group predicted a 20 percent to 30 percent
surplus of therapists as early as 2005, citing the rising numbers
of students and the managed-care companies' cost controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managed-care reimbursement has caused an impact on every
aspect of health care,'' said Sandra Howell, interim chairwoman of
the University of Southern California's physical therapy
department. ``Patients are being discharged from the hospital a lot
sooner, and there's less time for physical therapy, occupational
therapy and a number of ancillary health professions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Simmer, medical director of Health Alliance Plan, a
Detroit-based Health maintenance organization, said managed care
companies are emphasizing cutting drug and hospital costs. ``I do
not believe that national or locally, physical therapy is
undergoing that same type of energetic cost-reduction strategy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quillen of Indiana University said older patients already
receiving therapy might not be able to afford further care if, say,
they broke a bone.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, he said, people ``can very quickly exhaust their
Medicare benefits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
