A0856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT &LR;      06-10 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. VOTES ITSELF A MAJOR PEACEKEEPING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ After more than a day of frantic diplomatic
maneuvering, the U.N. Security Council approved Thursday a draft
resolution sending a large NATO-led force into Kosovo to keep the
peace and placing the United Nations in administrative charge of
the province.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the Council's 15 members voted in favor of the
resolution. China, which had pressed for changes in the text, only
two of which were adopted, abstained.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the resolution bestows U.N. legitimacy on the peace
plan and the NATO-led military operations in Kosovo. NATO's bombing
campaign, by contrast, never secured the world body's explicit
blessing, since resolutions authorizing it would have been blocked
by Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also gave a vast, challenging role to the United
Nations, which had been politically sidelined until now by American
insistence that NATO and Russia take the lead in efforts to end the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are seeing at least the beginning of the end of a
dark and desolate chapter in the history of the Balkans,'' said
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who nevertheless warned against
being ``triumphalist,'' warning of ``difficulties and dangers
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials, struggling with budget cutbacks and demands that
they do more with fewer resources, said they were pleased, but
daunted by the task ahead. For the resolution approved Thursday
turns Kosovo at least temporarily into a veritable U.N.
protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   Shashi Tharoor, Annan's director of communication, said that the
resolution ``reaffirmed the value of the United Nations and what it
stands for, and gives the United Nations its rightful
responsibilities.'' The war, he added, ``was a NATO war; the peace
will be a United Nations peace.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO members of the Council, bowing to China's sensibilities,
adopted a non-substantive change in the wording of the resolution's
preamble by referring to the ``principles and purposes'' of the
U.N. charter and the ``primary responsibility'' of the Security
Council in maintaining international peace and security.'' But the
Chinese representative, Shen Guofang, regretted that the Council
did not accept its other changes, adding that the resolution
``makes no mention of the disaster caused by NATO bombing'' of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 20 representatives who gave often impassioned
speeches in the Council defended NATO's campaign against Yugoslavia
and endorsed the peace plan. Peter Van Walsum, the Netherlands'
representative, said that the vote reflected a profound shift in
the balance between respect for human rights and for national
sovereignty. While the U.N. charter was ``more specific on respect
for sovereignty than respect for human rights,'' he said, the
balance had shifted. ``Today,'' he said, ``no sovereign state has
the right to terrorize its own citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, the British representative, asserted that
President Slobodan Milosevic had been ``defeated'' in his attempt
to destroy the lives and the homeland of the Kosovar people. ``We
have now stopped Milosevic's ethnic-cleansing machine in its
tracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's representative, Sergey Lavrov, one of the resolution's
13 co-sponsors, said that his country nevertheless ``sternly
condemned the NATO aggression'' against Yugoslavia. The bombing, he
said, had transformed a humanitarian crisis into a ``humanitarian
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   A far harsher note was sounded by Cuba, whose representative
heatedly attacked the United States and its NATO allies for the
bombing campaign, accusing the allies of conducting ``genocide''
against the ``innocent women and children'' of Serbia. This, in
turn, elicited equally sharp critiques of Cuba's human rights
record from the United States, the Netherlands and Croatia, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's representative, Vladislav Jovanovic, also expressed
disappointment that the resolution had authorized participation in
the U.N. mission by ``countries which have taken an active part in
the aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, China had sought to fix a firm 12-month limit on
the life of the peacekeeping force, soften criticism of Yugoslavia,
and limit the circumstances under which the NATO-led troops could
use military force to implement the resolution. It succeeded on
none of these points.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO-led force, which is to be some 50,000 strong, will
include civilian experts as well as soldiers. It will supervise the
refugees' return and the withdrawal of both Yugoslav forces and
paramilitary police. It will consult with Annan, but not be
directed by him.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual feature of the resolution, a senior U.N.
official said, is its unlimited authorization of the NATO-led
force. While the resolution authorizes the force for an ``initial
period of 12 months,'' it can continue to operate there ``unless
the Security Council decides otherwise.'' That means that the
Security Council, which has now ordered all parties to comply with
the resolution and its terms, would have to vote to dismantle it if
NATO chose to stay.
</P>
<P>
   What diplomats have called the ``post-conflict'' architecture
approved by the Council gives sweeping powers to both the NATO
forces and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, it charges the NATO force with ``deterring renewed
hostilities''; ``demilitarizing the Kosovo Liberation Army'';
establishing ``a secure environment in which displaced refugees and
displaced persons can return home in safety''; de-mining, and
``ensuring public safety and order.''
</P>
<P>
   Placing these powers under Chapter 7 of the world body's charter
means that the NATO-led soldiers can use force to ensure that the
Yugoslavs fulfill their commitments to the Council.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also authorizes Annan to establish an ``interim
administration'' for Kosovo, guaranteeing ``substantial autonomy''
within Yugoslavia and providing for free, democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats said that the far-reaching powers authorized by
the Council make Kosovo a virtual U.N. protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   While he declined to comment on that characterization, Tharoor,
the secretary-general's director of communications and a key
adviser, said that the resolution gives the United Nations its
``rightful responsibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
