<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs argue for class-action status in Coca-Cola suit
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Plaintiffs in the racial discrimination case against
Coca-Cola asked a federal judge in Atlanta on Thursday to block a
company effort to prevent class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had asked U.S. District Judge Richard Story to
postpone discovery, or information gathering, that would help
plaintiffs build their case for adding 1,500 other prospective
black plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys said Story should deny that request because the
gathering of statistics and other employment data on Coca-Cola is
critical to determining whether more plaintiffs should be included
in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts relating to Coca-Cola's employment practices and
treatment of African-American employees with respect to ...
compensation, promotions, job placement and performance evaluations
are necessary for reasoned consideration of the class-certification
issue,'' plaintiffs' attorneys said in their response.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, Story gave Coca-Cola until July 1 to turn over
to plaintiffs a detailed database on its work force. That order
appears to expedite the process of deciding whether the lawsuit can
get class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which denies that it discriminates against its
employees, has argued that plaintiffs have made ``general
references to discriminatory practices'' and that they have nothing
in common with the prospective plaintiffs, other than race.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of ``commonality'' makes the case inappropriate for
class action, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Even without class action, the four plaintiffs _ administrative
assistant Motisola Malikha Abdallah, security officer Gregory Allen
Clark, consumer information specialist Linda Ingram and former
director Kimberly Gray Orton _ can continue to pursue their claims.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rules against Coca-Cola, the plaintiffs still must
convince him later that the suit, filed April 22, merits
class-action status. That decision is not expected for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
