<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLES-DUCATI11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stylish Italian Ducati has motorcyle enthusiasts crooning
 &HT;    By David Tulis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Italian motorcycle maker Ducati may not have the name
recognition or macho image of the leader of the pack,
Harley-Davidson, but it does have European style, racing heritage
and engineering that is finding a market in America.
</P>
<P>
   American Demographics magazine noted in its June issue that
while sales of big boats have risen only slightly in the 1990s,
sales of motorcycles have climbed 150 percent as baby boomers try
to squeeze more fun into less time.
</P>
<P>
   From the Little Puppy, a scooter born during World War II, to
the powerful Monster motorcycle created a half-century later,
Ducati has been a boutique brand. Now, its cycles are finding their
way into more garages across the country as the company goes
mainstream, including a new store in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   During an open house last week at the recently opened Ducati
Atlanta showroom on Piedmont Road, enthusiasts, known as
Ducatistis, were able to sip Ducati-brand water and check out the
company gear, including custom red leather riding suits with black
trim ($1,595) with matching riding gloves and boots.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta architect Paul D'Arconte, 47, who had never even ridden
a motorcycle, was smitten during a European vacation. In Italy, he
saw his first Ducati and a couple with matching leathers. ``That's
the coolest thing I've ever seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he liked the idea of motorcycling, D'Arconte says he
didn't feel confident about it until he planted himself atop a
silver-and-gold Ducati 750 Monster two years ago. ``It fit me, it
was small and light, and I felt comfortable handling it. Now that
I'm confident on the bike, I feel I could ride anything.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Arconte cites the brand's heritage, superb manners and
unmistakable roar of its L-Twin engine as the reason for his
rapture over his Ducati. ``Hey, I'm Italian, what can I say!'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Changes have already come to Ducati since the 1996 takeover by
Texas Pacific Group, including the introduction of new models.
</P>
<P>
   From the base model Monster 750 selling for $6,995 to the
superbike-bred 996 priced at $16,495, the company has broadened its
lineup to include a pair of two-person sport-touring models.
</P>
<P>
   The ST2 at $12,495 and the more powerful ST4 at $14,495 are fine
for taking on Italy's autostrada or the Alps, with their
comfortable seats and matching hard luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women both say they appreciate the styling of their
machines, with the lumpy tan engine peeking out from under a
spaghetti frame.
</P>
<P>
   Ducati's rise to prominence began in the mid-1950s, when Italian
motorsports designer Fabio Taglioni _ known for avant garde designs
and an emphasis on performance _ jumped on board. His Mach 250
broke distance and speed records in the '60s, and Taglioni won the
hearts of motorcycle enthusiasts and sports fans with his
eye-catching designs. In the 1970s, Taglioni introduced the unusual
desmodromic valve system on a production bike. The system's
positive valve actuation gives more immediate response than
conventional valve systems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 30-year-old desmo valve design enabled Ducati 996
riders to take the top two positions in last weekend's Big Kahuna
Nationals road race at Road Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
