<SLUG> BC-DELTA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta decision on deferring 777 orders could come today
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines could announce as early as today
whether it will defer its remaining Boeing 777 orders because of a
stalemate over pilot pay.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would likely delay for months or years the
Atlanta-based carrier's plans to make the giant jet a significant
part of its international fleet.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Delta took delivery of its first two 777s in late March and put
them into service May 1, with plans to add five more to the fleet
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But talks with the carrier's pilot union over pay rates for the
new planes have produced little progress.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot union can refuse to fly a new type of plane if no pay
agreement is in place six months after they enter service, which
would be Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Delta says it needs assurances of a pact much sooner in order to
confidently schedule the planes for fall and winter use.
</P>
<P>
   It has already deferred four 2000 deliveries, citing uncertainty
created by the pay dispute, and indicated the five deliveries
scheduled for this year are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its newness and size, the 777 would be the
best-paying plane in Delta's fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has offered $239 an hour for captains, 5 percent
above the top rate at carriers already flying the jet.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot union's last demand was for $319 an hour, a figure it
says is based on the plane's revenue-generating potential.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the pilot union announced overwhelming
rank-and-file approval of a special dues assessment to pay pilots
affected by a possible 777 grounding, a vote the union termed a
``show of support and solidarity'' for its negotiating stance.
</P>
<P>
   Another negotiating session is scheduled Tuesday, but neither
side has offered new proposals in the last two sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
