<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-SERVICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRIERS NEAR AGREEMENT ON PASSENGER TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's major airlines, responding to growing
complaints about the mistreatment of passengers, are close to
signing an agreement to relax ticketing rules, do more to notify
customers of canceled flights, and better serve people stranded on
aircraft during long delays.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines had been set to announce the deal Thursday, but
they canceled at the last minute amid reports Senate leaders were
angry because they had not signed off on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is an attempt to head off at least four bills in
Congress, dubbed ``passenger bills of rights,'' that were spurred
by complaints about poor airline service. In one prominent
incident, which became a public relations disaster for the
industry, a January snowstorm left passengers stuck aboard a
Northwest Airlines Corp. aircraft on a runway for eight hours or
longer with inadequate food and restroom facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the airline industry is negotiating with some of the
lawmakers who have filed bills to make the airlines more
consumer-friendly. After calling a press conference Thursday,
however, the Air Transport Association, which represents airlines
covering 95 percent of US passenger traffic, abruptly canceled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan needed some further work, which it is undergoing
right now,'' said David Fuscus, spokesman for the airline
association. ``It will probably be next week before we are ready to
announce it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that some senators want tougher
language in the deal than the airlines had approved.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that any industry agreement will blunt the
effort in Congress to pass new laws. One airline critic,
Representative Louise Slaughter, Democrat of New York, dismissed
the talks as ``good public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm glad my friends in the airline industry recognize
they have a problem with poviding poor passenger service, Congress
should not close the books on what is clearly a concern to the
thousands of people who fly,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a draft of the agreement, airlines would be required to do
more to help passengers who are forced to remain on board aircraft
during long delays. The airlines would make new efforts to provide
food, water, and restroom facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Other pledges in the proposed 12-point agreement called on
airlines to do more to notify customers of delayed or canceled
flights. Airlines would promise to provide all customers with the
lowest fare available when customers call for a reservation, and to
return lost baggage within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, airlines might give customers 24 hours to cancel
nonrefundable tickets.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, however, whether airlines would face any
punitive action if they violated any of the pledges in the
agreement. The Air Transport Association would not discuss details
of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines stand ready to do everything within our power to
improve customer service,'' said Gerald Greenwald, chairman of
United Airlines and chief of the association's executive committee,
in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   However, the airlines' draft agreement does not include one of
the most controversial proposals now before Congress: a requirement
that airlines compensate travelers who are delayed for more than
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines have argued that a ``passenger bill of rights'' would
raise costs and have been lobbying against the measures. With
company encouragement, for example, about 15,000 Continental
Airlines employees had written letters to lawmakers opposing the
``bills of rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
