<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-BAAN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM, Baan devise resource planning process
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ IBM and Baan have developed a way to automate a lot of
the development work for custom computer programs that companies
use to do everything from managing a sales force to tracking what's
in the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The work is being done at the IBM Implementation Factory for
Baan, which is housed at one of IBM's Atlanta sites.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which IBM estimates cost $20 million to develop,
staff and house, already employs about 20 people. By year's end,
IBM could hire 80 more. IBM employs about 8,000 people in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise resource planning, or ERP, is software that lets a
company's data flow beyond department walls. Instead of separate
software for each department, it allows a company to have one
software program for everything: sales force automation to
bookkeeping to shipping and receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the software, installing it and training employees to use
it costs time and money: It can cost $200,000 to $50 million,
depending on the size of the company. Implementation can take from
three or four months to a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Baan, SAP America, J.D. Edwards and PeopleSoft have 61 percent
of what was a $16.6 billion market for ERP software in 1998,
according to AMR Research, a Boston firm specializing in the ERP
software market.
</P>
<P>
   Companies hire consultants like IBM or Arthur Andersen to
shepherd them through the process of implementing an ERP system,
which includes customizing the software to fit a specific company,
installing it, transferring data from the old system and training
the staff on how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Plymack, in charge of Baan ERP software for IBM, said
there is a certain amount of redundancy each time a software
program is developed for a company.
</P>
<P>
   That sameness was used to create templates that automated 60
percent to 80 percent of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The new implementation factory adds templates for training
employees and transferring the data from the company's old computer
system to the new one. AMR estimates the new IBM process could
automate 80 percent to 90 percent of the ERP implementation.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Plymack said the new process could cut implementation time
and cost in half. He said IBM plans to develop similar centers for
other ERP vendors that IBM works with.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Johnson, a senior analyst with AMR, said IBM's factory
concept is unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other consultants have just the basics,'' he said. ``But this
level of detail, expertise and technology? No one's even close
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
