<HEADER>
A0868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-REMODELING-COX     06-10 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-REMODELING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Renovation presents tough choices _ even for a pro
 &HT;    By Danny Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't try this at home.
</P>
<P>
   That seems like odd advice coming from a remodeling pro. But
after renovating his 1930s Atlanta home, Craig Kennedy admits the
job is no model for his clients. Although he and his wife, Lisa,
were pleased with the outcome, some decisions made along the way
proved inefficient and costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did things the hard way,'' said Kennedy, a partner in
HammerSmith, an Atlanta design/build firm. ``Like most homeowners,
we had no idea what we were getting into. Once you move in, it's
hard to renovate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, kitchens and baths, typically the most expensive _ and
disruptive _ remodeling projects, should be done while the house is
vacant. But like many young home buyers, the Kennedys couldn't
afford to do everything they wanted when they bought their Glendale
Estates home six years ago. So they tackled a variety of projects,
including the kitchen, in phases.
</P>
<P>
   That meant the renovation, like their tastes, continued to
evolve. Driving some of the changes were two family members _
Davis, 3, and Henry, 4 months _ who were born since they launched
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other homeowners, the Kennedys didn't fall victim to the
typical remodeling pitfalls _ hiring a contractor without first
checking references, putting down too much money up front, failing
to put all terms in writing. But when the homeowner is in the
business, the process can be frustrating in other ways, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough remodeling for yourself. I'm exposed to so much
stuff every day in my work. I see it, and I want it,'' he said.
``So we had to make some tough decisions that I usually have to ask
my clients to do.''
</P>
<P>
   They started by making just enough improvements to make their
home attractive and functional.
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 house had some structural problems _ the attic sagged
about 4 inches, some structural sills were rotten _ that required
repairs. While the three bathrooms had never been updated, the
Kennedys chose to only ``jazz them up a little'' for now, he said,
painting the walls in decorative finishes.
</P>
<P>
   In a second phase, they replaced the siding, selecting vinyl the
same size as wood to make the exterior appear old, replaced the
windows and refinished the hardwood floors.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the Kennedys tackled finished attic space, where they
created a den and office. Vinyl floors, jalousie windows and
fluorescent lights were traded for wall-to-wall carpet, new windows
and track lights. They also opened the office space by vaulting the
ceiling and adding skylights.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the back yard, building terraces and retaining walls
to correct drainage.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there was that kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen of their dreams
</P>
<P>
   Craig wanted the kitchen to contain everything, from a fireplace
and breakfast area to appliances with the latest bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the remodeler's curse,'' said Lisa, an attorney turned
full-time mom.
</P>
<P>
   But finances required the couple to approach the room in phases
_ a process they don't regret because it gave them time to get to
know the space and determine their needs.
</P>
<P>
   They began by replacing its laminate countertops with granite
and installing a new sink. Open, stainless steel restaurant-style
shelves were added as temporary storage, but they wound up liking
them so much they kept them instead of hanging new wall cabinets.
``We really fought the traditional kitchen so we went without
them,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the floors, ceiling and walls, all inspired by
kitchens in Tuscany where the Kennedys once vacationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest response we get is to the floor. When we moved in
we had no kids, just dogs, so we've since made it child proof,''
Lisa said of the Italian ceramic tile in three sizes and a combo of
colors, including rust, mauve, tan and gray, that hides dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys opened up more of the attic to create a cathedral
ceiling with Tuscan-style cedar trusses, where track lighting was
installed to supplement canned fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Then the dangers of not having a master plan for the room began
to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Dream or nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   New windows had been installed on each side of the stove, but
one later had to be removed when the couple decided to purchase a
48-inch wide Sub Zero refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we decided the walls were the problem,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   So they added old-style ceramic tile in a running-bond pattern
half way up the walls. Above, they applied an old plaster finish,
made of plaster of Paris, latex paint and tinted wax, to the
Sheetrock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of surfaces here,'' Craig said, ``but when you
spend a lot of time in the kitchen, things like that and proper
lighting really matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And spending time there proved something else: The Kennedys
wanted an eat-in kitchen, but a table and chairs made the new
kitchen crowded. Craig's parents suggested they convert the
adjacent dining room into a breakfast room and open it to the
kitchen by removing a wall. In place of the table, an island with
roll-out shelves gave them much-needed counter space.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, lack of planning, along with special features such
as roll-out windows with no center bar, a custom-designed range
hood and a child-proof dishwasher, made the $100,000 kitchen
project far more expensive than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you manage a project, you can get good results,'' Craig
said. ``We did it all in phases so that spread it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-learned lessons haven't cooled the Kennedys' remodeling
fever; they next plan to expand their bedroom to make a master
suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting close to being done,'' he said. ``We've
created a lifestyle out of renovation, so when we're done, does
that mean we move for a new lifestyle?''
</P>
<P>
   The couple don't think so. ``We like this house,'' Craig said.
``It isn't perfect . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   But what old house is?
</P>
<P>
   B E F O R E Y O U R E M O D E L
</P>
<P>
   Remodeling can be frustrating enough with the barrage of
decisions and constant disruption that accompany a project. But
those challenges pale in comparison with being victimized by
unreliable contractors and shoddy workmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching a renovation project, be sure to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Check with real estate agents for property values in your
neighborhood before deciding how much you should invest.
</P>
<P>
   -- Develop a realistic budget. Add at least 10 percent because
most remodels run over either from inaccurate budget forecasting or
from additions to the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ask friends for references on contractors they have used and
inspect their work.
</P>
<P>
   -- Interview several contractors who are licensed and have
Workers' Compensation and general liability insurance. Ask to see
licenses and insurance certificates as proof. All general estimates
for the work should be free.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ask contractors how long their companies have been in
business (It typically takes at least five years to establish a
financially sound business).
</P>
<P>
   -- Check court records to determine whether the contractor has
been sued.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make sure you can communicate well with the contractor
because misunderstanding can lead to cost overruns and delays.
</P>
<P>
   -- Insist on a written contract once you hire a contractor that
indicates the estimated start and completion dates and descriptions
of the work, materials and prices.
</P>
<P>
   -- Check to see if the contract includes a warranty covering
workmanship and materials.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ask for working drawings to ensure your ideas have been
properly translated.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make sure no work is done until the contractor purchases the
necessary building permits.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't pay cash for work and don't pay more than one-third of
the cost in advance, one-third midway into the project and the
balance upon completion.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't sign a completion certificate for the job before it has
been inspected and properly completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders, c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0611-COX     06-10 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TO KEEP THE PEACE: With bombing suspended, NATO mounts ground
combat force to fend off potential trouble in Kosovo
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MACEDONIA; KOSOVO-ALBANIA; KOSOVO-AIRWAR;
CLINTON-KOSOVO-1STLD.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABLE SENTRY BASE, Macedonia _ Moving to secure the peace in the
wake of war, NATO commanders here spent Thursday positioning a
powerful ground combat army to begin pouring northward across the
border into Kosovo as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO peacekeepers mustered, hundreds of Yugoslav troops began
filing out of northern Kosovo in convoys of military vehicles, the
first stages of a retreat that prompted the U.S.-led alliance to
suspend its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia after 78 days of
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton claimed a moral victory in the
11-week campaign, saying the NATO strikes had ended, if not halted,
Serb atrocities the alliance claims forced more than 1 million
ethnic Albanians to flee their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have achieved a victory for a safer world, for our
democratic values and for a stronger America,'' Clinton said in a
televised address from the Oval Office Thursday night. ``An
aggression against an innocent people has been contained and is
being turned back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed that NATO warplanes stood by to resume bombing
if Serb forces renege on the promise their commanders made
Wednesday to exit Kosovo by June 20.
</P>
<P>
   He warned the nation that the peacekeeping mission carries grave
risks. ``There may well be casualties,'' Clinton cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   And he braced the nation for the possibility that U.S. troops
might be required to spend years in Kosovo restoring order and
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put a timetable on it,'' Clinton said.
``We will define our objectives and proceed to implement them.''
</P>
<P>
   If NATO claimed victory, so did Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, used what's left of his state-run television network to
praise his forces as ``the greatest army in the world,'' and try to
convince his fellow Serbs that the destruction they endured had
saved Kosovo for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Citizens, the aggression is over, peace has prevailed
over violence,'' said Milosevic, appearing in his trademark
double-breasted suit. ``We did not give up Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, the United Nations Security Council met in New York
to approve a resolution that effectively hands control of Kosovo
over to a handful of U.N. civilian agencies and a NATO peacekeeping
force expected to swell to 50,000 troops within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The figure does not include troops from Russia. U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott spent Thursday in Moscow
discussing the prospects for adding Russian troops to the
peacekeeping contingent, as both Washington and Moscow have agreed
would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, NATO's 19 nations have pledged to send 44,000
peacekeepers to Kosovo; 11 NATO partner countries have pledged
about 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is ready for its new mission, a mission to bring people
back to their homes and to build a lasting and just peace in
Kosovo,'' NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told reporters in
Brussels, moments after suspending the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've insisted on the fact that NATO has absolutely nothing
against the people of Yugoslavia,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to Kosovo's ethnic Serbs, Solana said they have
nothing to fear from the advancing NATO forces, vowed to protect
them and urged them not to flee the war-ravaged province as Kosovar
Albanian refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely hope that the Serbs in Kosovo will remain in their
homes,'' said Solana. ``The NATO forces will defend their rights,
just as it will defend the rights of all other ethnic communities
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cologne, Germany, U.S. and European diplomats called for
establishing a Pact of Stability for Southeast Europe, an effort to
help stitch the war-torn Balkans back into the rapidly modernizing
region with the help of as much as $6 billion a year in foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seemed likely to dominate much of the agenda a week
from now, when Clinton joins Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and the heads of state from
Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan for a summit of the
so-called Group of Eight, or G-8, in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe cannot be fully secure,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said following the meeting in Cologne, ``unless its
southeast corner is free from strife.''
</P>
<P>
   The first crucial step, though, in what promises to be a long
and costly endeavor was taking shape here, where British troops
were preparing to form the vanguard of the NATO peacekeeping force
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall be off quite soon,'' said British Lt. Gen. Michael
Jackson, who will command the NATO peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 U.S. troops _ Marines and Army infantry forces _
poured into Macedonia throughout the day, prepared to enter Kosovo
and to counter any threat they might face there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to make sure that the forces that come in to keep the
peace are in fact the most powerful forces around,'' said U.S. Army
Col. Jeffrey Schlosser, who flew here Thursday at the head of a
column of 26 U.S. Army helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Among these were a dozen Apache attack helicopters. If NATO
commanders gave the orders, the Apaches would be available to plant
Hellfire missiles on anyone interfering with the peacekeepers _
whether that be Serb renegades or diehards of rebel the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any sort of violence, the Apaches are like a big
stick,'' said Schlosser. ``If anything bad does happen in Kosovo,
we can protect our forces so they won't get caught between opposing
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   An advance team from the British Fifth Paratrooper Regiment and
British Combat Engineers is expected to cross into Kosovo by
helicopter as early as Friday. After the British combat engineers
have cleared mines and barricades from the main road into the
provincial capital Pristina, the main initial column of Western
peacekeepers is likely to surge across the border on Sunday. That
first NATO occupation column may be 1,000 vehicles long.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the scenario provided late Thursday to
Canadian journalists from NATO liaison officers with access to the
exact plans for NATO's entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence must end immediately,'' said Jackson, making clear
that the admonition applied as equally to the KLA, made up of
ethnic Albanians, as to Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson warned KLA commanders that it would be ``foolish in the
extreme,'' to fire on withdrawing Serbs or take other actions that
would impede their departure from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said retreating Yugoslav forces ``are being
cooperative'' in providing NATO officers detailed maps showing the
locations of minefields and boobie traps. And he said he had
received a report that Yugoslav explosives experts were dismantling
the explosives from a bridge and tunnel complex at Kacanic, on the
road to Pristina, which had been designed to block any northward
invasion through Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the first big column of peacekeepers moves forward, the
United States will be providing only about 15 percent of the troops
_ but most of the combat punch.
</P>
<P>
   America's most heavily armored battle tanks, the M1A1 Abrams
that captured Kuwait a decade ago, are being flown in to this NATO
camp's busy airstrip. By Friday night, about 14 of the tanks are
expected to be poised to go into Kosovo. Another 14 were scheduled
to arrive as early as next week from a NATO tank base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, U.S. Marines were unloading massive
amphibious armored personnel carriers called Amtracs from flatbed
trucks that jammed the entryways to this makeshift NATO base, which
has sprung up next to the runway of the airport at the Macedonia
capital Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, meanwhile, was moving in a column of about 15 of its
Bradley armored personnel carriers across a mountain pass from
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, the United States will have ready to send into
Kosovo an elite force of 1,700 Army combat troops, including
paratroopers from the 82nd Airborne Division, plus another roughly
2,000 Marines of the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit based at Camp
Lejeune, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Counting support troops and other units already stationed in
Macedonia, the United States will be ready by this weekend to field
7,000 peacekeepers, most of them from elite units trained for
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is deploying a considerably larger peacekeeping
contingent, and sizeable contingents also will come from France and
Germany and lesser-sized units from roughly 15 other powers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
