<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0611-COX     06-10 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TO KEEP THE PEACE: With bombing suspended, NATO mounts ground
combat force to fend off potential trouble in Kosovo
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MACEDONIA; KOSOVO-ALBANIA; KOSOVO-AIRWAR;
CLINTON-KOSOVO-1STLD.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABLE SENTRY BASE, Macedonia _ Moving to secure the peace in the
wake of war, NATO commanders here spent Thursday positioning a
powerful ground combat army to begin pouring northward across the
border into Kosovo as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO peacekeepers mustered, hundreds of Yugoslav troops began
filing out of northern Kosovo in convoys of military vehicles, the
first stages of a retreat that prompted the U.S.-led alliance to
suspend its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia after 78 days of
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton claimed a moral victory in the
11-week campaign, saying the NATO strikes had ended, if not halted,
Serb atrocities the alliance claims forced more than 1 million
ethnic Albanians to flee their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have achieved a victory for a safer world, for our
democratic values and for a stronger America,'' Clinton said in a
televised address from the Oval Office Thursday night. ``An
aggression against an innocent people has been contained and is
being turned back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed that NATO warplanes stood by to resume bombing
if Serb forces renege on the promise their commanders made
Wednesday to exit Kosovo by June 20.
</P>
<P>
   He warned the nation that the peacekeeping mission carries grave
risks. ``There may well be casualties,'' Clinton cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   And he braced the nation for the possibility that U.S. troops
might be required to spend years in Kosovo restoring order and
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put a timetable on it,'' Clinton said.
``We will define our objectives and proceed to implement them.''
</P>
<P>
   If NATO claimed victory, so did Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, used what's left of his state-run television network to
praise his forces as ``the greatest army in the world,'' and try to
convince his fellow Serbs that the destruction they endured had
saved Kosovo for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Citizens, the aggression is over, peace has prevailed
over violence,'' said Milosevic, appearing in his trademark
double-breasted suit. ``We did not give up Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, the United Nations Security Council met in New York
to approve a resolution that effectively hands control of Kosovo
over to a handful of U.N. civilian agencies and a NATO peacekeeping
force expected to swell to 50,000 troops within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The figure does not include troops from Russia. U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott spent Thursday in Moscow
discussing the prospects for adding Russian troops to the
peacekeeping contingent, as both Washington and Moscow have agreed
would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, NATO's 19 nations have pledged to send 44,000
peacekeepers to Kosovo; 11 NATO partner countries have pledged
about 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is ready for its new mission, a mission to bring people
back to their homes and to build a lasting and just peace in
Kosovo,'' NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told reporters in
Brussels, moments after suspending the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've insisted on the fact that NATO has absolutely nothing
against the people of Yugoslavia,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to Kosovo's ethnic Serbs, Solana said they have
nothing to fear from the advancing NATO forces, vowed to protect
them and urged them not to flee the war-ravaged province as Kosovar
Albanian refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely hope that the Serbs in Kosovo will remain in their
homes,'' said Solana. ``The NATO forces will defend their rights,
just as it will defend the rights of all other ethnic communities
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cologne, Germany, U.S. and European diplomats called for
establishing a Pact of Stability for Southeast Europe, an effort to
help stitch the war-torn Balkans back into the rapidly modernizing
region with the help of as much as $6 billion a year in foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seemed likely to dominate much of the agenda a week
from now, when Clinton joins Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and the heads of state from
Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan for a summit of the
so-called Group of Eight, or G-8, in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe cannot be fully secure,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said following the meeting in Cologne, ``unless its
southeast corner is free from strife.''
</P>
<P>
   The first crucial step, though, in what promises to be a long
and costly endeavor was taking shape here, where British troops
were preparing to form the vanguard of the NATO peacekeeping force
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall be off quite soon,'' said British Lt. Gen. Michael
Jackson, who will command the NATO peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 U.S. troops _ Marines and Army infantry forces _
poured into Macedonia throughout the day, prepared to enter Kosovo
and to counter any threat they might face there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to make sure that the forces that come in to keep the
peace are in fact the most powerful forces around,'' said U.S. Army
Col. Jeffrey Schlosser, who flew here Thursday at the head of a
column of 26 U.S. Army helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Among these were a dozen Apache attack helicopters. If NATO
commanders gave the orders, the Apaches would be available to plant
Hellfire missiles on anyone interfering with the peacekeepers _
whether that be Serb renegades or diehards of rebel the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any sort of violence, the Apaches are like a big
stick,'' said Schlosser. ``If anything bad does happen in Kosovo,
we can protect our forces so they won't get caught between opposing
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   An advance team from the British Fifth Paratrooper Regiment and
British Combat Engineers is expected to cross into Kosovo by
helicopter as early as Friday. After the British combat engineers
have cleared mines and barricades from the main road into the
provincial capital Pristina, the main initial column of Western
peacekeepers is likely to surge across the border on Sunday. That
first NATO occupation column may be 1,000 vehicles long.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the scenario provided late Thursday to
Canadian journalists from NATO liaison officers with access to the
exact plans for NATO's entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence must end immediately,'' said Jackson, making clear
that the admonition applied as equally to the KLA, made up of
ethnic Albanians, as to Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson warned KLA commanders that it would be ``foolish in the
extreme,'' to fire on withdrawing Serbs or take other actions that
would impede their departure from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said retreating Yugoslav forces ``are being
cooperative'' in providing NATO officers detailed maps showing the
locations of minefields and boobie traps. And he said he had
received a report that Yugoslav explosives experts were dismantling
the explosives from a bridge and tunnel complex at Kacanic, on the
road to Pristina, which had been designed to block any northward
invasion through Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the first big column of peacekeepers moves forward, the
United States will be providing only about 15 percent of the troops
_ but most of the combat punch.
</P>
<P>
   America's most heavily armored battle tanks, the M1A1 Abrams
that captured Kuwait a decade ago, are being flown in to this NATO
camp's busy airstrip. By Friday night, about 14 of the tanks are
expected to be poised to go into Kosovo. Another 14 were scheduled
to arrive as early as next week from a NATO tank base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, U.S. Marines were unloading massive
amphibious armored personnel carriers called Amtracs from flatbed
trucks that jammed the entryways to this makeshift NATO base, which
has sprung up next to the runway of the airport at the Macedonia
capital Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, meanwhile, was moving in a column of about 15 of its
Bradley armored personnel carriers across a mountain pass from
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, the United States will have ready to send into
