<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-N     06-10 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX-EXEMPT STATUS REJECTED, CHRISTIAN COALITION REGROUPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Christian Coalition, a powerhouse in the
Republican Party for the last decade, has been denied tax-exempt
status because of its political activity, officials of the
organization said Thursday, and is reorganizing in an effort to
retain its influence.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the organization has successfully rallied voters
behind candidates, almost all Republicans, who supported the causes
of religious conservatives at the national, state and local level.
It has been especially influential in Iowa, which holds the first
party caucuses in presidential election years.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last couple of years, the coalition has had some
trouble raising money and its influence has seemed to be waning.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders who have tracked recent developments in the
organization said that it had never recovered from the loss of
Ralph Reed, the politically talented executive director who left
two years ago to become a political consultant in Atlanta, and that
Pat Robertson, the founder and president, was taking complete
control to change the course.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the coalition, which has headquarters in Chesapeake,
Va., announced that Reed's successor, Randy Tate, had been demoted
and that the chief operating officer, Kenneth Hill, would be
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, four other top officials either resigned or
were discharged. They are Donald P. Hodel, the president; Dave
Welch, the national field director; Arne Owens, the communications
director, and Charles H. Cunningham, the national operations
director.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, officials of the coalition confirmed that its
long-standing application to the Internal Revenue Service for
tax-exempt status would not be approved and that, as a result, the
coalition would be reorganized.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Robertson founded the coalition in 1988 after his
unsuccessful race for the Republican presidential nomination, it
sought tax exemption under section 501(c)(4) of the Internal
Revenue Code.
</P>
<P>
   Donors to such organizations may not deduct their contributions,
but the organizations themselves do not have to pay income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations that have such an exemption are not permitted to
engage in ``substantial'' political activity. The IRS generally has
interpreted this to mean that they could not support parties or
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main activities of the Christian Coalition has been
to prepare voter guides and to distribute them in churches. The
guides generally describe the candidates in a race and leave little
doubt about which one the coalition favors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 Senate race in Virginia between Sen. Charles S.
Robb, a Democrat, and Oliver L. North, a Republican, the guide said
that Robb, who had voted for an appropriation for the National
Endowment for the Arts, favored government-financed obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Russell, the coalition spokesman, said the group had
recently withdrawn its application for tax exemption. Other
officials said it was withdrawn after it became apparent it would
not be approved.
</P>
<P>
   As is its practice on such matters, the IRS refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of tax exemption means that the organization may have
to pay a small amount in income taxes each year. More important, it
may make churches reluctant to allow representatives of the
organization to speak and distribute material during services.
Churches are covered by another section of the tax law that
theoretically does not allow participation in any political
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the coalition would now be broken up into two
distinct organizations.
</P>
<P>
   One, to be called the Christian Coalition International, would
engage in political activities. This organization would not be
tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   A separate group, to be called the Christian Coalition of
America, would concentrate on voter education and would assume the
existing tax-exempt status of the Christian Coalition of Texas,
Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson will assume ``a greatly increased role'' in the daily
operation of the organizations, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson has recently taken a surprisingly pragmatic approach
to politics. During the impeachment trial last winter, he warned
that President Clinton had won the public relations battle and that
it was perilous for Republicans to expend their energy trying to
remove him from office. He has also conceded that Congress will not
approve a Constitutional amendment outlawing abortion and has said
Republicans should turn to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Robertson said he hoped to raise $21 million for
political activities in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Black, a Republican consultant, said he thought the
Christian Coalition would remain an important organizing force in
many states. Another Republican strategist, Richard N. Bond, who
was director of George Bush's presidential campaign in 1988, agreed
with that assessment but said it was important for the organization
to rise above ``a lingering image of intolerance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLINTON PROMISE DETERS HOUSE GOP FROM BARRING FUNDS FOR KOSOVO
FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton promised Thursday night to ask
Congress to fund security troops in Kosovo. His last-minute
maneuver stopped House Republicans from barring money for the
force.
</P>
<P>
   That promise, in a faxed letter from Clinton to House Speaker
Dennis Hastert was ``exactly what we wanted,'' said a spokesman for
the speaker, John Feehery. ``It shows that the president can't raid
the defense budget for peacekeeping. If there is going to be a
peacekeeping force, it will have to come out of money that is not
already earmarked for defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, though deliberately vague, bowed to Congress and
pledged to make a separate budget request for the troops. It
arrived after six hours of fierce argument on the House floor over
the U.S. presence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are expecting us to support an effort to
bring peace,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is duty-bound to keep that peace, Gephardt
said, adding, ``Turning our backs on this effort now would send a
horrible signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum for the debate was a $289 billion military-spending
bill that won final passage Thursday night, 365-58. The original
measure had prohibited using the money for combat or peacekeeping
operations in Yugoslavia in fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's letter arrived, the House voted, 270-155, to
strike the prohibition. The ``yes'' votes included 77 Republicans,
among them Majority Leader Dick Armey and Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
An amendment to ban all spending for peacekeeping in Kosovo lost,
97-328.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in the history of this country has the Congress voted to
deprive the nation of victory in the battlefield,'' said Rep. Ike
Skelton of Missouri, the ranking Democrat on the Armed Services
Committee who led the fight to remove the ban. ``The votes taken
today will tell whether we keep that victory or whether we sour it
or whether we throw ashes on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, whose approval of financing for the peacekeeping
force is by no means assured, said they feared a long deployment of
U.S. troops as an occupying force in hostile territory. ``After
bombing a country to smithereens, we're now occupying it,'' said
Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas. ``When will it end?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Donald Manzullo, R-Ill., said the administration had
``destroyed a country'' and ``wasted our precious military
resources.'' Paying for the troops, Manzullo added, is ``fiscally
wrong, and it's morally wrong, and the president needs to be
stopped. This war should never have been started, and the American
taxpayer should not be called upon to complete it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., said Clinton had ``undermined our
national interests'' and ``disguised the costs of this war,''
wasted billions on an ``ill-conceived operation'' that
``accelerated and augmented the tragic refugee crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Souder questioned whether the war had really been won. ``This is
certainly no victory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Randy Cunningham, R-Calif., called the NATO bombing
unconscionable and its outcome a disaster. ``We have killed
civilians,'' Cunningham said. ``That is not a win. Hundreds of
thousands of people are refugees. That is not a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Republicans sought something more than Clinton's word
that an emergency spending request was forthcoming. ``Get it in
writing,'' Cunningham said. ``I know what the meaning of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   The $289 billion sum is greater than the budgets for all other
agencies combined, greater than all military spending by the 10
biggest foreign armies in the world taken together. Nevertheless,
the Pentagon, House Republicans and conservative Democrats say the
U.S. military faces a financial crisis that threatens national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which gives legal authority, not appropriated money,
to the Pentagon programs, backs a 4.8 percent pay increase. It
includes $91 billion for new weapons, including $3.7 billion for
continuing attempts to build a missile-defense system and $3.1
billion to speed production of the F-22 fighter jet. The bill also
cuts the budget for declassifying Pentagon documents, from $200
million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate action, the House defeated, 116-307, an amendment
to cut U.S. troops in Europe, from 100,000 to 25,000, over three
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
