<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WOMEN11-COX     06-10 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WOMEN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Turner cable channel to put focus on women
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting is going after women with a new
cable channel set to launch early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The unnamed channel will feature news, information and how-to
shows, much of it based on magazines such as In Style, Parenting
and Cooking Light, owned by parent Time Warner. The channel will
also draw on a partnership with magazine giant Conde Nast, whose
titles include Vogue, House and Garden and Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Pat Mitchell, one of Turner Broadcasting's most
powerful executives, will head the channel, which will operate out
of Turner Broadcasting's new studio. The channel will also have a
studio in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are a huge under-served market and the number one
economic opportunity of the day,'' says Mitchell, producer of CNN's
award-winning series, ``Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting is the first to see a future in focusing all
of a channel's programming on women. The new channel will face the
well-established Lifetime Television, already in more than 70
million homes nationwide. Another women's channel, Oxygen, is
scheduled to launch in February. If Oxygen is not yet familiar,
some of its principal investors may be: former Nickelodeon boss
Geraldine Laybourne, ``Third Rock from the Sun'' and ``The Cosby
Show'' mastermind Marcy Carsey, and Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime's top executive wondered why it took everyone so long.
But now that it could become a battle, she said, Lifetime is
well-armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just experienced our best quarter ever in ratings and
demographics,'' said Carole Black, president and CEO of Lifetime
Television, which recently announced a new lineup of shows,
featuring such big names as Bette Midler, Dolly Parton and Vanessa
Williams. ``Women represent over 50 percent of the population, they
buy the majority of all products sold, so I can understand why
others are going after women now.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Lifetime's success, says Kris Magel, an analyst with
DeWitt Media, is that the network has been smart to create an
``emotional relationship'' with its female viewers, especially
those in the 25-54 and 35-64 age range, who ``have all the
disposable income.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell says her channel will differ from Oxygen and Lifetime,
which is heavy on entertainment programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you won't see on our channel is sitcoms, network
reruns and dramatic series,'' says Mitchell. About her competitors,
she adds, ``There is plenty of room for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman's channel, Turner Broadcasting's 19th, also will face
the difficult task of finding distributors in an increasingly
competitive industry. Laybourne has already signed up some big
cable operators, including the 5 million subscribers of Charter
Communications. She is expected to announce other distribution
deals at the National Cable Television Association in Chicago next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Jill Vejnoska contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Haddad
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting is planning to launch a new cable TV channel
designed to appeal specifically to women sometime early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The channel is as yet unnamed but will feature news, information
and how-to shows, much of the programming based on magazines owned
by parent Time Warner. The channel will also draw on the content of
magazine giant Conde Nast, a unit of Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of a partnership agreement between Time Warner and Advance
are still in negotiation and Turner Broadcasting executives
declined to discuss them.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and Conde Nast are among the largest magazine
publishers and each has a number of titles marketed to women. For
Time Warner, those titles include In Style, Parenting and Cooking
Light. Conde Nast's titles include House and Garden, Glamour and
Mademoiselle.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Time Warner's and Conde Nast's women's magazines reach
some 100 million readers a month, the companies say.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting's new channel will be headed by veteran
television newscaster and executive Pat Mitchell, who currently
works at CNN. Mitchell has been working on the woman's channel for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Why, though, is Turner Broadcasting moving to air the channel
now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because women are a huge under-served market and the number
one economic opportunity of the day,'' says Mitchell. ``And that's
a good business reason for the channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting is not alone in seeing a potentially big
market for women in television. For one, there already is a
successful cable TV channel marketing itself to women. It's called
Lifetime and it reaches more than 70 million homes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Another group is trying to begin a channel for women at the same
time as Turner Broadcasting. That channel is called Oxygen and is
the brainchild of Geraldine Laybourne, the cable TV veteran
programmer who used to head Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   Laybourne has already signed up some big operators, including
the 5 million subscribers of Charter Communications. She is
expected to announce other distribution deals at the National Cable
Television Association in Chicago next week.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen is expected to begin airing in February.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell says her channel will differ from Lifetime and Oxygen,
both of which feature fiction entertainment such as movies, sitcoms
and drama series.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Mitchell's channel will offer news, information and
discussion about issues considered important to women. The topics
include parenting, fashion, health and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you won't see on our channel is sitcoms, network
reruns and dramatic series,'' says Mitchell. About her competitors,
she adds, ``There is plenty of room for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman's channel, Turner Broadcasting's 19th, has no
distribution as of yet. Finding distribution remains hard these
days in the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell says she expects the channel to initially show up
on the new digital tiers of cable operators. It is here that most
operators are adding new channels. Subscribers pay additional fees
to receive digital packages from their cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's channel would be run out of the entertainment
division of Turner Broadcasting in Atlanta. It will use the new
digital studio under construction at the company's Techwood campus.
The channel would also have a studio in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
