<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      06-10 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEGACY ABROAD MAY LIE IN U.S. ROLE AS MEDIATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: 5graf insert, In an 11-minute, to add Clinton comments;
pickup: The president's foreign policy)  
 News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's enduring legacy in foreign
affairs may be his efforts to reconcile warring factions inside
sovereign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by international inaction during the slaughters in Bosnia
and Rwanda, the president has devoted much of his foreign policy to
crafting compromises designed to ease the ethnic, religious or
cultural animosities that often lead to bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton helped fashion compromises in Northern Ireland, Bosnia
and the Middle East. He opted for talk over combat in Haiti,
dispatching a team of heavy-hitters _ former President Jimmy
Carter, retired Gen. Colin Powell and then-Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga. _
on the eve of the U.S. invasion in 1994 to persuade a defiant
strongman to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has worked, as well, with African leaders to help stem
ethnic struggles in Burundi and in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   In an 11-minute address from the Oval Office Thursday night, the
president celebrated the U.S.-led campaign against ethnic
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This victory brings a new hope that when a people are singled
out for destruction because of their heritage and religious faith _
and we can do something about it _ the world will not look the
other way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0880 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-1STL     06-10 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEGACY ABROAD MAY LIE IN U.S. ROLE AS MEDIATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: 5graf insert, In an 11-minute, to add Clinton comments;
pickup: The president's foreign policy)  
 News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's enduring legacy in foreign
affairs may be his efforts to reconcile warring factions inside
sovereign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by international inaction during the slaughters in Bosnia
and Rwanda, the president has devoted much of his foreign policy to
crafting compromises designed to ease the ethnic, religious or
cultural animosities that often lead to bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton helped fashion compromises in Northern Ireland, Bosnia
and the Middle East. He opted for talk over combat in Haiti,
dispatching a team of heavy-hitters _ former President Jimmy
Carter, retired Gen. Colin Powell and then-Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga. _
on the eve of the U.S. invasion in 1994 to persuade a defiant
strongman to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has worked, as well, with African leaders to help stem
ethnic struggles in Burundi and in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   In an 11-minute address from the Oval Office Thursday night, the
president celebrated the U.S.-led campaign against ethnic
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This victory brings a new hope that when a people are singled
out for destruction because of their heritage and religious faith _
and we can do something about it _ the world will not look the
other way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the 79-day military campaign had ``sent a message
of determination and hope'' that the international community will
combat ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world too divided by fear among people of different
racial, ethnic and religious groups, we have given confidence to
the friends of freedom and pause to those who would exploit human
differences for inhuman purposes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its allies took a stand, Clinton said
earlier, adding: ``The United States should feel vindicated when
the people go home, and when they're safe, and when we can say that
we, as a nation, have played a role in reversing ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's foreign policy has been distinguished by heavy
reliance on personal diplomacy with the leaders of Russia and
China, a willingness to threaten military action, and reliance on
high-tech warfare with low risks of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's air-only operation against Yugoslavia was emblematic
of the tactics he used to strike Iraq, Sudan and Afghanistan in the
past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dallek, a professor of history at Boston University and
the author of ``Hail to the Chief: The Making and Unmaking of
American Presidents,'' said Clinton's willingness to confront
burgeoning humanitarian catastrophes may become the model for
American foreign policy in 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton may be establishing a new paradigm for American
foreign policy _ that whenever we see ethnic cleansing, even the
mere hint of genocide, it will be resisted by the United States,''
Dallek said. ``The United States may be emerging as the world
policeman to fight ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simon Serfaty, director of European studies at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, warned that
Clinton's willingness to intervene must be matched by a willingness
to follow through once hostilities end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe any of Clinton's interventions will prove to
be constructive in the long term,'' Serfaty said. ``There has just
not been enough follow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction lags in Bosnia, a former republic of Yugoslavia
ravaged by ethnic conflict. Nations are behind on promised
donations to a $5.1 billion recovery fund. Barely 574,000 of the
1.8 million uprooted Bosnians have returned to their homes more
than three years after a U.S.-brokered peace agreement ended the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction in Kosovo may require $30 billion, difficulties
lie ahead persuading uprooted Kosovars to return home and the
secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army may resist disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may well turn out that we've done the easy part with regard
to Kosovo,'' Serfaty said. ``Now we're there and we have no idea
what we're facing or how long it will take. We'll need follow up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House aides say the roots of Clinton's approach lie in the
frustrations of watching the international community stand idly by
as 200,000 people died in Bosnia during four years of communal
warfare there, and as more than 1 million people died in Rwanda in
internecine fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came face-to-face with the human cost of inaction during
a stopover at Kilgali airport in Rwanda in 1998, when survivors
vividly recalled the horror.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say the experience has shaped Clinton's thinking ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not act quickly enough after the killing began,''
Clinton lamented in remarks to the survivors in the Central African
nation. ``We did not immediately call these crimes by their
rightful name _ `genocide.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred back to the precedent in his remarks on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should be proud of standing up to the Yugoslav
leadership's crusade to drive Kosovars ``from their land _ dead or
alive,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what we have done in Bosnia, and the work we have been
doing in Africa to try to prevent a Rwanda from ever occurring
again, we will be able to see the world go into the 21st century
with a more humane future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
