<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S ECONOMY SHOWS SIGNS OF NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ After nearly two years of recession, Japan's dormant
economy leaped to life in the first three months of the year,
according to official figures so strong that they were immediately
played down by some of the government's own economists.
</P>
<P>
   The gross domestic product rose for the first time since the end
of 1997, gaining 1.9 percent from the last quarter of 1998,
compared with a drop of eight-tenths of a percent in the previous
quarter, according to the figures released today. If this pace were
maintained for a full year _ something virtually no one expects _
the economy would grow 7.9 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese government officials, long criticized for failing to
acknowledge the depths of the nation's economic crisis, hastened to
stamp out any sense of euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to say the economy has recovered or bottomed
out,'' said Taiichi Sakaiya, he head of the Economic Planning
Agency, which compiles the figures.
</P>
<P>
   Few are betting that the improvement in output will have much
momentum, and many worried that it would force the government to
postpone drafting a supplemental budget devoted to further
stimulating the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a risk of a slowdown in the economy in the
second half of this year because public expenditures are likely to
decrease,'' said Hiroyuki Inoue, chief economist at the Japan
Center for Research. ``Today's number doesn't mean the crisis is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest output figures appeared to indicate, though, that the
government's yearlong, $800 billion-plus spending program had begun
to have stimulative effects. The government estimates annual growth
of half of 1 percent for the year, a figure that until Thursday was
considered unrealistically rosy by many economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's projections will not be so difficult to
achieve, given today's figure,'' said Masaru Takagi, an economist
at Meiji University. ``The key point is whether private demand
continues to improve, especially in the second half of this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, stock buyers were impressed by the data. The
benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues shot up 480.12 points, or 2.89
percent, to 17,102.62. The yen spiked up against the dollar after
the new figures were announced and then fell back amid speculation
by currency traders that the Japanese central bank had intervened
in the markets and was selling yen. A strong yen could crush hopes
of an economic turnaround because so many big Japanese
manufacturers rely on exports. In late currency trading in New
York, though, the yen stood at 118.84 to the dollar, only slightly
higher than Wednesday's rate of 118.93.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Treasury Robert E. Rubin said in Washington
that the United States was not selling yen and would not confirm
that the Japanese authorities had in fact sold yen to buy dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he would not draw broad conclusions from the Japanese
output data. ``My instinct is that individual quarterly numbers
don't give you much sense about what's happening in an economy,''
he said. ``Clearly, they have enormous challenges ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, the magnitude of the improvement caught economists off
guard. The consensus forecast of 28 economists polled by Bloomberg
News this morning had been for growth of only 0.1 percent _ and
many forecasters grumbled that the government's statistics were
based on data that did not accurately reflect economic reality.
Just a day earlier, on Wednesday, Bloomberg's economists were
predicting the economy would contract by eight-tenths of a 8
percent until comments late in the afternoon by the prime
minister's spokesman, who suggested that the figures would be
positive, sent them back to rework their models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautious about the accuracy of the numbers in reflecting
what's really happening in the economy,'' said Chris Calderwood,
chief economist at Jardine Fleming Securities here. ``Even if the
numbers are vaguely right, it's possible we're getting all the good
news in one blow, and it's all downhill from here.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Calderwood and others looked askance at the
figures for private consumption and corporate investment, which
rose 1.2 percent and 2.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending, which was down 0.2 percent the previous
quarter, has always been the wild card in a Japanese recovery.
While there are signs that Mrs. Watanabe, the ubiquitous Japanese
housewife, is shopping more freely, companies are forcing workers
to retire early, and are cutting bonuses and perquisites.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers face new tax increases for the public pension system
and for medical insurance, which should also hold back spending.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the increase in corporate spending was due to a one-time
outlay for technology related to a new digital telephone system. In
the previous quarter, corporate expenditures dropped 5.5 percent,
and almost every major company has plans to cut capital spending
anywhere from 15 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists have been skeptical about the corporate profit
survey compiled by the Finance Ministry, which contains the figures
on company spending that are used to calculate the gross domestic
product. The same survey showed employment up 6.2 percent compared
with the period last year, according to one economist. Such a
figure seems so clearly out of sync with reality _ unemployment
rate is at a record high 4.8 percent _ that it raises questions
about the entire survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data on corporate spending doesn't really jibe with other
data we have,'' said Brian H. Rose, senior economist at Warburg
Dillon Read. ``I'd conclude that the survey just isn't that
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's output figures would appear to support the
government's strategy of setting aside fiscal caution in order to
goad the economy into action. More than $800 billion has been
invested in public works over the last year, and tax cuts, credit
guarantees and shopping vouchers have been handed out to encourage
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Economists worry that once spending stops, Japan will again fall
into a prolonged decline, and they say that spending is almost
certain to stop. The country's public-sector debt has ballooned,
with the Finance Ministry predicting it will stand at 108.5 percent
of the gross domestic product this year. Tax revenue is falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're approaching the peak of government spending,'' Rose
said. ``I think a lot of people, including us, are really more
worried about what will happen in 2000 rather than this year, when
it looks like they've propped things up pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Public investment rose 10.3 percent in the first quarter, on the
back of a 10.6 percent increase the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcies are down, largely because the government has spent
15 trillion yen in the last six months _ $126 billion at current
exchange rates _ on a loan guarantee program for small and midsized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Tax breaks have produced a surge in new housing, pushing housing
investment up 1.2 percent in the first quarter, compared with a 7
percent decline in the fourth quarter of 1998. Interest rates are
about as low as they can go without being negative.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the government will take the wraps off a plan to halt
the rise in unemployment, with $17 billion to $42 billion in new
spending aimed at creating 700,000 jobs and preserving existing
ones.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of pump-priming activities are applauded by
officials in the United States and other foreign governments; in
Japan, they draw criticism as an expensive effort to stave off
wrenching structural changes needed to put the economy on a
globally competitive footing.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists said that a danger inherent in today's figures
was complacency _ that hints of Asian economic recovery would
squelch the drive for market-driven changes that was so strong in
worse times a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a new set of risks,'' Inoue of the Japan Center
for Research maintained. ``If private corporations react to the
current numbers the wrong way, if they think the crisis is over,
they might not press ahead with restructuring and reform. And that
will postpone necessary structural readjustments to the economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
