<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AVERTS FUNDING BAN DESPITE MOVE BY HOUSE REPUBLICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid protests that their timing was extraordinarily
bad, House Republicans sought Thursday to deny funding for U.S.
peacekeeping operations in Kosovo even as American troops were
massing on the border of the Serbian province preparing to move in
with NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton managed to avert a ban on funding by
pledging in a letter to House members that he would seek the
express approval of Congress for additional money for peacekeeping
operations and by offering assurances that the mission would not
interfere with U.S. military readiness elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's effort to address GOP concerns about an extended
military involvement in Kosovo came after Republican opponents of
the war tried to pass language as part of the 2000 defense
authorization bill that would have prohibited the Pentagon from
spending any money on the peacekeeping operation after Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The language was later stripped from the $289 billion defense
bill by a vote of 270-155. The bill passed 365-58.
</P>
<P>
   The language banning Kosovo funding was included in the bill,
said Republican sponsors of the provision, to ensure that Congress
would continue to control ``the government's purse strings,'' as
one member put it, and to prevent the president from shifting money
from other defense operations to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   But a few GOP opponents of U.S. involvement in the Balkans were
able to use the debate on the language as a vehicle to denounce the
Kosovo peace agreement as ``a defeat'' for NATO, as Rep. Mark
Souder, R-Ariz., put it, and to accuse the allies of killing more
civilians during the bombing campaign than the Serb forces did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the bombing of NATO, there's been over twice the
number of people killed than were killed prior to our bombing. We
have killed more civilians ... than the Serbs,'' said Rep. Duke
Cunningham, R-Calif., adding that Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic ``had a plan (to rid Kosovo of ethnic Albanians), and we
implemented that plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of thousands of people today who would not
be refugees if we had not bombed. That is not a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, also criticized the peacekeeping plan,
calling it nothing more than a blueprint for the extended
occupation of sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   ``After bombing a country to smithereens, we are now going to
occupy it,'' Paul said, adding that taxpayer dollars are now
supporting a worldwide U.S. empire built on American military
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When will it end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate unfolded as Yugoslav military and paramilitary units
began withdrawing from Kosovo and as Clinton and other allied
leaders were celebrating the peace plan and expressing hope that
the peacekeeping mission would be a success.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused the Republicans of ``trying to snatch defeat
from the jaws of victory'' by moving to cut off funding just at
NATO forces are about to move in and prepare the way for Kosovar
refugees to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., who led the effort to strike the Kosovo
language from the defense bill, told his Republican colleagues that
``Congress would be the laughingstock of the world'' if it voted to
cut off spending on Kosovo on the day that the peace agreement was
being implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Taylor, D-Miss., also cautioned his GOP colleagues to
be careful about labeling the peace agreement a defeat for NATO.
Recounting a recent visit with U.S. forces in the Balkans, Taylor
drew applause when he said that many of the troops he spoke with in
Bosnia and Macedonia believe that their involvement is critical to
preventing rape, murder and genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's don't give away the peace that they have won,'' he said.
``We stopped the horror in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also objected to efforts to cut off funding on
the day the peace agreement was taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible time to pull the plug,'' Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., told members. ``This is not the time to give signals of
uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pleas of fellow Republicans and Clinton's letter,
many Republicans continued to insist that Congress restrict funding
for Kosovo operations. In the end 142 of 223 Republican members of
the House voted against taking out the restrictive language on
funding.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how much the peacekeeping operation in Kosovo will
cost taxpayers. But Defense Secretary William Cohen said Thursday
that it could run up to $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
