<SLUG> BC-FILM-POWERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POWERS' STARTS OUT GROOVY, BABY, THEN GOES RIGHT DOWN THE TUBES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's interesting about the Austin Powers phenomenon is that it
represents a rare instance in which a movie franchise has been set
off by the popularity of a video. The 1997 original, after all,
only grossed $54 million theatrically (less than the advertising
budget of ``Armageddon'').
</P>
<P>
   But the video has been a huge success for the past two years,
the character and his tag lines (``Oh, behave!'' etc.) have seeped
into the culture, and the sequel, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me,'' is entering the summer movie wars with only slightly
less media hype than ``Episode 1.''
</P>
<P>
   It debuted last Sunday at the 25th Seattle International Film
Festival, and opens this weekend. It's very much a mixed bag: a
movie that starts off marvelously and promises to be much more than
the original, but then nosedives into what could be the greatest
celebration of bathroom humor in the history of movies.
</P>
<P>
   The story has superspy Powers (Mike Myers) once again battling
his nemesis, Dr. Evil (also Myers), who, from his headquarters in
Seattle's Space Needle, has traveled back in time to 1969 to steal
Powers' most valuable possession, his ``mojo'' (libido).
</P>
<P>
   Powers also has a time machine, so he goes back as well, and,
teaming up with a beautiful secret agent of the '60s named Felicity
Shagwell (Heather Graham), finds himself in and out of one absurd
situation after another, until he's finally battling his enemy on
the moon.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Austin'' is even more of a sendup of James Bond than its
predecessor, with specific references to ``You Only Live Twice,''
``Goldfinger,'' ``Dr. No,'' ``The Spy Who Loved Me'' and
practically every other Bond epic of the '60s and '70s _ complete
with a voluptuously brassy, John Barry-like score.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a succession of dance routines ripped off from
``Laugh-in'' (linking the various sequences), a lengthy in-movie
commercial for Starbucks Coffee, a pint-size Dr. Evil-clone named
``Mini-me,'' and a cameo by Tim Robbins as a harried U.S.
president.
</P>
<P>
   The first half is a riot. Both of Myers' characterizations are
charming and cute, the gags are witty and inventive, the
retro-idyllic vision of London in the Swinging '60s is affectionate
and clever, and we're set up to believe we're in for one heck of a
great time.
</P>
<P>
   But the moment Myers introduces his third character _ a Scottish
villain named Fat Bastard, who weighs a metric ton and is obsessed
with his own bowel movements _ ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me'' disintegrates into non-stop defecation jokes, epic anal-sex
routines and flatulence gags.
</P>
<P>
   Myers and director Jay Roach probably know what they're doing _
aiming their humor straight at all those 13-year-old boys who sent
the video through the roof. But the repulsive turn of events erased
all my good memories of the first half, and makes the movie hard to
recommend to a normal human being.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me. Directed by Jay Roach.
Written by Michael McCullers and Mike Myers. Cast: Mike Myers,
Heather Graham, Rob Lowe, Robert Wagner, Michael York. New Line
Cinema. 100 minutes. Rated PG-13 for bathroom humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
