<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL COALITION THWARTS ANC IN WESTERN CAPE PROVINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Despite winning the largest share
of the vote in the province surrounding Cape Town, the African
National Congress has been largely shut out of power there as two
traditionally white parties formed a coalition with a tiny
religious party.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of trade unions aligned with the governing party have
called the arrangement racist and have threatened to strike or
demonstrate against it. The coalition parties have responded that
the deal is perfectly normal and that the governing party's use of
union threats is anti-democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In the June 2 election, the ANC won 42 percent of the vote in
the Western Cape province, which is home to the national
Parliament, a tourist mecca and an important farming, fishing and
wine-making region.
</P>
<P>
   The New National Party won only 38 percent, but joined with the
Democratic Party, which got 12 percent, and the African Christian
Democratic Party, which got 3 percent, for a total of 53 percent.
The coalition controls 23 of the 42 seats in the province's
parliament and will presumably return Gerald Morkel, provincial
head of the New National Party, to his post as premier.
</P>
<P>
   In the first post-apartheid elections of 1994, the National
Party had 54 percent of the province and ruled without partners.
</P>
<P>
   The tripartite coalition offered to let the African National
Congress join, but would only give it one Cabinet seat, that in
charge of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrahim Rasool, provincial head of the governing party, said,
``We have expressed ourselves as deeply insulted by that offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ehremreich, local branch leader of the Congress of South
African Trade Unions, a labor group that has traditionally
supported the governing party, said, ``When the white parties gang
up to exclude the black parties and the working man, then we're
going to demonstrate our dissatisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The union said unspecified ``mass actions'' might begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Party was once the whites-only party that
created apartheid, it now bridles at the ``white'' label. Its
biggest support base in the Cape is among mixed-race people
classified here as ``colored,'' and Morkel and his No. 2, Peter
Marais, are colored.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Democratic Party, Helen Zille, said the ANC had
been perfectly free to cut its own deal to form a majority
coalition but had been unable to do so. But other leaders of her
party had said even before the election that they would do nothing
to help the governing party increase its power.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC won nearly two-thirds of the national vote, and seven of
the country's nine provinces. In KwaZulu/Natal, the only other
province it lost, it appears to be on its way to forming a
coalition with the Inkatha Freedom Party to dominate the provincial
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northern Cape province, where the National Party was also
once powerful, the ANC won 63 percent of the vote to the National
Party's 26 percent. Thursday, it refused to offer the New National
Party a single seat in the Cabinet. There was suspicion that it
made the move in response to the shutout in the Western Cape,
though the governing party denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick van Zyl Slabbert, an independent political
commentator, said democracies usually allow minority parties the
freedom to band together and outvote the largest party, but he
suggested it might backfire here, since the ANC controls the
central government purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, it will lead to more tension in the Cape,''
he said, ``and I find that depressing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
