<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DNA-SHAPE-BOS &LR;      06-10 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-SHAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM FINDS THAT CURLED DNA PLAYS KEY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston scientists have solved a mystery they created 20 years
ago when they found an odd, reverse-twisting form of DNA, raising a
question that has bedeviled them since: Does it have a purpose in
nature?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they now say confidently.
</P>
<P>
   In a discovery hailed by other DNA experts, a Massachusetts
Institute of Technology group reports in the journal Science that
leftward-coiling DNA is an important part of cells' repertoire for
making proteins that all organisms need to keep humming along
smoothly. Conventional DNA curls rightward in the famous
double-helix curve that resembles a graceful spiral staircase.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery may open new vistas in biotechnology, some said,
by giving researchers new ways to manipulate DNA, the master
molecule that encodes the genetic instructions for an entire
organism. For instance, scientists said, it might lead to ways to
deactivate cancer-promoting genes, switch on cellular repair
mechanisms, or diagnose genetic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The unconventional DNA also appears to be a part of a key
evolutionary mechanism that gives rise to small changes in the
protein code, tiny modifications that sometimes confer a survival
advantage. ``It enormously broadens the way an organism can work,''
said professor Alexander Rich, who led the MIT team.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a change in only one amino acid in the protein
receptor for serotonin _ the brain hormone that the drug Prozac
enhances _ results in a weaker receptor, a state Rich dubbed
``serotonin lite.'' Having the ability to make both normal-strength
serotonin receptors and weaker ones enables the brain to modulate,
or fine-tune, serotonin effects as it needs to.
</P>
<P>
   The backwards-twisting DNA appears to facilitate this
fine-tuning by flagging genes that are switched on, early in the
process of transcribing the code from DNA to RNA, the template for
protein assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sort of beacon saying, `I'm on. I'm transcribing,' ''
Rich said of the DNA variant, which he called Z-DNA in 1979 because
it has a zig-zag backbone of sugar and phosphate molecules, in
contrast to the smooth spiral that DNA usually displays.
</P>
<P>
   Rich and his colleagues have discovered a region within Z-DNA
that is a strong chemical magnet for a particular ``editing
enzyme.'' This enzyme must do its work during a brief window of
time when the double strands of DNA are being ``unzipped'' so that
one of the strands can serve as a template for the RNA that carries
out the next step of protein synthesis.
</P>
<P>
   When the RNA editing is complete, Z-DNA snaps back to DNA's
conventional, right-handed conformation, called B-DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Because timing is critical, Rich believes nature ``invented''
Z-DNA, with its strong affinity for certain enzymes, to ensure that
molecular editing occurs when it's supposed to. But he said this
``targeting'' function for Z-DNA is a working hypothesis that will
require further studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this hypothesis very much,'' commented Maxim
Frank-Kamenetskii, a specialist in DNA structure at Boston
University. ``We know there are so many proteins involved in
regulation and transcription and editing, but we don't know how it
happens that they are located in the correct place. This is a very
interesting idea of how it may happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Research suggests that each gene among the 100,000 or so in
humans probably has at least one site structured so a portion of
its DNA can flip into the Z-DNA form _ another hint that the odd
form serves biological purposes. There may be many more
Z-DNA-forming sites, perhaps 580,000 or more, in the DNA of each
cell.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT scientists grew crystals of a stretch of Z-DNA tightly
bound to the editing enzyme, called RNA adenosine deaminase. This
enabled them to take X-ray photographs that unmasked the molecular
structure of this critical ``binding site.''
</P>
<P>
   These pictures constitute ``good evidence that there is a real
biological function for Z-DNA in the living cell,'' said professor
Richard R. Sinden, a specialist in DNA structure at Texas A&AMP;M
University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the new Z-DNA findings, coupled with other recent
discoveries about the various forms DNA can take, are expanding
scientists' ideas about how DNA encodes crucial information.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years we have thought of DNA as sort of a repository
of genetic information, like a computer hard disk,'' Sinden said.
``But in addition to the genetic code, DNA contains a lot of
information in its structure that is used biologically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
