<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS TRIES ON NEW SHADE OF BLUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't supposed to be like this for Eric
Karros, who sits in the Los Angeles Dodgers dugout and fantasizes
what it should be like in the fickle business in which he draws a
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   He peers out to the pitcher's mound, and can see Pedro Martinez
overpowering batters with a dominance not seen by anybody wearing a
Dodger uniform since Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   He looks over to the batter's box, and can see Mike Piazza
putting up hitting numbers for the Dodgers unmatched by any catcher
in all the seasons of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He hears the usual speculation about his being dealt even though
he's been one of the most reliable Dodger batsmen of the decade,
and accepts it with a calm resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no control over what happens in this game,'' he says
softly. ``I never thought they'd trade Mike (Piazza), but they did.
The same with Pedro (Martinez).
</P>
<P>
   ``We all came up together, and it would have been nice to have
stayed together. But this is a game of sudden change, unexpected
change. I don't worry one bit about being traded. If it happens, it
happens. You just have to learn to live with it...''
</P>
<P>
   His voice tails off, and his eyes drift out to the Dodger
Stadium outfield where the fences, once barren, are now covered
with pictures of people like Maury Wills and Duke Snider and Jackie
Robinson and Pee Wee Reese and advertisements for Bud Light and
Pacific Bell and Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   He looks around the field, and sees teammates named Onan Masoka,
Doug Bochtler, Jamie Arnold, Chance Sanford, Angel Pena and others
he knows only faintly go through their pre-game warmups.
</P>
<P>
   At a mere 31, Eric Karros is the Dodgers' elder statesman in
point of service on a team of strangers, a leftover memento from
the Peter O'Malley-Tom Lasorda-Fred Claire Dodger regime that
didn't stick ornaments on the outfield fences and didn't tamper
with the uniforms and didn't fill the stadium with crummy music and
didn't spend millions on free agent pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Karros is off to his traditional slow-motion start, and so is
his team that finds itself several games behind the Arizona
Diamondbacks and San Francisco Giants in the N.L. West Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never left this many base runners in scoring position,''
says Karros, always proficient at driving in runs during his
previous seven seasons with the Dodgers. ``But you go through
periods like that in this game. Things tend to even themselves out
over a whole season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to come a time when I'll start driving in runs
again. It'll happen. It always has in the past. I'm not concerned
about it. But it's frustrating for me right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros also doesn't seem that concerned about his team even
though its hitters and pitchers have been inconsistent and its
defense has been similarly erratic highlighted by catcher Todd
Hundley's unique knack of turning every runner into a base-stealing
wizard.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it that we've been struggling,'' he says. ``But
you look at the standings, and we're only a few games behind the
other teams. It's not like we're 10, 12 behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make up ground in no time. If this were July, or
August, I'd start getting concerned. But it's only June. It's too
early yet. We still haven't put together a decent winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team in baseball even the worst ones win seven, eight,
nine games in a row. And our turn will come. We just haven't put it
all together yet. But we will. It will happen. There's no reason to
panic this early.''
</P>
<P>
   It is all so different now for Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago that he and Mike Piazza shared a
bachelor pad at Manhattan Beach, and they were inseparables who
spent their evenings chasing pitchers out of games and ladies in
the nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Piazza would be cut loose by the Dodgers last summer,
and Eric Karros would forfeit his single status last November by
getting married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things change nothing in this world stays the same,'' says
Karros. ``I never dreamed that Mike Piazza would be gone from this
team before me. You just have to expect the unexpected in this
game. That's the nature of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't that bother you when your name keeps surfacing in
trade rumors?'' I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros shakes his head slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even an issue with me,'' he says. ``Actually, the way
it came up this time was disappointing to me. We were in Cincinnati
a couple of weeks ago, and Peter Gammons (ESPN baseball analyst)
said that I had missed three games because of knee problems and
that the Dodgers were trying to get rid of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear that, and it's a little upsetting because I haven't
missed a game this season because of injuries. But, honestly, all
that stuff just doesn't bother me that much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you ever think how it would have been with the Dodgers had
they kept Mike Piazza and Pedro Martinez?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   A wistful expression covers Eric Karros' face, as he gazes
forlornly out at the Dodger Stadium playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while,'' he says, and there is sadness in his voice.
``Oh yes, once in a while...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
