<SLUG> BC-FILM-BESIEGED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BESIEGED' SPEAKS VOLUMES WITH FEW WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Words aren't a big part of ``Besieged,'' Italian director
Bernardo Bertolucci's exquisite, intimate and fragile drama, so
it's hard to find the right way to explain this rich and sumptuous
piece of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a regular run Friday after successful screenings in the
Seattle International Film Festival, the film is from a script he
wrote with his wife, Clare Peploe.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci is masterful when it comes to making character-driven
films with artistic and political overtones _ ``The Conformist,''
``La Luna'' and ``Stealing Beauty'' are extraordinary,
well-composed works, but he stumbles with works made purely for
epic David Lean-esque glory, such as ``The Last Emperor'' and
``Little Buddha.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged,'' which reportedly began as a TV project, is a
quiet, lean actor's piece, with a delicate interwoven structure
that will either sweep you up or elude you.
</P>
<P>
   Thandie Newton plays Shandurai, a young African woman who moves
to Rome to study medicine after her husband is abducted for
unexplained _ but most certainly liberal political _ beliefs. She
takes lodging in the home of a quiet, loner pianist, Mr. Kinsky
(David Thewlis), who gives her board in exchange for housecleaning
and small jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He also falls in love with her. And after Kinsky
uncharacteristically reveals his feelings, the film takes an
extraordinary turn, with a series of events so elemental, human and
moving they seem small.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, an exceptional actress who has graced John Duigan's
films (``The Journey of August King,'' ``Flirting'') and who
managed to make a little something out of an incomprehensible role
in last year's ``Beloved,'' is breathtaking in her ability to
reveal vulnerability through body language.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Thewlis has never been more restrained and
accessible and he and Newton show us what the craft of acting is
about. The pair work like finely oiled clockwork and emit such a
daring depth of emotion in their looks and silences that we can't
foresee what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci lets the actors take command in this play of the
heart and what emerges is a study from a master filmmaker who is
back in form. He merges a love of letting visual elements tell a
story and reveal character with a talented cast. He _ and they _
make the final, unspoken moments all the more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Besieged. Directed by Bernardo Bertolucci. Written by
Bertolucci, Clare Peploe. Cast: Thandie Newton, David Thewlis. Fine
Line Features. 93 minutes. Rated R for nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
