<SLUG> BC-FILM-TWICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWICE UPON A YESTERDAY' SHOWS LOVE IS NEVER AS EASY AS WE HOPE IT
WILL BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be easy _ but unfair _ to compare ``Twice Upon a
Yesterday'' with Peter Howitt's 1998 romantic drama ``Sliding
Doors.'' Both are about the coincidence of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Sliding Doors'' was chock full of English trendiness and
its limited appeal depended upon whether audiences could engage
with an earnest and overly ingratiating tone as well as a tidily
stacked deck of a plot.
</P>
<P>
   Director Maria Ripoll has imbued her movie with the reality,
messiness, clutter and the chaos of an ethno-urban London life.
She's even given us a flawed and flailing protagonist in Victor
(Douglas Henshall), who is, of all things, an unemployed actor. As
the film opens, he's also a cad _ cheating on his seven-year,
live-in girlfriend Sylvia (Lena Headey).
</P>
<P>
   When Sylvia learns about his indiscretions, she moves out. And
Victor spends the next few months desperately trying to woo her
back. But Sylvia's moved onto something else; she's dating Dave, a
fellow who was seeing her best friend but with whom she sparked
when she met him again at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Victor embarks on a lonely life of drunken binges and painful
reminiscences. But what if Sylvia wasn't the true love that he
thought?
</P>
<P>
   One night, Victor, after stumbling through the rain-soaked
streets, meets two mysterious Spaniards who offer him a drink _ as
well as a surreal window into another plane of consciousness. It's
one that will provide him with a view into how life with Sylvia
might have turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel worlds collide and soon the tables are turned on both
Victor and Sylvia, proving love is never as easy as we hope it will
be.
</P>
<P>
   Henshall has a frenetic, chaotic appeal that gives Victor an
emotional vulnerability usually relegated to female characters. Yet
he's equally a slob _ destined to muddle through his life until
women take charge and give him a reason to exist. Victor doesn't
come into his own until he learns to take responsibility for his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'' thankfully doesn't apologize for its
fairy-tale sensibility and its foray into ``magic realism.''
Although it's sometimes difficult to engage with a character as
clueless as Victor, the women _ played by Headey and Penelope Cruz
_ are effective and ground the movie when he threatens to become
too manic and tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Twice Upon A Yesterday. Directed by Maria Ripoll. Written by
Rafa Russo. Cast: Douglas Henshall, Lena Headey, Penelope Cruz,
Elizabeth McGovern. Trimark. 96 minutes. Rated R for nudity,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
