<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-PALESTINIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING HIGHLIGHTS LEBANON'S PALESTINIAN `PROBLEM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDON, Lebanon _ No one yet knows exactly who fired Kalashnikov
rifles into a courtroom here two days ago in a massacre that killed
the chief judge and three other court officials. But the attack has
focused attention on a problem that Lebanon has long done its best
to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   A large and angry population of Palestinian refugees now numbers
more than 300,000, most living in camps _ like Ain Hilwe, just
outside Sidon _ that are ruled by armed militias. It was to Ain
Hilwe that the gunmen are believed to have fled. But like all the
camps, Ain Hilwe is a place where the Lebanese police and soldiers
do not dare to go.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of Lebanese troops were rushed to Sidon, and the
authorities have vowed to track the culprits down. But so far the
soldiers have kept a wary distance from Ain Hilwe, whose squalor
and violence is emblematic of a problem that Lebanese officials
clearly wish would go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lebanese forces went into that camp, there would be a
battle,'' one official said Thursday. ``The Palestinians have
always been a headache, but now it may be getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever before the attack, rivalries within the camps set off a
wave of internal Palestinian violence, and Lebanese officials say
some of the violence may now be directed at the Lebanese state.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have always insisted that the Palestinian
presence here is temporary, saying the Palestinians must be allowed
to return to lands they fled in 1948. But nearly all of the 125,000
or so Palestinians who fled to Lebanon at that time came from what
is now northern Israel, making it very unlikely that they or their
descendants will ever gain the right to go home.
</P>
<P>
   But with peace talks expected to resume soon between the Arabs
and Israelis, and the security setback in Sidon, Lebanon appears
ready to redouble its case. President Emile Lahoud has told recent
visitors that his government will press hard for the right of the
Palestinians to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see this as their last, faint chance to get rid of what
they see as a potential time bomb,'' a Western diplomat said of
Lebanon and its Palestinian population.
</P>
<P>
   A peace accord that does not give the Palestinians the right to
return would leave Lebanon to accommodate a fast-growing
Palestinian population that already accounts for about 8 percent of
Lebanon's residents _ something that Lebanese officials say would
upset a delicate internal political balance.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have long caused problems for Lebanon. In one of
the worst incidents, cross-border attacks on Israel by Palestinian
militias prompted the Israeli invasion of 1982, whose legacy
remains the Israeli-occupied border zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Though that invasion drove away Yasser Arafat and the guerrilla
fighters of his Palestine Liberation Organization, other combatants
stayed behind. Groups like the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine remain armed and active inside Ain Hilwe and other camps.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's response has been intentional neglect. Because most of
the militias oppose both Arafat and peace with Israel, Lebanon has
made no effort to rein them in, seeing them as instruments of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But because it does not want to encourage a permanent
Palestinian presence, Lebanon has refused to allow the refugees
citizenship, the right to work or even access to government
services. That has contributed to poverty, despair and the wave of
violence around Sidon, including shootings, car bombings and other
attacks that in the last 14 months have been directed against
several Palestinian factions and have claimed six lives.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's attack, by far the most serious, was the most brazen
against the Lebanese authorities since the end of the 1975-91 civil
war. Among those killed when the two gunmen broke ground-floor
windows and sprayed the courtroom with bullets were the chief
judge, the prosecutor and two court officials; five other people
were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind at the scene were not only the Kalashnikovs but also
a rocket-propelled grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Since the culprits have not been identified as Palestinians,
Lebanese politicians have been careful not point fingers. But the
reports that the gunmen had taken refuge in Ain Hilwe have prompted
Lebanese politicians to warn of the dangers posed by what are
described as ``islands outside the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no areas outside the law in Lebanon under the
pretext of just causes, including the Palestinian cause,'' Shaker
Abu Suleiman, a prominent member of Parliament, told reporters in
Beirut. ``The authorities should chase the criminals to any hiding
place they might take.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the attack, the court was on the verge of handing
down verdicts and sentences in eight cases involving charges of
murder, drug smuggling, forgery, robbery and sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, four Palestinians and four Lebanese, were in the
courtroom, but no attempt was made to free them, and Lebanese
officials said Thursday that they regarded the attack as a
political statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an organized act of terrorism,'' said the state
prosecutor, Adnan Addoum. ``One can only conclude that the goal was
to kill the judges and nothing else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
