<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICIAL SENTENCED IN CHINA'S LATEST CRACKDOWN ON DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A businessman and former government planner who
distributed a pro-democracy manifesto last year was sentenced
Thursday to four years in prison, the latest in a series of harsh
steps taken against dissidents in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Fang Jue, 44, was convicted here of illegal
business activities, on charges that he and his relatives insisted
were trumped up. He has been jailed since July.
</P>
<P>
   Months before then, he had distributed to foreign journalists a
long paper that called for political change that he said reflected
the secret thinking of many younger Communist Party members.
</P>
<P>
   Fang was not allowed to speak at a brief hearing but shouted,
``This trial was illegal!'' before being led out, his sister Liu
Jing told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a factory worker who founded the Hebei Province branch
of the outlawed China Democracy Party, Yu Feng, 37, was arrested on
suspicion of ``subverting state power,'' according to the
Information Center for Human Rights and Democratic Movement, based
in Hong Kong. That is a serious charge that was used last year to
give out long sentences to the most prominent party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, three other democracy advocates have received
prison terms ranging from three to four years on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   In late May. a democratic party member from the southern
province of Guangxi, Li Zhiyou, was sentenced to three years. He
was arrested in December after he having tried to protest the
11-year sentence given to a party founder.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, Liu Lixian of Beijing received a four-year sentence
for subversion. He had tried to publish a book of the writings of
two leading dissidents and democratic party leaders, Xu Wenli and
Qin Yongmin, who themselves were given sentences of 13 and 12 years
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On May 27, Zhang Youju, a democratic party member in the central
province of Hebei, was sentenced to four years. He was arrested
last fall after having posted fliers that called for the government
to reassess its violent suppression of the democracy demonstrations
at Tiananmen Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   An additional three democratic party members in the northern
province of Gansu were tried on subversion charges May 28 and are
awaiting sentences, and other activists around the country are in
detention and awaiting possible charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SILICON-PIRATES-$A     06-10 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SILICON-PIRATES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST WILD AND CRAZY GEEKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way TNT's film ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' tells it, the
story of the computer revolution as we know it begins with Steve
Jobs and Steve Wozniak running in slow motion through tear gas
during a student protest on the Berkeley campus in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a chronology that TNT has sent out with publicity
releases about the film notes that Job and Wozniak didn't meet
until 1973, when they were both employees of Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   But then the film doesn't claim to be a documentary _ or even a
docudrama. In it, the real-life events and real characters involved
in the early days of the computer age are given the star treatment
(as heroes or villains, depending on your perspective). The script
also goes beyond the office wars and gets personal about its
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The young Bill Gates is shown as a particularly ardent fan of
Playboy magazine, a devotee of strip clubs and the kind of guy who
actually says to a beautiful young woman he has just met, ``You
must have really great bandwidth.'' Gates is also shown singing
``My Way'' to himself as he drives.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs is portrayed as considerably more colorful. In his youth he
is seen as a happy drug user (the kind of guy who will trip on LSD
alone if none of his other friends want to join him) who seeks
truth in 1970s ways (``Like it's gone, the anger's gone,'' he tells
his therapy group) and eats fruit because it ``makes the soul
pure.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the film, when his computer company, Apple, has grown
huge, he is shown barging into a job interview conducted by one of
his employees, putting his bare feet up on the conference-room desk
and asking the job candidate if he's a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   The film also shows the young man who invented DOS selling it to
Bill Gates's representative for $50,000 (a figure disputed by some
computer historians) _ and being thrilled about the deal. And it
specializes in quotes, like the ones below, that sum up a lot:
</P>
<P>
   ``What on earth would ordinary people want with computers?'' (A
Hewlett-Packard executive to a young Steve Jobs.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The profits are in the computers themselves. Not this software
stuff.'' (An IBM executive to a young Bill Gates.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't just business. This is practically spiritual. This
is about overthrowing dead culture, dead gods.'' (Jobs, still
running his fledgling company from his parents' garage, to a man
offering him $250,000 in venture capital.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was practically like being a rock star or something.''
(Steve Wozniak in voice-over, describing the experience of manning
the Apple booth at an early computer trade show.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they say in the Mafia? Keep your friends close _
and your enemies closer.'' (Gates to his right-hand man.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the loot, Steve. And you're yelling `That's not fair! I
want to try to steal it first!' You're too late.'' (Gates to Jobs,
near the end.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
