A0909 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REAL-SPI &LR;      06-10 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE PREPARED FOR SOME TWISTS AND DETOURS IN `GET REAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This surprisingly anarchic English film is a rarity in that it
successfully makes the leap from stage (it's adapted from the play
``What's Wrong With Angry?'') to screen with agility and grace.
</P>
<P>
   And though it rides the heels of the recent coming of age/coming
out film, ``Edge of Seventeen,'' it tackles more topics than the
anguish and joy of being gay.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is an entire group of high schoolers who help
make ``Get Real'' so palpable and engaging. In the center of the
story is Steven Carter (Ben Silverstone), a journalism major who is
always picked on by the athletes in the school because he hangs out
with the girls and is a whiz in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Steven's secret is he's gay. And when he and the most unlikely
candidate for a boyfriend _ handsome, magnetic John Dixon (Brad
Gorton) _ embark on a secret ``relationship,'' chaos ensues.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this sounds predictable and routine _ the high school
hunk meets the intellectual outcast _ be prepared for a bit of a
twist. While it follows the road map when it comes to the teenage
angst formula, ``Get Real'' also takes some detours.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it look at Steven's plight, it actually gives
insight into the other side _ the difficulty of being a big fish in
a small pond. ``It's hard to be me,'' says John, and indeed, it is.
He's far less certain of himself than Steven; in fact, he's so
confused he has to keep up appearances in order to be accepted by
the sorry bunch of jocks who idealize him.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Steven and his gang have more freedom, more sense of
direction and a better defined place in the world than the guy who
has yet to discover who he is. In fact, the film hints that if John
doesn't come to grips with his sexuality, he may turn out to be one
of those high school wonders who fades into oblivion after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a nice touch about journalistic censorship that
parallels nicely with Steven's plight. But best of all, ``Get
Real'' is about diversity _ whether straight or gay _ and it
celebrates the idea that the world is indeed made up of many
different types of people.
</P>
<P>
   While recent _ and old (think ``Grease'') _ high school romantic
comedies often force a character to change in order to be accepted,
``Get Real'' does get real: it allows its kids to be themselves and
to simply ``be'' without judgment. That's an empowering enough
message for any movie.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Get Real. Directed by Simon Shore. Written by Patrick Wilde.
Cast: Ben Silverstone, Brad Gorton, Charlotte Brittain. Paramount
Classics. 108 minutes. Rated R for sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
