A0912 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FUTURE-900&AMP;ADD     06-10 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FUTURE-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS ENVISION A KOSOVO `WALLED OFF' FROM YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Although the political future of Kosovo is
left vague in the settlement that ended the war, American and NATO
officials say they envision an international protectorate that will
in theory be part of Yugoslavia but that may well, after a few
years, become independent.
</P>
<P>
   As refugees return and society is rebuilt, a senior NATO
official said Thursday, Kosovo will become virtually ``walled off''
from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   People living in Kosovo would not serve in the Yugoslav army or
pay taxes to Yugoslavia; a new police and judiciary would have to
be created without Yugoslav influence; the currency would probably
be either the Deutsch Mark or the American dollar; and trade would
turn south and west toward Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro
instead of north to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   None of these points are spelled out in the settlement that
President Slobodan Milosevic signed. Indeed, in framing a political
solution to the war, the NATO allies have been careful to state
that Kosovo will remain within Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on keeping the territorial integrity of Yugoslavia
and not allowing Kosovo to break away immediately was an essential
ingredient for winning the agreement of Milosevic and the Russians
to a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   But the resolution passed by the U.N. Security Council on
Thursday includes the phrase ``taking full account of the
Rambouillet accords,'' a signal that can be interpreted to infer
that down the road independence is a probability, Clinton
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Rambouillet accords _ which Milosevic refused to sign,
a move that led directly to the airstrikes _ the future status of
Kosovo was to be decided by calling an international conference in
about three years. The views of the conference, as well as the
``will of the people'' of Kosovo and an assessment of Serb views,
would determine the final status of the province, according to
those accords.
</P>
<P>
   The accords offered a detailed blueprint for an autonomous
Kosovo, including a 120-member parliament, election rules, an
independent judiciary, local government structures, a police force
and border security.
</P>
<P>
   As Kosovo becomes increasingly separated from Serbia, which is
the dominant republic in what is left of Yugoslavia, the likelihood
of Serbs having a significant say in the status of Kosovo will
diminish, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The physical reconstruction of Kosovo was addressed briefly
Thursday at a meeting here of the foreign ministers of the
so-called Group of 8 countries _ the richest industrial nations and
Russia _ who said they would soon organize a donors conference to
start raising the billions of dollars needed for the task.
</P>
<P>
   As well, the G8 announced a stability pact for Southeastern
Europe that is intended to help the poor economies of the region
that were made still poorer by the war. The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund would be called on for financing, the
G8 said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday that since the United States had
carried the cost of most of the military campaign, the cost of
rebuilding the burned homes, damaged roads and torched schools of
Kosovo would be borne mostly by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has requested $100 million in a supplemental
appropriations bill for Kosovo and the redevelopment of the
countries of southeastern Europe, but Congress is expected to
approve only a portion.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, is expected shortly to
announce his choice of special representative for Kosovo, a job
that will likely resemble that of a governor general.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the French foreign ministry, Anne
Gazeau-Secret, said Thursday that that her government had requested
that Annan appoint a European to the post. A European in charge of
Kosovo made the most sense, she said, because the bulk of the money
for reconstruction would come from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have said that despite doubts
about the efficiency of U.N. programs, they were resigned to the
United Nations taking overall responsibility for Kosovo, with the
European Union playing a major role as financier.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was a preferable choice as the dominant
player, Clinton administration officials said, because the United
States has influence there but not at the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization, the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, a 54 member trans-Atlantic body based in
Vienna, Austria, would also play a vital role in rebuilding Kosovo,
officials said. In particular, the OSCE would organize elections
for a time yet to be set and might assist in forming a new police
force.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, administration officials have been
careful not to flatly rule out independence for Kosovo, or
separation from Yugoslavia, even though European countries are more
fearful of the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has quietly held out the prospect because the
feasibility of independence is important as a way of trying to
encourage the Kosovo Liberation Army to lay down its arms.
</P>
<P>
   As a moral question, the possibility of independence is
important to the ethnic Albanian population, who before the war
outnumbered the Serbs by more than 90 percent. In all likelihood,
according to Balkans experts, much of the civilian Serb population
still left in Kosovo will probably go to Serbia proper, leaving the
province almost totally an ethnic-Albanian enclave.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Western Europe, the idea of an independent Kosovo or of a
Kosovo joined to Albania is more inconceivable than for the United
States, European diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   First, a breakaway Kosovo would set a precedent for other
separatist groups in Europe. Second, and less openly expressed, is
the fear that Kosovo, whose ethnic Albanian population is mostly
Muslim, could become an island of Islam in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As preparations get under way for Kosovo's reconstruction,
comparisons were being made Thursday to the efforts made in Bosnia
after the peace accord in 1995. There were many lessons to be
learned, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the reconstruction in Bosnia has been hampered
by poor management, competition among international agencies and
slow funding from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gazeau-Secret called the Bosnia experience a ``disaster''
which, she said, should not be repeated in Kosovo. The head of the
OSCE office in Bosnia, a former American ambassador, Robert Barry,
said that the Bosnia efforts had gone poorly. Funds pledged by the
European Union had been extremely slow to materialize, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at least in Bosnia, there were institutions, though not
very good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   One important difference was that almost as soon as the Dayton
peace accords were signed, Bosnia was admitted to the World Bank
and other international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo will not have such a luxury because its banks have been
part of the Yugoslav banking system and thus are banned, under
current sanctions, from international loans. Kosovo will no longer
be reliant on Serbia's banks or economy, a factor that will push it
further away from Serbia, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   A new court system and a police force would also have to be
created. ``There are no judges in Kosovo because they were all
Serbs,'' Barry said. ``What is to be done with people when they are
arrested? Who are they to be turned over to?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
