<SLUG> BC-SEMICONDUCTOR-LOSSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR CORP. REPORTS 5TH CONSECUTIVE QUARTERLY
LOSS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Me., Calif.)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The National Semiconductor Corp. reported its
fifth consecutive quarterly loss Thursday, but its results
essentially met analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's executives said National Semiconductor was on
track to return to profitability by its fiscal second quarter,
which ends in November. National said last month that it would exit
the personal computer microprocessor business, which has suffered
heavy losses amid the continuing price wars between the Intel Corp.
and Advanced Micro Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For its fiscal fourth quarter, which ended May 30, National
reported a loss of $783.5 million, or $4.65 a diluted share,
compared with a loss of $212.4 million, or $1.29 a share, in the
quarter a year earlier. Revenue fell 6 percent, to $477 million
from $510 million.
</P>
<P>
   The results include one-time charges of $688.4 million related
to the exit of the microprocessor business and sale of a plant in
Portland, Me., and $55.1 million related to inventory write-offs
and product returns. Excluding charges, the loss would have been
$40 million, or 24 cents a share, compared with $69.3 million, or
42 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The operating earnings matched analysts' estimates, according to
the First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the results were announced, shares of National
Semiconductor rose $1.8125, to $22.50, on the New York Stock
Exchange. The shares have rallied since the company announced last
month that it was leaving the PC microprocessor business, and
analysts say the company's non-PC businesses should sustain
profitable growth once the microprocessor unit is divested.
National paid $550 million to acquire the Cyrix Corp. in 1997 in
order to enter the business.
</P>
<P>
   Halla said that the company was seeing strong orders for analog
chips, which are used to process audio and video, and that its
strategy of producing so-called systems on a chip for the
information appliance market had begun to bear fruit, including an
order for chips to power a new device to be marketed by America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, National reported a loss of $1 billion, compared
with a loss of $98.6 million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
