<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FORCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ENTRY INTO KOSOVO TO BE DELAYED UNTIL SATURDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ NATO Thursday night scrubbed plans for a
dawn entry into Kosovo by British paratroopers on Friday,
suspending its peacekeeping operation for at least 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The British paratroopers were to have lifted off by helicopter
at 4 a.m. from the rapidly swelling military compound here as an
advance guard to secure the main highway running from the border to
Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital, but a Western official said
the deployment was likely to be delayed until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The paratroopers were to be swiftly followed by other British
soldiers as the lead element of the multinational peacekeeping
force intended to end the 11-week-old war in which Serbian forces
hounded more than a million members of the Kosovar Albanian
majority from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which had been kept secret, was quietly canceled
Thursday night, as was a technical and logistical briefing for
reporters that had been scheduled earlier in the day, at which NATO
officers had said they would outline the deployment of the various
forces, predominantly British, French, Italian and American at this
point, and their schedule for entering Kosovo behind the departing
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Thursday night that the delay was a result
of difficulty the Serbs were having in mounting their withdrawal. A
Western official who spoke on the condition of anonymity said the
Serbian withdrawal had been slowed by a fuel shortage and damaged
equipment as well as by land mines and a fear of moving out troops
at night when they might be vulnerable to the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian withdrawal is supposed to be completed within 11
days under the terms of the agreement signed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The force commander, British Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, promised
at a news conference Thursday night, that ``we shall be off
quickly,'' and that his troops would act in a manner ``both robust
and evenhanded.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about whether the peacekeepers would
aid investigators from the International War Crimes Tribunal in the
Hague and whether they would arrest war crimes suspects in their
territory, Jackson was vague on the subject of cooperation and
suggested that Bosnia, where major indicted suspects have roamed
free amid U.N. forces would be a model for his operation.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the peacekeepers face a daunting task. One immediate
fear, Jackson said, was mines and perhaps booby traps in areas the
Serbs are abandoning.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer run, what the peacekeepers must deal with is the
deep-seated hatred both ethnic groups feel toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Western peacekeeping efforts in Somalia, Haiti and
Rwanda, among other places, the soldiers heading for Kosovo will be
hobbled by their own goals: they want to ensure the safety of the
Albanians, but not give victory to the KLA, which commands
widespread loyalty among the displaced Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was very careful Thursday night to direct his remarks
about the ``evenhandedness'' of his troops at least as much at the
ascendant KLA fighters as against the departing Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence and noncompliance will not be tolerated,'' he said.
``We want a secure environment for the return of all refugees.
There will be peace and security to all the people of Kosovo. The
armed Kovoso groups, we will require them to demilitarize. We want
the people to have the confidence to return to a normal way of
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
