<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, June
11, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-AIR SHOW _ A bullish Airbus Industrie will have the home
field advantage. And this is the 30th anniversary of the launch at
the 1969 Paris Air Show of the A300, the first plane Airbus built
in what then appeared to be a Don Quixote-like quest to one day be
the equal of mighty Boeing in commercial aviation. So it's a no
brainer that Airbus will be out to make a big splash when the
world's biggest air show begins Saturday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   SLOTS-TRIBES (OLYMPIA, Wash.) _ The Washington state gambling
commission approves so-called cashless ``slot'' machines for Indian
casinos. The approval gives tribes the option of using the
machines, after they go through another commission review. When
it's all said and done, some tribes will be able to operate as many
as 1,500 machines.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Gavin. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GRADUATION-SPEAKER (OLYMPIA, Wash.) _ Gov. Gary Locke crumbled
at the first hint of pressure, but Evergreen College President Jane
Jervis continues to defend the right of a convicted cop killer to
address graduation ceremonies Friday. Everyone from U.S. House
Majority Leader Tom DeLay, R-Texas, to the Attorney General of
Pennsylvania to national police associations are condemning the
move. The source of the heat? Students at the very liberal liberal
arts college will hear a 13-minute taped speech at graduation
ceremonies Friday from Mumia Abu-Jamal, a former Black Panther
convicted of slaying a Philadelphia police officer in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Gavin. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VALEDICTORIAN (Undated) _ Nicole Sieminski is a normal
valedictorian in most respects _ overachiever, 4.0, aspiring
doctor. But the Marysville-Pilchuck High School senior is causing a
tremendous stir, not because of what she's done, but who she is _
the first member of the Tulalip Tribes to become a valedictorian.
Her success at the state's largest high school is a big honor for
the tribe, which has made education a huge priority in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   By Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-VIRUS (Seattle) _ Microsoft, GE, The New York Times and
hundreds of thousands of computer users around the world have been
hit by a polite but malicious virus. The virus, entitled
Worm.ExploreZip, hit Microsoft's computers last night, and forced
the company to shut down its e-mail servers throughout Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH (Undated) _ Tom Hirschfeld, venture
capitalist and father, has written a book especially for dads. It's
called ``Business Dad; How Good Businessmen Can Make Great Fathers
(and Vice Versa.) (Little Brown, 1999, $23.) Read as either a
business book or a parenting book, it has good advice for
navigating the sometimes chaotic world of work and family.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FATHERHOOD (Undated) _ The National Fatherhood Initiative of
Gaithersburg, Md., looked at 15 television series on five networks
last fall and decided that _ surprise! _ father rarely knows best.
</P>
<P>
   WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-PREDATORS (Undated) _ Unless you're a critic you don't have
to see this TBS Superstation movie, ``Silent Predators,'' because
you've already seen it. And you know how it ends. It is cinematic
schlock of the first order, featuring acting and writing so
pedestrian it could be arrested for jaywalking.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-POWERS (Undated) _ ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' is very much a mixed bag: a movie that starts off marvelously
and promises to be much more than the original, but then nosedives
into what could be the greatest celebration of bathroom humor in
the history of movies.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BESIEGE (Undated) _ Words aren't a big part of
``Besieged,'' Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci's exquisite,
intimate and fragile drama, so it's hard to find the right way to
explain this rich and sumptuous piece of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TWICE (Undated) _ In ``Twice Upon A Yesterday,'' Director
Maria Ripoll has imbued her movie with the reality, messiness,
clutter and the chaos of an ethno-urban London life. She's even
given us a flawed and flailing protagonist in Victor (Douglas
Henshall), who is, of all things, an unemployed actor.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REAL (Undated) _ ``Get Real,'' this surprisingly anarchic
English film, is a rarity in that it successfully makes the leap
from stage (it's adapted from the play ``What's Wrong With
Angry?'') to screen with agility and grace.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-HOMERS (Seattle) _ Feature on the Seattle Mariners'
home run pace.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
