<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-CONGRESS-BOS &LR;      06-10 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-CONGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SQUARE OFF OVER PEACEKEEPER FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To an outsider, the debate on the floor of the
House of Representatives might have seemed inconceivable: whether
the United States should block funding for peacekeeping troops in
Kosovo, just as months of NATO bombings were coming to an end with
a celebrated peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not about peace. It was not even, some members
conceded, simply about U.S. soldiers' lives or the federal budget.
It was politics, and as the debate lasted into the night _ with
frantic last-minute negotiations to avoid bringing the provision to
a vote _ House Republicans were clearly frustrated they had not
turned the Balkan conflict to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was timing, several congressional aides said. With
the vote coinciding precisely with the agreement in Belgrade,
Republicans found it difficult to criticize U.S. military strategy.
Many instead turned to questioning whether the Clinton
administration had actually won and when Congress could be asked to
pay for efforts to rebuild Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new and perhaps more troubling phase for our
country,'' said Representative Floyd Spence, a South Carolina
Republican who chairs the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is victory? Well, let the president call it whatever he
wants,'' said Representative William Goodling, a Pennsylvania
Republican on the House International Relations Committee. ``I call
it a total disaster. It's going to be billions and billions of
dollars for something we have no national security interest in. It
is a complete national security interest for Europe. And they sat
there and did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans had argued the provision to cut off funding for
peacekeeping troops was necessary because otherwise too much money
would be depleted from overall military funding.
</P>
<P>
   But their real intent was to oppose the Clinton administration,
members on both sides of the aisle said. The move would be
considered a routine partisan strategy on any other day, but it
could appear anti-patriotic on the heels of the administration's
military success.
</P>
<P>
   And so Thursday, after hours of behind-the-scenes negotiation
between House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, House Democrats and the
White House, a last-minute deal was struck. President Clinton
promised that the Kosovo effort would be paid for ``without harming
military readiness.'' That allowed Republicans to retreat from
their demand that the peacekeeping funding cutoff be included in
the $288.8 billion defense spending bill. In the end, the House
voted 270-155 to remove the provision from the bill, which was
expected to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans were embarrassed,'' said Representative Barney
Frank, a Newton Democrat. Explaining why the Republicans were
willing to reach an agreement, he added, ``Hastert is trying to
rehabilitate himself after his screw-up over airstrikes,''
referring to last month's House vote against supporting the U.S.
military effort.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry also said House Republicans had been on
the brink of making a ``very dangerous move with very serious
ramifications,'' saying it was ``incomprehensible that we'd fight a
war...and then just turn our backs on peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people really need to sort of stand back and take a
deep breath, and be very careful of trying to use politics here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate came a day after the House voted to end the U.S.
peacekeeping mission in Haiti, where troops have been installed for
nearly five years. In a 227-198 vote, the House approved pulling
U.S. forces out of Haiti by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it was clear that the debate over Kosovo is far from
over. Still to be resolved is the issue of helping rebuild the
Yugoslav province, as well as supplying economic aid to the entire
region. Many members, including Democrats, are urging Europe to
foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But only a few had hope that partisan politics would now be put
aside. Senator Jack Reed, a Rhode Island Democrat on the Senate
Armed Services Committee, said he hoped the victory in Kosovo had
``silenced those critics who were reflexively anti-Clinton and
viewed this...as a political opportunity to do damage to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, now, as we go forward, we can focus on the
substance rather than the politics,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2107EDT &QL; 
