<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINER-JUMBO-BOS &LR;      06-10 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINER-JUMBO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES PLAN SUPER JUMBO JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think Boeing's 747-400 _ with room for 416 passengers in three
classes and more than 550 in a domestic version used by Japan Air
Lines _ is a big airplane?
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   In 2004, Airbus plans to have the first flight of the A-3XX, a
double-decker airplane that that will seat between 550 and 650
passengers with three classes of service. It's wingspan will be 261
feet 10 inches _ nearly the length of a football field and 50 feet
longer than the 747s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also developing 747 models that might seat as many as
100 more people in three classes than the 747-400.
</P>
<P>
   These super jumbo jets or, in industry parlance, ``very large
transport'' are expected to meet the increasing demand for air
travel, especially in transoceanic, European-Asian and inter-Asian
routes.
</P>
<P>
   While the planes will be aerospace engineering marvels, they
will also create significant problems for everyone from passengers
to ramp service personnel, airport operators and emergency crews.
</P>
<P>
   And there is growing concern about the ability to evacuate the
airplanes in the 90 seconds required under federal law, especially
because the Federal Aviation Administration is considering a
regulation change that could do away with a live evacuation drill
and use instead computer simulations relying on data from previous
drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people you can cram into an aircraft, it means the
more people who will die if there is an accident,'' said
Christopher J. Witkowski, director of air safety and health for the
Association of Flight Attendants. ``If manufacturers can't meet the
current standard with a live drill, they should reduce the number
of seats on their airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials scoff at the suggestion that the plane will not
be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we believe computer simulated evacuation is the
safe way to go because pople are injured in the drills, but if
authorities decide otherwise, we would obviously concur,'' said
Mary Anne Greczyn, a spokeswoman for Airbus Industrie of North
America. ``If there were a safety question, we would not build the
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   In the closely regulated world of commercial aircraft
manufacturing, the number of seats that a plane may accomodate is
based on several criteria. First, the number of exit doors
determines roughly how many people may fit on an airplane. But
airlines and manufacturers have also had to demonstrate evacuation
procedures with a full drill by having a large number of volunteers
try to successfully leave the airplane within 90 seconds with dim
lighting and half of the exits blocked.
</P>
<P>
   While planes configured with first, business and economy class
sections hold fewer passengers than they are certified for,
replacing the drill with a computer analysis concerns some.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real problem when you get bigger and bigger,'' said
Paul Hudson, executive director of the Aviation Consumer Action
Project. ``The mathematical theory, the queuing theory, is that the
speed of the queue is governed by its slowest member. You don't
take average speed, which the computer model does. A line of 500
people will move much more slowly than fives times the speed of 100
people and the FAA is ignoring that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is about the evacuation of an airplane that size,''
said Hal Salfen, director of consumer affairs for the International
Airline Passanger Association. ``If there was an accident, they
would have an awful difficult time evacuating that many people.''
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokeswoman said the super jumbo jets are still too early
in their design phase to know whether special certification issues
would be required. But Airbus anticipates the A-3XX will receive
certification and enter service in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   That is not too soon for airports and firefighters to start
planning for the super jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Heathrow to JFK market, you have a lot of carriers
dispatching two 747s within three hours and they would put in one
larger aircraft if they had it,'' said Richard Marchi, senior vice
president for technical and environmental affairrs at Airports
Council International in North America. ``Now, we process 350
people each time over three hours, but if you have 600 people on
one flight it will increase the `peaking' at check-in and moving
people through the facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchi said huge planes would have no problem at new airports
like Denver, but operating restrictions would have to be placed? in
older airports, where tight gate space would create problems.
</P>
<P>
   The A-3XX is not expected to require a longer runway than a
Boeing 747-400, which can land at Logan. But the plane's 1.2
million pounds of weight will require airports to reinforce
taxiways, bridges and culverts that were built to withstand the
747-400, which weighs about 900,000 pounds, said Marchi.
</P>
<P>
   ACI estimated that airports will have to spend between $50
million and $100 million in upgrades to handle super jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   At Logan, in addition to trying to build a new runway, Massport
also wants to spend $35 million on a new centerfield taxiway to
supplement two taxiways so close to the terminals and each other,
that officials are concerned that wingtips of current jumbo jets
will strike other planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wingspans of the A-340, the 747-400 and the 777 do not
allow us to simultaneously taxi those airplanes on the inner and
outer taxiways,'' said Thomas Kinton, director of aviation for
Massport. ``The midfield taxiway will not give us seemless movement
around taxiways, but it does give the tower ability to get planes
in and out of the congested gate areas more easily.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we will have to worry about dealing with 600 or 700
victims in an accident, so we will have to step our emergency plan
and foucs on that,'' said Kinton.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft firefighting and rescue is a specialized field. Under
federal regulations, the longer the plane, the more equipment,
personnel and fire suppression material on hand. But with super
jumbo jets, it may not be enough, becuase the length of the planes
will not increase as much as their wingspan and interior size.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these larger planes coming out, additional technology
will have to evolve,'' said Gary Schott, chairman of the Aircraft
Rescue and Firefighting Working Group. ``They'll put severe
limitations on us because they will carry a lot more people and a
lot more fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   If traveling in close quarters with 600 other people seems
daunting to the most jaded traveler, consider baggage handlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loading and unloading of someting that size will impose a
tremendous burden on ramp service personnel,'' said James Sprang, a
spokesman for the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers. The planes will most likely require two loading
bridges for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, however, believes the turnaround time of the A-3XX will
be similar to that of a 747 and estimates future demand for air
travel will result in the need for some 1,300 new aircraft with
room for 400 or more passengers. As a result, it expects to spend
about $10 billion to develop the A-3XX to meet that need. The cost
of the plane is expected to be $213 million and up.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 airlines, including United and FedEx, have been invited
to work with Airbus in development of the A-3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is working on plans for new 747s with more capacity, but
it is not considering developing a new type of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that we don't believe there is a market for it,''
said Boeing Commercial Airplane spokesman Randolph C. Harrison.
``Some airlines would like to have it, but the issue is whether
there is enough of a market to make a business case for the
research and development costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing thinks the answer is no. One reason is the company sees
regulatory and technological changes doing for transpacific routes
what they did to transatlantic ones in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Open skies policies allowed more flights from the US to more
overseas cities, and regulations allowed two-engine aircraft to fly
over the Altantic _ and more recently the Pacific. As a result,
there has been rapid growth in flights from smaller East Coast
cities, like Pittsburgh, to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Jenkins, director of the Aviation Institute at the George
Washington University, says that putting 600 people on one plane
instead of 700 people on two will not necessarily save an airline
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible marketing risk in a plane that big,''
said Jenkins. ``It is much easier to market more frequent flights
with 200 seats than one flight with 600 seats. Smaller planes give
you more flexibility in routes and the off-season. If there is a
downturn, that plane will eat you up on cost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
