<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PRIORITY-GROUP-AR     06-10 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRIORITY-GROUP-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM OF ARMS BUDGET FROM UNUSUAL SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Iowa)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for BIZ-DEFENSE-ADS)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC QUINONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why must Bell Industries, a computer services company in El
Segundo, Calif., go all the way to India to hire programmers? The
company's co-chairman, Theodore Williams, thinks it's because
America doesn't have its priorities straight.
</P>
<P>
   Williams says his frustration at being unable to find enough
qualified Americans to fill his company's needs is why he backs
Business Leaders for Sensible Priorities, a group of business
people he helped found that is campaigning for fundamental change
in the way the government uses its resources.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Williams and other members of the group, the
shortage of programmers is symptomatic of an education system
starved of money and hurting American competitiveness while
billions of dollars are lavished on unproductive military spending.
</P>
<P>
   The group wants higher budgetary priority given to schools,
health care for children and other programs to insure America's
future economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was organized by an unabashed liberal activist, Ben
Cohen, co-founder of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, and has attracted
names that are decidedly not part of the business mainstream, like
Paul Newman and Ted Turner to its list of members, the group is
made up mostly of executives and business owners who hope their
practical business background will give them credibility with
lawmakers and voters.
</P>
<P>
   The group steers away from the usual ideological and partisan
camps. It does not ask its members about their party affiliations,
and in interviews several members maintained that eliminating waste
and encouraging wiser spending were goals that fit as well with a
conservative agenda as with a liberal one.
</P>
<P>
   ```Conservative' means prudence, and `conservative' means not
spending money indiscriminately without a return,'' said Arnold
Hiatt, chairman of the Stride Rite Foundation and one of the
group's founders. ``I think an awful lot of money is being spent,
particularly in the Defense Department, not for the right
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacifism isn't on the agenda either. ``We are in favor of a
strong military,'' said Bruce Klatsky, chairman and chief executive
of the Philips-Van Heusen Corp., a clothing and shoe manufacturer,
and another founder of the group. ``What we are against is the
waste in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's profile rose considerably when, late last year, it
began an advertising campaign arguing that, with the cold war over,
billions of dollars could safely be cut from nuclear weapons
programs and from new generations of fighter aircraft and attack
submarines meant to replace models that are already the world's
best.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing these views, the business group relies on several
military advisers, including Lawrence Korb, assistant defense
secretary under former President Ronald Reagan, and Paul C. Warnke,
who was former President Jimmy Carter's chief arms negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   The money thus saved can be spent on education, health and other
programs that Cohen and other members of the group argue will
provide the highest possible returns for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the group's message is anathema to the
military industry. The Pentagon spent $44 billion on weapons last
year, the least in more than a decade, said John W. Douglass,
president and chief executive of the Aerospace Industries
Association of America, in an interview. Overall, he said, arms
spending has fallen by 70 percent since the end of the cold war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to try to say that Americans have two choices, education
or Pentagon waste, is just an outrageous oversimplification and
unfair statement,'' Douglass said.
</P>
<P>
   The business leaders' group counters that military spending is
already on its way back up. Even before NATO began bombing
Yugoslavia in late March, the Clinton administration was asking
Congress for the biggest increase in military spending since the
1980s, an additional $112 billion over the next five years,
bringing the Pentagon budget up to $319 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're in a warlike state creates a climate for
larger budget increases and less examination of the wastefulness
that already exists,'' said Newman, in an interview conducted
before the Kosovo peace agreement was concluded late last week.
</P>
<P>
   The business leaders' group has grown from 5 members (Cohen,
Williams, Hiatt, Klatsky, and Alan Hassenfeld, chairman and chief
executive of Hasbro Inc.) in 1996 to 450 today.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ads, the group is using its money to pay for a
bus tour called ``U Slice the Pie.'' It began in April in
Washington and is to run through November, spending a lot of time
in Iowa, an early stop in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   At events like county fairs and church picnics, three young
actors present the group's message using huge inflatable displays
with statistics on budget allocations, military industry lobbying
and job creation. The bus itself is painted to look like piles of
cash. Some of the executives have spoken at the bus stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of federal budget priorities is kind of dry,'' said
Cohen. ``It's kind of off-putting to people. The object of the `U
Slice the Pie' performance is to make it fun and exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
