<SLUG> BC-BKN-HALLFAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE FORMER CELTICS NOMINATED FOR HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Celtic contingent in the Basketball Hall of Fame is about to
grow. The only unknown is by how many.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McHale, Dennis Johnson, and JoJo White were among 13
nominees for the Class of '99 to Springfield. McHale is a deadbolt
lock; they might as well commission the program piece. Johnson,
twice nominated before, and White, are less certain, although a
case can be made for both.
</P>
<P>
   Three other nominees also have Celtic ties: ex-Georgetown coach
John Thompson, who backed up Bill Russell for 74 games in the
mid-1960s, Wayne Embry, who played two seasons for the Celtics,
and, alas, Bob McAdoo, who was with Boston for one stormy stretch
(20 games) in 1978-79.
</P>
<P>
   Four other ex-NBA players were nominated: Maurice Cheeks, the
late Gus Johnson, Sidney Moncrief, and Chet Walker. Also nominated
were Mount St. Mary's coach Jim Phelan, whose 800-442 record gives
him more wins than any other active college coach; Tex Winter, an
assistant Chicago Bulls coach and proponent of the triangle offense
who has spent 52 seasons at Division 1 college and NBA teams _ more
than any active coach, and Morgan Wootten, the legendary coach at
DeMatha High School in Washington, D.C., whose record of 1,185-178
is the best ever for a high school coach.
</P>
<P>
   The inductees will be announced in 10 days. The enshrinement
ceremony is scheduled for Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' media guide lists 25 individuals in the Hall of
Fame with ties to the team, some as fleeting as McAdoo's. Pete
Maravich, for instance, played in just 26 games for the 1979-80
Celtics. Dave Bing spent one season with Boston. McHale will be No.
26.
</P>
<P>
   McHale spent his entire, 12-year career with the Celtics,
racking up numerous individual honors along with three championship
rings. He also was named as one of the top 50 players of all time
in the NBA's 50th anniversary season. His frontcourt teammate,
Larry Bird, was enshrined last year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson twice has been nominated (1995, '96) and fallen short.
He was never one for individual statistics, but he also owns three
title rings, one from Seattle (1979) and two with Boston (1984,
'86.) He was widely seen as one of the best defensive guards of his
time and was the consummate big-game player. Bird has referred to
him as ``the best teammate I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   White, also a two-time nominee, was a member of the 1974 and '76
Celtics title teams and also won a gold medal at the 1968 Olympics
at Mexico City. He spent 10 seasons with the Celtics before
finishing his career with less luminous stops in Golden State and
Kansas City. (He also returned in 1987 to play five games for the
CBA Topeka Sizzlers.)
</P>
<P>
   Thompson played 64 games for the 1964-65 champion Celtics and
stuck around for 10 games the following season. He retired from
Georgetown earlier this year, having made 14 straight NCAA
appearances and winning the title with Patrick Ewing in 1984. Embry
played two seasons for the Celtics, 1966-68, getting a ring with
the 1967-68 team. He was then taken by Milwaukee in the expansion
draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
