<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ORDERS HALT TO BOMBING OF YUGOSLAVIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO suspended its 11-week bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia on Thursday after Serb troops began to withdraw
from Kosovo. An international force that will oversee the return of
refugees as well as police the province, possibly for years, could
begin to move in Friday, the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   As armed units of President Slobodan Milosevic's army and police
moved in convoys north toward Serbia, the North Atlantic Council,
NATO's political arm, accepted that the pullout was genuine, and
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana ordered a halt to the
airstrikes that began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, backed by President Clinton and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, warned that the bombing would resume if the Serbs
backslide on the 11-day withdrawal plan. When challenged on whether
the 19-member alliance had the will to renew air attacks, Solana
said: ``I will speak the answer in a monosyllable: Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council quickly approved a resolution
mandating the international force that will sweep into Kosovo
behind the departing Yugoslav troops. The North Atlantic Council,
made up of an ambassador from each NATO nation, stood ready at
alliance headquarters here in the Belgian capital to issue the
activation order for the occupation force from Macedonia to cross
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time since the breakup of the former
Yugoslavia began in 1991 that a U.N.-backed force has been
dispatched to the Balkans to mop up a geopolitical mess created by
Milosevic's nationalistic reaching. A similar force remains in
Bosnia-Herzegovina in a bid to stabilize a shaky peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The multinational force is expected to eventually number more
than 50,000, including 7,000 U.S. troops. The final deployment
count will depend on how many, if any, troops are contributed by
Russia. Talks continued Thursday in Moscow on working into the
operation Russian forces, who refuse to be under direct NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
   The international force will establish a headquarters at the
provincial capital, Pristina, and begin to prepare for the return
of many of the almost 1 million ethnic Albanians who fled or were
driven away from Kosovo by Milosevic's troops over the past 15
months. More than 800,000 of the departures came during the NATO
bombing campaign. Another 500,000 are counted as displaced persons
still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The international force also will be guarding against outbreaks
by rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army. Solana warned that
``violence or noncompliance by any party will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   To signify Clinton administration reluctance that the United
States lead another peacekeeping force in Europe, British and
French troops will be at the head of the deployment. A British
officer, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, will command the force, and NATO
announced Thursday his deputy will be a French general, Jean-Claude
Thomann.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the U.S. forces, an armored contingent, will follow
quickly. Under the NATO command plan, U.S. forces will be primarily
in southeastern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of NATO nations acknowledged that they face a daunting
task to rebuild Kosovo, which has been shattered by Serb forces and
pummeled by the NATO bombardment, and to deal with the perpetual
threat to regional stability posed by Milosevic. But they expressed
confidence in the correctness of their aggressive course and relief
that the alliance's first-ever operation against a sovereign nation
had succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``War can be necessary sometimes to uphold civilization, and
this was one,'' Blair told a news conference in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a chance to replace violence with peace,''
President Clinton said at the White House. ``We now have a moment
of hope. We have to finish this job and build a peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Union is intent on a Balkans-wide rebuilding
campaign likely to cost between $20 billion and $100 billion. A
donor conference will be called soon, but the EU has ruled out
helping the Serbian section of Yugoslavia, which includes the
capital Belgrade, as long as Milosevic is in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot expect democracies to prop up dictatorships,''
Blair said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, in an address on Serb television, was neither defiant
nor contrite. He sidestepped details of how the NATO bombing has
savaged his nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are the heroes,'' Milosevic said. ``We survived and
defended the country. I wish all citizens of Yugoslavia much joy
and success in the reconstruction of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Official Yugoslav notice that the pullout was under way came
from Nebojsa Vujovic, deputy foreign minister, who said: ``Units of
the Yugoslav army and police started their withdrawal in absolute
order, implementing a very accurate, precise mechanism for
withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first departures was a 100-vehicle convoy, with about
2,000 Serb troops, that drove out of Kosovo at Merdare, about 20
miles north of Pristina. It was followed by about 20 cars filled
with ethnic Serbs fleeing Kosovo because of uncertainty about what
they face at the hands of returning ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO had its own technical means of verifying that the
military withdrawal had begun, the way to calling off the air
attacks was eased by the unblinking coverage of cable news
channels, including live broadcasts of a Yugoslav military convoy
moving north out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the North Atlantic Council was about to suspend the bombing,
a western diplomat said it was ``certification by CNN,'' and even
Solana mentioned the U.S.-owned outlet in briefing reporters about
the council's action.
</P>
<P>
   The multinational force will be only the latest in a long line
of foreign occupiers in the Balkans, a list that over the last half
dozen centuries has includes the Ottomans, Hapsburgs and Nazi
Germans. Each has paid at least lip service to the desire to create
a civil society.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. resolution establishes a civil authority, and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan will appoint the chief administrator.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, only the force of Marshal Tito's guile, will
and secret police held together the region's fiery ethnic brew that
most basically divides along religious lines _ Muslims left from
the Ottoman occupation and the Christianity of more indigenous
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic in his television address stressed that ``we have not
given up Kosovo.'' The peace proposal he rejected before the NATO
bombing campaign called for an independence referendum in Kosovo
after three years, but the provision was dropped in the latest
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of possible independence of Kosovo is closed,''
Milosevic said. ``There can be only talks about autonomy and
nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Milosevic's withdrawal of autonomy from the province,
which before the recent exodus was 90 percent ethnic Albanian, that
triggered a decadelong conflict culminating in the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   If the United Nations retains authority over the Kosovo peace
process, it is doubtful a referendum would ever be held under its
auspices, because China or Russia would veto the move in the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
