<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DECLARING VICTORY, ADDRESSES SERBS DIRECTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed ASAP.) 
(mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After declaring Thursday night that NATO had
``achieved victory'' in the war in Kosovo, President Clinton warned
the people of Serbia that as long as Slobodan Milosevic remained
their leader, they would get no help in reviving their bomb-scarred
land.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noting that Milosevic had been indicted as a war
criminal, addressed the Serbian people directly, saying, ``So long
as he remains in power, there will be no support for the
reconstruction of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   After maintaining a cautious reserve in the days since a deal
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was first reported last
Friday, Clinton went on national television Thursday evening to
declare victory in an air war that had been given little chance of
success by experts, and that had posed serious political risks for
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight for the first time in 79 days the skies over
Yugoslavia are silent,'' the president declared. ``The demands of
an outraged international community have been met. I can report to
the American people that we have achieved victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said that the Yugoslavs could have kept Kosovo as part
of their country without driving out or killing anyone, and
``without inviting a single NATO bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You too have suffered in Mr. Milosevic's war,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted much of his 13-minute address to a ringing
justification of the war, whose length, cost and destruction had
roused unease and doubt among Americans and in NATO.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in his address announcing the start of the bombing on
March 24, Clinton invoked images of unspeakable atrocities waged by
Milosevic first against Croatians, then against Bosnians, and
finally against Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should remember that the violence was the culmination of a
10-year campaign by Mr. Milosevic to exploit ethnic and religious
differences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Clinton said, 500 villages were burned, men were
separated from their families and killed, women were raped,
children watched parents die, and people were made to abandon their
hones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the Kosovo refugees I recently met,''
Clinton said. ``Some of them could hardly talk about what they had
been through.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
