<SLUG> BC-SEC-TITLES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC top league for titles
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Southeastern Conference has left little room this
year for argument about the nation's top league in men's athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine men's sports the conference competes in nationally,
an SEC school has won seven NCAA titles and will try for an eighth
beginning today as Alabama competes in the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Based on recent history, the Crimson Tide could fare well in its
final collegiate championship of the season. The SEC has won five
of the last nine College World Series titles.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Alabama finishes at the CWS, the conference
already has reached new levels of success this season. The seven
men's titles are a conference record, and with three women's titles
_ Georgia in gymnastics and in swimming and diving and Florida in
soccer _ the conference has hit double figures for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reached a high-water mark on total championships,'' said
Mark Womack, SEC executive associate commissioner. ``We had won
nine championships in 1992-93 and in 1995-96, counting both men's
and women's sports. We won three in women's this year, and with
seven already from the men, that's our greatest year yet.''
</P>
<P>
   To carry the SEC superiority even further, the conference had
nine of its 11 women's sports reach the final four, and, with the
men's success, the league could have one of its schools finish in
the final four in 17 of its 20 sports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
