<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ARE A GUILTY PLEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the day of Sports Judgment, I will have to answer to the
basketball gods for this. My punishment will be severe. And it
should be. What I have done is pathetic. No, it's worse than that.
It's unethical. Immoral. Ridiculous. A joke. I have taken an
interest in the New York Knicks. That is so disgusting that it
makes me feel ... fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   See? I'm a bad person. How can I possibly be fascinated by the
Knicks? Next thing you know, I'll be the star of Spike Lee's new
film, ``He Got (No) Shame.''
</P>
<P>
   No one outside of New York is supposed to like this team. It
seems as if the Knicks left the set of ``The Jerry Springer Show,''
slipped on some shorts and headed to the Eastern Conference finals.
If they win Game 6 Friday night at Madison Square Garden, they will
knock Larry Bird and his Pacers out of the playoffs. The NBA began
seeding its playoff teams, 1 through 8, in 1984. The Knicks would
become the first No. 8 seed to advance to the Finals. They would
also become the first unlikable underdog in modern sports history.
But I kind of like them. Please forgive me.
</P>
<P>
   You know what watching the Knicks will do? It will teach you
about being a sports fan. It will let you know if you love sport
for sport itself or if you love it, in part, for the people who
play it. I say that because the Knicks are the ultimate mixed
feelings team. Look at their roster and you can easily find someone
who makes you want to praise them while they're working and boycott
them when they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Larry Johnson. If there are any honest Knick
fans in the house, they will tell you that they wanted this man
traded two months ago. He's got an outrageous contract, which is
only exceeded by his outrageous sense of court fashion. Johnson
thinks it's fashionable to tuck his jersey into his athletic
supporter, leaving the supporter exposed. I know: That's not
exactly DKNY material. One of his most memorable Garden
performances was cussing out a New York reporter after the reporter
had the nerve to ask for an interview. He has been the subject of
complaints from women who aren't named Mrs. Johnson, women who say
he has fathered and not always supported their children.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't seem like a lot to like. But Bird probably wishes he
could take the heart of Johnson and put it in 7-foot-4-inch center
Rik Smits. Even with Patrick Ewing out, Smits has still struggled
to stay on the court. And when he is on the court, for an average
of only 20 minutes per game, he isn't doing much. Johnson? He won
Game 3 with a 4-point play (and drew a fine afterward for refusing
to talk about it). In Game 5, he made two 3-pointers in the fourth
quarter, shots that were taken in front of the Indiana bench. You
should have seen the look on Coach Bird's face. He knows true
champions make shots like that, rather than moan about missed
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Johnson began his remarks by saying that ``all
praises are due to Allah.'' I have no doubt that Allah knows
Johnson; I wonder if Johnson knows Allah. Marcus Camby was across
the room when Johnson said that and burst into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   You do remember Camby, right? He was the most dominant college
player in the country in 1996. His University of Massachusetts team
was one of only two to hand a defeat to Rick Pitino's champions
from Kentucky, a group that included pros Antoine Walker, Ron
Mercer, Derek Anderson, Tony Delk, and Walter McCarty. That UMass
team was also stripped of its Final Four status by the NCAA. Camby
had contact with a sports agent and took gifts from him. It was
literally a tale of sex, lies, and cash.
</P>
<P>
   But in this best-of-seven series, Bird has also wished he had
someone like Camby. The Pacers coach said Camby has been the best
player of the series ``and he gets better every game.'' The last
time he took the floor, he had 21 points, 13 rebounds, and six
blocked shots. Dale and Antonio Davis may be stronger, Smits may be
taller, and every Pacer may have more playoff experience, but no
one has been able to handle Camby.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know why I really shouldn't like the Knicks? Their
fans. They chanted the name of coach Jeff Van Gundy during their
last playoff series, a tribute to the coach who was on the verge of
being replaced a month ago. They should have been chanting:
``Er-nie Grun-feld.'' He is the former general manager who traded
for Camby and Latrell Sprewell. Grunfeld was fired for his efforts,
mostly because Van Gundy either couldn't or wouldn't make Camby and
Sprewell regulars in the starting lineup. Since that time, Sprewell
has emerged as the team's most explosive player.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, the Wall Street Journal had a story in
which the headline ``Jail Sprewell'' appeared, a reference to the
player choking his former coach. Knicks executive Dave Checketts
said at the time that a player such as Sprewell couldn't play for
his team. Guess what happened Thursday. All the New York papers had
stories praising Sprewell _ who now collects sizable paychecks from
Checketts _ for helping lead the Knicks toward the Finals. Come on.
Tell me you don't like that just a little.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Knicks are tough to deal with now, wait until
you see what happens if they make it to the Finals. The last time
they were there, in 1994, one of their broadcasts was interrupted
when a man and his friend climbed into a white Ford Bronco and
drove around the highways of Los Angeles. What will be the New York
encore for that?
</P>
<P>
   I like the Knicks. I know I'll be punished for this. Maybe I'll
become the Sisyphus of 1999, sentenced to eternally push
basketballs while listening to Marv Albert's New York commentary.
Yes. Marv Albert. Another controversial Knick. I like him, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
