<HEADLINE>
INITIAL INDONESIAN VOTE TALLY FAVORS OPPOSITION PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ An unofficial vote sample issued Thursday
showed that the opposition party of Megawati Sukarnoputri was
likely to emerge from Monday's election in the strongest position
to form a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   But the sample, based on voting for two-thirds of the seats in
Indonesia's Parliament, indicated that the governing party, Golkar,
would remain a strong political force in the country it has
dominated for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The count, from 11 of Indonesia's 27 provinces, was conducted by
Rectors Forum, an independent local group operating with foreign
financing and expertise. It carried out a tabulation based on what
it said was a statistically strong sample of 3 percent of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The sample was intended as a baseline against which to verify
the official results. But the government's count continued to go so
slowly Thursday that the group decided to issue its partial figures
to answer a growing outcry for information on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Thursday, the official count had reached only about
10 million out of a total of about 112 million votes cast, far too
low to allow for credible projections, electoral experts said. That
count, too, showed a lead for Mrs. Megawati's party, the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the 48 parties in the race is expected to gain a
majority, and the leader in the vote count will not necessarily win
the competition for Indonesia's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The votes that are being counted are for 462 parliamentary seats
that will form the core of a partly appointed 700-member assembly
that is to choose the President later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the results emerging now will simply position the
leading parties for the next stage: coalition building, influence
peddling and the possible big-money sale of seats from party to
party.
</P>
<P>
   But a big victory could put the leading party in a commanding
position. Two foreign election experts, extrapolating from the
material provided by Rectors Forum, said Mrs. Megawati's party
could be approaching a convincing margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the initials of her party, one of the experts said:
``PDIP has done as well or better than people would have thought it
would do in Java. What this is telling me _ this is real ball park
_ is that it got at least 35 percent nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   But the expert, speaking on condition of anonymity, added: ``It
looks like Golkar got at least 20 percent. That's very interesting.
Golkar has not crashed and burned. It is going to continue to be a
strong political presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Golkar, led by President B.J. Habibie, remains the party with
the strongest nationwide network, the most money to spend and a
grass-roots loyalty in many poor areas that has remained immune to
the changes that have transformed much of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Mrs. Megawati's party wins by a margin big enough to
sweep up other parties in its momentum, political experts say,
Golkar is in the stronger position to gain ground in the next
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Rectors Forum sampling suggested that this next stage of the
fight could be particularly rough and tumble. The parties of the
country's two other most prominent political figures both appeared
to have fallen short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   If these second-tier parties are not strong, coalition building
could be fluid and unpredictable. ``Things could get very
interesting,'' the electoral experts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
