A0943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-10 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO HALTS BOMBING AS SERBS BEGIN WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With victory at hand, NATO suspended its punishing
79-day bombing campaign of Yugoslavia on Thursday as Serb troops
began their pullout from Kosovo and hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians had reason to believe they soon could go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can report to the American people that we have achieved a
victory for a safer world, for our democratic values, and for a
stronger America,'' President Clinton said in a televised address
from the Oval Office Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The president praised the 19-member NATO alliance for its
solidarity and resolve, thanked Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin
for his diplomacy, and urged the Serbian people to blame President
Slobodan Milosevic for their suffering and the ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he remains in power, as long as your nation is
ruled by an indicted war criminal, we will provide no support for
the reconstruction of Serbia,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 15-minute speech came after a day of fast-moving
developments. NATO Secretary General Javier Solana called a halt to
the airstrikes after confirming the Serb convoys were rolling in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the United Nations Security Council passed a
resolution for a NATO-led force of nearly 50,000 to keep the peace
in Kosovo and ensure the refugees' safe return and resettlement. On
the Macedonia border, troops in the international force began
amassing for a mission that could start as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   British Lieutenant General Michael Jackson, who will lead the
peacekeeping troops, pledged ``robust and even-handed treatment''
of anyone who violates the terms of the agreement. The accord,
signed Wednesday night by NATO and Yugoslav generals, ends
hostilities in Kosovo and provides for the withdrawal of all
Serbian forces in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock started ticking last night,'' Jackson said in
Skopje, Macedonia. During the pullout, Jackson added, ``violence or
noncompliance, wherever it may come from, will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said the military mission had ``brought an end to
a vicious campaign of ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo, while
inflicting ``far, far fewer'' civilian casualities than occurred in
the Gulf War. But he said the next phase would be dangerous, and
``formidable challenges'' _ including clearing land mines,
rebuilding homes, and accounting for the missing _ were ahead for
NATO peacekeepers as they return an estimated 863,000 refugees to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past four months, we have seen some of the worst
inhumanity in our lifetime, but we've also seen the bravery of our
troops, the resolve of our democracy, the decency of our people,
and the courage and determination of the people of Kosovo,''
Clinton told reporters Thursday morning. ``We now have a moment of
hope, thanks to all those qualities, and we have to finish the job
and build the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The president refused to say when NATO peacekeepers might end
their mission in Kosovo, and he dodged the question of whether
Milosevic had to be removed from power first. He said he ``didn't
see'' how Serbia could become integrated into Europe until it had a
leader committed to a multiethnic Yugoslavia and a democracy
guaranteeing human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Milosevic appeared on state television and declared
victory because Kosovo had not gained its independence from
Yugoslavia. ``We never gave up Kosovo,'' Milosevic said. ``We
survived and defended the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said reconstruction of the country would begin
immediately, but under indictment for war crimes, he is not in a
good position to ask developed countries and international
organizations for aid.
</P>
<P>
   The UN resolution, adopted 14-0 with China abstaining,
authorizes the UN to set up an interim civilian administration in
Kosovo to oversee refugee resettlement and to promote the
establishment of substantial autonomy and self-government within
Kosovo. It also demands the demilitarization of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army, which has been fighting for independence for the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this resolution, the United Nations Security Council has
charted the way toward a better future for the inhabitants of
Kosovo,'' Secretary General Kofi Annan told the council.
</P>
<P>
   Because China did not veto, speculation rose here that Beijing
had wrested concessions from the US on one of several matters,
including a report on the bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade, and China's admission to the World Trade Organization.
Talks on details over China's admission were suspended by China
after the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese government spokesman at the UN denied any deals were
struck. ``We have no self-interest in this matter, we only want the
charter of the UN to be followed,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said the agency
was preparing to take the first convoy of ethnic Albanian refugees
to Kosovo as soon as it gets a ``green light'' from the NATO-led
security force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We _ all the UN agencies _ will go with them,'' said Dennis
McNamara, the UN's special envoy for refugees. ``We will take them
back to their homes when it is safe and help them rebuild. But we
urge the refugees to be patient. Our message to them is: wait until
it is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana said US General Wesley Clark, NATO's top commander,
informed him that the Serb withdrawal had begun. Both intelligence
reports and CNN broadcasts, Solana said, showed long lines of Serb
convoys in Kosovo heading north toward Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With the withdrawal underway and ``if everything goes OK,''
Solana said, ``tomorrow we may see the first K-FOR (Kosovo
peacekeeping force) soldiers deployed in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who will lead the peacekeeping troops, said, ``It is
inevitable that some unpleasantries will greet them.'' Jackson said
the Yugoslav military has been cooperative in providing data on
land mines, and he had unconfirmed reports Serb units were
dismantling devices on bridges and tunnels as they retreated.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 US troops, equally divided between Marines and Army
soldiers from the 82nd Airborne Division, will be in the first wave
of 23,000 international peacekeepers in Kosovo, said General Hugh
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. The province is
being divided into five military sectors run by the British,
Germans, French, Italians, and Americans. The force will grow to
50,000, including 7,000 Americans, who will be in place in the next
four weeks, Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke by telephone Thursday to alliance leaders as well
as to Yeltsin. In Moscow, Yeltsin called the suspension of NATO
airstrikes ``a step in the right direction,'' and Russia's defense
minister gave preliminary approval for a Russian airborne brigade
of 2,500 men to join the peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   But after a day of talks, US, Finnish, and Russian generals were
unable to agree on whether Moscow's troops will interact with the
rest of the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has promised up to 10,000 troops but insists its units
should not be under NATO command. Russian officials have suggested
that Kosovo could be divided to give the Russians a sector of their
own. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who arrived in
Moscow Thursday for talks with Russian leaders, ruled out a
``Russian sector'' and said all the peacekeeping troops would ``be
under one command arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised his foreign policy team and NATO military
leaders for staying the course amid criticism that the air war was
ill-conceived and inadequate for defeating Milosevic. He singled
out Defense Secretary William S. Cohen as ``vindicated'' by
developments so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo, we did the right thing,'' Clinton said Thursday
night. ``We did it the right way. And we will finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John Kerry, Democrats of
Massachusetts, said they were encouraged by the Serb withdrawal but
said the next week would be crucial in whether the peace will keep.
``Moving in there is not going to be easy,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Cohen and Shelton gave the most detailed
briefing to date on what they said was the success of the NATO air
campaign: 80 percent of Yugoslavia's fighter aircraft and
surface-to-air missiles destroyed; more than 50 percent of its
artillery and 33 percent of its armored vehicles in Kosovo wiped
out; and half of Milosevic's defense industry damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO aircraft flew thousands of missions, lost two planes, and
no fliers, although two pilots were killed while training. Of more
than 23,000 bombs and missiles dropped, 20 missed their targets and
killed civilians, Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2127EDT &QL; 
