r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MED-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     06-10 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MED-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN THEY WORK WITHOUT A NET?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles Dodgers and Anaheim Angels cable viewers must feel
like they've got to keep one hand on the remote and the other on
their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   But what's generally considered irrational behavior at this
point might just be wasted energy once Fox Sports Net's two
Southern California channels sort out their latest publicity
nightmare, made more confusing by those trying to explain two
separate things that have been combined to hit at once.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder cable subscribers have had the issues blurred by
their operators, who want to avoid looking like the tightwad bad
boys they often are portrayed (and rightly so) to be, and by Fox
brass, who don't want to look like price-gauging maniacs. Both have
thrown their arguments out at the court of public appeal.
</P>
<P>
   First, in the Fox-Charter/Marcus issue, Fox has acres of legal
ground to stand on during this skirmish with the new owners of the
cable company that serves 90,000 subscribers, including the cities
of Burbank and Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus happily signed a contract more than three years ago to
pay Fox X amount of cents per subscriber for FSW and FSW2. When
billionaire Paul Allen's Charter company bought the system late
last year, it decided to pay the Y amount to Fox that was in the
Charter contract. Y is less than X in this example, pennies on
paper, but thousands of dollars per month after the decimals are
done.
</P>
<P>
   So figure out who had the right to get mad in that issue? Fox's
last resort _ to turn off the juice to Charter/Marcus' customers
last Saturday morning after months of threats _ seems to have
finally grabbed their attention.
</P>
<P>
   But where Charter/Marcus has taken this to another level and
looks at it as a two-pronged attack is with the second issue _ a
Fox surcharge, which again is the company's legal right, for all
cable operators who are receiving twice the amount of Dodgers and
Angels games this season.
</P>
<P>
   For years, TV viewers in L.A. have cried for more Dodgers and
Angels games, especially when compared to what fans in Chicago and
New York have available for their NL and AL teams. Now that the
extra games are here _ FSW2 doubled the number of Dodgers games
this year from 40 to 80 and went from zero to 40 on the Angels for
FSW _ it's clear the terms of the contracts Fox signed with cable
operators have changed. But the cable operators knew this might _
and probably would _ happen when signing the deals in the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Century, Cox, TCI and DirecTV have already honored the surcharge
without complaint, again a pennies-per-customer increase. If
Charter/Marcus, Media One, Time Warner and Comcast systems don't
get on board by July 6, they'll have to explain to their customers
why the Dodgers suddenly disappeared from FSW2. Or why there's no
more Angels after Aug. 3. Those channels won't be switched off as
in the Marcus situation because that's not the issue. Fox will
simply supply alternative programming from the Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   The response from Charter/Marcus to both these issues has been
to lump them together and complain that it doesn't want to pay
anymore for the Fox Group's fiscal irresponsibility. Its claim that
Fox is trying to recoup cash to pay the contract of Dodgers pitcher
Kevin Brown certainly is an easy out and catches the public's
attention, but a business 101 student knows that simply ain't so.
Ironically, that's almost verbatim the argument spewed by Fox
nemesis Ted Turner before a group of cable operators last month in
Las Vegas, where he made a promise that his cable networks (HBO,
TNT, TBS and the Cartoon Network) would not take back local
advertising time for itself as Fox's over-the-air network recently
decided to do to recoup ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the surcharge issue works both ways. If Fox ever
reduced the number of games in the contract, it would refund money
to cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   So if the situation was so despicable, why have four major cable
companies already signed up? Will the other four big cable
companies eventually pay the surcharge? Sources within each company
are definitely not as vindictive as Charter/Marcus and say they
enjoy the benefit of more Dodgers games and will likely pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, meanwhile, don't seem too worried, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it is in the best interest of the Dodgers and their
fans to have the games distributed as widely as possible,'' said
Brent Shyer, the team's director of media relations and
broadcasting. ``Already a number of major cable systems have signed
up and we look forward to all remaining cable operators signing up
as quickly as possible. Fans will want to see more games as the
chase for the division title heats up.''
</P>
<P>
   And by then, cooler heads should prevail.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fox Sports mess, part II: Two months after Fox Sports Net and
Student Sports publications proclaimed they would sponsor and
televise a national prep-football championship tournament for the
2000 season, a louder backlash from some top high school
administrators across the country has threatened to stop it before
it happens.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion piece in the June 7 Street &AMP; Smith SportsBusiness
Journal written by Jack Roberts, the executive director of the
Michigan High School Athletic Association, notes that within 90
minutes of Fox's press release announcing the game, the MHSAA
declared none of its 620 member high schools that play football
would participate.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of State High School Associations has
already urged its members to avoid participation, emphasizing that
its bylaws prohibit any game or tournament designed to award a
national championship. The Washington Post reported Tuesday that
Florida, Texas and Ohio likely won't approve teams from those
states to join either, which would pretty much take the steam out
of the tournament's claim of a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network has gone from an ally to enemy with the
announcement,'' wrote Roberts in SBJ. ``My guess is a real
championship game will never occur, but what will happen is serious
stress to what has been an excellent adventure between Fox Sports
Net's regional affiliates and high school associations to convey
what is pure and wholesome about school sports, in sharp contrast
with most televised sports on other levels.'' &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ Ready to see Marv Albert show off his Fox attitude? Rumors
continue that he'll be added to the network's NFL coverage this
fall. And why not? He proved himself working for TNT on the NBA. &QL; 
__ During the second period of Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals
between Buffalo and Dallas, a Fox camera found a woman in the
stands wearing a Stars jersey. But then she started moving around
and before you knew it, she was lifting the jersey to breast-feed
an infant. Which, to some viewers, is more offensive than a woman
just wanting to expose herself. &QL; 
__ ESPN, ESPN2 and CBS gang up for College World Series coverage,
starting today with two games. Saturday afternoon's Cal State
Fullerton-Stanford game goes to ESPN2 at 5 p.m. (with Mike Patrick
and Harold Reynolds), and each team plays its second game Monday on
ESPN. CBS has a first-round game Saturday morning, as well as the
one-game final next Saturday. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ ESPN will use a three-man booth _ Mike Tirico, Kirk
Herbstreit and Lee Corso _ on its Thursday-night college football
game of the week. Herbstreit, good. Corso, not good. &QL; 
__ Not so much that the series-premiere episode of HBO's drama
series ``Arli$$'' was about as remarkably more miserable than
anticipated _ if it means anything, Robert Wuhl has credit for
co-writer and director, as well as, of course, lead actor _ but
they misspelled Keith Olbermann's name in the closing credits. It
would have been tough to get it right since a Fox Sports News
graphic that spelled Olbermann's name appeared during his cameo at
the beginning of the show. Just 11 episodes left in this batch. &QL; 
__ And be sure to watch Fox Sports News on Sunday to see
Olbermann's rendition of the Wrigley Field seventh-inning serenade,
continuing a tradition that ESPN's Chris Berman and Dan Patrick
have now joined this year _ a celebration of pseudo-celebrities who
can't sing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
