<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0611-1     06-10 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0611-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writethru, updated to add Clinton comments from address . .
.
 &HT;    CLINTON: FINISH THE JOB, BUILD THE PEACE IN KOSOVO, BALKANS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0611.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton declared victory Thursday over
Serb forces he blamed for ``some of the most vicious atrocities in
Europe'' since World War II, and he urged the country to shoulder
the added perils of securing peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may well be casualties,'' Clinton warned the nation in a
televised Oval Office address, as 3,000 U.S. Marines and Army
soldiers mustered in Macedonia for imminent deployment in NATO's
peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Clinton said, the troops will enter Kosovo
heavily armed and with orders to shoot to kill if anyone _ Serb or
otherwise _ threatens the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have the means and the mandate to protect itself while
doing its job,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 weeks of air strikes, Clinton said NATO had scored an
important win over one of the worst chapters in the history of this
bloody century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have achieved a victory for a safer world, for our
democratic values and for a stronger America,'' Clinton said, hours
after NATO suspended its air strikes against Yugoslavia.
``Aggression against an innocent people has been contained and is
being turned back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laid the blame for atrocities in Kosovo squarely at the
feet of Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
accusing him of waging a 10-year campaign of aggression against
non-Serbs throughout the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should know that your leaders could have kept Kosovo as a
part of your country without driving a single Kosovar family from
its home, without killing a single adult or child, without inviting
a single NATO bomb to fall on your country,'' Clinton said, in a
passage addressed to the people of Serbia. ``You endured 79 days of
bombing, not to keep Kosovo a province of Serbia but simply because
Mr. Milosevic was determined to eliminate Kosovar Albanians from
Kosovo _ dead or alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed that U.S. aid to Serbia _ excluding the shattered
province of Kosovo _ would be limited to humanitarian assistance so
long as Milosevic, indicted by the United Nations tribunal on war
crimes for alleged atrocities in Kosovo, remains in office in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he remains in power, as long as your nation is
ruled by an indicted war criminal, we will provide no support for
the reconstruction of Serbia,'' Clinton said. ``But we are ready to
provide humanitarian aid now and to help to build a better future
for Serbia, too, when its government represents tolerance and
freedom, not repression and terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracing the country for years of peacekeeping operations
involving thousands of U.S. troops, Clinton declined to set a date
certain for bringing American forces home from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put a timetable on it,'' Clinton told
reporters at the White House earlier. ``We will define our
objectives and proceed to implement them.''
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Serb troops, police and paramilitary thugs
have forced more than a million ethnic Albanians to flee their
homes in Kosovo, Clinton said the U.S. peacekeeping commitment
there is open ended.
</P>
<P>
   That approach differed sharply from Clinton's pledge in December
1995 that U.S. peacekeepers would remain in Bosnia for only one
year. There are still 6,200 U.S. troops in Bosnia, part of a larger
NATO peacekeeping force there of some 31,000. There are no plans to
remove the force.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 U.S. troops are staging to deploy into Kosovo as part
of a larger NATO force expected to crest near 50,000 forces.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
