<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-GRADUATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6,400 RECEIVE DEGREES FROM HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ On a day graced by clear blue skies and
polite protests, Harvard University observed its 348th commencement
Thursday, conferring degrees on 6,400 graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Holding red balloons, three dozen or so protesters left their
seats during an address by Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan
and headed for a ``counter-commencement'' outside the university's
gates.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, who have staged a half-dozen rallies on labor
issues this spring in Harvard Yard, said they were protesting
Greenspan's economic policies and his selection as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard senior Selamawi Asgedom, a refugee from the war between
Ethiopia and Eritrea, delivered the student English address,
telling graduates to work for change in distant lands, as well as
in their own communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big, sweeping revolutionary actions are always the most
noticeable,'' he said. ``But quite often, it will be the small
things that all of us can do that have the most impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Trice Edney, who delivered the Graduate English Address,
closed her remarks with the words: ``Take a chance, won't you?
Knock down the fences that divide. ... Reach out, Harvard. Reach
out, America. Reach out, world. Freedom lies just on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   For the women of Radcliffe College, it was a bittersweet day,
marking the last commencement exercise for the 100-year-old
institution, which will be supplanted by the Radcliffe Institute
for Advanced Study.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the ``indelible mark'' that Radcliffe has made on
the university, Harvard president Neil Rudenstine told alumni and
graduates that the new institute would provide opportunities for
the study of women, gender, and society. He pledged Harvard's full
support for the institute.
</P>
<P>
   The university conferred honorary degrees on Greenspan;
economist Kenneth Arrow; Harvard's Bernard Bailyn, professor
emeritus of early American history; cartoonist Herbert Block;
economist Andrew Brimmer; scientist David Cox; literary theorist
Julia Kristeva; and novelist Mario Vargas Llosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
