<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BROKERAGE-VENTURES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN AND VULCAN INVEST IN 2 ELECTRONIC TRADING SYSTEMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: In 2nd graf, reference to E(STAR)Trade (STAR) should be
replaced by symbol)  By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The race on Wall Street to build and expand
computer-based trading systems is picking up speed. J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. and the venture capitalist Paul G. Allen each announced new
investments Thursday in the fast-growing services.
</P>
<P>
   Through his venture capital firm Vulcan Ventures, Allen will
make a $25 million investment in Island ECN, a large electronic
communications network. Vulcan will get a 12 percent stake in
return. J.P. Morgan will purchase a 20 percent stake in
Archipelago, whose other major investors include Goldman, Sachs and
E(STAR)Trade. Terms of the Morgan deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks and brokerage firms are looking at ECN's as something
they need to be involved in,'' Bruce W. Weber, associate professor
of computer information systems at City University of New York.
``They're selling part of ownership to get necessary funding to
handle growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The trading systems are intended to provide investors with an
alternative, lower-cost market in which they can meet and trade
stocks. About a dozen electronic trading networks have sprung up,
most in the last three years. Their goal is to cut out
intermediaries between buyers and sellers in Nasdaq stock
transactions. Together, these networks, including Island,
Archipelago and Instinet, which is owned by Reuters, account for
about 30 percent of trading in Nasdaq stocks, though they all use
slightly different methods to tally their transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Archipelago, which is three years old,
executed about 375 million trades in April, up from 170 million in
December 1998. Five percent of Morgan's investment comes through
the mutual fund group American Century Cos., in which Morgan holds
a 45 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Island says it completes about $5 billion in transactions a day.
Earlier this year the company said it was preparing to file with
the Securities and Exchange Commission to become an exchange.
Allen's investment follows the announcement last month of a $25
million investment from the Waterhouse Investor Service. Island's
brokerage affiliate, Datek Securities, recently announced that it
had received an unspecified investment from Allen's group.
</P>
<P>
   Matt F. Andresen, president of Island ECN, said the additional
capital will help build a regulatory infrastructure needed to
become a national securities exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, two of Wall Street's largest investment
houses _ Goldman, Sachs and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. _ announced that
they were joining forces with Bernard L. Madoff Investment
Securities, a large stock trading firm, to form a new company to
offer investors access to an electronic communications network for
trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
