<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-10 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-MAIL `WORM' SPREADING AND DESTROYING DOCUMENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computer researchers reported a malicious computer program that
destroys documents created by popular Microsoft software programs.
The program, a form of computer attack known as a worm, shows up as
an attachment to e-mail that appears to come from someone known to
the computer user.
</P>
<P>
   Several corporations said their computers had been infected by
the program and moved to limit the damage, in some cases by
shutting down their e-mail systems.
</P>
<P>
   BANK OF ENGLAND CUTS KEY RATE
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England unexpectedly cut Britain's benchmark
interest rate to 5 percent, its lowest level in more than 20 years,
to weaken the pound, which has risen against the euro, and spur a
slow-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   STAKES BOUGHT IN TRADING SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   With the race on Wall Street to build and expand computer-based
trading systems picking up speed, both J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Paul
Allen, who heads the venture capital firm Vulcan Ventures,
announced new investments in the fast-growing services. Vulcan will
invest $25 million for a 12 percent stake in Island ECN, a large
electronic communications network. Morgan will buy 20 percent of
Archipelago, whose other major investors include Goldman, Sachs,
for undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SLIDE AS BOND YIELDS CLIMB
</P>
<P>
   Stocks staged a broad retreat as long-term interest rates
climbed, with the yield on the 30-year Treasury rising to 6.06
percent, from 6.02 percent on Wednesday. The NASDAQ composite index
fell 34.73 points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,484.62, while the Dow Jones
industrial average slumped for a third day, falling 69.02 points,
or six-tenths of a percent, to 10,621.27. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 15.82 points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,302.82.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MUNICIPAL ACCOUNTING RULES
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests from public officials, the accounting board
that sets the rules for how cities and states keep their books
approved a plan to require governments to include the value of
roads, bridges and other infrastructure projects in their financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
   `CUSTOMER SERVICE' PACT UNRAVELS
</P>
<P>
   A news conference called to announce a ``customer service
commitment'' plan by 14 passenger airlines was canceled by the
carriers, apparently because of a disagreement with lawmakers that
occurred minutes before the briefing was supposed to begin.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR POSTS LOSS
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor reported its fifth consecutive quarterly
loss as it exits the personal computer microprocessor business, but
its results met analysts' expectations. Executives said the company
was on track to return to profitability by its fiscal second
quarter, which ends in November. Before the results were announced,
shares of National Semiconductor closed at $22.50, up $1.8125.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT'S ENDURING BROWSER
</P>
<P>
   With Edward Felten, a Princeton University computer scientist
and the government's final witness in the Microsoft antitrust
trial, on the stand, lawyers for Microsoft sought to show that the
company's Web browser could not be removed from Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   CATHAY PILOTS AGREE TO PAY CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Less than a day before a deadline to sign new contracts or be
dismissed, pilots at Cathay Pacific Airways agreed to pay cuts in
return for stock options and the opportunity to fly cargo planes
for the first time in four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSHGALLERY11-COX     06-10 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHGALLERY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush Gallery at the National Museum of the Pacific War set to
open
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ Thursday afternoon, between Midway
Island and Guadalcanal, war was raging. This was a war against time
and it looked like time surely must win. In the building a block
off Main Street, electrical cables and half-assembled Lucite
displays littered the floor. Amid the smell of paint and a din of
hammers, saws and drills, Helen McDonald surveyed her allied forces
of contract workers and volunteers. She looked at her watch.
``Twenty hours,'' she said. ``We'll make it.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald is curator of exhibits and programs for the Admiral
Nimitz Museum, whose huge new expansion, the George Bush Gallery of
the National Museum of the Pacific War, will be dedicated today.
Former President George Bush will cut the ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the the $3 million expansion began about five years
ago. Nearly all the money was raised by the museum's nonprofit
foundation through private donations.
</P>
<P>
   The Nimitz Museum honors Fredericksburg native Fleet Adm.
Chester W. Nimitz, who was commander-in-chief of Allied forces in
the Pacific during World War II. The museum once was a hotel, which
Nimitz' grandfather bought in 1855.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the new expansion, adjacent to the original museum,
``is to teach young people that there were a lot of sacrifices,
lessons to be learned . . . and to tell that story to future
generations so they won't have to relive it,'' says retired Rear
Adm. C.D. ``Chuck'' Grojean, director of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the last American president to serve in WWII and was
the youngest aviator in the Navy when he was shot down in the
Pacific in 1944. Among the museum's features will be film of his
rescue by an American submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will enter the new facility's 25,000 square feet to
find themselves on the deck of a mock Japanese submarine, watching
the lights of Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, twinkle in the distance.
They'll share space with the only real, remaining mini-sub that
participated in the attack which brought America into the war.
</P>
<P>
   The trip through the new museum's labyrinth is then
chronological. There is a deck hatch from the sunken battleship
U.S.S. Arizona. One huge display features a B-25 bomber launching
from the carrier Hornet for the Tokyo raid of April, 1942. Entering
the room trips a light beam at which the plane's propellors turn as
its engines roar to life.
</P>
<P>
   Turn a corner and here are Marines at Henderson Field on
Guadalcanal, surrounded by crates of ammunition, talking about
heading back to their foxholes before dark, so they're not shot at
by their own sentries. The depth of research is such that the
simulated palm trees are exactly the kind that grew there.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout are hundreds of photos and artifacts _ uniforms and
helmets, binoculars and weapons, both Allied and Japanese. There
are displays about the home front, minorities and women in the
service.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the scribbled note dropped to American POWs by a
Corsair pilot near war's end: ``Hi fellows. You'll be free by
tomorrow. Our planes have landed on a field nearby . . . Loads of
luck. God bless you. Ensign Skomisdak, Toledo, Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
