<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-CONTROL BILL IN PERIL AS HASTERT STEPS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Thursday that he
would not pressure House Republicans to vote for new restrictions
on firearms, seemingly distancing himself from several Republican
gun-control proposals introduced earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's decision not to push for a party-line position, coming
in the wake of complaints from conservatives and moderates about
the proposals, raised questions about whether the House would
approve modest gun-control measures similar to those passed by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's remarks also provoked complaints from some House
Republicans that he was again failing to exert the leadership
needed on a touchy political issue, and the confusion and disarray
evident among House Republicans on Thursday suggested that they
might be fated to suffer the same kinds of political embarrassment
around gun control that Senate Republicans had.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a fresh defeat for their party leadership, some
Republicans worked on Thursday night to redraft gun-control
proposals unveiled earlier this week to try to soften them and make
them more palatable to conservatives in the party.
</P>
<P>
   But that strategy contained the risk that a coalition of
Democrats and moderate Republicans would reject the weakened
language. Those Democrats and Republicans have already complained
that the proposals in place need to be toughened.
</P>
<P>
   Those measures were introduced Tuesday by Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary Committee and is typically
more supportive of gun control than other House Republicans.
Republican aides had said Hastert generally supported the package,
and Hastert had given no indication to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Hastert held those measures at arm's length as it
became clear just how divided his conference was over the measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Hyde certainly has his own personal feelings about what
should be done,'' he said. ``I have my own personal feelings about
what I think is common-sense legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert declined to get too specific about those feelings, which
he said would not prevent Republicans and Democrats from getting to
vote on a wide variety of gun-control measures that appealed either
to conservative or liberal sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are going to whip this bill,'' Hastert said,
referring to the process by which party leaders exhort party
members to fall into a given line. ``We are letting everybody have
some type of amendment out there so they can express their view.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's remarks underscored the broad ideological spectrum
among Republicans on gun control, a divide which could bode ill for
the passage of any legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference is all over the map,'' said House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay. DeLay and Majority Leader Dick Armey oppose several
aspects of Hyde's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   As Hastert seemed to cut those proposals loose Thursday, Hyde
said he was reminded of the impeachment proceedings, when party
leaders left him to run the show and absorb any blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God,'' Hyde chuckled, ``I'm running out of fingerprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., who favors gun control, said Hastert
was staying true to his laissez-faire ways.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican aides said Hastert blundered in the first
place by letting Hyde's proposals be the first out of the gate,
because those measures never had the blessing of a large number of
Republicans or even fellow Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   These restrictions were modeled in large part on the Senate
legislation, but Democratic advocates Thursday continued to decry
the ways in which the restrictions were less strict, and said that
they would push for tougher proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., said Thursday night that
Democrats had determined that only about 30 party members might
defect and vote with conservative Republicans on gun control, but
that as many as 40 Republicans could side with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Republicans' narrow majority in the House, she said,
``It's going to be really, really close.''
</P>
<P>
   But the initial fight for Democrats is making sure that the
House Rules Committee allows their gun-control proposals to the
floor. All the gun measures will be offered as amendments to a
juvenile crime bill that is scheduled for debate Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
