<HEADLINE>
AFTER SIX FAILURES, TEST OF ANTIMISSILE SYSTEM SUCCEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.M.)   (af)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a succession of well-publicized failures, the
Pentagon announced Thursday that a 20-foot missile had slammed into
a test rocket high above the New Mexico desert Thursday morning, a
potential breakthrough in the ``Star Wars'' technology intended to
protect the United States from missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first successful test of the Army's troubled $3
billion antimissile system, a project that has been seen as the
forerunner of a much larger program to shield the nation from the
threat of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant because it demonstrates that the technology
can be made to work,'' said Brig. Gen. Richard Davis of the
Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, which manages
the program. ``It is a major milestone, because this is our first
successful interaept, but we still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the test, the Pentagon said, a missile flying at supersonic
speed 24 miles to 60 miles above the White Sands Missile Range in
New Mexico _ the exact altitude was not revealed _ hit and
destroyed a test rocket fired minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the rocket had been designed to resemble a Scud
ballistic missile like those fired by Iraq in the Persian Gulf war
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Six earlier test shoot downs failed, prompting critics of the
program in and out of the government to suggest that using missiles
to destroy missiles would never be practical.
</P>
<P>
   And even Thursday, the critics said that the successful test of
the Army's Theater High-Altitude Area Defense, or Thaad, rocket
proved little.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite possible for a system to work well in tests and
fail in the field,'' said the Union of Concerned Scientists, which
is often critical of Pentagon weapons systems. In a statement, the
group described the test as a ``relatively trivial step.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said that deployment of an antimissile system might
lead Washington to abandon the proven approach of diplomacy and
arms control in favor of a potentially false sense of security
backed up by a faulty defense system.
</P>
<P>
   But even the harshest attacks on the antimissile program
Thursday could not overwhelm the sense of delight and relief felt
by many in the Defense Department _ and at Lockheed Martin Corp.,
the prime contractor _ who have staked their careers on the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon news conference, Davis said the test proved that
the Defense Department now had ``the guidance control, accuracy and
the processing that allows us to hit a bullet with a bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides a capability against the entire threat regime that
we expect to be encountering,'' he said. ``We're obviously
concerned because of the growing theater missile defense threat.
Twenty-five countries currently have theater ballistic missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by reports that North Korea and Iran are testing
ballistic missiles and that China has obtained some of the
Pentagon's most sophisticated weapons technology, Congress has
pressed the Defense Department to deploy an ambitious missile
defense system early in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, dropping his opposition to such a concept,
has pledged $6.6 billion in next year's budget to develop a
national missile defense system, although he has decided to delay a
decision on whether to actually build one until the middle of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Thaad missiles are part of a small arsenal of similar
defensive weapons the Pentagon is developing. The culmination of
the program is intended to be a large interceptor meant to shield
the nation _ not just soldiers, ships and battlefields _ from enemy
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The next test of the system is scheduled for July and will be
conducted at a higher altitude, more than 60 miles up.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Army's contract with Lockheed Martin, there must be
three successful tests of the missiles before the program can go
into something closer to full production.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier test failures had brought calls from Congress for
the Army to find a competitor to Lockheed Martin, which was fined
$15 million after the most recent failure in March.
</P>
<P>
   The project has cost more than $3 billion since it began in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been a problem with respect to the quality of the
hardware,'' Davis said of Lockheed. ``We have expressed that in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said a new management team at Lockheed had ``turned the
program around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important message here is we really want
success,'' he said. ``The whole idea is not to penalize the
contractor but to have a teaming relationship that we can all get a
win-win situation and have a capability delivered to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman from Lockheed did not return a telephone call
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
