<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-WICCA-BOYCOTT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-Wicca movement has mixed support
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A conservative public policy organization said
Thursday that religious-based political groups are committing
political suicide by calling for Christians to boycott joining or
re-enlisting in the Army until witchcraft rituals are banned from
Army posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings back the specter of the Salem witch trials,'' said
Marc Levin, vice president of the American Freedom Institute. ``In
addition to being wrongheaded, conservative calls for a boycott of
the military are politically suicidal. Support for the military is
a bedrock conservative principle.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the 13 national groups that originally called for the
boycott Wednesday, the American Family Association, has withdrawn
its support.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Trueman, director of governmental affairs for the American
Family Association, said his group was asked Wednesday by a
conservative Christian organization to join in a statement against
the practice of the Wicca faith on military bases, but was unaware
the news release would call for an Army boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally blindsided by this,'' Trueman said. ``We don't
support witches, obviously, but calling for a boycott is not
something we would do.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for a boycott came after publicity stemming from an
Austin American-Statesman story last month about Wiccans at Fort
Hood in Killeen. The Army post for three years has sanctioned a
Wicca group by providing on-base space for rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the boycott is the Free Congress Foundation, led by Paul
Weyrich in Washington, D.C., a nationally known Christian
conservative credited with coining the phrase ``Moral Majority.''
</P>
<P>
   In its literature, the foundation says it ``works against the
government encroachment on individual liberties.'' But those
liberties do not extend to sanctioned witchcraft on Army
installations, said William S. Lind, director of the foundation's
Center for Cultural Conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things should be discriminated against,'' Lind said.
``All religions are not equal. Satan should be discriminated
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Seimer, president of the Austin-based American Freedom
Institute, said that thinking goes directly against the
conservative position that promotes religious values in the public
arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's insane about it is that we fight for the freedom to
practice religion in public, and now the conservatives who seek to
deny these groups their right to worship are espousing the
philosophy of 'freedom of religion for me and not for thee,' ''
Seimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Wicca, a neo-paganist faith whose adherents call themselves
witches, is rooted in pre-Christian Europe. Adherents celebrate the
cycles of the sun and moon and believe in the dual deity of god and
goddess. ``Although these groups are pagan, they are not satanic,''
Siemer said. ``Many of our founding fathers were not Christians but
were Deists. . . . As long as a religious group does not advocate
an illegal or unpatriotic position, which Wiccans do not, they
should be allowed freedom on worship on U.S. military
installations.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups calling for the boycott along with the Free Congress
Foundation include the Christian Coalition, Traditional Values
Coalition, Christian Action Network, Religious Freedom Coalition,
Home School Legal Defense Association, American Association of
Christian Schools, I Love Jesus Worldwide Ministries, the Madison
Project, 60 Plus, American Council for Immigration Reform, and
Tradition, Family, Property Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-10-99 2136E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
