<HEADLINE>
LIKE IT OR NOT, VAN GUNDY IS STILL STANDING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy parked his Honda Civic and hustled through a
hallway last week, a rumpled bag in his hand that contained a
sandwich he bought from the back of a wobbly lunch truck.
</P>
<P>
   Routinely parked on a worn spot beside a two-lane road near the
Knicks' practice facility at the State University of New York at
Purchase, this kitchen on wheels is frequented by road crews,
students, police officers and Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better get going,'' the Knicks' coach told someone who
inquired where to get a decent lunch in the area. ``It's gone by 3
p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   This is experience talking. This is a coach who has been here
long enough to understand what hour things come _ and go around _
during his 10-year tenure with the Knicks' organization. He has
trudged through the long, thankless hours as an assistant and
endured the criticism as head coach of a team that is one victory
away from eliminating the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern Conference
finals and advancing to the league championship series against the
San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   A victory Friday night in Game 6 at Madison Square Garden, and
the Knicks celebrate into the night. Just one more victory and Van
Gundy will instantly receive a one-year $3.5 million extension of a
contract that has one year and $2 million remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, whether he is eventually dismissed by the
Garden hierarchy for Phil Jackson, or decides to leave with a
settlement out of distaste for the cloak-and-dagger machinations of
the Garden's president, Dave Checketts, or he remains with the
team, Van Gundy will have the satisfaction of success to ease the
sting of a tumultuous season.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other year, the Van Gundy critiques _ everything
from his overt loyalty to Patrick Ewing to whether he trusts Marcus
Camby _ have become like daily advice from Ann Landers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they're on results, sometimes they're on
relationships,'' Van Gundy said Thursday, less than 24 hours after
his team won Game 5 on Indiana's home floor. ``It depends on if
we're winning or losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really thankful that I'm a part of a team that's
still playing. And what small part I play in it, I take very
seriously. I do the job the best I can. If you become paralyzed by
the thought that you may be criticized for doing something, you're
never going to be the risk taker you need to be as a good coach.
Risk taking is part of it. If it doesn't work out, you've got to
accept the responsibility for it not working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has been uncommonly daring during the conference
finals once faced with the season-ending injury of Ewing after Game
2. Although the Knicks won Game 3 on a 4-point shot aligned with
the stars from Larry Johnson, Van Gundy tinkered with fate. After
resisting voices calling for him to start Latrell Sprewell almost
all season, he put him in the lineup for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem like such a hot idea when Sprewell responded with
a meager performance: 6-for-14 shooting in a 90-78 loss. Van Gundy
stuck to his plan, though. In Game 5, Sprewell scored 29 points in
Wednesday's dramatic victory that included other games of chance
for Van Gundy. He allowed Allan Houston to play with three fouls in
the third quarter and with four early in the fourth, but he sat
down Camby for the bulk of the third quarter with three fouls to
make sure he was around for the finish.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Houston guarded Mark Jackson while Charlie Ward
took over the Reggie Miller watch. Miller scored (30 points) but so
did Houston (19), who was also able to hold off Jackson in the
post. Unencumbered by fouls, Camby played the fourth quarter freely
and took over the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to someone close to me when I was discussing,
between Games 3 and 4, whether to start Sprewell,'' Van Gundy said,
not identifying the person. ``That person, whom I really trust,
said to me: `Well, if you want to avoid criticism, don't start him.
That's the safe way to play it. Then you have to decide whether you
want to avoid criticism more than you want to win.' To me, that was
an easy decision. Winning is all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, by starting Latrell, it was neither genius last night
nor stupidity in Game 4. It was what I felt was in the best
interest of the team. That's how I make every decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The most nondescript of coaches has a chance to finish an
Eastern Conference coaching journey that has pitted him against
Miami's Pat Riley, Atlanta's Lenny Wilkens and Bird _ a trifecta
consisting of ring-holders, record-holders and legends.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy is quick to remind everyone that they are not
there yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's how do we break the cycle: win, lose, win, lose,
win,'' Van Gundy said of this seesaw series. ``It's very difficult
to win two in a row. The team that has had the mental edge coming
off a loss has won the next game. We have to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said: ``I think Jeff has done an excellent job. We had a
rough first of the season, but we responded well. And he's a great
coach for this team. He gets along with the guys and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that it was ``just disturbing'' to hear reports of
Jackson's imminent arrival.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Van Gundy was probably a little rumpled and
frayed when the plane touched down from Indiana in the early hours
Thursday morning, but he took a few minutes to speak with his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke 5 or 10 minutes on the plane about what we need to
do,'' Van Gundy said. ``We'll find out, and see what happens. I
think we know what we have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
