<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-2N     06-10 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: been through.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though delivered in solemn tones, as befits a historic message
proclaiming victory in war, Clinton's message contained
considerable satisfaction and relief.
</P>
<P>
   He praised NATO for having remained steadfast through its first
united military action, an achievement often doubted as the 19
member nations struggled for unanimity through the increasingly
troubling campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has achieved the campaign as a united alliance,'' Clinton
said. ``Nineteen democracies came and stayed together through the
stiffest military challenge in NATO's 50-year hist/ry.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also emphasized that not a single soldier was
killed in combat, and he noted that the Russians, for all their
opposition to the allied bombing, had been instrumental in its
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also stressed that ``formidable challenges'' lay
ahead. He said NATO remained ready to resume attacks should the
Yugoslavs falter in their withdrawal; he described the enormity of
the problem of bringing back hundreds of thousands of Kosovo
refugees to destroyed homes; he spoke of the problem of
demilitarizing the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The 50,000 NATO peacekeeping soldiers, including 7,000
Americans, still face possible casualties in Kosovo. And there is
the daunting challenge of rebuilding a region battered by war,
hostility and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union and the United States must plan for
tomorrow, not just today,'' he said, pointedly adding, ``Our
European partners must provide most of the resources for this
effort, but it is in America's interest to do our part as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the brief address, however, the president's dominant
theme was that when people were repressed for their religion and
nationality, ``the world did not look away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have sent a message of determination and hope to all the
world,'' Clinton said. ``Tonight I ask you to be proud of your
country, and proud of the men and who serve. In Kosovo we did the
right thing, and we did it the right way, and we will finish the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   While considerable questions and criticism persist _ including
charges from congressional Republicans that the withdrawal of
Yugoslav troops had been achieved at exorbitant cost, and that
rebuilding Kosovo and Serbia would cost many billions more _ the
administration seems satisfied at this juncture to relish the fact
that NATO forced Milosevic to back down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton claimed that the campaign had achieved its goals, which
included creating the conditions to bring home the refugees. But
that stood somewhat at variance with the fact that the purge of the
Albanians became systematic and much more extensive only after the
NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, in fact, Clinton declared that NATO's purpose was
to avert a ``humanitarian disaster'' in Kosovo and to prevent a
wider conflict. In the end, more than 850,000 Albanians were driven
out and many of their properties destroyed, and the stability of
neighboring Macedonia and Albania is not assured.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton declared that from the beginning, the
allies had three objectives in Kosovo, all of which had been met:
the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces, the deployment of a NATO-led
security force and the return of the Kosovars to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart,
said Clinton had made a series of calls to leaders of NATO and its
member countries, as well as President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, to
share the moment, but also to caution ``that there remains a great
deal of hard work to be done.'' On Friday Clinton is scheduled to
visit Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri, the staging base for B-2
sorties to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon news conference, Defense Secretary William Cohen
and Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
joined in trumpeting the victory with color briefing slides and a
videotape of retreating Yugoslav forces taken by an unmanned drone.
</P>
<P>
   They also provided the most detailed accounting to date of what
allied planes had destroyed: 450 artillery pieces, 220 armored
personnel carriers, 120 tanks, more than half of Yugoslavia's
military industry, and 35 percent of the country's electrical
power.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-3R     06-10 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: electrical power.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The officials said allied warplanes had flown 35,000 missions,
including just under 10,000 bombing runs, dropping 23,000 bombs and
missiles. About a third of these were guided weapons, dropped
largely by B-52 and B-1 bombers against Yugoslav troops in the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic miscalculated badly,'' Shelton said. ``He did not
believe that NATO would carry through on its threat to use air
power, and he surely did not expect that the alliance could sustain
and increase that effort as the operation progressed over the last
79 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction and relief were even more evident in an earlier
statement by Clinton in which he thanked various participants in
the military and diplomatic drama of the past month and a half.
``There are so many people to thank,'' he began, borrowing a tone
from awards ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   From his own team, he singled out Vice President Al Gore, who
had the most to fear politically from a conflict that threatened to
stretch into his presidential campaign, but now could claim that he
had contributed to the peace through his camaraderie with the
Russian envoy, Victor Chernomyrdin. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, reportedly the most hawkish administration official on
Kosovo, was praised by Clinton for her ``passionate commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The president reserved the highest praise for Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser, ``who has barely slept for the last
three months.''
</P>
<P>
   All those he named had come under varying degrees of criticism
for the operation, and in naming them Clinton appeared to be
vindicating their judgment. But while there was general agreement
that Clinton and his lieutenants could feel satisfaction at their
escape from potential disaster, there was no certainty that they
would harvest long-term political benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Already through the jubilation, the critics could be heard. At a
congressional debate on financing the security forces, Republicans
took turns casting aspersions on the claims of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to go in there and do what we have done is
unconscionable,'' said Rep. Randy Cunningham, R-Calif. ``We have
killed civilians. That is not a win. Hundreds of thousands of
people are refugees. That is not a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Souder, R-S.C., declared, ``After 11 weeks of bombing
we have a settlement we probably could have achieved at the
beginning. If this is a victory, what would defeat look like?''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Manzullo, R-Ill., said: ``Milosevic is still in power. We
have destroyed a country. This war should never have been
started.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also continuing criticism from experts on foreign
policy, though some acknowledged they had been wrong in their
conviction that bombs alone would not bring Milosevic to heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would sum it up this way,'' said Leslie Gelb, president of
the Council on Foreign Relations: ``The feeling is the situation
was very bad to begin with, and NATO and the Clinton administration
made it worse, and much to the surprise of the critics, they came
out with a deal far better than anyone expected. But they got it at
a hell of a heavy cost, and because of that, people aren't going to
give President Clinton credit for `success.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon news conference, Cohen said the Defense
Department would request additional spending from Congress to pay
for the 7,000 American troops who are to join the NATO force.
Congress has already approved $5.5 billion in additional spending
through Sept. 30, for the air war only. Some unspent money will go
toward returning American aircraft and troops to their home bases,
and the rest will go toward the cost of the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be enough. Cohen declined to estimate how long
the Americans would remain in Kosovo, but he said it would cost
about $1.5 billion to $2 billion a year, roughly what it costs to
keep the 6,900 American peacekeeping troops still in Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
