r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABORSIDE-LABORSIDE_S     06-10 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABORSIDE-LABORSIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BILLS THAT HAVE LABOR BACKING  &HT;     ILANA DEBARE
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Here are some of the most significant bills before the California
Legislature being backed by labor unions this year:
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Daily Overtime Pay &LR; , AB60, Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles.
Reinstates the requirement that nonunion employers pay overtime
after workers put in eight hours in one day. Allows workers to vote
for alternative schedules such as four 10-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Family Sick Days &LR; , AB109, Knox. States that employers who offer
sick leave must allow workers to use half of their leave to care
for sick family members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Underground Economy and Sweatshops &LR; , AB633, Assemblyman Darrell
Steinberg, D-Sacramento. Increases penalties and enforcement
measures for employers who violate wage and hour laws. Allows
workers to file lawsuits (not just administrative claims) over wage
and hour violations. Increases the state's ability to enforce wage
laws in the garment industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Arbitration &LR; , AB858, Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Santa Monica.
Prohibits companies from requiring workers to submit employment
disputes to arbitration. (Doesn't apply to union contracts that
require arbitration.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; CalOSHA Reform,  &LR; AB1127, Steinberg. Increases penalties for
employers who knowingly violate state occupational health and
safety standards. Makes companies legally responsible for safety
violations that affect contract workers, not just their own regular
employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Age Discrimination &LR; , SB26, Senator Martha Escutia, D-Huntington
Park. Strengthens state laws against age discrimination. States
that it's not only illegal to make employment decisions based on
age, it's also illegal to make employment decisions that
disproportionately harm one age group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Workers' Compensation Increase,  &LR; SB320, Senator Hilda Solis, D-La
Puente, Los Angeles County. Increases the maximum weekly benefit
from $450 to $650 and requires benefit levels to rise as the cost
of living rises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Unemployment Insurance Increase &LR; , SB546, Solis. Increases the
maximum weekly benefit from $239 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; State Disability Insurance Increase &LR; , SB656, Solis. Increases the
maximum weekly benefit from $336 to $490.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Family Leave &LR; , SB1149, Senator Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough.
Current law requires companies with 50 or more workers to offer 12
weeks of unpaid leave for serious medical conditions, childbirth or
an ill family member. This bill extends the leave law to companies
with 20 or more workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Contractors' Rights,  &LR; SB1670, Senate Judiciary Committee. Extends
state anti-discrimination laws to contract workers, not just
regular employees. Also makes other changes to state
anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
