<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      06-10 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI QUESTIONS HOUSTON ATTORNEYS ABOUT MORALES, TOBACCO SUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional ending) 
 
By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The FBI has questioned at least three local lawyers as
part of a Houston-based investigation of former Attorney General
Dan Morales' handling of the state's multibillion-dollar tobacco
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   None of the lawyers contacted Thursday would say what agents had
asked them. But the witnesses include Joe Jamail, a high-profile
Houston attorney who has alleged that Morales improperly solicited
$1 million from each of several attorneys he considered hiring for
the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who was unavailable for comment Thursday, denied those
allegations when they were raised in a document filed in federal
court last year.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent inquiry is detailed in letters from John Cornyn,
Morales' successor as attorney general, authorizing five Houston
lawyers and one in Dallas to answer the FBI's questions. An agent
had asked Cornyn to waive the lawyers' obligation to the state
under attorney-client privilege, an ethical constraint.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the FBI witness list are Wayne Fisher, Ronald Krist, E.
William Barnett and William Slusser, all of Houston, and Dallas
attorney Tom Luce. None was hired to represent Texas in the tobacco
suit, but all were believed to have been considered by Morales for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Krist already have given FBI agents the details of
conversations they had with Morales. Krist said he was interviewed
as recently as last week, but neither he nor Fisher would discuss
details.
</P>
<P>
   Jamail said Thursday that he also has been interviewed by
federal investigators. He, too, declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Slusser declined to comment, and Barnett and Luce were
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston investigation is one of two stemming from the
landmark tobacco suit, which produced a $17.3 billion settlement
for Texas taxpayers but sparked a controversy over the fees paid
several private lawyers hired by Morales on contingency agreements
to help represent the state.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Umphrey, a plaintiffs' attorney from Beaumont who
eventually headed the team of private lawyers in the tobacco case,
said Thursday that he did not receive any improper solicitations
from the former attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't happen to us. All I know about it is what I
read in the papers,'' said Umphrey, who was not on the FBI's
witness list.
</P>
<P>
   Five well-known plaintiffs attorneys, including Umphrey, were
awarded a total of $3.3 billion by a national arbitration panel for
their work for the state. Those fees are to be paid by cigarette
companies.
</P>
<P>
   A separate federal investigation in Austin is looking into
Morales' hiring of another Houston lawyer, Marc Murr, in the
tobacco litigation. Morales tried to help Murr, a longtime friend,
collect hundreds of millions of dollars in legal fees although
other lawyers said Murr did little work in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Murr dropped a claim for $260 million in legal fees last month,
one day after Cornyn accused him and Morales of falsifying
signatures and backdating contracts that Murr purportedly had with
the state.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana formally dismissed
Murr's claim Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn _ in near-identical letters to Jamail, Fisher, Krist,
Barnett, Slusser and Luce in March _ said he had been contacted by
Michael Mee, an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, Cornyn said, ``asked me to consider waiving any
attorney client privilege which might exist between the state of
Texas and you concerning certain discussions in 1995 regarding your
possible employment in the tobacco litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn told the lawyers that no attorney-client privilege
existed because they were not hired to represent the state in the
tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly can appreciate the fact that you may be
uncomfortable discussing these matters with the FBI without an
express written waiver from this office. Thus, I want this letter
to confirm that you have my permission as the state's top lawyer to
discuss this matter with the FBI,'' Cornyn wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle obtained the letters from the attorney
general's office under an open records request this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jamail's allegations against Morales surfaced in a 1998
document, filed as part of an effort by seven state legislators to
block payment of what they considered ``excessive'' legal fees to
the Umphrey team of outside lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The document, prepared from memoranda provided by Jamail, said
the $1 million that Morales allegedly solicited from each lawyer
was ``purportedly for the purpose of defending General Morales
against possible attacks from the tobacco companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The document did not specify what types of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A Morales spokesman said last year that the only money that
Morales asked the lawyers to provide was for lawsuit expenses. Each
of the five lawyers in the Umphrey group agreed to risk $2 million
of their own money in return for a 15 percent contingency
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers later estimated they actually spent $40 million
during their two years of work on the case. Cigarette companies
have reimbursed them for that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Michael Gallagher, who was Fisher's law partner
in 1995, said he was called by a federal investigator several
months ago. But he said he could provide little information because
he never attended a tobacco-related meeting with Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said he and Fisher turned down an opportunity to
become involved in the lawsuit because they had some ``grave
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal source said the Houston investigation centers on
possible violations of the Hobbs Act. A Department of Justice
manual for prosecutors describes the 48-year-old law, with its
extortion element, as a tool used by federal law enforcement
agencies to combat state and local corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, to obtain a bribery conviction, prosecutors must show
that a payoff influenced the actions of a public official. But
under the Hobbs Act, prosecutors must show only that officials and
go-betweens took property or money ``that was not due them or their
office'' _ whether or not the payments had any real effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, previously undisclosed FBI documents in another
Houston case indicate that Morales initially lied to agents who
were investigating bribery allegations against former Houston City
Councilman Ben Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in his office March 20, 1997, Morales told FBI
agents Ronald Stern and Carlos Stella that he never talked to Reyes
about an official opinion on the eligibility of both convention
center hotel proposals for special tax benefits, according to the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reyes had urged Morales to issue an opinion favorable
to developer Wayne Duddlesten in a Dec. 13, 1995, letter, Morales
insisted he never discussed the matter with the then-councilman and
had not even seen Reyes in about two years.
</P>
<P>
   But agents returned to Morales' office three weeks later _ armed
with evidence of a Dec. 13, 1995, telephone conversation and a Dec.
19 meeting involving Morales, Reyes and an undercover FBI
operative.
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal document, Morales changed his statement
after agents Ronald Stern and John Bienkowski confronted him by
reading a portion of the Dec. 13, 1995, transcript in which the
opinion was discussed by Morales and First Assistant Attorney
General Jorge Vega.
</P>
<P>
   ``After hearing the quote, Morales stated that he did recall
having a conversation with Reyes over the telephone regarding the
convention center hotel. Morales recalled that Reyes wanted the
attorney general's opinion to allow the Duddlesten group to receive
the tax benefits associated with House Bill 2282,'' the document
states.
</P>
<P>
   Although Morales' Dec. 15, 1995, opinion was favorable to both
proposals, Morales has said he was not influenced by Reyes'
request.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Reyes and Betti Maldonado, the former Houston port
commissioner, were convicted of bribery after being caught in an
FBI sting that was linked to the hotel project. They plan to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
