r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-FORWIRES &LR;      06-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-FOR </SLUG>
 WIRES  
 Labor Unions Gain Ground in Legislature  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
We're not in a new century yet _ but when it comes to labor
legislation in California, it's starting to feel that way.
<P>
   Labor unions are making more headway in Sacramento than they
have in 16 years, and their efforts could change some aspects of
life on the job for everyone from working parents to independent
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Unions are backing an ambitious array of about 20 bills that
address issues such as overtime pay, civil rights for contract
workers, and using sick leave to care for sick kids.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the labor bills have sailed smoothly through either
the Assembly or Senate. More significantly, unions are hoping that
Democratic Governor Gray Davis will sign the bills once they've
been approved by both houses _ something that rarely happened
during the past 16 years of Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 16 years, the pendulum swung very far one way, so it's
time it swung back toward California workers,'' said Assemblyman
Darrell Steinberg, a Sacramento Democrat who is carrying several
major bills for the union movement. ``Labor is going to make gains
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Business groups, meanwhile, hope that Davis' efforts to carve
out a middle-of-the-road image will lead him to rein in or veto
some of the labor proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor has been very effective so far, but I do believe the
governor will be tempered in the number of bills he signs and what
he signs,'' said Jack Stewart, president of the California
Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   So far, labor has racked up two clear victories with Davis'
help.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, the governor signed a bill backed by state
construction unions that reversed an effort by former Governor Pete
Wilson to lower the wages paid on public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   And last month Davis' office weighed in to support AB60,  &LR; a bill
by Assemblyman Wally Knox, AB60, that would restore overtime pay
after eight hours _ one of labor's top priorities for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson administration had replaced California's longtime
eight-hour overtime law with one requiring overtime after a 40-hour
week.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions asked Knox, a Los Angeles Democrat, to carry a bill
repealing the change, which they said cost California workers about
$1 billion a year in lost overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   As the Assembly prepared to vote on the bill last month, Davis
pressed Knox to make some minor modifications in response to
employers' concerns. When the Assembly approved the bill with
Davis' amendments, the governor's signature became a near
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Labor activists cheered the progress of the legislation, AB &LR;  60,
 &LR; which still must win Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have a lot of work ahead of us, but union members
and working families are optimistic about the future,'' said Sharon
Cornu, a spokeswoman for the California Labor Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups remained unhappy about the bill, even with
Davis' amendments. ``It started out very badly and was reduced to
maybe simply bad,'' said Fred Main, senior vice president of the
California Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, labor and business are sparring on other issues that
could affect thousands of California workers:
</P>
<P>
   _Labor is pushing two work-related bills that were passed last
year but vetoed by Wilson. One of them AB109,  &LR; says that companies
offering sick leave must let workers use up to half their sick time
to take care of ill children.
</P>
<P>
   The other one SB 26,  &LR; would overturn a court case that weakened
state laws against age discrimination _ making it illegal to hire
or fire people in a way that disproportionately affects one age
group.
</P>
<P>
   _Labor is also pushing two complex bills AB 633 and AB 1127, &LR; 
 &LR; that would beef up penalties and enforcement procedures for
employers who violate wage laws or occupational safety laws.
</P>
<P>
   _Labor is supporting three bills to significantly increase
benefits for workers compensation, unemployment insurance, and
state disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _And labor is backing several measures that would give more
legal protection to independent contractors, who make up a growing
percentage of the workforce. One broad civil rights bill _ AB 1670
_  &LR; includes a section saying that contractors and regular employees
must be covered by state anti-discrimination laws. AB 1127,  &LR; An
occupational safety bill would make employers liable for safety
violations affecting contractors, not just employees.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups are attacking most of labor's measures as ``job
killers'' _ warning that they will force companies to shut down or
leave the state because of increased costs and paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   But despite business opposition, most of these bills will
probably be approved by the Legislature, both houses of which are
controlled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card remains Davis _ and how much he feels he can do
for his longtime allies in labor without jeopardizing his
middle-of-the-road image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally feel there are certain injustices that have to be
corrected,'' said Senator Martha Escutia, the Huntington Park (Los
Angeles County) Democrat who wrote the age discrimination bill.
``If the governor feels we're jamming him with too much (labor
legislation), that's his problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these bills will reach Governor Davis' desk,'' said
Main, ``but whether they will be vetoed or amended is the $64
question.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
