A0991 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRUS-VIRUS_SFCHRON &LR;      06-10 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-VIRUS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Melissa's Evil Twin Attacks PCs  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A virulent new computer program masquerading as e-mail has wiped
out the files of thousands of PC users in at least three countries.
<P>
   The ExploreZip.worm _ the latest in a string of malicious
Internet bugs that is drawing comparisons to the widespread Melissa
virus _ prompted the temporary shutdown of e-mail servers at
Microsoft, Intel and Lucent Technologies. Computer security experts
said they received scattered reports of data damage from AT&AMP;T,
Boeing and General Electric and consumers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Melissa's evil twin sister,'' said Brian McElroy,
senior product manager at Trend Micro Inc., an antivirus software
maker in Cupertino. ``It has a destructive payload.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It swept through here like a cyclone,'' said the employee of
one Fortune 500 company, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ExploreZip is classified as a worm, and not a virus, because it
can't replicate itself. Computer viruses like Melissa, which
surfaced in March, reproduce themselves. Melissa choked e-mail
servers with a deluge of messages but did not destroy data.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer strain, which originated mysteriously in
Israel, was discovered on Wednesday. It already has infected at
least 10,000 PCs at scores of companies in the United States,
Germany and France. Antivirus experts also have reported incidents
in Israel, South Africa, the Czech Republic, Peru and the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Like Melissa, ExploreZip is disguised as an e-mail that appears
to be a reply to an earlier message. ``Hi (Recipient Name)! I
received your e-mail and I shall send you a reply ASAP,'' the
message states. ``Till then, take a look at the attached zipped
docs.'' &UR;  &LR; (Zipped docs refer to a compressed file sent along with
e-mail.)
</P>
<P>
   If opened, the ``zipped--files.exe'' attachment infects the
e-mail software and destroys the content of Microsoft Word, Excel
and PowerPoint documents and programming files.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key issue here is that (these) messages are very credible
and normal-looking replies to messages you have sent earlier,''
said Mikko Hypponen, manager of antivirus research at Data Fellows
Corp. in San Jose. ``You're quite likely to trust these messages
and open the attachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer-security firm Network Associates has given ExploreZip a
``high risk'' classification _ its most dangerous. They said it
would take days before they could accurately assess damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs are becoming more sophisticated and more
deadly,'' said Wes Wasson, director of security product marketing
at Network Associates. ``(ExploreZip) doesn't spread as quickly as
Melissa, but it delivers a far more destructive payload.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melissa was a wake-up call,'' Wasson said. ``If it hadn't
opened our eyes to these types of worm programs, the damage from
this latest program would be far more severe.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Network Associates officials said they don't know who created
the new bug and have notified the FBI, the Department of Justice
and the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Mellon University's Computer Emergency Response Team in
Pittsburgh said it received 20 calls yesterday from victims of the
worm program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon to compare to Melissa, but we're taking it quite
seriously,'' said CERT spokesman Bill Pollak.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec, Network Associates' rival, said about a dozen U.S.
companies have been bitten by the ExploreZip bug, but it declined
to name those affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of one to four, this is about a two, maybe three,''
said Joe Wells, founder of the WildList Organization International
in Newbury Park, which tracks computer viruses. ``Melissa was a
four. With this new worm, you have to run a program; Melissa was
spread by simply clicking an attachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Security experts advise computer users to delete any suspicious
e-mail. They suggest companies block the destructive program by
shutting down e-mail servers and Internet gateways.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman said the software giant closed its
e-mail servers for precautionary reasons a few hours yesterday
morning. She said it found no signs of ExploreZip after
``cleaning'' its system.
</P>
<P>
   ExploreZip is the fourth cyberattack to wipe out data and
paralyze computer systems this year. Melissa, Chernobyl and
BackDoor-G already have wreaked havoc on thousands of computers.
Antidotes for all four programs are readily available via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
