<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-10 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell Gets OK to Raise Some Rates  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Insuring the telephone wiring inside your home and making a
person-to-person call is about to get more expensive under rate
increases approved yesterday by state regulators.
<P>
   The California Public Utilities Commission approved Pacific
Bell's request to increase ``inside wire repair'' insurance to
$1.20 per month from 60 cents per month. The PUC also granted Pac
Bell the right to raise rates on person-to-person calls to $4 from
$2.95.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also opens the door to more increases down the road
on other services such as collect and calling card calls.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the PUC approved Pac Bell's request to
recategorize many of its services as ``fully competitive.'' Pac
Bell can raise rates more easily on competitive services than on
regulated ones. Classifying services as competitive means that the
market dictates the rates _ not state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's meeting was the first one attended by two new &LR; 
 &LR; commissioners appointed on Wednesday by Governor Gray Davis. One
of the new appointees, Carl Wood, had not been sworn in and did not
vote. The other new commissioner, Joel Hyatt, abstained from the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, a temporary commissioner appointed last week, Loretta
Lynch, voted against the proposal, which passed 3-1. The proposal,
drafted by Commissioner Henry Duque, recommended increasing the
inside wiring fees and reclassifying services but rejecting Pac
Bell's request for rate increases on other services.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell had asked to raise the maximum rate it could charge for
collect calls to $1.60 from 95 cents, for calling card calls to 60
cents from 35 cents and for bill-to-third number calls to $1.60
from 95 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC said Pac Bell had not justified its need for higher
rates. But by reclassifying those services as competitive, &UR;  &LR; Pac
Bell can more easily raise the rates for those services in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not good for consumers,'' said Paul Stein, an attorney
with The Utility Reform Network, a consumer group in San Francisco.
``Reclassifying these services as competitive means the commission
would be very hard pressed to deny a request by Pac Bell to raise
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a spokesman for Pac Bell, said the company may
seek rate increases on collect and other calls in the future but
has no immediate plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, Pac Bell will increase the cost of inside
wire repair for the 6 million customers who pay for the service.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of Pac Bell's customers pay the monthly fee so
they can get phone wiring problems inside their homes fixed for
free by Pac Bell. Those who don't have the inside wire repair plan
can either pay Pac Bell for repairs or hire somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Britton praised the ruling, saying the company had been charging
less than what it costs to provide inside wire repair. Pac Bell had
asked the PUC to let it raise rates on the service to $1.50, but
Britton said the company was satisfied with $1.20.
</P>
<P>
   A PUC administrative law judge had recommended letting Pac Bell
raise inside wiring rates to just $1. Duque drafted the winning
proposal that allowed $1.20.
</P>
<P>
   The law judge's proposal, which was supported by consumer
groups, also recommended denying Pac Bell's request to reclassify
inside wiring as a competitive service. But Duque said Pac Bell had
proved that the inside wire market was open to competition so it no
longer needed to be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is virtually a monopoly service. There aren't many other
options besides Pac Bell for inside wiring,'' said Kelly Boyd,
senior telecommunications analyst with the Office of Ratepayer
Advocates, the consumer arm of the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, with TURN, said most customers don't even know they can
go to another company besides Pac Bell for wiring repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of confusion about this service,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that even with minimal competition, Pac Bell has not
lost any market share on inside wiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is supposed to bring lower prices and more
options, but so far, all we've seen are rate increases for basic
services,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Britton defended Pac Bell, saying customers are seeing the
benefits of competition. He pointed to ads in the Yellow Pages for
electricians who will work inside wiring as proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of other companies advertising for customers'
business,'' Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
