r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS_SFC     06-10 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKWAYS/ILANA DEBARE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Going From Big to Small 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have worked in field sales for a large corporation with $10
billion in annual sales revenues for almost five years. Recently,
the company went through a merger and I decided to leave. I am
currently in negotiation with a much smaller niche player with
about $25 million in annual sales. Any things I should bear in mind
when moving from such a large company to a smaller one?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hats off to you for asking this question. Too many people
change jobs without realizing they're also changing corporate
cultures _ and sometimes end up paying a steep price in gaffes or
misunderstandings. Here are a few tips from people who have worked
with both big and small companies:
</P>
<P>
   _Before you take the job, make sure you're comfortable with the
values and work style of the owner or chief executive. Even more
than at a big company, that person will set the tone for your daily
work life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to spend a lot more time with the person you work
for than if you were at a big company,'' said Igor Sill, an
executive recruiter with the Geneva Group International in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _Keep your antennae out for office politics. At big companies,
you can sometimes use an organizational chart to figure out who the
key players are. At small companies, titles are less meaningful:
The CEO's secretary may be the one who really controls the budget.
</P>
<P>
   _Be prepared to take risks. ``Small companies are interested in
growth, and growth depends on trying new things,'' said Jim Kouzes,
a management consultant with the Tom Peters Group in Palo Alto and
author of ``The Leadership Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   _Be willing to do more with less and to wear more hats than at
your previous job. ``Before, you may have had the resources to put
together a $300,000 marketing campaign, while now there may be a
$10,000 marketing budget for the whole company,'' said Roger King,
an executive recruiter with TechSearch in Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   _Button your lip when you're tempted to lecture people about the
way your old company did things. Sure, your old firm was big and
successful. But your new colleagues will get very sick, very fast,
of hearing, ``When I was at XYZ Corp., we did things this way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask people things _ don't tell them,'' said Mitchell Marks, a
San Francisco management consultant and author of ``Joining Forces:
Making 1+13 in Mergers and Acquisitions.'' ``Instead of saying that
your old company never had this many meetings, ask questions like
`Why do you have this meeting every month?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Taxes and the Baby Sitter
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have hired a baby sitter to care for my two children at
home after school. What kinds of tax papers do I need to file as
her employer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The short answer is: Probably more tax papers than you want.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with federal taxes, which are somewhat easier than
state taxes. If you pay the baby sitter less than $1,100 a year,
you don't have to pay any federal employment taxes, according to
Oakland accountant David Roberts. Or if she's taking care of the
kids in her own home _ rather than yours _ you don't have to pay
federal employment taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the sitter is earning more than $1,100 per
quarter while working in your home, you will need to obtain her
Social Security number and fill out a W-2 for her by January 31
each year. You don't need to withhold any federal taxes from her
paychecks. Instead, you can pay Social Security and Medicare taxes
for her once a year, by filing a Schedule H with your annual tax
return.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the considerably more complicated California state tax
picture. ``The state doesn't have the equivalent of Schedule H,
where you can just throw all the payroll taxes in with your annual
filing,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   If you pay the sitter less than $750 per quarter, you don't have
to file any state tax documents. But if you pay more than $750 per
quarter, you must file a registration form (DE 1HW) with the state
Employment Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   If your sitter is paid $750 to $999.99 per quarter, you must pay
state disability insurance. If she is paid $1,000 or more per
quarter, you must also pay unemployment insurance and employment
training taxes.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to file quarterly reports on your sitter's wages
with the state, but you may not have to make tax payments every
quarter. For example, if you pay her less than $20,000 per year,
you can make state payroll tax payments on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   More confused than ever? Call your local office of the state
Employment Development Department and ask for a copy of the 1999
Household Employers Guide (DE 8829). It's also available online at
 &LR; www.edd.cahwnet.gov &LR;   &LR; /De8829.pdf.  &LR; For U.S. taxes, see the IRS
Household Employer's Tax Guide (Publication 926) at
 &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
