<SLUG> BC-MED-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ED ARNOLD ON THE MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a page out of Ed Arnold's busy date book:
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday: Attend a board meeting for the Salvation Army. Serve
as MC for an entrepreneur of the year reception. Drop by a
children's hospital for a function featuring former Dodger Matt
Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Today: Finish jury duty. Attend a meeting regarding upcoming
events for the Boy Scouts of America. Serve as MC for the opening
ceremonies of the Southern California Special Olympics at Long
Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: Help organize a charity event for foster kids.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: Anchor KTLA's Sunday night sports show.
</P>
<P>
   Monday: Find a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Television's unquenchable need to fix things that aren't
necessarily broke claimed the 1968 Long Beach State grad late last
month. After 13 years as KTLA's reliable No. 2 sportscaster,
someone who brought more to the table than just scores, the station
decided it was time for a change. His last sportscast will be on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The reason provided was typically vague. Station management said
it wanted to go in a different direction and find someone with more
energy.
</P>
<P>
   The subtext? KTLA is an affiliate of the infant WB Network, and
its prime time programming (8-10 p.m.) is aimed at a young, urban
crowd. KTLA's Nielsen ratings for its 10 p.m. newscast have been in
decline for a while, losing viewers to competitors at KTTV (Fox)
and KCOP (UPN), whose news shows also follow programming aimed at
the young.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Arnold's misfortune was turning 59 and letting some of his
hair turn gray. The fact that he did good work and his charity work
was a tremendous resource for the station couldn't overcome his
birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, we all eventually face it, and my contract
was up,'' said Arnold this week between engagements. ``It does have
a lot to do with the programming. KTLA is trying to reach a
particular audience, and that factors into a lot of decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that likes to remake itself every few months, the
L.A. market sports-wise has been pretty static. The only major
personnel changes have been the arrival of Newy Scruggs at KCOP and
KABC's trade of Todd Donoho for Bill Weir. The only new sports
programming has been Scruggs' underpromoted and poorly scheduled
half-hour show on Sundays and KCBS' NFL-driven Sports Central.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold believes more fundamental change is coming, and it's not
good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consultants are playing way too much of a role in the
decisions for local news,'' he said, ``and one of their suggestions
is to cut back on sports. Jim Hill is getting little more than a
minute for sports on the 11 p.m. newscast at KCSB, and only KNBC is
regularly giving all the scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consultants say that no one cares, and that real sports
fans watch ESPN or Fox Sports News. But not everyone has 30 or 60
minutes to watch SportsCenter. Plus, whenever there's a major
sports story, it gets bumped to the top of the newscast.''
</P>
<P>
   Money could have been a factor in KTLA's decision. Even though
Arnold has always been cast as a No. 2 man, often by choice because
of his civic work, his contract reflects 30 years experience in the
market. (Tony Hernandez is KTLA's lead sportscaster.) The trend of
hiring young has the side benefit of smaller salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnold gave KTLA exceptional residual value with his more
than 200 days of charity work a year. It's one thing for viewers to
see his face on TV, and another altogether for potential viewers to
see his face in person at community events.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the aforementioned events, Arnold will be feted soon at
a Black Chamber of Commerce event; will host the Boys Scouts golf
tournament; will serve as grand marshall of a parade in Tustin; and
will host the annual Huntington Beach July 4 parade.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of a normal year, Arnold will also work for
the Goodwill Industries, March of Dimes, Marine Corp Toys for Tots,
cystic fibrosis, the Orange County Multiple Sclerosis Society,
Rancho Santiago College Foundation, fund drives at KCET and KOCE,
and Rotary and Friars events. He also was integral in a
fund-raising campaign that once saved 49er football, and has been
the regular announcer for the Tower of Power Sunday telecasts for
38 years.
</P>
<P>
   You tell me what's more valuable -- Arnold's steady sportscasts
and his community profile, or some wise ass sportscaster with video
of a squirrel who surfs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to retire,'' he said. ``My own long range goal
was to work at least until 2002. But I doubt if I'll get many TV
opportunities because of my age. Things aren't moving in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold will pinch-hit for some of the talk show hosts at radio
station KRLA in August and has received some other feelers from
radio. There is even a modest ``Save Ed'' campaign on the Internet
(home.digitalcity.com/Los Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's flattering,'' said Arnold. ``Hey, if things don't
work out, I'll just have more time to play with my two
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   ZAMBONIED: Fox Sports is preparing to bid adieu to the NHL, with
two Stanley Cup finals telecasts left (Games 5 and 7), if
necessary). The end will mark Fox's first losing effort since it
entered the sports realm.
</P>
<P>
   cf,hel,8,8.2 AND NOW THE NEWS Arnold, a native of Arkansas,
first visited Southern California while he was in the Marines and
never left. He served at El Toro for three years, then went right
to Santa Ana College (now Rancho Santiago) after his discharge. He
eventually wound up at Long Beach State, earning a degree in speech
and broadcasting. ... KCOP is expected to add Michelle Bonner as a
sports anchor sometime in July. She comes from Houston... KTTV will
air a postgame baseball show, Fox Extra Innings, after Fox Saturday
telecasts this season. Rick Garcia hosts. ... ESPN Classic will
debut a new one-hour show titled ``NBA Vintage'' next Thursday (8
p.m.), hosted by Robin Roberts and produced by NBA Entertainment. A
different current star will be linked to a legend, featuring
footage and interviews with both players. The first episode
features Julius Erving and Grant Hill. A future episode will
feature Jerry West and Kobe Bryant (July 1). Classic also airs a
U.S. Open marathon Saturday and Sunday in advance of the upcoming
1999 event next week. ... ESPN's Lee Corso and Kirk Herbstreit will
leave the safety of their studio to become the new co-analysts on
Thursday night college football games this fall. Thankfully, the
closest the insane Corso will get to L.A. is Oregon in the
season-opener (against Michigan State). ... Fox's baseball coverage
Saturday featuring interleague play earned a 3.2 Nielsen, up three
percent from Fox's previous high for its first telecast. Here's a
little statement on the status of baseball here while Fox earned a
10.0 rating for the Yankees-Mets in New Jack City, the
Dodgers-Angels game did a 4.1 locally. ... Fox's Hardcore Baseball
Tuesday will look at father-son combos, including the obvious
(Bonds, Griffey) and the more obscure, like Torrance's Jason
Kendall and his dad Fred. ... NASCAR rules! CBS has added a
half-hour prerace show (9:30 a.m.) to its coverage of a NASCAR race
from Michigan Saturday (10 a.m.), and it will provide a weeks worth
of drop-in NASCAR programming on prime time shows leading up to the
Pepsi 400 on July 3. ... Sunday's Tiger Woods-driven coverage of
the Memorial earned CBS a 3.8, the highest rating for the tourney
in a decade. ... Monday's edition of ``Real Sports'' on HBO takes a
look at the shaky relationship between baseball and its umpires.
... CBS has added former Toronto Blue Jays star Joe Carter to its
College World Series broadcast team. CBS will air Texas A&AMP;M-Florida
State Saturday and then the title game a week later. ESPN and ESPN2
provides the meat of the CWS coverage, including the Fullertons
against Stanford Saturday (5 p.m.). Harold Reynolds and Joe Morgan
will split analysis duty. ...
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD OF TV SPORTS ACCORDING TO ME: A suggestion in this
space a few weeks ago, that KXTA (1150 am) rerun an hour or two of
Jim Rome's show at noon instead of any live talk, caught fire with
several readers. Personal mail, phone calls and email indicates a
lot of Rome's fans sleep in, and that a rerun of The Jungle is
preferable to anything or anyone KXTA program director Mike
Thompson airs between Rome and Dodger games. ... Speaking of
XTRA/KXTA management, a pox on both houses for some erratic
programming decisions, like airing NBA playoff games on XTRA on
weekends but not during the week; for the over-the-top Dodger KXTA
pregame shows featuring Vic Jacobs, who set a new world record for
shilling by defending footloose Chan Ho Park; and for Saturday's
decidedly non-sport romance/sex talk show. What's up with that? ...
Confidential your-eyes-only memo to KCOP/KXTA double threat Newy
Scruggs: Save yourself ... Here's a trend to mull: Fox's NHL
coverage in cities like Birmingham are outdrawing major cities like
Chicago, New York and Philadelphia that have NHL teams. I'd
classify this as bad news, not good. Major market tune out is
deadly. ... The X Games begin June 27 on ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC. Plan
your vacations accordingly.
</P>
