<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JUDGMENT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FAMILY WINS $234 MILLION JUDGMENT AGAINST RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ED ASHER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Texas family who claimed that ancestral property in
St. Petersburg, Russia, was illegally seized has won a $234 million
judgment against the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Lee Alexander Magness and his mother and aunt
said the government expropriated the property twice, after the
Russian revolution in 1917 and again in 1994 after the family
reclaimed it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Hittner, who had earlier rejected the
Magness request to hold a Romanov jewel exhibit touring this
country as collateral, awarded the damages this week.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the Russian Embassy and the Russian
Federation's attorney, Tim Dickinson, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we can collect the judgment,'' said the
Magness attorney, Daniel B. Nelson. ``There are post-judgment
methods and remedies we can undertake. But I don't want to discuss
that at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Magness' mother, Nina Schroder Magness, and aunt, Agnes Schroder
Atkins, are daughters of Johann Schroder, who in 1917 owned three
valuable properties in St. Petersburg: the K.M. Schroder Piano
Factory, now known as the Red October Factory; a retail shopping
center and a 30-room downtown mansion, Hittner said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   All were seized by the communists after the Bolshevik revolution
in 1917, he said. The family claimed the property then was worth
more than 16 million gold rubles, or about $162 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of communism, the Russian government initiated
reforms, including laws that prohibited the nationalization or
expropriation of foreign investments, Hittner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Magnesses traveled to St. Petersburg in 1994 to reclaim the
family fortune. After presenting historic documents showing they
were Schroder's heirs, the family was assured by Russian
authorities that they would receive titles to the property,
Hittner's ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Magness also purchased two antique Schroder pianos, one
built in 1889 and the other in 1910, according to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Later in 1994, the Russian Federation claimed that all of the
properties were ``national treasures'' or ``historical'' in nature
and expropriated them, Hittner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Magness family sued in 1997 to stop the Russian Ministry of
Culture from removing a touring $100 million Romanov jewel exhibit
from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The jewels belonged to Russia's ruling Romanov family overthrown
by the communists.
</P>
<P>
   After Hittner refused to stop the tour, the Magness family
pressed on with its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Hittner's ruling said the Russian government's seizure of the
Schroder property violated international law.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the family was never compensated.
</P>
<P>
   Hittner also awarded Lee Magness $400,000 for the two pianos.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of his ruling, interest on the award is building at
an estimated $31,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
