u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUS-AIR-SHOW-SPI &LR;      06-10 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-AIR-SHOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS OUT TO MAKE A BIG SPLASH AT PARIS AIR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the next week, at least, a bullish Airbus
Industrie has the home field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say it's a no-brainer that the European
airplane-maker will be out to make a splash _ and a statement that
it has arrived as The Boeing Co.'s equal _ when the world's biggest
air show opens Saturday at Le Bourget field outside of Paris, where
Charles Lindbergh landed his Spirit of St. Louis in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 30th anniversary of the launch at the 1969 Paris Air
Show of the A300, the first jetliner Airbus built in what then
appeared to be a Don Quixote quest to one day be the equal of
mighty Boeing in commercial aviation.
</P>
<P>
   But The Boeing Co. will not go quietly into the night at the
last big air show of the millennium. Although the aerospace giant
is well behind Airbus in announced new orders this year, it is
expected to have improved its anemic order book by the time the
show ends next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will announce at least one ``significant'' order in
Paris, which involves a mix of next generation 737s and other
models, according to people familiar with the deal. In addition,
Boeing has several smaller orders to announce. But one order that
Boeing had been counting on from China Airlines may not be
finalized in time to be announced in Paris as hoped, sources said.
China Airlines, the largest carrier in Taiwan, has been negotiating
with Boeing for up to a dozen 747s. The order would be worth as
much as $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Boeing and Airbus both have used the Paris show
to beef up their order books.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Boeing has announced firms orders for 52
planes worth $3.9 billion. Airbus has announced firm orders for 153
planes.
</P>
<P>
   That represents a sharp decline for both airplane makers from
1998, when Boeing had 656 orders and Airbus had 556. After several
boom years, the industry cycle has clearly turned, in part due to
the Asian economic crisis and the fact that many of the major
airlines have already placed orders for new Airbus or Boeing planes
to replace aging fleets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has been doing very well at winning narrow-body
airplane orders,'' said analyst Peter Jacobs of Seattle's Ragen
MacKenzie. ``Right now, as was the case in 1998, narrow body orders
are a much higher percentage of overall orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boeing's orders are down, the company is in much
better shape than it was two years ago when production problems led
to several billion dollars in write-offs. Those problems continued
for much of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will deliver a record 620 planes this year, compared with
fewer than 300 for Airbus, and analysts say the Seattle-based
company is doing what it needs to do to regain its financial
footing and its reputation on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have said they will no longer compete with
Airbus for market share if it means they can't make money on the
planes they sell.
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry remains intense, and this year it will play out
during the air show against the backdrop of several developing
stories that will occupy much of the industry talk at Paris.
</P>
<P>
   One of those stories is the future of Boeing's 717.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will use the event to showcase the newest and smallest
member of its jetliner family. The 100-seater so far has had
disappointing sales. To try and find more customers, Boeing will
take the plane on a 10-day European tour after the air show as part
of an intense marketing blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say this could be the last chance for the 717
to prove itself, and Boeing could decide to kill the Long Beach,
Calif.-based program if sales don't pick up.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus answer to the 717 is the A318, which is not yet in
production, and Airbus plans a media briefing at Paris to tout the
virtues of its plane.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, what amounts to civil war has broken out
within the Airbus consortium over the development of the A318.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four Airbus partners, Aerospatiale Matra of France
and Daimler Chrysler Aerospace of Germany, are squabbling over the
allocation of work for the new plane. Though Airbus officials
declined comment, the respected industry publication Flight
International reported this week that there is even confusion
whether the Airbus board actually gave its approval for the launch
of the A318. Airbus boss Noel Forgeard officially announced the
launch of the A318 in April.
</P>
<P>
   The four Airbus partners have been trying for some time to
transform the consortium into a single corporate entity to better
compete with Boeing. That transformation was to have taken place
this year, but progress has been slowed by political bickering.
</P>
<P>
   The latest spat could work in Boeing's favor as it pushes the
717. Industry executives and analysts will be paying close
attention to anything Airbus officials have to say in Paris about
the reported A318 rift, and the progress towards turning Airbus
into a single corporate entity.
</P>
<P>
   Another story that will be followed closely at the Paris show is
the proposed A3XX super jumbo jet that Airbus has been talking
about for several years. This is the plane Airbus needs to break
Boeing's stranglehold on jetliners that can carry more than 400
passengers. The A3XX would carry as many as 600 people. But the
development costs are least $10 billion, and perhaps as high as $15
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Boeing decided not to proceed with the
development of a similar-size jumbo jet, arguing the worldwide
market is not big enough to recover the staggering developement
costs. Boeing's latest long-range market forecast, which the
company plans to make public Monday at the air show, reportedly
shows that the market for a super jumbo has declined to fewer than
400 planes, according to a person familiar with the forecast. The
forecast looks at the commercial aircraft market for the next 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   While commercial aviation will make news at Paris, so will the
defense side of the aerospace industry. The airshow opens just days
after NATO's long air war against Yugoslavia ended.
</P>
<P>
   The ear-splitting thunder of fighters will fill the skies daily
over Le Bourget field. Lockheed Martin's F-16 will be at Paris, as
will the Eurofighter and Russian fighters.
</P>
<P>
   But missing from Paris this year will be any fighter with
Boeing's name on it. Because of the air war over Yugoslavia, the
U.S. military could not spare either an F-18 Hornet or an F-15
Eagle, a Boeing spokesman said. Both fighters are built by Boeing
in St. Louis have been used extensively in the air campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
