u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      06-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES `FORMIDABLE CHALLENGES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton savored victory while warning of
the ``formidable challenges'' ahead in the Balkans as he addressed
the nation Thursday for the first time since Serb troops agreed to
leave war-torn Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal to Serbians, he suggested they replace President
Slobodan Milosevic if they expect help in rebuilding their bombed
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demands of an outraged and united international community
have been met,'' Clinton said in a prime-time televised address on
the same day that NATO forces verified Serb troop withdrawals from
Kosovo and halted the 79-day bombing campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can report to the American people that we have achieved a
victory for a safer world, for our democratic values and for a
stronger America,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said challenges remain as NATO forces enter Kosovo
to ensure the return of ethnic Albanian refugees and to maintain
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   While the president noted there were no direct U.S. combat
casualties during the bombing campaign, he said ``this next phase
also will be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitter memories may still be fresh and there may well be
casualties.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the United States will contribute 7,000 of the
50,000 peacekeeping soldiers in Kosovo, which will be under NATO
control.
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of Clinton's 15-minute speech was aimed at a
domestic audience, he also directed part of his message at Serbs,
suggesting that their suffering was due to the ``ethnic cleansing''
policies engineered by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should know that your leaders could have kept Kosovo part
of your country without driving a single Kosovar family from its
home, without killing a single adult or child, without inviting a
single NATO bomb to fall on your country,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He further suggested that until Milosevic is removed, the Serbs
may continue to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he remains in power, as long as your nation is
ruled by an indicted war criminal, we will provide no support for
the reconstruction of Serbia,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We are ready to provide humanitarian aid now and
help build a better future for Serbia, too, when its government
represents tolerance and freedom, not repression and terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended NATO's military air campaign, saying that ``we
have averted the wider war this conflict might well have sparked.''
</P>
<P>
   And clearly with an eye on his own legacy, the president said:
``Because of our resolve, the 20th century is ending, not with
helpless indignation, but with a hopeful affirmation of human
dignity and human rights for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's address capped a day devoted to thanking aides
and international allies while pounding out details of the
complicated NATO peace effort in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Clinton continued to deal with complications at
home as some Republicans in Congress sought unsuccessfully to limit
funding for the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike earlier in the week, when the administration remained
wary about commenting on the peace process, the White House
appeared ready Thursday to begin the victory lap.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton appeared before reporters in the
White House briefing room to announce the suspension of the NATO
air campaign and the beginning of the Serb withdrawal from the
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt vindicated by the bombing's success, the
president responded: ``The United States should feel vindicated
when the people go home, and when they're safe and when we can say
that we, as a nation, have played a role in reversing `ethnic
cleansing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The president spent much of the day calling many of the world
leaders that have stood with him during a sometimes unpopular
military campaign. Among the first to hear from Clinton was British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who has been a firm U.S. ally and among
the most hawkish proponents of the use of military force.
</P>
<P>
   The president also spoke to the Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
of Italy, from where many of the bombing missions were staged, and
President Jacques Chirac of France, whom he will visit next week.
</P>
<P>
   He also telephoned Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who was
critical of NATO's bombing campaign but who later was instrumental
in helping forge the peace accord with the Serb leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a somewhat strained relationship with the
congressional GOP leadership, which has been less than supportive
of the bombing, Clinton spoke to leaders of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton also chatted
with Wesley Clark, supreme commander of NATO, and told him that
``the future is now what we need to concentrate on.''
</P>
<P>
   In his conversation with Blair, Clinton also was moving on to
the next step, speaking about the urgency to get a civilian
administration up and running in Kosovo, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Clinton stressed the challenges that
remain ahead, including the operational difficulties of moving in a
50,000-person peace force.
</P>
<P>
   Also mindful of Milosevic's dubious record of credibility,
Clinton warned that the bombing could resume if the Yugoslav army
failed to live up to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we have to make sure that Serbs keep their
commitments,'' he said. ``That means the forces must rapidly and
peacefully leave Kosovo under the agreed timetable, 11 days from
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will continue in a celebratory mode today as he travels
to Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri to thank military personnel.
Whiteman is the home of the 509th Bomb Wing and was the staging
base for the B-2 bomber sorties to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
