<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      06-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R.J. REYNOLDS PLANS DIVIDEND AFTER SEPARATION FROM NABISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To ease the separation anxiety investors may feel
when R.J. Reynolds leaves RJR Nabisco behind, the company is
planning to dispense a generous dividend.
</P>
<P>
   Though RJR has refused to say how big that payout will be, a
tobacco company stock analyst for Goldman, Sachs estimates it will
be $3.25 a share this year. That would be a whopping 9.7 percent
yield based on the when-issued price Thursday of $33.375 a share
for RJR, which has been part of RJR Nabisco for 14 years but will
stand as its own company and its own stock on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Cohen, the Goldman analyst, forecasts about $6.50 a share
in cash earnings at the tobacco company and expects the dividend to
be at least half that amount. ``It's  &UR; very &LR;  generous,'' Cohen said
of the anticipated payout.
</P>
<P>
   The RJR board, which has only filled five of its nine seats
according to a recent securities filing, will meet this summer to
decide the dividend. A company spokeswoman, Maura Payne, would not
comment on Cohen's estimate and said no dividend policy had been
established yet.
</P>
<P>
   A big payout could help soothe jittery investors. The tobacco
giant has been battered by a string of costly settlements and could
be subject to much more litigation, including a lawsuit from the
federal government that President Clinton discussed in his State of
the Union Message.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's estimate puts the payout ahead of that on the 30-year
Treasury bond, now yielding 6.06 percent, and much greater than
that on the average stock in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index,
which is 1.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be far higher than the 4.17 percent from Philip
Morris. RJR Nabisco now has a 6.34 percent dividend yield, while
Nabisco gives shareholders 1.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect the spun-off RJR to be a vigorous company,
able to maintain that size payout. Long burdened by billions of
dollars of debt from the 1988 leveraged buyout of RJR Nabisco by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., the tobacco company will be
competing against its archrival, Philip Morris, for the first time
with money to spend on marketing its brands, including Camel,
Winston, Salem and Doral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're on the same playing field, and RJR is definitely
in a position to compete,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a global
consumer-products analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``What you had
previously was Philip Morris in another stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco is also contracting, with plant closings commonplace and
sales volume shrinking. Takeover opportunities have largely dried
up. Thus tobacco companies tend not to face big capital
expenditures, Goldman noted. ``If you don't have the capital
needs,'' he said, ``and you aren't planning to acquire anything, it
makes sense to pay out to your shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   On RJR's books, as the curtain rises, is some $2 billion in cash
left over after RJR Nabisco sold its international division to
Japan Tobacco and paid down $6 billion of debt that had been on
RJR's balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The $8 billion sale was announced in March, along with the news
that the domestic tobacco division would be spun off. The plan
prompted a brief protest from Carl C. Icahn, RJR Nabisco's biggest
shareholder, who nominated his own board but dropped the effort
before the annual meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said that shareholders would be better off if the Nabisco
food holdings were a separate company, instead of tobacco. He
expressed concern that Nabisco would be subject to future tobacco
lawsuit claims should RJR be unable to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Steven F. Goldstone, the outgoing chief executive of RJR
Nabisco, disputed that suggestion. ``Nabisco would take the point
of view that they were never in the tobacco business,'' he said in
a recent interview in his office, where he has a cabinet for the
Mallomars, Wheat Thins, Lifesavers and other Nabisco brands and a
separate one _ much farther from his desk _ for the cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm separating these businesses for financial and strategic
reasons,'' he said, ``not for legal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, RJR Nabisco, whose stock symbol was RN, ceases to
exist. The stock rose 56.25 cents Thursday, to $32.3125. The
tobacco company will be traded as RJR, and the holding company
becomes NGH. And whether the promise of a hefty dividend is enough
to guarantee investors' loyalty _ even a dividend described as
``attractive, competitive and sustainable'' in the road show now
making the rounds _ remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
