<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CAMBY-NYT &LR;      06-10 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CAMBY REJUVENATED, A LOST SEASON IS SAVED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In late March, with the New York Knicks floundering, Coach Jeff
Van Gundy spoke to his players before a practice in Sacramento,
Calif. The one Knick singled out most for sacrificing playing time
in the name of the team was Marcus Camby, the 24-year-old forward
who privately wondered if he would have a chance to show off his
skills.
</P>
<P>
   If Van Gundy thought he was staving off a young player's
frustration with genuine praise, Camby perceived the coach's words
to mean something totally different. He believed Van Gundy was
stroking his ego for no other reason than to prepare Camby for not
playing more minutes during the team's Western road swing.
</P>
<P>
   The level of mistrust between the two became a prism for the
once-fractured Knicks, who less than two months ago were all on
separate pages.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, with Camby lifting his arms to the Madison Square
Garden rafters and leading their rejuvenation, the Knicks have an
opportunity to become the first eighth-seeded team in league
history to advance to the National Basketball Association finals.
With a 3-games-to-2 lead over Indiana, they can wrap up the Eastern
Conference final and continue their surprising post-season surge.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of Camby in New York _ from disgruntled role
player to skyscraping star _ is extraordinary and stunning.
Replacing one of the most popular Knicks of the last two decades,
Charles Oakley, Camby was scrutinized and pilloried more than New
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the notion that this doe-eyed 7-footer would
emerge as the most terrorizing force in the series seemed
far-fetched. But the disbelief has disappeared as Camby has
scorched the Pacers by averaging 14.2 points, 11 rebounds and 3
blocked shots against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a gift that a lot of us wish we had,'' said Chris
Childs, the Knicks' point guard. ``That age and that height. As
long as he continues to work _ we told him from Day 1 to go as hard
as you can and play the game like you know how to play it _
everything will fall in place.''
</P>
<P>
   How a player noted for poor work ethic and inconsistency in
Toronto developed into an elastic, shot-blocking demon over the
last five months is a tale not only of perseverance, but maturity,
tolerance and, above all, patience.
</P>
<P>
   Camby demonstrated that rare virtue for a young athlete in his
Game 5 demolition of Indiana on Wednesday night, biding his time on
the bench for 10 minutes in the third quarter as Van Gundy waited
to insert him back into the game after a stirring first half in
which he picked up three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about managing fouls with our big guys as much as we
can,'' Van Gundy said today. ``Certainly, his play warranted him
playing earlier. But I didn't want him to be at risk with four
fouls, because I wanted him to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 21 points, 13 rebounds and 6 blocked shots,
leading New York to a 101-94 victory before a stunned and almost
angry crowd at Market Square Arena. Along with Latrell Sprewell,
Allan Houston and Larry Johnson, this kid with arms that go on
forever had pinned their team's best shots against the glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just itching to get back in there,'' Camby said. ``You
always want to get in there and play, but I just have to be patient
like I have done all year. When I got in there, I just wanted to
make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   When Camby was acquired last June for the popular Oakley, Dave
Checketts, the Madison Square Garden president, said that it was
the most difficult move he had ever made. But Checketts also made a
point to insure his critics that it would ultimately be the right
move, that Camby would be the kind of player to help scale the
emerging power in the East, the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, more than anyone, understood how hard that thought
would be for fans to digest. He returned to his Connecticut home
the night of the deal and informed his wife, Deb, that the team had
moved Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You traded Oak?'' Deb asked incredulously. ``What are you,
crazy? He was New York. He was the Knicks. You can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby did not make the adjustment easier when he reported to
training camp in less-than-perfect shape. He quickly became the
flashpoint for a covert feud between the former general manager,
Ernie Grunfeld, and Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Having staked his professional reputation on acquiring Camby for
the workmanlike Oakley, Grunfeld wanted Camby to play more minutes.
Van Gundy wanted Camby to earn those minutes, and refused to
compromise on what he thought was best for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Winning seems to cure all ills, and Camby appears to have set
aside whatever reservations he had about Van Gundy. But there was a
time they spoke infrequently.
</P>
<P>
   Whether there is a lingering residue of resentment is unclear.
Because Camby did not blossom until late in the season, his agent,
Alex Johnson, did not have the leverage to secure the maximum $78
million contract extension for his client this past February.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Camby signed for an incentive-laden deal worth $48
million, $32 million of which is guaranteed. Essentially, by not
waiting to sign in the off season, Camby may have lost about $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, who is to say how much Camby's perseverance _
proving he belonged and earning his minutes on a playoff-hardened
team _ enriched his development as a player?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond practice wars, he began working long hours with the
conditioning coach, Greg Brittenham, to increase strength, stamina
and flexibility. Soon, all the old labels heaped on Camby in
Toronto _ too soft, too carefree and lack of desire _ began to
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing for Marcus was when people in the
organization were publicly questioning him,'' said Rick Kaplan, who
serves as Camby's media relations adviser. ``He felt the whole
time, other than Day 1 of training camp, he did everything that was
asked of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then to be asked about Oakley every day, it was tempting
for him to blow up, say something. But he never pouted. Truthfully,
I didn't know if he had it in him. For him to go through all this
and play like he's playing, it's inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   The gifted physical specimen who single-handedly has rejected
the Pacers over the last 10 days has been a work in progress,
growing, maturing and getting better every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus has been great in this series,'' said Van Gundy, who
had little time to work with Camby this season due to the labor
strife between the players and owners. ``I don't know if he's
better than I expected. I really didn't know him as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``I didn't see him much in Toronto, and the
lockout hurt. The thing that he's done all season is make steady
progress, especially his conditioning. He's felt more comfortable
and gotten more minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he stands one game from the finals, looking taller and more
talented than ever.
</P>
<P>
   There is delicious twist here: The player whom Van Gundy once
had the least amount of faith in became trustworthy enough to help
save the Knicks' season and perhaps the coach's job. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
