<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSCOW-DEBTS-560(2TAK     06-10 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-DEBTS-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBTS TROUBLING MOSCOW'S MR. FIX-IT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a nation where not much seems to work, the
all-powerful mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, has earned a reputation
as Mr. Fix-it.
</P>
<P>
   After inheriting a grimy Soviet museum piece of a city in 1992,
he has, with plenty of political elbow grease and borrowed money,
turned it into something almost befitting its status as one of
Europe's largest cities. Russians approve, and now Luzhkov is among
the early favorites to succeed Boris Yeltsin as the country's next
president.
</P>
<P>
   And so the conversations unfolding lately between Luzhkov's
aides and some European bankers are far more interesting than the
typical banker-borrower face-off. For transforming Moscow has cost
billions of dollars, and suddenly Luzhkov's can-do government is
having trouble paying the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's immediate troubles come from three German and Swiss
banks that lent the city $200 million in 1997, then quickly got
cold feet. Instead of the leisurely repayment plan initially
envisioned, the banks grasped an escape clause and demanded half
their money back last year, and the rest _ with interest _ by next
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The acting director of the Moscow City Loan Committee, Sergei
Pokhomov, says the city will hand over every cent ``in an orderly
and civilized manner.'' But not by Thursday's deadline. The money
simply isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   The city did make a $23.8 million interest payment on a Eurobond
loan on May 31. Defaults on Eurobonds are almost unheard of; next
to repudiating a nation's sovereign debt, nothing ruins a
government's credit rating faster or for longer.
</P>
<P>
   Pokhomov nevertheless declined to guarantee that the city would
always meet such lofty obligations. ``The only thing I can say is
that there will be a desperate search for money, and I can't
exclude our having certain problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Luzhkov's political ambitions, this cash crunch
could not have come at a worse time. His well-laid plan was to
breeze to re-election as mayor, then hit the presidential campaign
trail next spring.
</P>
<P>
   But forces opposed to his presidential bid _ among them,
apparently, Yeltsin _ gummed up that strategy last month by
fielding a mayoral opponent, former Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko. Kiriyenko immediately said he would make an issue of
Luszkov's management of Moscow, where, he charged, nothing gets
done without a bribe and the city's finances are suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing as Kiriyenko was in charge when Russia's own economy
collapsed last August, that may not seem a stroke of political
genius. But Kiriyenko may have struck a nerve: Luzhkov's spokesman
was forced to deny rumors that the City Council moved up the
mayoral election to beat a looming default on the city's debt. And
Kiriyenko was far ahead of Luzhkov in a recent poll.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the mayor is to blame can be debated, but there is
little question that Moscow is in a fiscal bind. During Russia's
brief go-go days, the city built and renovated with abandon thanks
to nearly $2 billion in loans from Western banks and investors who,
like Luzhkov, believed the boom would endure. It did not, and now
as the loans come due, Moscow is paying a heavy price.
</P>
<P>
   An example: The $200 million loan European bankers are trying to
reclaim was worth about a billion rubles when Moscow got the money
in 1997. Today, repaying that principal would cost 5 billion
rubles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the city might borrow Western currency elsewhere.
But Westerners are so gun-shy of Russia, Pokhomov says, that they
are already snatching back their old loans.
</P>
<P>
   The city could simply walk away from the loan, but only to its
own ruination. Much of Moscow's foreign debt, including $1 billion
in Eurobonds, contains clauses allowing other lenders to call their
loans should the city stiff even one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems to know how likely default is, because nobody
outside Luzhkov's aides has a complete grasp of Moscow's finances.
His unique approach to budgeting includes a public accounting for
many run-of-the-mill expenses, but conceals the rest _ perhaps 40
percent of all spending _ in a rat's nest of accounts he often
personally controls.
</P>
<P>
   That unaccountable cash helped Luzhkov jump-start Moscow's
economy _ and create new streams of revenue _ by putting city
property and money into an empire of construction projects and
businesses. The city has stakes in 500 Moscow companies and
controls nearly 200 of them outright
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how many of those investments have soured since
last August's fiscal collapse, because most of their books are not
open.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant underground mall opposite the Kremlin, which soaked
up $425 million in city money, has shifted from upscale shops to
less classy retailing. Outside experts say it has been a drain on
the city treasury, though city officials disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The Zil truck plant in Moscow, beneficiary of some $60 million
in loans, employs 23,000 workers and, according to The Moscow
Times, produced less than one truck per employee in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bank of Moscow lost $250 million _ more than a quarter
of its assets _ when the August crash rendered government bonds
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Moscow City Council's budget committee,
Michael Vyshegorodtsev, said in an interview that the Council was
determined to take more direct control of the off-the-books
accounts. But he said that fiscal collapse has not made the city's
many businesses unprofitable, ``just less profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscow will need whatever profits it can find to pay the
mountain of debt facing it in the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In written answers to questions, city officials said last month
that Moscow has made $255 million in loan payments since the crash
last August, not including May's Eurobond payment. Two more
Eurobond interest payments, totaling about $40 million, are due in
November.
</P>
<P>
   All told, domestic and foreign loan payments comprise a
manageable 10 percent or so of the 1999 city budget of 73 billion
rubles, or $3 billion. But that does not account for inflation,
more than 20 percent so far this year, which would raise the cost
of loan repayments and government services alike.
</P>
<P>
   The city clearly feels the pinch. Spending for items like
building restorations and traffic lights has been slashed, and the
next budget will be even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   From a political point of view _ no small matter to a
presidential hopeful _ there may not be a lot of choice. Luzhkov
already has had to put his populist image at risk, boosting rents,
utility rates and the sales tax to replace revenue lost to the
economic downturn. Once he could have looked to his mentor Yeltsin
for help.
</P>
<P>
   But that relationship has soured, and political experts now say
the president could make the mayor's life even harder by moving the
headquarters of big city taxpayers, like the nation's gas and
electricity monopolies, out of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard enough for a Muscovite to become president in Russia,
where the power and wealth of the capital city are almost
universally envied and resented. Should Moscow tumble from its
fiscal pinnacle into the swamp of Tatarstans and Yakutias, which
borrowed a lot and can pay only a little, there may be no return
for Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even those people who hate him as a Muscovite still tend to
say, `If he was able to do this for Moscow, maybe he'll be able to
do the same for us,''' said Masha Lipman, the deputy editor of the
weekly news magazine Itogi. ``He wants the election to be held as
soon as possible _ before the economy collapses.''
</P>
<P>
   That race may go down to the wire. Moscow's largest foreign-debt
payment ever _ a whopping $500 million Eurobond payoff _ is set for
May 31, 2000. Russia's presidential election will take place the
next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
