<HEADER>
A1020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE11-COX     06-10 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilot hurt slightly as plane noses into house
 &HT;    By Erin Coyle
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As Sylvia Graham sat in her television
room Thursday morning reading a newspaper story about the best of
the high-school graduating class, she heard a loud boom.
</P>
<P>
   She had been planning to go back to bed to sleep off a sinus
infection. Instead, dressed in her pink pastel housecoat and
cream-colored nightgown, she stepped outside to see whether
lightning had struck her home.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 77, found a bleeding woman walking from a crashed Cessna
182 that was pressed up against her house near Lantana.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Eikenberg of West Palm Beach asked to use a phone to
call her husband, Terry. He's a paramedic, she said. Graham took
one look at Eikenberg and invited the stranger into her home,
offering a towel to wipe off her cuts. Graham later chuckled and
said, ``Who would expect an airplane in their house at 9 in the
morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Eikenberg, 42, a student pilot, was taking a practice solo
flight from the Lantana Airport. Shortly after taking off, she
radioed the airport with electrical problems, airport officials
said. Her power cut out, and the engine sputtered in the plane that
she owned with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to land on the runway twice, but the power problems
prevented the landings. She then planned to glide the plane to an
empty field between Interstate 95 and Lantana Road.
</P>
<P>
   But the plane clipped a power line and a palm tree over Lake
Bass Circle. The line fell to the ground, knocking out power to the
area for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Cessna dived into Graham's yard. It nearly pulled an
aluminum awning off a window and moved one of the front porch's
steel posts almost 6 inches. But the nose did not break through the
front wall.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 40 gallons of gas dripped from the plane onto the grass,
said Nigel Baker, Palm Beach County Fire-Rescue battalion chief.
</P>
<P>
   With gas on the ground and an electrical wire down, rescue
officials worked quickly to prevent an explosion. They sprayed the
plane and covered the ground with a neutralizing foam. They also
evacuated three neighboring homes until the power line was fixed
and the plane removed.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, mainly women and children, spilled into the street to
see what was behind the police tape and emergency vehicles'
flashing lights. They later joked about who heard the crash and who
slept through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up with a fireman in the front living room,'' said Toni
Harris, who lives next to Graham. She and her daughter had slept
through the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Atkinson had peeked out her kitchen window as she
cleaned and saw the unmistakable plane's tail facing her home. The
response from the 911 operator: Are you sure it's a plane?
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Eikenberg's brown and white plane with a broken left
wing and a crumpled nose, rescue workers called her lack of serious
injuries amazing. She was treated at JFK Medical Center. She could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``By keeping the plane under control and flying at a very low
speed, she was able to minimize the damage,'' said J. Steve Marlowe
of the Lantana Airport Aircraft Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration Officials started preliminary
investigations Thursday for the FAA and the National Transportation
Safety Board, said Tim Monville, an NTSB investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Workers from the Lantana Airport towed the plane away from
Graham's home, and rescue workers reopened Lake Bass Circle to
traffic about five hours after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, Sylvia Graham, still wearing her
floor-length robe, returned home with her husband, Walker. She was
looking forward to going back to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
