<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1023 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS     06-10 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ The New York Knicks have talked about it since the
final buzzer sounded Wednesday on their 101-94 victory over the
Indiana Pacers in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That win at Market Square Arena gave the Knicks a 3-2 lead in
the best-of-seven series, and they can wrap things up tonight at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   However, in their only previous shot at closing out a playoff
series at home this postseason, the Knicks lost Game 4 of the first
round to the Heat and had to finish the job by winning the deciding
game at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks say they have learned their lesson and are
concentrating on winning tonight's game, for more than the obvious
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake we made after Game 3 against Miami is the mindset
that we don't want to go back to Miami,'' said Knicks coach Jeff
Van Gundy. ``That shouldn't be. We shouldn't focus on what we don't
want, but what we want. All we want to do is get to the Finals, get
a chance to play San Antonio, get a chance to win the championship.
That's the biggest mental factor _ focus on what we want and not
what we don't want.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a last-second runner by Allan Houston to polish off the
perenially underachieving Heat, and the Knicks, the No. 8 seed in
the East, have used that shot as a springboard to where they are
now _ one game from the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to win it for the fans at home _ they've been very
supportive, especially for myself, coming from everything I had
gone through in the past,'' Latrell Sprewell said. ``They've been
there for me. I would like to finish it off there in front of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how the New York fans feel. The Knicks won Game 3 at
Madison Square Garden, but it took a play that bordered on the
miraculous _ a four-point play by Larry Johnson _ to eke out the
victory. The Pacers responded by dominating Game 4, cruising to a
12-point win, so the Knicks are anything but comfortable at home.
</P>
<P>
   Especially because they must play without center Patrick Ewing,
who tore his left Achilles' tendon and will watch tonight's game _
and the rest of the playoffs _ from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity _ we're one away from the Finals,''
Kurt Thomas said. ``That's all we're thinking about. We're not
thinking negatively. And we definitely don't want to come back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did coach Larry Bird and the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   For Indiana, the conference finals have been one missed
opportunity after another _ and plenty of missed shots. And now the
Pacers, who were the favorites in the East after taking the Bulls
to seven games in last year's conference finals, are on the verge
of being eliminated by a most unlikely opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a situation we want to be in, but that's the way it
is,'' Bird said after losing Game 5. ``We played two very good
games in New York last time. I'm very confident we'll give the
maximum effort. It's going to be tough. The only thing is, we have
to have everybody play. It's very disappointing that in a game like
this (Game 5), for some reason some of our guys just didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   The name Rik Smits comes to mind. Smits is playing with
chronically sore feet and a broken toe on his left foot, but that
doesn't explain the struggles he has endured. Foul problems have
limited Smits to just 20 minutes per game, and he has scored more
than 12 points just once in the series. Worse, the 7-4 center has
been outrebounded by 6-3 point guard Mark Jackson (27-19).
</P>
<P>
   Those problems came to a head Wednesday, when the Pacers had a
chance to go a game up on the Knicks. Smits hit just one of his
first 10 shots and finished 4-of-14 from the field, scoring only
eight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Bird said. ``I have no answers. I really
thought Rik would come out and have a big game (Wednesday). It
didn't happen, and I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our success,'' Jackson said of Smits. ``We
need him to score and to be a presence down low. That's when we're
at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits shrugs when pressed about his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get passive, I end up not playing well at all,'' Smits
said. ``It really hasn't seemed to make much of a difference this
year. If I get fouls, I don't play well. If I don't get any fouls,
I haven't been playing all that well.''
</P>
<P>
   And one game from advancing to the NBA Finals, the Knicks hope
that trend continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an impossible dream two months ago,'' Herb Williams
said. ``We've proven to be a pretty good team after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
