<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PICKING TEAM, MRS, CLINTON AGREES WITH MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: skedded earlier as CLINTON-YANKEES)  
 (af)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now she's really hit a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary Rodham Clinton was looking for a way to get under
Rudolph Giuliani's skin, she may have found it Thursday. She
claimed lifelong allegiance to the New York Yankees, the mayor's
hometown team; pulled a Yankees cap over her hair, and used the
power of her current out-of-town address to pose with the Bronx
Bombers on her own turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, I've always been a Yankees fan,'' the first lady,
who was born and bred in Chicago, asserted Thursday morning to
Katie Couric on NBC's ``Today Show'' in anticipation of the
championship team's visit to the White House Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   When the puzzled Ms. Couric said she thought Mrs. Clinton was a
lifelong Chicago Cubs fan, the first lady, in a classic Clintonian
gesture, quickly claimed loyalty to the Cubs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Cubs fan,'' said Mrs. Clinton, who threw out the first
pitch at Wrigley Field in Chicago on opening day in 1994. ``But I
needed an American League team because when you're from Chicago,
you cannot root for both the Cubs and the Sox. I mean, there's a
dividing line that you can't cross there. So as a young girl, I
became very interested and enamored of the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who has portrayed himself as the reigning No. 1
Yankees fan, was gracious upon hearing of Mrs. Clinton's comments,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be more than happy to teach anybody in the White House
about the history of the Yankees, or go over statistics with
them,'' the mayor told reporters at New York City Hall when asked
if his team was betraying him for a White House photo opportunity
with the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show them where Yankee Stadium is located, where Shea Stadium
is located,'' the mayor continued, warming to the possibilities.
``I could take them through things. Or we could discuss, `Where
were you when Reggie Jackson hit three home runs to win the 1977
World Series?' I was at Yankee Stadium. Or, `Where were you when
the Yankees won the 1996 World Series at home?' Gee, I was there.
Or, um, `Who do you think was a better center fielder _ Joe
DiMaggio, Mickey Mantle, Bernie Williams?' Things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he hit on what he seemed to think was the best idea of all:
``Under the right set of circumstances,'' the mayor posited, ``we
could even have a debate about this.''
</P>
<P>
   They might compare photo ops. Giuliani could show scores of
pictures of himself, including one from earlier this month at
DiMaggio's funeral at St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York, where he
sat with George M. Steinbrenner III, the Yankees' principal owner,
and Yogi Berra, the legendary catcher and former manager.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady could show her pictures from, well, Thursday,
also with Steinbrenner and the whole team arrayed in front of the
White House's gleaming white South Portico, which was ringed with
red geraniums.
</P>
<P>
   And herself in her cap.
</P>
<P>
   In the clearest sign yet that Mrs. Clinton intends to run for
the U.S. Senate from New York, she gleefully donned a Yankees cap,
ignoring one of the principal rules of politics: Never wear the
hat. Politicians are given hats all the time; the smart ones just
grin and do not put them on because they usually look too silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to relish this moment together,'' Mrs.
Clinton, who almost never attends sports-related events at the
White House, told a lawnful of fans as she scrapped her prepared
remarks. She introduced Steinbrenner, thanking him for ``standing
up for this franchise'' and ``helping to create one of the greatest
baseball teams of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were charmed but not fooled. Asked if the mayor or
the first lady was a bigger Yankees fan, Dave Cone, the pitcher,
told reporters: ``Mayor Giuliani has the edge. He's been a lifelong
fan.'' Of the Clintons, he said: ``We welcome them with open arms.
We'll show them Yankee Stadium any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the first lady's declaration of her lifetime loyalty to
the Yankees came as a bit of a surprise. As recently as Saturday,
she was neutral, ducking the question of whether she would root for
the Yankees or the Mets. She said the ``politic'' answer was that
she would root for both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
