A1061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-CLIENTS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-CLIENTS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HMOs WARNED ON RECRUITING ONLY FIT MEDICARE CLIENTS  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For years, federal officials say, they have heard
reports that health maintenance organizations try to recruit
healthy elderly people by marketing insurance at sports clubs,
dance halls and places inaccessible to the sick and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in a new policy statement, the federal government
demanded a halt to such practices. And it threatened to fine HMOs
that skimped on necessary care.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services, issued a compliance manual for HMOs explaining
how they can police themselves to prevent violations of Medicare
fraud and abuse laws. Similar standards will apply to Medicaid, the
health program for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   In the compliance manual the government said it was ``very
concerned about the practice known as cherry-picking, or selective
marketing,'' by which HMOs try to sign up healthy patients while
discouraging enrollment of the sick and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown also expressed concern about the accuracy of data
submitted to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said some HMOs delayed reporting a patient's
death in order to continue receiving monthly Medicare payments.
Likewise, they said, some HMOs receive inflated payments because
they report incorrectly that some patients are in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   An HMO gets $1,200 to $1,400 a month for a nursing home resident
compared with $500 for an average Medicare patient.
</P>
<P>
   In paying HMOs, Medicare assumes that they will enroll a
representative mix of elderly people. But if an HMOs patients are
healthier than the average, the government says, the plan's costs
will be lower, and Medicare will overpay.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs deny that they avoid sick patients. But there is an immense
financial incentive for them to do so. The most expensive 5 percent
of Medicare beneficiaries cost almost as much as the remaining 95
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said it was inappropriate for HMOs to ``target
healthier beneficiaries'' _ for example, by marketing their plans
in health clubs or on the upper floors of buildings with no
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, an HMO can be fined up to $100,000 if it is
found to have discouraged the enrollment of Medicare beneficiaries
because of their anticipated need for medical services. In
addition, a health plan may be fined up to $25,000 if it fails to
provide medically necessary services covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, one HMO settled a case for $50,000 after
confirming that its marketing director had told his staff that the
company was enrolling too many sick people. Another HMO paid
$250,000 to settle charges that it had denied certain benefits to
Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, which represents the managed-care industry, said:
``We welcome the guidance from the inspector general. But we
completely reject the caricature of HMOs as marketing only to
healthy individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Ms. Ignagni said, health plans have many
patients with serious illnesses, and federal Medicare payments are
so inadequate that many HMOs are pulling out of the government
program.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, federal investigators have focused on overpayments in
the traditional fee-for-service Medicare program. But Thursday they
said they were stepping up investigations of HMOs, which get $35
billion a year to care for more than six million Medicare
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   D. McCarty Thornton, chief counsel to the inspector general,
said HMOs must not ask Medicare beneficiaries about their medical
condition before allowing them to enroll. Also, Thornton said, it
is improper for a Medicare HMO to conduct a special campaign to
re-enroll former subscribers who had low medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   John T. Bentivoglio, a Justice Department official, said federal
prosecutors were investigating ``the selective enrollment of
relatively healthy beneficiaries, to keep costs low, and
allegations of health plans' causing the disenrollment of
beneficiaries requiring expensive care.''
</P>
<P>
   In its compliance guide, unveiled Thursday at a conference of
health care lawyers and auditors, the government offered this
advice:
</P>
<P>
   _ Each HMO should have a written compliance program, a
compliance officer and a special telephone line to receive
complaints from employees, doctors and patients about possible
fraud and misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   _ An HMO should distribute copies of its compliance policies to
all employees, doctors and independent contractors who may be
affected. Some HMOs have contracts with tens of thousands of
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   _ HMOs may use their own employees to recruit subscribers, but
should not hire outsiders as marketing agents, because such agents
are harder to control. HMOs should not use doctors to recruit
subscribers, especially if the doctors are rewarded for signing up
customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ If an HMO discovers evidence of misconduct, it should report
the problem to federal authorities within 60 days. If the health
plan was overpaid, it should repay the government and take other
corrective action.
</P>
<P>
   Just as doctors and hospitals may violate the law by performing
too many tests and procedures, Ms. Brown said, HMOs can violate the
law by withholding or delaying care they promised to provide to
Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
