A1159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-CUSTOMER-SER     06-10 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-CUSTOMER-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES AGREE ON PLEDGES TO MAKE TO THEIR CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fourteen passenger airlines have agreed to a
``customer service commitment'' that is intended to pre-empt
legislation pending in Congress. But a news conference called
Thursday morning at the Air Transport Association to announce the
plan was canceled by the airlines, apparently because of a
disagreement with lawmakers that occurred minutes before the
briefing was supposed to begin.
</P>
<P>
   As United Airlines chairman and chief executive Gerald Greenwald
apologized for not having anything to say, staff members at the
transport association scurried around a conference room trying to
gather up press kits that had been set out for distribution. The
association, which says its members carry 95 percent of all
passenger traffic, is the industry's main lobbying arm.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines' customer service commitment includes promises to
``quote the lowest available fare for which the customer is
eligible'' to people who telephone for tickets, and to hold
reservations for 24 hours, without requiring immediate purchase, so
that customers can comparison-shop.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are also promising to tell customers about delays
or diversions when they are known in advance and to give some
information on redemption of seats with frequent flier miles,
although not as much data as some legislation would require.
</P>
<P>
   And they are promising to ``make every reasonable effort to
provide food, water, restroom facilities and access to medical
treatment for passengers aboard an aircraft that is on the ground
for an extended period of time without access to the terminal.''
That provision grows out of a monumental tie-up in Detroit last
winter during a snowstorm, when thousands of passengers on
Northwest Airlines sat for hours on planes without food, water or
usable toilets. Under the promise, airlines would share gates
during such emergencies, making it easier to unload planes.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement broke down, and people involved in the
negotiations became like passengers after a semi-audible
announcement over an airport public address system, giving
different explanations of who had said what to whom and what it
meant.
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional aides said Thursday that they were told
Wednesday night that no announcement was imminent. But when they
were presented with the deal Thursday morning, there was not enough
time for members of Congress to decide whether it was sufficient to
merit dropping the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives were describing the provisions of the
agreement to officials of the Clinton administration Thursday
morning as if they were still planning to go ahead with the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald, in a brief statement to reporters, said, ``The
commitment of the airlines to improved customer service is real;
after all, airline passengers are the heart of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlines' proposal does not cover as much ground as some of
the legislation, which is intended to guarantee ``passenger
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Some proposals before Congress would require the airlines to pay
passengers who are stranded for more than two hours. In addition,
some bills would allow ``back to back'' ticketing, in which a
passenger buys two round-trip tickets, with a Saturday night
stayover on each, and then throws away half of each round-trip and
flies more cheaply than would be possible with a straightforward
purchase. Another practice that some bills would legalize but the
airlines are trying to stamp out is ``hidden city'' ticketing, in
which a passenger buys a ticket from city A to city C and gets off
in city B, an intermediate stop, paying less than a simple ticket
to city B.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines differ in how they treat passengers who do not fly all
segments for which they hold tickets and in how they disclose their
policies on such tactics. The airline proposal would have the
carriers disclose their policies.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines also said they would provide information on when a
passenger would have to change planes at an intermediate stop, on a
trip described by the airline as a single ``flight'' with a single
flight number, and information regarding aircraft seat width and
leg room.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who is co-author of one passenger bill
with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said through a spokesman that some
parts of the package were too vague and that it lacked clearly
enforceable standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
