</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ATHLETICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STUDENTS FIRST, ATHLETES SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, June 11: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basketball is the richest college sport, with a television
contract worth nearly $2 billion. It is also the most troubled
college sport. Players fail to graduate in alarming numbers. Others
transfer repeatedly in search of more playing time elsewhere. Still
others leave early in search of a professional career.
</P>
<P>
   This sorry record has now prompted a National Collegiate
Athletic Association advisory committee to consider a plan that
would make freshmen ineligible for the sport, forcing them to focus
on academics for their first year on campus. The plan makes good
sense _ and should probably be expanded to football.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen did not become eligible to play varsity sports until
1972, when the games, especially basketball, began to attract more
television attention and revenues expanded. Eager to get the best
talent into harness as quickly as possible, coaches junked a system
that had traditionally allowed freshmen to get their bearings at
college while playing a modest schedule of 10 or so basketball
games a year. As things now stand, freshmen who make the varsity
team endure a grueling schedule that begins in October and runs
into March, with as many as 40 games, constant practices and a
rigorous travel schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic directors who defend freshman eligibility argue that
many students handle the schedule well, finishing their degrees on
time. But the latest statistics show that graduation rates for
basketball players have actually declined, despite more rigorous
admissions standards that have raised the graduation rates for
college athletics as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith, formerly the basketball coach at The University of
North Carolina, serves on the NCAA committee that will deliver its
recommendations to the organization's board of directors later this
month. Smith is one of a group of distinguished coaches who were
early critics of freshman eligibility. Even though he coached
talented freshmen like Michael Jordan, Smith maintains that varsity
play in the freshman year is contrary to a student's best interest,
making the adjustment to college more difficult than it already is.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed plan, players would still get scholarships.
The only difference is that they would have to focus on the books
for a year. Revoking freshman eligibility is a common-sense
solution to a deepening problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
