<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' WOES ARE HARD TO CONCEAL BENEATH A FAKE MUSTACHE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mets' version of Inspector Clouseau, that master of
disguise, could be in trouble. Bobby Valentine is under
investigation by the National League for donning sunglasses and a
fake mustache _ or was it a strip of black tape? _ and returning to
the dugout after his ejection from the game Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The masquerade is only one of several issues that have immersed
the Mets in a sea of turmoil that is reminiscent of, well, as a
member of the Mets' organization asked Thursday, ``Is this what it
was like with the Yankees?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, only Billy Martin never disguised himself so that no one
would recognize him. If only he had, he might have avoided all of
those bar fights. But that's another time and another story. This
one is about the Mets and their attempt to get their season back on
the playoff track.
</P>
<P>
   With their current winning streak, they may be headed there, but
the ancillary developments left Steve Phillips, their good-natured
general manager, gasping for air Thursday. More than 30 minutes
into a conference call with reporters, he said: ``When can we talk
about baseball? We won four in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the call was consumed by Bobby Bonilla and
his recalcitrance in the face of his demotion to bench status. He
refused to pinch-hit in the game with Toronto on Tuesday night, and
Valentine chose punitively not to ask him to pinch-hit on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But just as with other elements of Yankeeland East, Valentine
apparently triggered this one, too, and not simply by deciding he
could no longer abide Bonilla's presence regularly in the outfield.
Bonilla, an associate said, was irate that Valentine told a
reporter about his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets have a decision to make: what to do about Bonilla.
Phillips readily acknowledged that it had become an ``extremely
difficult'' matter. ``It's something that should and needs to be
resolved sooner rather than later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonilla crisis never had to develop. The Mets never had to
bring Bonilla back. It was a step _ they were warned before they
took it _ that could boomerang. Talk about throwing good money
after bad. Fred Wilpon and Nelson Doubleday didn't make their
millions making deals like this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could have released Mel Rojas last winter and paid him
$4.5 million, his salary for the 1999 season. But nooooooo, they
had to get equal value for him, and oh did they. Bonilla has been
every bit as bad for them this season as Rojas was for them last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But economically, Bonilla is far more costly. Subtracting the $1
million they received from the Dodgers in the deal, the Mets will
spend $10.8 million on Bonilla for this year and the next. In
monetary terms alone, they are out a net of $6.3 million, which
could have paid a good player a nice salary for one year.
</P>
<P>
   To Valentine's credit, he did not want Bonilla in the first
place. As soon as the trade was announced last November, he talked
about the risk Bonilla posed. ``The risk,'' he said, ``is whether
or not he catches the ball when it comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets, who owe Bonilla $9.6 million for the rest of this
season and next, are faced with the likelihood of having to release
him.
</P>
<P>
   This predicament comes at a confusing time for the Mets. An
eight-game losing streak produced grumbling from some players about
Valentine's ever-changing lineup, and it was accompanied by the
surprise sacking of half of Valentine's coach staff over his
strenuous objections.
</P>
<P>
   But since the changes _ and no one is suggesting cause and
effect here _ the Mets have won four straight, winning the last two
without the pinch-hitting help of the sulking hulk. Yet the winning
streak has been punctuated by the manager's decision to initiate
verbal battles with reporters he doesn't like, fabricating or
imagining incidents or situations to support his arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Inspector Clouseau. Ejected in the Toronto half of the
12th inning for arguing a call against Mike Piazza, Valentine
reappeared on the bench in a disguise: black Mets T-shirt,
baseball-type cap, sunglasses and a fake mustache.
</P>
<P>
   The television camera quickly spotted him and focused on him
periodically the rest of the game, but he later tried to deny he
was that masked man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was somebody else who didn't look like me,'' Valentine said
weakly.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Inspector Clouseau never tricked anyone, Valentine
did not fool the league office. Katy Feeney, the league's senior
vice president, said the league was investigating the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting information,'' she said. ``We don't have
everything yet, but we're getting it. We'll have the rest of it
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeney said managers have been fined or reprimanded for
remaining in the tunnel leading from the dugout to the clubhouse
after they had been ejected. ``But,'' she added, ``I don't remember
anybody being fully back in the dugout nor do I remember anybody
being in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeney said it was her understanding that the fake mustache
actually was a piece of black tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at the film and see if we can tell,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question, however, that the man sitting in the
Mets' dugout was not Peter Sellers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
