A1175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-FIRSTLADY-2TAK     06-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-FIRSTLADY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISH FIRST LADY'S ARMOR: ELEGANCE, TACT, AND BACKBONE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ The first lady of Poland said she gave Hillary
Rodham Clinton some helpful hints when they first met in Cracow
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her that from my point of view, I should always be
three steps behind my husband,'' Jolanta Kwasniewska, the young,
elegant wife of president Aleksander Kwasniewski, said.
</P>
<P>
   She added with a bright smile, ``And I think in the next term of
President Clinton, Hillary was even more steps behind her husband
than I. And that is one of the reasons that she has such good press
and high popularity now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years after her husband's election, Mrs.
Kwasniewska, 43, is one of the most admired _ and closely watched _
women in Poland. When Pope John Paul II arrived at the Gdansk
airport last Saturday, Polish reporters on the tarmac spent little
time measuring the handshake between the Polish pope and the
ex-Communist president.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as Mrs. Kwasniewska, a practicing Catholic, curtsied
and kissed the Pope's ring, the reporters craned for a glimpse of
the First Lady's hemline. It was just below the knee.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who exchanged her real estate business for charity work
after the election, but never lost her taste for alluring designer
clothes, Mrs. Kwasniewska (pronounced kvash-NYEFF-ska) was
described early on as a combination of Jackie Kennedy and Hillary
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she has proven to be something quite different _ a
post-feminist First Lady who has reaped the rewards of emancipation
by assuring the world that she doesn't mind subordination.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, her tenure in the Presidential Palace exemplifies
some of the contradictions that sprang up during the country's
fast, edgy transition from Communism to capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist issues were largely buried under the broader Polish
struggle for freedom from a totalitarian state. When democracy
suddenly sprang loose, many battles for women's rights were either
swept under the rug or skipped forward in the race for
Westernization.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kwasniewska explained that she eschews politics, advising
her husband only on matters related to her social causes, yet she
did not hesitate to speak her mind on one of the more divisive
issues currently churning in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Parliament, which is dominated by right-wing
parties, recently approved legislation that could inhibit the use
of amniocentesis, a prenatal diagnostic test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is terrible,'' Mrs. Kwasniewska said swiftly.
``It's the first time in my life I have heard such stupid
information. I think that the members of our Parliament made a
mistake _ and think that prenatal testing is pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would do her best to block it. ``I think it is just
a mistake and I will talk to my husband,'' she said firmly. ``I am
sure that as soon as possible it will be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Her candor was all the more surprising given the timing. On
Friday, she is to be host to John Paul II during his courtesy visit
to the Presidential Palace, where he will pray in the palace
chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope warned against amniocentesis in his 1995 encyclical
``Evangelium Vitae'' (``The Gospel of Life''), saying it was
acceptable only as a means of treating an unhealthy fetus and
complaining that it was too often used as a pretext for what he
called ``eugenic abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kwasniewska defended the diagnostic test as a means of
giving a defective fetus early treatment. But her explanation that
Poland's rate of spontaneous abortions as a result of the test _ 2
percent and the same as other countries and ``quite normal,'' _ is
unlikely to delight the Vatican or Poland's conservative bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would feel offended if someone called her a
feminist,'' said Eleonora Zielinska, a feminist and law professor
at Warsaw University. ``But by my standards, she is one.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kwasniewska's self-assurance is bolstered by the obvious
pride Poles take in her glamour and dedication. She started gently
with conventional causes, setting up a foundation to help children
and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   She has since expanded into more daring areas, campaigning for
greater breast cancer awareness and early testing, as well as
compassionate care for AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is perceived as a strong woman,'' said Monica Olejnik, a
prominent political journalist in Warsaw. ``But what is important
to Poles is that she is not seen as controlling her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Novelty also helped. Poland was accustomed to dowdy, anonymous
wives of Communist Party leaders. Her immediate predecessor, Danuta
Walesa, wife of the founder of Solidarity, Lech Walesa, who was
president from 1990 until 1995, stayed in Gdansk to raise their
eight children, and was far less visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My situation is different,'' Mrs. Kwasniewska said. ``I only
have one child and I am full of energy, I hate when I have nothing
to do, it would kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   Poles in fact describe her as the country's first first lady,
which deeply irritates Walesa. They had met only once, at a hotel
elevator in Washington, at the ceremonies surrounding the inclusion
of Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary into NATO in April.
</P>
<P>
   But for once, it seems, Mrs. Kwasniewska's legendary charm
failed. Back home, he continues to complain that Mrs. Kwasniewska
had a much softer life than his first lady, who had to run their
modest home _ and represent him _ when he was jailed during martial
law in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kwasniewska's husband was a junior minister in the
Communist government during those dark days. When democracy emerged
he formed a new, non-Marxist party and ran a youthful,
American-style campaign against Walesa, promising pragmatism and
economic reform. In office, he has earned most voters' respect but
she is the one they love.
</P>
<P>
   He is an atheist, and her Catholicism is seen as his best bridge
to the powerful church. (There is a chaplain in the Presidential
Palace who celebrates Mass daily.)
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, she wore a form-fitting, Italian-made navy
pants suit. At official functions, she wears skirts, and conceded
with a smile that they have grown longer over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that while in Washington last spring, she caught a
television interview with Monica Lewinsky, whose celebrity status
became a hot topic among the other first ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry, she is not a star,'' Mrs. Kwasniewska said hotly.
``In Poland we've known what her kind of profession is for hundreds
of years. If she were my daughter, I would tell her to get plastic
surgery and leave the country. To escape the shame.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she admired Mrs. Clinton's fortitude and restraint,
noting with a laugh that if her husband had put her in a similar
situation, ``he would get a black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she didn't know whether she would have chosen the same
path as the Clintons. Again, the first lady didn't hesitate to
bring up divorce, which is legal in Poland but condemned by the
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no obligation to live together, there is the
opportunity to build a new life, to find a new husband or wife, and
sometimes that is better _ truth is better than lies,'' she said
pensively. ``But it's easy to talk in theory, life is rarely so
simple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
