<HEADLINE>
DODGERS COUNT ON BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the exception of opening day and the six-run
disaster in Philadelphia, right-hander Kevin Brown has filled the
role of Los Angeles Dodgers ace to near perfection. He's been
outstanding at stopping or preventing losing streaks, going 5-1
with a 1.99 ERA following Dodgers losses.
</P>
<P>
   However, one thing manager Davey Johnson won't do is overextend
Brown by making him throw a Randy Johnson-ish 130 pitches in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets around 105 pitches, 110 pitches, he's pretty much
gone,'' Johnson said. ``He's gassed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why Brown, who is ninth in the major leagues in average
pitches per start (109), is yet to throw a pitch in the ninth
inning this season. He threw 114 pitches in eight innings during
Wednesday's 7-2 win against the Texas Rangers. The most he's thrown
is 118 in an April 21 start against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It's obviously a conclusion Johnson reached more from watching
Brown rather than examining his numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is 7-3 with a 2.69 ERA, has given up earned runs
after the sixth inning on two occasions. Of course, one of those
was the three runs he surrendered in the eighth inning against
Atlanta. Still, Brown's ERA is 2.78 from the first to the sixth
inning and is 2.25 after the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so darn competitive,'' Johnson said. ``I know he always
wants to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Vero Beach presses on: After meeting with Dodgers officials
last week, Vero Beach, Fla., and Indian River County will continue
their quest to keep the Dodgers' spring-training home in Dodgertown
despite having only $12.5 million in funding available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dead, in my opinion,'' Dodgertown managing director
Craig Callan said. ``The representatives here, (Indian River County
Administrator) Jim Chandler and (Vero Beach city manager) Rex
Taylor, it's my understanding they'll say, `Here's what we can do
and here's what we can't do.' We're still discussing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Callan said local officials, stung by Gov. Jeb Bush's rejection
of a bill that would have provided $7.5 million in funds, are
searching for alternative funding but are not optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bush did sign the expected one-cent tourist
tax that can go towards the acquisition of a spring-training
complex that will provide part of the $12.5 million in funds the
city and county possess.
</P>
<P>
   __ FYI: The Dodgers certainly are a .500 club in many aspects.
Not only are they 29-29 overall, they're 18-17 against clubs with a
.500 or better record and they're 22-21 against right-handed
starting pitchers. Johnson said he might use lefty Dave Hansen as
the designated hitter when the Dodgers face right-handers in the
last two games of the series in Oakland. . . . The bullpen is 2-2
with a 1.58 ERA and five saves in the last 14 games. . . .
Outfielder Trenidad Hubbard, nicknamed ``The Solution,'' has six
hits in his last two games and is hitting .321. . . . Right fielder
Raul Mondesi drew his 29th walk Wednesday. He walked 30 times in
1998 and collected 159 walks in 2,886 at-bats before this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
