<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE11-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER MORT GAGE RATES DIS APPOINTING HOME BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Home buyers got bad news Wednesday when mortgage rates
hit their highest level in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages
climbed to 7.51 percent from 7.41 a week ago and the highest since
September 1997, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Rates have been steadily rising since April and now are almost a
percentage point higher than in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disheartening,'' said Greg Sexton who is in the process
of buying a new east Mesa home with his fiance Cori Krawcyk. ``We
could have locked in at 7.25 (percent) just a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That move would have saved the couple at least a few hundred
dollars a year. But like many other home buyers, they had no idea
rates would rise so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A $150,000 mortgage with a 10 percent down payment of $15,000
costs a home buyer with a 7 percent mortgage $898 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The same loan with a 7.5 percent interest rate costs $943 each
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rates have gone straight up during the past few months,'' said
Terry Turk, president of Sun America Mortgage. ``Usually, they will
pause a few weeks after a big hike before going up again.''
</P>
<P>
   The average payment on a $100,000 loan with this week's rate is
$699. Exactly one year ago when the rate was 7.04 percent, the
payment on that same loan was $668.
</P>
<P>
   The hike in rates also has quashed the refinancing boom.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Luber of North American Mortgage said mortgage refinancings
have dropped off by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Refinancings hit a high last year when rates hovered around 6.5
percent, a record low.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders say there are still plenty of people buying homes so the
new-mortgage business isn't taking a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Low mortgage rates have fueled the nation's and the Valley's
home markets for several years. In 1998, more than 100,000 deals
for new homes and existing houses were struck, making it a record
year.
</P>
<P>
   The average mortgage rate for 1998 was about 6.6 percent, nearly
a percentage point lower than today's rate.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists have warned that if rates go much higher, the
housing boom will start to wane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers have to remember that 7.5 percent is still low,'' said
Jay Butler, director of Arizona State University's Real Estate
Center. ``Rates will have to hit 9 percent for the market to really
slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates haven't been that high since almost a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is expected to raise the federal funds rate
by a quarter to a half a percentage point later this month. The
current increase in mortgage interest rates is in anticipation of
that increase, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   Where loan rates go from here depends on how big the Fed's move
is and how it's received by the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, buyers like Sexton are cautiously watching. He and
Krawcyk, like many other people purchasing new Valley homes, which
take months to build, don't have to lock into a rate right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If rates don't go back down, we can still afford the house
with all the upgrades we want,'' said Sexton, an editor of a
Phoenix magazine. ``But it may push back when we can buy all the
new appliances and furniture that we want to fill it.'' &QL; 
Catherine Reagor can be reached at 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
