<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURTING ANGELS KEEP EYES ON PRIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's right there in black and white every day.
In newspapers, on stats sheets, for all the organization to see.
</P>
<P>
   It's the standings, the dreaded standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels don't like to look because it shows where they stand
_ last place. It doesn't seem to matter to them that at 28-31 they
wouldn't be in last place in any other division but the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem to matter that the combined record of the teams
in the AL West is 13 games over .500, the best of any division in
the American League and second-best in the majors behind the NL
Central (21 over).
</P>
<P>
   What matters is that the Angels are 7{ games out of first place
and in danger of falling too far out to have a chance to win the
division.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, they were 8{ games out, their largest
deficit under manager Terry Collins' two-plus years at the helm and
the biggest since they finished 19{ games out at the end of the
1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels admit they are trying to hang on and stay close until
key players return from injuries. Shortstop Gary DiSarcina should
be back within a couple of weeks. Right fielder Tim Salmon should
be back within a month. Center fielder Jim Edmonds should be back
in about two months.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the Angels are doing everything they can to ignore
the standings and win every game possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never look at the standings until we're .500,'' first
baseman/DH Mo Vaughn said. ``It's too disappointing. We've got to
get to .500 before I look at the standings. It can be frustrating,
but there's still a lot of season to play. Once you get to .500,
you can take off from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels haven't been at .500 since April 17, when they were
6-6. They've gotten to within one game of .500 a few times only to
lose their next time out.
</P>
<P>
   In order to get to .500, though, the Angels need to change their
recent pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more than one win every three or four days,'' pitcher
Tim Belcher said. ``We need to string some together. What we've
been putting out there on the field is better than what we've
shown.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Rangers reeled off nine consecutive wins
recently. But the last thing Collins does is think about what the
Rangers are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about them,'' he said. ``I've still got to
concern myself with my team. You take care of your own business, no
matter what the standings say. You've still got to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   What's strange is that the Angels are proving that the old adage
_ you win with pitching and defense _ isn't necessarily true. They
rank No. 1 in team defense (.985 fielding percentage) and No. 2 in
pitching (4.30 ERA) in the league, but they are No. 12 in team
batting average (.259) and No. 12 in runs per game (4.5).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Seattle Mariners have a winning record (30-28)
despite the worst pitching in the league with an ERA just under 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hitters' league,'' Collins noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
