<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LIKELY TO BE ACTIVE IN TRADE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every couple of weeks or so, the Yankees' general
manager, Brian Cashman, touches base with other general managers,
to see what they are looking for, to see what they are offering.
Checking traps, he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Cashman will be deeply involved in trade talks as
the Yankees try to refine their roster, plug holes, fill gaps.
Cleveland, the Yankees' primary competition in the American League,
will do the same; the Indians are said to be looking at the likes
of the right-hander Darryl Kile, currently with Colorado, in their
search for a front-line pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not swapped prospects for an established
veteran since trading for Chuck Knoblauch in February 1998, but
that is probably what will take place before the July 31 trade
deadline. The Yankees' farm system, considered one of the best in
baseball, is teeming with talent even though some of their top
prospects, like pitcher Ryan Bradley, have struggled this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot to work with,'' a rival general manager
said. ``It's pretty amazing, considering how much talent they have
in the majors, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman and manager Joe Torre will continue to evaluate the
needs of the major league club. The Yankees have considered five
left-field combinations this season and are now using the platoon
of the left-handed-hitting Tony Tarasco (who is batting .217) and
the right-handed-hitting Shane Spencer. Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee
and Spencer all were given opportunities to win the job, and it is
expected that the veteran Darryl Strawberry will be suspended _
perhaps as soon as Friday _ for violating his aftercare program.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with other teams believe that, in the next month, the
Yankees will try to acquire an established left fielder with the
experience to help them in the playoffs. The Cincinnati Reds are in
contention for a playoff spot, but if they were to fall out, they
might make available the left-handed-hitting Michael Tucker or the
right-handed-hitting slugger Greg Vaughn (in the midst of a
disappointing season). The Detroit Tigers will listen to offers for
Bobby Higginson, and Kansas City's Johnny Damon might become too
expensive for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   If Jason Grimsley and Ramiro Mendoza do not rebound from recent
failures, the Yankees will be in the market for a right-handed
set-up man, along the lines of Minnesota's Mike Trombley or San
Diego's Dan Miceli, and the Yankees could go after Detroit's Doug
Brocail or Todd Jones or Florida's Matt Mantei. There are few
quality left-handed relievers available. Kansas City's Matt
Whisenant throws hard but has been inconsistent, and the Yankees
have expressed interest in Pittsburgh's Jason Christiansen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have the goods to make deals, though there might be
a few untouchables in their farm system. Alfonso Soriano, signed as
a free agent last year, is batting .336 with 13 home runs and 53
runs batted in for Class AA Norwich. Soriano is a shortstop, but
can play just about any position other than catcher. ``I don't know
if there's a more valuable minor league player in the business
right now,'' said Mark Newman, the Yankees' vice president for
player development and scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Henson, the University of Michigan quarterback playing
third base for Class A Tampa, probably falls into the untouchable
category, along with the young slugger Jackson Melian, also playing
for Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams constantly ask for Bradley, a hard-throwing
right-hander who advanced from Class A to the major leagues last
year. Bradley has had control trouble this season with Columbus,
throwing 10 wild pitches and walking 30 in 65 2/3 innings, and
scouts with two other teams said they were leery of the stress his
delivery might place on his arm. Newman isn't worried. ``He had a
bad outing his last time out, but he had four good games before
that,'' Newman said. ``He's making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Johnson is an aggressive left-handed-hitting first baseman
playing for Class AA Norwich, and the Yankees like his potential,
but he has a peculiar problem: Johnson keeps getting hit by
pitches, 23 times this year, tying an Eastern League record.
Johnson looms over the plate, and for that reason, the Yankees have
``padded him up,'' said Newman. ``He's the only player in our
system who we've given the Mo Vaughn treatment, pads all over
him,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee has recovered from pneumonia and is trying to shorten his
swing and adapt to breaking balls, but circumstances are such that
Ledee will establish his career elsewhere. Ledee, currently with
Columbus, will remain in the minors for the time being, and because
he will be out of options next spring, the Yankees may look to
trade him in the next seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Donny Leon, a 23-year-old switch-hitting third baseman, might be
the organization's most tradeable commodity. He is batting .309
with nine home runs and 51 RBI at Norwich. Other Yankees prospects
who will be talked about in the weeks ahead: the left-handed
pitcher Ed Yarnall (Columbus), the right-handed pitcher Luis De Los
Santos (currently out with a rib-cage strain), and the right-handed
pitcher Todd Noel, whose fastball was recently clocked at 98 miles
an hour with the Tampa farm team.
</P>
</TEXT>
