<SLUG> BC-MUNICIPAL-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES AND STATES TOLD TO ALTER BOOKKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite public officials' protests, the accounting board that
sets the rules for how cities and states keep their books approved
a plan Thursday that will require governments to include the value
of roads, bridges and other infrastructure in their financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach, which for example will require New York City
to value the Brooklyn Bridge and New York state to value 37,000
miles of highways, is part of a 200-page document that sets out new
accounting rules for state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, praised by taxpayer groups, are aimed at helping
citizens know where their taxes are being spent and whether a
government's financial health is improving or deteriorating. The
rules will also help prevent a common ploy _ a current
administration's shifting costs to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most significant change to occur in the history of
governmental financial reporting,'' said Tom Allen, chairman of the
seven-member Governmental Accounting Standards Board, which voted
unanimously to approve the new rules. ``Never before has the public
been able to get a comprehensive overview of a state or local
government's finances in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   But, citing the costs of researching assets that were built
decades ago, the Governmental Finance Officers Association vowed
yesterday to try to persuade the accounting board to abandon the
new valuation rule, which begins to take effect in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything we can to get them to rescind
that decision,'' said Jeffrey Esser, executive director of the
association, which has 14,000 members. ``Do we really want to spend
scarce taxpayer dollars to gather this information when we could
instead spend it on education or garbage pickup?''
</P>
<P>
   Other financial experts, however, said they believed that the
cost would be worth the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman Grossman, a managing director at Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp.,
which rates the quality of governments' financial health, said
disasters like the 1983 collapse of the Mianus River bridge on
Interstate 95 in Connecticut had brought the issue to the attention
of the accounting rule makers, who are based in nearby Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules will require governments to determine how many
years their roads, prisons, schools, firetrucks and other major
assets will last, and Grossman said: ``The public should know the
condition of bridges and roads. Neglect of infrastructure brings
added cost to the government in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   But Esser called the new infrastructure rules ``the Full
Employment Act'' for the accountants, consultants and engineers
whom governments will have to hire.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Comptroller Phoebe Selden said the rules would require
the city to install a new computer system to track infrastructure
costs. ``This will take a long time,'' she said. ``We're talking
about our city streets, the curbs, the gutters, the sidewalks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
