<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DAVEY-LADN     06-10 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DAVEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' START IS FOR THE BIRDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson had pitchers who couldn't pitch and
a catcher who couldn't throw.
</P>
<P>
   He had a clubhouse filled with stars, high-priced and
indifferent, an unpredictable owner and impatient fans with fading
memories of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds familiar, it should. Johnson's 1996 Baltimore
Orioles yawned through the first four months of the season before
going on a run that got them within a few games of the World
Series. So if you like happy endings, maybe Johnson's first season
as Los Angeles Dodgers manager has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a little hard to see right now, says the Texas
Rangers' Rafael Palmeiro, Johnson's first baseman in Baltimore. But
if most people feel nothing but disappointment in Johnson's 29-29
club so far, Palmeiro is here to guarantee the Dodgers a place in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, they'll be there and Davey is the reason,'' said
Palmeiro, who had 142 RBI in 1996. ``Things started a little slow,
but we didn't get going until August. I mean, we came out right
after the All-Star break and were swept by the division leaders
(New York Yankees). How bad does that look?
</P>
<P>
   ``But we never doubted Davey would bring it together. He has
always been a winner and he makes you believe you are a winner,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 55, was beginning a two-year run with the Orioles in
1996 and qualified for the playoffs both seasons. He averaged 96
victories in six full seasons with the New York Mets. His
Cincinnati Reds teams had a .542 winning percentage in three years
and a playoff series victory over the Dodgers in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the respect of everyone who plays for him,'' Palmeiro
said. ``Respect can make or break a manager. It means everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Respect has enabled Johnson to avoid the criticism for the
disappointing season that continues tonight in Oakland with the
first of three games against the A's.
</P>
<P>
   The owners at Fox have come under fire for being heavy handed
and spending too much. Even new general manager Kevin Malone has
been chastised for brash World Series predictions and proclamations
that ``There is a new sheriff in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been fired in New York, Cincinnati and Baltimore.
His confidence often has been called arrogance by owners, but he
always won.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been through some wars,'' Malone said, ``and that
obviously has helped shape the way he approaches his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Johnson is in Los Angeles and things are different. Or are
they?
</P>
<P>
   __ The Dodgers and Orioles were prototypes of building through
the farm system in the 1960s and '70s. When the talent pool dried
up, they tried _ mostly unsuccessfully _ to replenish through
trades and free-agent signings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Instead of Todd Hundley, who is drawing boos for his .224
batting average and the inability to throw out baserunners, the
Orioles had Chris Hoiles, who threw out just 15 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Dodgers might not have a dependable starting pitcher
beyond Kevin Brown, but the Orioles had little other than 19-game
winner Mike Mussina until Scott Erickson and David Wells came on at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   __ There were injuries to both bullpens. The Orioles lost
right-hander Armando Benitez and left-hander Arthur Rhodes for
extended periods. The Dodgers are without Antonio Osuna, whose
elbow surgery Johnson said has broken the link between the starters
and late-inning men Alan Mills and Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   __ Then there was the issue of clubhouse chemistry, a problem
with the Dodgers since Kirk Gibson left a decade ago. In Baltimore,
lines were starting to form between white and Latin players, many
of whom were becoming upset with double standards applied to Cal
Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the obstacles, you have to keep moving, keep
working and always in a positive way,'' Johnson said. ``You have to
get the team believing in what you are trying to do, that your
moves are for the betterment of the team. In 1996 we overcame a lot
because we built confidence in the team that never wavered. That
will happen here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1996 Orioles never dropped below second place in
the American League East, they went from 46-39 to 51-52 during a
three-week span in mid-July to fall 10 games behind the Yankees.
General manager Pat Gillick was ready to unload veterans Wells and
Bobby Bonilla at the July 31 trading deadline, but owner Peter
Angelos killed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   They picked up all-time Orioles great Eddie Murray for the
stretch and he hit his 500th career homer on Sept. 6. They finished
the final 59 games 37-22 and beat Cleveland in the first round of
the playoffs before losing to the Yankees in the American League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   But as in Baltimore, where there hadn't been a winner since
1983, Dodgers fans are uncomfortable with the slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did it take so long to come together? I guess that is the
$64,000 question,'' said Mills, who pitched in Baltimore from 1992
through last season. ``I don't think teams necessarily jell right
away. The Orioles had been together a while but had a new manager.
The Dodgers are still putting the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most glaring pieces is Hundley, acquired from the New
York Mets for his left-handed power even though he was recovering
from September 1997 reconstructive elbow surgery. He missed most of
spring training and has thrown out just 12 percent of opposing
baserunners.
</P>
<P>
   Hoiles was even worse defensively than Hundley but hit 25 homers
and drove in 73. Although there is not as much running in the
American League, Johnson never let Hoiles' problems infect the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran in that league, too,'' Johnson said Tuesday after the
Rangers stole six bases against Hundley. ``But that isn't going to
be the difference between winning and losing this thing. Teams
should be running on us right now. But his problems are more
mechanical than arm strength. By July, he should be OK and there
will be a lot of baseball left.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who played in the last two World Series before signing a
seven-year, $105 million contract last winter, says the key to
Johnson's success is the honesty he shows his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no self-promotion, no hidden agendas with him,''
Brown said. ``He isn't in the clubhouse much, he gives players
their room. But he lets them know he will accept nothing less than
winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
