<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-MALPRACTICE11-CO     06-10 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MALPRACTICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ban fought on suits for medical mistakes
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Bonnie Strickland's mother died at 54 when
scar tissue blocked her colon. A doctor diagnosed it as stress, or
gas, until it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a second shock: Under a quirk in Florida law,
Strickland, as a child older than 25, could not sue for pain and
suffering resulting from a medical mistake that killed her parent.
All she could hope to collect was funeral costs, hardly enough to
interest a lawyer in taking the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outraged by her medical treatment,'' said Strickland, a
St. Petersburg resident. ``When I found out about the law, I didn't
believe it. I walked into a bathroom and got physically sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The law protects doctors and hospitals _ but not airlines, drunk
drivers and virtually everyone else _ from such claims and should
be declared unconstitutional, lawyers for victims' children in two
South Florida cases argued Thursday before the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Medical professionals contend the law has avoided frivolous
lawsuits and helped keep down overall health-care costs. Plaintiffs
face ``a very heavy burden'' to persuade the court to second-guess
the legislature and grant a right to sue that Floridians never had
before, said Janis Brustures Keyser, a West Palm Beach attorney
representing doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome has relevance to millions of grown-up children of
elderly Floridians and _ to whatever extent it affects
malpractice-insurance rates _ to anyone who pays a medical bill.
Justices questioned both sides extensively Thursday but are not
expected to issue a decision for several weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1990, children over 25 had little opportunity to sue for
pain and suffering in the wrongful death of a parent in any
circumstance. The same applied to parents of children over 25 who
died.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Florida legislators voted to allow such lawsuits
against negligent airlines, employers and others _ but protected
doctors and hospitals, who protested that there was a crisis in
malpractice-insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Because it arbitrarily leaves out a certain class of people, the
law is ``flawed, irrational and not reasonable,'' attorney Arnold
Ginsberg told the justices. He represents victims' children Lynn
Garber, Nathan Mizrahi and Ava Ruthman in consolidated Miami-Dade
cases against Mount Sinai Medical Center, Parkway Regional Medical
Center and several doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg was joined by West Palm Beach lawyers Harriet Rae
Freeman and Theodore Babbitt of the Association for Responsible
Medicine, a victims' rights group.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the predictions on which the 1990 law was based
were flawed.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Insurance study projected a rise of 2.5 percent
annually in general liability insurance premiums and 4.5 percent
for malpractice insurance. It's impossible to know how accurate the
second prediction would have been if older children were allowed to
sue, but even the first prediction turned out to be overblown, the
attorneys contended.
</P>
<P>
   The crafting of the 1990 law really came down to politics,
Babbitt said after the hearing _ and there, the medical lobby won
the battle against the trial bar. Attempts to change the law have
been introduced in the legislature during each of the past three
years and have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Medical Association President Glenn Bryan said: ``The
Florida Legislature acted responsibly in passing the 1990 version
of the Florida Wrongful Death Act. The legislature recognized the
extreme volatility of professional liability insurance in Florida
and properly exempted claims for medical malpractice from the
provisions of the act allowing suits for non-economic damages.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong disciplinary system within the profession _ not
lawsuits _ is the best way to hold physicians accountable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits are ``not the proper means by which physicians should
be held accountable for their actions,'' Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The words bring little comfort to Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My case was not frivolous,'' she said. ``My mother suffered
tremendously. I had no clue Florida's law said too bad, there's
nothing you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
