A1206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL     06-10 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG, HOT SUMMER SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, June 11: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each day seems to bring more dreary news about New York City's
public school system. Unfortunately, these excruciating details
about how poorly many of the city's students fare on new
standardized tests or how badly they perform after graduation have
produced more criticism and plans than promises of extra resources.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal from Chancellor Rudy Crew would end social
promotion in grades 3 to 12 after next year. This instant pass-fail
policy could mean that about a third of the city's schoolchildren
would find themselves in summer school. The lucky ones might have
air-conditioning and good teachers, but whatever their educational
draw, if they do not attend regularly and pass a final exam, they
would not move up a grade in September. One estimate is that next
year 360,000 students will attend summer school and 88,000 will
still fail the test.
</P>
<P>
   Some raising of standards in the city schools is definitely
necessary given the poor performance of students on reading,
writing and math tests. But improving the schools will not be as
easy as failing students. Many of these new tests, with strict time
limits and essays that test grammar, give educators far more
information about how well students are understanding math,
learning to read and write creatively and even learning how to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   But money for teacher training, smaller class size and
pre-kindergarten classes is stalled in the state legislature.
Students who fail cannot simply be shoved back into the same
classroom. They need remedial work, another costly item that
requires the attention of state and city budget makers.
</P>
<P>
   Crew started ending social promotion at a reasonable pace this
year by notifying 70,000 children that their attendance at summer
school was mandatory if they wanted to move up a grade in
September. With 130,000 more children also planning to attend
summer school, finding air-cooled classrooms and 10,000 teachers
who are not going on vacation or taking refresher courses has been
a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But what is merely difficult this summer could be Herculean by
next summer. Without enough political and financial support, an end
to social promotion is little more than a political slogan that
sentences students to a long, hot, unproductive summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLOTS-TRIBES-SPI &LR;      06-10 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOTS-TRIBES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE APPROVES TWO ELECTRONIC GAMING SYSTEMS FOR INDIAN CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ The state Gambling Commission on Thursday
approved two electronic gambling systems for Indian casinos,
clearing the way for Washington tribes to install what are commonly
called ``cashless slot machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the commission vote, the Muckleshoot Indian
Casino near Auburn had 100 of the machines up and running, and
planned to have 325 more operating by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The Squaxin Island Tribe, which operates a casino near Shelton,
planned to open Friday with 98 machines, and quickly bring the
total to 150.
</P>
<P>
   Both tribes already had completed a rigorous review by the
Gambling Commission and were only waiting for the panel to give
final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 3-1 to approve two electronic gambling
systems, one manufactured by Multimedia Games of Tulsa, Okla., and
the other by Sierra Design Group of Reno, Nev. The systems were
licensed after months of technical and legal scrutiny, including
testing at an independent laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new machines add a whole new dimension to our casino,''
said Virginia Cross, vice chairwoman of the Muckleshoot Tribal
Council. ``The machines will make the Muckleshoot Indian Casino a
destination location. They will add jobs and dollars to Auburn's
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Muckleshoots operate the largest casino in the state and
employ more than 900.
</P>
<P>
   The Squaxin Island Tribe said it hoped the machines will boost
revenues that have lagged behind projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of revenues in most gaming jurisdictions are from
machines,'' said Dennis Wisner, chief financial officer of the
Squaxin Island casino. ``We're very anxious to add these machines
to help the overall economic viability of the tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gambling Commission approved the electronic systems under an
agreement negotiated last year between Gov. Gary Locke and 12
Indian nations that operate casinos, including the Muckleshoots and
Squaxin Island tribe. The 10 other tribes now will be able to
install either system, once they complete the same pre-operation
review as the Muckleshoot and Squaxin Island casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other tribes that don't have casinos also are covered by
the agreement, which says Indian casinos can operate up to 425
machines in the first year and 675 the second. They also can buy
machines from other tribes, allowing them to operate a maximum of
1,500 machines.
</P>
<P>
   The cashless slots are technically known as video lottery
machines. They are designed to fall within state law, which bans
slot machines, and are described as electronic versions of the
state lottery's scratch tickets.
</P>
<P>
   While said to have the look and feel of slot machines, they have
no lever to pull and no coins are dropped in the slot. Players
instead use electronic cards similar to debit cards to track
winnings and losings. They push buttons or touch screens to
``scratch'' an electronic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal law that regulates Indian gaming, tribal
casinos can only operate slot machines if allowed by state law. But
one tribe, the Shoalwaters, have defied state and federal
authorities and installed slots in their casino near Willapa Bay.
The federal government has sued.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, The Gambling Commission licensed another
manufacturer of electronic gambling systems, IGT of Reno, Nev.,
which now must submit its system to testing by the both the
commission and an independent laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth manufacturer, a subsidiary of the Oneida Indian Nation
of New York, is seeking licensing. The Oneidas operate a casino
under a state compact similar to Washington's and developed their
own system to fall within New York law, which also bans slots.
</P>
<P>
   Only Indian nations can operate casinos in Washington. The state
Legislature in 1997, however, allowed card rooms to offer
house-banked games, such as blackjack, which has led to the
proliferation of card rooms know as ``mini-casinos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
