<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RACE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GETTING THE FACTS ON RACIAL PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, June 11: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made it clear that he finds racial
profiling, the targeting of suspects by race or ethnic background,
morally indefensible. On Wednesday he ordered federal law
enforcement agencies to find out ``exactly who is being stopped and
why'' by collecting more precise data on the race and gender of the
people they stop to question.
</P>
<P>
   The new executive order amounts to an acknowledgment that racial
profiling is a matter of concern not only for local police
departments but federal agencies as well, including customs,
immigration and drug enforcement agents. The federal Customs
Service has already begun a review of its inspection process
following persistent complaints that black and Hispanic people are
unfairly singled out for searches at airports and border crossings.
Clinton also strongly endorsed legislation sponsored by two
Democrats, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan and Sen. Frank
Lautenberg of New Jersey, that would provide funds to encourage
states to collect data on police stops.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been no nationwide studies analyzing the rate
of stops and searches by race, the anecdotal evidence strongly
suggests that racial profiling is a widespread problem. Moreover,
narrower surveys in New Jersey, Maryland and elsewhere have
produced findings that Conyers has called ``too outrageous to be a
mere coincidence.'' Requiring law enforcement agents to gather more
factual data is a useful if modest step toward raising their
consciousness about bias and developing a consensus around steps to
address it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
