</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOONE-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH ORIGINALLY RULED ACCIDENTAL BECOMES A MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ On a cold, cloudy day three months ago,
family members found Patricia Noone at the bottom of a wooded
embankment near a creek across the street from her home.
</P>
<P>
   Noone, a 61-year-old widow, was lying between two logs, a tree
branch across her body. The mother of seven was wearing slacks and
a blouse, but no winter coat.
</P>
<P>
   She had disappeared 18 hours earlier from her home in the 1600
block of North 36th Street, about four blocks south of Parallel
Parkway and east of Interstate 635.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Noone had been outside all night, a night when
temperatures plunged to 29 degrees. Her body temperature was about
65 degrees when she arrived at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She could not be revived.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wyandotte County Coroner Alan Hancock ruled Noone's
death accidental.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas City, Kan., police detectives considered her death
suspicious and refused to drop the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Wyandotte County District Attorney Nick Tomasic
charged Matthew Miles McSpadden with second-degree murder and
Noone's daughter, Hayley Evans _ McSpadden's girlfriend _ with
aiding a felon.
</P>
<P>
   Noone lived with McSpadden, 35, and Evans, 37. Both remained in
the Wyandotte County Detention Center Thursday. McSpadden's bond is
$100,000; Evans' is $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   McSpadden and Evans did not have attorneys as of Thursday and
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Noone's oldest son, Rickey Noone, said McSpadden, Evans and
Noone apparently argued on March 10 and that Noone might have been
assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Noone left the house about 6 p.m. March 10 and was found about
noon March 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how she got there (in the wooded area),''
Tomasic said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The break in the case came late last month when police received
a tip. They refused to reveal the tip or where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put enough feelers out there and everyone knows you're
trying to solve this,'' said Police Det. Greg Lawson. ``Eventually
somebody comes forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and Rickey Noone said that after family members found
Noone, an ambulance crew took her to Bethany Medical Center, where
emergency room personnel tried to revive her. She was pronounced
dead at 3:11 p.m. Detectives were notified about 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the call came in, it was nothing more than an elderly
person who walked away from a house,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson and Det. Bill Howard interviewed McSpadden and Evans and
some other family members at the hospital. They told the detectives
that Noone had left the house after an argument the previous day.
McSpadden and Evans reported her missing about 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Noone said Evans and McSpadden told him they had argued
with his mother before she left the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it seemed reasonable (that she walked out), because I
knew they were in a fight,'' said Noone, who talked to detectives
at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock ruled Noone's death accidental, with the cause being
hypothermia. His autopsy report also noted, however, that Noone had
several small bruises she had suffered over several days before her
death. She also had fractured ribs and a bruise on the right side
of her forehead. Toxicology tests revealed that Noone had alcohol
and sedatives in her system when she died.
</P>
<P>
   Although Noone could have suffered the head wound during a fall,
it was the various other bruises that made detectives wonder
whether they had a case of elder abuse on their hands, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   So the detectives kept Noone's file on their desk, following up
on leads as they surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we called it suspicious is because of the
circumstances,'' Howard said. ``She didn't have Alzheimer's, and
the position of her clothes and her body caused us not to think it
was an accident or a suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, detectives said, interviews with McSpadden and
Evans revealed small inconsistencies, which fueled police
suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Rickey Noone also was suspicious, but he didn't have
any evidence to give detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he knew that his mother never would leave the house
without her purse, which she apparently did on March 10. She also
would have worn a coat, he said, because it was cold that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Noone said, his mother wouldn't have walked into a
wooded area because she had diabetes and was unstable on her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a case of elder abuse,'' Noone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
