<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHERING-COURT-KAN &LR;      06-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERING-COURT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Fathering Court is helping men becoming better dads  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA THESING  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Steve McMichael smiled Thursday as he
graduated from a program that uses counseling, education and social
services instead of jail to make men into better fathers.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael was one of Jackson County Fathering Court's first five
graduates. The program began in March 1998 as an alternative to
jail for fathers delinquent in their child-support payments. It now
includes 45 men who are getting help with everything from job
training to transportation to housing.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jackson County prosecutor's office started the program,
Jane Knitzer, deputy director of the National Center for Children
in Poverty, called the effort unique, broad and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It reflects a shift from jailing so-called deadbeat dads.
Experts have questioned that practice because jailed fathers cannot
earn money to pay child support.
</P>
<P>
   And the Fathering Court has some successes.
</P>
<P>
   Before enrolling in the program, none of the 45 men was
regularly paying child support. Now 26 are paying support, 30 are
working and 31 are spending time with their children. If the other
fathers stay on track, they, too, will earn a diploma from
Fathering Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think it's made me a better person and a better
parent,'' McMichael said. ``I've got a new lease on life.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael said that he had a $40,000-a-year job with the Post
Office when he divorced in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he paid child support regularly, but became depressed
after his divorce and left his Post Office job. He bounced through
other jobs and ended up living out of his car because he could not
afford a place of his own. Still he tried to make his child-support
payments, but fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997 he wound up in court. At that time, the
fathering program was still on the planning table. When it was
ready a few months later, so was McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have dug myself out of that hole by myself. Keep
the program going,'' he said. ``It was an opportunity for me to
turn myself around.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael has now been paying child support for one year and is
employed full time. He said that he is also spending more time with
his sons, ages 12, 14 and 16. He wants them to avoid their father's
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, some fathers attended regular
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helped me pay more attention to my kids,'' McMichael
said. ``Now I try and listen real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Franklin of the National Center for Fathering held 15
two-hour sessions for McMichael and his peers. The participants
talked about their childhoods and their aspirations as fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin said he learned some things from McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who would live in their car to support their children
_ that said a lot to me and to all of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Beaird, Jackson County prosecutor, said he believes the
Fathering Court is the only program of its kind in the country. He
hopes it can serve as a national model and can expand to include
more than 50 participants, the current maximum number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five (graduates) is a small number. We know that,'' Beaird
said. ``We're going to increase it and increase it and increase it
until we've got a program that's the pride of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fathering Court is supported by 30 local agencies. It costs
the county nothing. To expand it, the county is looking toward
national funding or government grants, said Melissa Mauer-Smith,
director of the family support division for the prosecutor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri divisions of family services and child-support
enforcement operate a similar program for noncustodial parents of
children on welfare. Parents Fair Share helps those parents _
usually fathers _ improve their education, find jobs, pay child
support and become more active in their children's lives. Hundreds
of Jackson Countians have participated.
</P>
<P>
   In the prosecutor's program, fathers are eligible for graduation
when they have held a job for several months, paid child support
for several months and are visiting their children regularly,
Mauer-Smith said. All charges related to child-support delinquency
are dropped at graduation, but that doesn't end the fathers'
connections to the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in this program have had trouble facing the
responsibility of a life they created,'' Beaird said. ``Our hope is
that we don't have to deal with them in a criminal setting (again),
but we're there. If they stumble, we're there for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
