<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-ADCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TWO LARGE AGENCIES REVAMP TO SERVE CLIENTS WORLDWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.) (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two big agencies are embarking on reorganizations
that are indicative of the changes being made by Madison Avenue to
meet the needs of clients who market products and services
globally.
</P>
<P>
   One agency is D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications in
New York, part of MacManus Group, which is combining
responsibilities for four regions into a trans-Atlantic operation
to be headed by two top executives.
</P>
<P>
   The other agency is McCann-Erickson North America, a unit of
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, which is combining its two
agencies in San Francisco into a single shop named
McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L, with billings estimated at $335 million.
</P>
<P>
   The DMB&AMP;B reorganization, effective immediately, unites
oversight for North America, Europe, the Middle East and Africa
under John Farrell and Susan Gianinno, who will share the title of
president for the new trans-Atlantic region.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, 41, who had been president at DMB&AMP;B North America, also
becomes regional chief executive for the new regional operation.
Ms. Gianinno, 49, who had been chief branding officer and global
marketing director for DMB&AMP;B, will retain her worldwide branding
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Selkowitz, chairman and chief executive at DMB&AMP;B,
described the reorganization as the largest undertaken by the
agency since it was formed in 1985 by the merger of Benton &AMP; Bowles
with D'Arcy MacManus Masius. DMB&AMP;B has billings estimated at $5.8
billion from clients like Coca-Cola, General Motors, Mars and
Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really changing how we work,'' Ms. Gianinno said
Thursday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to make the borders between offices and regions
more invisible,'' she added, ``linking offices together to access
talent more broadly and open up opportunities to design service
offerings around clients, who are increasingly global.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, who joined Ms. Gianinno for the interview, said that an
earlier reorganization at DMB&AMP;B North America had helped that
regional office land new accounts including Capital One,
Firstsource.com, Ernst &AMP; Young and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to replicate some of the success, and the
different ways of working, on a broader basis,'' Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, two executives will add the duties of regional
chief executive to their portfolios: Paulo Salles, 43, president at
DMB&AMP;B Latin America in Sao Paulo, Brazil, and Garry Titterton, 50,
president at DMB&AMP;B Asia-Pacific in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Also, David Jones, 52, who had been president at the United
Kingdom Group at DMB&AMP;B in London, will take the new post of
European client service director. There will no longer be a British
agency group post, nor will there be a replacement for Johan
Hofstra, who resigned abruptly last month as president for Europe,
the Middle East and Africa; his duties are being assumed by Farrell
and Ms. Gianinno.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the message DMB&AMP;B is seeking to convey about the
extent of the reorganization, as of September its ``short-form
brand'' _ the nickname the agency uses informally _ will be changed
to D'Arcy from DMB&AMP;B The formal corporate name remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to McCann-Erickson, which is part of the McCann-Erickson
World Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies, the
agencies being combined in San Francisco are McCann-Erickson San
Francisco, with estimated billings of $205 million, and Anderson &AMP;
Lembke, with estimated billings of $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   The merger comes two weeks after the two agencies teamed up to
win a large account from the Microsoft Corp., handing the
introduction of the Windows 2000 operating system in the United
States. McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L will also work for clients including
Hewlett-Packard, Nestle, Safeway and SGI, formerly Silicon
Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Bishop, 37, a longtime McCann-Erickson executive who has
been president and chief executive at Anderson &AMP; Lembke, was named
executive vice president and chief executive at
McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L. Ron Benza, 46, executive vice president and
general manager at McCann-Erickson San Francisco, is leaving to
consider opportunities in high-technology marketing, he said, after
exploring other posts at McCann-Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   The merger marks the disappearance of the full Anderson &AMP; Lembke
name; the agency's New York office was absorbed in March by an
Interpublic sibling, Angotti, Thomas, Hedge.
</P>
<P>
   But if DMB&AMP;B wants to go by D'Arcy, what's to prevent
McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L deciding one day to rename itself
McCann-Anderson or even Lembke-Erickson? On second thought, wasn't
Lembke Erickson that famous Viking explorer?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990610.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS &LR;      06-10 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ Dallas Stars coach Ken Hitchcock talked of desperation. He
suggested his team might squeeze off 70 shots, if that's what it
took to dominate The Dominator. His Stars, in turn, assured a more
determined effort than they gave in the opening game of these
Stanley Cup Finals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desperation took more than 57 minutes to make a difference
Thursday night, but the Stars won't quibble about the wait. At the
end of a tense evening at Reunion Arena, Brett Hull's shot beat
Dominik Hasek at 17:10 of the third period, providing the
game-winner as Dallas beat the Buffalo Sabres 4-2 to even the
series at one game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to keep sending something at the net and
make something happen,'' said Hull, who watched linemate Mike
Modano leave the ice with about 10 minutes to play after injuring
his left wrist when he was checked into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Hull finally made something happen. And for the Stars, it was
none too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 is Saturday night in Buffalo, but Dallas assured itself
of bringing the series back to Texas, which was by no means a
certainty for much of the evening. An empty-net goal by Derian
Hatcher with 25.8 seconds left gave the Stars a cushion, but it
came on the heels of a scramble on the other end in which Ed
Belfour struggled to keep the Sabres from sending another game to
OT.
</P>
<P>
   It was every bit that close, and a heavily favored Dallas team
had to feel fortunate about not leaving town with a 2-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a series,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's going to be
this way all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, said Hitchcock, is day-to-day with an injury the coach
termed ``not serious.''
</P>
<P>
   A relatively uneventful first period ended on a livelier note as
emotions spilled over at the horn. Hasek, who earlier drew a charge
from Brian Skrudland in the corner, went down again when Modano
flipped him near the crease in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for guys to get out of the way all the time,''
Hatcher said. ``I know for a fact that Dominik is one to take the
odd dive here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing mini-melee was much ado about nothing, because the
penalties canceled each other out. Still, the emotional ante
clearly had been raised after a relatively civil Game 1 and an
additional 20-minute standoff.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone responded to that early in the second period, it were
the Sabres, and Buffalo finally got tangible results.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Woolley, who scored the game-winner in overtime in Game 1,
was handling the puck at the point near the end of a power play
when he spotted Michael Peca alone across ice on the other side of
the net. Woolley slipped a pass that found its way through the
defense and Peca wristed a quick shot over a sliding Belfour,
making it 1-0 at 7:27 of the period.
</P>
<P>
   That lead held up for more than 10 minutes, including another
failed Dallas power play that drew boos from an increasingly
frustrated Reunion crowd. But the Stars came alive in the final two
minutes, and Jamie Langenbrunner evened the score when he deflected
a Richard Matvichuk blast by Hasek at 18:26 to even things up
entering the final 20 minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, Buffalo was having the best of it. The Sabres
had outshot the Stars 17-12 and had killed three more Dallas power
plays.
</P>
<P>
   A tripping penalty against Alexei Zhitnik at the end of the
second gave Dallas another power play chance to open the third, but
the Stars again failed to capitalize, making it 13 consecutive
successful kills for Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas got a rare goal from defenseman Craig Ludwig early in the
third to take a 2-1 lead, but it didn't last long. Within a minute,
Daryl Sydor was in the penalty box for a high stick, and Zhitnik
made the Stars pay when he picked up the rebound of a Curtis Brown
slap shot and poked it by Belfour to again tie the score at 2.
</P>
<P>
   The game seemed headed to overtime as the Stars flailed away,
but Hull finally found a bit of open space just inside the post and
blasted a shot past Hasek to allow Dallas to escape with the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept coming,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
