<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH COW SOON MIGHT BE A STRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The administration's view of tobacco as a cash cow
calls for an economics lesson relating to the concept of
elasticity.
</P>
<P>
   As the GOP majority in Congress mulls deep cuts in domestic
programs such as education and health care to stay within mandated
spending caps, the White House budget director has urged a
revenue-enhancing alternative. High on his list is yet another hit
on smokers to raise about $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Personal feelings about the merits of tobacco use aside, this
approach to tax policy gives irrationality a bad name. Its problem
is that it ignores the question of how large the cigarette tax
burden must get before smokers stop allowing government to rip them
off.
</P>
<P>
   When economists consider such matters, they do so in the context
of price elasticity of demand. It's used to quantify a consumer's
sensitivity to prices by measuring the change in demand for a good
or service as its price rises or declines.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, demand for something is relatively elastic,
raising its price can be expected to reduce demand. If this sounds
counterintuitive, think of the situation as one where consumers are
flexible when it comes to need for the particular good. They may
cut consumption or substitute something else.
</P>
<P>
   If demand for something is relatively inelastic, on the other
hand, the effect of a price boost won't be as significant. This is
true, however, only up to a point, and defining that point is
tricky work.
</P>
<P>
   Those whose life's work has become enhancing government revenue
by taxing cigarettes have found smokers an inelastic lot. Despite
escalating taxes sending the cost of cigarettes into the
stratosphere, many Americans refuse to be deterred by the soaring
cost of their habit.
</P>
<P>
   This has led those in revenue-enhancing circles to assume the
sky's the limit as far as cigarette taxes are concerned. Facing a
fiscal challenge in Washington? No problemo. Just slap another few
billion dollars worth of tax levies on hapless smokers. Not only
will smokers put up with anything, but they also are one of the few
species unprotected by political-correctness constraints.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, however, inelasticity will start to turn elastic.
Those who can't afford the added cost will quit. Many for whom
money isn't a problem will also quit rather than allow themselves
to be cynically abused by their government.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the substitution option, but what substitutes for
cigarettes? Since corn silk and coffee grounds aren't acceptable
alternatives, what gets substituted is the source of the product.
When the price of legal cigarettes becomes too high, it's
reasonable to expect the emergence of a cigarette black market.
Where the illegal supply would come from remains to be seen, but
humankind has always been very creative in these matters.
</P>
<P>
   Government uses economists to figure price elasticities, and it
would be interesting to know whether the administration is
consulting them in its quest to see how long this golden goose can
be flogged before it dies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what makes this policy approach all the more bizarre
is that government pursues fairly expensive efforts to discourage
smoking while simultaneously using it as a cash cow.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
