</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. ASSEMBLY APPROVES PARENTAL NOTIFICATION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey moved closer Thursday to enacting its
first significant restriction on abortion in decades as the General
Assembly passed a bill that would require girls under 18 to notify
their parents before they can receive an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which received enthusiastic support from the
Assembly speaker, Jack Collins, is also expected to win approval in
the state Senate. If it passes, New Jersey would be the 38th state
to require that teen-agers receive parental notification or
parental consent to obtain abortions. Texas has approved a similar
bill, which is to take effect on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey bill marks a departure for Gov. Christie Whitman.
She had been a staunch supporter of abortion rights who has opposed
parental notification in the past, but she has agreed to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents hailed the vote, which was 59-17, and said
they hoped it signaled a turning point in the abortion debate in
New Jersey, which has historically had some of the most
unrestrictive abortion laws in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the polls show a shift in our favor, that a majority of
New Jersey residents now support some restrictions on abortion,''
said Marie Tasy, director of New Jersey Right to Life. ``The laws
are now starting to reflect that. It started two years ago, with
the partial-birth abortion vote, and now it has escalated with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Legislature passed a ban on an abortion procedure
that its opponents call partial-birth abortion by overriding
Whitman's veto, but the governor has successfully challenged the
measure in court.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said last month that she supported the parental
notification bill after changes were made to broaden the
circumstances under which a judge could grant a waiver of the rule.
For instance, a teen-ager would be allowed to have an abortion if
she seemed mature enough to make that decision herself. And the law
would not apply to married teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters, who were stunned late last month
when conservatives introduced the proposal and quickly won the
governor's support, vowed to continue lobbying against the parental
notification bill. Elizabeth Volz, president of the New Jersey
chapter of the National Organization for Women, said it was
irresponsible for state leaders to appeal to conservative voters by
restricting a young woman's access to a safe abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not stand by as young women are returned to the bad
old days of fear, humiliation and botched abortions,'' Ms. Volz
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her group has tried to persuade the governor to reverse
her position in recent days to no avail. So NOW and other groups
that support abortion rights will conduct an emergency
demonstration on the State House steps on Monday in an effort to
sway state senators to oppose the bill. The Senate is expected to
vote on the bill next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked by what the governor did,'' Ms. Volz said.
``Christie Whitman has always been pro-choice. So everyone was
stunned to see her take such an anti-choice position.''
</P>
<P>
   The notification bill is one of five pieces of legislation
introduced by conservatives last month in an effort to win
concessions from Whitman, who needs right-wing support for her race
for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   In another action Thursday, the Assembly, whose members are up
for re-election this year, passed another conservative social
initiative: a bill that would mandate that teachers and students in
public schools begin each day by reciting the second paragraph of
the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Two other pieces of legislation proposed by conservatives are
likely to be voted on before the Legislature begins its summer
recess later this month. One would require sex-education
instructors to teach that abstinence is the only fail-safe way to
avoid contracting the HIV virus. The other would require parental
consent before a minor could get a tattoo. Another bill, which
would ban gay marriages, is unlikely to clear its committee before
the fall, said John Tomicki, executive director of the League of
American Families, who has coordinated the conservative legislative
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman John Rooney, who sponsored the parental notification
bill, said the measures were both good policy and sound politics.
Rooney, a Republican from Bergen County, said the notification bill
was primarily intended to protect parents, who he said should have
the right to be informed before their children make a major life
decision and undergo a complicated medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Lowenstein, executive director of Right to Choose, said
that if the notification measure is passed by the state Senate and
is signed into law as expected, it will mark the most momentous
setback for abortion rights since 1982, when the Legislature voted
to ban the use of public funds for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Parental notification laws have survived court challenges in
many states. But Ms. Lowenstein said, ``The Legislature's action in
1982 was overturned in court, and we think this one is
unconstitutional, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
