<SLUG> BC-KAUFFMAN-REFUND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES KAUFFMANS' 1991 TAX REFUND CLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ A federal judge Thursday ruled that the
Ewing and Muriel Kauffman estates were not entitled to a tax refund
of nearly $22 million stemming from the buyback of Avron B.
Fogelman's interest in the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   In a summary judgment, U.S. District Judge John W. Lungstrum in
Kansas City, Kan., ruled that on their 1991 joint tax return the
Kauffmans could not write off $35.8 million as a bad debt that they
said resulted from a $34 million loan on which Fogelman defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing Kauffman died in 1993, and Muriel Kauffman died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After the deduction was rejected by the Internal Revenue
Service, the Kauffman estates paid $22.8 million in taxes and
interest in 1995 _ most but not all of which was related to the
bad-debt claim _ and then filed suit in 1997 for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   The purported loan was the culmination of a complex series of
financial transactions that began in 1983 with the goal of Fogelman
eventually becoming majority owner of the Royals. It was derailed
in the late 1980s when his Memphis, Tenn., real estate empire
encountered severe financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   The purported loan was secured by 50 percent of the Royals stock
held by Fogelman. The stock was redeemed by the Royals in 1991
after Fogelman defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   The $34 million transaction was set up as a loan and designed to
protect Fogelman's stock, his only unencumbered asset, from his
creditors, who might try to grab it and sell or move the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Kauffmans said the Royals stock in 1991 had no value because
an attempt to sell the team at auction in December 1990 brought no
bids that would cover the Royals' existing financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that claim, the Kauffmans took the entire $34 million,
plus interest, as a bad-debt deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Lungstrum found that under federal tax laws the transaction with
Fogelman was not a loan _ despite the way it was set up _ but a
stock redemption on which no deduction could be claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Before the transaction, in July 1990, Fogelman agreed to give up
any right to retain an ownership interest in the Royals even if he
had paid off the so-called loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence in this case ... adds up to the legal conclusion
that the ($34 million) transaction was a redemption of Mr.
Fogelman's stock and not a bona fide debt,'' Lungstrum wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said Fogelman ``had no incentive or obligation to
repay his purported debt in `money,' and he parted with all of the
burdens and ... benefits of his Royals interest.''
</P>
<P>
   After recovering full ownership of the team, Ewing Kauffman left
the team to a charitable organization.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley D. Sears, the lawyer representing the Kauffman estates,
said he had not had time to study the ruling and could not comment.
The Kauffman estates are expected to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Department of Justice said the
department did not comment on tax cases.
</P>
<P>
   Lungstrum gave the parties until July 17 to notify him if there
are any unresolved issues in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
