<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRAUD-VERDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSMAN CONVICTED OF FRAUD BUT JURY DEADLOCKS ON PYRAMID
SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick R. Bennett, the businessman accused of
orchestrating one of the largest financial swindles in U.S.
history, was convicted Thursday of fraud and money laundering by a
federal jury in Manhattan _ but not of running a Ponzi scheme, a
charge that was at the heart of the indictment against him.
</P>
<P>
   The jury reported that it was deadlocked over 11 securities and
mail fraud charges that related to the operation of Bennett's
company, Bennett Funding Group, in Syracuse, which purported to
finance leases on office equipment like copiers and fax machines.
Prosecutors contend that the company was basically a giant Ponzi,
or pyramid, scheme that defrauded more than 10,000 investors, many
of them elderly people living in New York, New Jersey and Florida,
out of more than $600 million before it collapsed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Martin declared a mistrial on the unresolved charges;
prosecutors have not yet decided whether they will retry Bennett,
said Herbert Hadad, a spokesman for Mary Jo White, the U.S.
attorney for the Southern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's deadlock marked the second time a jury has been
unable to reach a verdict on those charges; in early March, a
different jury failed to reach a verdict on any of the charges in
the case except for some _ involving perjury and obstruction of
justice _ to which Bennett confessed on the witness stand. He did
not testify in the latest trial, which began in May.
</P>
<P>
   The charges Bennett was convicted of Thursday involved illegal
money manipulation and securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett faces a sentence of more than 20 years in prison on
those charges, and he was ordered to forfeit $109 million, money
his lawyers say he does not have.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gombiner, one of Bennett's lawyers, said Bennett planned to
appeal the verdict. ``We think there are some significant legal
issues involving their failure to reach a verdict'' on the
underlying leasing issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's lawyers described him as an inept businessman who was
overwhelmed by his rapidly growing company, rather than a criminal
mastermind. They did not deny that investors had lost huge sums
investing in Bennett leases and other securities, but suggested
that some of Bennett's business associates may have been
responsible for any fraud. Several of them, including Bennett's
brother, Michael, have pleaded guilty to various charges in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The unresolved charges involved the assignment of office
equipment leases to investors, who were to receive monthly income.
The government contended that many investors were assigned
nonexistent leases, or leases whose income was committed to other
investors. In a Ponzi scheme, some of the money put in by later
investors is used to make payments to earlier investors, and some
is siphoned off by the scheme's operators.
</P>
<P>
   Martin revoked Bennett's bail and ordered him imprisoned
immediately, a move which some lawyers said is unusual for
white-collar defendants who have not yet been sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Bennett ``a totally amoral individual who would engage
in any criminal conduct that would benefit him in any way,'' Martin
said he was concerned that if Bennett remained out on bail, ``he
would look for some scheme to get money he needed without any
concern for the impact on others.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin warned Bennett that trying to keep any of the assets he
had acquired as a result of the fraud could lead to a longer prison
sentence. ``If, when we get to the time of sentencing, I find Mr.
Bennett and his family trying to hang on to money taken by this
massive fraud, that act will have consequences,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge may also impose fines, and require Bennett to pay
restitution to his victims. The victims may also apply to the
Justice Department to try to claim any money that Bennett forfeits
as a result of his conviction on the money-laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he has any money to forfeit is unclear. Bennett owns
a large house outside Syracuse. Prosecutors said he spent millions
of dollars he took from Bennett Funding buying a local horse racing
track, hotels and several gambling enterprises. Breeden said he
believes the Bennett family has assets hidden overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has said he is indigent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
