<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-CHANCELLOR11-COX     06-10 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-CHANCELLOR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Texas chancellor announces resignation
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ William Cunningham, a leading figure in Texas
higher education for the past 14 years, stunned lawmakers, faculty
and many others Thursday when he announced he will resign next year
to pursue interests in the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who has been chancellor of the 15-campus University
of Texas System since 1992 and was UT-Austin president the seven
years before that, said he is leaving ``the best job in the world''
because the system is in good shape and he wants to explore a new
career. He and his bosses _ the UT System Board of Regents _ said
the decision to resign by Aug. 31, 2000, was entirely Cunningham's.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 55, is credited with extending higher education
opportunities in South Texas, raising the system's profile and
effectively courting donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad to see him leave,'' said regents' Chairman Donald
Evans. ``He's an extraordinary leader for the UT System and the
state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some lawmakers and others said privately that he
clashed with some legislators during the pressure-filled
legislative session that just ended. Cunningham also must work with
a Board of Regents that is drastically different than the one that
hired him as chancellor, when Democrat Ann Richards was governor.
The new board consists entirely of Republican Gov. George W. Bush's
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a close friend of Bush's, said he has grappled with false
rumors for the past two years that Bush wanted a new chancellor _ a
claim Bush's office also denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely 100 percent Dr. Cunningham's decision,''
Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Patrick Oxford said the board never discussed the
possibility of changing chancellors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way to look at it is from his perspective,''
Oxford said. ``He's got to deal with new sets of regents every
year, the legislative sessions are brutal, more and more so. He had
a good session and this gave him the opportunity to leave on a high
note.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford and Evans said it was premature to talk about a
successor, and the system's No. 2 official, Vice Chancellor Ed
Sharpe, would not say whether he is interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' Sharpe said. ``The board will make that
decision. ... As for Bill, he has given careful thought to this,
and I understand his decision and respect his reasons. I really
think he has a good sense of timing...and is going out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, known for his optimism and ability to charm
audiences, was upbeat when he announced his decision at a crowded
news conference in the board's spacious meeting room. He said the
decision was a hard one because he loves his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I like better than a crisis or a problem to
solve,'' he said, adding that he wished he could have done more to
increase college graduation rates _ a major problem in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview later, he said he told his only child, John, a
senior at Texas A&AMP;M University, that it was time for him to try
something different, perhaps a career in electronic commerce or
some other business opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Dad, you deserve it,''' Cunningham said, his eyes
starting to fill up. He said having the support of his son _ whom
he once said he wished he had spent more time with _ ``made me feel
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, a quintessential manager of information, made calls
throughout the day along with his staff to lawmakers and other
state leaders, letting them know of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   As the chief executive of one of the largest and most complex
university systems, Cunningham spoke of his accomplishments _
greatly expanding higher education into South Texas, offering
degree programs on the Internet, instituting a cost-savings
initiative throughout the UT System, raising endowments and helping
to win a record $1.2 billion in new dollars for higher education
from the Legislature this year.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders credited Cunningham with fostering Austin's
high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He provided important leadership at a time of a lot of change
in Austin and at UT,'' said Steve Papermaster, director of
Powershift Group and CEO of Agillion Inc., local high-tech
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Cunningham also had his share of controversies, including
recommending a UT campus building be a named for his friend,
Freeport-McMoRan Chief Executive Jim Bob Moffett, and serving on
Freeport's board while it threatened to sue three UT professors for
slander. He also pursued a major buildup of athletics facilities,
which faculty decried; accepted large pay raises when surveys
showed nonteaching staff were vastly underpaid; and was believed by
many to be a key force behind the 1997 departure of a popular UT
president, Robert Berdahl.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said he was control freak who refused to let go of the
Austin campus and made it difficult for Berdahl to be president.
Berdahl's successor, Larry Faulkner, said his relationship with
Cunningham has been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will feel a keen sense of loss with his departure from the
post,'' Faulkner said. ``I have been continually impressed by his
energy, his resilience and his commitment to the university, to the
system and to the people of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty, however, are not impressed by Cunningham, who was
educated at Michigan State University and came to UT as an
assistant business professor in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be charming, articulate and clever, but I
haven't always found him to be on the cutting edge of what we
needed academically,'' said Michael Siciliano, past president of a
systemwide Faculty Advisory Council and a professor of cancer
genetics at UT's M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. ``He's a good,
practical person and someone you could trade horses with.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his ability to charm with humor, Cunningham also could
be abrasive.
</P>
<P>
   The state's six university chancellors had approached the
Legislature in January as a coalition, but it almost collapsed
because of bickering and differences.
</P>
<P>
   During a particularly tense time, Cunningham and Texas A&AMP;M
Chancellor Barry Thompson had a loud confrontation in a hallway at
the Capitol that prompted Texas Tech Chancellor John Montford to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of doing physical harm, but I was maybe a
little heated,'' Thompson said, adding that he has grown to respect
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the chancellors got back together and accomplished
parts of their agenda. Cunningham won the Legislature's approval of
a proposed constitutional amendment that will allow the UT and
Texas A&AMP;M Systems to spend more money from the Permanent University
Fund _ provided voters say yes in November.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
