<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-REGENT11-COX     06-10 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-REGENT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regent quits Introgen post after question of conflict
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A University of Texas regent is stepping down as
a director of a potentially lucrative company to which he and other
regents awarded the rights to develop and market a UT invention.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Loeffler of San Antonio said Thursday he was resigning from
the board of Introgen Therapeutics Inc. of Austin after ``a
legitimate question'' was raised a day earlier by the Austin
American-Statesman about his role as a director and shareholder of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the questions being raised, I think it is more important
not to go through a discussion about whether one should or should
not be on a board like that,'' he said. ``Because of my
responsibilities and commitments to the UT System, I've made a
decision to resign from the board'' of Introgen.
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler, who is also a lawyer, lobbyist and a fund-raiser for
Gov. George W. Bush's probable presidential bid, voted with eight
other regents in October 1994 to authorize UT to sign a licensing
agreement with Introgen. The company was created specifically to
commercialize a promising cancer-fighting gene therapy discovered
at UT's M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. In March 1997, Loeffler joined
Introgen as a director, with stock options.
</P>
<P>
   If the company sells the stock publicly or is acquired, its
holdings would be substantial and could be worth between $500
million to $1 billion, said William Doty, director of technology
development at M.D. Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The head of a government watchdog group in Austin said he would
urge Bush to order a review of regents and their business ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted to see Mr. Loeffler has chosen to resign to
reduce any conflicts,'' said Tom ``Smitty'' Smith, Texas state
director of Public Citizen. ``But I think there ought to be a
complete review of whether there are conflicts between board
members of universities and the companies who do business with
universities and sell products that are spun off from university
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler said Thursday he had no idea when he voted in 1994 that
he would later become affiliated with Introgen. Asked in retrospect
whether it was appropriate for him to join the company, Loeffler
said he did not violate ethics policies and wanted to put the issue
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a choice of picking between the University of Texas and a
private company, and I chose the University of Texas,'' Loeffler
said.
</P>
<P>
   UT System legal counsel Ray Farabee said that, as far as he
knew, Loeffler's role in the company was not a conflict of
interest. The law says a regent can be a director of a company that
the university does business with as long as the regent does not
own more than 5 percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler said Thursday he could not recall how many shares of
stock he had an option to purchase. But he said the amount was
``well below'' 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler, who was appointed to the UT board in 1989, also said
he will not exercise his stock options ``during the time I am part
of the UT System.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler disclosed on the financial statement he is required to
file with the Texas Ethics Commission that he had options on
``10,000 or more'' shares of Introgen stock. The company is
privately held, and it could not be determined from public
documents whether the amount of his options are close to or
significantly more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The company had planned to go public in November 1996 by selling
2.5 million shares on the stock market for $11 a share. But because
of market conditions, it withdrew those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
