u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEY-CUP-NYT &LR;      06-10 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL SEES FEWER EVILS IN THE FINALS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Should Brian Skrudland of the Dallas Stars have been
suspended for head-butting Vaclav Varada of the Buffalo Sabres?
Colin Campbell, the senior vice president of the National Hockey
League, dismissed the question Thursday as unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you suspend a guy for that during the Stanley Cup
finals?'' Campbell asked, in a tone of voice that implied such a
thing was unthinkable to him.
</P>
<P>
   Some people would have said yes, but Campbell said no _ and he
makes these decisions as the league's chief enforcer of discipline.
So Skrudland was again available to the Stars for Game 2 of the
championship round Friday night in Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   During Game 1, a 3-2 Buffalo victory in overtime Tuesday night,
Skrudland, with some force, thrust his helmeted head into Varada's
face late in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the incident was ``part of the play,'' although it
took place after a whistle had blown. Campbell said neither of the
referees, Terry Gregson and Bill McCreary, thought the incident
merited a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something both referees didn't think was callable; they
didn't even see it as it happened,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   This may be true, but players are sometimes suspended for deeds
that are observed later on videotape, though the players have not
been penalized for them on the spot. Skrudland's head butt was
replayed by the Fox network, which televised the game live, and was
shown several times later on ESPN. Campbell said head-butting has
resulted in suspensions at least twice, but added that these
instances took place ``in a fight when a player stops and
head-butts a guy and it does damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell apparently decided that this particular head-butt did
not merit suspension because it did not occur during a fight and
did no damage to Varada. Campbell said that during the regular
season, the league might suspend a player for such a head butt to
prove a point, but that ``there's a lot at stake'' in the finals, a
four-of-seven-game series that will move to Buffalo for Games 3 and
4 on Saturday and Tuesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland is a 35-year-old center who played for Campbell
briefly in 1997-98 when Campbell coached the Rangers. Varada is a
23-year-old right wing from the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Buffalo News, Varada discussed the head
butt. ``That was terrible,'' he said. ``It was a cheap shot. The
referee, McCreary, looked at him, then right in my eyes. He told me
it was nothing. I couldn't believe it. They have a very old team.
When you're older than 35, you can get away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabres Coach Lindy Ruff said Varada might have got a more
supportive reaction from the referees if he had fallen to the ice
and acted as if he had been injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it doesn't warrant a suspension at this time of year,''
Ruff said. ``But it is a major penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Twin Deal?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One regular event during the Stanley Cup finals is the
appearance of the top prospects in the amateur entry draft, which
will be held June 26 in Boston. Scouts consider this year's crop of
18-year-olds to be better than average, and European-born forwards
are among the best of the bunch. Few have attracted as much
interest as the twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin, who play for MoDo of
Sweden and hope to play together in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Their agent, Mike Barnett, who also represented Wayne Gretzky,
is talking to general managers in the league about placing the
twins on the same team. ``It would be a dream,'' Daniel Sedin said.
``We're working on it.'' Daniel Sedin is a left wing; Henrik is a
center.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel is listed as 6 feet 1 inch and 194 pounds; Henrik is 6-2
and 196. They are the top two players, not including goalies, from
Europe in the Central Scouting ranking.
</P>
<P>
   The top two North American prospects, Patrik Stefan and Pavel
Brendl, are also European-born, from the Czech Republic, but play
for teams on this continent. Stefan plays for Long Beach of the
International Hockey League, a professional circuit. Brendl plays
for Calgary of the Western Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Power-Play Nod to Stars  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special teams usually make a difference, and Game 1 of the
finals proved no exception. The Stars had 10 power plays but scored
only one goal with manpower advantages over 19 minutes 41 seconds.
The Sabres also scored one power-play goal, but had only four power
plays over 7:09.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time in the second period on the bench, one of the
TV timeouts, where we said, `Enough is enough,''' Coach Lindy Ruff
said, adding that Buffalo's Dixon Ward had just taken a ``totally
undisciplined penalty'' for punching a Dallas player. ``I just
said, `No more, we can't take any more of these,''' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Stars Coach Ken Hitchcock said his team had 21 scoring chances
on its power plays, ``which is a lot for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we didn't score, but it is very difficult to criticize
our power play with the opportunities,'' Hitchcock said. ``We had a
ton of chances. We are a diagonal group. We aren't a group that
just pulls it back to the point and hammers it. We are a group that
really relies on seams, and we found those seams. In the two power
plays that were given in the overtime, we found great seams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
