<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AND REPUBLICANS ACT ON SOCIAL SECURITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and Democrats took a first, tentative
step Thursday toward negotiating a deal to shore up Social
Security, agreeing that the House Ways and Means Committee would
meet in private sessions to explore whether the two parties can
bridge their differences.
</P>
<P>
   There still appears to be little prospect of an agreement on the
issue, which is among the most politically sensitive and complex
facing Congress and the Clinton administration. Given the deadlock
that has prevailed for nearly a year and a half, the decision to
hold bipartisan talks at least improved the odds and suggested that
neither party wanted to be seen as having given up.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough, such as it was, came when Rep. Bill Archer,
the Texas Republican who is chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, picked up on a comment made at a hearing on Wednesday by
Rep. Charles B. Rangel of New York, the panel's senior Democrat.
Rangel said any progress would have to be made away from the
microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the second of two days of hearings called to review the
array of proposals for strengthening Social Security to insure it
can weather the retirement of the baby boom generation, Archer
offered Thursday to hold private sessions ``to discuss areas of
common ground and a potential legislative outline.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel and other Democrats quickly accepted, although Rangel
suggested that he wanted to involve the White House in any
discussions and that the talks could only be meaningful if they
were blessed by the leadership of both parties. Both parties are
suspicious that the other is more interested in laying a political
trap before the 2000 elections than in finding a bipartisan
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Archer did not say when he would hold the closed-door sessions,
at which members of both parties would presumably be more willing
than in public to talk about the politically painful tradeoff that
both sides would have to make to reach a deal. He called on
President Clinton to meet with the committee's Republicans to help
``keep this process moving forward in a bipartisan fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the White House economic adviser, said that he
did not know the details of Archer's proposal, but that the
administration welcomed ``any good faith, constructive efforts at
bipartisan cooperation.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
