<SLUG> BC-GOOD-SHEPHERD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK FROM SCANDAL MAKES NONPROFIT GROUP A CANDIDATE FOR AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Leaders of the Community of the Good Shepherd
say they didn't know what to expect last year when they set a
$45,000 fund-raising goal.
</P>
<P>
   The sum was the largest the nonprofit organization had asked for
since a financial scandal five years ago almost put it out of
business. To the leaders' surprise, the drive hit its goal and then
surpassed it almost fourfold.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback has landed the organization in the running for
national recognition from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Good Shepherd is one of more than two dozen Kansas City-area
organizations and 3,000 nationally that are nominated for what the
Department of Housing and Urban Development calls its Best
Practices Award.
</P>
<P>
   The awards are given to organizations and programs that HUD
officials consider to be the top 100 in the nation for creative
problem-solving and effective use of resources.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 winners will be named at a national symposium of about
5,000 social service officials that HUD is holding July 20-24 at
Bartle Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Good Shepherd was nominated ``because they have come back from
such a terrible position,'' said Rosanne Smith, the HUD senior
project manager in Kansas City who initially proposed Good Shepherd
for the award.
</P>
<P>
   Good Shepherd's need for the money seemed plain when the fund
drive began.
</P>
<P>
   HUD-financed group homes that Good Shepherd runs in south Kansas
City needed repairs and improvements that couldn't be put off any
longer without compromising the services provided for the
developmentally disabled men living there.
</P>
<P>
   And Kansas Citians are generous. A higher percentage of area
households give regularly to charities than in many other major
cities. The average household gift of $1,319 annually is about 23
percent larger than the national average, according to one
independent study.
</P>
<P>
   But previous donors to Good Shepherd had been burned.
</P>
<P>
   A former executive director went to prison for stealing hundreds
of thousands of dollars in the early 1990s. Leery potential donors
shunned the organization immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our top financial priority for a long time was simply keeping
the homes from closing,'' said Kandice Walker, whom Good Shepherd
hired as development director as part of the reforms after the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The organization immediately instituted a much tighter system of
financial checks and balances. The homes then managed to scrape by
with funding from federal programs and private grants, usually no
larger than $2,000 or $5,000, during the leanest years after the
scandal, said Sharon Higney, the organization's administrator.
</P>
<P>
   When directors approved the $45,000 fund-raising target, to pay
for repairs, redecoration and replacement of equipment that the
homes' more than 30 residents had been using for almost a decade,
Higney was guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would take at least a couple of years to reach
our goal,'' Higney said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it took just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate and civic donors whom fund-raisers approached were
cautious at first. Some asked for formal documents outlining the
new checks and balances. Others asked for copies of independent
audits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we had all our ducks in a row, we provided everything
they asked for,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, some funders visited the home and met the guys. That
helped, too, because they could see we were spending money where we
were supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, ``no one turned us down because of our past
history,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as heartening, individual contributors responded
generously, too, she said. Of the approximately $170,000 ultimately
raised in the drive, about $30,000 came from individual
contributors, ``often $10 or $20 at a time,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Good Shepherd will use the extra money to increase the care it
provides for its residents, to whom staff members refer informally
as ``the guys,'' in the face of another challenge, Higney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are getting older,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, many Good Shepherd residents are men in their late
teens to late 60s who need help with basic living activities such
as bathing, dressing or meal preparation, but are otherwise healthy
enough to enjoy jobs, hobbies and other interests outside the
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Good Shepherd officials worry about what will happen to the
residents as time passes and normal changes that are a part of
aging kick in on top of the developmental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Without additional care provided by successful fund raising,
many of the community's residents presumably will have to turn to
nursing homes or a similar facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might not be what they need, but it may be the only other
choice,'' Higney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
