<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-WEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST TO CLOSE RESERVATIONS CENTER IN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ America West Airlines will close its
reservations center near Kansas City International Airport in
September, eliminating about 180 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   America West officials told the Kansas City Aviation Department
recently that the airline would not renew its lease, which expires
in November, said Joe McBride, an Aviation Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   America West opened the Kansas City facility in 1992. But in
recent years, employment at the call center has dropped from 300 to
the current 180 workers.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the airline was not refilling jobs lost through
attrition as it prepared to open a call center in Reno, Nev. The
Reno facility opened last week. The Phoenix-based airline also has
a reservations center in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Nowack, an America West spokeswoman, said Thursday that
trying to recruit workers in Kansas City had become difficult in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many call centers in that market for us to be
competitive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The call center industry employs more than 40,000 people in the
Kansas City area, with some making up to $17 an hour. America West
paid its reservations agents $7.50 to $12.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   America West has installed a reservations system that would have
required the Kansas City call center to be upgraded if it remained
open, Nowack said.
</P>
<P>
   Area America West employees are being offered transfers to the
airline's call centers in Tempe or Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The severance package includes a week's pay for each year
worked. In addition, America West employees will be provided a
$1,500 moving allowance if they transfer and a $1,000 bonus to stay
with the company until Sept. 1, Nowack said.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said the city was seeking a new tenant for the
city-owned facility at 10801 N. Amity Road.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, including one airline, have expressed interest in
the facility, McBride said. He declined to identify the companies.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said the building would be useful for data processing or
other office operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the building is configured, we think it's pretty
marketable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vanguard Airlines recently looked at the building, the
low-cost carrier decided to stay with its reservations center in
Mission, said Dick Barr of Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``If any of the displaced (America West) people want to
stay with an airline, we would be happy to recruit them,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before America West occupied the building, Braniff Inc. operated
a reservations center there. Braniff collapsed in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
