<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CENTURY ACQUIRES STAKE IN ELECTRONIC STOCK TRADING
SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ American Century Investments has acquired a 5
percent interest in an electronic stock trading system, the Kansas
City-based mutual fund company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   American Century acquired an ``indirect economic interest'' in
Archipelago Holdings LLC. Archipelago operates an electronic
communications network. Such networks use computers to match buyers
and sellers of stocks without working through traditional stock
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund company acquired its stake through J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. Inc., which owns 45 percent of American Century. Morgan
acquired a 20 percent interest in Archipelago, and a fourth of that
holding was funded from American Century, said Harold Bradley, who
manages the American Century Heritage Fund and previously led the
fund family's stock trading operations.
</P>
<P>
   The companies did not disclose terms of the investments in
Archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   Before the transaction, Archipelago was owned by four groups:
ETrade Group Inc., Goldman Sachs Group Inc., Virago Enterprises LLC
and Townsend Analytics Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, American Century acquired an 8.6 percent
interest in Tradepoint Financial Networks PLC. Tradepoint is an
electronic stock exchange in London. The transaction involved an
investment consortium among Instinet Corp., which is an electronic
communications network owned by Reuters Group PLC; Archipelago;
American Century; J.P. Morgan; and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   American Century also had acquired less than 5 percent of W.R.
Hambrecht &AMP; Co., which conducts stock offerings over the Internet
at www.openIPO.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said other such strategic investments by American
Century were likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not done. This is a very exciting and quickly
evolving period,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
