<SLUG> BC-MORGANSTANLEY-SCANDAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY'S GENERAL COUNSEL RESIGNS IN INFORMANT PAYMENT
SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CORRECTS spelling to Bernhein in third graf, age of Edwards
in 11th graf) 
(ATTN: Calif., Ill.) (rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's general counsel stepped
down from her job and a senior in-house lawyer resigned in
connection with a $10,000 payment to a police informant, as the
Wall Street giant sought to end what two top executives said in a
statement was ``a difficult time for our firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine A. Edwards, the general counsel, stepped aside and
accepted a part-time role as an advisory director, Morgan Stanley
said, calling the decision voluntary and against the wishes of the
firm's management committee.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe R. Sonnenborn, a managing director in the legal
department who had been suspended with pay last month, resigned
under pressure. Carol Bernhein, a third in-house lawyer who
reported to Sonnenborn and had also been suspended with pay last
month, will resume her duties.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel changes were announced together with the results
of an internal investigation into the circumstances surrounding
Morgan Stanley's decision to pay $10,000 to Charles Joseph Luethke,
an informant involved in the arrest last year of former employee
Christian L. Curry.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, conducted by Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP;
Garrison, a Manhattan law firm, found that there was ``no
satisfactory explanation'' for why Morgan Stanley failed to keep
the Manhattan district attorney's office informed about
developments in the Curry case. That failure prompted the district
attorney's office to launch a criminal investigation of Morgan
Stanley's conduct, which is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard on our organization to see the firm's name look
bad in the public domain day after day,'' said Philip J. Purcell,
Morgan Stanley's chairman and chief executive officer ``That's why
the pressure was on to get this out publicly, get the facts out,
and hope it's the end of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell and John J. Mack, Morgan Stanley's president, said they
were especially dismayed at how their legal department responded to
requests for information about the $10,000 payment from the
district attorney's office. It took six weeks to inform the
district attorney's office about the payment, a Paul, Weiss report
on the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation also found that legal department
officials did not respond quickly even after the district attorney
had issued two grand jury subpoenas to the firm last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is our interaction with the D.A.,'' said Mack.
``Our employees do not understand how this breakdown happened with
the D.A., and we want to lay it out for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards, the general counsel, was not found to be directly
responsible for the mistakes, according the the Paul, Weiss report.
She was informed of the $10,000 payment to Luethke a short time
before it was made, the report said, but was not kept abreast of
troubles with the district attorney's office. Ms. Edwards decided
to step down on her own, and a statement issued by the firm quoted
her as saying that the problem ``happened on my watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old general counsel, who earned $7.5 million in
total compensation last year, had been a close colleague of
Purcell. They served together at Dean Witter before that retail
brokerage firm merger with Morgan Stanley two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, both worked at Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. The families of
Purcell and Ms. Edwards still live in Chicago, and the two
sometimes commute together to Chicago and back to New York, where
Morgan Stanley is based.
</P>
<P>
   Both Purcell and Mack said they were surprised by Ms. Edwards'
decision to step down and said that they had not pressured her to
do so. They said she would continue to handle some legal and public
affairs issues for the firm in her new role.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the blame for the mistakes surrounding the $10,000
payment fell on Sonnenborn, a 15-year veteran of Morgan Stanley.
Sonnenborn was the senior-most official involved directly in
managing the relationship with Luethke, authorizing the $10,000
payment and dealing with the district attorney's office, people
close to the firm said. Sonnenborn did inform Ms. Edwards about the
payment before it was made, but only one day before, and then not
in detail, the internal report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the report suggested, Sonnenborn did not
keep Ms. Edwards abreast of brewing troubles with the district
attorney's office. Ms. Edwards did not learn until May of this year
that the district attorney had convened a grand jury to issue
subpoenas to the firm half a year before, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also reiterated that neither Purcell nor Mack knew of
the payment to Luethke, adding that they did not learn of it until
April of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenborn could not be reached for comment Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's two top executives also sought to clear up confusion
about Morgan Stanley's own descriptions of the payment to Luethke.
It called it a ``mistake in judgment'' in one statement last last
month. Earlier this week, it referred to the payment in court
documents as a ``reward'' for Luethke that its lawyers deemed
``entirely legal.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are not contradictory, Purcell said. He said that the
payment should never have been made. But he said that the payment
itself was not illegal. He said he understood the decision to make
the reward payment to a good Samaritan who helped thwart a crime,
but did not agree with the decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Legal or not, both Morgan Stanley and the district attorney's
office view the payment as a mistake. The reason is that the
payment appeared to reduce the chances of persuading a jury to
convict Curry, who was charged with conspiracy to plant fake e-mail
messages on Morgan Stanley's computers. The payment was seen as
likely taint the credibility of Luethke, who had a role in the
Curry arrest, people close the case said.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been true even if Morgan Stanley had immediately
told prosecutors about the payment and entered it into its books
properly. But the firm did not. To this day, prosecutors are still
piecing together what happened. But several people see the events
as having unfolded in the following way.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley paid Luethke $10,000 late last August, a few days
after Curry's arrest, apparently intending it as a gratuity for the
tip Luethke provided. The firm did not inform the Manhattan
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of September, the office had learned of the payment _
possibly from Luethke. The office then asked Morgan Stanley about
it. According to people involved, Ms. Bernheim, one of the in-house
lawyers, denied having paid the informant. People close to Morgan
Stanley, however, said that Ms. Bernheim might have answered `no'
to a narrowly phrased question about whether Luethke had
``extorted'' money from the firm rather than deny outright the fact
of the payment.
</P>
<P>
   By early October, Ms. Bernheim and Sonnenborn acknowledged to
prosecutors that they had paid Luethke. But prosecutors weren't
satisfied. Among the concerns was that the firm had paid Luethke by
wire transfer to a numbered account, not by check. Morgan Stanley
also could not produce the kind of documentation that would
normally accompany a payment to an outside vendor.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, when Morgan Stanley produced accounting records, that
only complicated things. The records showed that the payment had
been assigned a billing code that Morgan Stanley used when it paid
millions of dollars in settlements stemming from the Orange County
bond-trading scandal, a completely unrelated event.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley told prosecutors that the error was made in the
firm's accounting department. Sonnenborn and Ms. Bernheim had
intended that payment to be assigned to the real-estate finance
division, where Curry had worked, prosecutors were told.
</P>
<P>
   Some people involved said they believed that Morgan Stanley was
acting in a way that suggested it wanted to disguise ties to
Luethke. Morgan Stanley insisted all along that it had no such
intention. Months passed without a resolution. The fact that the
case was handled by three different assistant district attorney's
during nine months did not help matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one big comedy of errors,'' said one person close to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible that Morgan Stanley could face criminal
charges. If prosecutors decided that the firm had sought to falsify
business records to disguise a payment it thought to be criminal,
the firm could be charged with a felony under New York state's
general business laws, people close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   But several people involved said they considered it more likely
that prosecutors would accept Morgan Stanley's arguments that the
errors were unintentional. The personnel changes at Morgan Stanley
and the bad publicity the firm has suffered have are likely to be
considered punishment enough, these people said.
</P>
</TEXT>
